                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application made for a search warrant under ''by sworn information''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By the information on oath and in writing, in the form of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant.","By the information on oath and in writing, provided by any member of the public.","By the information on oath and in writing, in the form of a judge or magistrate.","By the information on oath and in writing, submitted electronically by a member of the Garda Síochána below the rank of sergeant."],"justification":"Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing, in the Form [34.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e0fdf15c-d42c-41c9-bc8e-0185a3b965ed/Information - Criminal Law Amendment Act, 1935 section 19 No. 34.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- by sworn information.* (2) Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing, in the Form [34.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e0fdf15c-d42c-41c9-bc8e-0185a3b965ed/Information - Criminal Law Amendment Act, 1935 section 19 No. 34.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act is this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Sexual Offences Act 2000 (No. 15 of 2000)","Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998 (No. 22 of 1998)","Juvenile Justice Act 1997 (No. 20 of 1997)","Prevention of Corruption Act 1998 (No. 23 of 1998)"],"justification":"- under the Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998 (No. 22 of 1998)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## - under the Child Trafficking and Pornography Act 1998 (No. 22 of 1998)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application for a search warrant made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Through a formal letter signed by any member of the Garda Síochána, regardless of rank.","By the information on oath and in writing in Form 34.24, Schedule by a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant.","By submitting a verbal request to a judge during a public hearing.","By filling out an electronic form available on the Garda Síochána website."],"justification":"Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the Form [34.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/912b3d43-3d90-4209-9829-e6e9fb09613d/Information For Issue Of Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- by sworn information.* (2) Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the Form [34.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/912b3d43-3d90-4209-9829-e6e9fb09613d/Information For Issue Of Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of sergeant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 34 - Miscellaneous Search Warrants', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant issued on foot of such information take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 34.25, Schedule A","Form 34.24, Schedule","Form 34.26, Schedule A","Form 34.25, Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2585d723-f60d-4eba-982b-c63e9d48db96/Search Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Form of warrant.* (3) A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the Form [34.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2585d723-f60d-4eba-982b-c63e9d48db96/Search Warrant - Child Trafficking And Pornography Act 1998 section 7 No. 34.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given to the relevant financial institution before the order is to be obeyed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["one clear day","five clear hours","two clear days","three clear days"],"justification":"three clear days before the order is to be obeyed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Order* (8) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c87e56e1-1d64-4d4d-b54e-8c6d237e94aa/Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books Or Records - Taxes Consolidation Act 1997 section 908a as amended No. 38.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be served upon the relevant financial institution three clear days before the order is to be obeyed. Service may be effected by delivering a copy of the order to the office of the financial institution wherein the relevant books or records are kept.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Notice to Coroner of commencement of proceedings","Notice to Coroner of result of proceedings","Notice to Solicitor of result of proceedings","Notice to Coroner of cause of death"],"justification":"**Notice to Coroner of result of proceedings**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Notice to Coroner of result of proceedings**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court granting the application take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form [38.13], Schedule","Form [38.14], Schedule A","Form [38.15], Schedule","Form [38.12], Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c87e56e1-1d64-4d4d-b54e-8c6d237e94aa/Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books Or Records - Taxes Consolidation Act 1997 section 908a as amended No. 38.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- Order* (8) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [38.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c87e56e1-1d64-4d4d-b54e-8c6d237e94aa/Order To Inspect And Take Copies Of Entries In Books Or Records - Taxes Consolidation Act 1997 section 908a as amended No. 38.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be served upon the relevant financial institution three clear days before the order is to be obeyed. Service may be effected by delivering a copy of the order to the office of the financial institution wherein the relevant books or records are kept.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order authorising the detention beyond forty-eight hours of seized cash take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The order should be in the form specified in Form [38.5], Schedule","The order should be in the form specified in Form [40.2], Schedule A.","The order should be in the form specified in Form [39.7], Schedule","The order should be in the form specified in Form [37.1], Schedule"],"justification":"An order of the Court made on such application authorising the detention beyond forty-eight hours of cash seized by virtue of section 38 shall be in the Form [38.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c53f1153-6752-458f-8202-667e77fc4a4d/Order Authorising Detention Of Cash Beyond Forty Eight Hours - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds Of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Form and service of order* (2) An order of the Court made on such application authorising the detention beyond forty-eight hours of cash seized by virtue of section 38 shall be in the Form [38.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c53f1153-6752-458f-8202-667e77fc4a4d/Order Authorising Detention Of Cash Beyond Forty Eight Hours - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds Of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule The applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served upon the person from whom the cash was seized and upon any person by or on whose behalf the cash was being imported or exported.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for further detention of seized cash?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The submission of a detailed financial audit report to the relevant authority","The issue and service of a notice of application on the person from whom the cash was seized and any other person directly affected by the previous order","The filing of a formal complaint by the person from whom the cash was seized","The approval of a judge for an emergency detention order without prior notice"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the person from whom the cash was seized and upon any other person directly affected by the order previously made under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c1a1fe0f-1295-4a10-9a1b-946d89878d79/Notice Of Application For An Order Authorising The Further Detention Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds Of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for order authorising further detention of cash* 6.(1) An application to the Court by a member of the Garda Síochána or an officer of Customs and Excise under section 38(3) of the 1994 Act for an order authorising the further detention in accordance with section 38(3) of the 1994 Act of cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the cash was seized. Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the person from whom the cash was seized and upon any other person directly affected by the order previously made under section 38(2) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c1a1fe0f-1295-4a10-9a1b-946d89878d79/Notice Of Application For An Order Authorising The Further Detention Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds Of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The payment receipt for the court filing fee.","The original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of such notice.","The affidavit of the applicant''s lawyer regarding the case details.","The updated list of witnesses and their contact information."],"justification":"The original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of such notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of application* (2) Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Such notice may be served in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings). The original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of such notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for releasing seized cash?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The submission of a formal complaint by the owner of the seized cash to the High Court","The issuance of a warrant by a magistrate","The approval of the application by the Minister for Justice","The issue and service of a notice of application on the relevant Garda Síochána or Customs and Excise officers"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the member(s) of the Garda Síochána or officer(s) of Customs and Excise who applied for any order previously made under section 38(2) or section 38(3) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fe876c2c-2e37-4ee5-8a75-a25057d8a7fd/Notice Of Application For An Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application for order releasing cash* 7.(1) An application to the Court under section 38(5) of the 1994 Act for an order releasing cash seized by virtue of section 38 of the 1994 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the cash was seized. Such application shall be preceded by the issue, and service upon the member(s) of the Garda Síochána or officer(s) of Customs and Excise who applied for any order previously made under section 38(2) or section 38(3) of the 1994 Act in respect of the cash, of copy of a notice of application, in the Form [38.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fe876c2c-2e37-4ee5-8a75-a25057d8a7fd/Notice Of Application For An Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must notice of an application be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Within twenty-four hours before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","At least three days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","At least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","At least fourteen days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."],"justification":"Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of application* (2) Notice of such application shall be served at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Such notice may be served in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings). The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Court''s order take on an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The order should follow the standard format outlined in Rule 23 of the Civil Procedure Rules.","The order should be in the form specified in Form [38.7], Schedule A.","The order must adhere to the template provided in Appendix of the Court''s internal guidelines.","The order should be in the form specified in Form [38.9], Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab17f375-ede1-4b91-b635-f776d7cd7994/Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Form of order* (3) The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab17f375-ede1-4b91-b635-f776d7cd7994/Order Directing The Release Of Cash Seized - Criminal Justice Act 1994, section 38 (as amended by section 20, Proceeds of Crime (Amendment) Act 2005) No. 38.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Where can applications under the 1994 Act be brought, heard and determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Before a magistrate judge in any federal judicial district","Before a jury in the state where the cash was seized","Before the Secretary of the Treasury in Washington D.C.","Before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district wherein the cash was seized"],"justification":"Applications to the Court under the 1994 Act may be brought, heard and determined before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district wherein the cash was seized at any sitting of the Court within such Judge’s district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 8.(1) Applications to the Court under the 1994 Act may be brought, heard and determined before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district wherein the cash was seized at any sitting of the Court within such Judge’s district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Certificates and applications under the Criminal Law Reform Act 1998","Certificates and applications under Sex Offenders Act 2001 (as amended)","Certificates and applications under the Child Protection Act 2003","Certificates and applications under the Youth Justice Act 2005"],"justification":"## **Certificates and applications under Sex Offenders Act 2001 (as amended)**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Certificates and applications under Sex Offenders Act 2001 (as amended)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a certificate under the Sex Offenders Act 2001 be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 38.14, Schedule A","Form 38.13, Schedule","Form 38.15, Schedule","Form 38.14, Schedule"],"justification":"A certificate for the purposes of section 14 of the [Sex Offenders Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/18) shall be in the Form [38.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/55b14cb6-3365-4c69-ab7f-019f965a6705/Certificate Of Conviction And-Or Sentence - Sex Offenders Act, 2001, Section 14 No. 38.14.docx/docx/1) , Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Certificate* 9.(1) A certificate for the purposes of section 14 of the [Sex Offenders Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/18) shall be in the Form [38.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/55b14cb6-3365-4c69-ab7f-019f965a6705/Certificate Of Conviction And-Or Sentence - Sex Offenders Act, 2001, Section 14 No. 38.14.docx/docx/1) , Schedule and shall be signed by a District Court clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order for post-release supervision take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 38.16 Schedule A","Form 38.14 Schedule","Form 38.15 Schedule","Form 38.15 Schedule A"],"justification":"may be in the Form [38.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3697915-fed8-4d22-9b07-7f4f1f8b8f1f/Order For Imprisonment And Post-Release Supervision - Sex Offenders Act, 2001 section 29 No. 38.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order imposing post-release supervision* (2) An order imposing post-release supervision pursuant to section 29 of the Sex Offenders Act 2001 may be in the Form [38.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3697915-fed8-4d22-9b07-7f4f1f8b8f1f/Order For Imprisonment And Post-Release Supervision - Sex Offenders Act, 2001 section 29 No. 38.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such Order shall be transmitted to the Governor of the Prison to which the accused is committed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'When must notice of the application be served on the sex offender?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least three days before the date of hearing","At least seven days before the date of hearing","At least fourteen days before the date of hearing","On the same day as the date of hearing"],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served on the sex offender concerned at least seven days before the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application under section 30A* (3) An application to the Court pursuant to section 30A of the Sex Offenders Act 2001 (inserted by section 51 of the Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Act 2017) for an order amending any condition attached to, or for the inclusion of any new condition in, any order of the Court providing for post-release supervision may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the order providing for post-release supervision was made. Notice of the application shall be served on the sex offender concerned at least seven days before the date of hearing. A copy of the notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when the Court amends a condition or adds a new one to the order for post-release supervision?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The changes must be communicated verbally to the supervised individual and recorded in their case file.","The terms of any such change may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the order and re-signed by the Judge.","The updated terms should be printed on a new document and attached to the original without requiring additional signatures.","The amendments are to be filed separately and do not require the Judge''s signature again."],"justification":"Where the Court amends a condition or includes any new condition attached to, or includes any new condition in, the order providing for post-release supervision, the terms of any such change may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the order and re-signed by the Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Indorsement of new terms* (4) Where the Court amends a condition or includes any new condition attached to, or includes any new condition in, the order providing for post-release supervision, the terms of any such change may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the order and re-signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Under which sections of the 2015 Act can a person be committed to a place of detention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Sections 21(3)(a), 21(10), or 21(12) of the 2015 Act.","Sections 20(9), or 20(11) of the 2015 Act.","Sections 20(3)(a), 20(10), or 20(12) of the 2015 Act.","Sections 18(3)(a), 18(10), or 18(12) of the 2015 Act."],"justification":"as provided for in section 20(3)(a), section 20(10), or as the case may be, section 20(12) of the 2015 Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Commitment to detention 11. Where a person who has been detained pursuant to section 20(1) or section 20(9) of the 2015 Act is brought before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the person is being detained and is committed by the Court to a place of detention as provided for in section 20(3)(a), section 20(10), or as the case may be, section 20(12) of the 2015 Act, the order of detention shall be in the Form [38.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b74d51c7-7456-4bf7-b2ba-f26d5d38683a/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(3)(a) No 38.16.docx/docx/1), [38.16A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/817becce-c3ed-4dbc-99d8-97150f97fbf3/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(10) No 38.16A.docx/docx/1), or as the case may be, [38.16B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4c105597-77b0-4b67-a37d-65a088a9d970/Order of Committal to a Place of Detention - International Protection Act 2015 section 20(12) No 38.16B.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of release take when a person is released under sections or 20(11) of the 2015 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 38.17, Schedule","Form 20.15, Schedule","Form 38.16, Schedule A","Form 40.17, Schedule"],"justification":"the order of release shall be in the Form [38.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19aebd09-6bff-477c-b247-ae082310c06a/Order of Conditional Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect sect 20(10) No 38.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Conditional release 12. Where a person who has been detained pursuant to section 20(1) or section 20(9) of the 2015 Act is brought before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the person is being detained and is released pursuant to the provisions of section or section 20(11), as the case may be, of the 2015 Act, the order of release shall be in the Form [38.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19aebd09-6bff-477c-b247-ae082310c06a/Order of Conditional Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect sect 20(10) No 38.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Types of Probation Violations","Legal Framework for Imprisonment","Variation of conditional release","History of Conditional Sentencing"],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Variation of conditional release'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Who can make an application to vary, revoke or add a condition to a person''s release?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A judge from the Supreme Court","The person released, an immigration officer, or a member of the Garda Síochána","A local school principal","An immigration lawyer representing the person released"],"justification":"by the person, an immigration officer, or a member of the Garda Síochána to vary, revoke or add a condition to the person’s release."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - application - service - order 13. Where a person has been released from detention on conditions in accordance with section of the 2015 Act, an application in the Form [38.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/93ec30f7-670e-4445-9605-f01609039818/Application to Vary Revoke Add a Condition of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(5) sect 20(10) No 38.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule may be made pursuant to section 20(5) or section 20(10) of the 2015 Act, to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the person’s dwelling place is situated, by the person, an immigration officer, or a member of the Garda Síochána to vary, revoke or add a condition to the person’s release. Such application shall be served in the manner provided by section 5 of the 2015 Act and shall be served at least four clear days before the date for hearing the application. The original of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of hearing. The order of the Court on the application shall be in the Form [38.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ffa8ea69-7288-4df6-ab27-8790d4fbc9a3/Order Varying Revoking Adding a Condition of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(5) sect 20(10) No 38.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of release take when a person is released under sections 20(4) or 20(10) of the 2015 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 20.38, Schedule","Form 40.20, Schedule","Form 38.10, Schedule A","Form 38.20, Schedule"],"justification":"the order of release shall be in the Form [38.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/10b22ec9-be2b-4e64-b26f-0d9805aae3c3/Order of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(4) sect 20(11) No 38.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Order of release 14. Where a person who has been detained pursuant to the provisions of section 20 of the 2015 Act is brought, under the provisions of section 20(4) or section 20(10) of the 2015 Act before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district where the person is being detained and the Court orders the release of that person, the order of release shall be in the Form [38.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/10b22ec9-be2b-4e64-b26f-0d9805aae3c3/Order of Release - International Protection Act 2015 sect 20(4) sect 20(11) No 38.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Judge be in when a person detained under section 20 of the 2015 Act is brought before a Judge?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 37.19, Schedule","Form 40.10, Schedule A","Form 38.22, Schedule","Form 38.21, Schedule"],"justification":"the order of the Judge under the provisions of section of the 2015 Act shall be in the Form [38.21](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d3c8ca4a-13b2-4038-be57-c5092e9f31b2/Order under Section - International Protection Act 2015 No 38.21.docx/doc/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Order where the person indicates a desire to leave the State 15. Where a person detained pursuant to the provisions of section 20 of the 2015 Act is brought before a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district where the person has been detained, the order of the Judge under the provisions of section of the 2015 Act shall be in the Form [38.21](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d3c8ca4a-13b2-4038-be57-c5092e9f31b2/Order under Section - International Protection Act 2015 No 38.21.docx/doc/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Orders under Part 3 of the Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the 2010 Act'' refer to in rules 16, 17, and 18?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Criminal Justice (Tax Evasion and Fraud) Act 2010 (No. 6 of 2010)","The Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010 (No. 6 of 2010)","The Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2009 (No. 6 of 2009)","The Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2011 (No. 6 of 2011)"],"justification":"“**the 2010 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 2010)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interpretation – rules 16 to 18* 16. In this rule and rules 17 and 18, “**the 2010 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 2010).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the application be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Submitted electronically via the official website without any specific form.","On affidavit but in Form 45.17.","On oath and in writing, in Form 38.22","Orally presented during a court hearing."],"justification":"Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing of the applicant, in the Form [38.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0906e9a4-b703-4680-90a0-7507c8ca6612/Information - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 17 No. 38.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applications under section 17* 17. An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 17(2) of the 2010 Act ordering a person not to carry out a specified service or transaction shall be made parte and otherwise than in public to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order is proposed to be served. Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing of the applicant, in the Form [38.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0906e9a4-b703-4680-90a0-7507c8ca6612/Information - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 17 No. 38.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule Where the application is for a second or subsequent order in relation to a particular service or transaction, there shall be produced with the information a copy of any previous order of the Court in relation to that service or transaction. An order of the Court under section 17(2) of the Act shall be in the Form [38.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/96cae89f-a5b5-4aca-9535-e4b6886cb9e3/Order - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 17 No. 38.23.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'To whom should an application under section 19 or 20 of the 2010 Act be directed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Secretary of State for Justice","The Attorney General","A Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order or direction was made","A Magistrate from any local magistrate''s court"],"justification":"An application to a Judge of the Court under section 19 of the 2010 Act to revoke an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act, or an application under section 20 of the 2010 Act for an order in relation to any of the property concerned in an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order or direction was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applications under section 19 or 20* 18.(1) An application to a Judge of the Court under section 19 of the 2010 Act to revoke an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act, or an application under section 20 of the 2010 Act for an order in relation to any of the property concerned in an order or direction made under section 17 of the 2010 Act shall be made to a Judge of the Court assigned to the Court district in which the order or direction was made. Such application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application, in the Form [38.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bafe0aa8-9a13-4e9f-8fcc-572e873f7cf0/Notice of Application - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 19 - section 20 No. 38.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule and service of a copy of that notice, in the manner provided by [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings), upon the member of the Garda Síochána on whose application the order under section 17 of the 2010 Act was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given for an application under sections 19 or 20 unless the court allows otherwise?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","At least two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","At least three hours before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","At least one week before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"],"justification":"Unless the Court permits otherwise, notice of such application shall be served at least four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice of applications under section 19 or 20* (2) Unless the Court permits otherwise, notice of such application shall be served at least four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application together with a statutory declaration as to the service of copy of the notice shall be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the Court take regarding persons affected by a direction or order but not given notice of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may issue a public apology to those persons for lack of notification.","The Court may ignore the presence of those persons as they were not notified.","The Court may dismiss the case involving those persons without further notice.","The Court may direct that such persons be joined in, or put on notice of, the application."],"justification":"the Court may direct that any person affected by the direction or order who was not given notice of the application be joined in, or put on notice of, the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Service of applications under section 19 or 20* (3) Where it seems appropriate to the Court to so direct, in any application under section 19 or section 20 of the 2010 Act, the Court may direct that any person affected by the direction or order who was not given notice of the application be joined in, or put on notice of, the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 38 - Miscellaneous Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order of the Court under section 20 of the 2010 Act take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 27.5, Schedule","Form 40.15, Schedule A","Form 38.25, Schedule","Form 38.25, Schedule"],"justification":"An order of the Court under section 20 of the 2010 Act shall be in the Form [38.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/41c0df42-fe72-4b01-a988-adabb2fe9bd4/Order - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 20 No. 38.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Order under section 19 or 20* (4) An order of the Court under section 20 of the 2010 Act shall be in the Form [38.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/41c0df42-fe72-4b01-a988-adabb2fe9bd4/Order - Criminal Justice (Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing) Act 2010, section 20 No. 38.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order 39 - General Rules","Order 38 - Administrative Guidelines","Order 39 - Special Exceptions","Order 40 - Specific Regulations"],"justification":"# Order 39 - General Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 39 - General Rules - Court: District # **Order 39: General Rules******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What does the section number indicate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The section is numbered 2.","The section is numbered 1.","The section is numbered with a letter.","The section is numbered 0."],"justification":"1-"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1- WHERE NO PROCEDURE PROVIDED FOR'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What forms can be used in District Court proceedings when no specific form is prescribed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any form in use in the Supreme Court exclusively for appellate cases, with necessary modifications.","Any form in use in the Magistrates'' Court for the corresponding step, notification or other action in criminal proceedings, with necessary modifications.","Any form prescribed by the local municipal council for the corresponding step, notification or other action in civil proceedings, with necessary modifications.","Any form in use in the Circuit Court or High Court for the corresponding step, notification or other action in civil proceedings, with necessary modifications."],"justification":"where no form for use in the Court in respect of a step, notification or other action in a civil proceeding is for the time being prescribed, any form for the time being in use in the Circuit Court or the High Court for the corresponding step, notification or other action in civil proceedings may be used in civil proceedings in the Court with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Where no procedure provided for* 1. (1) If the procedure for the conduct of civil proceedings is not prescribed by these Rules or by an enactment, or for any other reason there is doubt about the manner or form of the procedure, the Court may determine what procedure is to be adopted and may give directions. (2) Subject to [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), rule 9(4), where no form for use in the Court in respect of a step, notification or other action in a civil proceeding is for the time being prescribed, any form for the time being in use in the Circuit Court or the High Court for the corresponding step, notification or other action in civil proceedings may be used in civil proceedings in the Court with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title of this rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["3 - PROCEDURES FOR ENFORCING COMPLIANCE","2 - NON-COMPLIANCE WITH THESE RULES","1 - COMPLIANCE WITH THESE RULES","4 - PENALTIES FOR NON-COMPLIANCE"],"justification":"2 - NON-COMPLIANCE WITH THESE RULES"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - NON-COMPLIANCE WITH THESE RULES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Does a failure to comply with the Rules render a civil proceeding void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Failure to comply with the Rules results in immediate dismissal of the case without further proceedings.","No, it is considered an irregularity and does not render the proceeding void.","Yes, any failure to comply with the Rules automatically renders the civil proceeding void.","While a failure to comply does not always render the proceeding void, it can lead to severe sanctions that could effectively nullify the outcome."],"justification":"Subject to any provision of an enactment, a failure to comply with these Rules is an irregularity and does not render a civil proceeding or a step taken, or any document or order in the proceeding void."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Effect of non-compliance* 2. (1) Subject to any provision of an enactment, a failure to comply with these Rules is an irregularity and does not render a civil proceeding or a step taken, or any document or order in the proceeding void. (2) If there has been a failure to comply with these Rules, the Court may— - (a) set aside the proceeding, either wholly or in part; - set aside any step taken in the proceeding, or any document or order therein; - exercise its powers under these Rules to allow amendments and to make orders dealing with the proceeding generally.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["MOTION","SPACE","PLACE","TIME"],"justification":"TIME"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - TIME'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Court take if there has been no activity in a civil proceeding for over twelve months?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may cause the civil proceeding to be listed before the Court to explain the failure to proceed.","The Court may dismiss the civil proceeding automatically without further notice.","The Court may extend the time limit for proceedings indefinitely.","The Court may order the parties to pay a fine for lack of activity in the proceeding."],"justification":"Where no step by a party requiring the filing of a document with the Clerk or notification to the Court under these Rules has been taken in a civil proceeding for twelve months or more since the last such step, the Court may cause the civil proceeding to be listed before the Court to explain the failure to proceed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Dormant proceedings* 4. (1) Where no step by a party requiring the filing of a document with the Clerk or notification to the Court under these Rules has been taken in a civil proceeding for twelve months or more since the last such step, the Court may cause the civil proceeding to be listed before the Court to explain the failure to proceed. (2) The Clerk must notify the parties of any listing in accordance with sub-rule (1). The notification may be in [Form 39.02, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce279976-c45b-4654-b033-db71d3483461/Notice of listing of proceedings No. 39.02.docx/docx/1). (3) A party may file a written explanation of the failure to proceed with the Clerk and if the Court is satisfied that there were sufficient reasons for the failure to proceed, may direct that the civil proceeding be removed from the list to explain the failure to proceed and direct that the Clerk notify the parties accordingly. (4) On the listing of a civil proceeding in accordance with sub-rule (1), the Court may make such orders and give such directions as are in the opinion of the Court likely to ensure the civil proceedings are prepared for trial in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances does the Court not have the authority to enlarge or abridge time?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court cannot enlarge or abridge time if it is fixed by an Act of the Oireachtas, a statute in force in Saorstát Éireann before the Constitution, or an application to which rule 10(2) of Order 40 applies.","The Court cannot enlarge or abridge time if it is fixed by a decision made by the European Court of Justice.","The Court cannot enlarge or abridge time if it is fixed by a resolution passed by the United Nations General Assembly.","The Court cannot enlarge or abridge time if it is fixed by a decree issued by the President of the European Commission."],"justification":"Sub-rules (1) and (2) do not apply: - (a) to any period of time fixed by an Act of the Oireachtas, or - to any period of time fixed by a statute which was in force in Saorstát Éireann immediately before the date of the coming into operation of the Constitution and which continued in force by virtue of Article 50 of the Constitution, or - to any application to which rule 10(2) of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Enlargement or abridgement of time* 5. (1) Subject to sub-rules (3) and (4), the Court may, on any terms it considers reasonable, enlarge or abridge any of the times fixed by these Rules, or by a prior order of the Court, for taking any step or doing any act in any civil proceedings. (2) Subject to sub-rules (3) and (4), the Court may also, on any terms as to costs or otherwise as it considers just, declare any step taken or act done in any civil proceedings to be sufficient, even though not taken or done within the time or in the manner prescribed by these Rules. (3)[2] Sub-rules (1) and (2) do not apply: - (a) to any period of time fixed by an Act of the Oireachtas, or - to any period of time fixed by a statute which was in force in Saorstát Éireann immediately before the date of the coming into operation of the Constitution and which continued in force by virtue of Article 50 of the Constitution, or - to any application to which rule 10(2) of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) applies. (4) Without limiting the generality of sub-rule (3), any application to state a case under section 2 of the Summary Jurisdiction Act 1857 must be made within the time prescribed by that Act. (5) Unless otherwise directed or permitted by the Court, an application to enlarge or abridge time must be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties who would be affected by the enlargement or abridgement of time.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39 - General Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What form is recommended for a statutory declaration under sections 14(2) or 15(2) of the Mediation Act 2017?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 39.01, Schedule","Form 39.02, Schedule","Form 39.03, Schedule","Form 39.02, Schedule"],"justification":"The statutory declaration required by section 14(2) or 15(2) of Mediation Act 2017 may be in the [Form 39.02, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce279976-c45b-4654-b033-db71d3483461/Notice%20of%20listing%20of%20proceedings%20No.%2039.02.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Statutory declaration required by section 14(2) or 15(2) of Mediation Act 2017* 6.[3] The statutory declaration required by section 14(2) or 15(2) of Mediation Act 2017 may be in the [Form 39.02, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce279976-c45b-4654-b033-db71d3483461/Notice of listing of proceedings No. 39.02.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 39 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 39 sub-rule (3) of rule 5 substituted by [S.I. 423 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/423/made/en/print?q 423&years 2019), effective 2 September 2019 [3] Order 39 rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'What does sub-rule (2A) state about signing court documents transmitted digitally?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Such requirement shall be satisfied by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the Electronic Commerce Act 2000 and/or Article 3 of Regulation","The requirement is met if the document is simply marked ''Signed Electronically'' without any specific form of electronic signature.","Such requirement shall be satisfied by the inclusion of a handwritten signature on paper documents only.","Sub-rule (2A) states that any digital signature must be accompanied by a physical copy sent via postal service within 7 days."],"justification":"Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement shall be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of [that Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or that Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents - Court: Circuit # Order 4: Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents [1] 1[2] [3] [4] [5] (1). The Court shall have for use in each County an embossing Seal or, in circumstances in which the Office has multiple locations, embossing Seals with an appropriate inscription, as directed by the Minister, specifying the name of the Circuit in connection with which it is to be used. Such Seal shall be placed and retained in the custody of the County Registrar. It shall not be necessary that any Decree, Order, Warrant or other document shall be signed by the Judge. (2) Every document requiring under any provision of statute or statutory instrument, rule of law or any other Order of these Rules to be issued under Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the Seal of the Court impressed thereon and the signature of a person mentioned in sub-rule (4). (2A)[6] Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement shall be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of [that Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or that Regulation. Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be sealed, such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic seal in accordance with [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng) (3) Every document requiring authentication other than one referred to in sub-rule (2), and every Decree, Order and Warrant, shall be authenticated by the signature of a person mentioned in sub-rule (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when an embossing Seal is not available due to Circuit re-arrangement?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["In the absence of the embossing Seal, all documents must be accompanied by a written affidavit from the parties involved, attesting to the authenticity of the document.","Documents required by Rule 1 of this Order to be authenticated by the Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the signatures of both the Circuit Court Judge and the County Registrar or a nominated staff member of the combined court office.","Documents will be considered unauthenticated and invalid until a new embossing Seal is created.","The documents can be authenticated solely by the signature of the Circuit Court Judge without the need for the County Registrar or their staff member."],"justification":"Where by reason of the re-arrangement of Circuits an embossing Seal is not available for a particular Circuit Court area then until such time as an embossing Seal becomes available, all documents required by Rule 1 of this Order to be authenticated by the Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the signatures of both the Circuit Court Judge and the County Registrar for the said area or where paragraph of rule 1(4)of this Order applies, the combined court office manager concerned or member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in the combined court office nominated in writing for that purpose by that combined court office manager."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The persons who may authenticate the impression of the Seal of the Court on a document mentioned in sub-rule (2) or a document mentioned in sub-rule (3) are: - (a) the County Registrar, or - such person, or one of such persons, as may, for such period as may be specified, be nominated in writing for that purpose by the County Registrar, or - where any business of the office of the Court in a county is specified in accordance with section 14 of the [Courts and Court Officers Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) as business that shall be transacted in a combined court office established under that section, and for the purposes of such business: - the combined court office manager appointed under section 19 of [that Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) for that combined court office, or - such member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in that combined court office under section 21 of the [Courts and Court Officers Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/36/enacted/en/html) as may, for such period as may be specified, be nominated in writing for that purpose by the combined court office manager concerned. (5)[8] The proper officer may certify any printed version of the legible content of any original document which was transmitted to or by the proper officer by digital delivery as a certified copy of the original. 2.[9] Where by reason of the re-arrangement of Circuits an embossing Seal is not available for a particular Circuit Court area then until such time as an embossing Seal becomes available, all documents required by Rule 1 of this Order to be authenticated by the Seal of the Court shall be authenticated by the signatures of both the Circuit Court Judge and - (a) the County Registrar for the said area or - where paragraph of rule 1(4)of this Order applies, the combined court office manager concerned or member of the staff of the Courts Service employed in the combined court office nominated in writing for that purpose by that combined court office manager.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 4 - Court Seal and Authentication of Court documents', 'Court Rules', 'What was the title of Order 4 amended by?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["19 of 2019","19 of 2020","Order 4 was not amended by any","4 of 2019"],"justification":"Title amended by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[1] Title amended by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019. [2] Order 4 rule 1 substituted by 409 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/409/made/en/print), effective 28 August 2006. [3] Order 4 rule 1(2) and 1(3) substituted by 583 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/583/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2010. [4] Order 4 rule 1(4) inserted by 583 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/583/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2010. [5] Order 4 rule 1(4) substituted by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019. [6] Order 4 rule 1(2A) inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [7] Order 4 rule inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [8] Order 4 rule 1(5) inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025. [9] Order 4 rule 2 inserted by 19 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/19/made/en/print), effective 19 February 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 4 - Mode of Address', 'Court Rules', 'How should a judge be addressed in court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["As ''Chief Justice''","As ''Your Majesty''","As ''Honorable Sir/Madam''","As ''A Bhreithimh'' or ''Judge''."],"justification":"A Judge shall be addressed in court as \"**A Bhreithimh**\" or as \"**Judge**\"."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 4 - Mode of Address - Court: District # Order 4: Mode of Address [1] A Judge shall be addressed in court as "**A Bhreithimh**" or as "**Judge**". [1] Order 3 inserted by[S.I. No. 93/1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93)- District Court Rules, 1997'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'What does the indorsement of claim on a summary summons and a special summons need to include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["the date and time of the court hearing","specifically and with all necessary particulars the relief claimed and the grounds thereof","a detailed history of the relationship between the parties","the names of all parties involved in the lawsuit"],"justification":"and shall state specifically and with all necessary particulars the relief claimed and the grounds thereof."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '2.[[5]](#_ftn5) Save in the case of a personal injuries summons as defined in [Order 1A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-1A-Superior-Procedure-by-Personal-Injuries-Summons), the indorsement of claim on a plenary summons shall be entitled “**General Indorsement of Claim**” and there shall be an indorsement of the relief claimed and the grounds thereof expressed in general terms in such one of the forms in [Appendix Part II](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#weds2) as shall be applicable to the case, or, if none be found applicable, then such other similarly concise form as the nature of the case may require. The indorsement of claim on a personal injuries summons shall be as provided by [Order 1A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-1A-Superior-Procedure-by-Personal-Injuries-Summons). 3. In the indorsement required by rule 2 it shall not be essential to set forth the precise ground of complaint or the precise remedy or relief to which the plaintiff considers himself entitled. 3A.[[6]](#_ftn6) In the case of proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003, the indorsement of claim shall contain a statement - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, - specifying the section of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003 or the rule made under section 46(3) of that Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation. 4. The indorsement of claim on a summary summons and on a special summons shall be entitled “**SPECIAL INDORSEMENT OF CLAIM,**” and shall state specifically and with all necessary particulars the relief claimed and the grounds thereof. The indorsement of claim on a summary summons or a special summons shall be in such one of the forms in [Appendix Part III](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#weds2), as shall be applicable to the case, or, if none be found applicable, then such other similarly concise form as the nature of the case may require.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'What should the indorsement include when a claim is for a liquidated sum?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The indorsement should indicate that no action is required if the amount is paid within one month, with no mention of staying further proceedings.","The indorsement should only state the amount claimed in respect of the demand, without mentioning any costs or the stay of proceedings.","The indorsement should state the amount claimed in respect of the demand, the amount claimed for costs, and that on payment of these amounts within six days after service, further proceedings will be stayed.","The indorsement should state that on payment of the claimed amount within three days after service, further proceedings will commence."],"justification":"Whenever a claim indorsed on a summary summons is for a liquidated sum only, the indorsement, besides stating the amount claimed in respect of the demand, shall state the amount claimed for costs, and shall further state that on payment of such amounts for demand and costs within six days after service, or in the case of a summons not for service within the jurisdiction, within the time limited for appearance, further proceedings will be stayed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. (1) Whenever a claim indorsed on a summary summons is for a liquidated sum only, the indorsement, besides stating the amount claimed in respect of the demand, shall state the amount claimed for costs, and shall further state that on payment of such amounts for demand and costs within six days after service, or in the case of a summons not for service within the jurisdiction, within the time limited for appearance, further proceedings will be stayed. (2)[[7]](#_ftn7) [[8]](#_ftn8) The amount claimed for costs shall be: - (a) If the demand does not exceed €15,000: Such sum as would be appropriate to a proceeding for a like amount in the District Court. - If the demand exceeds €15,000 but does not exceed €75,000: Such sum as would be appropriate to a proceeding for a like amount in the Circuit Court. - If the demand exceeds €75,000: €70 with €7 for each additional service after the first, and the costs of any order for issue and service, or service of the summons or notice in lieu thereof outside the jurisdiction, or for substituted or other service, or for the substitution of notice for service, or for declaring service effected sufficient, or for notice by advertisement of the issue of the summons, and this amount shall be exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. (3) The statement shall be in the form incorporated in the [Form No 2 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon4). In any case within this rule the defendant may, notwithstanding payment, have the costs taxed, and if more than one-sixth of the amount paid shall be disallowed the amount disallowed shall be refunded and the plaintiff’s solicitor shall pay the costs of taxation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'What details must be included in the indorsement for actions by a moneylender or assignee?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The indorsement should contain the address of the moneylender, the phone number of the borrower, and a copy of the signed contract.","The indorsement must include the fact that the plaintiff is a licensed moneylender, or if by an assignee or personal representative, that the original assignor or testator/intestate was a licensed moneylender, along with the date of loan, amount lent, interest rate, contract date, signed note, delivery date of note, amount repaid, and amount due.","The indorsement needs to state the reason for lending the money, the borrower''s credit score, and the repayment plan schedule.","The indorsement must only include the name of the borrower, the amount lent, and the signature of the moneylender."],"justification":"the indorsement on the summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, the fact that the plaintiff is a licensed moneylender, or (in an action by an assignee or by the personal representative or personal representatives of a deceased moneylender) that the original assignor, or the testator or intestate, as the case may be, was at the time of the loan a licensed moneylender, and if the action be commenced by summary summons or special summons, shall also state, in addition to any other particulars:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '9. If the plaintiff sues or the defendant is sued in a representative capacity, the indorsement shall show in manner appearing in such of the forms in [Appendix Part I](https://courts.ie/content/indorsements-pleadings#Weds1), as shall be applicable to the case, or by any other statement to the like effect, in what capacity the plaintiff or defendant sues or is sued. 10. In probate actions the indorsement shall show whether the plaintiff claims as creditor, executor, administrator, residuary legatee, legatee, next-of-kin, heir-at-law, devisee, or in any and what other capacity. 11. In all cases in which the plaintiff, in the first instance, desires to have an account taken, the summons shall be indorsed with the claim that such account be taken. 12. In actions by a moneylender or an assignee or by the personal representative or personal representatives of a deceased moneylender for the recovery of money lent by a moneylender or any interest thereon or the enforcement of any agreement or security relating to any such money or interest, the indorsement on the summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, the fact that the plaintiff is a licensed moneylender, or (in an action by an assignee or by the personal representative or personal representatives of a deceased moneylender) that the original assignor, or the testator or intestate, as the case may be, was at the time of the loan a licensed moneylender, and if the action be commenced by summary summons or special summons, shall also state, in addition to any other particulars: - (a) the date on which the loan was made; - the amount actually lent to the borrower; - the rate per cent. per annum of interest charged; - the date when the contract for repayment was made; - the fact that a note or memorandum of the contract was made, and was signed by the borrower; - the date when a copy of the note or memorandum was delivered or sent to the borrower; - the amount repaid; - the amount due but unpaid;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'What additional information must be included in the special endorsement of claim on a summary summons in actions to recover a debt or liquidated demand in money arising under a hire-purchase agreement?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["That the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Hire-Purchase Act 1946 have been complied with.","That the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Sale of Goods Act 1979 have been complied with.","That the requirements specified in section 2 or section 5 (as the case may be) of the Hire-Purchase Act 1946 have been complied with.","That the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Consumer Credit Act 1974 have been complied with."],"justification":"In actions to recover a debt or liquidated demand in money arising under a hire-purchase agreement or credit-sale agreement (as defined by the Hire-Purchase Act 1946) or any contract of guarantee relating to such an agreement, the special indorsement of claim on a summary summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, that the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Hire-Purchase Act 1946, have been complied with."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the date upon which such unpaid sum or sums became due; - the amount of interest accrued due and unpaid on every such sum. 13. In actions to recover a debt or liquidated demand in money arising under a hire-purchase agreement or credit-sale agreement (as defined by the Hire-Purchase Act 1946) or any contract of guarantee relating to such an agreement, the special indorsement of claim on a summary summons shall state, in addition to any other particulars, that the requirements specified in section 3 or section 4 (as the case may be) of the Hire-Purchase Act 1946, have been complied with. # Indorsement of address** 14.[[9]](#_ftn9) The solicitor of a plaintiff shall indorse upon the summons and notice in lieu of service of a summons, the address and occupation or description of the plaintiff and also his own name or that of his firm and: - the registered place of business where documents may be left for him, and - where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form. 15.[[10]](#_ftn10) A plaintiff suing in person shall indorse upon the summons and notice in lieu of service of a summons his occupation or description and: - an address for service, where documents may be left for him, and - where the plaintiff consents to the receipt of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of an address for service) to which documents may be sent in electronic form. 16. In all cases where proceedings are commenced otherwise than by summons, rules 14 and 15 shall apply to the document by which such proceedings originate as if it were a summons. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 4 rule 1A inserted by 14 of 1989](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1989/en/si/0014.html), effective 1 February 1989. [[2]](#_ftnref2) Order 4 rule 1A substituted by 506 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0506.html), effective 10 August 2005.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 4 - Indorsement of Claim', 'Court Rules', 'What was Order 4 rule 1A substituted by?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["4 of 2016","Order 4 Rule of 2016","9 of 2015","9 of 2016"],"justification":"Order 4 rule 1A substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 4 rule 1A substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 4 rule 1A(3) deleted by 307 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2013/en.si.2013.0307.pdf), effective 26 August 2013. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 4 rule 2 substituted by 248 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0248.html), effective 2 June 2005. [[6]](#_ftnref6) Order 4 rule 3A substituted by 186 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/186/made/en/print), effective 1 June 2017. [[7]](#_ftnref7) Order 4 rule 5(2) substituted by 16 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2014/en.si.2014.0016.pdf), effective 3 February 2014. [[8]](#_ftnref8) Superseded amendment: Order 4 rule amended by 585 of 2001](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2001/en/si/0585.html), effective 1 January 2002. This replaced “**£55**” with “**€70**” and “**£5**” with “**€7**”. This replaced some amounts in pounds in the RSC with convenient euro equivalents. Unless specifically adjusted by 585 of 2001, other references to “**£**” in the RSC were converted to euro at the rate of €1 £0.787564, effective 1 January 2002. [[9]](#_ftnref9) Order 4 rules 14 and 15 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017. [[10]](#_ftnref10) Order 4 rule 15 originally substituted by 307 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2013/en.si.2013.0307.pdf), effective 26 August 2013, but re-substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order related to beginning civil proceedings in the court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order 51 - Filing Complaints For Criminal Matters","Order 78 - Preliminary Hearings For Civil Disputes","Order 39 - Commencing Civil Proceedings Outside The Court","Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court"],"justification":"# Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court - Court: District # Order 40:Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["1- OVERVIEW","1- SPECIFIC","**1- GENERAL**","1- GENERAL REQUIREMENTS"],"justification":"**1- GENERAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1- GENERAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can a claimant do if they have a claim exceeding the Court''s limit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A claimant may abandon the excess by stating it in the claim notice.","A claimant may ignore the excess amount and proceed with the claim as usual without any adjustments.","A claimant may reduce the claim amount to fall within the Court''s limit by settling the excess privately with the defendant.","A claimant may split the claim into two separate claims, one within the Court''s limit and another to be pursued in a different jurisdiction."],"justification":"A claimant who has a claim for more than the amount for which a claim may be made in the Court may abandon the excess by so stating in the claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Claim not to be divided* 2. (1) A claimant must not divide a claim for the purpose of making the claim the subject of two or more claim notices. (2) A claimant who has a claim for more than the amount for which a claim may be made in the Court may abandon the excess by so stating in the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What information must a claim notice contain regarding the claimant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The full name and social security number of the claimant and a mailing address for service of documents on the claimant.","The alias and physical description of the claimant and a legal representative''s contact details for service of documents on the claimant.","The full name and email address of the claimant and a phone number for service of documents on the claimant.","The full name and address of the claimant and an address for service of documents on the claimant."],"justification":"state the full name and address of the claimant and an address for service of documents on the claimant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Names, addresses and representation of parties* 3. (1) A claim notice must— - (a) state the full name and address of the claimant and an address for service of documents on the claimant; and - if the claimant sues in person, state an address for service of documents on the claimant; and - if the claimant sues or the respondent is sued in a representative capacity, state the capacity in which the claimant sues or the respondent is sued in a representative capacity; and - state the name and address of the respondent; and - if the claimant sues by a solicitor, state the name or firm and business address of the solicitor and also, if the solicitor is the agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal. (2) Where a solicitor’s name is given on a claim notice as solicitor for a claimant— - (a) the solicitor must, on request in writing by a respondent, confirm in writing whether the claim notice was filed by or with the authority of the solicitor on behalf of that claimant; and - if the solicitor confirms in writing that the claim notice was not filed by or with the authority of that solicitor, the Court must stay the civil proceedings and no further step may be taken in the civil proceedings without the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How must a civil proceeding be commenced?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By the filing for issue and service of a claim notice.","Through the publication of a notice in a local newspaper.","By the submission of a criminal complaint.","By the issuance of a verbal summons."],"justification":"Subject to the provisions of these Rules which apply to particular categories of claims or cases, a civil proceeding must be commenced by the filing for issue and service of a claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Commencement of civil proceedings* 4. (1) Subject to the provisions of these Rules which apply to particular categories of claims or cases, a civil proceeding must be commenced by the filing for issue and service of a claim notice. (2) Save where otherwise provided by these Rules or by an Act and subject to [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) and the Conventions to which it relates, a claim notice must be filed with and issued by the Clerk for the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or at the election of the claimant, - in proceedings founded on contract, (except proceedings arising from an agreement under the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24) or the [European Communities (Consumer Credit Agreements) Regulations 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/281) (S.I. 281 of 2010)) in which the contract is alleged to have been made, or - in proceedings founded on tort, in which the tort is alleged to have been committed, or - in ejectment proceedings, in which the lands the subject of the proceedings are situated. (3) Filing must be effected by filing with the Clerk assigned to the Court area referred to in sub-rule (2), in person or by post. (4) Unless otherwise provided by law, civil proceedings in the Court must be heard and determined at a sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the civil proceeding was brought. (5)[2] Except in a case to which section 7(6)(a)(ii) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html) applies, a claim notice which has been issued by a Clerk is deemed to have been issued on the date on which it was filed with the Clerk for issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a claim notice take if it is to be served out of the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any standard letter format as long as it reaches the party served.","The form required by Order 42A (service within the State with the permission of the Court) or Order (service within the State without the permission of the Court).","The form required by Order 39 (general order regarding service of documents within the jurisdiction).","The form required by Order 41A (service out of the State with the permission of the Court) or Order (service out of the State without the permission of the Court)."],"justification":"If a claim notice is to be served out of the State, the claim notice must be in the form required by [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) (service out of the State with the permission of the Court) or, as the case may be, Order (service out of the State without the permission of the Court)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Form of claim notice* 5. (1) Unless sub-rule (2) applies, a claim notice must be in , Schedule or in [Form 40.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/95a3c20f-d07f-4dc8-a4dd-ba53f8c3672c/Claim notice - debt claim not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule in a debt claim. (2) If a claim notice is to be served out of the State, the claim notice must be in the form required by [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) (service out of the State with the permission of the Court) or, as the case may be, Order (service out of the State without the permission of the Court). (3) A claim notice must contain a statement of claim. (4) A statement of claim must— - (a) contain, in a summary form, a statement of all material facts on which the claimant relies, but not evidence by which those facts are to be proved; - contain the necessary particulars of every fact; - if the claim arises by or under any enactment, identify the specific provision of the enactment that is relied on; - state specifically the amount or other relief or remedy sought; state the place where and the date when the claim arose. (5) A statement of claim in a debt claim must state that the claim is for debt or liquidated damages, must specify the amount claimed by way of debt or liquidated damages and must include particulars of the claimant’s demand for payment. (6) A statement of claim must be divided into paragraphs numbered consecutively, and each fact or matter stated, so far as practicable, must be contained in a separate paragraph. (7) Where the claim is founded on any written document, the statement of claim must state the date of the document and the parties to the document and: - (a) if the claim is for the payment of money, the amount claimed, or - if the claim is for breach of contract, the alleged breach or breaches of the contract.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a statement of claim contain regarding documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A summary of all personal emails between the parties involved in the dispute, without dates or descriptions.","The names of all witnesses who will testify at the trial, excluding any mention of documents.","A list of all social media posts related to the case, omitting any specific dates or descriptions.","A list of all correspondence and other documents on which the claimant will rely at the trial, including the date and a brief description of each document."],"justification":"A statement of claim must contain a list of all correspondence and other documents on which the claimant will rely at the trial including the date if any and a brief description of each document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A statement of claim must contain a list of all correspondence and other documents on which the claimant will rely at the trial including the date if any and a brief description of each document. (9) Any claim notice in which damages are claimed is assumed to include a claim for interest from the date of judgment, where permitted by law, and for the costs of the civil proceedings, whether or not expressly claimed. (10) Where a claimant alleges that he or she was unable, at the time at which a claim notice was issued, to include in the claim notice any of the information required by this rule to be specified in the claim notice, he or she must include in the claim notice a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the claim notice. The claimant must, when the claim notice is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the respondent pays the amounts claimed within the time limit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The respondent is required to pay additional fees for court costs.","The civil proceeding is automatically escalated to a criminal case.","The civil proceeding continues with increased penalties.","The civil proceeding is concluded."],"justification":"If a claim notice is indorsed in accordance with sub-rule (1), and the respondent pays the amounts claimed within the time limited for filing and serving an appearance and defence, then the civil proceeding is concluded."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Costs to be specified* 6. (1) In a debt claim, the claim notice must be indorsed with a statement as follows— "If you pay the amount of €...... and costs of €....... to the claimant or the claimant''s solicitor within ten days and without filing and serving an appearance and defence you may avoid further costs.". (2) The amount of costs in the indorsement must be the appropriate amount set out in the Schedule of Costs. (3) If a claim notice is indorsed in accordance with sub-rule (1), and the respondent pays the amounts claimed within the time limited for filing and serving an appearance and defence, then the civil proceeding is concluded. (4) The claimant must notify the Clerk in writing when civil proceedings are concluded in accordance with sub-rule (3).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the consent take when civil proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the 1924 Act are brought before the District Court and the amount claimed exceeds €15,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The consent must be in Form 40.03, Schedule","The consent must be in Form 40.04, Schedule","The consent must be in Form 40.01, Schedule A.","The consent must be in Form 40.02, Schedule"],"justification":"the consent must be in the [Form 40.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d66c6fe2-a616-46f0-82d7-752450a2eed5/Consent No. 40.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Consent proceedings* 7. (1) Where civil proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the [1924 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/10/enacted/en/html) are brought before the District Court and the amount claimed in such proceedings is in excess of €15,000 and, pursuant to the proviso (inserted by section of the 1991 Act) to paragraph A of section 77, the necessary parties to the proceedings sign a form of consent either before or at any time during the hearing, the consent must be in the [Form 40.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d66c6fe2-a616-46f0-82d7-752450a2eed5/Consent No. 40.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) When completed, the consent must be attached to and filed together with the original claim notice or other originating document or, as appropriate, must be produced to the Court during the hearing. (3) Every consent so filed or produced must be retained by the Clerk with the original claim notice or other originating document and must be noted on the court record and on any order issued in relation to the civil proceedings. (4) Costs, where allowed in any such civil proceedings, must be in accordance with the relevant provisions of the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the claimant do within 14 days of the perfection of the order for remittal or transfer?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Submit a written affidavit confirming receipt of the order for remittal or transfer to the court within 14 days.","Notify the opposing party of the order for remittal or transfer via registered mail.","File with the Clerk a certified copy of the order and the summons, civil bill or other originating document (or a copy thereof) and copies of all documents already delivered and orders made in the proceedings.","Serve the opposing party with a notice of appearance and a request for discovery within 14 days."],"justification":"the claimant must, within 14 days from the date of perfection of the order for remittal or transfer, file with the Clerk a certified copy of the order and the summons, civil bill or other originating document (or a copy thereof) and copies of all documents already delivered and orders made in the proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Proceedings transferred from the High Court or Circuit Court* 8. (1) Where civil proceedings are remitted or transferred to the District Court by the High Court under section 25 of the [1924 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/10/enacted/en/html) or by the Circuit Court under section 15 of the [1991 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/20/enacted/en/html), the claimant must, within 14 days from the date of perfection of the order for remittal or transfer, file with the Clerk a certified copy of the order and the summons, civil bill or other originating document (or a copy thereof) and copies of all documents already delivered and orders made in the proceedings. (2) Where the claimant omits or refuses to file the documents within the 14 day period mentioned in sub-rule (1), the respondent must do so as soon as may be after the expiration of the 14 day period. (3) The party filing the documents must give notice to every other party to the proceedings of such filing. (4) After filing of the order and documents, the civil proceedings must continue as if they had been commenced in the Court and any respondent who has not served a defence and filed an appearance must do so within the 21 days of service of the notice referred to in sub-rule (3). (5) The civil proceedings must be heard and determined by the Court as if they had originally been commenced in the Court. (6) A note of the remittal or transfer must be entered on the court record and on any order issued in relation to the proceedings. (7) Costs, where allowed in any such civil proceedings, must be in accordance with the provisions of the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How must a claim by a consumer for damages under section 74 of the Consumer Protection Act 2007 be commenced?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By sending a formal letter of intent to sue the seller or manufacturer via registered mail.","By posting a public notice of the claim on a prominent social media platform and tagging the relevant parties.","By filing a complaint with the local consumer protection agency within 30 days of the purchase.","By issuing and serving a claim notice in accordance with this Order, entitled in the matter of section 74 of the Consumer Protection Act 2007 and otherwise in Form 40.01, Schedule with appropriate modifications."],"justification":"Any claim by a consumer for damages under section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) (No. 19 of 2007) must be commenced by the issue and service in accordance with this Order of a claim notice, entitled in the matter of section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) and otherwise in the [Form 40.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1) with such modifications as are appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Proceedings under section 74 of the Consumer Protection Act 2007* 9. (1) Any claim by a consumer for damages under section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) (No. 19 of 2007) must be commenced by the issue and service in accordance with this Order of a claim notice, entitled in the matter of section 74 of the [Consumer Protection Act 2007](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/act/19) and otherwise in the [Form 40.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1) with such modifications as are appropriate. (2) Any consent under section 74(4) of the Consumer Protection Act 2007 must be in the [Form 40.03, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d66c6fe2-a616-46f0-82d7-752450a2eed5/Consent No. 40.03.docx/docx/1) but, instead of reciting that it is given under section 77A of The Courts of Justice Act 1924, must recite that it is given under section 74(4) of the Consumer Protection Act 2007, and must be lodged with the Clerk either before or at any time during the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How long is a claim notice valid for service after it is filed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Nine months","One year","Two years","Six months"],"justification":"A claim notice is valid for service for one year after the day it is filed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Duration* 10.[3] (1) A claim notice is valid for service for one year after the day it is filed. (2) If a claim notice has not been served on a respondent, the Court may extend the validity of the claim notice for three months from the day of the order. (3) An order may be made under sub-rule (2) before or after expiry of the claim notice. (4) The Court may on an application made under sub-rule (2) before the expiry of the claim notice make an order extending the validity of the claim notice if it is satisfied that reasonable efforts have been made to serve the respondent, or for other good reason. (5) The Court may on an application made under sub-rule (2) after the expiry of the claim notice make an order extending the validity of the claim notice if it is satisfied that there are special circumstances which justify an extension, such circumstances to be stated in the order. (6) The claimant may apply under sub-rule (2) without notice to the respondent, but if the Court considers that the respondent ought to be heard, the Court may adjourn the further hearing and direct the claimant to give written notice to the respondent of the place and time to which the application was adjourned. (7) If a witness summons has not been served on a witness, the Court may from time to time extend the validity of the witness summons for such period from the day of the order as the Court directs, not being more than six months from that day. (8) An order may be made under sub-rule (7) before or after expiry of the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40 - Beginning Civil Proceedings In The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''data protection action'' mean in this rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It signifies the annual audit of data protection compliance conducted as per section 123 of the Data Protection Act 2018","It refers to the process of deleting personal data after a set period as defined in section 135 of the Data Protection Act 2018","It has the meaning assigned to it by section 117 of the Data Protection Act 2018","It means the encryption methods used to protect data from unauthorized access as detailed in section 97 of the Data Protection Act 2018"],"justification":"“**data protection action**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 117 of the 2018 Act;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Data Protection Actions* 11[4].(1) In this rule: the “**2018 Act**” means the [Data Protection Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/7/enacted/en/html) (No. 7 of 2018); “**data protection action**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 117 of the 2018 Act; “**GDPR**” means [Regulation 2016/679](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/679/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 27 April 2016 on the protection of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data and on the free movement of such data, and repealing Directive (General Data Protection Regulation); each of the expressions “**controller**”, “**data subject**” and “**processor**” has the same meaning as in the GDPR or the 2018 Act as the context requires. (2) A data protection action must be brought in the court area in which— - (a) the controller or processor against whom the data protection action is taken has an establishment, or - the data subject has his or her habitual residence. (3) Where a data protection action is brought on behalf of a data subject by a not-for-profit body, organisation or association to which section 117(7) of the 2018 Act applies that has been mandated by the data subject to do so, the claim notice must: - include a statement to that effect, and - confirm that the claimant satisfies each relevant requirement of Article 80 of the GDPR, and must otherwise be in the Form [40.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such further modifications as are appropriate. (4) The Court may, of its own motion or on the application of another party to a data protection action, direct the provision to it of such additional information as is necessary in order to confirm that the claimant is such a body, organisation or association.” [1] Order 40 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 40 sub-rule (5) of rule 4 substituted by [S.I. 513 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/513/made/en/print?q 513&years 2016), effective 8 November 2016 [3] Order 40 rule 10 substituted by [S.I. 423 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/423/made/en/print?q 423&years 2019), effective 2 September 2019 [4] Order 40 rule 11 inserted by 13 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/13/made/en/print#:~:text Minister for Justice.&text 1.,the time being in force.), effective 20 January 2024.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 40A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme Court","District","Session Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings - Court: District # Order 40A:Personal Injuries Proceedings[****1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["DEFINITIONS","EXAMPLES","HISTORICAL BACKGROUND","INTRODUCTION"],"justification":"DEFINITIONS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - DEFINITIONS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Civil Disputes Resolution under the 2004 Act","Personal Injuries Proceedings under the 2004 Act","Criminal Proceedings under the 2004 Act","Personal Injuries Proceedings under the 1998 Act"],"justification":"2 - PERSONAL INJURIES PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE 2004 ACT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - PERSONAL INJURIES PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE 2004 ACT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done to institute proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Proceedings must be initiated by sending a formal letter to the Attorney General requesting an investigation and subsequent legal action.","Proceedings must be instituted by filing a complaint with the local Garda station rather than through the court system.","Proceedings must be instituted by filing an originating document called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons with the Clerk assigned to the Court area where the respondent has their principal office or where the malicious incident is alleged to have occurred.","Proceedings must be started by registering a case online on the court’s official website and paying a registration fee."],"justification":"proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by filing an originating document, to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons, with the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent has his or her principal office, or - at the election of the claimant, in which any malicious incident alleged in the Garda compensation personal injuries summons is alleged to have occurred, and by the issuing of that Garda compensation personal injuries summons by the Clerk concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Venue* 3.(1) Save where otherwise provided by these Rules or by an Act and subject to [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) and the Conventions to which it relates, a personal injuries summons must be filed with and issued by the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - at the election of the claimant, in which any tort alleged in the personal injuries summons is alleged to have been committed. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by filing an originating document, to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons, with the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent has his or her principal office, or - at the election of the claimant, in which any malicious incident alleged in the Garda compensation personal injuries summons is alleged to have occurred, and by the issuing of that Garda compensation personal injuries summons by the Clerk concerned. (2) Unless otherwise provided by law, personal injuries proceedings in the Court must be heard and determined at a sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the personal injuries proceedings were brought. (3) Except in a case to which section 7(6)(a)(ii) of the Courts Act 1964 applies, a personal injuries summons which has been issued by a Clerk is deemed to have been issued on the date on which it was filed with the Clerk for issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What form number is used for personal injuries proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form No. 41A.09","Form No. 40A.09","Form No.","Form No."],"justification":"personal injuries proceedings in the Court which are proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the [Form No. 40A.09](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a201467f-8689-419e-897b-ba29c9f98fb3/Garda compensation personal injuries summons - Garda Síochána Compensation Act 2022 - No 40A.09.docx/doc/1), Schedule to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form of personal injuries summons and Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 4.(1) Personal injuries proceedings in the Court must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the Form No. [40A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/940afe85-406e-40fc-8b09-0cc375ed14cf/Personal injuries summons No. 40A.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), personal injuries proceedings in the Court which are proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act must be instituted by the issue for service on each respondent of a personal injuries summons in the [Form No. 40A.09](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a201467f-8689-419e-897b-ba29c9f98fb3/Garda compensation personal injuries summons - Garda Síochána Compensation Act 2022 - No 40A.09.docx/doc/1), Schedule to be called a Garda compensation personal injuries summons. (3) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, the provisions of these Rules which apply to a claim notice apply, with appropriate modifications, to a personal injuries summons and to Garda compensation personal injuries summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must be included in a personal injuries summons for proceedings requiring authorisation under specific sections of the 2003 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A statement confirming authorisation by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, specifying the relevant section or rule, and citing the date and reference number of the authorisation.","A statement confirming authorisation by any court, specifying the relevant section or rule, and citing the date and reference number of the authorisation.","A statement confirming authorisation by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, but without specifying the relevant section or rule, and including the date and reference number of the authorisation.","A statement confirming authorisation by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, specifying the relevant section or rule, but omitting the date and reference number of the authorisation."],"justification":"confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, specifying the section of the 2003 Act or the rule made under section 46(3) of the 2003 Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Content of personal injuries summons* 5.(1) A personal injuries summons must specify: - the claimant’s name, the address at which he or she ordinarily resides and his or her occupation; - the claimant’s Personal Public Service Number (and where a claimant has not been issued with a PPSN, this must be stated in the personal injuries summons); - (iii) the respondent’s name, the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (if known to the claimant) and the respondent’s occupation (if known to the claimant). (2) In any proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the 2003 Act, the personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons must contain a statement: - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, - specifying the section of the 2003 Act or the rule made under section 46(3) of the 2003 Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must a Garda compensation personal injuries summons include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A summary of the Garda''s duties and responsibilities during the incident without including the specifics of the injuries or death.","A brief mention of the injuries or death and a general description of the malicious incident without specific details.","Full and detailed particulars of the injuries or death, the malicious incident, and applicability of section of the 2022 Act if applicable, along with a schedule of all items of special damage claimed.","A list of witnesses'' names and contact information without any details about the injuries or the malicious incident."],"justification":"A Garda compensation personal injuries summons must: - (a) set out full and detailed particulars of-: - the injuries or death alleged to have been occasioned by the malicious incident concerned; - the malicious incident, and - (iii) in the case of proceedings brought by one or more persons to whom section of the 2022 Act refers, the applicability of that section to each person by whom or for whose benefit the proceedings are brought, and. - contain a schedule of full particulars of all items of special damage in respect of which the claimant is making a claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Particulars of claim in personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 6. (1) A personal injuries summons must: - (a) set out full and detailed particulars of- - the nature of the claim and of each allegation, assertion or plea comprising that claim; - the injuries to the claimant alleged to have been occasioned by the wrong of the respondent; - (iii) the acts of the respondent constituting the wrong and the circumstances relating to the commission of the wrong; - each instance of negligence by the respondent, and - contain a schedule of full particulars of all items of special damage in respect of which the claimant is making a claim. (2) A Garda compensation personal injuries summons must: - (a) set out full and detailed particulars of-: - the injuries or death alleged to have been occasioned by the malicious incident concerned; - the malicious incident, and - (iii) in the case of proceedings brought by one or more persons to whom section of the 2022 Act refers, the applicability of that section to each person by whom or for whose benefit the proceedings are brought, and. - contain a schedule of full particulars of all items of special damage in respect of which the claimant is making a claim. (3) Where a claimant who has not served the notice required by section 8(1) of the 2004 Act within the time prescribed for service of that notice alleges that there was a reasonable cause for failing to do so within that time, the personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summon must include details of the cause of that failure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'When must a claimant provide and verify the missing information after issuing a summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When the defendant responds to the summons.","When the claimant files the initial lawsuit.","After the court renders its final decision on the case.","When the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter, whether by amendment or otherwise."],"justification":"The claimant must, when the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide and verify such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where a claimant alleges that he or she was unable, at the time at which a personal injuries summons Garda compensation personal injuries summon was issued, to include in the summons any of the information required by this rule to be specified therein, he or she must include in the summons a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the summons. The claimant must, when the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide and verify such of the information required by this rule as was not included in the summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a counterclaim be in if a respondent makes one in personal injuries proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 40A.02","Form","Form [40A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab6c0721-b772-42f9-af8f-64a7c1de36eb/Personal injuries counterclaim No. 40A.03.docx/docx/1)","Form"],"justification":"Where any respondent makes a counterclaim, the counterclaim must be in the Form [40A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab6c0721-b772-42f9-af8f-64a7c1de36eb/Personal injuries counterclaim No. 40A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be appended to the defence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Form of personal injuries defence* 7.(1) Each respondent who intends to defend personal injuries proceedings must deliver to the claimant (or his solicitor) an appearance and defence in the Form [40A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/816a97df-5fe3-41bd-9871-ad64dbe48558/Personal injuries defence No. 40A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule and file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk within 28 days after the service on him or her of the personal injuries summons. (2) Where any respondent makes a counterclaim, the counterclaim must be in the Form [40A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ab6c0721-b772-42f9-af8f-64a7c1de36eb/Personal injuries counterclaim No. 40A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be appended to the defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What type of application must be made for an extension of the period within which any document may be served or thing may be done?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An informal email to the judge requesting an extension of time for service or completion of actions","An application under section 9(2) of the 2004 Act (in the absence of agreement between or among the parties)","An application under section 10(3) of the 2004 Act (regardless of whether there is agreement between the parties)","A verbal request to the court clerk (without the need for any formal documentation under the 2004 Act)"],"justification":"an application under section 9(2) of the 2004 Act (in the absence of agreement between or among the parties) for the extension of the period provided for in this Order or otherwise in these Rules, within which any document may be served or thing may be done"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Applications by notice of motion in personal injuries proceedings* 9.(1) The following applications in personal injuries proceedings must be made by application to the Court by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties. The notice of motion must be in the Form [40A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b48ee3d-2e7c-4a96-9208-96acdcf26ccb/Notice of motion (personal injuries action) No. 40A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be supported by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application under section 9(2) of the 2004 Act (in the absence of agreement between or among the parties) for the extension of the period provided for in this Order or otherwise in these Rules, within which any document may be served or thing may be done; - an application by a respondent under section 10(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay or dismissal of proceedings by reason of a claimant’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 10 of the 2004 Act; - (iii) an application by a respondent under section 11(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay or dismissal of proceedings by reason of a claimant’s failure to provide further information requested under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the 2004 Act; - an application by a claimant under section 12(3) of the 2004 Act for a stay of proceedings or for judgment by reason of a respondent’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 12 of the 2004 Act; - an application by a party for a direction of the Court under section 15 of the 2004 Act that a mediation hearing be held; - an application to the Court to order delivery by the opposing party of further and better particulars of any pleading delivered by that opposing party; - (vii) an application by a party wishing to have evidence given by affidavit, under section 19 of the 2004 Act;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'When must copies of the notices be filed with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["As soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period.","At the end of the fiscal year following the expiry of the prescribed period.","Before the expiry of the prescribed period.","Within one month after the expiry of the prescribed period."],"justification":"Copies of the notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be filed by being delivered, together with an affidavit or statutory declaration of service of the notice on the opposing party, to the Clerk as soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period referred to in section 17(3) of the 2004 Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Offer of settlement* 11.(1) Copies of the claimant’s notice of an offer of terms of settlement required by section 17(1) of the 2004 Act and of the respondent’s notice required by section 17(2) of the 2004 Act must be filed in Court. (2) Copies of the notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be filed by being delivered, together with an affidavit or statutory declaration of service of the notice on the opposing party, to the Clerk as soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period referred to in section 17(3) of the 2004 Act. (3) The notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must be in the Form [40A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cc9350a5-acea-4ab4-8aaa-e6830d61a3bf/Notice as to terms No. 40A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4) The notices referred to in sub-rule (1) must not be given or produced to the Judge before the determination of the personal injuries proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What can a Judge do during a pre-trial hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Determine the guilt or innocence of the defendant based on preliminary evidence.","Decide the final verdict of the case before it goes to trial.","Give such directions and make such orders as he or she considers necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the proceedings are in dispute.","Appoint new jurors if any of the existing ones are found to be biased or disqualified."],"justification":"A Judge presiding over a pre-trial hearing may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as he or she considers necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the proceedings are in dispute."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Pre-trial hearing* 12.(1) A pre-trial hearing as provided for in section 18 of the 2004 Act must be held in personal injuries proceedings where the Court, on the application by motion on notice to the opposing party or parties by the party wishing to apply for a pre-trial hearing, considers that a pre-trial hearing is appropriate. (2) A Judge presiding over a pre-trial hearing may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as he or she considers necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the proceedings are in dispute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Implementations Under The 2005 Act","Applications Under The 1998 Act","Provisions Under The 2003 Act","Applications Under The 2003 Act"],"justification":"3 - APPLICATIONS UNDER THE 2003 ACT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - APPLICATIONS UNDER THE 2003 ACT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an application for approval of an assessment be made in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 40A.08, Schedule","Form Schedule","Form 40A.07, Schedule","Form [40A.07], Schedule"],"justification":"An application for the approval by the Court of an assessment under section 35(2) of the 2003 Act must be made by notice of motion in the Form [40A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1cb50a26-3393-4963-ad8c-22bce14cf860/Notice of application for approval of Injuries Board assessment No. 40A.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Application for approval of an assessment* 13. (1) An application for the approval by the Court of an assessment under section 35(2) of the 2003 Act must be made by notice of motion in the Form [40A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1cb50a26-3393-4963-ad8c-22bce14cf860/Notice of application for approval of Injuries Board assessment No. 40A.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The notice of motion must be filed with and issued by the Clerk assigned to the Court area: - (a) in which the respondent or one of the respondents ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - at the election of the applicant, in which any tort to which the relevant claim mentioned in section 35 of the 2003 Act relates is alleged to have been committed (3) The notice of motion must be supported by an affidavit entitled “IN THE MATTER OF THE PERSONAL INJURIES ASSESSMENT BOARD ACT 2003 and IN THE MATTER OF AN APPLICATION RELATING TO A.B., A [WARD, CHILD OR PERSON WHO IS THE SUBJECT OF A DECISION-MAKING REPRESENTATION ORDER], OF [ADDRESS] BY C.D., ACTING AS [STATE CAPACITY] ON BEHALF OF THE SAID A.B.” (4) The notice of motion must be addressed to the respondent by name and must be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the return date. (5) The notice of motion must be served - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (or in the case of a company, its registered office) or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished by the respondent, at that address, or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides (or in the case of a company, its registered office) or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Personal Injuries Assessment Board must send a copy of the order to pay to the judge overseeing the case via secure email.","The Personal Injuries Assessment Board must send a copy of the order to pay to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or in electronic form.","The Personal Injuries Assessment Board must send a copy of the order to pay directly to the defendant by registered post.","The Personal Injuries Assessment Board must send a copy of the order to pay to the parties involved in the case by hand delivery."],"justification":"If an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy of the order to pay must be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or in electronic form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) When considering an application concerning such an assessment the Court may appoint a person of full age to act as guardian litem of the child. (7) Where applicable, the provisions of [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment), rule 7 (concerning lodgments) apply mutatis mutandis to assessments made in favour of children, wards or persons the subjects of Decision-Making Representation Orders which are approved in accordance with this rule in respect of the amount recoverable in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act. (8) The Clerk must send by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail to the Personal Injuries Assessment Board a certified copy of any order made pursuant to this rule. (9) If an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy of the order to pay must be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or in electronic form. (10) If an order to pay issues in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, the Court may direct investment in accordance with [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), rule 12.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40A - Personal Injuries Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the return date must notice of the application be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Seven days","Five days","Three days","Ten days"],"justification":"Notice of the application must be served by the applicant not later than seven days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Application to Court by assessors* 14.(1) An application by an assessor for an order under section 27(2) of the 2003 Act must be made at a sitting of the District Court in the Court area within which the person against whom the order concerned is sought resides or carries on business. (2) Such an application must be by notice of application in the Form [40A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ebc937f0-fe1e-4b15-9e27-cfb59be03be5/Notice of application by assessors No. 40A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be addressed to the respondent by name. (3) Notice of the application must be served by the applicant not later than seven days before the return date. The notice must be served: - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, at that address; or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address. [1] Order 40A originally inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014; substituted in entirety by 231 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/231/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,Compensation) Act 2022) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of May, 2024.), effective 31 May 2024. [2] Order 40A Rule 10 subsection (4) inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018 Superseded amendments: Order 40A sub-rule (1) of rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 599 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/599/made/en/print?q 599&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014 Order 40A sub-rule (3) of rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 513 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/513/made/en/print?q 513&years 2016), effective 8 November 2016 Order 40A sub-rule (2) of rule 5 substituted by [S.I. 102 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/102/made/en/print?q 102&years 2017), effective 24 April 2017 Order 40A rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 327 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/327/made/en/print?q 327&years 2019), effective 1 August 2019 Order 40A sub-rule (4) of rule 10 inserted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 2 January 2018 Order 40A sub-rule (2) of rule 13 substituted by [S.I. 599 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/599/made/en/print?q 599&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) : - Court: District # *Order 40B:*Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) *[1]*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''1860 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Landlord and Tenant Law Amendment Act Ireland 1860","The Marriage Act Scotland 1860","The Education Act Ireland 1860","The Agricultural Reform Act England 1860"],"justification":"the “**1860 Act”** means the [Landlord and Tenant Law Amendment Act Ireland 1860](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1860/act/154/enacted/en/print.html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— the “**1860 Act”** means the [Landlord and Tenant Law Amendment Act Ireland 1860](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1860/act/154/enacted/en/print.html); any reference in an enactment to “**ejectment**” must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to recovery of the possession of premises by a landlord or other person claiming to be entitled to possession of premises; “**landlord and tenant claim notice**” means a claim notice beginning landlord and tenant proceedings in the District Court in accordance with these Rules, and any reference in an enactment to an ejectment civil summons must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to a landlord and tenant claim notice; “**landlord and tenant proceedings**” means any civil proceedings which may be brought in the District Court between a landlord and a tenant, and any reference in an enactment to proceedings for ejectment or for the recovery of possession of premises in the District Court must, for the purposes of this Order, be taken to include a reference to landlord and tenant proceedings; any reference to an “**order**” must, for the purposes of this Order, unless the context otherwise requires, be taken to include a reference to a judgment, decree or dismiss.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What are the requirements of this Order in relation to Order 40?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No additional requirements, only those of Order 40 apply.","Additional to the requirements of Order 40 as regards claim notices","Requirements that replace those of Order 40 entirely.","The requirements of Order 40 are reduced by this Order."],"justification":"The requirements of this Order are additional to the requirements of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) as regards claim notices."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Requirements of this Order additional to Order 40* 2. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to landlord and tenant proceedings in the Court. (2) The requirements of this Order are additional to the requirements of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) as regards claim notices.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What must a landlord and tenant claim notice specify regarding the tenancy?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The nature of the tenancy and whether it is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register.","The color of the walls and whether the property has air conditioning.","The duration of the lease and whether the property is furnished or unfurnished.","The monthly rent amount and the preferred breed of pets allowed."],"justification":"specify the nature of the tenancy and state whether the tenancy is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register maintained under section 127 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and where the tenancy is required to be so registered, either give particulars of registration or confirm that it is not so registered;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional particulars required in landlord and tenant claim notice* 3. (1) A landlord and tenant claim notice must: - (a) specify the names of the landlord and the tenant; - specify the nature of the tenancy and state whether the tenancy is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register maintained under section 127 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and where the tenancy is required to be so registered, either give particulars of registration or confirm that it is not so registered; - contain a description of the premises to which the claim relates, including the full address and any other details necessary to establish the Court area in which the premises are situated; - specify the rent under the tenancy; - where it is part of the claim that the tenancy has determined, the facts of the determination of the tenancy and the means by which it was determined; - where non-payment of rent is part of the claim, specify the amount of rent due after all fair and just allowances, and the date up to which that rent was due; - explain why the claimant is not precluded from bringing civil proceedings in the Court in respect of the tenancy by section 182 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html); - set out the appropriate costs in the Schedule of Costs payable if the claimant’s claim is settled before appearance and defence. (2) A claim notice claiming for the recovery of possession of premises from a tenant at will, a permissive occupant, or a caretaker or servant must also: - (a) state that a demand for possession was made by or on behalf of the owner of the premises; - specify the date of the demand for possession; - confirm the respondent’s refusal or omission to quit and deliver up possession. (3) The Court may stay proceedings in respect of any tenancy which is required to be registered in the private residential tenancies register maintained under section 127 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) but is not so registered.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a claim notice take when seeking recovery of possession from a tenant at will?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It should follow the guidelines outlined in Form Schedule","It must be in accordance with Form Schedule","It needs to adhere to the requirements set forth in Form Schedule","It must be submitted via Form Schedule A."],"justification":"recovery of possession of premises from a tenant at will, a permissive occupant, a caretaker or a servant or,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Form of claim notice* 4. A claim notice in a claim for: - (a) recovery of possession of premises for overholding, - recovery of possession of premises from a tenant at will, a permissive occupant, a caretaker or a servant or, - recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent must be in accordance with [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e0dcf0a-82cc-49e3-8416-3760171832de/Landlord and tenant claim notice, recovery of possession of premises No. 40B.01.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Who must a landlord and tenant claim notice be served on?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The local housing authority, not the individuals residing on the premises.","Any individual who has signed a lease agreement with the landlord, regardless of their current presence on the premises.","Every person in actual possession of the premises specified in the claim notice, whether as tenant, sub-tenant, or otherwise.","Only the primary tenant, excluding any sub-tenants or other occupants."],"justification":"A landlord and tenant claim notice must be served on every person in actual possession of the premises specified in the claim notice, whether as tenant, sub-tenant, or otherwise."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Service of claim notice* 5. (1) A landlord and tenant claim notice must be served on every person in actual possession of the premises specified in the claim notice, whether as tenant, sub-tenant, or otherwise. (2) The claim notice must be served in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (3) Where the immediate tenant of the claimant in landlord and tenant proceedings is not in actual possession of the premises, the claim notice must be served on that immediate tenant in addition to any person on whom service is required under sub-rule (1). (4) Where no person is in actual possession of the premises, a copy of the claim notice must be affixed to the door or some other conspicuous part of the premises claimed. In such a case, the affixing of a copy of the claim notice must be taken to be sufficient service of the claim notice. (5) Where the person who was last in actual possession of the premises was a sub-tenant, and no person is in actual possession, the claim notice must also be served on the immediate tenant of the claimant, as provided by sub-rule (3).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have when making an order for recovery of possession of premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court can only grant a stay of execution if the occupier agrees to leave voluntarily within 24 hours.","The Court must immediately evict the occupier without granting any stay of execution.","The Court has no authority to make orders for recovery of possession of premises.","The Court may grant a stay of execution on such conditions as it thinks reasonable in the circumstances."],"justification":"the Court may grant a stay of execution on such conditions as it thinks reasonable in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Stay of execution* 7. On making an order on foot of any landlord and tenant claim notice claiming recovery of possession of premises, the Court may grant a stay of execution on such conditions as it thinks reasonable in the circumstances.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'What must the respondent or any person with a specific interest in the contract of tenancy pay or tender to the claimant before an order for recovery of possession for non-payment of rent is executed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A lump sum payment equivalent to six months'' rent, irrespective of the actual arrears and claimant’s costs.","Only the most recent month''s rent and no additional costs, as long as it covers the claimant’s immediate financial needs.","All rent and arrears of rent due at the time of the execution of the eviction order, and a sum sufficient to cover the respondent''s legal fees.","All rent and arrears of rent due at the time of the service of the claim notice, and a sum sufficient to cover the claimant’s costs."],"justification":"all rent and arrears of rent due at the time of the service of the claim notice, and a sum sufficient to cover the claimant’s costs, or may tender those amounts to the claimant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Payment or tender in claims for recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent* 8. (1) At any time before an order on a claim for recovery of possession of premises for non-payment of rent has been delivered to the County Registrar or Sheriff for execution, the respondent or any person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy may pay to the claimant: - (a) all rent and arrears of rent due at the time of the service of the claim notice, and - a sum sufficient to cover the claimant’s costs, or may tender those amounts to the claimant. (2) If tender of the amounts mentioned in sub-rule (1) is refused, the respondent or other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy may deposit those amounts with the Clerk. (3) The Clerk must give a receipt for any amounts deposited under sub-rule (2) and give notice to the claimant of receipt of the amounts deposited. (4) In such a case, the Court may order that all further proceedings be stayed on payment to the claimant of the money deposited, and such further amount, if any, for costs up to the date of tender as the Court thinks reasonable. (5) A decision of the Court under sub-rule (4) is subject to appeal as if it were a final order on foot of a claim notice in ejectment for non-payment of rent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the Court award a writ of restitution?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When a property owner seeks to evict a tenant for minor disturbances that do not affect the rental conditions.","When a tenant requests it due to a landlord''s breach of the lease agreement.","When an order for possession for non-payment of rent has been executed, the Court may award a writ of restitution on the application of the respondent or any other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy.","When a landlord applies for it after the expiration of the lease term without renewal."],"justification":"When an order for possession for non-payment of rent has been executed, the Court may award a writ of restitution on the application of the respondent or any other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Writ of restitution* 9. (1) When an order for possession for non-payment of rent has been executed, the Court may award a writ of restitution on the application of the respondent or any other person having a specific interest in the contract of tenancy. (2) A writ of restitution may be awarded in accordance with sub-rule (1) on the payment to the claimant or the deposit with the Clerk of the amount due for rent, arrears of rent and costs within six months after the execution of the judgment, as provided by sections 70 and 71 of the 1860 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40B - Landlord And Tenant Proceedings (Ejectment) :', 'Court Rules', 'When can a warrant for possession be issued under section 86 of the 1860 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Immediately after the date of the order, without any time limit.","At any time not exceeding six months after the date of the order.","At any time more than one year after the date of the order.","Within one year after the date of the order."],"justification":"A warrant for possession under section 86 of the 1860 Act may be issued at any time not exceeding six months after the date of the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Warrant for possession* 10. (1) A warrant for possession under section 86 of the 1860 Act may be issued at any time not exceeding six months after the date of the order. (2) After the expiration of six months from the date of the order a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant by motion on notice to the respondent. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme Court","High Court","District Court","Family Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application - Court: District # Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''relevant application'' in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A submission made by a legal entity to the Court to challenge the validity of a decision or determination made by a relevant authority.","An application to the Court under an enactment by any individual to request voluntary compliance with a decision of a relevant authority.","An application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by law to direct, require, or compel a person to take steps or do things, or enforce decisions/determinations/orders of a relevant authority.","A petition filed by a citizen to seek compensation for damages caused by a relevant authority''s decision or order."],"justification":"“**relevant application**” means any of the following applications– - (a) an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court for an order directing, requiring or compelling a person to take any step or do any thing (including, without limitation, to provide information or to produce a document or thing) or prohibiting or restraining a person from, or directing a person to cease or refrain from, taking a step or doing a thing (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “**direction application**”), - an application to the Court by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court, for an order of the Court directing, requiring or compelling a person to perform, comply with, carry out or implement, or for the enforcement of, a decision, determination, notice or order of a relevant authority (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as an “**enforcement application**”)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. (1) In this Order - “**relevant authority**” means any agency, board, authority, commission, council, ombudsman, tribunal, or other body (not including a company formed under the Companies Acts) established by or under an enactment, which is authorised by an enactment: - (a) to exercise powers under an enactment to determine or decide, any complaint or issue, or - to issue any notice or order addressed to a person requiring the taking or ceasing of any action, and includes, where the context so requires, any committee, officer or member of the staff of such a body who has been authorised by an enactment or by such a body to exercise those powers; “**relevant application**” means any of the following applications– - (a) an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court for an order directing, requiring or compelling a person to take any step or do any thing (including, without limitation, to provide information or to produce a document or thing) or prohibiting or restraining a person from, or directing a person to cease or refrain from, taking a step or doing a thing (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “**direction application**”), - an application to the Court by a person authorised by law to apply to the Court, for an order of the Court directing, requiring or compelling a person to perform, comply with, carry out or implement, or for the enforcement of, a decision, determination, notice or order of a relevant authority (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as an “**enforcement application**”) but does not include: - any application for the issue by the Court or the Clerk of any order for execution of any such decision, determination, recommendation, or settlement which an enactment provides may be enforced or executed as, or in the like manner to, a judgment of the Court; or - any application for the issue of a summons; or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'What type of application is referred to as a ''licence application''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An application for any licence, certificate, authority or permission or for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding or restriction on holding any licence, certificate, authority or permission.","An application for registering a business trademark or brand name.","A request for employment verification or work authorization documents.","An application for obtaining a loan or financial credit from a bank."],"justification":"an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by that enactment to apply to the Court, for any licence, certificate, authority or permission or, as the case may be, for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding or restriction on holding any licence, certificate, authority or permission (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a \\\"licence application\\\")"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) any claim for damages (which must be commenced by claim notice); - except where a particular procedure for such an application is specified in another Order of these Rules, an application to the Court under an enactment by a person authorised by that enactment to apply to the Court, for any licence, certificate, authority or permission or, as the case may be, for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding or restriction on holding any licence, certificate, authority or permission (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as a “licence application”), - except where a particular procedure for such an application is specified in another Order of these Rules, any other application to the Court for relief under an enactment (other than relief by way of damages, liquidated or unliquidated) which is, required, authorised or permitted by these Rules to be brought or made in accordance with this Order. (2) Where an enactment provides for or permits a relevant application to be made to the Court or to a Judge and no other provision is made for the applicable procedure either by the enactment concerned or by these Rules, the procedure set out in the following rules applies. (3) Sub-rule (2) is subject to any requirement of the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'Where must a licence application be brought if it is not for the purpose of a trade, profession or business?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["To the nearest police station where the activity permitted by the licence, certificate, authority or permission is intended to be conducted.","To the municipal office where the applicant resides.","In the Court area where the activity permitted by the licence, certificate, authority or permission is intended to be conducted.","To the provincial department of licensing regardless of the location of the intended activity."],"justification":"in the Court area where the activity permitted by the licence, certificate, authority or permission is intended to be conducted;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Venue for relevant application* 2. (1) A relevant application must be brought: - (a) in the case of a direction application or an enforcement application, in the Court area where the person or one of the persons against whom an order or other relief is sought resides or carries on any trade, profession or business; - in the case of a licence application: - in the Court area where the applicant intends, in reliance on the licence, certificate, authority or permission sought (or, as the case may be, sought to be restored) to carry on any trade, profession or business; or - where the licence, certificate, authority or permission is not sought for the purpose of a trade, profession or business, in the Court area where the activity permitted by the licence, certificate, authority or permission is intended to be conducted; or - (iii) where the application is for the restoration of, or other relief from disqualification from holding, any licence, certificate, authority or permission, in the Court area where the disqualification or restriction concerned was imposed; or otherwise - in the Court area where the applicant resides. (2) Sub-rule (1) is subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'How must a relevant application be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By notice of application","Via social media announcement","Through an oral declaration in a court hearing","By submitting a formal email"],"justification":"The relevant application must be made by notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Commencement of relevant application* 3. (1) The relevant application must be made by notice of application (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as “**the notice of application**”). (2) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of the provision of the enactment under which the application is made. (4) Where any order, direction or other relief is sought against any person, the notice of application must also be entitled as between the applicant as applicant and such person as respondent, and must contain the names and addresses of the applicant and of each respondent. (5) Where the application is authorised by an enactment to be made parte, or where no order, direction or other relief is sought as against any person or persons, the notice of application must be entitled in the matter of the provision of the enactment pursuant to which the application is made and on the application of the applicant, and must contain the name and address of the applicant. (6) The notice of application must specify the particular relief sought against each respondent and the particular provision of the relevant enactment authorising the granting of each such relief.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'What must be attached to the notice of application for an enforcement application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The original document that led to the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing.","A true copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing.","A certified copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing.","A detailed summary of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing."],"justification":"a true copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing, must be attached to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on any respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Documents to be attached to the notice of application* 4. Where the relevant application is an enforcement application, a true copy of the decision, determination, notice or order concerned, if in writing, must be attached to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on any respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant adduce at the hearing of every relevant application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A list of potential witnesses who have not been involved in the matter at hand","A written personal statement detailing the applicant''s background and experience unrelated to the case","Evidence of the applicant''s financial status unrelated to their standing or the application","Evidence of the standing and authority of the applicant, capacity of the applicant or respondent, facts or circumstances supporting the application, and relevant correspondence and documents."],"justification":"The applicant must adduce at the hearing of every relevant application: (a) evidence of the standing and authority of the applicant to make the application under the relevant provision of the enactment; if the applicant is acting in a representative capacity, or relief is sought against any respondent in a representative capacity, evidence of the capacity of the applicant or, as the case may be, the respondent; evidence of the facts or circumstances which it is alleged authorise or entitle the applicant to make, or justify the applicant in making, the application and which support the granting of the relief sought; and all correspondence and documents passing between the applicant and each respondent (if any), or otherwise issuing from any of them, relevant to the matter or matters in respect of which relief is sought, but not including any correspondence or document which, by law, a person is obliged or entitled to refuse to produce."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Evidence required at hearing in every case* 5. (1) The applicant must adduce at the hearing of every relevant application: - (a) evidence of the standing and authority of the applicant to make the application under the relevant provision of the enactment; - if the applicant is acting in a representative capacity, or relief is sought against any respondent in a representative capacity, evidence of the capacity of the applicant or, as the case may be, the respondent; - evidence of the facts or circumstances which it is alleged authorise or entitle the applicant to make, or justify the applicant in making, the application and which support the granting of the relief sought; and - all correspondence and documents passing between the applicant and each respondent (if any), or otherwise issuing from any of them, relevant to the matter or matters in respect of which relief is sought, but not including any correspondence or document which, by law, a person is obliged or entitled to refuse to produce. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not operate to limit the evidence which the applicant is required to adduce at the hearing of the relevant application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'When must each respondent be served with a copy of the notice of application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Not later than fourteen days before the court appearance","Not later than seven days before the return date","Not later than three days before the hearing date","Not later than two weeks after the application is filed"],"justification":"Each respondent must be served, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), with a copy of the notice of application (and copies of any documents required to be attached) not later than seven days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Period of notice* 6. (1) Not less than 21 days’ notice of an application by notice of application must be given to the Court. (2) Each respondent must be served, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), with a copy of the notice of application (and copies of any documents required to be attached) not later than seven days before the return date. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date. (4) Where the relevant enactment requires prior publication of notice of the intended application, a print of the newspaper or other publication in which notice was published must also be lodged with the Clerk within the time specified in sub-rule (3). (5) Sub-rules (1) and (2) are subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'What types of directions/orders can the Court issue under sub-rule', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Directions/orders can include appointing new judges to preside over the case.","Directions/orders can include ordering the immediate arrest of individuals named in the case.","Directions/orders can include issuing fines to individuals or organizations involved in the case.","Directions/orders can include serving notice on others, furnishing written submissions, and delivering/filing affidavits."],"justification":"Directions and orders under sub-rule may, where appropriate, include: - (a) directions that notice of the application be served on any other person, including mode of service and the time allowed for such service; - directions that the parties furnish written submissions to the Court and deliver those written submissions to one another; - an order directing the delivery and filing of any affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Orders which may be made by Court on return date* 7. (1) On the return date, the Court may: - (a) hear the application; or - give directions and make orders for the conduct of the proceedings as appear convenient for determining the application in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings. (2) Directions and orders under sub-rule may, where appropriate, include: - (a) directions that notice of the application be served on any other person, including mode of service and the time allowed for such service; - directions that the parties furnish written submissions to the Court and deliver those written submissions to one another; - an order directing the delivery and filing of any affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40C - Procedure In Statutory Applications By Notice Of Application', 'Court Rules', 'How must an application to vary or discharge an order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By notice of motion to vary or discharge","By filing a petition for appeal","Through an oral request during a scheduled court hearing","By submitting a written letter to the court"],"justification":"the application to vary or discharge the order must be made by notice of motion to vary or discharge (as the case may be)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Application to vary or discharge an order* 8. (1) Where the relevant enactment permits any subsequent application to vary or discharge an order made by the Court on the relevant application, the application to vary or discharge the order must be made by notice of motion to vary or discharge (as the case may be). (2) A notice of motion to vary or discharge must be in [Form No. 44.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case. The notice must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) Not less than 21 days’ notice of an application to vary or discharge must be given to the Court. (4) The applicant for the original order and every respondent served with that application must be served, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), with a copy of the notice of motion to vary or discharge not later than seven days before the return date. (5) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of motion on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date. (6) Sub-rules (3), (4) and (5) are subject to any provision or requirement to a different effect in the relevant enactment. # [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High","Supreme","District","Magistrates"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court - Court: District # Order Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''respondent'' mean in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The judge or official who will hear the appeal","The person who gave the notice, decision or direction from which the appeal is brought","The person who is bringing the appeal against the notice, decision or direction","The lawyer representing the party bringing the appeal"],"justification":"“**respondent**” means the person who gave the notice, decision or direction from which the appeal is brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1. (1) In this Order— “**appellant**” means the person making an appeal to the Court; “**respondent**” means the person who gave the notice, decision or direction from which the appeal is brought. (2) Where an enactment provides for or permits an appeal to be made to the Court or to a Judge from any notice given or served or from any decision or direction given in any matter and no other provision is made for the applicable procedure either by the enactment concerned or by these Rules, the procedure for the appeal (in the remainder of this Order, referred to as the “relevant appeal”) set out in the following rules applies. (3) Sub-rule (2) is subject to any requirement of the relevant enactment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["1 - INTRODUCTION","3 - SPECIFICATIONS","2 - GENERAL","PART A - OVERVIEW"],"justification":"## 2 - GENERAL"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - GENERAL'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the appellant attach to the notice of appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A summary of all legal arguments to be presented during the appeal","A detailed affidavit explaining the reasons for the appeal","A list of all witnesses who will testify on behalf of the appellant","A copy of the notice, decision or direction appealed from and, where appropriate, copies of any other documents or exhibits used in relation to the notice, decision or direction."],"justification":"The appellant must also attach to the notice of appeal and to any copy of the notice of appeal served a copy of the notice, decision or direction appealed from and, where appropriate, copies of any other documents or exhibits used in relation to the notice, decision or direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Copy documents to be attached* 4. The appellant must also attach to the notice of appeal and to any copy of the notice of appeal served a copy of the notice, decision or direction appealed from and, where appropriate, copies of any other documents or exhibits used in relation to the notice, decision or direction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the court direct the service of a notice of appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["If the court considers it proper, it can direct the service of a notice of appeal on any person not already served.","If the court considers it improper, it can direct the service of a notice of appeal on any person not already served.","The court can only direct the service of a notice of appeal if all parties have agreed in writing to such action.","The court can direct the service of a notice of appeal only when requested by the losing party."],"justification":"The Court hearing the appeal may, if it considers it proper, direct that the notice of appeal be served on any person not already served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Court may direct service of the notice of appeal* 5. The Court hearing the appeal may, if it considers it proper, direct that the notice of appeal be served on any person not already served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the format of the section title?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["3. Particular Appeals Under Statute","### 3 - PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE","Section 3: Particular Appeals Under Statute","## 3 - PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE"],"justification":"## 3 - PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - PARTICULAR APPEALS UNDER STATUTE'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant do after an appeal is made against an improvement notice, prohibition notice, or information notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Pay a fine to the court as a penalty for the issued notice.","Notify the court that the notice has been received and provide a written response within 14 days.","Ensure that a copy of any order of the Court made on the appeal is served promptly on the respondent and on any other person directly affected by the order.","Attend a mandatory training session related to the notice issued."],"justification":"the applicant must ensure that a copy of any order of the Court made on the appeal is served promptly on the respondent and on any other person directly affected by the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Safety Health and Welfare at Work Act 2005* 6. (1) In this rule - the “Act of 2005” means the [Safety Health and Welfare at Work Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/10/enacted/en/print) (No. 10 of 2005). (2) Where an appeal has been brought in the manner prescribed under— - (a) section 66(7) of the Act of 2005 against an improvement notice, - section 67(7) of the Act of 2005 against a prohibition notice, or - section 72(3) of the Act of 2005 against an information notice, the applicant must ensure that a copy of any order of the Court made on the appeal is served promptly on the respondent and on any other person directly affected by the order. (3) Where an application has been brought in the manner prescribed under section 67(6) of the Act of 2005 for the suspension of a prohibition notice, the applicant must ensure that a copy of any order of the Court made on the application directing that the operation of a prohibition notice be suspended is served promptly on the respondent and on any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40D - Procedure In Statutory Appeals By Notice Of Appeal To The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Act'' refer to in Rule 7?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Privacy Act 2001 (No. 25 of 2001)","The Employment Act 2001 (No. 25 of 2001)","The Education Act 2001 (No. 25 of 2001)","The Mental Health Act 2001 (No. 25 of 2001)"],"justification":"the **Act** means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25) (No. 25 of 2001);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Mental Health Act 2001* 7. (1) In this rule- the “**Act**” means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25) (No. 25 of 2001); the expressions “**approved centre**”, “**centre**”, “**Commission**”, and “**registered proprietor**” each has the meaning given to it by the Act. (2) An appeal under section 65(1) of the Act by: - (a) a registered proprietor or, as the case may be, - a person intending to be the registered proprietor of an approved centre, against a decision of the Commission: - to refuse to register the centre; - to remove the centre from the register, or - (iii) to attach a condition, or to amend or revoke a condition attached, to the registration of the centre may be made to the Judge assigned to the Court district in which the centre concerned is situated, at any sitting of the Court for that Court district. (3) The notice of appeal, in the [Form 40D.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e71f6594-afca-45bb-9369-de3b333d3581/Notice of appeal to District Court - Mental Health Act 2001, section 65(1) No. 40D.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be served on the Commission by the appellant not later than seven days before the return date. (4) A copy of the decision of the Commission appealed from must be annexed to the notice of appeal. (5) A statutory declaration of service of the notice of appeal must be filed with the Clerk at least two days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What type of court handles proceedings under Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","High Court","Magistrates'' Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters - Court: District # **Order Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters****\*[**[1]**](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1)** ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application to sign and issue a summons be made if the person is ordinarily resident or carries on business in another court area?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["To the highest-ranking judge in the court area where the person is not ordinarily resident or does not carry on business.","To the local post office in the area where the person is ordinarily resident or carries on business.","To the Clerk for the Court area wherein that person ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","To the nearest police station within the other court area."],"justification":"be made to the Clerk for the Court area wherein that person ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application for summons* 1. (1) In any case where these Rules provide that an application to the Court is to be made or civil proceedings in the Court are to be begun by a civil summons, then the applicant, moving party or claimant may apply to the Clerk for the Court area in which the application is to be made or the proceedings are to be begun for the issue of a civil summons for service. (2) When it is intended to begin proceedings (which are not proceedings to which the [Courts (No. 3) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/33/enacted/en/html) relates) in the District Court against a person, and the issue of a summons requiring the appearance of that person before the Court is necessary, on a matter or issue which the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine by summons, an application to sign and issue the summons may, unless otherwise provided by an enactment or these Rules, be made to the Clerk for the Court area wherein that person ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What details must the summons include regarding the relief sought?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The summons must include a general description of the plaintiff''s financial status.","The summons must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case.","The summons must include a detailed account of the defendant''s financial status.","The summons must include the names of all witnesses who will testify in the trial."],"justification":"The summons must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Form, signing and issue of summons* 2. (1) The applicant for the issue of the summons must lodge with the Clerk a duly completed summons, which may be in the [Form 40E.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/33195e4d-431e-492f-bf24-df0861589d33/Summons issued by a Clerk in a matter other than a criminal matter No. 40E.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (with such modifications as are appropriate to the case), together with a copy or copies for service. (2) The summons must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (3) The Clerk must unless otherwise provided by an enactment or these Rules, list the matter or issue for hearing at a sitting of the Court, record the place, date and time of hearing on the summons and copies and, having signed and dated the summons and copies, issue them to the applicant for service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What must every summons issued under this Order require?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The appearance of each person to whom it is directed at any sitting of any Court, regardless of the Court''s jurisdiction over the matter or issue.","The appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Supreme Court, irrespective of the specific Court area or district.","The appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Court having jurisdiction to deal with the matter or issue set out in the summons, for the Court area to which the Clerk issuing the summons is assigned, and within the Court district in which a Judge of the District Court has jurisdiction in relation to the matter or issue.","The appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Court only if the matter or issue is criminal in nature."],"justification":"Every summons issued under this Order must require the appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Court: (a) having jurisdiction to deal with the matter or issue set out in the summons; for the Court area to which the Clerk issuing the summons is assigned; within the Court district in which a Judge of the District Court has jurisdiction in relation to the matter or issue."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Court to which the summons is returnable* 3. Every summons issued under this Order must require the appearance of each person to whom it is directed at a sitting of the Court: - (a) having jurisdiction to deal with the matter or issue set out in the summons; - for the Court area to which the Clerk issuing the summons is assigned; - within the Court district in which a Judge of the District Court has jurisdiction in relation to the matter or issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What order''s service of documents provisions apply to summonses in proceedings under Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order 50","Order 42","Order 39","Order 41"],"justification":"the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) (Service of Documents) apply to summonses signed and issued in proceedings to which this Order relates"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Service and filing* 4. Save where otherwise provided, the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) (Service of Documents) apply to summonses signed and issued in proceedings to which this Order relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40E - Proceedings Begun By The Issue Of A Summons In Matters Other Than Criminal Matters', 'Court Rules', 'What note is provided about the application of Order 15?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of criminal proceedings are contained in Order 15 of these Rules.","Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of offences are contained in Order 15 of these Rules.","Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of civil matters are contained in Order 15 of these Rules.","Provisions relating to the issue of warrants in respect of civil matters are contained in Order 15 of these Rules."],"justification":"Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of offences are contained in [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Order 15 (in part) to apply* 5. The provisions of rules 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9 (with any necessary modifications) of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) apply to summonses signed and issued in proceedings to which this Order relates. \* Note: Provisions relating to the issue of summonses in respect of offences are contained in [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order - Intellectual Property","Order - Data Privacy","Order - Employee Benefits","Order - Environmental Regulations"],"justification":"# Order - Intellectual Property"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Intellectual Property - Court: District # **Order Intellectual Property******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''1992 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Trade Marks Act 1992 (No. 1 of 1992)","The Copyright Act 1992 (No. 1 of 1992)","The Designs Act 1992 (No. 1 of 1992)","The Patents Act 1992 (No. 1 of 1992)"],"justification":"the “**1992 Act**” means the [Patents Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1992);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— the “**1992 Act**” means the [Patents Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1992); the “**1996 Act**” means the [Trade Marks Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6) (No. 6 of 1996); the “**2000 Act**” means the [Copyright and Related Rights Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) (No. 28 of 2000); the “**2001 Act**” means the [Industrial Designs Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) (No. 39 of 2001). the “**2019 Act**” means the [Copyright and Other Intellectual Property Law Provisions Act 2019](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/19/enacted/en/html) (No. 19 of 2019); “**intellectual property claim**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What does this Order apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Contract disputes unrelated to intellectual property","Criminal cases involving intellectual property theft","Personal injury cases in the Court","Intellectual property claims in the Court"],"justification":"The provisions of this Order apply to intellectual property claims in the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 Requirements of this Order additional to Order 40** 2. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to intellectual property claims in the Court. (2) The requirements of this Order are additional to the requirements of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) as regards claim notices.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What must an intellectual property claim notice state regarding the registered number of any registered intellectual property right?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It must state the trademark name of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates.","It must state the filing date of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates.","It must state the registered number of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates.","It must state the expiration date of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates."],"justification":"state the registered number of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 Additional particulars required in claim notice in intellectual property claim** 3. (1) An intellectual property claim notice must: - state the registered number of any registered intellectual property right to which the claim relates; - set out full particulars of the ownership of any unregistered intellectual property right concerned in the proceedings, or of the right of the claimant to claim infringement; - (iii) include particulars of the nature and extent of any intellectual property right relied upon by the claimant (including the capacity in which the claimant sues if not the registered proprietor or proprietor of the intellectual property right concerned); - include particulars of the nature and extent of the alleged infringement of any intellectual property right relied on by the claimant; - set out the material facts relied on in support of the intellectual property claim; - state specifically the relief sought against each respondent and every provision or rule of law relied on in support of each such relief and, where relief under the [1992 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/1/enacted/en/html), [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6), [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) and/or [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) is sought, the particular provisions under which relief is sought and the grounds for each such relief; - (vii) set out clearly the basis upon which the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine the intellectual property claim; - (viii) set out the appropriate costs in the Schedule of Costs payable if the claimant’s claim is settled before appearance and defence. (2) A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must be in accordance with [Form 40.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05fcfa04-41cd-42dd-92c8-4ab56170ad80/Claim notice - general damages not exceeding €15,000 No. 40.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the modifications necessitated by this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What must a claim notice in an intellectual property claim do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Name as respondent and serve on every person against whom relief is sought.","Include a copy of the intellectual property in question as an attachment.","State the date of creation for all disputed intellectual properties.","Provide a detailed description of the intellectual property in dispute."],"justification":"A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must name as respondent, and must be served on, every person against whom relief is sought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4 Service of claim notice** 4. A claim notice in an intellectual property claim must name as respondent, and must be served on, every person against whom relief is sought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What types of items can be delivered up under a civil application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Illegal substances, contraband, or prohibited weapons","Personal data, private documents, or confidential files","Infringing goods, material or articles; infringing article, copy, or device; illicit recording, article or device; infringing product or article","Infringing services, performances, or actions"],"justification":"infringing goods, material or articles under section 20 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6); or an infringing article, copy, or device under section 131 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or (iii) an illicit recording, article or device under section 255 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or an infringing product or article under section 61 of the [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **5 Civil application for delivery up** 5. (1) An application to the Court in or by way of a civil proceeding for the delivery up of: - infringing goods, material or articles under section 20 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6); or - an infringing article, copy, or device under section 131 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or - (iii) an illicit recording, article or device under section 255 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html); or - an infringing product or article under section 61 of the [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html) may be made parte to any sitting of the Court for the Court District wherein it is believed that the infringing matter concerned is or are in the possession, custody of control of any person. (2) The application may be grounded upon an information on oath and in writing by or on behalf of the proprietor of the registered trade mark concerned, or the copyright owner or a person having rights conferred by Part III of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html) or the registered proprietor or his or its authorised representative, as the case may be. (3) Where an application has been made, and remains undetermined, in a criminal proceeding, for the delivery up of some or all of the same article(s), copies, devices or products, an application under this rule shall not be determined until the determination of the application in the criminal proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What form is an order made on an application under rule 5, whether parte or inter partes?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form Schedule A","Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule"],"justification":"An order made on an application under rule 5, whether parte or inter partes, may be in the [Form 40F.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c56c1a04-8de6-4002-b292-d1d0ea028372/Order for delivery up No. 40F.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **7 Form of order for delivery up** 7. An order made on an application under rule 5, whether parte or inter partes, may be in the [Form 40F.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c56c1a04-8de6-4002-b292-d1d0ea028372/Order for delivery up No. 40F.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an application for erasure, removal, obliteration, destruction, or forfeiture of infringing goods, materials, articles, copies, recordings, devices, or products be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule A"],"justification":"must be in the [Form 40F.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c7da7f4-09cf-476f-bb28-4fd68b03f69d/Notice of Application for Erasure Forfeiture Disposal No. 40F.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **8 Civil application for erasure etc of offending sign or for forfeiture or disposal** 8. (1) Subject to sub-rule (4), an application to the Court in or by way of a civil proceeding for: - an order to cause an offending sign to be erased, removed or obliterated from any infringing goods, material or articles, or to secure the destruction of infringing goods, materials or articles under section 19 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6), or - an order for the destruction or forfeiture of infringing goods, material or articles under section 23 of the 1996 Act, or - (iii) an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an infringing copy, article or, device under section 145 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html), or - an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an illicit recording, article or device under section 264 of the [2000 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/28/enacted/en/html), or - an order for the forfeiture or disposal of an infringing product or article under section 72 of the [2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/39/enacted/en/html), must be in the [Form 40F.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c7da7f4-09cf-476f-bb28-4fd68b03f69d/Notice of Application for Erasure Forfeiture Disposal No. 40F.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must be served by the applicant, by personal service or by prepaid registered post: - (a) on the respondent thereto, - on any other person appearing to have an interest in the goods, materials, articles, copies, devices or products concerned, and - on any other person directed by the Court to be served. (2) If served personally, the notice must be served at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable; if served by prepaid registered post, the notice must be served at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (3) Where an application has been made, and remains undetermined, in a criminal proceeding, for the delivery up of some or all of the same article(s), copies, recordings, devices or products, an application under this rule shall not be determined until the determination of the application in the criminal proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can the Court determine an application under section 19 of the 1996 Act without issuing a further notice of application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the Court has received written submissions from all interested parties but has not conducted any hearings.","When the Court has issued a preliminary ruling in favor of one party, regardless of whether all interested parties have been heard.","When the Court has determined an intellectual property claim and all interested parties are present and heard.","When the Court has only reviewed the intellectual property documents but not yet made a determination on the claims."],"justification":"the Court may, where it has determined an intellectual property claim, determine an application under section 19 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6) made orally to the Court concerning infringing goods, material or articles which were the subject of that intellectual property claim, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that all persons having an interest in the infringing goods, material or articles are before the Court and have had an opportunity to be heard."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Notwithstanding sub-rules (1), (2) and (3), the Court may, where it has determined an intellectual property claim, determine an application under section 19 of the [1996 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/6) made orally to the Court concerning infringing goods, material or articles which were the subject of that intellectual property claim, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that all persons having an interest in the infringing goods, material or articles are before the Court and have had an opportunity to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 40F - Intellectual Property', 'Court Rules', 'What form may an Order of the Court take on an application under rule 8?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It may be in the form of Form Schedule","It may be in the form of Form Schedule A.","It may be in the form of Form Schedule","It may be in the form of Form Schedule"],"justification":"An Order of the Court on an application under rule 8 may be in the [Form 40F.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58b729d-2c8e-4698-8d1e-1fbb296cb363/Order for Erasure Forfeiture Disposal No. 40F.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **9 Form of order for erasure etc of offending sign or for forfeiture or disposal** 9. An Order of the Court on an application under rule 8 may be in the [Form 40F.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58b729d-2c8e-4698-8d1e-1fbb296cb363/Order for Erasure Forfeiture Disposal No. 40F.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 284 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/284/made/en/print), effective 12 August 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State - Court: District # **Order 41: Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''document'' mean in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["an International Treaty document","a State Senate document","a District Court document","a High School diploma"],"justification":"a “**document**” means a “**District Court document**” within the meaning of section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Definitions* 1. In this Order- a “**document**” means a “**District Court document**” within the meaning of section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What is the fee structure for a summons-server serving documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The fee is fixed at 50 for each document served.","The fee is set at 10 per mile traveled by the server.","The fee is as determined by the County Registrar from time to time, payable on proof of each separate service effected.","The fee is determined by the court on a case-by-case basis."],"justification":"The fee to be paid to a summons-server for the service of any document is the sum as determined by the County Registrar from time to time, payable on proof of each separate service effected."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Persons authorised to serve documents* 2. (1) In civil proceedings, a document may be served by: - (a) a summons-server standing assigned to the Court area concerned; or - any person authorised to do so by the party or person on whose behalf the document is served, unless these Rules or statute otherwise provide or unless the Court otherwise directs. (2) The fee to be paid to a summons-server for the service of any document is the sum as determined by the County Registrar from time to time, payable on proof of each separate service effected. Where the fee to be paid for the service of any document is for the time being prescribed by rule of court or otherwise, the fee becomes payable on proof of each separate service effected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Who is authorized to post the document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The person on whose behalf it purports to be issued or a person authorized by them.","The first person who drafts the document","The IT department of the organization","Any employee of the company where the document is being posted"],"justification":"The document may be posted by the person on whose behalf it purports to be issued or by a person authorised by him in that behalf."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3. Mode of service - registered post* 3. (1) A document in proceedings to which section 7(1) of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html) relates may, subject to and in accordance with the provisions of, section 7 of the [Courts Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/11/enacted/en/html), be served by sending a copy of the document by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his or her last known residence or place of business in the State. (2) The document may be posted by the person on whose behalf it purports to be issued or by a person authorised by him in that behalf.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How can a document be served on a company?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By leaving a copy of the document at or sending a copy of the document by post to the registered office of the company, or by registering the document at the office of the Registrar of Companies if the company has not given notice of its registered office.","By posting a copy of the document on the company''s social media accounts.","By delivering a copy of the document to the company''s main customer service email address.","By leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the company during business hours."],"justification":"A document may be served on a company by leaving a copy of the document at or sending a copy of the document by post to the registered office of the company or, if the company has not given notice to the Registrar of Companies of the situation of its registered office, by registering the document at the office of the Registrar of Companies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5. Service on a company* 5.(1) A document may be served on a company by leaving a copy of the document at or sending a copy of the document by post to the registered office of the company or, if the company has not given notice to the Registrar of Companies of the situation of its registered office, by registering the document at the office of the Registrar of Companies. (2) For the purposes of this rule, any document left at or sent by post to the place for the time being recorded by the Registrar of Companies as the situation of the registered office of a company must be deemed to have been left at or sent by post to the registered office of the company notwithstanding that the situation of its registered office may have been changed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How can a document be served on a local authority or an unincorporated body?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By delivering a copy of the document to the CEO''s home address or by sending it by prepaid registered post to the CEO''s home address.","By leaving a copy of the document with any employee at the principal office or by sending it by prepaid registered post to the principal office.","By leaving a copy of the document with any employee at the secondary office or by sending it by prepaid registered post to the secondary office.","By posting the document on the official website of the local authority or unincorporated body."],"justification":"by leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the authority, board, body, society or club at its principal office or by sending a copy of the document by prepaid registered post to its principal office"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6. Service on a local authority or an unincorporated body* 6. A document may be served on a local authority, statutory board or body, or an unincorporated society or club by leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the authority, board, body, society or club at its principal office or by sending a copy of the document by prepaid registered post to its principal office.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How can a document be served on a partnership?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Either on any one or more of the partners or at the principal place within the State where the business is carried on, on any person having control or management of the partnership business there.","Via email notification to the private email addresses of all partners as specified in the internal partnership records.","Only through registered mail sent to the personal residences of all partners listed in the official partnership agreement.","By delivering it to any individual employee of the partnership, regardless of their role or position within the company."],"justification":"Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, a copy of the document must be served either: (a) on any one or more of the partners; or at the principal place within the State at which the business of the partnership is carried on, on any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7. Service on a partnership* 7.(1) Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, a copy of the document must be served either: - (a) on any one or more of the partners; or - at the principal place within the State at which the business of the partnership is carried on, on any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there; and such service must be deemed good service on the firm sued, whether any of the members of the partnership are outside the State or not. (2) The permission of the Court is not necessary for the issue and service on a partnership of a claim notice or other originating document where one or more of the partners is in the State and one or more outside the State, provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the claimant before the civil proceedings are begun, the claim notice or other originating document must be served on every person within the State sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How can a document be effectively served on a child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By posting the document in a local newspaper or online forum where the child or their guardians might see it.","By serving it on the father, mother, or other guardian having actual custody of the child or with whom the child resides, or if the child has no such guardian, on the person with whom the child resides or under whose care the child is, or on the child’s solicitor unless the Court otherwise decides.","By sending the document via email to any adult relative of the child, without verifying that they have custody or guardianship responsibilities.","By serving it directly to the child, regardless of their age or ability to understand the document."],"justification":"Where the person to be served is a child, a document is effectively served if served: - (a) on the father, mother or other guardian having actual custody of the child or with whom the child resides; or - if the child has no father, mother or other guardian, on the person with whom the child resides or under whose care the child is; or - on the child’s solicitor unless the Court otherwise decides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8. Service on a child* 8. Where the person to be served is a child, a document is effectively served if served: - (a) on the father, mother or other guardian having actual custody of the child or with whom the child resides; or - if the child has no father, mother or other guardian, on the person with whom the child resides or under whose care the child is; or - on the child’s solicitor unless the Court otherwise decides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How must service on a relevant person be carried out?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["In accordance with Order 12, rule 3.","In accordance with Order 7, rule 8.","In accordance with Order 5, rule 6.","In accordance with Order 9, rule 2."],"justification":"Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) must be in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9. Service on a relevant person* 9[3].(1) Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) must be in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8. (2) Where the person to be served is a ward of court, a document is effectively served if served: - (a) on the person’s solicitor; or - on the committee of the ward of court, unless the Court otherwise decides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Who can serve documents on a prisoner or detained person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The prisoner''s legal counsel.","The prisoner''s immediate family members.","The governor, director or other person in charge of the prison or place of detention.","Any law enforcement officer from outside the prison or detention facility."],"justification":"service on the governor, director or other person in charge of the prison or place of detention is, unless the Court otherwise decides, good service on the prisoner or person detained."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10. Service on a prisoner* 10. Where the person to be served is a prisoner or a person detained in a place of detention under the order of any court or tribunal, service on the governor, director or other person in charge of the prison or place of detention is, unless the Court otherwise decides, good service on the prisoner or person detained.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What constitutes good service when a solicitor accepts a document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Service of a document is deemed good if the Court is satisfied that the document was delivered to the wrong address.","Service of a document is deemed good if the Court is satisfied that a solicitor acting on behalf of the person to be served has accepted it.","Service of a document is deemed good if the Court is satisfied that the document was left unattended in a public place.","Service of a document is deemed good if the Court is satisfied that the recipient refused to accept the document."],"justification":"Service of a document must be deemed good service if the Court is satisfied that a solicitor acting on behalf of the person to be served has accepted service of the document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11. Acceptance of service* 11. (1) Service of a document must be deemed good service if the Court is satisfied that a solicitor acting on behalf of the person to be served has accepted service of the document. (2) Service on the solicitor for a party may be effected: - (a) by delivering a copy of the document to the solicitor; or - by leaving a copy of the document at the solicitor’s office; or - by sending a copy of the document by post in an envelope to, the solicitor; or - by sending a copy of the document to a document exchange service designated by that solicitor in accordance with sub-rule (3) through which that solicitor accepts documents. (3) Delivery or service through a document exchange service under sub-rule (2): - (a) is effective provided that the solicitor concerned has confirmed in writing to the party serving the document or copy (or that party’s solicitor) that he or she will accept service of documents in the civil proceedings through the document exchange service designated by him or her; - ceases to be effective where, prior to delivery or service, the solicitor concerned has in writing revoked such confirmation. (4) Any statutory declaration verifying delivery or service through a document exchange service must exhibit the written confirmation referred to in sub-rule (3) and contain a statement that the confirmation had not, at the time of the delivery or service concerned, been revoked in accordance with this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the Court direct that service of documents be effected in another manner?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["If the recipient refuses to accept the documents.","If the Court is satisfied that the prescribed mode of service would be excessively costly.","If the document is deemed too sensitive to be served through standard means.","If the Court is satisfied that any particular mode of service prescribed is not then available."],"justification":"Where the Court is satisfied that any particular mode of service prescribed is at any time not then available, the Court may by order in writing direct that the service of documents or of any particular class of documents be effected in such other manner as it thinks proper."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12. Substituted service* 12.(1) Where the Court is satisfied that, for good cause shown, service of a document cannot be effected in a manner or in any manner prescribed by these Rules, the Court may make an order: - (a) for substituted or other service; or - for the substitution for service of notice by advertisement or otherwise. (2) Particulars of any order for substituted or other service must be endorsed on the original and on each copy of the document to be served. (3) An application for an order for substituted or other service may be made parte. (4) Where the Court is satisfied that any particular mode of service prescribed is at any time not then available, the Court may by order in writing direct that the service of documents or of any particular class of documents be effected in such other manner as it thinks proper. (5) A direction under sub-rule (4) must be retained by the Clerk and remains in force until the mode of service concerned is again available or until the direction is revoked by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can the Court deem the service of a document to be good?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["If the document is served electronically but the recipient does not have access to email.","If the document is served by a party who is not a lawyer or legal professional.","If the Court considers it just to do so, it may deem the service of any document actually effected in civil proceedings to be good, even if it was not served in a manner prescribed by the Rules.","If the document is served after the deadline specified in the Rules but before the hearing date."],"justification":"The Court may, if it considers it just to do so, deem the service of any document actually effected in any civil proceedings to be good and effected service, even though the service was not effected in a manner prescribed by these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13. Service deemed good* 13. The Court may, if it considers it just to do so, deem the service of any document actually effected in any civil proceedings to be good and effected service, even though the service was not effected in a manner prescribed by these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How can a person prove the service of a document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By providing a signed acknowledgment from the recipient stating that they received the document via email.","By evidence given orally before the Court or by statutory declaration as to service made in accordance with the Statutory Declarations Act 1938.","By submitting a text message confirmation from the recipient indicating they have received the document.","By presenting a certified copy of the document to the court without any additional proof of delivery."],"justification":"by evidence given orally before the Court; or by statutory declaration as to service made in accordance with the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14. Proof of service* 14. (1) A person who serves a document may prove the service: - (a) by evidence given orally before the Court; or - by statutory declaration as to service made in accordance with the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html). (2) A statutory declaration as to service must be in the [Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), [41.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1ce8e29-61fe-41d6-b1e4-0be6fe055224/Declaration as to service by ordinary post No. 41.02.docx/docx/1) or [41.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d590fd61-c2f8-49d3-9efa-e869eb833fc7/Statutory declaration as to personal service No. 41.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be. (3) When service of a document on a person has been effected by registered prepaid post, a statutory declaration of service, which must be in the [Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made not earlier than ten days after the day on which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service was posted. (4) A statutory declaration of service by registered post must: - (a) be made by the person who posted the envelope; and - exhibit the certificate of posting; and - state, where appropriate, that the original document was duly stamped at the time of posting, and - state that the envelope has not been returned undelivered to the sender.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What is the effect of filing a statutory declaration under rule 19?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It dismisses the case automatically if not contested within 7 days.","It requires all parties to appear in court within 24 hours.","It acts as a formal request for a jury trial.","It serves as prima facie evidence of the mode, time and place of service."],"justification":"the statutory declaration is prima facie evidence of the mode, time and place of service as set out in the statutory declaration;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15. Person proving service by statutory declaration need not attend Court* 15. Where a statutory declaration is made, and filed with the Clerk under rule 19: - (a) the statutory declaration is prima facie evidence of the mode, time and place of service as set out in the statutory declaration; and - it is not necessary for the person who effected service to attend in person at the Court to prove service on oral evidence, but the Court may, if it considers it necessary, require the person who effected service to attend before it and give evidence concerning the service notwithstanding the making of a statutory declaration.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'When is a document deemed to be served if sent via registered prepaid post or ordinary prepaid post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At the time the envelope containing the document would be delivered in the ordinary course of post.","When the recipient signs for the delivery of the envelope containing the document.","At the moment the document is placed into the postal system by the sender.","When the post office marks the envelope as undeliverable and returns it to the sender."],"justification":"the document must be deemed to be served on the person to whom it was directed at the time at which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service would be delivered in the ordinary course of post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16. Deemed time of service* 16. Where service of a document is effected by registered prepaid post or by ordinary prepaid post, the document must be deemed to be served on the person to whom it was directed at the time at which the envelope containing the copy of the document for service would be delivered in the ordinary course of post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a document required by law to be stamped is served without being stamped?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The document is automatically considered stamped upon service.","Service of the unstamped document results in a fine but does not affect its validity.","Service of the document has no effect or validity.","The recipient is legally obligated to stamp the document themselves upon receipt."],"justification":"service of the document has no effect or validity unless, at the time of service, the original document was so stamped"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17. Service invalid unless document stamped, where required* 17. Where a document is required by law to be stamped (or payment of a Court fee on the document otherwise recorded), service of the document has no effect or validity unless, at the time of service, the original document was so stamped (or payment of the appropriate Court fee on the document otherwise recorded).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before a hearing must a document be served if not by registered prepaid post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least five days","at least ten days","at least three days","at least seven days"],"justification":"a document which must be served before a hearing in the Court must be served at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18. Time for service before hearing* 18. Save where otherwise provided by another enactment or by these Rules, a document which must be served before a hearing in the Court must be served at least seven days or, in the case of service by registered prepaid post, at least 21 days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before a hearing must a document be filed with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Exactly three days, regardless of the method of filing.","No specific deadline exists; it can be filed any day before the hearing.","At least four days, or seven days if filing by prepaid post.","At least two days, or five days if filing by prepaid post."],"justification":"a document which must be filed with the Clerk before a hearing in the Court, including any statutory declaration of service, must be filed at least four days or, in the case of filing by prepaid post, at least seven days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *19. Time for filing before hearing* 19. Subject to any order or direction of the Court, a document which must be filed with the Clerk before a hearing in the Court, including any statutory declaration of service, must be filed at least four days or, in the case of filing by prepaid post, at least seven days, before the date fixed for the hearing concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'In which section of the Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004 is the manner of delivery or service prescribed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section 10","Section 5","Section 3","Section 4"],"justification":"must be in the manner prescribed in section 4 of that Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *20. Service under Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004* 20. The delivery or service of any notice for the purposes of section 8 or section 17 of the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) must be in the manner prescribed in section 4 of that Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''electronic system'' refer to in Rule 21?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An electronic system utilized for internal email communication within the Courts Service.","An electronic system provided by the Courts Service for transmitting and receiving documents and information related to applications before the Court.","An electronic system designed for social media interactions among court staff.","An electronic system used exclusively for personal communication between judges."],"justification":"“e**lectronic system**” means an electronic system for the time being made available by the Courts Service which enables permitted users, officers of the Court and members of the staff of the Courts Service to transmit and receive documents and information concerning applications before the Court;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *21. Electronic service in licensing matters**[4]* 21. (1) This rule applies to licensing matters within the original jurisdiction of the Court. (2) In this rule: “e**lectronic system**” means an electronic system for the time being made available by the Courts Service which enables permitted users, officers of the Court and members of the staff of the Courts Service to transmit and receive documents and information concerning applications before the Court; “**p****ermitted user**” means a person who is for the time being permitted to use the electronic system; “**terms and conditions of use of the electronic system**” means any terms and conditions of use of the electronic system for the time being published, on a website maintained by it or otherwise, by the Courts Service or notified by the Courts Service to permitted users. (3) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, and subject to compliance by the permitted user with the terms and conditions of use of the electronic system, a party to or person interested in any licensing matter before the Court or intended to be brought before the Court (or a solicitor acting for such party or person) may be designated as a permitted user and when so designated is thereby permitted: - to deliver to or file or lodge with the Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system any application which may be made to the Court and any document which may be delivered, filed or lodged in any such application, - to serve by electronic means through the electronic system any document or notice concerning such application upon any person required by statute or these Rules to be served with, or put on notice of, any such application, document or notice, provided that: - (a) such service may be effected by the Clerk (or by a member of the staff of the Courts Service acting with the authority of the Clerk) on behalf of the person serving such document or notice, and - such service is deemed not to be effective unless the person to be served is a permitted user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41 - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents In The State', 'Court Rules', 'What can be transmitted electronically to a permitted user in licensing matters?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Oral testimony during a licensing hearing can be transmitted electronically.","Any other document or information concerning such application may be transmitted electronically.","Any physical evidence related to the criminal case must be transmitted electronically.","Biometric data, such as fingerprints, must be transmitted electronically."],"justification":"Any other document or information concerning such application may be transmitted to a permitted user by or on behalf of the Court or Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Any other document or information concerning such application may be transmitted to a permitted user by or on behalf of the Court or Clerk by electronic means through the electronic system. (5) A document transmitted by electronic means through the electronic system may be authenticated, and the identity of the person in whose name it has issued may be verified, by being— - (a) transmitted from an information system or e-mail address of a permitted user, accepted for the purpose of this rule by the Courts Service, or - transmitted to or created within the electronic system by or on behalf of the Clerk or by a permitted user, without the need for the incorporation in the document of a manuscript signature of the person in whose name it has issued. (6) If a permitted user is not complying with the terms and conditions (or any of them), permission to use the electronic system may be withdrawn in respect of that user. (7) An originating notice of application submitted for issue by electronic means in accordance with this rule is deemed to be issued when it has been assigned a record number and/or a return date. (8) Where an originating notice of application or a notice of motion is issued in accordance with the preceding provisions of this rule, - (a) a print or copy of the originating notice of application or notice of motion as transmitted for issue shall, when issued, be treated as the original of that document, and - the Clerk may certify any printed version of such document as a certified copy of the original. [1] Order 41 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 41 Rule 4A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025 [3] Order 41 rule 9 substituted by [S.I. 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [4] Order 41, rule 21 inserted by [S.I. 498 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/498/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 41A apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High Court","Supreme Court","County Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court - Court: District # **Order 41A: Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''document'' include in this context?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["An interjudicial agreement","An intrajudicial document","A judicial verdict","An extrajudicial document"],"justification":"includes an extrajudicial document"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order - “**Central Authority**”: - (a) when used in relation to the State, means the Master of the High Court; and - when used in relation to another State which is a party to the Hague Convention means the authority or authorities designated by that State under Article 2 of the Hague Convention to receive requests for the service of documents; “**document**” includes an extrajudicial document; the “**Hague Convention**” means the [Hague Convention of 15 November 1965](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 17) on the Service Abroad of Judicial and Extrajudicial Documents in Civil or Commercial Matters; “**Receiving Agency**”, for the purposes of the Service Regulation: - (a) when used in relation to the State means any County Registrar; and - when used in relation to another State in which the Service Regulation applies, means the authority or authorities designated by that State under Article 2 of the Service Regulation to receive requests for the service of documents; “**Service Regulation**” means [Regulation No. 1393/2007](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 13 November 2007 on the service in the Member States of judicial and extra-judicial documents in civil or commercial matters (service of documents) and repealing [Council Regulation No. 1348/2000](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2000/1348/oj/eng) (O.J. 324/79); “**Transmitting Agency**”, for the purposes of the Service Regulation: - (a) when used in relation to the State means any County Registrar; and - when used in relation to another State in which the Service Regulation applies, means the public officers, authorities or other persons designated by the relevant State under Article 2 of the Service Regulation to transmit requests for the service of documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'When may service outside the State be allowed in proceedings relating to a child or a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Where the child or relevant person has been resident in the State for less than one year","Where the child or relevant person has a significant financial interest in the State","Where the child or relevant person is temporarily residing in the State due to educational purposes","Where the child or relevant person is domiciled in or a citizen of the State"],"justification":"in proceedings relating to a child or a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) who is domiciled in or a citizen of the State;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Cases in which service outside the State may be allowed* 2. Service outside the State of a claim notice or other originating document (or of notice of an originating document), may be allowed by the Court in the following cases- - (a) in proceedings for ejectment where the premises sought to be recovered are within the State; - in proceedings in contract, where the contract is - made in the State, or - made by or through an agent trading or residing in the State on behalf of a principal trading or residing out of the State, or - (iii) by its terms or implications to be governed by Irish law; - in proceedings for a breach committed in the State of a contract wherever made (even if such breach was preceded or accompanied by a breach outside of the State which rendered impossible the performance of the part of the contract which ought to have been performed in the State); - in proceedings in tort, where the tort was committed in the State; where any relief is sought against a person domiciled or ordinarily resident in the State; - where any person outside the State is a necessary or proper party to an action properly brought against another person duly served in the State; in proceedings relating to a child or a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) who is domiciled in or a citizen of the State; - where necessary, in proceedings brought under section 38(3) of the [Criminal Justice Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/15) (and in accordance with [Order 38]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-38-District-Miscellaneous-Matters), rule 6) for an order authorising the further detention of cash seized.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition will permission not be granted for serving documents outside the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Permission must not be granted unless it sufficiently appears to the Court that the case is a proper one for service out of the State under this Order.","Permission will not be granted unless the defendant consents to service outside the State.","Permission will be denied if the plaintiff has not established residency in the State for at least one year.","Permission must not be granted if the case involves solely state law and does not affect interstate commerce."],"justification":"Permission must not be granted unless it sufficiently appears to the Court that the case is a proper one for service out of the State under this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 How an application for permission to serve outside the State is made* 3. (1) An application for permission to serve a claim notice or other originating document, (or notice thereof), on a person outside the State must be made parte and must be supported by an affidavit, or other evidence, which shows: - (a) that in the belief of the deponent, the claimant has a good cause of action; and - where the respondent is or probably may be found; and - whether the respondent (or, as the case may be, the relevant respondent) is or is not a citizen of Ireland; and - the grounds on which the application is made. (2) Permission must not be granted unless it sufficiently appears to the Court that the case is a proper one for service out of the State under this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served on a non-Irish citizen respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the respondent''s passport.","An invitation to a citizenship ceremony.","Notice of the claim notice or other originating document, along with any other required documents.","A letter of recommendation from an Irish citizen."],"justification":"if the respondent to be served is not, or is not known or believed to be, a citizen of Ireland, notice of the claim notice or other originating document (instead of the document itself) must be served on that respondent, together with any other document required in any particular case to be served;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Documents to be served on the respondent (or relevant respondent)* 4. When an order is made granting permission to serve outside the State under the provisions of this Order, (1) if the respondent to be served is a citizen of Ireland, the claim notice or other originating document must be served on that respondent, together with any other document required in any particular case to be served; (2) if the respondent to be served is not, or is not known or believed to be, a citizen of Ireland, notice of the claim notice or other originating document (instead of the document itself) must be served on that respondent, together with any other document required in any particular case to be served; (3) a copy of the order granting permission must also be served on the respondent with the documents required by sub-rules (1) and (2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What proof is required for service by registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Signed receipt from the recipient, proof of postage, and a notarized affidavit","Proof of purchase of the post stamp, receipt from the post office, and a copy of the letter sent","Confirmation email, tracking number, and witness signature","Statutory declaration of service, certificate of posting, and advice of delivery form (when returned)."],"justification":"Proof of service by post must be by the production of a statutory declaration of service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Mode of service on the respondent (or relevant respondent)* 5. (1) When permission is granted to serve outside the State under this Order, service must be by registered post or by insured post, as appropriate, or by such other method as the Court directs. (2) When service under this rule is by registered post, application for an advice of delivery must be made to the postal authorities at the time of posting. Proof of service by post must be by the production of a statutory declaration of service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned). These documents must be lodged with the Clerk with the originals of the documents of which copies were posted. (3) Service under this rule by registered post must be taken to have been effected on the day on which the envelope containing the documents would be delivered in the ordinary course of post or on such other day as may be proved.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What method of service is allowed under the Service Regulation when serving a person in another state?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Service by leaving documents at the person''s last known address","Service via email without acknowledgment of receipt","Service by diplomatic or consular agents or direct service","Service through social media channels"],"justification":"service by diplomatic or consular agents, in accordance with Article 13 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated, in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation, that it is opposed to the service of documents in its territory by diplomatic or consular agents), or direct service, in accordance with Article 15 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation that it is opposed to direct service of documents in its territory)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Where the Service Regulation applies (service in the European Union outside the State)* 6.[3] Where the person to be served is in another State in which the Service Regulation applies, service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation which, in addition to lodgment for service with the Transmitting Agency in accordance with rule 11(2), may include: - (a) service by diplomatic or consular agents, in accordance with Article 13 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated, in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation, that it is opposed to the service of documents in its territory by diplomatic or consular agents), or - direct service, in accordance with Article 15 of the Service Regulation (save where that Member State has communicated in accordance with Article 23(1) of the Service Regulation that it is opposed to direct service of documents in its territory).”.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How should documents be served when the person to be served is in another State which is a party to the Hague Convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Service can only be performed through diplomatic channels as specified in the Hague Convention.","Service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention, including service by post if the destination State has not objected to postal service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention.","Service must be conducted personally by a process server from the originating state, even if the destination state is a signatory to the Hague Convention.","Documents must be served electronically via email, regardless of whether the destination State has objected to postal service under Article 10(a)."],"justification":"service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention, which may include service by post under rule 5 provided the destination State has not objected to postal service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Where the Hague Convention applies (outside the European Union)* 7. Where the person to be served is in another State which is a party to the Hague Convention (and in which the Service Regulation does not apply), service must be in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention, which may include service by post under rule 5 provided the destination State has not objected to postal service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What types of documents does Rule 9 apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Rule 9 applies to initial claims filed by the plaintiff.","Rule 9 is applicable to appeals filed in higher courts.","Counterclaims against the claimant and another person joined as respondent, and third party notices.","Rule 9 governs the documents submitted during the discovery phase, such as interrogatories and requests for production."],"justification":"This rule applies to - - (a) a counterclaim against the claimant and another person joined as respondent in accordance with [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties) if the person joined is not already a party to the proceeding; and - a third party notice filed in accordance with [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Service of counterclaim or third party notice* 9. (1) This rule applies to - - (a) a counterclaim against the claimant and another person joined as respondent in accordance with [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties) if the person joined is not already a party to the proceeding; and - a third party notice filed in accordance with [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure). (2) A counterclaim or third party notice may be served out of the State without permission where the claim made by the respondent in the counterclaim or third party notice is of such a kind that, if the claim were made by claim notice, the claim notice could be served out of the State without permission of the Court under [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How should a document be served on a person in another State where the Service Regulation applies?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By following the local postal service rules of the state where the person is located","Through personal delivery by any means, regardless of the Service Regulation","In accordance with the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure only","In accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation."],"justification":"that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Procedure* 10. (1) Where a document for use in civil or commercial proceedings in the Court is to be served on a person in another State in which the Service Regulation applies, that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation. (2) Where a document for use in civil or commercial proceedings in the Court is to be served on a person in another State in which the Service Regulation does not apply but which is a party to the Hague Convention, that document must be served in accordance with the provisions of the Hague Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who can make a request for service of documents outside the State in civil proceedings in the District Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A witness in the trial","A court bailiff","A judge presiding over the case","A party, a solicitor acting for a party, or a Clerk"],"justification":"A request for service of documents outside the State in civil proceedings in the District Court may be made by: (a) a party; a solicitor acting for a party; or a Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Lodgment of documents for service* 11.(1) A request for service of documents outside the State in civil proceedings in the District Court may be made by: - (a) a party; - a solicitor acting for a party; or - a Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a person requests service of a document abroad under the Service Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Service of documents abroad is not permitted under the Service Regulation.","The person requesting service must pay an international fee equivalent to the local court fees.","The relevant provisions of Order of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply instead.","The relevant provisions of Order of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case."],"justification":"the relevant provisions of [Order 11D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-11D-Superior-Service-of-Documents-Outside-of-the-Jurisdiction-but-within-the-EU-Regulation-No-1393-2007) of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service Regulation* (2) A person requesting service of a document abroad under the Service Regulation must lodge with the Transmitting Agency as appropriate: - a request for service of the document in the form specified in the Annex to the Service Regulation, and a copy thereof; - two copies of the document to be served, and an additional copy for each person to be served; - (iii) a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept, unless that document is already in one of those languages; - an undertaking to pay the costs of service, payment or reimbursement of which these may be sought by the Receiving Agency of the State addressed; and the relevant provisions of [Order 11D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-11D-Superior-Service-of-Documents-Outside-of-the-Jurisdiction-but-within-the-EU-Regulation-No-1393-2007) of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a document is already in one of the official languages of the state addressed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The document must still be translated into all official languages of the state.","A certified translator must sign off on the document even if it''s in an official language.","Translation is required to ensure that the document adheres to the cultural norms of the state.","No translation is required unless the state has indicated it can accept another language."],"justification":"a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept, unless that document is already in one of those languages"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Hague Convention* (3) A person requesting service of a document abroad under the Hague Convention must lodge with the Central Authority (Master of the High Court): - a request for the service of the document in the form specified in the Annex to the Hague Convention, and a copy thereof; - two copies of the document to be served, and an additional copy for each person to be served; - (iii) a translation of each document into the official language or one of the official languages of State addressed, or in another language which that State has indicated it can accept, unless that document is already in one of those languages; - an undertaking to pay the costs of service, payment or reimbursement of which these may be sought by the Central Authority of the State addressed; and the relevant provisions of [Order 11E]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-11E-Superior-Service-of-Documents-Outside-of-the-Jurisdiction-(Hague-Convention)) of the Rules of the Superior Courts apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the claimant (or their solicitor) do upon receiving a certificate of service?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Submit the certificate to the court registry.","Send the certificate to the opposing party''s attorney.","File the certificate with the local sheriff''s office.","Lodge the certificate with the Clerk."],"justification":"the claimant (or the claimant’s solicitor) must lodge the certificate with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Certificate of service* 12. (1) A certificate of service completed and forwarded under: - (a) Article 10 of the Service Regulation by the Receiving Agency; or - Article 6 of the Hague Convention by the Central Authority addressed or any authority which it may have designated for that purpose must be taken to be prima facie evidence of the facts stated in that certificate. (2) A document purporting to be such a certificate must, until the contrary is proved, be deemed to be such a certificate. (3) On receipt of a certificate mentioned in sub-rule (1), the claimant (or the claimant’s solicitor) must lodge the certificate with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be established before judgment can be given if the respondent has not appeared or defended?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["That the originating document or notice was served by a method prescribed by the internal law of the State or was actually delivered to the respondent or their residence by another method provided for by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, and that the service or delivery was in sufficient time to enable the respondent to defend.","That the originating document or notice was posted on the official government website and remained there for a period of one month.","That the originating document or notice was left at the respondent''s place of work with no proof of actual delivery to the respondent.","That the originating document or notice was sent via email to the respondent''s last known email address without requiring any confirmation of receipt."],"justification":"Where a claim notice or other document instituting proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and the respondent has not filed and served an appearance and defence or otherwise given notice of intention to defend the claim, judgment must not be given until it is established that: - (a) the originating document or notice was served by a method prescribed by the internal law of the State addressed for service of documents in domestic civil proceedings on persons within its territory, or - the document or notice was actually delivered to the respondent or to the respondent’s residence by another method provided for by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, and, in either of these cases, the service or the delivery was in sufficient time to enable the respondent to defend."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Procedure on non-appearance of the respondent* 13. (1) Where a claim notice or other document instituting proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and the respondent has not filed and served an appearance and defence or otherwise given notice of intention to defend the claim, judgment must not be given until it is established that: - (a) the originating document or notice was served by a method prescribed by the internal law of the State addressed for service of documents in domestic civil proceedings on persons within its territory, or - the document or notice was actually delivered to the respondent or to the respondent’s residence by another method provided for by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, and, in either of these cases, the service or the delivery was in sufficient time to enable the respondent to defend. (2) An application for judgment in default of appearance and defence in a case mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be made by filing an affidavit with the Clerk, but the Clerk may in any such case list the application before the Court for hearing and notify the claimant of the return date of the application. (3) At the hearing of any application in the proceedings the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is one of the conditions required for the court to give judgment without a certificate of service?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The document or notice was delivered in person by a certified process server.","The document or notice was transmitted by a method provided for in the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention.","The document or notice was posted on the court''s public bulletin board.","The document or notice was sent via email to the opposing party''s personal account."],"justification":"(a) the document or notice thereof was transmitted by a method provided for in the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Judgment may be given despite absence of certificate of service* 14. Despite rule 10, the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided by the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention has been received, if all of the following conditions are fulfilled- - (a) the document or notice thereof was transmitted by a method provided for in the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention, - a period of not less than six months, considered adequate by the Court in the particular case, has elapsed since the transmission of the document or notice, - no certificate of any kind has been received, even though every reasonable effort has been made to obtain it through the competent authorities of the State addressed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41A - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State With The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can a respondent apply to extend the time for appealing from a judgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Where a claim notice or other document instituting civil proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and judgment has been given against a respondent who has not appeared, the respondent may apply to extend the time for appealing from the judgment.","Where the respondent has fully participated in the proceedings but disagrees with the court''s decision on procedural grounds.","When the respondent has missed the deadline due to a clerical error by their legal representative, provided they can prove no fault on their part.","If the respondent wishes to appeal based on new evidence that was unavailable at the time of the original trial."],"justification":"Where a claim notice or other document instituting civil proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and judgment has been given against a respondent who has not appeared, the respondent may apply to extend the time for appealing from the judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Time for appeal may be extended* 15. (1) Where a claim notice or other document instituting civil proceedings (or notice thereof) was transmitted abroad for service under the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and judgment has been given against a respondent who has not appeared, the respondent may apply to extend the time for appealing from the judgment. (2) An application by a respondent under sub-rule (1) must be made by motion on notice and must be grounded on the affidavit of the moving party. (3) On hearing the application, if the Court is satisfied that- - (a) the application was made within a reasonable time after the respondent had knowledge of the judgment and - without any fault on his or her part, the respondent did not have knowledge of the documents in sufficient time to defend or, as the case may be, knowledge of the judgment in sufficient time to appeal, and - the respondent has a prima facie defence to the claim on the merits, the Court may extend the time for appealing from the judgment on such terms and conditions as the Court considers just. [1] Order 41A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 41A, rule substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [3] Order 41A rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 471 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/471/made/en/print?q 471&years 2018), effective 10 December 2018'),
