                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the agreement between European Community member states concerning maintenance payments?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Lisbon Treaty","The Maastricht Agreement","The Rome Convention","The Brussels Protocol"],"justification":"the “Rome Convention”"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **THE ROME CONVENTION BETWEEN THE MEMBER STATES OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES ON THE SIMPLIFICATION OF PROCEDURES FOR THE RECOVERY OF MAINTENANCE PAYMENTS (the “Rome Convention”) AND T[HE MAINTENANCE ACT 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the international agreement mentioned?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["THE NEW YORK TREATY ON INTERNATIONAL TRADE AND COMMERCE","THE LONDON CONVENTION ON THE RECOVERY ABROAD OF MAINTENANCE","[THE NEW YORK CONVENTION ON THE RECOVERY ABROAD OF MAINTENANCE]","THE BRUSSELS AGREEMENT ON CROSS-BORDER FAMILY LAW"],"justification":"[THE NEW YORK CONVENTION ON THE RECOVERY ABROAD OF MAINTENANCE]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE NEW YORK CONVENTION ON THE RECOVERY ABROAD OF MAINTENANCE](https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetailsIII.aspx?src TREATY&mtdsg_no XX-1&chapter 20&Temp mtdsg3&clang (the “New York Convention”) AND THE [MAINTENANCE ACT 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the common name given to the convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Lisbon Agreement on Trademarks","The Hague Maintenance Convention","The Geneva Convention on Diplomatic Immunities","The Vienna Convention on Consular Relations"],"justification":"(the “Hague Maintenance Convention”)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE HAGUE CONVENTION ON THE INTERNATIONAL RECOVERY OF CHILD SUPPORT AND OTHER FORMS OF FAMILY MAINTENANCE 2007](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 131) (the “Hague Maintenance Convention”)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **[THE HAGUE CONVENTION ON JURISDICTION, APPLICABLE LAW, RECOGNITION, ENFORCEMENT AND CO-OPERATION IN RESPECT OF PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY AND MEASURES FOR THE PROTECTION OF CHILDREN 1996](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 70) (the “Hague Child Convention”)** # **1 - DEFINITIONS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''1998 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998 (No. 52 of 1998)","The Human Rights Act 1998","The Data Protection Act 1998","The Freedom of Information Act 1998"],"justification":"the “**1998 Act**” means the [Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/52/enacted/en/html) (No. 52 of 1998);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Civil and commercial matters: definitions* 1. (1) In and for the purposes of Part 2 of this Order- the “**1998 Act**” means the [Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/52/enacted/en/html) (No. 52 of 1998); the “**Brussels Convention**” means the Convention on Jurisdiction and the enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters (including the Protocol annexed to that Convention) done at Brussels on the day of September, 1968, (as adjusted by the Accession Conventions of 1978, 1982, 1989 and 1996); the “**Conventions**” means the Brussels Convention, the 1971 Protocol, the 1978 Accession Convention, the 1982 Accession Convention, the 1989 Accession Convention and the 1996 Accession Convention (each as defined in section 2 of the 1998 Act); “**domiciled**” must be construed, having regard to the instrument applicable in any given case, in accordance with Articles 2 and 59 to 61 of either the Jurisdiction Regulation or the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, section 15 and the Ninth Schedule of the 1998 Act and Articles 52 and 53 of the Brussels Convention; “**judgment**” has the meaning assigned to it in section 4(1) of the 1998 Act; the **“Jurisdiction Regulation**”[3] means Regulation No 1215/2012 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 12 December 2012 on jurisdiction and the recognition and enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters (recast) (O.J. 351/1 of 20 December 2012) the “**Lugano Convention**” means the Convention on jurisdiction and the enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters, done at Lugano on the day of October 2007, as approved on behalf of the European Community by Council Decision of 27 November 2008, as given further effect in the State by the 1998 Act as amended by the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (Amendment) Act 2012, and includes the Protocols and Annexes; “**Member State**” means a member state of the European Union in which the Jurisdiction Regulation applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''1976 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 (No.11 of 1976)","The Family Law (Custody of Children) Act 1976 (No. 10 of 1976)","The Family Law (Marriage and Divorce) Act 1976 (No. 12 of 1976)","The Family Law (Property Settlements) Act 1976 (No. 13 of 1976)"],"justification":"the “**1976 Act**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No.11 of 1976);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Maintenance matters: definitions* (2) In and for the purposes of Parts 3 to 7 of this Order: the “**1976 Act**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No.11 of 1976); the “**1994 Act**” means the [Maintenance Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28) (No. 28 of 1994); the “**2011 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Maintenance) Regulations 2011 ([S.I. No. 274 of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print#:~:text 274/2011 - European Communities (Maintenance) Regulations 2011.,-View SI&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of June, 2011.&text 1.,Communities (Maintenance) Regulations 2011.)) as amended by the European Communities (Maintenance)(Amendment) Regulations 2011 ([S.I. No. 612 of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/612/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,612/2011 - European Communities (Maintenance,) (Amendment) Regulations 2011.&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2011.&text 1.,) (Amendment) Regulations 2011.)); [4] “**2019 Regulations**” means the European Union (Hague Maintenance Convention) Regulations 2019 ([S.I. No. 594 of 2019](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print#:~:text 594/2019 - European Union (Hague Maintenance Convention) Regulations 2019,-View SI&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2019.&text Citation-,1.,Hague Maintenance Convention) Regulations 2019.)); “**Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation**” means the Minister for Justice and Equality as designated by Regulation 16 of the 2011 Regulations (but includes any other person for the time being designated by the State to discharge in or for the State the duties imposed by the Maintenance Regulation on such an authority); “**Central Authority under the 1994 Act**” means a Central Authority appointed by order of the Minister for Justice and Equality under section 4(1)(a) of the 1994 Act to discharge the functions required of it under the 1994 Act or required of a Central Authority under the Rome Convention or of a transmitting agency or receiving agency under the New York Convention; “**central authority of a Member State**” means the person designated by a Member State in which Chapter VII of the Maintenance Regulation applies to discharge in or for that State (in accordance with Article 49 of the Maintenance Regulation) the duties imposed by the Maintenance Regulation on such an authority; “**central authority of a reciprocating jurisdiction**”, when used in the context of proceedings under Part III of the 1994 Act, means:-'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who qualifies as a ''claimant'' in the context of maintenance matters?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A claimant can only be defined as a legal entity or corporation that operates within the boundaries of a Member State and is pursuing financial compensation under the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005.","A claimant refers to an individual who has been granted citizenship in a Member State and is seeking social welfare benefits under the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005.","A claimant is exclusively a person residing outside of any Member State or designated jurisdiction who seeks to recover maintenance from within the State.","A claimant can be a person residing in a Member State or a designated jurisdiction, or a person residing in the State, including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005, who claims entitlement to receive or recover maintenance."],"justification":"“**claimant**” means, according to the context, either:- - (a) a person residing in a Member State (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in a designated jurisdiction (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a Member State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the [Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a designated jurisdiction;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) the central authority of such a jurisdiction which has been designated pursuant to paragraph 1 or, where appropriate, paragraph 2 of Article 2 of the Rome Convention, or - an authority of such a jurisdiction with functions corresponding to those exercisable by the Central Authority within the State; “**central authority of a designated jurisdiction**” means:- - (a) a transmitting or receiving agency in a state which is a contracting party to the New York Convention, or - an authority of a designated jurisdiction with functions corresponding to those exercisable by the Central Authority within the State; “**claimant**” means, according to the context, either:- - (a) a person residing in a Member State (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in a designated jurisdiction (including any body which under the law of that jurisdiction is entitled to exercise the rights of redress of or to represent that person) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to receive maintenance from a person residing in the State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005) and claiming pursuant to the Maintenance Regulation to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a Member State, or - a person residing in the State (including a competent authority within the meaning of Part 12 (Liability to Maintain Family) of the [Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) and claiming pursuant to Part III of the 1994 Act to be entitled to recover maintenance from a person residing in a designated jurisdiction; “**Contracting State**”, - (a) when used in the context of proceedings under the Brussels Convention, has the meaning assigned to it in section 4(1) of the 1998 Act,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Maintenance Regulation'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Council Regulation 4/2010 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1).","Council Regulation 4/2009 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1).","Council Regulation 4/2009 of 18 December 2009 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1).","Council Regulation 5/2009 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1)."],"justification":"Council Regulation 4/2009 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- when used in the context of proceedings under the Lugano Convention, means a State in respect of which that Convention has entered into force or taken effect in accordance with Article 69 or 72 thereof; “**designated jurisdiction**” means:- - (a) any state which is a contracting party to the New York Convention, or - any other state or jurisdiction which is declared by order of the Minister for Foreign Affairs to be a designated jurisdiction for the purposes of Part III of the 1994 Act; “**domiciled**” and “**habitually resident**”, when used in relation to maintenance proceedings, must be construed in accordance with the Maintenance Regulation; [5] “**the terms “2007 Hague Protocol**” and “**enforcement order**”, have the meanings assigned to them respectively in Regulation 2 of the 2011 Regulations; “the terms “**decision**”, “**enforceable maintenance order**” and “**maintenance debtor**” each have the meaning assigned to them respectively in Regulation 2 of the 2011 Regulations or, as the context requires, Regulation 2 of the 2019 Regulations; “**Hague Maintenance Convention**” means the Convention on the International Recovery of Child Support and Other Forms of Family Maintenance done at The Hague on 23 November 2007; “**maintenance creditor**” includes any body which, under the law of a reciprocating jurisdiction, is entitled to exercise their rights of redress of, or to represent, the creditor, and references in these Rules to a maintenance creditor or to a claimant (as defined herein) must be construed as including references to the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention; the “**Maintenance Regulation**” means Council Regulation 4/2009 of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1); “**Member State**”, when used in relation to maintenance proceedings, means a member state of the European Union in which the relevant provision of the Maintenance Regulation applies;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Hague Convention'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Hague Convention of 15 November 1965 on the Service Abroad of Judicial and Extrajudicial Documents in Civil or Commercial Matters","The Hague Convention of 25 October 1980 on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction","The Hague Convention of 18 October 1954 on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction","The Hague Convention of 1954 on the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict"],"justification":"“**Hague Convention**” means the Hague Convention of 15 November 1965 on the Service Abroad of Judicial and Extrajudicial Documents in Civil or Commercial Matters"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Service: definitions (3) In this Order: “**Hague Convention**” means the Hague Convention of 15 November 1965 on the Service Abroad of Judicial and Extrajudicial Documents in Civil or Commercial Matters “**Service Regulation**” has the same meaning as in [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 1. # **2 - CROSS-BORDER CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL PROCEEDINGS IN THE STATE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Where can such proceedings be brought, heard and determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business only if it is held in the specific district court nearest to the place where the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business located exclusively in the capital city of the country where the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of criminal business for the Court area in which the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation."],"justification":"the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Venue in cross-border insurance matters* 2.[6] When it is proposed to bring proceedings before the District Court by virtue of: - (a) Article 11 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, or - Article 9 of the Lugano Convention, or - Article 8.2 of the Brussels Convention, (all of which relate to insurance matters) against an insurer domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State and the policy-holder is domiciled in the State, the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the policy-holder is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What types of regulations/articles allow a consumer domiciled in the State to bring proceedings against a party domiciled in another Member/Contracting State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Article 15 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 17 of the Hague Convention, or Article 9 of the Brussels Convention","Article 21 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 13 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 19 of the Brussels Regulation","Article 7 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 20 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 12 of the Brussels Convention","Article 18 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 16 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 14 of the Brussels Convention."],"justification":"by virtue of: - (a) Article 18 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, or - Article 16 of the Lugano Convention, or - Article 14 of the Brussels Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Venue in cross-border consumer contract claims* 3.[7] When a consumer who is domiciled in the State proposes to bring proceedings before the District Court by virtue of: - (a) Article 18 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, or - Article 16 of the Lugano Convention, or - Article 14 of the Brussels Convention (all of which relate to consumer contracts) against the other party to a contract and that other party is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, the proceedings may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the Court area in which the consumer is ordinarily resident or carries on any profession, business or occupation'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served on a person domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State when they are not or are not known or believed to be a citizen of Ireland?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Notice of the document commencing the proceedings in Form must be served, not the document itself.","The physical document initiating the proceedings must be mailed to their last known address.","The summons and complaint must be served personally by a bailiff.","An electronic copy of the court order must be sent via email to their known address."],"justification":"notice of the document commencing the proceedings in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and not the document itself must be served on that person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Beginning proceedings against a person domiciled abroad* 5. (1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), service of proceedings begun in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 of this Order and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention) without prior permission of the Court. (2) When proceedings are instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or the Lugano Convention against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State and that person is not or is not known or believed to be a citizen of Ireland, notice of the document commencing the proceedings in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and not the document itself must be served on that person. (3) A claimant or claimant’s solicitor may begin such proceedings by completing, signing, stamping (if so required) the claim notice or other document beginning the proceedings and filing it, together with duly completed originals and copies of the notice ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and of a certificate in the [Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the Clerk for the Court area for which the proceedings are to be issued. (4) The Clerk must stamp them with the official stamp showing the date of issue and return the documents to the claimant or claimant’s solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence when documents are served in any non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["four weeks","three months","eight weeks","six weeks"],"justification":"Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State, the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least six weeks from the date of service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) A notice and certificate returned under sub-rule (3) must be served on the respondent as indicated in rule 4 (which may include service by post provided that if such service is into a Contracting State in which the Hague Convention applies, the State of destination has not made an objection to such service under Article 10(a) of the Hague Convention) or, where appropriate, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court). (6) Where the documents are to be served in the European territory of another Member State or Contracting State the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least five weeks from the date of service. Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State or Contracting State, the time permitted for filing and entering an appearance and defence must be at least six weeks from the date of service. (7) On receipt of the certificate of service prescribed in Article 10 and the Annex of the Service Regulation or Article 6 of the Hague Convention, the claimant (or solicitor for the claimant) must lodge with the Clerk the originals of: - the claim notice, civil summons or other document instituting the proceedings, - (where appropriate) the notice of commencement of proceedings ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1)) which was served, - the certificate ([Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1)) which was served, and - the certificate of service, at least four days before the date on which the proceedings are first listed before the Court. (8) Where service has been effected by registered post or insured post the following provisions must apply- - (a) the claimant or claimant’s solicitor must, not earlier than ten days after the date of posting, lodge with the Clerk the relevant documents listed in sub-rule (7), together with a statutory declaration as to service of the documents posted, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned);'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'When are documents issued for service deemed to have been served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At the moment the documents are dropped off at the post office.","At the time the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post.","Upon the posting of the documents with proof of postage.","When the recipient signs for the documents upon delivery."],"justification":"the documents issued for service must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, Article 15 of the Hague Convention, be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the documents issued for service must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, Article 15 of the Hague Convention, be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post; - the statutory declaration as to service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the said Article 15 of the Hague Convention, together be deemed to be sufficient evidence of service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What applies to such cases subject to sub-rule (1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The requirements of rule 4 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly.","The requirements of rule 5 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly.","The requirements of rule 6 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly.","The requirements of sub-rule (2) apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly."],"justification":"Subject to sub-rule (1), the requirements of rule 5 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Where the respondent is a citizen of Ireland* 6. (1) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or the Lugano Convention against a person who is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, and that person is a citizen of Ireland, the claim notice or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice of the document). (2) Subject to sub-rule (1), the requirements of rule 5 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a respondent file if they intend to appear or be represented for defending the proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An application for summary judgment","A declaration of non-participation in the proceedings","An appearance in proceedings begun by claim notice, or a notice of appearance and intention to defend in proceedings begun by civil summons or other document.","A formal complaint against the initiating party"],"justification":"in proceedings begun by claim notice, an appearance; or - in proceedings begun by civil summons or other document, a notice of appearance and intention to defend"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Appearance and defence* 7.[8] Where, in proceedings to which rule 5 or rule 6 relates, a respondent intends to appear or to be represented at the hearing for the purpose of: - (a) defending the proceedings and/or, - by virtue of Article 26 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 24 of the Lugano Convention, or Article 18 of the Brussels Convention for the purpose of contesting the jurisdiction of the Court, the respondent or respondent’s solicitor must file: - in proceedings begun by claim notice, an appearance; or - in proceedings begun by civil summons or other document, a notice of appearance and intention to defend so soon as to reach the Clerk within the period of five weeks or, as the case may be, six weeks, prescribed by rule 5(6) and within the same period serve a copy on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor (together with a defence, where required). Where the respondent contests the jurisdiction of the Court, the appearance must include a statement to that effect.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk produce to the Court at the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 5 or 6?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Any communication or correspondence received from the respondent","Any communication or correspondence received from the applicant","The original complaint filed by the applicant","Any financial records pertaining to the case"],"justification":"the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Hearing of proceedings* 8. (1) The provisions of [Order 47A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47A-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Non-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default in Non-Debt Claims) apply to proceedings to which this Part relates with the modifications identified in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims). (2) At the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 5 or 6, the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the claimant show to the court if applying for judgment by default when the respondent has not filed an appearance?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The claimant must establish that the claim is of a value above a certain monetary threshold set by the court.","The claimant must demonstrate that the respondent has agreed to the terms of the claim in writing.","The claimant must show to the satisfaction of the Court that each claim made in the document instituting the proceedings is one which, by virtue of the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine; that no other Court has exclusive jurisdiction within the meaning of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention to hear and determine any such claim; that no proceedings involving the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State or, as the case may be, in another Contracting State; that the respondent was duly served with the document beginning the proceedings or notice of that document; and that the respondent has been able to receive the document beginning the proceedings or notice in sufficient time to enable him or her to arrange for his or her defence, or all necessary steps have been taken to this end, as required by Article 28 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 26 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 20 of the Brussels Convention.","The claimant must prove that the respondent has previously been found guilty of similar claims in another jurisdiction."],"justification":"the claimant must, if applying for judgment by default, show to the satisfaction of the Court- - (a) that each claim made in the document instituting the proceedings is one which, by virtue of the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine, - that no other Court has exclusive jurisdiction within the meaning of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention to hear and determine any such claim, - that no proceedings involving the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State or, as the case may be, in another Contracting State, - that the respondent was duly served with the document beginning the proceedings or notice of that document, and - [9] that the respondent has been able to receive the document beginning the proceedings or notice in sufficient time to enable him or her to arrange for his or her defence, or all necessary steps have been taken to this end, as required by Article 28 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 26 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 20 of the Brussels Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Where the respondent does not appear (3) Where the respondent fails to appear and is not represented at the hearing, the Court may, if it considers it necessary to do so, require the production of the advice of delivery form confirming delivery to the respondent or to the respondent’s address of the envelope containing the copy documents for service referred to in rule 5(5). (4) Where the respondent has not filed an appearance, the claimant must, if applying for judgment by default, show to the satisfaction of the Court- - (a) that each claim made in the document instituting the proceedings is one which, by virtue of the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Conventions or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention, the Court has jurisdiction to hear and determine, - that no other Court has exclusive jurisdiction within the meaning of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, the Lugano Convention to hear and determine any such claim, - that no proceedings involving the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State or, as the case may be, in another Contracting State, - that the respondent was duly served with the document beginning the proceedings or notice of that document, and - [9] that the respondent has been able to receive the document beginning the proceedings or notice in sufficient time to enable him or her to arrange for his or her defence, or all necessary steps have been taken to this end, as required by Article 28 of the Jurisdiction Regulation; Article 26 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 20 of the Brussels Convention (5) Where the respondent has filed an appearance or otherwise given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment must not be given until the requirements of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, Article 15 of the Hague Convention (as set out in [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 10) have been complied with.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the claimant do after obtaining a judgment against a respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The claimant (or claimant’s solicitor) must immediately notify the respondent of having obtained the judgment.","The claimant must serve the judgment to the respondent via certified mail within 7 days.","The claimant must file an appeal within 14 days of obtaining the judgment.","The claimant must pay the court fees within 30 days of obtaining the judgment."],"justification":"Where the Court gives judgment against a respondent in proceedings to which this rule relates, the claimant, (or claimant’s solicitor) must immediately notify the respondent of having obtained the judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Notwithstanding sub-rule (5), the Court may give judgment even if no certificate of service or delivery as provided for by the Service Regulation or by the Hague Convention has been received, if all the conditions listed in Article 19 of the Service Regulation or Article 15 of the Hague Convention (as set out in [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 14) are fulfilled. (7) Where the Court gives judgment against a respondent in proceedings to which this rule relates, the claimant, (or claimant’s solicitor) must immediately notify the respondent of having obtained the judgment. (8) Where judgment has been given in such proceedings against a respondent who has not appeared and the respondent wishes to apply for an extension of time for appeal from the judgment, the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 15 apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must an interested party lodge with the Clerk when requesting the provision of documents for a judgment given in the District Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["One original and three copies of the judgment, a certificate in duplicate in Form Schedule and an original and two copies of the document or documents establishing service of notice.","Two originals and one copy of the judgment, a single certificate in Form Schedule and no requirement for any additional documents related to the service of notice.","An original and one copy of the judgment, a certificate in triplicate in Form Schedule and an original and three copies of the document or documents establishing service of notice.","An original and two copies of the judgment, a certificate in duplicate in Form Schedule and where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent."],"justification":"An interested party who, for the purposes of Articles 53 and 54 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 46 and 47 of the Brussels Convention, requests the provision of the documents mentioned in section 14 of the 1998 Act in respect of a judgment given in the District Court, must lodge with the Clerk for the Court area in which the judgment was given - - (a) an original and two copies of the judgment duly completed, - a certificate in duplicate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and - where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Enforcement of judgments abroad: provision of documents* 9.[10] (1) An interested party who, for the purposes of Articles 53 and 54 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 46 and 47 of the Brussels Convention, requests the provision of the documents mentioned in section 14 of the 1998 Act in respect of a judgment given in the District Court, must lodge with the Clerk for the Court area in which the judgment was given - - (a) an original and two copies of the judgment duly completed, - a certificate in duplicate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and - where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent. (2) When the judgment has been signed by the Judge and served in accordance with the provisions of rule 10, the Clerk must give to the party requesting them a duly authenticated copy of the judgment, a certificate in the [Form 41B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/570d3fb1-8040-4d38-a129-5fb61dbd8af0/Certificate as to judgment No. 41B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a certified true copy or copies of the document or documents referred to in sub-rule and must retain the other documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done when serving a judgment on a respondent outside the state?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part.","Service must be effected directly by the court of the state where the respondent resides, regardless of the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention.","Service can be effected by any third party within the state without regard to the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention.","Service must be effected by or on behalf of the respondent in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part."],"justification":"Where, for the purposes of Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 53 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 47 of the Brussels Convention, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a judgment given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Service of judgment and proof of service* 10.[11] (1) Where, for the purposes of Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, Article 53 of the Lugano Convention or, as the case may be, Article 47 of the Brussels Convention, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a judgment given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or the Hague Convention and this Part. (2) When service has been effected and duly certified, the certificate of service or, where appropriate, the certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service and the advice of delivery form, must be lodged with the Clerk for retention with the original judgment. (3) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the documents referred to in Article 47.1 of the Brussels Convention, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the [Form 41B.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e30f0b06-b26a-4e7b-b6f1-2ea34fd31f4b/Certificate that a judgment is enforceable No. 41B.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule (with any necessary modifications) and a certified copy or copies of the relevant document or documents lodged under sub-rule (2). (4) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the certificate referred to in Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the form in Annex to the Jurisdiction Regulation; (5) On the request of a party applying for enforcement of a judgment for the provision of the certificate referred to in Article 54 of the Lugano Convention, the Clerk must give to that party a certificate in the form in Annex to the Lugano Convention 339/3 of 21 December 2007). # **3 - CROSS-BORDER MAINTENANCE PROCEEDINGS IN THE STATE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Maintenance Regulation*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What regulations apply when serving documents in a non-EU country that adheres to the Hague Convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Geneva Conventions and its Articles 5 to 8","The Hague Convention and its Articles 8 to 11","The Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations and its Articles 12 to 15","The New York Convention on the Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign Arbitral Awards and its Articles 3 to 6"],"justification":"When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another State which is a state in which the Service Regulation does not apply but in which the Hague Convention applies, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 8 to 11) of the Hague Convention and this Part."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Application of the Hague Convention or Service Regulation* 12. (1) The provisions of the Service Regulation or of the Hague Convention apply, where relevant, to proceedings brought in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation. (2) When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another Member State, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 7 to 10) of the Service Regulation and this Part. (3) When any document for use in such proceedings is required by this Part to be served on a person in another State which is a state in which the Service Regulation does not apply but in which the Hague Convention applies, service must be effected in accordance with the provisions (including Articles 8 to 11) of the Hague Convention and this Part.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'When can proceedings be initiated against a person domiciled abroad without prior court permission?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings may be initiated if they are instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, without any need for court permission.","Proceedings may be initiated if they are instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State.","Proceedings may be initiated if they are instituted in the District Court by virtue of the 2011 Regulations alone, against a person who is not domiciled in the State.","Proceedings may be initiated if they are instituted in the High Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State."],"justification":"service of proceedings which may be instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention), without prior permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Beginning proceedings against a person domiciled abroad* 13. (1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), service of proceedings which may be instituted in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation and the 2011 Regulations against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State may be effected (in accordance with rule 4 and, where applicable, the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as the case may be, the Hague Convention), without prior permission of the Court. (2) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, and that person is not or is not known or believed to be a citizen of Ireland, notice of the document beginning the proceedings (in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule and not the document itself must be served on that person. (3) A claimant or claimant’s solicitor may begin proceedings mentioned in sub-rule (2) by completing, signing, stamping (if so required) the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings and filing it, together with duly completed originals and copies of the notice ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule and of a certificate in the [Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the Clerk for the Court area for which the proceedings are to be issued. (4) The Clerk must stamp the documents showing the date of filing and must, having regard to the provisions of sub-rule (6), list the proceedings for hearing before the Court. (5) Having recorded the place, date and time of hearing on the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings and the notices, the Clerk must return all documents to the claimant or claimant’s solicitor. (6) A notice and certificate returned under sub-rule (5) must be served as indicated in rule 12 or, where appropriate, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), on the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How many weeks before the court sitting must documents be served in a non-European territory of another Member State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least two weeks","At least six weeks","At least eight weeks","At least four weeks"],"justification":"Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State, they must be served at least six weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(7) Where the documents are to be served in the European territory of another Member State they must be served at least five weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing. (8) Where the documents are to be served in any non-European territory of another Member State, they must be served at least six weeks before the date of sitting of the Court before which the proceedings have been listed for hearing. (9) On receipt of the certificate of service prescribed in Article 10 and the Annex of the Service Regulation, the claimant (or claimant’s solicitor) must lodge with the Clerk the originals of: - the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, - (where appropriate) the notice that proceedings have been begun ([Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule which was served, - the certificate ([Form 41B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/39e0efb3-d336-4a9a-a96e-9cec08b71e5e/Certificate as to jurisdiction No. 41B.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule which was served, and - the certificate of service, at least four days before the date of the sitting of the Court. (10) Where service has been effected by registered post or insured post the following provisions apply- - (a) the claimant or claimant''s solicitor must, not earlier than ten days after the date of posting, lodge with the Clerk the relevant documents listed in sub-rule (9), together with a statutory declaration as to service of the documents posted, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form (when returned); - the documents issued for service must be deemed to have been issued at the time at which the envelope containing the copies for service was posted; - the documents must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation, be deemed to have been served at the time at which the envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post; - the statutory declaration as to service, the certificate of posting and the advice of delivery form must, subject to the provisions of Article 9 of the Service Regulation together be deemed to be sufficient evidence of service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'When can a maintenance summons or other document beginning proceedings be served directly on a respondent who is a citizen of Ireland?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the respondent is a citizen of Ireland and has been absent from the State for more than one year, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served directly.","When the respondent is a citizen of Ireland and is habitually resident in another country, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served directly.","When the respondent is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served directly rather than just giving notice thereof.","When the respondent is domiciled or habitually resident in the State, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served directly."],"justification":"When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, and that person is a citizen of Ireland, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice thereof)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Where the respondent is a citizen of Ireland* 14. (1) When proceedings are begun in the District Court by virtue of the Maintenance Regulation against a person who is neither domiciled nor habitually resident in the State, and that person is a citizen of Ireland, the maintenance summons or other document beginning the proceedings, with necessary modifications, may be served (rather than notice thereof). (2) Subject to sub-rule (1), the requirements of rule 13 apply in such cases and must be construed accordingly. Two notices of appearance and intention to defend must be served in each case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What additional action must a respondent take if they intend to appear or be represented at the hearing to contest the jurisdiction of the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The respondent or their solicitor must also verbally notify the claimant or their solicitor of their intent to appear or be represented at the hearing.","The respondent or their solicitor must also complete, detach and send by post to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant the other notice of appearance and intention to defend received.","The respondent or their solicitor must also complete and send an affidavit confirming their intention to contest the jurisdiction of the court.","The respondent or their solicitor must also submit an electronic copy of the notice of appearance and intention to defend to the court via email."],"justification":"and must at the same time complete, detach and send by post to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant the other such Notice received."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Notice of appearance and intention to defend* 15. Where, in proceedings to which rule 13 or rule 14 relates, a respondent intends to appear or to be represented at the hearing: - (a) for the purpose of defending the proceedings and/or, - by virtue of Article 5 of the Maintenance Regulation for the purpose of contesting the jurisdiction of the Court, the respondent or his or her solicitor must complete, detach and send by post to the Clerk one of the notices of appearance and intention to defend which were received so soon as to reach the Clerk not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing, and must at the same time complete, detach and send by post to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant the other such Notice received.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk produce at the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 13 or rule 14?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The list of witnesses to be called during the hearing","Any communication or correspondence received from the respondent","Minutes of previous meetings between the parties","Any documents related to the petitioner"],"justification":"At the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 13 or rule 14, the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Hearing of proceedings* 16. (1) Subject to this rule, the provisions of [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) apply to proceedings to which this Part relates. (2) The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default) and [Order 47A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47A-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Non-Debt-Claims) (Judgment in Default in Non-Debt Claims) do not apply to proceedings to which this Part relates. (3) At the hearing of proceedings referred to in rule 13 or rule 14, the Clerk must produce to the Court any communication or correspondence received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a party file with the Clerk when requesting the provision of documents under Article 20 or Article 28 of the Maintenance Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An original and three copies of the application form and a certified copy of the parties'' identification documents.","One original and two copies of the motion for summary judgment, accompanied by all relevant case law citations.","An original and two copies of the order recording the decision, and where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent.","Two originals and one copy of the affidavit supporting the request, along with a notarized letter from the attorney stating the urgency of the case."],"justification":"must file with the Clerk for the Court area in which the decision was given an original and two copies of the order recording the decision and, where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Enforcement of judgments abroad: provision of documents* 17. (1) A party who requests the provision of the documents mentioned in Article 20 or, as the case may be, Article 28, of the Maintenance Regulation- - (a) must file with the Clerk for the Court area in which the decision was given an original and two copies of the order recording the decision and, where appropriate, an original and copy or copies of the document or documents establishing that notice of the institution of proceedings was served on the respondent, and - must provide the Clerk with any additional information required by the Clerk. (2) When the order has been signed and served in accordance with the provisions of rule 18, the Clerk must give to the party requesting them a duly authenticated copy of the order recording the decision, the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the Maintenance Regulation and a certified true copy or copies of the other documents referred to in sub-rule 1(a), and must retain the other original documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be filed with the Clerk after service has been effected?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["petition, cross-petition, and response to petition","writ of summons, notice of motion, and order of court","certificate of service, certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service, and advice of delivery form","affidavit of service, notice of appearance, and motion for summary judgment"],"justification":"the certificate of service or, where appropriate, the certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service and the advice of delivery form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Service of decision and proof of service* 18. (1) Where, for the purposes of enforcing a decision under the Maintenance Regulation, it is necessary to serve on a respondent a decision given at a sitting of the District Court, service must be effected by or on behalf of the claimant and in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation (or, where applicable, the Hague Convention) and this Part. (2) When service has been effected and duly certified, the certificate of service or, where appropriate, the certificate of posting, statutory declaration as to service and the advice of delivery form, must be filed with the Clerk for retention with the original judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application to the District Court under Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The payment of a specified amount of money by the applicant to the respondent as a form of initial settlement.","The issue and service on the respondent of the appropriate summons or notice of application mentioned in Order 54 or, where appropriate, notice thereof in Form Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is outside the State.","An oral agreement between the applicant and the respondent regarding the terms of maintenance.","The filing of a formal complaint with the local law enforcement agency related to the maintenance dispute."],"justification":"must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of the appropriate summons or notice of application mentioned in [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) or, where appropriate, notice thereof in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is outside the State, and the provisions of this Part apply to any such application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Application for variation or revocation by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation* 19. (1) An application to the District Court being brought- - (a) by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation, by a maintenance creditor domiciled in the State against a maintenance debtor outside the State, or - by virtue of Chapter of the Maintenance Regulation, by a maintenance creditor outside the State against a maintenance debtor habitually resident or domiciled in the State must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of the appropriate summons or notice of application mentioned in [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) or, where appropriate, notice thereof in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is outside the State, and the provisions of this Part apply to any such application. (2) An order of the Court granting any such application must be served on a party within the State by registered post and on a party outside the State in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation (or, where applicable, the Hague Convention) and this Part.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How should the Clerk receiving the forwarded documents proceed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Proceed by treating the documents as if they were received from a local magistrate''s office.","Proceed by sending the documents back to the originating court for reissuance.","Proceed as if the copy of the maintenance order and the copy of the enforcement order had been received from the Master of the High Court.","Proceed as if the documents had been received directly from the parties involved in the case."],"justification":"The Clerk receiving the documents must proceed as if the copy of the maintenance order and the copy of the enforcement order had been received from the Master of the High Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Transmission of documents on change of address by maintenance debtor* 20. (1) Where a maintenance debtor ceases to reside in the Court area in which the proceedings have been registered and commences to reside elsewhere in the State, the Clerk for the first Court area must forward to the Clerk for the Court area in which the maintenance debtor is for the time being residing the following documents- - (a) a copy of the maintenance order and a copy of the relevant enforcement order or, as the case may be, a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the Maintenance Regulation, of the decision issued by the court of origin, - a certificate of arrears in the [Form 41B.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/795a1a10-42a3-486a-966b-ab7e17fa3a97/Certificate of arrears No. 41B.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule - a copy of the variation order (if any), - any other relevant document. (2) The Clerk receiving the documents must proceed as if the copy of the maintenance order and the copy of the enforcement order had been received from the Master of the High Court. # **4 - ENFORCEMENT OF MAINTENANCE ORDERS UNDER THE MAINTENANCE REGULATION AND THE 2011 REGULATIONS: DECISIONS GIVEN IN A MEMBER STATE BOUND BY THE 2007 HAGUE PROTOCOL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Appropriate Clerk to register decisions* 21. (1) Where a maintenance creditor or the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation wishes to seek the enforcement in the State of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation, the party or the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation must send to the Clerk for the appropriate Court area for the district referred to in Regulation 3, 4 or 6 (as the case may be) of the 2011 Regulations (in this Part, the “appropriate Clerk”) the documents referred to in Article 20 of the Maintenance Regulation. (2) Where the Central Authority makes a request under Regulation 17(6) of the 2011 Regulations that payments of maintenance be made directly to the maintenance creditor, the Clerk must enter the matter before the Court. (3) On receipt of the documents, the Clerk must - - (a) register particulars of the decision concerned, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used to inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the decision?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"by notice in the [Form 41B.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a5caee07-b1a3-4ad1-aca2-9bff1c1e104f/Notice of registration No. 41B.05.docx/docx/1) Schedule inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the decision."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Notice to maintenance debtor* - by notice in the [Form 41B.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a5caee07-b1a3-4ad1-aca2-9bff1c1e104f/Notice of registration No. 41B.05.docx/docx/1) Schedule inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the decision. (4) The notice must be sent by registered prepaid post and a copy must also be sent by registered prepaid post to the person on whose behalf registration was sought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What action must the appropriate Clerk take when a decision is varied or revoked?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Register the variation or revocation only in a private database, not informing the maintenance debtor.","Notify the maintenance creditor of the decision without registering any particulars.","Inform the maintenance debtor verbally instead of providing a written notice.","Register particulars of the variation or revocation and inform the maintenance debtor by notice."],"justification":"Where a decision referred to in sub-rule (1) has been varied or revoked by the court which made the decision and the appropriate Clerk has received the documents referred to in Article 20 of the Maintenance Regulation in respect of the variation or revocation, he or she must register particulars thereof and must by notice inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the variation or revocation order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Appropriate Clerk to register particulars of variation etc.* (5) Where a decision referred to in sub-rule (1) has been varied or revoked by the court which made the decision and the appropriate Clerk has received the documents referred to in Article 20 of the Maintenance Regulation in respect of the variation or revocation, he or she must register particulars thereof and must by notice inform the maintenance debtor of the registration of the variation or revocation order. (6) This rule does not limit the ability of a party who has not complied with sub-rule (1) to invoke in the State a decision recognised within the meaning of Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation otherwise than for the purpose of enforcement of the decision.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a District Court Clerk do upon receiving a copy of a maintenance order or an order varying or revoking such an order, along with the relevant enforcement or recognition order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Forward the documents to the relevant enforcement agency for immediate action.","Register particulars of each document received.","File the documents in a separate archive without registration.","Notify the parties involved via email about the receipt of the documents."],"justification":"the Clerk must register particulars of each document received."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Registration of orders [13]* 23.(1) Where a copy of a maintenance order or a copy of an order varying or revoking such an order, in respect of which an enforcement order has been made under the 2011 Regulations or a recognition order has been made under the 2019 Regulations, is received together with a copy of the relevant enforcement order or recognition order by a District Court Clerk from the Master of the High Court or the Central Authority, the Clerk must register particulars of each document received. (2) If the enforcement order or, as the case may be, recognition order, referred to in sub-rule (1) has been made in respect of a maintenance order or an order varying a maintenance order, the Clerk must send by registered post to the maintenance creditor and the maintenance debtor a notice in the [Form 41B.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f2fd74b9-1423-42da-9391-aa5ddad30330/Notice of registration No. 41B.06.docx/docx/1) or as the case may be, [Form 41B.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1a74011e-939f-4a0a-bf4e-157899a22307/Notice of Registration District Court Maintenance Rules 202 of 2021 No 41B.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) If the enforcement order or, as the case may be, recognition order, referred to in sub-rule (1) has been made in respect of an order revoking a maintenance order, the Clerk must send by registered prepaid post to the maintenance debtor a copy of the revocation order and a statement of any amounts still due and payable under the maintenance order, which statement must contain, or be sent together with, an endorsement to the like effect as the endorsement on a notice under sub-rule (2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can a District Court Clerk do if they notice sums payable under an enforceable maintenance order are in arrears and no request under Regulation 10(9) has been received?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk may notify the maintenance creditor of the means of enforcement available in respect of the order.","The Clerk may amend the maintenance order to reduce the arrears.","The Clerk may increase the sums payable without notifying the parties involved.","The Clerk may immediately garnish the debtor''s wages without further notice."],"justification":"Where it appears to a District Court Clerk that any sums payable to him or her under an enforceable maintenance order for transmission to the maintenance creditor are in arrears and he or she has received no request in writing under the said Regulation 10(9) in relation thereto, the Clerk may in his or her discretion, having considered the extent of the arrears and any other relevant matter, notify the maintenance creditor of the means of enforcement available in respect of the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Request from maintenance creditor* 24. (1) When a District Court Clerk receives a request in writing from a maintenance creditor under Regulation 10(9) of the 2011 Regulations in relation to any sum payable by virtue of an enforceable maintenance order but not duly paid, the Clerk may proceed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 56]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-56-District-Attachment-Of-Earnings) (Attachment of Earnings) or rules 3 and 4 (but not rules 7 and 8) of [Order 57]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url proceedings-under--section-8-of-the-enforcement-of-court-orders-act-1940-etc) (Proceedings under section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940). (2) Where it appears to a District Court Clerk that any sums payable to him or her under an enforceable maintenance order for transmission to the maintenance creditor are in arrears and he or she has received no request in writing under the said Regulation 10(9) in relation thereto, the Clerk may in his or her discretion, having considered the extent of the arrears and any other relevant matter, notify the maintenance creditor of the means of enforcement available in respect of the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How must the order of the Court granting the application be served on a party domiciled in another Member State or Contracting State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["In accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, the Hague Convention (including Articles 8 to 11 thereof).","Through diplomatic channels as per international treaties on diplomatic immunity","In accordance with the local laws of the receiving country, disregarding any international agreements","By registered mail within 7 days of the issuance of the order"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application must be served on a party within the State by registered post and on a party domiciled in another Member State or Contracting State in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, the Hague Convention (including Articles 8 to 11 thereof) and this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Application by virtue of Articles 2 and 5.2 of Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention* 25. (1) An application to the District Court being brought- - (a) by virtue of Article 5.2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance creditor domiciled or habitually resident in the State against a maintenance debtor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State for the variation of a maintenance order, - by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance creditor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State against a maintenance debtor domiciled in the State for the variation of a maintenance order, or - by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention by a maintenance debtor domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State against a maintenance creditor domiciled in the State for the variation or revocation of a maintenance order, must be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent of a summons in the [Form 41B.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/27ef99e9-cbbb-48f4-9513-47aea508db73/Summons to vary or revoke a maintenance order No. 41B.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule or, where appropriate, notice of summons in the [Form 41B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c1a9c97-a1c0-4443-b8f3-139fc4706b9c/Notice of commencement of proceedings No. 41B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, where the respondent is domiciled in a Member State or Contracting State other than the State, and the provisions of this Order apply. (2) The order of the Court granting the application must be served on a party within the State by registered post and on a party domiciled in another Member State or Contracting State in accordance with the provisions of the Service Regulation or, as appropriate, the Hague Convention (including Articles 8 to 11 thereof) and this Order. # **6 - RECOVERY OF MAINTENANCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What act''s Part is referenced in this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Sustainability Act 1994","The Maintenance Act 1984","The Preservation Act 1994","The Maintenance Act 1994"],"justification":"The Maintenance Act 1994"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **- [Maintenance Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28) - Part **- Reciprocating Jurisdictions**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a judgment or instrument does not relate solely to maintenance?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The judgment or instrument is automatically void if it does not relate solely to maintenance.","These rules apply to all parts regardless of whether they relate to maintenance.","These rules apply only to those parts that relate to maintenance.","Only parts unrelated to maintenance are subject to these rules."],"justification":"If a judgment or an instrument or settlement referred to in Articles 50 or 51 of the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 57 or 58 of the Lugano Convention does not relate solely to maintenance, these Rules apply only to those parts that relate to maintenance,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Enforcement Order* 26. If a judgment or an instrument or settlement referred to in Articles 50 or 51 of the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 57 or 58 of the Lugano Convention does not relate solely to maintenance, these Rules apply only to those parts that relate to maintenance, and on receipt of an enforcement order made by the High Court, in relation thereto, the Clerk must proceed as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'To whom does the Central Authority send the application for recognition or enforcement of a maintenance order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It sends the application to the Registrar General.","It sends the application to the Secretary of State.","It sends the application to either the Master of the High Court or the High Court.","It sends the application to the District Judge."],"justification":"sends the application to - (a) the Master of the High Court for determination in accordance with section 7 of the 1998 Act, or - the High Court for determination in accordance with Articles 31 and 32 of the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 38 and 39 and Annex of the Lugano Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Registration under section 7 of the 1994 Act* 27. Where, pursuant to section 7(1) of the 1994 Act, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act, on receipt of an application for the recognition or enforcement in the State of a maintenance order which has been transmitted by the Central Authority of a reciprocating jurisdiction, sends the application to - (a) the Master of the High Court for determination in accordance with section 7 of the 1998 Act, or - the High Court for determination in accordance with Articles 31 and 32 of the Brussels Convention or, as the case may be, Articles 38 and 39 and Annex of the Lugano Convention and, where an enforcement order is made under sections 7(2) or 7(7) of the 1994 Act, as appropriate, and the orders are sent to the appropriate District Court Clerk, the Clerk must register the documents and proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order in accordance with the provisions of this Order. # **7 - RECOVERY OF MAINTENANCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Which convention is mentioned in this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Geneva Convention","The Paris Agreement","The New York Convention","The Washington Treaty"],"justification":"**-The New York Convention**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **-[Maintenance Act 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/28)** **-Designated Jurisdictions** **-The New York Convention**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions does the Central Authority transmit a request to the Master of the High Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the Central Authority receives a request from any individual resident in the State to initiate legal proceedings for maintenance recovery, without the involvement of a foreign court.","When the Central Authority receives a request from a central authority of a designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance from a person residing in the State, accompanied by an order of a Court in a Contracting State, and the request is transmitted pursuant to section 14(1)(a) of the 1994 Act.","When the Central Authority needs to communicate with the local police force regarding enforcement actions on maintenance orders issued within the State itself.","When the Central Authority receives a request from a non-designated jurisdiction''s central authority for the recovery of maintenance, provided that there is no accompanying court order from a Contracting State."],"justification":"the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request from a central authority of a designated jurisdiction on behalf of a claimant for the recovery of maintenance from a person for the time being residing in the State (the “respondent”), and the request is accompanied by an order of a Court in a Contracting State (within the meaning of the 1998 Act), and the Central Authority under the 1994 Act transmits the request pursuant to section 14(1)(a) of the 1994 Act to the Master of the High Court for determination in accordance with section 7 of the 1998 Act, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Enforcement Order* 28. Where: - (a) the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request from a central authority of a designated jurisdiction on behalf of a claimant for the recovery of maintenance from a person for the time being residing in the State (the “respondent”), and - the request is accompanied by an order of a Court in a Contracting State (within the meaning of the 1998 Act), and - the Central Authority under the 1994 Act transmits the request pursuant to section 14(1)(a) of the 1994 Act to the Master of the High Court for determination in accordance with section 7 of the 1998 Act, and - the Master, having made an enforcement order in respect of the maintenance order, sends those orders to the appropriate District Court Clerk, the Clerk must proceed as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for enforcement under section of the 1994 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The issue and service of a notice in Form on the respondent.","The filing of a complaint with the local council.","The submission of a formal petition to the High Court.","The issuance of a warning letter from the applicant to the respondent."],"justification":"An application mentioned in sub-rule (1) must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form 41B.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1decda26-498d-444e-a953-675ca98283b9/Notice of application for enforcement No. 41B.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Application for enforcement under section 14 of the 1994 Act* 29. (1) Where the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request referred to in rule 28 and the request is accompanied by an order made by any other Court and the Central Authority under the 1994 Act is of opinion that the order may be enforceable in the State, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act may apply pursuant to section of the 1994 Act at any sitting of the District Court for the relevant Court district (as set out in section 14(11) of the 1994 Act) for the enforcement of the order. (2) An application mentioned in sub-rule (1) must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form 41B.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1decda26-498d-444e-a953-675ca98283b9/Notice of application for enforcement No. 41B.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the respondent. The notice must be accompanied by a copy of the documents mentioned in section 14(6) of the 1994 Act. Service must be effected by registered post at least 21 days prior to the return date. (3) When service has been effected, the applicant must lodge with the Clerk the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, at least four days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do when the Court makes an order for the enforcement of the order of the court in a designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Send copies of the order to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the respondent.","Publish the enforcement order in a national newspaper.","Submit a report to the court every month regarding the progress of enforcement.","Notify the local police department about the enforcement order."],"justification":"copies of the order of the Court must be sent by the Clerk to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Clerk to send copy orders (4) Where, on hearing the application, the Court makes an order for the enforcement of the order of the court in the designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance, copies of the order of the Court must be sent by the Clerk to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act and the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do when the Court makes such an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Consult with the Judge to determine the next steps in enforcing the maintenance order.","Notify the parties involved that the Court has made an order but take no further action.","File a motion to reconsider the enforceable maintenance order as indicated in rule 27.","Proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order as indicated in rule 27."],"justification":"When the Court makes such an order the Clerk must proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order as indicated in rule 27."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### Clerk to enforce order (5) When the Court makes such an order the Clerk must proceed to enforce the enforceable maintenance order as indicated in rule 27.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances is enforcement of an order refused?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the Central Authority receives a request under the 1984 Act and enforcement of the order is refused.","When the local court decides that the order does not meet the jurisdictional requirements of the country.","When the Central Authority receives a request under the 1994 Act and enforcement of the order is refused.","When the requesting party fails to provide sufficient evidence to support the enforcement of the order."],"justification":"or - enforcement of the order is refused,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 Enforcement procedure where not accompanied by order* 30. (1) Where the Central Authority under the 1994 Act receives a request referred to in rule 27 and either:- - (a) the request is not accompanied by an order referred to in rule 27 or in rule 28, or - enforcement of the order is refused,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application under section 14(1)(c)(ii) of the 1994 Act be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district","In writing to the Chief Justice of the relevant Court district","Online through the official court website of the relevant Court district","At the nearest police station within the relevant Court district"],"justification":"the application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district (as set out in section 14(11) of the 1994 Act)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - application to District Court and the Central Authority under the 1994 Act intends to make an application to the District Court under section 14(1)(c)(ii) of the 1994 Act, for the recovery of maintenance in accordance with the request, the application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the relevant Court district (as set out in section 14(11) of the 1994 Act) and must be deemed (as provided in section 14(3) of that Act) to be an application for a maintenance order under section 5, 5A or 21A of the 1976 Act, as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the return date must the notice be served by registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["exactly 30 days","at least 14 days","no specific time frame is required","at least 21 days"],"justification":"Service must be effected by registered post at least 21 days before the return date of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### - on notice (2) The application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the [Form 41B.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dec35386-f2e6-407c-9959-03ac62b7eaa1/Notice of application for the recovery of maintenance No. 41B.10.docx/docx/1) , Schedule on the respondent. The notice must be accompanied by copies of the documents mentioned in section 14(6) of the 1994 Act. Service must be effected by registered post at least 21 days before the return date of the application. (3) When service has been effected, the applicant must lodge with the Clerk the original of the notice, together with the certificate of posting, at least four days prior to the return date. (4) Where, on hearing the application, the court makes a maintenance order, the Clerk must proceed in accordance with the relevant provisions of [Order 54]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-54-District-Maintenance-of-Spouses-and-Children) and this Order, and the forms therein provided (with any necessary modifications) may be used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the deposition take when taken from the respondent on sworn deposition?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 30","Form","Schedule","Form Schedule"],"justification":"the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fc615c33-3203-4ce5-8658-14f3925fbde7/Deposition of respondent No. 41B.11.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *31 Deposition* 31. Where the Court, on an application to it under section of the 1994 Act, takes evidence from the respondent on sworn deposition, the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fc615c33-3203-4ce5-8658-14f3925fbde7/Deposition of respondent No. 41B.11.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the deposition must be sent by the Clerk to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the central authority of the designated jurisdiction with a request that the claimant provide an answering affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances does the Court make an order for proceedings to be transferred to another district?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the case involves international laws requiring a specialized jurisdiction","When the local court is on holiday break","When facilities are available for taking evidence via a live television link.","When there is a need to avoid a conflict of interest with local judges"],"justification":"Where, at the hearing of an application under section of the 1994 Act, the Court makes an order pursuant to section 14(7) of that Act transferring the proceedings to a Court district where facilities are available for taking the evidence of the claimant or of any witness through a live television link"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *32 Transfer to facilitate videolink evidence* 32. Where, at the hearing of an application under section of the 1994 Act, the Court makes an order pursuant to section 14(7) of that Act transferring the proceedings to a Court district where facilities are available for taking the evidence of the claimant or of any witness through a live television link, the Clerk must forward a copy of the order together with any other documents in his or her possession relating to the proceedings, to the appropriate District Court Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a deposition taken under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It must be in Form 41A.12, Schedule","It must be in Form Schedule A.","It must be in Form Schedule","It must be in Form Schedule"],"justification":"A deposition, taken under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act must be in the [Form 41B.12,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/71a24723-8cd7-4f98-932c-7a5d584cc5d0/Deposition of claimant No. 41B.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Request to give evidence by deposition* 33. (1) A request by the claimant to give evidence on sworn deposition before the District Court under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the claimant resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) A deposition, taken under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act must be in the [Form 41B.12,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/71a24723-8cd7-4f98-932c-7a5d584cc5d0/Deposition of claimant No. 41B.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule and must include the certificate of the Court required under section 15(2)(a) of the 1994 Act at the foot of the deposition. A certified copy of the deposition and certificate must be given by the Clerk to the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the certificate given by the Clerk to a claimant be in, pursuant to section of the 1994 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form 41A.13"],"justification":"must be in the [Form 41B.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e813f11-fb0f-4c8a-9a45-685177710d27/Certificate - Maintenance Act 1994, section No. 41B.13.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *34 Certificate under section of the 1994 Act* 34. The certificate to be given by the Clerk to a claimant on request, pursuant to section of the 1994 Act, must be in the [Form 41B.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e813f11-fb0f-4c8a-9a45-685177710d27/Certificate - Maintenance Act 1994, section No. 41B.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do if it is not possible to take the evidence within four months of the receipt of the request by the Central Authority?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Transfer the case to another clerk and inform the Central Authority of the change in responsibility.","Request an extension from the requesting authority before taking any action with the Central Authority.","Certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and send the certification to the Central Authority for transmission to the requesting authority.","Notify the requesting authority directly about the delay without providing any certified reason."],"justification":"the Judge must certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and the Clerk must send the same to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the requesting authority."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *35 Procedure under section 19 of the 1994 Act or Regulation 16 of the 2019 Regulations [14]* 35.(1) Subject to the provisions of section 19(8) of the 1994 Act, where on request from the Master of the High Court, pursuant to section 19(2) of the 1994 Act, a Judge of the District Court proposes to take the evidence of a person for the purposes of proceedings in a designated jurisdiction for the recovery of maintenance, the Clerk must issue and serve notice, in the [Form 41B.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f8e2a05-8cb5-4bc8-8eed-db4e2ef730f6/Notice that evidence will be taken - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(3) No. 41B.14.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the person concerned, the Central Authority under the 1994 Act, the Master of the High Court and on such other persons as the Court thinks fit. The notice must be served by registered post at least 21 days prior to the date fixed for taking the evidence. (2) Where such evidence is taken on sworn deposition, the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/72e39e2d-457f-4f23-b474-c663331d540f/Deposition - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(4) No. 41B.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk must send a certified copy thereof to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the requesting authority. (3) Where, as provided for in section 19(9) of the 1994 Act, the requesting authority makes a request for the taking of evidence directly to the District Court, the provisions of this rule must, with any necessary modifications, apply in relation to such a request. (4) If it is not possible to take the evidence within four months of the receipt of the request by the Central Authority under the 1994 Act, the Judge must certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and the Clerk must send the same to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act for transmission to the requesting authority.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the notice take when serving notice on a person residing in the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form Notice 2023","Form","Form","Form Legal Service Notification"],"justification":"the [Form 41B.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f8e2a05-8cb5-4bc8-8eed-db4e2ef730f6/Notice that evidence will be taken - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(3) No. 41B.14.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Subject to the provisions of Regulation 16 of the 2019 Regulations, where on request from the Master of the High Court, pursuant to Regulation 16(3) of the 2019 Regulations, a Judge of the Court proposes to take the evidence of a person of a person residing in the State on foot of such request, the Clerk must issue and serve notice, in the [Form 41B.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f8e2a05-8cb5-4bc8-8eed-db4e2ef730f6/Notice that evidence will be taken - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(3) No. 41B.14.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the person concerned, the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention, the Master of the High Court and on such other persons as the Court thinks fit. The notice must be served by registered post at least 21 days prior to the date fixed for taking the evidence. (6) Where such evidence is taken on sworn deposition, the deposition must be in the [Form 41B.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/72e39e2d-457f-4f23-b474-c663331d540f/Deposition - Maintenance Act 1994, section 19(4) No. 41B.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk must send a certified copy thereof to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention for transmission to the requesting Central Authority concerned. (7) If it is not possible to take the evidence within three months of the receipt of the request by the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention, the Judge must certify the reasons for the non-execution of the request or for the delay in executing it and the Clerk must send the same to the Central Authority under the Hague Maintenance Convention for transmission to the requesting Central Authority concerned. # **8 - MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS APPLICABLE TO PROCEEDINGS TO WHICH PARTS 3 TO 7 REFER**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'If the amount is stated in a currency other than Euro, how should it be converted for payment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["On the basis of the exchange rate prevailing on the date of the making of the enforcement order or of the order of a court in the State for the enforcement of the decision for the recovery of maintenance between that other currency and euro.","Using the fixed conversion rate set by the European Central Bank at the end of the year in which the enforcement order was issued.","On the basis of the exchange rate prevailing at the time of the initial agreement between the parties, before any enforcement order is made.","According to the average exchange rate over the period during which the maintenance was due."],"justification":"the payment must be made on the basis of the exchange rate prevailing on the date of the making of the enforcement order or of the order of a court in the State for the enforcement of the decision for the recovery of maintenance between that other currency and euro"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *36. Currency of payments* 36. An amount payable in the State under:- - (a) a decision recognised within the meaning of Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation; - an enforceable maintenance order by virtue of an enforcement order as provided for in the 2011 Regulations, or - an order for recovery of maintenance which is made by a Court in a jurisdiction other than the State and is enforceable in the State as provided for in the 1994 Act, must be paid in euro and if the amount is stated in the decision, enforceable maintenance order or order for recovery, as the case may be, in a currency other than euro, the payment must be made on the basis of the exchange rate prevailing on the date of the making of the enforcement order or of the order of a court in the State for the enforcement of the decision for the recovery of maintenance between that other currency and euro.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do after receiving a payment under rule 36?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Give a receipt to the maintenance debtor and transmit the payment to the person entitled to receive it.","Deposit the payment into the court''s general fund and notify the maintenance debtor.","Record the payment in the clerk''s personal log and keep it in cash.","Notify the local newspaper about the payment received."],"justification":"The Clerk must give, or send by ordinary post, to the maintenance debtor a receipt for each payment made by him or her under an order referred to in rule 36 and must transmit such payment forthwith by registered post, by insured post or by any other appropriate method to the person entitled to receive it, having due regard to the provisions of subsections 2(a) and of section 4 of the 1994 Act, where applicable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *37 Clerk to give receipt for and transmit payments* 37. (1) The Clerk must give, or send by ordinary post, to the maintenance debtor a receipt for each payment made by him or her under an order referred to in rule 36 and must transmit such payment forthwith by registered post, by insured post or by any other appropriate method to the person entitled to receive it, having due regard to the provisions of subsections 2(a) and of section 4 of the 1994 Act, where applicable. (2) Before transmitting any such payment abroad the Clerk must comply with any Exchange Control regulations for the time being in force governing the transmission of such payments and must, where necessary for that purpose, produce the order referred to in rule 36 to an authorised dealer, (i.e. a licensed bank) for inspection.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings be brought if the maintenance debtor is employed by someone residing or having a business in the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the County Court where the debtor''s employment contract was signed.","At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the debtor''s residence or business.","At any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the creditor resides or the body has its seat.","At any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which that person resides or, as the case may be, the body has its seat."],"justification":"in case the maintenance debtor does not reside in the State but is in the employment either of a person residing or having a place of business in the State or of a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which that person resides or, as the case may be, the body has its seat, in accordance with Regulation of the 2011 Regulations."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *38 Venue for proceedings by creditor* 38. (1) Proceedings by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor being brought in the District Court under the 2011 Regulations and the Maintenance Regulation for the enforcement of an enforceable maintenance order, may be brought, heard and determined: - (a) in case the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State or is deemed under Regulation 6 of the 2011 Regulations to be habitually resident in the Dublin Metropolitan District, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the maintenance debtor habitually resides or, as the case may be, is deemed to be habitually resident, in accordance with Regulation 10(7)(a) of the 2011 Regulations; - in case the maintenance debtor does not reside in the State but is in the employment either of a person residing or having a place of business in the State or of a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which that person resides or, as the case may be, the body has its seat, in accordance with Regulation of the 2011 Regulations. (2) Proceedings being brought by the maintenance creditor by virtue of Article 2 of either the Brussels Convention or the Lugano Convention for the variation of a maintenance order made in a Contracting State other than the State may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the maintenance debtor is domiciled. # **9 - MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS APPLICABLE TO PROCEEDINGS TO WHICH PARTS 2, 5 AND 6 REFER**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be used when filing notice of an application for an order to provide information?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","[Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1)","Form","Form"],"justification":"[Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *39 Application for order to provide information under Regulation 19(2) of the 2011 Regulations* 39. (1) An application by the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation to the Court under Regulation 19(2) of the 2011 Regulations for an order requiring a person or body (not being a person or body mentioned in Regulation 19(1) of the 2011 Regulations) to provide to the Central Authority under the Maintenance Regulation information as to the whereabouts, place of work, or location and extent of the assets, of a maintenance creditor or debtor (within the meaning of the 2011 Regulations) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the person or body to whom the order sought is to be directed resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. Notice of the application in the [Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing. (2) Where the Court grants the application and makes the order sought, the Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Court grants the application under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Central Authority must immediately enforce the order without forwarding any copies.","The Court must issue a public apology to the applicant.","The Court must dismiss all other pending cases related to the application.","The Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned."],"justification":"Where the Court grants the application and makes the order sought, the Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *40 Application for order to provide information under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act* 40. (1) An application by the Central Authority under the 1994 Act to the Court under section 20(2) of the 1994 Act for an order requiring a person or body (not being a person or body mentioned in section 20(1) of that Act) to provide to the Central Authority under the 1994 Act information as to the whereabouts, place of work, or location and extent of the assets of a maintenance debtor (within the meaning of the 1998 Act) or respondent may be made at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the person or body to whom the order sought is to be directed resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. Notice of the application in the [Form 41B.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f4c2178-44b1-403c-ac37-196da1b0b516/Notice of application for an order to provide information No. 41B.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be filed with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing. (2) Where the Court grants the application and makes the order sought, the Central Authority must forward a copy of the order to the person or body concerned. # **10 - PROCEEDINGS UNDER THE HAGUE CONVENTION 1996**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Clerk'' mean in this context?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The jury member responsible for presenting the verdict.","The bailiff in charge of maintaining order in the courtroom.","The Clerk for the Court area in which the original application was or is to be heard and decided or in which the original order was made","The legal advisor who assists the judge in making decisions."],"justification":"the “**Clerk**” means the Clerk for the Court area in which the original application was or is to be heard and decided or in which the original order was made;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *41 Definitions (this Part)* 41. In this Part (rules 41 to 52 inclusive), unless the context otherwise requires: the “**2000 Act**” means the [Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/37/enacted/en/html) (No. 37 of 2000); the “**Clerk**” means the Clerk for the Court area in which the original application was or is to be heard and decided or in which the original order was made; each of the expressions “**another contracting state**”, “**Central Authority**”, “**contracting state**”, “**the Convention**”, “**decision**”, “**judgment**”, and “**measure**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 1 of the 2000 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *42 Venue for proceedings under the 2000 Act or the Convention* 42. Subject to section 4(2) and section 4(3) of the 2000 Act, proceedings before the Court under the 2000 Act or under the Convention by virtue of the 2000 Act may be brought, heard or determined: - (a) in the case of proceedings to which section or section of the 2000 Act applies, at any sitting of the Court for any Court area in the Court district determined in accordance with section or, as the case may be, section of the 2000 Act; - in the case of any other proceedings under the 2000 Act or under the Convention by virtue of that Act, at such sitting of the Court or otherwise as is prescribed by these Rules or by statute for proceedings seeking the relief concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do when it considers that another contracting state is better placed to assess the best interests of the child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Court may dismiss the case entirely and instruct the parties to resolve the matter outside of legal proceedings.","The Court may stay the proceedings and direct the Central Authority to make a request to the proper authority of the other contracting state to assume jurisdiction.","The Court may transfer the entire case to the jurisdiction of any non-contracting state that has better resources to assess the situation.","The Court may order the immediate return of the child to the other contracting state without further assessment."],"justification":"the Court may stay the proceedings before it for a period specified by the Court and, as the Court considers appropriate, either: - (a) direct the Central Authority to make a request on its behalf to the proper authority of the other contracting state concerned to assume jurisdiction to take such measures of protection as it considers necessary in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention, or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *43 Stay of proceedings* 43. (1) Where the Court has jurisdiction in any proceedings to which the Convention applies, under Article 5 or 6 of the Convention but, on application of a party to the proceedings or of its own motion, considers in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention that the authority of another contracting state would be better placed in the particular case to assess the best interests of the child, the Court may stay the proceedings before it for a period specified by the Court and, as the Court considers appropriate, either: - (a) direct the Central Authority to make a request on its behalf to the proper authority of the other contracting state concerned to assume jurisdiction to take such measures of protection as it considers necessary in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention, or - invite the parties to introduce such a request before the proper authority of the other contracting state concerned in accordance with Article 8 of the Convention, and the Court may, for those purposes, limit the period of any stay to a period specified by the Court, and adjourn the matter for further consideration. (2) The Court may discharge a stay ordered in accordance with sub-rule (1) and direct the withdrawal of any request made under paragraph (a) of that sub-rule if the authority in the other contracting state concerned does not assume jurisdiction within the period for which the Court granted the stay. (3) The Court may discharge a stay ordered in accordance with sub-rule (1) if the parties do not, within the period specified by the court, request the authority in the other contracting state concerned to assume jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must the document commencing appropriate proceedings include if the Court is asked to exercise jurisdiction as the appropriate court of a contracting state?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It must be titled ''Request for Assistance'' and contain a notarized affidavit from the applicant affirming their identity and the facts of the case.","It must be labeled ''Proceedings Under International Agreement'' and must attach a translated copy of the relevant national law instead of the request made by the competent authority.","It must be entitled in the matter of the relevant provision of the Convention and have appended a copy of any relevant request in writing made by the competent authority of another contracting state, with a certified translation into Irish or English, or set out the basis of the request.","It must be entitled ''Application for Jurisdiction'' and include a detailed summary of the case history in any official language of the European Union."],"justification":"must additionally be entitled in the matter of the provision of the Convention in accordance with which the Court is asked to exercise jurisdiction, and must additionally have appended a copy of any relevant request in writing made by the competent authority of another contracting state, together with a certified translation, where necessary, into Irish or English, or must otherwise set out the basis on which the request to exercise jurisdiction is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *44 Application for court to exercise jurisdiction as appropriate court of a contracting state* 44. Where the Court is asked in accordance with the Convention to exercise a jurisdiction conferred on it to take any measures by virtue of being the appropriate court of a contracting state, the document commencing the appropriate proceedings in accordance with these Rules: - must additionally be entitled in the matter of the provision of the Convention in accordance with which the Court is asked to exercise jurisdiction, and - must additionally have appended a copy of any relevant request in writing made by the competent authority of another contracting state, together with a certified translation, where necessary, into Irish or English, or - (iii) must otherwise set out the basis on which the request to exercise jurisdiction is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do to facilitate participation in exchanges of views?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may mandate that all exchanges of views be conducted in a specific language only.","The Court may provide financial incentives directly to individuals participating in exchanges of views.","The Court may issue a ruling that prohibits any exchanges of views to maintain order.","The Court may give directions to the Central Authority to facilitate participation in exchanges of views."],"justification":"The Court may give such directions to the Central Authority as are appropriate to facilitate participation in any exchange of views referred to manner and by such means as the Court considers most suitable to meet the purposes of the Convention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *45 Exchange of views* 45. The Court may give such directions to the Central Authority as are appropriate to facilitate participation in any exchange of views referred to manner and by such means as the Court considers most suitable to meet the purposes of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court direct the Central Authority to do after making an order under Article 11 of the Convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order and make inquiries about measures taken under Article 11.","Instruct the Central Authority to issue a warrant for the arrest of the person against whom the order was made.","Notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order and request them to take immediate custody of the child.","Direct the Central Authority to provide financial compensation to the parties involved in the case."],"justification":"the Court may direct the Central Authority to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order and may direct the first-mentioned Central Authority to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether measures referred to in paragraph 2 of Article 11 of the Convention have been taken and, if so, as to the content of those measures."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *46 Orders under Article 11 and Article 12 of the Convention* 46. (1) In any case where the Court has made an order under Article 11 of the Convention, the Court may direct the Central Authority to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making of that order and may direct the first-mentioned Central Authority to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether measures referred to in paragraph 2 of Article 11 of the Convention have been taken and, if so, as to the content of those measures. (2) In any case where the Court has been asked to make an order under Article 12 of the Convention, the Court may direct the Central Authority: - (a) to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether any measures have been taken by the authorities having jurisdiction under Articles 5 to 10 of the Convention and, if so, as to the content of those measures; - to make inquiries of the Central Authority of another contracting state as to whether a decision (in respect of the measures of protection which may be required by the situation) referred to in paragraph 2 of Article 12 of the Convention has been taken and, if so, as to the content of that decision; or - to notify the Central Authority of another contracting state of the making by the Court of an order under Article 12 of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have regarding adjourning proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may adjourn proceedings under the 2000 Act for the purpose of making a request under Article 34 of the Convention.","The Court has the authority to adjourn proceedings indefinitely without any specific reason.","The Court must adjourn proceedings whenever a new evidence is presented.","The Court can adjourn proceedings only at the request of the parties involved."],"justification":"the Court may adjourn proceedings under the 2000 Act for the purpose of making a request under Article 34 of the Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *47 Adjournment to make request under Article 34* 47. Without limiting any other power of the Court, the Court may adjourn proceedings under the 2000 Act for the purpose of making a request under Article 34 of the Convention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'When can a request under Article 24 be made parte?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It can only be made parte if the opposing party consents in writing before the application is filed.","At the election of the applicant, it may be made parte in the first instance subject to the prior filing with the Clerk of a notice in Form Schedule","At the election of the applicant, it may be made parte only after a full hearing has been conducted.","The request can be made parte immediately without any prior notice or filing requirements."],"justification":"may at the election of the applicant, be made parte in the first instance subject to the prior filing with the Clerk of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule or otherwise must be made on notice to the respondent by the issue and service on the respondent at least 4 days prior to the date fixed for the hearing of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *48 Request under Article 24* 48. (1) A request to the Court by an interested party (in accordance with section 3(2) of the 2000 Act) pursuant to Article 24 of the Convention to decide on the recognition or non-recognition of a measure taken in another contracting state and/or pursuant to Article 26 of the Convention that a measure be declared enforceable or registered for the purpose of enforcement in the State may at the election of the applicant, be made parte in the first instance subject to the prior filing with the Clerk of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule or otherwise must be made on notice to the respondent by the issue and service on the respondent at least 4 days prior to the date fixed for the hearing of a notice in the [Form 41B.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e62ca532-23b9-4cca-95f7-bbdc35435705/Notice of Application for order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An application for such recognition and/or enforcement must be grounded on an affidavit which: - (a) exhibits the judgment or decision (in this rule referred to as the “decision”) constituting or recording the measure concerned or a certified or otherwise duly authenticated copy thereof (together with a certified translation, where necessary, into Irish or English) and - where necessary, states the name of the authority in the contracting state concerned and the date on which and place at which the measure was given or ordered, and - explains concisely the nature and effect of the measure and - sets out or verifies (or which exhibits and verifies documents which set out): - the full name, address and date and place of birth (where available) of each child to whom the measure relates; - the full name, address and date and place of birth (where available) of each person who has, in relation to each such child, rights and/or obligations of a kind mentioned in Article 3 of the Convention;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be included regarding the jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Chapter of the Convention and, where relevant, any findings of fact on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction.","The jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Article 4 of the Treaty and, where relevant, any legal opinions issued by the International Court of Justice on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction.","The jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Section of the Agreement and, where relevant, any precedents established in domestic courts on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction.","The jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Chapter III of the Convention and, where relevant, any findings of law on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction."],"justification":"the jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Chapter of the Convention and, where relevant, any findings of fact on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) where the request concerns the enforcement of a measure concerning access: - the practical arrangements for exercise of rights of access (to the extent stated in the decision), including date and time, start, end and place; any specific obligations on the holders of parental responsibility; (III) any specific obligations on the person with a right of access; any restrictions attached to the exercise of rights of access; - the jurisdiction of the authority concerned to take the measure by reference to Chapter of the Convention and, where relevant, any findings of fact on which the authority of the contracting state where the measure was taken based its jurisdiction; - whether the child concerned was given the opportunity to be heard, or where relevant, that the measure was taken in a case of urgency; - whether any person having parental responsibility in respect of the child concerned was given the opportunity to be heard, or where relevant, that the measure was taken in a case of urgency; - (vii) where relevant, whether any measure in respect of the child concerned has been taken in a non-contracting state of the habitual residence of the child; - (viii) where relevant, that the procedure provided in Article 33 of the Convention has been complied with; - documents which establish that, according to the law of the contracting state in which it has been given, the measure is enforceable; - where applicable, the grounds on which the right to request recognition or non-recognition or that a measure be declared enforceable or registered for the purpose of enforcement is vested in the party making the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the court take if a party does not produce the required evidence or documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court may impose a fine on the party that does not produce the required evidence or documents.","The court may automatically rule in favor of the party that did not produce the required evidence or documents.","The court may adjourn the application, accept equivalent evidence, or dispense with the production of such evidence or documents.","The court may extend the deadline for producing the required evidence or documents indefinitely."],"justification":"the Court may: - (a) adjourn the application to allow the applicant an opportunity to produce that evidence or those documents, or - accept equivalent evidence or documents, including by way of oral evidence, or - dispense with the production of such evidence or documents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *49 Where evidence not produced* 49. Where the party applying under rule 48 does not produce the evidence or documents referred to in rule 48, the Court may: - (a) adjourn the application to allow the applicant an opportunity to produce that evidence or those documents, or - accept equivalent evidence or documents, including by way of oral evidence, or - dispense with the production of such evidence or documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the time limit for an application to set aside or discharge an order if the person was served with the order in another contracting state?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within one month of such service","Within two months of such service","Within six weeks of such service","Within three months of such service"],"justification":"by a person served with the order in another contracting state, within two months of such service"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *50 Enforcement, setting aside and discharge of order* 50. (1) The order of the Court granting a request to decide on the recognition of a measure taken in another contracting state and/or that a measure be declared enforceable or registered for the purpose of enforcement in the State is, subject to sub-rule (2), enforceable for all purposes in accordance with these Rules. (2) The Court may direct the service by such means as it directs of the order on any person who it appears to the Court may be affected by the making of the order and may stay the operation of the order for a specified period. (3) Any application consistent with the requirements of the Convention to set aside or discharge such an order must, unless the Court otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service on the original applicant of a notice (or, as the case may be, on every person on whom the Court’s order has been served) in the [Form 41B.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1324e26-e5b3-41b8-9b64-3306023c8f11/Notice of Application to vary or revoke an order - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the original notice must, unless the Court otherwise allows, be filed with the Clerk at least two days before the return date of the application. (4) An application under sub-rule (3) must, unless the Court otherwise permits, be brought: - (a) by a person served with the order in the State, within one month of such service, or - by a person served with the order in another contracting state, within two months of such service. (5) The Court may stay the enforcement of the order, on such terms as it sees fit, where such an application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 41B - Service Of Documents In Civil Proceedings - Service Of Documents Outside The State Without The Permission Of The Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be provided on application in writing to the Clerk for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A signed affidavit of income","A notarized letter of recommendation","A declaration of intent from the applicant","A certificate of the Court"],"justification":"A certificate of the Court for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act (in the [Form 41B.19,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22ac957e-0cad-4f76-b6bd-eca8f0be6d4d/Certificate - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be provided on application in writing to the Clerk for that purpose."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *51 Certificate under section 6 of 2000 Act* 51. (1) A certificate of the Court for the purposes of section 6 of the 2000 Act (in the [Form 41B.19,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22ac957e-0cad-4f76-b6bd-eca8f0be6d4d/Certificate - Protection of Children (Hague Convention) Act 2000 No. 41B.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be provided on application in writing to the Clerk for that purpose. Where appropriate, certified copies of any relevant order of the Court in the proceedings and of any document filed as proof of service in the proceedings may be appended to the certificate. (2) Where the applicant (or an authority of another contracting state) requests further particulars of the proceedings to which the certificate relates, the Clerk, having consulted with the Judge, and subject to Article 37 of the Convention, may certify such further particulars.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order discussed in this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim","Order 13 - Civil Procedure Rules","Order 50 - Appeals Process","Order 37 - Summary Judgment"],"justification":"# Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim - Court: District # **Order 42: Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the heading of the section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["## **1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**","## **1 - PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS**","## **2 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**","### **1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**"],"justification":"## **1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 - APPEARANCE AND DEFENCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the deadline for a respondent to file an appearance and defence when served within the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["30 days after the service of the claim notice","28 days after the service of the claim notice","14 days after the service of the claim notice","20 days after the service of the claim notice"],"justification":"not later than 28 days after the service on him or her of the claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Appearance and defence* 1. (1) A respondent who intends to defend civil proceedings must give, or send by post, to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant an appearance and defence, in the [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule not later than 28 days after the service on him or her of the claim notice, and must at the same time file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk. (1A)[2] A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court)) may file and/or serve an appearance and defence by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with Order 39A and, in the case of service, where the claimant or claimant’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user. (2) Where a claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) is served outside the State in accordance with these Rules and any order of the Court, the time within which a respondent served outside the State must serve his or her appearance and defence on the claimant and file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk is: - (a) five weeks after the service of the claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) exclusive of the day of service where the claim notice, other originating document or notice is served in the European territory of another Member State of the European Union, or - six weeks after the service of the claim notice or other originating document (or notice thereof) exclusive of the day of service where the claim notice, other originating document or notice is served in any non-European territory of a Member State of the European Union. (3) A defence must - - (a) contain a statement that the respondent intends to defend the claim notice; and - state the name and address of the respondent and an address for service in the European Union at which documents required to be served on the respondent may be left; and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What information must be provided if a respondent defends by a solicitor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The email address and social media profiles of the solicitor.","The name or firm and business address within the European Union of the solicitor, and if the solicitor is an agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal.","The name and residential address of the solicitor outside the European Union.","The personal contact details including home address and phone number of the solicitor."],"justification":"if the respondent defends by a solicitor, state the name or firm and business address within the European Union of the solicitor and also, if the solicitor is an agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- if the respondent defends by a solicitor, state the name or firm and business address within the European Union of the solicitor and also, if the solicitor is an agent of another, the name or firm and business address of the principal. (4) Where a civil summons which does not require the delivery of a written defence (or notice thereof) is served outside the State in accordance with these Rules and any order of the Court, the respondent may notify his or her intention to appear and contest the claim by serving an appearance in [Form 42.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b8cdf3dc-212d-4fd5-9579-4961fe689f1c/Notice of appearance and intention to defend a claim notice or civil summons served outside Ireland which requires an appearance No. 42.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the claimant and filing a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk within the period specified in sub-rule (2). A respondent on whom a civil summons which does not require the delivery of a written defence is served within the State is not required to serve or file such an appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an appearance and defence in a debt claim take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 42.05, Schedule","Form 42.01, Schedule A","Form 42.03, Schedule","Form 42.07, Schedule"],"justification":"An appearance and defence in a debt claim must be in [Form 42.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/613a061f-1571-42a9-95fc-15790472b3df/Appearance and defence - debt claim No. 42.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Appearance and defence to debt claim* 2. (1) An appearance and defence in a debt claim must be in [Form 42.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/613a061f-1571-42a9-95fc-15790472b3df/Appearance and defence - debt claim No. 42.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule A respondent who intends to defend a debt claim must give, or send by post, to the claimant or solicitor for the claimant his or her appearance and defence not later than 28 days after the service on him or her of the claim notice, and must at the same time file a copy of his or her appearance with the Clerk. (2) A defence in a debt claim must state whether the claim is: - (a) disputed as to both liability and amount; - disputed only as to amount and if so, what amount is admitted to be due; - admitted in full and if so, whether the respondent proposes to pay immediately or requires time for payment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What must a respondent do if they contest or dispute all or part of a claimant’s claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Serve a counterclaim in Form 42.02 on the claimant at the address for service stated in the claim notice and file a copy of the counterclaim with the Clerk.","Submit a formal objection to the court within 30 days of receiving the claim notice without the need to serve any documents on the claimant.","Provide a written notice of disagreement to the claimant via email within 14 days of receiving the claim notice and send a copy to the Clerk.","Serve an appearance and defence in Form 42.01 on the claimant at the address for service stated in the claim notice and file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk."],"justification":"Unless the respondent requires further particulars of statement of claim, a respondent to a claim other than a debt claim who contests or disputes all or part of a claimant’s claim must serve an appearance and defence in [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the claimant at the address for service stated in the claim notice and must file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Appearance and defence in claims other than debt claims* 3. (1) Unless the respondent requires further particulars of statement of claim, a respondent to a claim other than a debt claim who contests or disputes all or part of a claimant’s claim must serve an appearance and defence in [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule on the claimant at the address for service stated in the claim notice and must file a copy of the appearance with the Clerk. (2) A defence must state which of the facts stated in statement of claim are— - (a) admitted; - denied; - not admitted. (3) A respondent who, in the defence, does not state whether a fact stated in statement of claim is— - (a) admitted; - denied; - not admitted— must be taken to admit the fact. (4) A respondent who states that a fact stated in statement of claim is denied must— - (a) give reasons for denying the fact; and - if the respondent intends to prove a fact different from that stated in the statement of claim, state, with necessary particulars, the fact that the respondent intends to prove. (5) The respondent must state specifically, with particulars, any fact or matter which— - (a) makes the claim of the claimant not maintainable; or - if not stated specifically, might take the claimant by surprise; or - raises questions of fact not arising out of the statement of claim. (6) If the defence arises by or under any enactment, the defence must identify the specific provision relied on. (7) A defence must be divided into paragraphs numbered consecutively, and each fact or matter stated, so far as is practicable, must be contained in a separate paragraph. (8) A defence must contain a list of all correspondence and other documents (other than any documents already identified in the statement of claim) on which the respondent will rely at the trial including the date if any and a brief description of each document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'When can a respondent serve an appearance and defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within 7 days of receiving the claim notice without the need for the claimant''s consent.","At any time after the service of a claim notice with the written consent of the claimant.","Before the service of a claim notice with the written consent of the claimant.","Only immediately after the claimant files the lawsuit."],"justification":"A respondent may serve an appearance and defence and file an appearance at any time after the service of a claim notice with the written consent of the claimant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Late filing and service of appearance and defence* 4. A respondent may serve an appearance and defence and file an appearance at any time after the service of a claim notice with the written consent of the claimant, but an appearance and defence may not be served, except by permission of the Court, if the claimant has obtained judgment in default of appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the rule regarding amending a defence if further particulars have been requested?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Once a respondent has served their initial defence, they cannot request further particulars from the claimant''s statement of claim.","A respondent who has provided further particulars in their own defence can amend the claimant''s statement of claim.","Despite rules 2 and 3, a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant''s statement of claim may not serve or file an amended defence.","Despite rules 2 and 3, a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant''s statement of claim may serve and file an amended defence."],"justification":"Despite rules 2 and 3, a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim may serve and file an amended defence:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Amendment of defence where particulars given* 5. Despite rules 2 and 3, a respondent who has required further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim may serve and file an amended defence: - (a) not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars of the claimant’s statement of claim; or - at any other time with the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["TERMINATION OF SOLICITOR SERVICES","CHANGE OF COURT DATE","APPOINTMENT OF SOLICITOR","CHANGE OF SOLICITOR"],"justification":"**2 - CHANGE OF SOLICITOR**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 - CHANGE OF SOLICITOR**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party appoint a solicitor without an order if they are suing or defending in person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No, a party can only appoint a solicitor with a court''s permission.","Yes, a party may appoint a solicitor without an order for the purpose.","A party must have a legal representative present before they can appoint a solicitor without an order.","Only the court can appoint a solicitor for a party, regardless of whether they are suing or defending in person."],"justification":"A party suing or defending in person may appoint a solicitor without an order for the purpose."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Notice of change, appointment or discharge of solicitor* 6. (1) A party suing or defending by a solicitor may change his or her solicitor, or discharge his or her solicitor and sue or defend in person. (2) A party suing or defending in person may appoint a solicitor without an order for the purpose. (3) Notice of any change, discharge or appointment of a solicitor ([Form 42.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c30cd90d-8359-4aec-8bfc-71d65892d4cc/Notice of change - appointment of solicitor No. 42.04.docx/docx/1) or [42.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f1f07705-50c6-4788-9e8c-c86cba3d5e38/Notice of discharge of solicitor No. 42.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate) must be filed with the Clerk, and served on the opposite party, or his solicitor (if any), and on the solicitor discharged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["NOTICE REQUIRING COPY DOCUMENTS OR FURTHER PARTICULARS","NOTICE OF HEARING ON DEFAULT","ACKNOWLEDGEMENT OF RECEIPT","CERTIFICATE OF SERVICE"],"justification":"**3 - NOTICE REQUIRING COPY DOCUMENTS OR FURTHER PARTICULARS**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - NOTICE REQUIRING COPY DOCUMENTS OR FURTHER PARTICULARS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Does this Part apply to small claims?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["No","Yes"],"justification":"This Part does not apply to small claims"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Does not apply to debt claims or small claims* 7. This Part does not apply to small claims and unless otherwise ordered by the Court, this Part does not apply to debt claims.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What else can a respondent ask the claimant to provide?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supplementary documents requested by the court without input from either party.","Additional evidence that the respondent believes is unnecessary but would like to see anyway.","Further particulars which the respondent asserts are reasonably necessary as to specified matters in the statement of claim.","Further particulars which the claimant asserts are reasonably necessary as to specified matters in the defence."],"justification":"requiring the claimant to provide further particulars which the respondent asserts are reasonably necessary as to specified matters in the statement of claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Copy documents or further particulars from claimant* 8. A respondent may at any time before or at the time of delivery of a defence apply to the claimant in writing: - (a) for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the statement of claim on which the claimant relies or referred to in the statement of claim ([Form 42.06,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e6f835-a2eb-4f86-8cf7-396bc2c735cd/Notice requiring copy documents No. 42.06.docx/docx/1) Schedule - requiring the claimant to provide further particulars which the respondent asserts are reasonably necessary as to specified matters in the statement of claim ([Form 42.07,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f51331f-49b2-4f93-8dcc-6804bb812c27/Notice requiring further particulars No. 42.07.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What can a claimant ask the respondent to provide within 28 days after delivering a defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["copies of all or any of the documents listed in the defence on which the respondent relies or referred to in the defence; further particulars which the claimant asserts are reasonably necessary","personal emails between the parties not referenced in the defence","an apology letter from the respondent acknowledging fault","a detailed financial report unrelated to the defence"],"justification":"for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the defence on which the respondent relies or referred to in the defence; requiring the respondent to provide further particulars which the claimant asserts are reasonably necessary"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Copy documents or further particulars from respondent* 9. A claimant may within 28 days after delivery of a defence apply to the respondent in writing: - (a) for copies of all or any of the documents listed in the defence on which the respondent relies or referred to in the defence ([Form 42.06,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e6f835-a2eb-4f86-8cf7-396bc2c735cd/Notice requiring copy documents No. 42.06.docx/docx/1) Schedule - requiring the respondent to provide further particulars which the claimant asserts are reasonably necessary ([Form 42.07,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0f51331f-49b2-4f93-8dcc-6804bb812c27/Notice requiring further particulars No. 42.07.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What consequences can arise if a party fails to comply with an order requiring them to provide copies or particulars?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The party will automatically lose the case without any further proceedings.","The party''s legal representation will be barred from practicing law.","The party will be required to pay triple damages to the opposing side.","If the party is a claimant, the claim notice may be dismissed; if the party is a respondent, their defence may be struck out."],"justification":"Such an order may provide that on failure to do so - if the party is a claimant, that the claim notice be dismissed; or if the party is a respondent, that the party''s defence, if any, be struck out."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Failure to give copies or particulars* 10. (1) If a party fails to comply with a notice requiring copies of listed documents or requiring further particulars within 21 days of service of the notice, the Court may make an order requiring the party to provide the copies or the necessary particulars within a time specified by the Court. (2) Such an order may provide that on failure to do so - - if the party is a claimant, that the claim notice be dismissed; or - if the party is a respondent, that the party''s defence, if any, be struck out. (3) An application for an order under sub-rule (1) must be made before a date is fixed for hearing of the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'When can a party amend their pleading after receiving further particulars?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any time within 60 days after receipt of further particulars, or with the permission of the Court.","Not later than 14 days after receipt of further particulars, or at any other time with the permission of the Court.","Not later than 30 days after receipt of further particulars, unless the Court grants an extension of time.","Not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars, or at any other time with the permission of the Court."],"justification":"not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars; or at any other time with the permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Amendment of pleading where particulars given* 11. A party who has required further particulars of another party’s pleading may serve and file an amended statement of claim or other pleading: - (a) not later than 28 days after receipt of further particulars; or - at any other time with the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'How is a counterclaim treated under Order 42?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["as if it were a civil proceeding","as if it were a summary judgment","as if it were a criminal proceeding","as if it were an administrative hearing"],"justification":"as if the counterclaim or the third party claim were a civil proceeding"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Application to counterclaims and third party claims* 12. This Order applies, with any necessary modification, to a counterclaim and to a claim by third party notice as if the counterclaim or the third party claim were a civil proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can the unsuccessful party recover the costs of replying to particulars from the successful party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["If the particulars are certified as unnecessary by the opposing party.","If the particulars are deemed frivolous or vexatious by the Court.","If the particulars are not certified as necessary by the Court.","If the particulars are submitted after the deadline set by the Court."],"justification":"the costs of replying to particulars may be recovered by the unsuccessful party against the successful party where the particulars are not certified as necessary by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Costs of particulars* 13. Unless otherwise ordered by the Court: - (a) the costs of requesting particulars may only be allowed as part of the successful party’s costs against the unsuccessful party where, and only where, the particulars are certified as necessary by the Court; and - the costs of replying to particulars may be recovered by the unsuccessful party against the successful party where the particulars are not certified as necessary by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Cross-examination","Counterclaim","Opening statement","Direct examination"],"justification":"**4 - COUNTERCLAIM**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4 - COUNTERCLAIM**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'When can a respondent set off or set up a counterclaim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A respondent may set off or set up any right or claim they allege they have against the claimant as a counterclaim against the claim of the claimant, regardless of whether it is a claim in damages.","A respondent may set off or set up a counterclaim only if it involves claims for punitive damages.","A respondent can only set off or set up a counterclaim if it is directly related to the initial claim made by the claimant.","A respondent is allowed to set off or set up a counterclaim only when it pertains to a different jurisdiction than the initial claim."],"justification":"A respondent may set off or set up any right or claim the respondent alleges he or she has against the claimant as a counterclaim against the claim of the claimant, whether the respondent’s claim is a claim in damages or not."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 When counterclaim permitted* 14. (1) A respondent may set off or set up any right or claim the respondent alleges he or she has against the claimant as a counterclaim against the claim of the claimant, whether the respondent’s claim is a claim in damages or not. (2) A set off or counterclaim has the same effect as a cross action, so as to enable the Court to determine both the claim and the counterclaim at the same trial. (3) The Court may, on the application of the claimant before the trial, refuse permission to the respondent to avail himself or herself of the counterclaim if in the opinion of the Court, the set off or counterclaim cannot be conveniently disposed of in the trial of the claimant’s claim, or ought not to be allowed. (4) These Rules apply to a counterclaim as if the claimant were the respondent and the respondent were the claimant. (5) A respondent who counterclaims must file and serve the counterclaim with his or her defence, unless the Court otherwise permits. (6) A counterclaim must be in [Form 42.08,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/269d5e24-5305-463b-82e4-58181471951b/Statement of counterclaim No. 42.08.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have regarding pleadings that are unnecessary or scandalous?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Court may order the parties involved to pay a fine.","The Court may order them to be struck out or amended.","The Court may ignore the unnecessary or scandalous parts without taking any action.","The Court may extend the deadline for submitting pleadings."],"justification":"The Court may at any stage of the civil proceedings order to be struck out or amended any matter in any pleading which is unnecessary or scandalous"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Stay or order in proceeding* 15. (1) The Court may at any stage of the civil proceedings order to be struck out or amended any matter in any pleading which is unnecessary or scandalous, or which may tend to prejudice, embarrass, or delay the fair trial of the civil proceedings. (2) The Court may in any such case, if it thinks fit, order the costs of the application to be paid as between solicitor and client. (3) The Court may order any pleading to be struck out, on the ground that it discloses no reasonable cause of action or answer and in any such case or in case of the claim or defence being shown by the pleadings to be frivolous or vexatious, the Court may order the claim to be stayed or dismissed, or judgement to be entered accordingly, as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42 - Defence, Particulars And Counterclaim', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can the Court strike out a statement of claim or defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["If the statement of claim or defence is submitted after regular business hours on a weekday.","If the statement of claim or defence contains minor typographical errors or spelling mistakes.","If the party involved in the case fails to pay the court fees within a day of filing the claim or defence.","If it does not disclose a cause of action or defence, is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious, may prejudice, embarrass or delay the fair hearing of the proceeding, or is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court."],"justification":"If a statement of claim or defence or any part of a statement of claim or defence - - (a) does not disclose a cause of action or defence; is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious; - may prejudice, embarrass or delay the fair hearing of the proceeding; or - is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court— the Court may order that the whole or part of the statement of claim or defence be struck out or amended."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Striking out a pleading* 16. (1) If a statement of claim or defence or any part of a statement of claim or defence - - (a) does not disclose a cause of action or defence; is scandalous, frivolous or vexatious; - may prejudice, embarrass or delay the fair hearing of the proceeding; or - is otherwise an abuse of the process of the Court— the Court may order that the whole or part of the statement of claim or defence be struck out or amended. (2) This rule, with any necessary modification, applies where the respondent counterclaims or claims against a third party. [1] Order 42 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 42 Rule 1 Sub-rule 1A inserted by 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What forms can a third party notice take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form 42A.05","Form 42A.01 or Form 42A.02"],"justification":"(in [Form 42A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7a463659-45c6-4aec-855b-ecf3e1f36b4b/Third%20party%20notice%20(indemnity%20or%20contribution)%20No.%2042A.01.docx/docx/1) or [42A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/35cae99e-6a23-43ee-8e95-4da4d4ae63cf/Third%20party%20notice%20(issue)%20No.%2042A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claim against a person not already a party* 1. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent - (a) claims any contribution or indemnity against any person not already a party (in this Order, a “**third party**”), or - claims against a third party any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the claimant, or - requires that any question or issue relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings should be determined not only as between the claimant and the respondent but also as between either or both of them and a third party, the respondent may within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) issue and serve on the third party a notice (in this Order, a “**third party notice**”) (in [Form 42A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7a463659-45c6-4aec-855b-ecf3e1f36b4b/Third party notice (indemnity or contribution) No. 42A.01.docx/docx/1) or [42A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/35cae99e-6a23-43ee-8e95-4da4d4ae63cf/Third party notice (issue) No. 42A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be), containing a statement of the nature of the claim against the respondent and the nature and grounds of the respondent''s claim against the third party or of the question or issue to be determined. 1A.[2] Notwithstanding rule 4, a digital user (within the meaning of [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court)) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 39A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings--documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-court) and, in the case of service, where the third party or third party’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must the respondent serve on the third party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the original complaint without the third party notice","A formal apology and settlement offer to the third party","A copy of the claim notice or notice of application with the third party notice.","A personal letter of intent to sue the third party"],"justification":"The respondent must serve a copy of the claim notice or notice of application on the third party with the third party notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Copy of claim notice to be served* 2. The respondent must serve a copy of the claim notice or notice of application on the third party with the third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Within how many days must the respondent serve a copy of the third party notice on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["five days","twenty days","fifteen days","ten days"],"justification":"The respondent must within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) serve a copy of the third party notice on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor and file a copy of the third party notice with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Copy to be filed* 3. The respondent must within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) serve a copy of the third party notice on the claimant or claimant’s solicitor and file a copy of the third party notice with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What order''s provisions concerning document service apply to third party notices?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order 6","Order 52","Order 37","Order 41"],"justification":"The provisions of [Order 41] relating to the service of documents apply to the service of a third party notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Service* 4. The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) relating to the service of documents apply to the service of a third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a third party notice is served on a third party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The third party must respond by providing evidence that supports the claimant''s case within a specified timeframe.","The third party becomes a party to the civil proceeding with the same rights as if they were sued in the ordinary way by the respondent who issued the third party notice or by the claimant.","The third party is automatically considered guilty of the claims made against them without the need for further proceedings.","The third party is required to pay damages immediately upon receiving the notice."],"justification":"Where a third party notice is served on the third party, the third party is, as from the time of service, a party to the civil proceeding with the same rights as if he or she had been sued in the ordinary way by the respondent by whom the third party notice was issued or by the claimant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Third party becomes a party on service* 5. Where a third party notice is served on the third party, the third party is, as from the time of service, a party to the civil proceeding with the same rights as if he or she had been sued in the ordinary way by the respondent by whom the third party notice was issued or by the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Within what timeframe must a third party provide notice of appearance and defence after receiving a third party notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["within 30 days of the receipt of the third party notice","within 21 days of the filing of the third party notice","within 28 days of the service of the third party notice","within 14 days of the service of the third party notice"],"justification":"within 28 days of the service of the third party notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Appearance and defence to third party notice* 6. (1) Where a third party disputes the claim by the respondent against him or her or the claim by the claimant against the respondent, [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) applies as if the third party notice were a claim notice served by the respondent on the third party. (2) The third party must, within 28 days of the service of the third party notice, give or send by post to the respondent or respondent’s solicitor and to the Clerk notice of appearance and defence to the third party notice (in the [Form 42.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/28a0f379-5c16-47f4-a8d7-7b89ddfb16e0/Appearance and defence - general No. 42.01.docx/docx/1) or [42.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/613a061f-1571-42a9-95fc-15790472b3df/Appearance and defence - debt claim No. 42.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications) or an appearance and notice requiring particulars, and the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)(relating to defence and counterclaim) and [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment) (relating to lodgment) apply mutatis mutandis to the proceedings on the third party notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for the Court to grant a judgment or order in civil proceedings involving a third party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A unanimous decision from all jury members in a non-trial civil case.","A written consent from all parties involved in the civil proceedings.","An application by motion if the proceedings are decided otherwise than by trial.","A verbal agreement between the parties involved in the civil proceedings."],"justification":"on an application by motion grant such judgment or order to or against any party or parties as the nature of the case requires."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Court may grant judgment or order* 9. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent has served a third party notice, the Court may at or after the trial, or if the proceedings are decided otherwise than by trial, on an application by motion grant such judgment or order to or against any party or parties as the nature of the case requires.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must occur before execution can be issued against a third party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The third party must be found guilty in a separate trial.","The judgment or order against the respondent must be satisfied.","The third party must provide consent to be executed against.","The court must issue a preliminary injunction against the third party."],"justification":"until the judgment or order against the respondent has been satisfied."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Execution not to issue without leave* 10. Where in civil proceedings judgment is given or an order is made against a respondent and judgment is given or an order is made in favour of that respondent against a third party, execution may not issue against the third party without the leave of the Court until the judgment or order against the respondent has been satisfied.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 42A - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What types of claims are covered under Order 42A Rule 11?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Claims for punitive damages, relief or remedy unrelated to the original subject matter of the proceedings, and questions or issues to be determined as between the parties and another party.","Claims for compensation for loss of earnings, relief or remedy related to the original subject matter of the proceedings, and questions or issues to be determined as between the parties and their respective insurers.","Claims for contribution or indemnity, relief or remedy related to the original subject matter of the proceedings, and questions or issues to be determined as between the parties and another party.","Claims for breach of contract, relief or remedy related to the original subject matter of the proceedings, and questions or issues to be determined as between the parties and any third party not involved in the original proceedings."],"justification":"Where in any civil proceedings a respondent claims against any person already a party: - (a) any contribution or indemnity, or - any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the claimant, or - that any question or issue relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings should be determined not only as between the claimant and the respondent but also as between either or both of them and that person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Claim against person already a party* 11. Where in any civil proceedings a respondent claims against any person already a party: - (a) any contribution or indemnity, or - any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the claimant, or - that any question or issue relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the proceedings should be determined not only as between the claimant and the respondent but also as between either or both of them and that person, the respondent may, within ten days of the service on him or her of the claim notice or notice of application (exclusive of the date of service) issue and serve on that other party a notice in the prescribed form ([Form 42A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/464596fe-19cb-4aac-b882-3438e8c4fcdf/Notice of indemnity, contribution or issue against a party No. 42A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule containing a statement of the nature and grounds of the respondent’s claim or of the question or issue to be determined. This rule does not apply to any claim which could be made by counterclaim. [1] Order 42A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 42A Rule 1A inserted [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) by effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 43 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["County Court","Supreme Court","High Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties - Court: District # Order 43: Joining Claims And Parties [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''birth certificate'' mean in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["an official government form used to report the birth of a child","a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of a person’s birth","a medical record detailing the health history of a newborn","a legal document issued by a hospital upon discharge of a new mother"],"justification":"“**birth certificate**” means a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of a person’s birth;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order— “**birth certificate**” means a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of a person’s birth; [2]“**vulnerable person**” includes a child, a ward of court, and a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["VALIDATING CLAIMS","JOINING CLAIMS","DEFINING CLAIMS","AMENDING CLAIMS"],"justification":"JOINING CLAIMS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - JOINING CLAIMS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have if joined claims cannot be conveniently tried together?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may merge all claims into a single trial to expedite proceedings.","The Court may dissolve the claims entirely and declare them void.","The Court may refer the claims to arbitration instead of conducting trials.","The Court may order separate trials, exclude any claim, order necessary amendments, and make orders as to costs."],"justification":"if it appears to the Court that claims joined in a civil proceeding cannot be conveniently tried together, the Court may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the necessary amendments, and may make such order as to costs as the Court considers just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Joining claims* 2. (1) Two or more claims may be made in one originating document, either alternatively or otherwise, so long as the claims are not mutually inconsistent or based on inconsistent allegations of fact. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), if it appears to the Court that claims joined in a civil proceeding cannot be conveniently tried together, the Court may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the necessary amendments, and may make such order as to costs as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the numerical identifier for this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["1","4","2","3"],"justification":"3"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - JOINING MULTIPLE PARTIES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the court prevent multiple persons from joining as claimants?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The court may prevent joining if it is satisfied that the claimants are related to each other.","The court may prevent joining if it is satisfied that the claimants have previously settled their disputes out of court.","The court may prevent joining if it is satisfied that the claimants are all from different jurisdictions.","The court may prevent joining if it is satisfied that doing so would embarrass or delay the trial."],"justification":"if the Court is satisfied on an application by a respondent by notice of motion, that joining all of those persons may embarrass or delay the trial, the Court may order separate trials, or make such other order as it considers just"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Joining claimants* 3. (1) All persons may join as claimants in one civil proceeding in whom any right to relief arising out of the same transactions is claimed to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if all of those persons brought separate civil proceedings, a common question of law or fact would arise, but the total amount awarded in a civil proceeding on any single claim form may not exceed the maximum amount which the Court has jurisdiction to award in a civil proceeding, regardless of the number of claimants who may share in, or be awarded a portion of, that amount. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), if the Court is satisfied on an application by a respondent by notice of motion, that joining all of those persons may embarrass or delay the trial, the Court may order separate trials, or make such other order as it considers just. (3) When numerous persons have the same interest in one claim (whether as claimants or as respondents), one or more of those persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Court to defend, in the civil proceedings, on behalf of or for the benefit of all of the interested persons. (4) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to claims in tort. (5) No person may be made a claimant without his or her consent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a claimant is uncertain about who should be held liable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The claimant must drop the case as uncertainty invalidates the claim.","The claimant should seek a court order to determine liability without joining any respondents.","The claimant may join two or more respondents to determine which, if any, of the respondents is liable and to what extent.","The claimant can only proceed by naming a single respondent and hoping they accept liability."],"justification":"When the claimant is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more respondents, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the respondents is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Joining respondents* 4.(1) All persons may be joined as respondents in one civil proceeding against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. (2) When the claimant is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more respondents, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the respondents is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. (3) When a person residing outside the Court district within which the civil proceedings must be begun under any enactment or these Rules, but within the State, is a necessary and proper party to a civil proceeding properly begun in the Court against a person within the Court district, the first mentioned person may be served with the claim notice or other document without special permission of the Court. (4) It is not necessary that every respondent be interested in resisting all or every relief sought, or in defending every cause of action included in a civil proceeding in which he or she is a respondent; but the Court may make any order which it considers just, to prevent any respondent from being embarrassed, or put to unnecessary expense, by being required to attend any hearing or application in which he or she has no interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Who may join as respondents to the same civil proceeding?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The claimant may join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.","The claimant may join as respondents to the same civil proceeding only government entities that have a regulatory interest in the case.","The claimant may join as respondents to the same civil proceeding any individual who has a casual acquaintance with the parties involved in the contract.","The claimant may join as respondents to the same civil proceeding only those individuals who have previously been involved in litigation with them."],"justification":"The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Respondents to a claim in contract* 5. The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'When can the Court add a new respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When at least one claimant verbally consents during a court session.","With the consent in writing of all claimants.","When the judge decides unilaterally that it is necessary.","When a majority of claimants agree through email communication."],"justification":"The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Court may join necessary parties* 6.(1) No claim or cause of action may be defeated by reason of the failure to join particular persons as parties. (2) The Court may in every civil proceeding deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before the Court. (3) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings, either on or without the application of any party, and on such terms as the Court considers just, make an order: - (a) striking out the name of any party, whether claimant or respondent, who has been improperly joined, or - adding as a claimant or as a respondent the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Court to adjudicate on and settle all the questions involved in the civil proceeding. (4)[3] A person may only be added as a claimant: - (a) with his or her consent in writing, if he or she is not a vulnerable person, or - if the person is a child, following the appointment of a guardian litem or next friend, who must give his or her consent in writing to act in that capacity, or - if the person is a relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8, or - if the person is a ward of court, by his or her committee. (5) Every person whose name is added as a respondent must be served with the claim notice in the manner prescribed by an order of the Court or otherwise in a manner permitted by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (6) A civil proceeding must be taken to have been begun against a person added as a respondent: - (a) on the date of the filing by a claimant of an application to join the party or - where the Court does so of its own motion on the making of the order by the Court adding that person as a respondent. (7) The Court may not of its own motion add a respondent without the consent in writing of all claimants.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title of this part of Order 43?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["PARTIES WITH A DISABILITY","DISABLED PARTIES","PARTIES IN ABILITY DISABILITY","PARTIES UNDER A DISABILITY"],"justification":"4 - PARTIES UNDER A DISABILITY"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 4 - PARTIES UNDER A DISABILITY'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court change a next friend or guardian litem?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["No, the court cannot change a next friend or guardian litem once they have been appointed.","The court can only change a next friend or guardian litem if the current one requests it themselves.","Only the next friend or guardian litem can request a change, not the court.","Yes, the court may change a next friend or guardian litem and appoint another person in their place"],"justification":"The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Court may appoint next friend or guardian litem* 7.[4] (1) When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the child. (2) The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Who can a child defend by?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A child may defend by their favorite teacher.","A child may defend by their older sibling.","A child may defend by their guardian litem appointed for that purpose.","A child may defend by their school principal."],"justification":"A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Child may defend by guardian litem* 9. (1) A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose. (2) Where a child defends by his or her guardian litem, a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''relevant person'' allowed to do under Order 43?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A relevant person may provide evidence under Order 56, rule 10.","A relevant person may sue or defend in accordance with Order 7, rule 8.","A relevant person may request a summary judgment under Order 24, rule 5.","A relevant person may appeal a decision made under Order 42."],"justification":"A relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) may sue or defend in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10**Relevant person* 10.[5] A relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) may sue or defend in accordance with [Order 7]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-7-District-Minors-And-Other-Persons-Under-Disability), rule 8.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for a compromise, payment, or acceptance of an offer in a civil proceeding involving a vulnerable person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Written consent of the vulnerable person","Consent from a medical professional","Approval by a legal guardian only","Approval of the Court"],"justification":"no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11**Compromise of claim by a vulnerable person* 11.*[6]*(1) If in a civil proceeding a claim is made by or on behalf of or against a child or a person in respect of whom a decision-making representation order has been made under section of the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html) and is in force, no compromise, payment of money or acceptance of an offer, whenever entered into or made, so far as it relates to that claim, is valid without the approval of the Court. (2) Application for approval must be by notice of motion (which may be in the [Form 43.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications) filed not later than 28 days after the compromise, payment or acceptance. (3) No affidavit is required in support of the notice of motion. (4) The Court may dispense with the requirement of a notice of motion if the application for approval is made at the hearing of the civil proceeding. (5) On the application, evidence must be given of the date of the compromise, payment or acceptance and the date of birth of the child or person, and the dates must be stated in any order approving the compromise, payment or acceptance. (6) If the acceptance of an offer of compromise is approved, the child or person must be taken to have made or accepted the offer at the time of approval.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done with a copy of any order made under this rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A copy of any order made under this rule must be posted to all parties involved in the case.","A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.","A copy of any order made under this rule must be filed with the local police department.","A copy of any order made under this rule must be uploaded to the official court website."],"justification":"A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Court may direct investment of an award to a child* 12. (1) The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable. (2) A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'How can an application for an interim payment be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Through submission of an oral request during a court hearing","Via written agreement between the parties involved without court involvement","By filing a petition with the court in Form 45.02","By motion, which may be in Form 43.03"],"justification":"by motion (which may be in the [Form 43.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Interim payments* 13.(1) Unless the Court otherwise decides, no interim payment out of any money secured or invested on behalf of a child may be made except under an order of the Court made on the application of the child''s next friend or guardian litem. (2) An application for an interim payment may be made by motion (which may be in the [Form 43.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the civil proceedings were heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application be made for a child to proceed or defend in their own name after attaining majority?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An application can be made when the child attains majority, even if the proceedings have concluded more than a year ago.","An application can be made when the child attains majority while the proceedings are still before the Court.","An application can be made when the child attains majority, provided that the proceedings have not yet begun.","An application can be made when the child attains majority only if the case has already been concluded."],"justification":"When a child attains majority while proceedings to which this Order relate are still before the Court, an application may be made parte by the former child''s solicitor, next friend or guardian litem at any sitting of the Court for the Court area in which the proceedings are being heard for an order that the claimant or respondent, formerly a child, may proceed or defend in his or her own name."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Proceeding in own name on attaining majority* 14. When a child attains majority while proceedings to which this Order relate are still before the Court, an application may be made parte by the former child''s solicitor, next friend or guardian litem at any sitting of the Court for the Court area in which the proceedings are being heard for an order that the claimant or respondent, formerly a child, may proceed or defend in his or her own name.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must a person produce to the Clerk when applying for payment out of sums invested on attaining majority?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Birth certificate and a form of identifying document including a photograph of the person.","Social security card and driver''s license without a photograph","Passport and high school diploma","Marriage certificate and utility bill as proof of residence"],"justification":"producing to the Clerk his or her birth certificate and a form of identifying document including a photograph of the person sufficient to identify the person as the person entitled to payment, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Payment out of sums invested on attaining majority* 15. (1) A person who, on attaining majority, seeks the payment of any money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit while the person was a child, may, where the order directing investment of the award to the child so provides, apply for payment out by request in writing to the Clerk (which may be in the [Form 43.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/40212e5e-3420-483b-8d18-b875e0c8be7d/Notice of application for payment out of Court of money secured or invested for the benefit of a child No. 43.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and: - (a) producing to the Clerk his or her birth certificate and a form of identifying document including a photograph of the person sufficient to identify the person as the person entitled to payment, and - filing with the Clerk a certified copy of his or her birth certificate. (2) If satisfied by the production of the person’s birth certificate and other identifying document, and any other information the Clerk in his or her discretion requires, the Clerk may authorise payment out of the balance of any money remaining to the credit of the person. (3) In any case of doubt, the Clerk may list the request for payment out before the Court. (4) In any other case, an application for payment out may be made parte to the Court. (5) On hearing a request or application under this rule, the Court may by order direct the payment out to the person of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to him or her, together with any accrued interest or investment gain, or may make any other order the Court considers just on the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the default rule for serving documents on a vulnerable person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Service of documents on a vulnerable person can be performed via any method deemed convenient by the legal representative.","Documents must always be served through a legal guardian or next of kin, regardless of the specific circumstances.","Service of documents on a vulnerable person should follow standard procedures outlined in Order 39, unless specified by the court.","Service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41 unless the Court otherwise orders."],"justification":"Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Service of documents* 16.[7] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents on a vulnerable person must be in accordance with the provisions of Order 41.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["TRUSTEERS, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS","TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND GUARDIANS","TRUSTEERS, EXECUTORS AND MANAGERS","TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ATTORNEYS"],"justification":"TRUSTEERS, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can trustees, executors, and administrators sue or be sued on behalf of a trust or estate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["They can only be sued personally and not in their representative capacity for the trust or estate.","Trustees, executors, and administrators can only sue on behalf of the trust or estate, but they cannot be sued themselves.","No, trustees, executors, and administrators cannot sue or be sued on behalf of a trust or estate.","Yes, they can sue and be sued on behalf of the trust or estate without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate."],"justification":"Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and must be taken to represent the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Trustees, executors and administrators* 17. (1) Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and must be taken to represent the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate. (2) The Court may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the number associated with this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["8","6","5","7"],"justification":"6"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 6 - PARTNERS'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'When can partners sue or be sued in the firm''s name?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Partners can only sue or be sued in the firm''s name if they have been registered with the State for at least one year.","Partners can only sue or be sued in the firm''s name if they have explicitly written a consent letter stating their willingness to be named in any legal proceedings.","Two or more persons claiming or being liable as partners and carrying on business in the State may sue or be sued in the name of the firm of which those persons were partners when the cause of action accrued and in the names of those persons.","Individual partners can sue or be sued in the firm''s name regardless of whether they were active in the business at the time of the cause of action."],"justification":"Two or more persons claiming or being liable as partners and carrying on business in the State may sue or be sued in the name of the firm of which those persons were partners when the cause of action accrued and in the names of those persons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Partners may sue or be sued in firm name* 18. Two or more persons claiming or being liable as partners and carrying on business in the State may sue or be sued in the name of the firm of which those persons were partners when the cause of action accrued and in the names of those persons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'How is the statement of partners'' details to be provided and verified?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["As directed by the Court.","According to the internal audit department''s findings.","In accordance with the company''s internal policy.","As requested by the partners themselves."],"justification":"to be provided and verified as the Court directs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1**9 Court may direct provision of particulars of all partners* 19. Any party to a civil proceeding by or against partners suing in the name of a firm may apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time the cause of action accrued, partners in the firm, to be provided and verified as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the claimants or their solicitors fail to comply with a demand under sub-rule (1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["All proceedings on the claim may be stayed on such terms as the Court directs.","The claimants or their solicitors may be fined by the court.","The opposing party may be granted immediate judgment in their favor.","All proceedings on the claim may be dismissed outright without further notice."],"justification":"If the claimants or their solicitors fail to comply with a demand under sub-rule (1), all proceedings on the claim may, on an application for that purpose, be stayed on such terms as the Court directs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Claimants must provide particulars of all partners* 20. (1) When a claim notice is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the claimants or their solicitors must, on receipt of a written demand by any respondent, immediately confirm in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. (2) If the claimants or their solicitors fail to comply with a demand under sub-rule (1), all proceedings on the claim may, on an application for that purpose, be stayed on such terms as the Court directs. (3) When the particulars of the partners are provided, the claim may proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects follow, as if each of the partners had been named as claimants in the claim notice, but the civil proceedings must nevertheless continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'How must a claim notice be served when persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["In accordance with Order 41, rule 10.","In accordance with Order 42, rule 3.","In accordance with Order 35, rule 8.","In accordance with Order 41, rule 9."],"justification":"the claim notice must be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 10."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Service on partners* 21. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, the claim notice must be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the defence be in the name of the firm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The defence can only be conducted by individual partners, not the firm itself.","No, the defence cannot be in the name of the firm.","Yes, the defence may be in the name of the firm.","Defence actions must always be anonymous and cannot be attributed to any entity."],"justification":"the defence may be in the name of the firm"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *22 Appearance and defence* 22. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, the appearance must show individually the names of the persons on whose behalf it is filed; but the defence may be in the name of the firm and all subsequent proceedings may nevertheless continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What type of proceedings does this Order apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Criminal proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and criminal proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State.","Civil proceedings between a firm and a third party who is not a member, and civil proceedings between firms having no common members, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State.","Administrative proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and administrative proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State.","Civil proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and civil proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State."],"justification":"The provisions of this Order apply to civil proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and to civil proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Application to proceedings between a firm and a partner* 23. (1) The provisions of this Order apply to civil proceedings between a firm and one or more of its members, and to civil proceedings between firms having one or more members in common, provided that the firm or firms carry on business within the State. (2) No execution may be issued in proceedings mentioned in sub-rule (1) without the permission of the Court, which must be sought by motion on notice to the party to be affected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 7 - PERSONS USING BUSINESS NAMES AND CARRYING ON ACTIVITIES AS A CLUB'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person carrying on business in a name or style other than their own be sued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes, but only if they have registered the name or style with the government.","Yes, they may be sued in the name or style under which they carry on business.","They cannot be sued at all if they are operating under a different name or style.","No, they can only be sued using their legal name."],"justification":"A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Person trading under a business name* 24. (1) A person carrying on business in the State in a name or style other than his or her own name, which is not registered under the [Registration of Business Names Act 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in the name or style under which he or she carries on business. (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing the business to provide and verify as the Court directs the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time the cause of action accrued was carrying on the business concerned. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)on the person carrying on business or on the person who at the time of service appears to have control or to be managing the business, at the place where the business is carried on. (4) Service in accordance with sub-rule (3) must be taken to be effective service on the person sued whether or not that person is in or outside the State, and the permission of the Court to issue the claim notice or other document is not necessary.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can a club be sued in its own name?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Only if the club has been registered as a non-profit organization.","Yes, but only if the club has been officially registered with the government.","No, because clubs cannot be recognized as legal entities.","Yes, if it is carrying on any activity in the State as a club, regardless of registration status."],"justification":"Persons carrying on any activity in the State as a club may, in addition to any other manner in which they may be sued, be sued in the name of the club, whether or not the club is registered under the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Person carrying on activity as a club* 25. (1) Persons carrying on any activity in the State as a club may, in addition to any other manner in which they may be sued, be sued in the name of the club, whether or not the club is registered under the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the persons who appear to have control or to be managing the activity to provide and verify as the Court directs the names, description and places of residence of the persons who at the time the cause of action accrued were the officers or trustees of the club or the persons otherwise in control of the activity carried on by the club. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) on one of the persons who at the time of service appears to be an officer or trustee of the club, or to have control of the activity carried on by the club, at a place where the activity is carried on.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What does this rule state about the application of provisions related to proceedings against firms?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply only to cases where rule 24 explicitly mentions firms, regardless of the nature of the case.","The provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply to all cases to which rule 24 or rule 25 applies, insofar as the nature of the case permits.","According to these Rules, the provisions concerning proceedings against firms are limited to cases where rule 24 applies exclusively, without considering the applicability of rule 25.","These Rules state that the provisions regarding proceedings against firms do not apply unless both rule 24 and rule 25 are invoked simultaneously."],"justification":"In so far as the nature of the case permits, the provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply to all cases to which rule 24 or rule 25 applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Provisions concerning firms to apply in a claim against a person trading under a business name or against a club* 26. In so far as the nature of the case permits, the provisions of these Rules relating to proceedings against firms apply to all cases to which rule 24 or rule 25 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title of this part of Order 43?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["CHANGE OF LOCATION","PARTY INVITATIONS","CHANGE OF PARTIES","ORDER AMENDMENT"],"justification":"8 - CHANGE OF PARTIES"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 8 - CHANGE OF PARTIES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to a claim if there is a death of a party after the verdict or judgment but before recording?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claim automatically transfers to the deceased party''s heirs without the need for any legal proceedings.","The claim abates and cannot be recorded until a new party is formally substituted in the case.","The claim is frozen until a court order determines the next course of action.","The claim does not abate and the judgment or order can still be recorded."],"justification":"Whether the cause of action survives or not, a claim does not abate by reason of the death of any party between the verdict or the finding of the issues of fact and the judgment, or between the announcement and recording of the judgment or order. In any such case, the judgment or order of the Court may be recorded or entered notwithstanding the death."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Claim does not abate on death or bankruptcy* 27. (1) A claim does not abate by reason of the death or bankruptcy of a party, if the cause of action survives or continues. (2) A claim or civil proceeding does not become defective by the assignment, creation, or devolution of any estate or title pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate). (3) Whether the cause of action survives or not, a claim does not abate by reason of the death of any party between the verdict or the finding of the issues of fact and the judgment, or between the announcement and recording of the judgment or order. (4) In any such case, the judgment or order of the Court may be recorded or entered notwithstanding the death.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What actions can the court take regarding personal representatives in civil proceedings under Rule 28?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may order the personal representative to be made a party to the proceedings or served with notice of the proceedings, on terms the court deems just.","The court may mandate the personal representative to dissolve the estate immediately, regardless of the proceedings.","The court may compel the personal representative to testify under oath in any unrelated criminal case.","The court may require the personal representative to provide financial compensation to the opposing party as a penalty."],"justification":"the Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: (a) be made a party to the civil proceedings; or be served with notice of the civil proceedings, on such terms as the Court thinks just"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Court may join personal representative* 28. (1) This rule applies where a party to civil proceedings dies or is adjudicated bankrupt, or the estate of a party to civil proceedings devolves by operation of law. (2) In a case to which this rule applies, the Court may, if it considers it necessary for the complete settlement of the questions involved, order that the personal representative, assignee, trustee, or other successor in interest of a party: - (a) be made a party to the civil proceedings; or - be served with notice of the civil proceedings, on such terms as the Court thinks just, and the Court may make such orders for the disposal of the civil proceedings as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can a civil proceeding continue after the assignment, creation, or devolution of an estate or title?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When an estate or title is assigned, created, or devolved parte (without notice to the opposing party), a civil proceeding may not continue by or against the person to whom the estate or title has come or devolved.","When an estate or title is assigned, created, or devolved pendente lite (pending administration of an estate), a civil proceeding may continue by or against the person to whom the estate or title has come or devolved.","When an estate or title is assigned, created, or devolved sine die (without setting a date for further proceedings), a civil proceeding terminates immediately.","When an estate or title is assigned, created, or devolved post mortem (after the death of the individual), a civil proceeding cannot continue by or against the person to whom the estate or title has come or devolved."],"justification":"Where any estate or title to any property is assigned, created or devolved pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate), a civil, proceeding may be continued by or against the person to, or on whom, the estate or title has come or devolved."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Continuation of civil proceedings pending administration of an estate* 29. Where any estate or title to any property is assigned, created or devolved pendente lite (or pending administration of an estate), a civil, proceeding may be continued by or against the person to, or on whom, the estate or title has come or devolved.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances does Rule 30 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the party involved changes their address or place of residence.","When the death or bankruptcy of a party or another event causes a change or transmission of legal interest or liability, or when a person interested in the claim or proceeding comes into existence after the proceeding began.","When a new witness is discovered who can provide testimony unrelated to the legal interest or liability of the parties.","When the court decides to reschedule the hearing due to unforeseen circumstances."],"justification":"This rule applies where: (a) the death or bankruptcy of a party or another event which occurred after the civil proceeding was begun causes a change or transmission of the legal interest or liability; or a person interested in the claim or civil proceeding has come into existence after the civil proceeding was begun."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 Change of parties on death or bankruptcy or other event* 30. (1) This rule applies where: - (a) the death or bankruptcy of a party or another event which occurred after the civil proceeding was begun causes a change or transmission of the legal interest or liability; or - a person interested in the claim or civil proceeding has come into existence after the civil proceeding was begun. (2) Where, in a case to which sub-rule (1) applies, it becomes necessary or desirable that: - (a) a person who is not already a party should be made a party; or - a person who is already a party should be made a party in another capacity, the Court may, by order made parte, order that the proceedings be carried on between the continuing parties, and a new party or parties, where the Court is satisfied that there has been a change or transmission of a legal interest or liability as specified in sub-rule (1)(a), or that a person interested has come into existence as specified in sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Who must an order obtained under Rule 30 be served on?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The judge who issued the order and the court clerk","Each of the existing parties and their solicitors, but not the new parties","Only the new parties involved in the case","Each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is themselves the only new party)."],"justification":"Unless the Court otherwise directs, an order obtained under rule 30 must be served on each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is himself or herself the only new party)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *31 Service of an order under rule 30* 31. (1) Unless the Court otherwise directs, an order obtained under rule 30 must be served on each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is himself or herself the only new party). (2) Subject to rules 32 and 33, an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served, and every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a person under a disability without a guardian litem is served with an order under rule 30?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The person should wait for a guardian litem to be appointed before taking any action.","The person can ignore the order as they are considered legally incompetent.","The person must immediately comply with the order without any further action.","The person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order within ten days after a guardian litem is appointed."],"justification":"the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Service of an order under rule 30 on a person under a disability* 33. Where a person under a disability who does not have a guardian litem in the civil proceeding is served with an order under rule 30, the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person and, until the period of ten days has expired, the order under rule 30 has no force or effect against the person under a disability.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the consequence if the claimant does not proceed within the time fixed by the court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The case will be postponed indefinitely.","The claimant will receive a warning and additional time to proceed.","The claim will be dismissed with costs.","The defendant will automatically win the case."],"justification":"the claim be dismissed with costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *34 Order on failure to proceed following death of a party* 34. (1) Where: - (a) a claimant in a civil proceeding dies, and - the cause of action survives, but the person entitled to proceed fails to proceed, the respondent (or the person against whom the action, proceeding or matter, may be continued) may apply by motion on notice to compel the claimant (or the person entitled to proceed), to proceed within a period to be fixed by the Court. (2) Where the Court makes an order on an application under sub-rule (1), the court may make an order that, in default of proceeding within the time fixed by the Court, the claim be dismissed with costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the number of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["5","8","9","10"],"justification":"9"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 9 - CONSOLIDATION'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 44 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","Supreme Court","County Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["JURY SELECTION PROCEDURES [1]","PRE-TRIAL APPLICATIONS: GENERAL [1]","POST-TRIAL MOTIONS [1]","RULES OF EVIDENCE [1]"],"justification":"PRE-TRIAL APPLICATIONS: GENERAL [1]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - PRE-TRIAL APPLICATIONS: GENERAL [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What does this Order apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any final judgment in a civil proceeding.","Any application in a criminal proceeding.","Any criminal prosecution.","Any interlocutory or other application in a civil proceeding."],"justification":"Unless otherwise provided by these Rules, this Order applies to any interlocutory or other application in a civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application of this Order* 1. (1) Unless otherwise provided by these Rules, this Order applies to any interlocutory or other application in a civil proceeding. (2) Nothing in this Order limits the power of the Court to make any interlocutory order or give a direction (whether in the presence of some only or all of the parties) without the issue of a notice of motion in an appropriate case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum notice required for applications to the Court other than parte applications or applications for adjournment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least 48 hours'' notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court.","At least 1 week''s notice verbally communicated to the court clerk.","At least 7 days'' notice in writing to the Judge directly.","At least 24 hours'' notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court."],"justification":"Unless any statute or rule otherwise provides, the moving party in any application to the Court other than an parte application or an application for an adjournment must give at least 48 hours’ notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court at which such application is to be made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Form and timing of application* 2. (1) An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit. (2) An application by notice of motion is made when the notice of motion is filed in accordance with rule 4. (3) Unless any statute or rule otherwise provides, the moving party in any application to the Court other than an parte application or an application for an adjournment must give at least 48 hours’ notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court at which such application is to be made. This filing of a notice of motion or notice of application for issue is deemed to be notice to the Clerk of intention to make the application contained in the notice on the return date assigned to it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court order on the return date of a notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may order that the person making the application pays a fine if they lose the case.","The Court may order that the person making the application serves as a juror in another trial.","The Court may order that the person making the application must attend a legal seminar before proceeding.","The Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest."],"justification":"On the return date of a notice of motion the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Notice of application to other parties or persons* 3. On the return date of a notice of motion the Court may order that the person making the application give notice of it to any other person having a sufficient interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a notice of motion be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 44.02, Schedule without modifications","Form 45.01, Schedule A, regardless of the case specifics","Form 44.01, Schedule with no regard for case modifications","Form 44.01, Schedule modified as appropriate to the case"],"justification":"A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form and filing* 4. (1) A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case and must include particulars of the order, direction or other relief sought as appropriate to the case, a summary of the grounds of the application and, where relevant, a statement of the provisions of law including the provisions of any enactment or these Rules relied on in making the application. (2) A notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk assigned to the Court area in which the proceedings concerned have been issued and assigned a return date by the Clerk. (3) Where the grounds for the order, direction or other relief sought include the failure or refusal of the opposing party to agree a matter, copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached to the original notice of motion. (4) Where more than one order, direction or other relief is sought against the same party in the same civil proceeding: - (a) so far as practicable, all such orders, directions or other reliefs must be sought in the same notice of motion and a party must not suffer any adverse consequence in the costs to which the party is found to be entitled by reason of having sought several orders, directions or other reliefs in the same notice of motion; and - where practicable, a party must seek all of the interlocutory orders, directions or other reliefs which the party seeks in the civil proceeding on the same return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Who must serve a copy of a notice of motion and any supporting affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The respondent","The court clerk","The legal advisor","The applicant"],"justification":"The applicant must serve a copy of a notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit in support of the notice of motion on every person to whom notice of the motion is to be given unless otherwise provided by these Rules or by an order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Service* 5. (1) The applicant must serve a copy of a notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit in support of the notice of motion on every person to whom notice of the motion is to be given unless otherwise provided by these Rules or by an order of the Court. (2) Every notice of motion must be served on every other party against whom any relief is sought in the motion not less than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Who can amend a notice of motion if it has not been served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A Clerk, at the request of the party who filed it","An Attorney, on behalf of the recipient of the notice","The opposing party, once they have received the notice","A Judge, upon the application of any interested party"],"justification":"If a notice of motion has not been served a Clerk may, at the request of the party who filed it, amend the notice of motion on or before the return date named in the notice of motion to name another return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Return date* 6. (1) If a notice of motion has not been served a Clerk may, at the request of the party who filed it, amend the notice of motion on or before the return date named in the notice of motion to name another return date. (2) In any other case, a notice of motion may only be amended by the Court. (3) A notice of motion must not be amended under sub-rule (1) more than once.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Does sub-rule (1) limit the ability of any party to rely on affidavits or documents during the hearing of a motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Sub-rule (1) requires all affidavits and documents to be reviewed by a judge prior to being used in the hearing of a motion.","Sub-rule (1) limits the reliance on affidavits and documents to only those that are deemed relevant by the opposing party.","Sub-rule (1) restricts the use of affidavits and documents to only those that were submitted before the motion was filed.","No, it does not limit the ability of any party to rely on affidavits or documents."],"justification":"Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any affidavit or document at the hearing of an application by motion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Copies for Court* 7. (1) The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: - (a) any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and - any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any affidavit or document at the hearing of an application by motion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the court have regarding the adjournment of a hearing for an application by notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court can only adjourn the hearing if there is a legal holiday scheduled on the day of the hearing.","The court cannot adjourn the hearing except by unanimous agreement of both parties involved in the motion.","The court may adjourn the hearing on such terms as it thinks just.","The court must adjourn the hearing if requested by either party."],"justification":"The Court may adjourn the hearing of an application by notice of motion on such terms as it thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Adjournment* 8. The Court may adjourn the hearing of an application by notice of motion on such terms as it thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served.","The Court will dismiss the case for lack of attendance.","The Court will automatically rule in favor of the party who failed to attend.","The Court must postpone the hearing until the next available date."],"justification":"If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Absence of party served with notice of motion* 9. (1) If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served. (2) If on an application by notice of motion the applicant fails to attend, the Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Applications to Set Aside or Vary","Applications to Invalidate or Nullify","Applications to Set Forth or Explain","Applications to Amend or Modify"],"justification":"2 - APPLICATIONS TO SET ASIDE OR VARY"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - APPLICATIONS TO SET ASIDE OR VARY'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the court discharge, set aside or vary an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["When the application for the original order was made on notice to the person affected but they did not attend the hearing, or when the application was not made on notice to the person.","When the person affected has attended all hearings and responded to the original application.","When the court finds that the original order was made with full compliance with procedural rules and no party requested a variation.","When the person affected consented to the original order without any objections."],"justification":"The Court may, on an application by notice of motion ( [Form 44.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate to the case) by the person affected, on notice to the applicant for the original order, discharge, set aside or vary an order which affects a person where the application for the order— - (a) was made on notice to that person, but the person did not attend the hearing of the application; or - was not made on notice to that person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Application to discharge, set aside or vary an order* 10. (1) The Court may, on an application by notice of motion ( [Form 44.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate to the case) by the person affected, on notice to the applicant for the original order, discharge, set aside or vary an order which affects a person where the application for the order— - (a) was made on notice to that person, but the person did not attend the hearing of the application; or - was not made on notice to that person. (2) An order under sub-rule (1) may be subject to such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just. [1] Order 44 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 45 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme","High","District","County"],"justification":"District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment - Court: District # **ORDER 45: LODGMENTS AND TENDERS IN LIEU OF LODGMENT****[**[1]**](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title of this chunk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["INTRODUCTION","DEFINITION","METHODS","INTERPRETATION"],"justification":"INTERPRETATION"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - INTERPRETATION'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["LODGEMENT","LODGING","LODGMENT","LODGEMANTLE"],"justification":"## 2 - LODGMENT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - LODGMENT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What must a notice of lodgment contain?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A declaration of non-compliance with the court order","A statement to the effect that it is served in accordance with this Order.","The date and time of service by postal mail","A copy of the defendant''s signature"],"justification":"The notice of lodgment must contain a statement to the effect that it is served in accordance with this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application* 2. (1) The respondent may in respect of any claim in a civil proceeding, at any time up to the time prescribed for filing and service of the respondent’s appearance and defence, lodge in Court a sum of money which he or she alleges is sufficient to satisfy the claim. (2) A lodgment in respect of a claim may be on terms that take into account any other claim between the claimant and the respondent made in the proceeding. (3) A notice of the making of the lodgment ( [Form 45.01,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/316453b8-eaa8-459b-b446-26f94604972d/Notice of lodgment No. 45.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be made in writing in a document other than the appearance and defence. (4) The notice of lodgment must contain a statement to the effect that it is served in accordance with this Order. (5) A copy of the notice of lodgment must be served on the party whose claim the lodgment is intended to meet when the appearance and defence to the claim is served on that party. (6) The original of the notice of lodgment must be filed with the Clerk who must keep it in a separate file. (7) Neither the Clerk nor any other person may disclose the fact (or the amount) of any lodgment to the Court until all issues between the parties concerned have been decided. (8) Neither the fact nor the amount of a lodgment may be intimated in a defence or other pleading or document filed in Court (other than the notice of lodgment or any notice of acceptance of a lodgment).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What is required if a party wishes to accept a lodgment beyond the initial 28-day period?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["a formal notice sent by the court","verbal agreement from the party who made the lodgment","written consent from any party involved in the process","written consent of the party who made the lodgment"],"justification":"with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Time for accepting a lodgment* 3. (1) The party whose claim a lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged ( [Form 45.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ccf352c0-e18f-4d6c-aa65-52d5ea012416/Notice of acceptance of lodgment No. 45.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule within 28 days after the notice of lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment. (2) Where a late lodgment or an increase to a lodgment is made in accordance with rule 6, the party whose claim the lodgment or increased lodgment is intended to meet may accept the amount lodged within 28 days after the notice of lodgment or notice of increased lodgment was served, or at any later time with the written consent of the party who made the lodgment or increased lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done if the amount of costs cannot be agreed upon after accepting a lodgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may determine the scale of costs to apply.","The costs will automatically be set to a standard rate.","The parties must engage in a new round of negotiations.","The case is dismissed due to inability to agree on costs."],"justification":"the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Consequences of accepting a lodgment* 4. (1) On acceptance of a lodgment, the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court, provided that the party accepting the lodgment has lodged with the Clerk or with the Accountant a signed notice of acceptance of the lodgment in full satisfaction of the claim, save as to costs and, where acceptance of the lodgment requires the consent of the party who made the lodgment, the written consent of that party to late acceptance of the lodgment. (2) If the amount of costs to which a party who has accepted a lodgment is entitled cannot be agreed between the parties concerned, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What must a party do after making a lodgment or increasing an existing one?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Publish the notice of lodgment or increased lodgment in a local newspaper instead of serving it directly.","Provide a written acknowledgment to the court without notifying the specific party whose claim is intended to be met.","Serve a notice of lodgment or notice of increased lodgment on any unrelated third party.","Serve a notice of lodgment or notice of increased lodgment on the party whose claim is intended to be met."],"justification":"A party who makes or increases a lodgment in accordance with sub-rule (1) must serve a notice of lodgment (or notice of increased lodgment) on the party whose claim is intended to be met."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Permission to make a late lodgment* 6. (1) Despite rule 2(1), a party may make a lodgment, or may make a further payment into court to increase an existing lodgment— - (a) in any case where an amendment has been made to the statement of claim in the claim notice (or, as the case may be, the counterclaim or third party notice) in which the claim is made, within 28 days after the amended pleading is served on the party making the lodgment; or - with the written consent of the party whose claim is intended to be met by the lodgment, within such further period as is permitted in that party’s consent, the original of which must be lodged with the Clerk; or - with the permission of the Court, within such further period as is permitted in the Court’s order. (2) A party who makes or increases a lodgment in accordance with sub-rule (1) must serve a notice of lodgment (or notice of increased lodgment) on the party whose claim is intended to be met.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What does the Court do if it decides the amount to which a party is entitled is less than the amount lodged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court gives judgment for the party making the claim for the amount found due and awards the costs incurred after lodgment to the party who made the lodgment.","The Court reduces the claim amount proportionally among all parties involved in the case.","The Court awards the full amount lodged to the party who made the claim, disregarding the actual amount found due.","The Court dismisses the case as there is no sufficient amount to warrant a judgment."],"justification":"Where a Court decides that the amount to which a party is entitled in respect of a claim is less than the amount lodged to meet that claim, the Court must give judgment for the party making the claim for the amount the Court finds to be due, but must award to the party who made the lodgment the costs incurred in respect of the proceedings after the lodgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Liability for costs where a lodgment is not accepted* 7. (1) Where a party does not accept the amount lodged within the time prescribed, that party is liable for all costs incurred after the lodgment (or increased lodgment) in respect of the proceeding unless the Court decides that the amount due in respect of the claim is greater than the amount lodged in respect of the claim. (2) Where a Court decides that the amount to which a party is entitled in respect of a claim is less than the amount lodged to meet that claim, the Court must give judgment for the party making the claim for the amount the Court finds to be due, but must award to the party who made the lodgment the costs incurred in respect of the proceedings after the lodgment. (3) The Court may make an order as to the disposal of the amount lodged in court as the Court thinks just. (4) Despite sub-rules (1) and (2), the Court may, due to the special circumstances of the case specifically identified by the Court, order that the party who did not accept the lodgment - - (a) is not liable for any, or a specified amount of the costs incurred after lodgment of the party who made the lodgment; or - may recover a specified amount of that party’s costs incurred after lodgment from the party who made the lodgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What does Section 3 cover?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Tender offer by any party regardless of qualification status","Procedures for issuing public announcements","Legal requirements for shareholder meetings","Tender offer by a qualified party in lieu of lodgment"],"justification":"## 3 - TENDER OFFER BY QUALIFIED PARTY IN LIEU OF LODGMENT"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - TENDER OFFER BY QUALIFIED PARTY IN LIEU OF LODGMENT'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Who qualifies as a ''qualified party'' under this rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A citizen of the State who has filed a tax return in the last year","An individual residing in the State for more than five years","Any person holding a valid driver''s license issued by the State","A Minister of Government, the Attorney General, the Government, the State, any party in respect of whom the State is providing an indemnity, an indemnifier of any party authorised to carry on business in the State as an insurance undertaking, the Motor Insurers Bureau, or the Visiting Motor Insurers Bureau."],"justification":"A party is as a qualified party for the purposes of this rule if the party is: - (a) a Minister of Government; or - the Attorney General; or - the Government; or - the State; or - any party in respect of whom the State is providing an indemnity; or - an indemnifier of any party authorised to carry on business in the State as an insurance undertaking under the law for the time being in force; or - the Motor Insurers Bureau; or - the Visiting Motor Insurers Bureau."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Qualified parties* 9. (1) A party is as a qualified party for the purposes of this rule if the party is: - (a) a Minister of Government; or - the Attorney General; or - the Government; or - the State; or - any party in respect of whom the State is providing an indemnity; or - an indemnifier of any party authorised to carry on business in the State as an insurance undertaking under the law for the time being in force; or - the Motor Insurers Bureau; or - the Visiting Motor Insurers Bureau. (2) Where a qualified party is entitled to make or increase a lodgment on the qualified party’s own behalf or on behalf of any other party under Part 2 of this Order or by order of the Court, then the qualified party may, in lieu of lodging money in Court, make an offer of tender of payment to the party whose claim is intended to be met. (3) A tender offer made under this rule is deemed to be a lodgment and to have the same effect as a lodgment. (4) The provisions of Part 2 of this Order apply mutatis mutandis to tender offers as regards time for making and accepting them as they apply to a lodgment. (5) A tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c615f98-b1cb-4e49-8de0-893c7e83d3ed/Notice of tender offer No. 45.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule and must state whether liability is admitted or denied and, subject to rule 2, is to be taken to be part of the pleadings. (6) Notice of acceptance of a tender offer must be made in writing in accordance with [Form 45.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9d5e1b73-6967-49af-9b94-71cb34a75358/Notice of acceptance of tender offer No. 45.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the provisions of rules 4 and 5 apply to such acceptance. (7) Where a tender offer has been accepted, the qualified party who made the tender offer must pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a qualified party fails to pay the sum specified in their tender offer within 28 days of receiving notice of acceptance?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The qualified party''s liability is waived, but they must provide a written apology to the relevant authority.","The qualified party is exempt from paying the sum and no further action can be taken against them.","The qualified party is required to pay double the sum as a penalty, but no interest is charged.","The qualified party remains liable to pay the sum and is also liable to pay interest on the sum at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after the 28-day period."],"justification":"A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid. (9) Any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer and the Court may make any order or give any directions on that application as the Court considers just and proper. [1] Order 45 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'If the party from whom security has been sought does not agree to provide security, what can the applicant do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Terminate the legal proceedings immediately without further notice.","Apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided.","Request a refund for the application fees submitted so far.","Seek mediation with the party to resolve the disagreement amicably."],"justification":"Where the party from whom security has been sought does not undertake in writing to provide security, the applicant for security may apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application for security* 1. (1) A party who requires security for costs from another party may apply in writing to that other party for security for costs. (2) Where the party from whom security has been sought does not undertake in writing to provide security, the applicant for security may apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided. (3) On hearing the application, the Court may order the claimant to lodge in Court the costs of an order dismissing the claim, or may make such other order as it thinks appropriate. (4) If an order is made requiring a party to give security for costs, security must be given in the manner and at the time the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Can an order for security for costs be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Only if the individual has previously been involved in similar litigation.","Yes, if the case involves significant cross-border implications.","No.","Yes, provided that the individual''s financial status indicates they may not cover the costs."],"justification":"No order for security for costs may be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 If the claimant is outside the State or is a foreign national* 2. (1) A respondent is not entitled to an order compelling a claimant to give security for costs solely on the ground that the claimant resides outside the State unless the respondent shows to the satisfaction of the Court that he or she has a defence on the merits. (2) No order for security for costs may be made against a natural person who is a national of and resident in another Member State of the European Union or against a party who applies, under the provisions of the Jurisdiction Regulation or the 1968 Convention (each as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court)), for enforcement of a judgment given in another Member State or Contracting State, solely on the ground that the claimant is a foreign national or that the claimant is not domiciled or resident in the State.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can the Court dismiss a claimant''s claim notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["If the claimant wins the case before the trial begins.","If the claimant files the claim notice after the designated time period has expired.","If the claimant fails to give the security required by an order.","If the claimant refuses to participate in mandatory arbitration."],"justification":"If a claimant fails to give the security required by an order, the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Failure to give security* 3. If a claimant fails to give the security required by an order, the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the court have regarding orders requiring a claimant to give security for costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court can only increase the amount of security required without variation.","The court is obligated to enforce such orders strictly as issued by the lower court.","The court may set aside or vary such orders.","The court cannot modify or nullify such orders under any circumstances."],"justification":"The Court may set aside or vary any order requiring a claimant to give security for costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Variation or setting aside* 4. The Court may set aside or vary any order requiring a claimant to give security for costs. [1] Order 45A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","High Court","Supreme Court","County Court"],"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents - Court: District # **Order Discovery and Inspection of Documents******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Does this Order apply to debt claims?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Yes, if the debtor requests a formal defense review.","No, unless the claim exceeds a specified monetary threshold.","No, unless an order has been made giving leave to defend.","Yes, it applies to all types of debt claims."],"justification":"This Order does not apply to debt claims (unless an order has been made giving leave to defend)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application of this Order* 1. This Order does not apply to debt claims (unless an order has been made giving leave to defend) or to small claims.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What can a respondent request from a claimant after receiving a claim notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An immediate payment of the amount claimed by the claimant as outlined in the notice.","Copies of all or any of the correspondence or other documents listed in the statement of claim, and any other document referred to in the statement of claim.","A detailed account of the financial transactions between the parties involved in the case.","A summary of the witness testimonies that will be presented during the trial."],"justification":"A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of: (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the statement of claim; any other document referred to in the statement of claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Request for inspection or copies of documents listed in claim notice or defence* 2. (1) A respondent may, at any time after service of a claim notice on him or her and before delivery of an appearance and defence make a request to the claimant in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the statement of claim; - any other document referred to in the statement of claim. (2) A claimant may, at any time after service of an appearance and defence on him or her make a request to the respondent in writing for copies of all or any of: - (a) the correspondence or other documents listed in the appearance and defence; - any other document mentioned in the appearance and defence. (3) The party to whom a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) is made must within seven days after receipt of the request: - (a) provide copies of such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement on payment of the reasonable charges for copying them; or - produce such of the documents requested as are in his possession or power of procurement for inspection by the party who made the request, or by his or her solicitor, and permit him or her to take copies. (4) If so agreed by the parties: - (a) copies of documents may be provided in electronic form or such other form as is agreed or directed; and - inspection may be permitted of electronic copies of documents or of documents in electronic form. (5) A party who fails to comply with a request under sub-rule (1) or (2) may not afterwards put any such document in evidence on his or her behalf, unless the Court is satisfied that there was a sufficient reason for not complying with the request, in which case the Court may allow the document to be put in evidence on such terms as to costs and otherwise as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the party requested fails to respond to the discovery request?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The party seeking discovery must immediately cease all other discovery activities until a response is provided.","The party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath.","The party requested can be charged with contempt of court and face potential fines or imprisonment.","The party requested is automatically granted additional time to respond without any further action."],"justification":"If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Application for discovery following request* 3. (1) Where a party wishes to have discovery of documents in addition to those which may be produced under rule 2, the party must first make a request in writing for voluntary discovery within a period of 21 days from the date of the request. (2) The request must specify the precise documents or categories of documents in respect of which discovery is sought; provide the reasons why each category of documents is required to be discovered and explain why discovery of the documents sought is necessary for disposing fairly of the claim or for saving costs. (3) If the party requested fails, refuses or neglects to make discovery or ignores the request, the party seeking discovery may apply to the Court by notice of motion supported by an affidavit for an order directing the party requested to make discovery on oath of the documents which are or have been in his possession or power of procurement, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceeding. (4) The notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit must be served not less than four clear days before the return date. (5) On hearing the application, the Court may, having regard to the value of the claim: - (a) refuse or adjourn the application, if satisfied that discovery is not necessary, or not necessary at that stage of the proceeding; or - make such order on such terms as to the security for the costs of discovery or otherwise, and either generally or limited to certain classes of documents, as he or she thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'In what format should the affidavit be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["In accordance with Form Schedule","In accordance with Form Schedule","In accordance with Form Schedule","In accordance with Form Schedule"],"justification":"must be in accordance with [Form 45B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c207105-72a0-418f-a30c-45d618b1f461/Affidavit as to documents No. 45B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Affidavit* 5. The affidavit to be made by a party against whom an order for discovery has been made must specify which, if any, of the documents scheduled in the affidavit he or she objects to produce, and must be in accordance with [Form 45B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c207105-72a0-418f-a30c-45d618b1f461/Affidavit as to documents No. 45B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice is required for an application under sub-rule (2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["One week after the return date.","Four clear days before the return date.","Seven clear days before the return date.","Two clear days before the return date."],"justification":"An application under sub-rule (2) must be made by motion on notice to be served not later than four clear days before the return date"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Order to produce documents for inspection* 6. (1) The Court may at any time while civil proceedings are pending order the production by any party to the civil proceedings, on oath, of such of the documents in his possession or power, relating to any matter in question in the civil proceedings, as the Court thinks right; and the Court may deal with such documents, when produced, in the manner the Court considers just. (2) If a party served with a request under rule 2(1) or (2) omits to provide copies or notify a time for inspection, or objects to allowing inspection, the Court may, on the application of the party desiring it, make an order for inspection at such time and in such place and in such manner as the Court directs. (3) An application under sub-rule (2) must be made by motion on notice to be served not later than four clear days before the return date and supported by an affidavit showing of what documents inspection is sought and that they are in the possession or power of procurement of the other party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant will be required to pay all legal fees associated with the case.","The claimant''s case will automatically be awarded to the defendant.","The claimant will receive a warning but no further action will be taken.","The claimant''s claim may be dismissed for want of prosecution."],"justification":"If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Failure to comply with order for discovery* 7. (1) If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution. (2) If a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her appearance and defence, if any, struck out, and to be placed in the same position as if he or she had not defended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition does the Court certify discovery as necessary?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["When it is deemed necessary by the Court","When the discovery process has not been initiated yet","When the Court finds that the discovery may lead to a settlement","When requested by either party in the lawsuit"],"justification":"where, and only where, discovery is certified as necessary by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Costs of discovery* 8. In every civil proceeding, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, the costs of discovery are part of the costs of the party seeking discovery, either as between party and party or between solicitor and client, where, and only where, discovery is certified as necessary by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'To whom does this Order apply when a party is a child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Order only applies if the child is under the age of 10.","The Order applies to children only if they are represented by a legal advisor, not a next friend or guardian litem.","The Order applies exclusively to adult parties and not to children at all.","The Order applies to any claimant or respondent who is a child, and to the next friend or guardian litem of any such party."],"justification":"This Order applies to any claimant or respondent who is a child, and to the next friend or guardian litem of any such party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Application to children* 9. This Order applies to any claimant or respondent who is a child, and to the next friend or guardian litem of any such party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Court gives directions concerning discovery or inspection of documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Parties are encouraged to negotiate and agree on discovery procedures independently, ignoring the Court''s directions.","The Court''s directions have no impact on future discovery requests; parties can continue to serve requests as before.","No party may serve a request for discovery on any other party without further order, except in accordance with those directions.","All parties must immediately comply with all discovery requests regardless of the Court''s directions."],"justification":"If the Court gives directions concerning discovery or inspection of documents, no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Discovery after directions* 11. If the Court gives directions concerning discovery or inspection of documents, no party may, without further order, serve a request for discovery on any other party except in accordance with those directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Request for summary judgment (Form 33.01, Schedule","Petition for appeal (Form 55.01, Schedule","Notice of motion (Form 44.01, Schedule","Affidavit of service (Form 28.01, Schedule"],"justification":"must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), modified as appropriate)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Form of application* 1. An application to have a claim forwarded to the Circuit Court or to the High Court under section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [Courts Act 1971](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1971/act/36/enacted/en/html)), must be by notice of motion ([Form 44.01, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), modified as appropriate).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum time requirement for serving a copy of the notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least five days after the return date","At least fourteen days before the return date","At least seven days before the return date","At least three days before the return date"],"justification":"at least seven days before the return date"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Service of application* 2. (1) The original notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk and a copy of the notice of motion must be served on the other party to the proceeding in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least seven days before the return date. (2) When the copy of the notice of motion has been served, a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 19A - Security","Order - Financial","Order - Admissions","Order - Disciplinary"],"justification":"# Order - Admissions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Admissions - Court: District # **Order Admissions******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can costs of proving a document be allowed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Costs of proving a document may be allowed if the party seeking to prove the document did not serve notice to admit.","Costs of proving a document may be allowed if the document has been stored in a digital format.","Costs of proving a document may be allowed if the party seeking to prove the document served notice to admit or if the court certifies that the omission to serve notice to admit was a saving of expense.","Costs of proving a document may be allowed if the document is over 50 pages long."],"justification":"No costs of proving a document may be allowed unless: - (a) the party seeking to prove the document served notice to admit; or - the Court certifies that the omission to serve notice to admit was a saving of expense."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Admission of documents* 1. (1) Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c17f7252-bdbe-4880-8f53-f156167a0029/Notice to admit documents No. 45D.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule call on any other party to admit the authenticity of any document. An admission may be in the [Form 45D.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68a4075d-1d23-407e-8c24-401cabe3d3e4/Notice of admission of documents No. 45D.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a document, after written notice to admit has been served, the costs of proving the document must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable. (3) No costs of proving a document may be allowed unless: - (a) the party seeking to prove the document served notice to admit; or - the Court certifies that the omission to serve notice to admit was a saving of expense.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a party fails to admit a fact within the required timeframe?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The fact will be considered admitted by the opposing party without any further proof.","The party who failed to admit the fact will automatically lose the case.","The costs of proving the fact must be paid by the party who neglected or refused to admit","The court will impose a fine on the judge presiding over the case."],"justification":"Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a fact within seven days after written notice to admit has been served, or within such further time as is allowed by the Court, the costs of proving the fact must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable, or unless the Court at any time otherwise orders or directs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Admission of facts* 2. (1) Any party may, by written notice ([Form 45D.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b7097e4-d07c-4788-a691-ccf66f7bfe0a/Notice to admit facts No. 45D.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any time not later than ten days before the date fixed for the trial, call on any other party to admit, for the purposes of the trial only, any specific fact mentioned in the notice. An admission may be in the [Form 45D.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64f44eba-4bed-49da-b3a0-d1f03dc0c354/Notice of admission of facts No. 45D.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where a party refuses or neglects to admit a fact within seven days after written notice to admit has been served, or within such further time as is allowed by the Court, the costs of proving the fact must be paid by the party who has neglected or refused to admit, regardless of the result, unless at the trial or hearing the Court certifies that the refusal to admit was reasonable, or unless the Court at any time otherwise orders or directs. (3) Any admission made in response to a notice under this rule must be taken to be made only for the purposes of the particular civil proceedings, and not as an admission that may be used against the party on any other occasion or in favour of any person other than the party giving the notice. (4) The Court may at any time allow any party to amend or withdraw any admission made under this rule on such terms as the Court considers just. (5) Unless the Court orders otherwise, all costs and expenses as in the opinion of the Court have been caused by the failure of a party to serve a notice to admit documents or a notice to admit facts must, regardless of the result, be paid by the party who failed to serve the notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an admission take if it is not made during the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It can be conveyed through a verbal message relayed by another party involved in the case.","It must be in writing and signed by the party making the admission or by their solicitor.","It must be orally confirmed over a video call with the judge present.","The admission can be made via email without the need for a signature."],"justification":"Any admission, if not made during the hearing, must be in writing, and must be signed by the party making the admission, or by his solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Admissions in writing* 3. Any admission, if not made during the hearing, must be in writing, and must be signed by the party making the admission, or by his solicitor. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order - Amendment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["High","District","Supreme","Magistrate"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Amendment - Court: District # **Order Amendment******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions must all amendments be permitted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["All amendments must be permitted if they are requested by the judge during the trial.","All amendments must be permitted if they are necessary for determining the real questions in controversy between the parties.","All amendments must be permitted if they are submitted within one week after the discovery period ends.","All amendments must be permitted if they involve new evidence that was discovered after the initial filing of the case."],"justification":"All amendments must be permitted as are necessary for the purpose of determining the real questions in controversy between the parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Court’s power to permit amendment* 1. (1) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: - (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just; - disallow any amendment already made; or - amend any defect or error in any proceeding. (2) All amendments must be permitted as are necessary for the purpose of determining the real questions in controversy between the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for distinguishing amendments from the original text?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["All amendments must be underlined","All amendments must be capitalized","All amendments must be in bold","All amendments must be enclosed in parentheses"],"justification":"All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Manner of amendment* 2. (1) A pleading or other document may be amended by written alterations in the copy which has been served, and in the copy which has been filed. Where necessary, extensive amendments may be set out on additional sheets of paper to be inserted into the pleading at a place indicated in the pleading. (2) When an amendment has been made, the amended document must be indorsed as follows: "Amended on the ..... day of ..... 20.... pursuant to Order dated the ...... day of ....... 20....". (3) All amendments must be underlined so as to distinguish the amendments from the original text.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the Clerk make corrections?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["With the approval of the Court and written consent of all affected parties.","At any time, provided the Clerk believes the corrections are necessary.","With the approval of the Court only, without needing consent from affected parties.","Without the approval of the Court, with written consent of all affected parties."],"justification":"Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), on application in writing of any party, the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Clerical errors* 3.[2] (1) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a judgment or order, or any error arising in a judgment or order from any accidental slip or omission, at any time on the application by notice of motion of the party seeking the correction on notice to the party sought to be affected by the correction. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), on application in writing of any party, the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk. (3) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a warrant issued in civil proceedings, or any error arising in a warrant issued in civil proceedings from any accidental slip or omission, at any time before execution of the warrant on the application parte by the party seeking the correction. [1] Order inserted by [S.I.17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 598 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/598/made/en/print?q 598&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order related to attendance of witnesses and production of documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 12 - Rules for Summoning Witnesses and Providing Evidence","Order 46 - Witness Testimonies and Document Submission","Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents","Order 34 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents"],"justification":"# Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents - Court: District # Order 46: Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Witness Testimonies","Selection of Jurors","Attendance of Witnesses","Admission of Evidence"],"justification":"1 - ATTENDANCE OF WITNESSES"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 1 - ATTENDANCE OF WITNESSES'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What does the witness summons require the witness to do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Attend the trial as a juror at the time and place stated in the witness summons","Provide evidence directly to the opposing party at the time and place stated in the witness summons","Pay a fine at the time and place stated in the witness summons","Comply with the requirements of the witness summons at the time and place stated in the witness summons"],"justification":"requiring the witness to whom the summons is directed to comply with the requirements of the witness summons at the time and place stated in the witness summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application to Clerk to issue witness summons* 1. Any party desiring the attendance of a person (in this Order, a “**w****itness**”) to give evidence or produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court, in any civil proceedings must apply for, and the Clerk may issue, a witness summons ( [Form 46.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3398e73-d381-42d7-a057-6b46c8eb5657/Witness summons No. 46.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule requiring the witness to whom the summons is directed to comply with the requirements of the witness summons at the time and place stated in the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application for a witness summons *duces tecum* be issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By the prosecuting attorney in criminal cases only.","Upon the request of a witness who wishes to provide evidence voluntarily.","By any party to the litigation without the need for a court order.","Only by order of the Court on an application parte."],"justification":"An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons ducetecum) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application to Court to issue witness summons* 2. (1) An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte. (2) In any case of difficulty as regards the issue of any other witness summons, the party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons. (3) On an application under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the issue of a witness summons, with or without conditions as it considers appropriate, or may make such other order as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'How must a witness summons be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By email or fax, unless the Court orders otherwise.","Personally or by registered post, unless the Court orders otherwise.","Through a social media message, unless the Court orders otherwise.","By leaving it at the witness''s last known address, unless the Court orders otherwise."],"justification":"A witness summons must be served personally or by registered post on the witness named in the witness summons, unless the Court orders otherwise."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Service of witness summons* 3. (1) A witness summons must be served personally or by registered post on the witness named in the witness summons, unless the Court orders otherwise. (2) If it appears to the Court that a witness served with a witness summons was not given reasonable time to enable him or her to appear as directed in the witness summons, or that his or her reasonable expenses of attending have not been paid or offered to him or her, the Court may set aside or disregard service of the witness summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'In what cases can a witness summons duces tecum be directed to more than one person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["If the witnesses are part of a club or association, regardless of their relationship.","When the individuals involved are co-defendants in a legal case.","Only when the witnesses are from the same household.","Only in the case of partners, where all the members of the firm may be addressed in the witness summons."],"justification":"except in the case of partners, where all the members of the firm may be addressed in the witness summons in which event the attendance of any one of the members of the firm to produce the document or thing must be taken to be sufficient compliance with the witness summons unless the Court thereafter directs a specific member of the firm to so attend."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Persons named in witness summons* 4. (1) A witness summons requiring a witness to attend to give evidence only (witness summons testificandum*) may be directed to and served on more than one person. (2) A witness summons requiring a witness to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may be directed to only one person, except in the case of partners, where all the members of the firm may be addressed in the witness summons in which event the attendance of any one of the members of the firm to produce the document or thing must be taken to be sufficient compliance with the witness summons unless the Court thereafter directs a specific member of the firm to so attend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What must the party requiring the officer''s attendance deposit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A written promise to pay future legal fees","A bond equivalent to the officer''s annual salary","A sufficient sum of money to cover reasonable charges and expenses for attendance.","A nominal fee of 10 for the officer''s time"],"justification":"deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Officer of the Court may require expenses* 5. If any officer of the Court is required by a witness summons to attend with any record or document at any sitting or place outside the Court district in which he or she is serving, the officer may require that the party requiring his or her attendance (or that party’s solicitor) must: - (a) deposit with the officer a sufficient sum of money to answer his or her reasonable charges and expenses in respect of attendance, and - undertake to pay any further reasonable charges and expenses which may not be fully met by the deposit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What kind of liability allows for joining respondents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Persons who are collectively liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.","Persons who are severally, or jointly and severally, liable on different contracts, excluding parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.","Persons who are severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.","Persons who are individually liable on separate contracts, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes."],"justification":"all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Respondents to a claim in contract* 5. The claimant may, at his or her option, join as respondents to the same civil proceeding all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the court appoint a next friend or guardian litem?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child","When an adult is involved in a contractual dispute and needs legal assistance","When a person is unable to represent themselves due to mental incapacity in criminal proceedings","When a business entity requires representation in commercial litigation"],"justification":"When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the child."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Court may appoint next friend or guardian litem* 7.[4] (1) When civil proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against a child, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the child. (2) The Court may change a next friend or guardian litem, and appoint another person in his or her place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What must be filed when a child defends by their guardian litem?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A letter of intent from the proposed guardian litem expressing their interest in defending the civil proceeding on behalf of the child.","A consent form signed by both the child and the proposed guardian litem indicating their agreement to proceed with the case.","An oral declaration made in court by the proposed guardian litem stating their willingness to defend the civil proceeding on behalf of the child.","A written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence."],"justification":"a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Child may defend by guardian litem* 9. (1) A child may defend by his or her guardian litem appointed for that purpose. (2) Where a child defends by his or her guardian litem, a written authority signed by the proposed guardian litem authorising the conduct of the defence of the civil proceeding on behalf of the child and the use of the name of the proposed guardian litem as guardian litem must be filed with the appearance and defence.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court direct regarding money or personal property awarded to a child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court may direct that such money or property be transferred to the parents or legal guardians of the child.","The Court may direct that such money or property be used to pay off any debts owed by the parents or legal guardians of the child.","The Court may direct that such money or property be secured or invested for the benefit of the child.","The Court may direct that such money or property be donated to a charity instead of being used for the benefit of the child."],"justification":"The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Court may direct investment of an award to a child* 12. (1) The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any money or other personal property to which a child is declared entitled in proceedings before the Court, or the proceeds of any order to pay to a child issued under the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), be secured or invested for the benefit of the child in the manner the Court considers advisable. (2) A copy of any order made under this rule must, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Who can apply for an interim payment on behalf of a child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The child''s neighbor","The child''s teacher","The child''s next friend or guardian litem","The child''s school principal"],"justification":"the child''s next friend or guardian litem"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Interim payments* 13.(1) Unless the Court otherwise decides, no interim payment out of any money secured or invested on behalf of a child may be made except under an order of the Court made on the application of the child''s next friend or guardian litem. (2) An application for an interim payment may be made by motion (which may be in the [Form 43.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c764c139-07fc-4999-bed6-4b727ec1e7e2/Notice of motion for direction under Civil Liability Act 1961, section 63(1) No. 43.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule at any sitting of the Court for the Court district in which the civil proceedings were heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the court have regarding the inclusion of beneficially interested persons in proceedings involving trusts or estates?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court may exclude any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate from being made parties to the proceedings.","The court has no discretion to include or exclude beneficially interested persons; their inclusion is mandatory by law.","The court may order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties.","The court can only include persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate if they request to be involved themselves."],"justification":"The Court may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Trustees, executors and administrators* 17. (1) Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing, the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and must be taken to represent the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate. (2) The Court may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What can a party apply for regarding the partners in a firm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An affidavit confirming the employment history of each partner in the firm since its establishment.","A declaration of the personal assets owned by each partner in the firm as of the date the lawsuit was filed.","A statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the partners in the firm at the time the cause of action accrued.","A certificate verifying the financial status of each partner in the firm at the time of application."],"justification":"Any party to a civil proceeding by or against partners suing in the name of a firm may apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time the cause of action accrued, partners in the firm, to be provided and verified as the Court directs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1**9 Court may direct provision of particulars of all partners* 19. Any party to a civil proceeding by or against partners suing in the name of a firm may apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time the cause of action accrued, partners in the firm, to be provided and verified as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'How can a claimant obtain information about the officers or trustees of a club?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By posting a public notice in local newspapers asking for the identities of the club''s officers or trustees.","By sending a formal letter to the club''s general assembly requesting the details of the officers or trustees.","By requesting the information directly from the current members of the club.","By applying to the court for an order to direct those in control of the club to provide and verify the names, descriptions, and places of residence of the officers or trustees at the time the cause of action accrued."],"justification":"The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the persons who appear to have control or to be managing the activity to provide and verify as the Court directs the names, description and places of residence of the persons who at the time the cause of action accrued were the officers or trustees of the club or the persons otherwise in control of the activity carried on by the club."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Person carrying on activity as a club* 25. (1) Persons carrying on any activity in the State as a club may, in addition to any other manner in which they may be sued, be sued in the name of the club, whether or not the club is registered under the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The claimant may in such a case apply by notice of motion to the Court for an order directing the persons who appear to have control or to be managing the activity to provide and verify as the Court directs the names, description and places of residence of the persons who at the time the cause of action accrued were the officers or trustees of the club or the persons otherwise in control of the activity carried on by the club. (3) In cases to which sub-rule (1) applies, service of a claim notice or any other document may be effected by service in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) on one of the persons who at the time of service appears to be an officer or trustee of the club, or to have control of the activity carried on by the club, at a place where the activity is carried on.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person served with an order under Rule 30 do if they are not already a party to the civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Notify the court within 14 days that they have received the order but take no further action.","File a counterclaim against the plaintiff instead of serving a defense.","Attend a mandatory mediation session within 7 days of receiving the order.","File and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time and in the same manner as if they had been served with the claim notice."],"justification":"every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *31 Service of an order under rule 30* 31. (1) Unless the Court otherwise directs, an order obtained under rule 30 must be served on each of the continuing parties (or their solicitors) and on each new party (unless the person making the application is himself or herself the only new party). (2) Subject to rules 32 and 33, an order under rule 30 is from the time of service binding on the person served, and every person served with an order under rule 30 who is not already a party to the civil proceedings must, if a respondent, file and serve an appearance and serve a defence within the same time, and in the same manner, as if he or she had been served with the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Does the order under rule 30 have any effect against the person under a disability before the guardian litem is appointed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Yes, the order takes immediate effect against the person under a disability as soon as it is issued.","The order has full effect against the person under a disability once the disability status is confirmed by medical documentation.","No, the order has no force or effect against the person under a disability until a guardian litem is appointed and the ten-day period expires.","The order has partial effect against the person under a disability immediately upon issuance, pending further court review."],"justification":"until the period of ten days has expired, the order under rule 30 has no force or effect against the person under a disability"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *33 Service of an order under rule 30 on a person under a disability* 33. Where a person under a disability who does not have a guardian litem in the civil proceeding is served with an order under rule 30, the person may apply to the Court to discharge or vary the order under rule 30 at any time within ten days from the appointment of a guardian litem for the person and, until the period of ten days has expired, the order under rule 30 has no force or effect against the person under a disability.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["BACKGROUND","INTRODUCTION","METHODS","CONSOLIDATION"],"justification":"CONSOLIDATION"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 9 - CONSOLIDATION'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'Does this Order limit the Court''s power to make interlocutory orders or give directions without a notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Order restricts the Court''s ability to give directions without a notice of motion, except in cases involving public interest.","No, it does not limit the Court''s power.","It only allows the Court to make interlocutory orders with prior written consent from all parties involved.","Yes, it significantly limits the Court''s power to make interlocutory orders."],"justification":"Nothing in this Order limits the power of the Court to make any interlocutory order or give a direction (whether in the presence of some only or all of the parties) without the issue of a notice of motion in an appropriate case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Application of this Order* 1. (1) Unless otherwise provided by these Rules, this Order applies to any interlocutory or other application in a civil proceeding. (2) Nothing in this Order limits the power of the Court to make any interlocutory order or give a direction (whether in the presence of some only or all of the parties) without the issue of a notice of motion in an appropriate case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'How must an application in a proceeding made on notice to any person be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Orally, during a court hearing without prior notice.","By email, without any supporting documents or affidavits.","In writing, by notice of motion, supported by an affidavit.","Through a verbal request made directly to the judge outside of a formal hearing."],"justification":"An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Form and timing of application* 2. (1) An application in a proceeding made on notice to any person must be made in writing, by notice of motion, unless the Court otherwise orders, and must be supported by an affidavit. (2) An application by notice of motion is made when the notice of motion is filed in accordance with rule 4. (3) Unless any statute or rule otherwise provides, the moving party in any application to the Court other than an parte application or an application for an adjournment must give at least 48 hours’ notice in writing to the Clerk of the Court at which such application is to be made. This filing of a notice of motion or notice of application for issue is deemed to be notice to the Clerk of intention to make the application contained in the notice on the return date assigned to it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What must be included in a notice of motion if the grounds for the order, direction or other relief sought include the failure or refusal of the opposing party to agree a matter?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["a detailed financial statement of both parties involved","the names of all legal representatives involved in the case","copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached","a signed affidavit from a witness unrelated to the case"],"justification":"copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached to the original notice of motion"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Form and filing* 4. (1) A notice of motion must be in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case and must include particulars of the order, direction or other relief sought as appropriate to the case, a summary of the grounds of the application and, where relevant, a statement of the provisions of law including the provisions of any enactment or these Rules relied on in making the application. (2) A notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk assigned to the Court area in which the proceedings concerned have been issued and assigned a return date by the Clerk. (3) Where the grounds for the order, direction or other relief sought include the failure or refusal of the opposing party to agree a matter, copies of the correspondence or documents passing between the parties concerned, relevant to the subject matter of the motion must be attached to the original notice of motion. (4) Where more than one order, direction or other relief is sought against the same party in the same civil proceeding: - (a) so far as practicable, all such orders, directions or other reliefs must be sought in the same notice of motion and a party must not suffer any adverse consequence in the costs to which the party is found to be entitled by reason of having sought several orders, directions or other reliefs in the same notice of motion; and - where practicable, a party must seek all of the interlocutory orders, directions or other reliefs which the party seeks in the civil proceeding on the same return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'How many times can a notice of motion be amended under sub-rule (1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Three times","Twice","Unlimited times","Only once"],"justification":"A notice of motion must not be amended under sub-rule (1) more than once."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Return date* 6. (1) If a notice of motion has not been served a Clerk may, at the request of the party who filed it, amend the notice of motion on or before the return date named in the notice of motion to name another return date. (2) In any other case, a notice of motion may only be amended by the Court. (3) A notice of motion must not be amended under sub-rule (1) more than once.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must the claimant or moving party have available in court on the return date of a motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A signed contract between the parties involved and a financial statement from each party.","Copies of the pleadings and any letters of intent related to the motion.","The original will of the deceased and a list of all beneficiaries named in it.","Copies of the notice of motion and any affidavits (with exhibits) in support of or in opposition to the motion."],"justification":"The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: - (a) any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and - any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Copies for Court* 7. (1) The claimant or other moving party must have available in Court on the return date of any motion, for use by the Judge, copies of: - (a) any notice of motion before the Court on that return date; and - any affidavit (and any exhibits) delivered by any party in support of or in opposition to the motion. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any affidavit or document at the hearing of an application by motion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do if the applicant fails to attend an application by notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just.","The Court may increase the penalties on the applicant.","The Court must grant the application by default.","The Court is required to postpone the hearing indefinitely."],"justification":"If on an application by notice of motion the applicant fails to attend, the Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Absence of party served with notice of motion* 9. (1) If any person to whom a notice of motion is addressed fails to attend, the Court may hear the application if satisfied that the notice of motion was duly served. (2) If on an application by notice of motion the applicant fails to attend, the Court may dismiss the application or make such other order as the Court thinks just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 44 - Applications By Notice Of Motion', 'Court Rules', 'What terms can an order under sub-rule (1) be subject to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Such terms as to damages or otherwise as the Court finds reasonable.","Such terms as to penalties or otherwise as the Court deems appropriate.","Such terms as to interest or otherwise as the Court believes necessary.","Such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just."],"justification":"An order under sub-rule (1) may be subject to such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Application to discharge, set aside or vary an order* 10. (1) The Court may, on an application by notice of motion ( [Form 44.02,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b59de40a-e385-4847-a3eb-9bde579615b6/Notice of motion to vary or discharge an order No. 44.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate to the case) by the person affected, on notice to the applicant for the original order, discharge, set aside or vary an order which affects a person where the application for the order— - (a) was made on notice to that person, but the person did not attend the hearing of the application; or - was not made on notice to that person. (2) An order under sub-rule (1) may be subject to such terms as to costs or otherwise as the Court considers just. [1] Order 44 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a lodgment is accepted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The party accepting the lodgment must pay additional fees to the court before the amount can be released.","The amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court.","The amount lodged is held in escrow until a court judgment is made.","The court reviews the lodgment for a period of 30 days before releasing the funds to the accepting party."],"justification":"On acceptance of a lodgment, the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Consequences of accepting a lodgment* 4. (1) On acceptance of a lodgment, the amount lodged may be paid to the party accepting it, without any judgment or order by the Court, provided that the party accepting the lodgment has lodged with the Clerk or with the Accountant a signed notice of acceptance of the lodgment in full satisfaction of the claim, save as to costs and, where acceptance of the lodgment requires the consent of the party who made the lodgment, the written consent of that party to late acceptance of the lodgment. (2) If the amount of costs to which a party who has accepted a lodgment is entitled cannot be agreed between the parties concerned, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can a party make a late lodgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When the court grants an extension due to unforeseen circumstances, within 30 days after the initial pleading is served.","When a party wishes to appeal the decision, within 14 days after the judgment is delivered.","When a new witness comes forward with evidence, within 7 days after the witness is identified.","When an amendment has been made to the statement of claim, within 28 days after the amended pleading is served."],"justification":"in any case where an amendment has been made to the statement of claim in the claim notice (or, as the case may be, the counterclaim or third party notice) in which the claim is made, within 28 days after the amended pleading is served on the party making the lodgment;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Permission to make a late lodgment* 6. (1) Despite rule 2(1), a party may make a lodgment, or may make a further payment into court to increase an existing lodgment— - (a) in any case where an amendment has been made to the statement of claim in the claim notice (or, as the case may be, the counterclaim or third party notice) in which the claim is made, within 28 days after the amended pleading is served on the party making the lodgment; or - with the written consent of the party whose claim is intended to be met by the lodgment, within such further period as is permitted in that party’s consent, the original of which must be lodged with the Clerk; or - with the permission of the Court, within such further period as is permitted in the Court’s order. (2) A party who makes or increases a lodgment in accordance with sub-rule (1) must serve a notice of lodgment (or notice of increased lodgment) on the party whose claim is intended to be met.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45 - Lodgments And Tenders In Lieu Of Lodgment', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party or qualified party apply to the Court regarding a tender offer?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, only the issuer of the tender offer can apply to the Court.","Parties cannot apply to the Court unless they have been directly affected by the tender offer.","Yes, any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer.","Only unqualified parties are allowed to apply to the Court regarding a tender offer."],"justification":"Any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer and the Court may make any order or give any directions on that application as the Court considers just and proper."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) A qualified party whose tender offer has been accepted but who has failed to pay the sum specified in the tender offer within 28 days of receipt of notice of acceptance of the tender offer continues to be liable to pay the sum specified and is also liable to pay interest on the sum specified at the rate fixed for judgments of the Court for each day after that 28 day period for which the specified sum or any part of the specified sum remains unpaid. (9) Any party or qualified party may apply to the Court in relation to any tender offer or any matter relating to a tender offer and the Court may make any order or give any directions on that application as the Court considers just and proper. [1] Order 45 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What is the initial step a party must take if they require security for costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Notify the court directly without approaching the other party first.","Request an oral agreement from the other party for security for costs.","File a lawsuit against the other party for security for costs.","Apply in writing to the other party for security for costs."],"justification":"A party who requires security for costs from another party may apply in writing to that other party for security for costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Application for security* 1. (1) A party who requires security for costs from another party may apply in writing to that other party for security for costs. (2) Where the party from whom security has been sought does not undertake in writing to provide security, the applicant for security may apply to the Court for an order that security for costs be provided. (3) On hearing the application, the Court may order the claimant to lodge in Court the costs of an order dismissing the claim, or may make such other order as it thinks appropriate. (4) If an order is made requiring a party to give security for costs, security must be given in the manner and at the time the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45A - Security For Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a claimant fails to provide the required security?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may order the claimant to pay additional legal fees to the defendant.","The Court may extend the deadline for providing the required security.","The Court may increase the claimant''s claim notice amount.","The Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice."],"justification":"the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Failure to give security* 3. If a claimant fails to give the security required by an order, the Court may dismiss the claimant''s claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45B - Discovery And Inspection Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The respondent will receive a warning and be required to pay the requesting party''s legal fees.","The respondent will be forced to pay a fine equivalent to the cost of the discovery process.","The respondent will be awarded additional time to comply with the order without any consequences.","The respondent''s appearance and defence may be struck out, and they may be placed in the same position as if they had not defended."],"justification":"If a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her appearance and defence, if any, struck out, and to be placed in the same position as if he or she had not defended."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Failure to comply with order for discovery* 7. (1) If a claimant fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her claim dismissed for want of prosecution. (2) If a respondent fails to comply with an order for discovery or inspection of documents, he or she is liable to have his or her appearance and defence, if any, struck out, and to be placed in the same position as if he or she had not defended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45C - Application To Have A Claim Forwarded To The Circuit Court Or To The High Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done after serving the copy of the notice of motion?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Submit a confirmation of receipt from the recipient to the court","Lodge a statutory declaration of service with the Clerk","Notify the court via email that the notice has been served","File an affidavit confirming the service of the notice with the court registrar"],"justification":"When the copy of the notice of motion has been served, a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Service of application* 2. (1) The original notice of motion must be filed with the Clerk and a copy of the notice of motion must be served on the other party to the proceeding in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least seven days before the return date. (2) When the copy of the notice of motion has been served, a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45D - Admissions', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["County","High","Supreme","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Admissions - Court: District # **Order Admissions******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'What powers does the court have regarding amendments in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may permit alterations or amendments to statements of claim or pleadings, disallow amendments already made, or correct defects or errors in proceedings.","The court can only amend pleadings if all parties agree to the changes.","The court may prevent any party from making further amendments once the case has been filed.","The court is solely responsible for initiating amendments without input from the parties involved."],"justification":"The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just; disallow any amendment already made; or amend any defect or error in any proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Court’s power to permit amendment* 1. (1) The Court may, at any stage of civil proceedings: - (a) permit any party to alter or amend his or her statement of claim or pleading in the manner and on the terms the Court considers just; - disallow any amendment already made; or - amend any defect or error in any proceeding. (2) All amendments must be permitted as are necessary for the purpose of determining the real questions in controversy between the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 45E - Amendment', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court correct under sub-rule (1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Factual inaccuracies discovered in the evidence presented during the trial.","Clerical mistakes in judgments or orders and errors arising from accidental slips or omissions.","Substantive errors made by judges during the trial proceedings.","Legal arguments presented by attorneys that were found to be invalid after the judgment was issued."],"justification":"The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a judgment or order, or any error arising in a judgment or order from any accidental slip or omission, at any time on the application by notice of motion of the party seeking the correction on notice to the party sought to be affected by the correction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Clerical errors* 3.[2] (1) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a judgment or order, or any error arising in a judgment or order from any accidental slip or omission, at any time on the application by notice of motion of the party seeking the correction on notice to the party sought to be affected by the correction. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), on application in writing of any party, the Clerk assigned to the Court area concerned may with the approval of the Court, make such correction where each and every party affected consent in writing, each such consent to be lodged with the said Clerk. (3) The Court may correct any clerical mistake in a warrant issued in civil proceedings, or any error arising in a warrant issued in civil proceedings from any accidental slip or omission, at any time before execution of the warrant on the application parte by the party seeking the correction. [1] Order inserted by [S.I.17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 598 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/598/made/en/print?q 598&years 2014), effective 31 December 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if there is difficulty issuing any other witness summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The party seeking the attendance of a witness may request a jury trial instead.","The court automatically issues a warrant for the arrest of the witness.","The opposing party must immediately agree to provide the witness.","The party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons."],"justification":"In any case of difficulty as regards the issue of any other witness summons, the party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Application to Court to issue witness summons* 2. (1) An application for the issue of a witness summons requiring an officer of the State to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may not be issued except by order of the Court on an application parte. (2) In any case of difficulty as regards the issue of any other witness summons, the party seeking the attendance of a witness may apply parte to the Court for the issue of a witness summons. (3) On an application under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the issue of a witness summons, with or without conditions as it considers appropriate, or may make such other order as it considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Can a witness summons testificandum be directed to more than one person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"A witness summons requiring a witness to attend to give evidence only (witness summons testificandum*) may be directed to and served on more than one person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Persons named in witness summons* 4. (1) A witness summons requiring a witness to attend to give evidence only (witness summons testificandum*) may be directed to and served on more than one person. (2) A witness summons requiring a witness to attend and produce any books, papers or documents to the Court, or to an officer of the Court (witness summons *duces tecum*) may be directed to only one person, except in the case of partners, where all the members of the firm may be addressed in the witness summons in which event the attendance of any one of the members of the firm to produce the document or thing must be taken to be sufficient compliance with the witness summons unless the Court thereafter directs a specific member of the firm to so attend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a witness does not remain in attendance throughout the hearing without being excused?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The witness is automatically considered uncooperative and dismissed from further proceedings.","The court may issue a warrant for the witness''s arrest.","The witness will be required to pay compensation to the opposing party.","The court may impose a fine on the witness for their default or make another just order."],"justification":"the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default, or may make such other order as is just in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Consequences of failure to comply with a witness summons* 6. If a witness who has been duly summoned: - (a) fails without lawful excuse to attend or to give evidence or to produce the books, papers or documents according to the witness summons; or - unless duly excused, fails to remain in attendance throughout the hearing, the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default, or may make such other order as is just in the circumstances.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What section title is given for evidence provided via videoconference?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["EVIDENCE BY VIDEOCONFERENCE","EVIDENCE BY EMAIL","TELEPRESENCE EVIDENCE","EVIDENCE BY TELEPHONE"],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 - EVIDENCE BY VIDEOCONFERENCE'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'How can an application for a live television link be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By posting a public announcement on social media","By sending an email to the broadcasting company","By motion on notice to the other party or parties","By requesting through a formal letter to the legal authority"],"justification":"may be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Application for use of live television link* 8. An application for a direction that a party may participate in a hearing in the proceedings, or that a witness give evidence in any such hearing, from a location other than the Court itself, by means of a live television link in accordance with section 26 of the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/14/enacted/en/html): - (a) may be made by motion on notice to the other party or parties; - may be heard and decided without the prior issue of a notice of motion by the Court on any occasion when the Court is considering case management directions.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What notice is taken of the seal or signature of those authorised to administer oaths in foreign affidavits?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Foreign affidavits are disregarded unless accompanied by a diplomatic certification.","Judicial notice is taken of the content of the affidavit, not the seal or signature of the administrator.","Judicial notice is taken of the seal or signature of those authorised to administer oaths in foreign affidavits.","Affidavits from foreign countries are only valid if notarized by a US official."],"justification":"judicial notice shall be taken of the seal or signature, as the case may be, of any such diplomatic or consular representative or agent, notary public or other person attached, appended or subscribed to any such affidavit, or to any document exhibited to any such affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - FOREIGN PUBLIC DOCUMENTS AND FOREIGN LANGUAGE DOCUMENTS 9.[2] Any affidavit for use in proceedings in the Court may be taken outside Ireland: - before any Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent exercising such functions in the country concerned, or - before any notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or - (iii) in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place; and judicial notice shall be taken of the seal or signature, as the case may be, of any such diplomatic or consular representative or agent, notary public or other person attached, appended or subscribed to any such affidavit, or to any document exhibited to any such affidavit. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What is the definition of ''public documents'' under the 2016 Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Public documents refer to any written material produced by private entities.","Public documents are exclusively emails sent within a governmental department.","Public documents have the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation.","Public documents are defined as personal correspondence between government officials."],"justification":"“**public documents**” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Proof of Foreign Public, Diplomatic and Consular Documents of Member States of the European Union 10.[3] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfil functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation; the “**2016 Regulation**” means [Regulation 2016/1191](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/1191/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 6 July 2016 on promoting the free movement of citizens by simplifying the requirements for presenting certain public documents in the European Union and amending [Regulation No 1024/2012](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2012/1024/oj/eng); “**public documents**” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation. (2) A document which purports to be a public document to which the 2016 Regulation applies (or a certified copy, within the meaning of Article 3(7) of the 2016 Regulation, thereof) is, without proof of: - any formal procedure for certifying the authenticity of a signature, - the capacity in which the person signing the document has acted, or - (iii) where appropriate, the identity of the seal or stamp which it bears, admissible in evidence as such if otherwise admissible. (3) In any case in which the Court has a reasonable doubt as to the authenticity of a public document or certified copy produced in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the taking of any step permitted by Article 14 of the 2016 Regulation to dispel such doubt. In any such case the Court must in its directions set out the grounds upon which the directions are based. 11.[4] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Contracting State designated in accordance with Article 5 of the 1987 Convention; the “**1987 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Legalisation of Documents in the Member States of the European Communities](https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/documents/treaties-agreements/agreement/?id 1987011) done at Brussels on the May, 1987;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''1968 Convention'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The International Convention on the Reduction of Legal Formalities in Cross-Border Trade Agreements","The European Convention on the Establishment of the Euro as Common Currency","The Global Convention on the Uniformity of Passport Regulations","The European Convention on the Abolition of Legalisation of Documents Executed by Diplomatic Agents or Consular Officers"],"justification":"the “**1968 Convention**” means the [European Convention on the Abolition of Legalisation of Documents Executed by Diplomatic Agents or Consular Officers](https://rm.coe.int/1680902928) done at London on the June, 1968;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proof of Foreign Diplomatic and Consular Documents (London Convention 1968)* 12.[5] (1) In this rule: the “**1968 Convention**” means the [European Convention on the Abolition of Legalisation of Documents Executed by Diplomatic Agents or Consular Officers](https://rm.coe.int/1680902928) done at London on the June, 1968; a “**Contracting State**” means a State, other than Ireland, which is a party to the 1968 Convention; “**document**” means and includes any document or documents to which Article 2 of the 1968 Convention applies. (2) A document which purports to have been executed by the diplomatic agents or consular officers of a Contracting State is, without proof of: - any formality used to certify the authenticity of the signature on such a document, or - the capacity in which the person signing such a document has acted, or - (iii) where appropriate, the identity of the seal or stamp which such document bears, admissible in evidence without such proof if otherwise admissible in evidence. (3) The Court may, where necessary, give such directions as to the verification of the authenticity of any document as it thinks fit. (4) This rule shall not apply to any document to which rule 10 or rule 11 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''apostille'' mean in the context of the 1961 Convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A diplomatic note sent between governments to request authentication of a document","A legal document used to certify the authenticity of documents in countries not party to the 1961 Convention","A type of official seal used exclusively in non-Hague Convention member states","An apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention"],"justification":"an “**apostille**” means an apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proof of Foreign Public Documents (Hague Convention 1961)* 13.[6] (1) In this rule: an “**apostille**” means an apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention; the “**1961 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Requirement of Legalisation for Foreign Public Documents done at The Hague on the October, 1961](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 41); a “**Contracting State**” means a State, other than Ireland, which is a party to the 1961 Convention other. (2) A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown. (3) This rule does not apply to any document to which rule 10, rule 11, or rule 12 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 47 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","High Court","County Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47: Judgment In Default In Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can the claimant do if the respondent fails to serve and file an appearance or defence within the prescribed time?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant may seek to have the case dismissed due to the respondent''s failure to respond.","The claimant may request a postponement of the case until the respondent serves and files their appearance or defense.","The claimant may appeal to a higher court for immediate judgment without waiting for the respondent''s response.","The claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default."],"justification":"the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance or defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a debt claim does not serve and file an appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'When can a certificate under seal be used instead of an affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim.","Whenever a notary public needs to verify a document in international legal proceedings, substituting a certificate under seal for an affidavit.","When the claimant is a private individual seeking to verify a personal claim without any statutory entitlement to use a certificate under seal.","In cases where the claim involves criminal proceedings rather than civil claims, allowing a certificate under seal to replace an affidavit."],"justification":"Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) Where an application under rule 1 is by a Minister of a Government Department or the Commissioners of Public Works or another body or person entitled by statute to verify a claim for a sum due by a certificate under seal which is by statute made evidence of the matters certified instead of by affidavit, the applicant may file such a certificate instead of an affidavit verifying the claim. (3) Where a respondent has executed a consent to judgment which has been duly witnessed, the applicant may file an affidavit ([Form 47.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36e14c1b-9b52-4447-958f-03255d2d12a7/Affidavit exhibiting consent No. 47.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule verifying the consent instead of an affidavit of debt; and where the consent is to judgment by instalments, the form of judgment (decree) in [Form 47.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ac82b1bc-3683-4311-9494-5fb6e362b178/Instalment judgment (decree) by consent No. 47.07.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be used. (4) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) must be given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. Judgment may not be given where the affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim was not sworn (or the certificate specified in sub-rule (2) was not given) within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (5) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must the court ensure before giving judgment in default when the claim notice was served abroad under the Service Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court must ensure that the provisions of Article 17 of the Service Regulation have been complied with and that the provisions of Order apply.","The court must ensure that the provisions of Article 20 of the Service Regulation have been complied with and that the provisions of Order apply.","The court must ensure that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with and that the provisions of Order 41A or Order apply.","The court must ensure that the provisions of Article 18 of the Service Regulation have been complied with and that the provisions of Order apply."],"justification":"Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Service Regulation and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 3. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Service Regulation and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can a judge do if they are satisfied that an order should be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The judge may delay making any order until a full court hearing is conducted.","The judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court and fix the amount of costs and interest as appropriate.","The judge may dismiss the case without making any order.","The judge may refer the matter to a jury for a decision on whether an order should be made."],"justification":"If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court, and may fix the amount of costs and interest as is appropriate in the circumstances in accordance with the Schedule of Costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 A Judge may issue a default judgment or refer to the Court* 4.(1) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court, and may fix the amount of costs and interest as is appropriate in the circumstances in accordance with the Schedule of Costs. (2) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is not satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may, or if the claimant so requests, the Judge must, refer the matter to the Court for decision. (3) An application to which rule 3 applies must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (4) If the Judge refers an application to the Court or an application is assigned a return date, the Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) make the order sought in the application; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed; - give directions as to the application; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (5) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (6) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can a claimant do if they obtain an order for judgment in default against one respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant is required to dismiss the case against all respondents.","The claimant must wait for the defaulting respondent to respond before taking any action.","The claimant should appeal the order for judgment in default to a higher court.","The claimant may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."],"justification":"A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 5. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent, further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the Court take if a party fails to comply with an order in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Court may automatically award full damages to the other party without further proceedings.","The Court may dismiss the proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order as if the party in default had not pleaded.","The Court may issue a warning letter to the party that failed to comply.","The Court may increase the legal costs awarded to the compliant party by a fixed amount."],"justification":"If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Default of compliance* 8. If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded. [1] Order 47 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order - Summary Judgment On The Basis Of Debt Claims","Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims","Order 69 - Dismissal For Lack Of Prosecution","Order - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims"],"justification":"Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47A: Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can the claimant do if the respondent fails to serve and file an appearance or defence within the prescribed time?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant must wait for the court to notify them of the next steps.","The claimant should seek a summary judgment against the respondent.","The claimant may request a dismissal of the case.","The claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default."],"justification":"the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance and defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a claim other than a debt claim does not serve and file and appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must the claimant do before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The claimant must inform the court in writing at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion that they intend to serve such a notice.","The claimant must write to the respondent at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion, informing them of the intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence.","The claimant must advertise their intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment in a national newspaper at least 14 days prior to issuance.","The claimant must wait until the respondent has served an appearance and defense before issuing the notice of motion for judgment."],"justification":"Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and at the same time consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence within 14 days from the date of that letter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application by motion on notice* 2. (1) In any case in which this Order applies, the claimant may, subject to the provisions of this rule, at any time after the respondent’s default in serving and filing an appearance or serving a defence, by motion on notice to the respondent served on the respondent not less than four clear days before the return date of the motion, apply to the Court for judgment. (2) Before issuing and serving a notice of motion for judgment under sub-rule (1), the claimant must at least 14 days before issuing the notice of motion write to the respondent giving the respondent notice of the claimant’s intention to serve a notice of motion for judgment and at the same time consenting to the late service of an appearance and defence within 14 days from the date of that letter. (3) If an appearance and defence is not served within 14 days from the date of that letter, the claimant may issue (by filing with the Clerk to obtain a return date) and serve a notice of motion for judgment in default which must be returnable to a return date not less than 14 days from the date of the service of the notice of motion. (4) An application under this rule must be supported— - by an affidavit or statutory declaration ([Form 41.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a3578c53-647b-42b8-9533-d1266525edf5/Statutory declaration of service of a document by registered post No. 41.01.docx/docx/1), [41.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1ce8e29-61fe-41d6-b1e4-0be6fe055224/Declaration as to service by ordinary post No. 41.02.docx/docx/1) or [41.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d590fd61-c2f8-49d3-9efa-e869eb833fc7/Statutory declaration as to personal service No. 41.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate) of service of the claim notice; and - by a certificate ([Form 47.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5d865ffc-a14c-473b-b3a1-7326645c45cd/Certificate of no appearance - defence No. 47.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule which may be endorsed on the verifying affidavit signed by the claimant’s solicitor or by the claimant (if acting in person) that no appearance, notice requiring particulars or defence has been received from the respondent; and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum notice period required for serving a notice of motion for judgment in default?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Not less than one week''s notice.","Not less than four clear days'' notice.","Not less than three clear hours'' notice.","Not less than two clear days'' notice."],"justification":"If the claimant can establish special reasons making it necessary to serve a notice of motion for judgment under this rule with greater urgency than in accordance with the notice periods provided, he or she may apply parte to the Court for an order giving the claimant permission to serve a notice of motion for judgment in default giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent, or in the alternative the Court may deem good the service of a notice of motion actually served giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) by an affidavit verifying the claim notice (provided that in a personal injuries action, a further affidavit is not required if the personal injuries summons has previously been verified); and - by a form of judgment (decree) ([Form 49.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae2bca29-5e13-446e-a4da-d9c458134623/Judgment (decree) following trial - damages No. 49.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications). (5) A copy of the affidavit verifying the claim notice must (unless previously served) be served on the respondent with the notice of motion. The remaining documents mentioned in sub-rule (4) must be produced on the hearing of the motion but, where permitted by the Court, the form of judgment (decree) may be filed with the Clerk subsequently. (6) If the claimant can establish special reasons making it necessary to serve a notice of motion for judgment under this rule with greater urgency than in accordance with the notice periods provided, he or she may apply parte to the Court for an order giving the claimant permission to serve a notice of motion for judgment in default giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent, or in the alternative the Court may deem good the service of a notice of motion actually served giving not less than four clear days’ notice to the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a respondent files a defence with the Clerk at least 6 days before the return date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The motion for judgment is upheld, and the respondent is not required to pay any costs.","The motion for judgment stands struck out and the respondent is liable to pay the claimant the costs of the motion for judgment.","The motion for judgment is automatically dismissed and no costs are awarded to either party.","The motion for judgment is continued to a later date, and no costs are awarded to the claimant or the respondent."],"justification":"the motion for judgment will stand struck out and the respondent will be liable to pay to the claimant the costs of the motion for judgment in accordance with the Schedule of Costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Motion struck out with costs if defence filed not less than 6 days before return date* 3. If, after the service of a notice of motion for judgment, the respondent delivers a defence to the claimant and not less than six days before the return date files a copy of the defence with the Clerk, with a certified copy of the notice of motion attached, the motion for judgment will stand struck out and the respondent will be liable to pay to the claimant the costs of the motion for judgment in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'When must the affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim be sworn?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within one week after the date of the application for judgment.","Within one month before the date of the application for judgment.","At any time before the final hearing of the case.","Within three months before the date of the application for judgment."],"justification":"The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn within one month before the date of the application for judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Affidavit verifying claim* 4. (1) The affidavit verifying the claimant''s claim must be sworn within one month before the date of the application for judgment. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply where the claimant relies on an affidavit of verification of a personal injuries summons made more than one month before the date of the application. (3) Where the application for judgment includes a claim in respect of value-added tax, the affidavit (or certificate) must verify whether or not value-added tax is payable by the claimant on his or her legal costs, and if payable whether or not the sum payable is recoverable by the claimant from the Revenue Commissioners.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must the court be satisfied about before giving a judgment in default when the claim notice was served abroad under the Service Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court must be satisfied that the provisions of Article 17 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of Order apply to any such application.","The court must be satisfied that the provisions of Article 20 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of Order apply to any such application.","The court must be satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of Order 41A or Order apply to any such application.","The court must be satisfied that the provisions of Article 18 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of Order apply to any such application."],"justification":"Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the [Service Regulation](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 5. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the [Service Regulation](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2007/1393/oj/eng) and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of [Article 15 of the Hague Convention](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 77) have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit and may be included in the affidavit verifying the claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must all applications by motion for judgment under this Order be assigned?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["a confirmation of service","a specific trial date","a preliminary injunction","a return date for hearing before the Court"],"justification":"All applications by motion for judgment under this Order must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Return date* 6. (1) All applications by motion for judgment under this Order must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (2) The Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) give judgment on the claimant’s claim contained in the claim notice in such amount as the Court is satisfied is just; - give permission to the respondent to defend the whole or part of the claim on such terms as the Court considers just; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed, or adjourn the application for the hearing of further evidence; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (3) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (4) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court. (5) On the hearing of an application for judgment under this Order, the Court may make an Order for costs in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the claimant recovers the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant is required to discontinue all legal action immediately, regardless of further costs claims.","Proceedings against remaining respondents can only proceed if the initial respondent agrees to the continuation.","Further proceedings against any remaining respondent must continue without interruption.","Further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent."],"justification":"In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 7. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What does rule 1 to 6 become when a counterclaim is served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Rule 1 to 6 are applied as if the respondent becomes the claimant, appearance refers to the counterclaim, and the original claimant becomes the respondent.","Rule 1 to 6 are suspended until the counterclaim is resolved.","Rule 1 to 6 are applied as if the claimant becomes the respondent, and the original respondent becomes the judge in the case.","Rule 1 to 6 are ignored entirely, and new rules specific to counterclaims are applied."],"justification":"rules 1 to 6 apply as if— - (a) the respondent were the claimant; - a reference to the appearance in those rules were a reference to the appearance to the counterclaim; and - the claimant were the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Default of appearance and defence to counterclaim* 8. If a respondent serves a counterclaim, rules 1 to 6 apply as if— - (a) the respondent were the claimant; - a reference to the appearance in those rules were a reference to the appearance to the counterclaim; and - the claimant were the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'When was Order 47A inserted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order 47A was inserted by S.I. 17 of 2014 and became effective on 3 February 2014.","Order 47A was inserted by S.I. 17 of 2015 and became effective on 3 February 2015.","Order 47A was inserted by S.I. 2014/17 and became effective on 3 March 2014.","Order 47A was inserted by S.I. 17 of 2014 and became effective on 1 March 2014."],"justification":"Order 47A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17\u0026years 2014), effective 3 February 2014"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Default of compliance* 10. If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded. [1] Order 47A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","Supreme Court","County Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Discontinuance And Withdrawal - Court: District # **Order Discontinuance And Withdrawal******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a claimant discontinues or withdraws their claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The respondent must pay the claimant''s costs incurred up to the point of discontinuation.","The claim is automatically dismissed without any cost implications for either party.","The claimant must pay the respondent''s costs of the proceedings or the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn","The claimant receives compensation from the respondent for discontinuing the claim."],"justification":"Where a claimant serves a notice under sub-rule (1), the claimant must pay the respondent’s costs of the proceedings or, if the claim is not wholly discontinued, the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Discontinuance or withdrawal of claim or part of claim* 1. (1) The claimant may: - (a) before receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence; or - after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application), - wholly discontinue his claim against all or any of the respondents by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk; or - withdraw any part or parts of his alleged cause of action by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk. (2) Where a claimant serves a notice under sub-rule (1), the claimant must pay the respondent’s costs of the proceedings or, if the claim is not wholly discontinued, the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn. (3) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to small claims. (4) If not agreed, the applicable scale or amount of costs may be determined by the Court. (5) Discontinuance or withdrawal under sub-rule (1) is not a defence to any subsequent claim. (6) Save as provided in this Order, a claimant may not withdraw or discontinue a claim without the permission of the Court. (7) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the claimant’s application, order or permit the claim to be discontinued, or any part of the alleged cause of action to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'What does the court consider when deciding to allow withdrawal of defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court considers what is just, including terms as to costs and other actions.","The court considers the color of the courtroom walls.","The court considers the popularity of the defendant on social media.","The court considers the time of day when the application for withdrawal is made."],"justification":"The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the respondent’s application, order or permit all or any part of the respondent’s grounds of defence to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Withdrawal of defence* 2. (1) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the respondent’s application, order or permit all or any part of the respondent’s grounds of defence to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just. (2) A party who has filed an appearance and defence in a proceeding may not withdraw the defence or any part of it without the permission of the Court in accordance with sub-rule (1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Does sub-rule (1) apply if the claim notice has been assigned a trial date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"Sub-rule (1) applies whether or not the claim notice has been assigned a trial date"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 Withdrawal of claim on consent 3. (1) When a claim which is the subject of any claim notice has been settled or compromised by the parties, and does not require to proceed before the Court, the parties must produce to the Clerk a written consent signed by both parties (or their solicitors) confirming that the claim is not proceeding. (2) Sub-rule (1) applies whether or not the claim notice has been assigned a trial date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'What entitlement does a respondent have if proceedings are wholly discontinued against them?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Entitlement to a full refund of any legal fees incurred","Entitlement to judgment for the costs of the proceedings","Entitlement to continue the proceedings without paying further costs","Entitlement to a retrial"],"justification":"A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Judgment for costs of discontinuance* 4. A respondent is entitled to judgment for the costs of any proceedings which are wholly discontinued against him or her, or for the costs occasioned by the matter withdrawn, if the action be not wholly discontinued, if the costs concerned are not paid within four days after their amount is agreed or fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court do if a witness fails to attend or give evidence without lawful excuse?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court may grant the witness a certificate of good conduct.","The court may impose a fine on the witness for their default or make another just order.","The court may award compensation to the witness for failing to attend.","The court may issue a formal apology to the witness for their inconvenience."],"justification":"the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default, or may make such other order as is just in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Consequences of failure to comply with a witness summons* 6. If a witness who has been duly summoned: - (a) fails without lawful excuse to attend or to give evidence or to produce the books, papers or documents according to the witness summons; or - unless duly excused, fails to remain in attendance throughout the hearing, the Court, if satisfied that the witness has been duly summoned and that his or her reasonable expenses have been tendered, may impose a fine on the witness for his or her default, or may make such other order as is just in the circumstances.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an affidavit for use in proceedings in the Court be taken outside Ireland?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before any citizen of Ireland residing abroad, provided they are not currently involved in the proceedings.","Before any local official in the country where the proceedings are taking place, regardless of their authority to administer oaths.","Before an Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent, a notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or in any part of the European Union, before a notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place.","Before a foreign lawyer who is licensed to practice law in the country concerned, even if they are not authorised to administer oaths."],"justification":"before any Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent exercising such functions in the country concerned, or before any notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 3 - FOREIGN PUBLIC DOCUMENTS AND FOREIGN LANGUAGE DOCUMENTS 9.[2] Any affidavit for use in proceedings in the Court may be taken outside Ireland: - before any Irish diplomatic or consular representative or agent exercising such functions in the country concerned, or - before any notary public lawfully authorised to administer oaths in the country concerned, or - (iii) in any part of the European Union, before any notary public or other person authorised to administer oaths in such place; and judicial notice shall be taken of the seal or signature, as the case may be, of any such diplomatic or consular representative or agent, notary public or other person attached, appended or subscribed to any such affidavit, or to any document exhibited to any such affidavit. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Central Authority'' mean in the context of the 2016 Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The non-governmental organization designated by the United Nations to oversee the implementation of the 2016 Regulation across member states.","The highest court in the European Union that adjudicates disputes related to the 2016 Regulation.","The Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfill functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation.","The financial institution responsible for monitoring the currency exchange rates within the European Union as per the 2016 Regulation."],"justification":"“**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfil functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Proof of Foreign Public, Diplomatic and Consular Documents of Member States of the European Union 10.[3] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Member State of the European Union designated in accordance with Article 15 of the 2016 Regulation to fulfil functions relating to the application of the 2016 Regulation; the “**2016 Regulation**” means [Regulation 2016/1191](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2016/1191/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 6 July 2016 on promoting the free movement of citizens by simplifying the requirements for presenting certain public documents in the European Union and amending [Regulation No 1024/2012](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2012/1024/oj/eng); “**public documents**” has the same meaning as in Article 3 of the 2016 Regulation. (2) A document which purports to be a public document to which the 2016 Regulation applies (or a certified copy, within the meaning of Article 3(7) of the 2016 Regulation, thereof) is, without proof of: - any formal procedure for certifying the authenticity of a signature, - the capacity in which the person signing the document has acted, or - (iii) where appropriate, the identity of the seal or stamp which it bears, admissible in evidence as such if otherwise admissible. (3) In any case in which the Court has a reasonable doubt as to the authenticity of a public document or certified copy produced in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court may direct the taking of any step permitted by Article 14 of the 2016 Regulation to dispel such doubt. In any such case the Court must in its directions set out the grounds upon which the directions are based. 11.[4] (1) In this rule: “**Central Authority**” means the Central Authority of a Contracting State designated in accordance with Article 5 of the 1987 Convention; the “**1987 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Legalisation of Documents in the Member States of the European Communities](https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/documents/treaties-agreements/agreement/?id 1987011) done at Brussels on the May, 1987;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 46 - Attendance of Witnesses and Production of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What is the effect of a document that is purportedly an apostille issued in a Contracting State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It requires additional authentication from a foreign embassy before it can be deemed valid.","It can only be used as evidence if it has been translated into the official language of the court.","It is considered invalid and cannot be used as evidence under any circumstances.","It is deemed to be an apostille and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown."],"justification":"A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proof of Foreign Public Documents (Hague Convention 1961)* 13.[6] (1) In this rule: an “**apostille**” means an apostille issued in pursuance of the 1961 Convention and conforming to the model set out in the annex to the 1961 Convention; the “**1961 Convention**” means the [Convention Abolishing the Requirement of Legalisation for Foreign Public Documents done at The Hague on the October, 1961](https://www.hcch.net/en/instruments/conventions/full-text/?cid 41); a “**Contracting State**” means a State, other than Ireland, which is a party to the 1961 Convention other. (2) A document which purports to be an apostille duly issued and executed in a Contracting State in accordance with the 1961 Convention is, without further proof, deemed to be such and is admissible as evidence of the facts stated therein unless the contrary is shown. (3) This rule does not apply to any document to which rule 10, rule 11, or rule 12 applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order related to judgment in default in debt claims?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order 32 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims","Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims","Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Contract Disputes","Order 47 - Summary Judgment In Debt Claims"],"justification":"# Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47: Judgment In Default In Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the claimant apply for an order of judgment in default?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["If the claimant fails to provide evidence supporting their case within the time prescribed by Order 42 or any other time fixed by the Court.","If the respondent files an appearance but fails to attend the hearing on the scheduled date.","If the claimant and respondent reach a settlement agreement before the prescribed deadline.","If the respondent does not serve and file an appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by Order 42 or any other time fixed by the Court."],"justification":"If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a debt claim does not serve and file an appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance or defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a debt claim does not serve and file an appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must the court ensure before giving judgment in default when the claim notice was served abroad under the Hague Convention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court must ensure that the claim notice was translated into the official language of the country where the defendant is located.","The court must ensure that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with.","The court must ensure that the claim notice was served by a diplomatic courier.","The court must ensure that the defendant has responded within 14 days of service of the claim notice."],"justification":"Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Additional requirements where the claim notice was served outside the State* 3. (1) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Service Regulation and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation have been complied with, and the provisions of [Order 41A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41A-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-With-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) or, as appropriate, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court) apply to any such application. (2) Where the claim notice (or notice of the issue of the claim notice) was sent abroad for service under the provisions of the Hague Convention and the respondent has not served or filed an appearance and defence or given notice of his or her intention to defend, judgment in default of appearance may not be given until the Court is satisfied that the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention have been complied with. (3) Evidence of compliance with the provisions of Article 19 of the Service Regulation or the provisions of Article 15 of the Hague Convention may be given by affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47 - Judgment In Default In Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the judge is not satisfied that an order should be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The judge may dismiss the case entirely if they are unsatisfied with the application.","The judge must immediately make a decision without referring the matter to the Court.","The judge may refer the matter to the Court for decision, or if requested by the claimant, must refer it.","The judge may request additional evidence from both parties before making a decision."],"justification":"If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is not satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may, or if the claimant so requests, the Judge must, refer the matter to the Court for decision."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 A Judge may issue a default judgment or refer to the Court* 4.(1) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may make such an order otherwise than at a sitting of the Court, and may fix the amount of costs and interest as is appropriate in the circumstances in accordance with the Schedule of Costs. (2) If an application has been made to which rule 2(1) applies and a Judge is not satisfied that an order should be made, the Judge may, or if the claimant so requests, the Judge must, refer the matter to the Court for decision. (3) An application to which rule 3 applies must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (4) If the Judge refers an application to the Court or an application is assigned a return date, the Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) make the order sought in the application; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed; - give directions as to the application; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (5) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (6) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 47A apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Supreme Court","District Court","County Court"],"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims - Court: District # **Order 47A: Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the claimant apply for judgment in default?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["If the respondent does not serve and file an appearance or defence within the time prescribed by Order 42 or any other time fixed by the court.","If the claimant and respondent agree to extend the deadline for filing an appearance or defense beyond the time prescribed by Order 42.","If the claimant fails to provide sufficient evidence to support their case within the time prescribed by Order 42 or any other time fixed by the court.","If the respondent serves and files an appearance or defense within the time prescribed by Order 42 but contests the jurisdiction of the court."],"justification":"If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a claim other than a debt claim does not serve and file and appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Claimant may apply for judgment in default of appearance and defence* 1. If a respondent who has been served with a claim notice in a claim other than a debt claim does not serve and file and appearance or serve a defence within the time prescribed by [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim), or within any other time fixed by the Court for serving and filing his or her appearance or for serving his or her defence, the claimant may apply for an order of judgment in default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What must accompany the defence when it is filed with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A certified copy of the notice of motion must be attached.","A signed declaration from the plaintiff must be attached.","A photocopy of the original complaint should be provided.","A notarized affidavit from the defendant must be included."],"justification":"with a certified copy of the notice of motion attached"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Motion struck out with costs if defence filed not less than 6 days before return date* 3. If, after the service of a notice of motion for judgment, the respondent delivers a defence to the claimant and not less than six days before the return date files a copy of the defence with the Clerk, with a certified copy of the notice of motion attached, the motion for judgment will stand struck out and the respondent will be liable to pay to the claimant the costs of the motion for judgment in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do when hearing an application for judgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["give judgment on the claimant’s claim, give permission to the respondent to defend the claim, direct further affidavits to be filed, refuse the order sought, or make any other appropriate order","extend the deadline for filing the claimant''s affidavit","order a retrial of the entire case","grant a summary judgment in favor of the respondent without hearing any further evidence"],"justification":"The Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate—(a) give judgment on the claimant’s claim contained in the claim notice in such amount as the Court is satisfied is just; give permission to the respondent to defend the whole or part of the claim on such terms as the Court considers just; direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed, or adjourn the application for the hearing of further evidence; refuse to make the order sought in the application; make any other order it considers appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Return date* 6. (1) All applications by motion for judgment under this Order must be assigned a return date for hearing before the Court. (2) The Court may on hearing the application, and any evidence the Court considers appropriate— - (a) give judgment on the claimant’s claim contained in the claim notice in such amount as the Court is satisfied is just; - give permission to the respondent to defend the whole or part of the claim on such terms as the Court considers just; - direct that a further affidavit or affidavits be filed, or adjourn the application for the hearing of further evidence; - refuse to make the order sought in the application; - make any other order it considers appropriate. (3) If the Court, under sub-rule directs a further affidavit or affidavits to be filed, the Court may make a peremptory order which is effective on the filing of such affidavit or affidavits, without the application being heard again before the Court. (4) The Clerk must notify the claimant of any order made by the Judge or (if the application has been referred to the Court) any decision or order of the Court. (5) On the hearing of an application for judgment under this Order, the Court may make an Order for costs in accordance with the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What can a claimant do after obtaining an order for judgment in default against a respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent.","Cease all legal proceedings since the default judgment is final.","Appeal the order for judgment in default to a higher court.","Dismiss the case as the respondent has admitted to all claims."],"justification":"A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Proceeding continued against other respondents* 7. A claimant who obtains an order for judgment in default against a respondent in accordance with this Order may enforce the order and continue the proceeding against any other respondent. In the event that the claimant recovers by enforcement or otherwise the full amount of his claim including costs against any respondent further proceedings against any remaining respondent must be stayed save in respect of any further costs as may be claimed against any other respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47A - Judgment In Default In Non-Debt Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the court take if a party fails to comply with an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs).","The court may award the non-compliant party a default win as a form of punishment.","The court may extend the deadline for compliance indefinitely to accommodate the non-compliant party.","The court may increase the penalties for the non-compliant party by imposing additional fines unrelated to the case."],"justification":"If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Default of compliance* 10. If a party fails to comply with an order made by the Court in civil proceedings, the Court may, where it considers it just to do so, dismiss the civil proceedings or strike out any defence or counterclaim and proceed to give judgment or make any order (including any order for costs) as is then appropriate as if the party in default had not pleaded. [1] Order 47A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order - Continuation and Extension","Order - Discontinuance And Withdrawal","Order 56A - Implementation and Enactment","Order - Revocation and Abolishment"],"justification":"# Order - Discontinuance And Withdrawal"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Discontinuance And Withdrawal - Court: District # **Order Discontinuance And Withdrawal******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'When can a claimant discontinue their claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["During the hearing when the judge has not yet made a decision","Only after the final judgment has been delivered","After receipt of the respondent''s appearance and defence and after taking any other steps in the proceedings","Before receipt of the respondent''s appearance and defence or after receipt but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except interlocutory applications)"],"justification":"(a) before receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence; or after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Discontinuance or withdrawal of claim or part of claim* 1. (1) The claimant may: - (a) before receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence; or - after receipt of the respondent’s appearance and defence or defence, but before taking any other step in the proceedings (except any interlocutory application), - wholly discontinue his claim against all or any of the respondents by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk; or - withdraw any part or parts of his alleged cause of action by written notice ([Form 47B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12e1f5a7-c344-4a73-bae6-bb4f6d09b57b/Notice of discontinuance No. 47B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule served on each respondent and filed with the Clerk. (2) Where a claimant serves a notice under sub-rule (1), the claimant must pay the respondent’s costs of the proceedings or, if the claim is not wholly discontinued, the costs occasioned by the part of the alleged cause of action withdrawn. (3) Sub-rule (2) does not apply to small claims. (4) If not agreed, the applicable scale or amount of costs may be determined by the Court. (5) Discontinuance or withdrawal under sub-rule (1) is not a defence to any subsequent claim. (6) Save as provided in this Order, a claimant may not withdraw or discontinue a claim without the permission of the Court. (7) The Court may at the hearing or trial, on the claimant’s application, order or permit the claim to be discontinued, or any part of the alleged cause of action to be struck out, on such terms as to costs, and as to any other action and otherwise as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the amount of costs is not specified in the Schedule of Costs or agreed by the parties?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court will automatically assume that no costs are applicable and the case proceeds without any cost considerations.","The Court may impose a fixed statutory fine on one of the parties as a penalty for unspecified costs.","The parties must resolve the issue through arbitration outside of the Court''s jurisdiction.","The Court may determine the scale of costs to apply, and if no appropriate scale exists, it may determine the amount of such costs."],"justification":"the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply, and if there is no such appropriate scale the Court may determine the amount of such costs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Costs* 6. If the amount of costs referred to in this Order is not specified in the Schedule of Costs or is not agreed by the parties, the Court may, on the application of the claimant or respondent, as the case may be, determine the scale of costs to apply, and if there is no such appropriate scale the Court may determine the amount of such costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 47B - Discontinuance And Withdrawal', 'Court Rules', 'Can a claimant discontinue a small claim proceeding or withdraw any part of a small claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes, at any time before the small claim proceeding has been referred to the Court, without the permission of the Court or the consent of the other parties.","No, a claimant can only withdraw parts of their claim during the small claim proceeding with the permission of the Court.","No, a claimant can only discontinue the proceedings after obtaining the permission of the Court and with the consent of all other parties.","Yes, but only if the small claim proceeding has already been referred to the Court and with the consent of the other parties."],"justification":"Despite rule 1, a claimant may discontinue a small claim proceeding or withdraw any part of a small claim at any time before the small claim proceeding has been referred to the Court without the permission of the Court or the consent of the other parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claims—discontinuance or withdrawal of proceeding or claim* 7. Despite rule 1, a claimant may discontinue a small claim proceeding or withdraw any part of a small claim at any time before the small claim proceeding has been referred to the Court without the permission of the Court or the consent of the other parties. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Authorization And Submission Of Papers","Verification And Archiving Of Materials","Authentication And Filing Of Documents","Certification And Registration Of Records"],"justification":"Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents - Court: District # **Order 48: Authentication And Filing Of Documents****[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What conditions must a claim notice, counterclaim, or third party notice meet to be considered valid?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["It must have been stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee, and bear the allocated Court number and the date of filing.","It must be accompanied by a signed affidavit from a witness.","It must contain a photograph of the parties involved in the case.","It must include a detailed legal argument supporting the claim."],"justification":"A claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice is valid for all purposes if it has, where necessary, been stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee, and bears the allocated Court number and the date of filing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Validity of claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice* 2. A claim notice, counterclaim or third party notice is valid for all purposes if it has, where necessary, been stamped to record payment of any applicable court fee, and bears the allocated Court number and the date of filing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'Who can receive a certified copy of a document mentioned in sub-rule (1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Only the original author of the document","Any member of the public upon request","A party or their solicitor, or another person directed by the Court.","The court clerk without any specific request"],"justification":"A certified copy of a document mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be provided on payment of any applicable charges to: - (a) a party or party’s solicitor; - another person on the direction of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Authentication of documents in civil proceedings* 3. (1) The signature of the Clerk for the time being assigned to the Court area in which the civil proceedings were brought is sufficient– - (a) to authenticate any order or document issued by the Court in civil proceedings other than an order which requires to bear the signature of the Judge; or - to certify as a copy- - any copy of a document issued by the Court in civil proceedings; or - any copy of a document filed in civil proceedings or sent to the Court by a party or other person. (2) A certified copy of a document mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be provided on payment of any applicable charges to: - (a) a party or party’s solicitor; - another person on the direction of the Court. 3A.[2] The Clerk may certify any printed version of the legible content of any original document which was transmitted to or by the Clerk as a certified copy of the original.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done for an order or warrant for attachment or committal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It must be notarized by a public notary.","It must be approved by a jury.","It must be endorsed by a legal attorney.","It must be signed by a Judge."],"justification":"Any order or warrant for attachment or committal must be signed by a Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Orders signed by Judge* 4. Any order or warrant for attachment or committal must be signed by a Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 48 - Authentication And Filing Of Documents', 'Court Rules', 'What must be included on the face of a duplicate document issued by the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The date of issuance must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document.","The signature of the issuing judge must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document.","The word ''Original'' must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document.","The word ''Duplicate'' must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document."],"justification":"the word \"Duplicate\" must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Issue of duplicates* 5. (1) Where it appears to the Court that an original judgment, order or warrant in civil proceedings has been lost or destroyed or is unavailable to the parties, or to the party entitled to it, the Court may issue a duplicate of the judgment, order or warrant. (2) An application for a duplicate must be made on 48 hours'' notice to the opposite party and to the Clerk. (3) Where the Court permits the issue of a duplicate judgment, order or warrant, as the case may be, the word "Duplicate" must be clearly written or stamped on the face of the duplicate document. [1] Order 48 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 48 Rule 3A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 49 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","County Court","High Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings - Court: District # Order 49: Hearing Of Civil Proceedings**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["INTRODUCTION","CONCLUSION","EVIDENCE","METHODS"],"justification":"**1 - EVIDENCE**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 - EVIDENCE**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the Court order that a fact be proved by affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the matter at hand involves national security.","When the Court deems it appropriate for such reasons as it thinks right.","When the parties involved agree to it unanimously.","When the fact in question is deemed too trivial to warrant oral testimony."],"justification":"Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Oral evidence* 1. (1) Unless otherwise agreed in writing by all of the parties to the proceeding, and subject to these Rules and the law of evidence, witnesses at the trial of any claim must be examined orally on oath in open Court. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable. (3) An order may not be made authorising the evidence of a witness to be given by affidavit where it appears to the Court that another party bona fide requires the production of the witness for cross-examination, and that the witness can be produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What can a court permit regarding the examination or deposition in proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court can permit a party to give the examination or deposition in evidence only if it is related to criminal proceedings.","The court can permit a party to give the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings on such terms as directed","The court can prohibit a party from giving the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings on any terms.","The court can require that all examinations and depositions be conducted in a foreign language."],"justification":"the order may permit a party to the proceedings to give the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings on such terms, if any, as the Court directs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Deposition evidence* 3. In any case where it appears necessary in the interests of justice, a Court may order that a witness or other person be examined on oath and the order may permit a party to the proceedings to give the examination or deposition in evidence in the proceedings on such terms, if any, as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the subsection number of this chunk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["2","4","1","3"],"justification":"**2 - SETTING DOWN FOR TRIAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 - SETTING DOWN FOR TRIAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum notice period required for a trial?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Not less than five days","Not less than three weeks","Not less than two days","Not less than ten days"],"justification":"Not less than ten days’ notice of trial must be given to the respondent and all other necessary parties, save that the parties may agree that a shorter notice period must apply."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Notice of trial* 4. (1) When an appearance and defence have been served and filed, the claimant may serve notice of trial ([Form 49.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/422a0eab-8d63-4467-acfe-66f7f11335c7/Notice of trial No. 49.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Not less than ten days’ notice of trial must be given to the respondent and all other necessary parties, save that the parties may agree that a shorter notice period must apply. (3) Notice of trial must be filed with the Clerk promptly following service, and a separate copy of the notice must be filed for each additional party. (4) Unless otherwise requested by the party giving notice of trial, or otherwise directed by the Court, notice of trial operates to set the claim (including any counterclaim) down for hearing at the next available time following the expiry of the period mentioned in the notice of trial as is assigned by the Clerk. (5) Unless the Court directs the Clerk otherwise, the next available time is at the next available sitting of the Court for civil business for the Court area in which the claim must be heard, at such time at which the claim comes on in its order in the list. (6) In any case in which the parties are agreed that the claim (and any counterclaim) is ready for hearing, the notice of trial may include any request agreed between the parties for the hearing to be specially fixed (and any reasons for such request), provided that the notice of trial is accompanied by a letter from the opposing party consenting to the request. (7) The Clerk may set down a claim (including any counterclaim) to which sub-rule (6) applies for hearing in accordance with any request, or may request the Court to give a direction in accordance with such request.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'When must a notice of motion for discovery or further particulars not be issued after serving a notice of trial?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No later than 30 days after notice of trial has been served.","No later than 21 days after notice of trial has been served.","No later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served.","No later than 7 days after notice of trial has been served."],"justification":"No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) The Clerk must notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed, and may do so by returning to that party a copy of the notice of trial with those details inserted. The party who has served notice of trial must promptly notify all other parties of the time and place at which the trial is listed. (9) No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition is the respondent allowed to serve a notice of trial?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the respondent serves notice of trial within three days after receiving a counterclaim from the claimant.","When the claimant serves notice of trial within five days after the delivery of the respondent''s defence.","When the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent''s defence.","When the respondent decides to serve the notice of trial immediately after filing their own defence without waiting for the claimant''s action."],"justification":"Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Service of notice of trial by respondent* 5. Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What orders can the Court make on the hearing of an application to dismiss?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may order the claim to be dismissed, and/or may make such other order, on such terms, as he or she considers just.","The Court may order the claim to be indefinitely suspended without prejudice to any party.","The Court must order the claim to be dismissed, with no possibility of making any other orders.","The Court can only order the claim to be transferred to another jurisdiction."],"justification":"On the hearing of an application under sub-rule (1), the Court may order the claim to be dismissed, and/or may make such other order, on such terms, as he or she considers just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Application to dismiss* 6. (1) If the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may, instead of serving notice of trial in accordance with rule 5, apply to the Court by notice of motion to dismiss the claim for want of prosecution. (2) On the hearing of an application under sub-rule (1), the Court may order the claim to be dismissed, and/or may make such other order, on such terms, as he or she considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Does sub-rule (1) limit the ability of any party to rely on any document at the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any document at the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Papers for Court* 7. (1) The party serving notice of trial must, at the same time as filing the notice of trial, file with the Clerk, for use by the Judge: - (a) a set of copies of the pleadings, including particulars, and any affidavits in the case, in chronological sequence; - a set of copies of any correspondence relied on by either party, in chronological sequence; - copies of any other documents directed to be filed, and - where so directed for the time being by: - the President of the District Court in respect of civil proceedings in the Dublin Metropolitan District, or in respect of particular categories of civil proceedings including the proceedings concerned, in the Court generally or - by a Judge permanently assigned to the Court district in which the civil proceedings were brought in respect of civil proceedings, or in respect of particular categories of civil proceedings including the proceedings concerned, in that Court district, a completed case management questionnaire ([Form 49.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e332b02-0eb1-483c-b5d7-be343b8c9736/Case management questionnaire No. 49.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit the ability of any party to rely on any document at the hearing. 7A.[2] Rule 7 is subject to the provisions of any Practice Direction or direction of the Judge where digital delivery of documents has applied to the proceedings, and subject to the direction of the Judge in any other case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["TESTING","EVIDENCE","TRIAL","VERDICT"],"justification":"**3 - TRIAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - TRIAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a counterclaim be proceeded with separately?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Counterclaims must always be heard in conjunction with the primary lawsuit and cannot proceed independently.","A counterclaim can only be pursued if it is directly related to and dependent on the outcome of the initial claim.","Yes, a counterclaim may be proceeded with separately.","No, a counterclaim can only be processed as part of the initial claim."],"justification":"A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Hearing of counterclaim* 9. (1) A counterclaim may be proceeded with separately. (2) If a counterclaim is proceeded with separately, it must be treated as a claim, irrespective of whether the original claim in which the counterclaim was made is withdrawn, stayed, discontinued or dismissed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court order a non-party witness to do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The court can order a non-party witness to take an oath of confidentiality that prevents them from discussing the case outside of the courtroom.","The court can order a non-party witness to serve as a juror during the trial.","The court can order a non-party witness to provide financial support to either party involved in the trial.","The court can order a non-party witness to leave the court until their evidence is required, leave after giving evidence, or remain in court until the trial ends."],"justification":"A witness who is not a party may be ordered by the Court: - (a) to leave the Court until his evidence is required; or - to leave the Court after his or her evidence has been given; or - to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Directions to witnesses* 10. A witness who is not a party may be ordered by the Court: - (a) to leave the Court until his evidence is required; or - to leave the Court after his or her evidence has been given; or - to remain in Court after his evidence has been given, until the trial is terminated or adjourned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a judgment be given in favor of or against respondents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No, a judgment can only be given in favor of the plaintiff.","Yes, a judgment can be given in favor of or against respondents.","A judgment is always neutral and cannot be given specifically in favor of or against any party.","Judgments are not applicable to respondents; they apply only to petitioners."],"justification":"and against or in favour of one or more respondents"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Judgment* 11. Judgment (which may be recorded in one of the [Forms 49.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae2bca29-5e13-446e-a4da-d9c458134623/Judgment (decree) following trial - damages No. 49.03.docx/docx/1) to [49.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c73e68ac-3fad-49b0-a864-50126316776f/Judgment (decree) following trial for recovery of possession of premises (ejectment) No. 49.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary) may be given for one or more claimants, and against or in favour of one or more respondents (which may be recorded in [Form 49.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/95dc5b1c-1e17-4262-855d-018ff2f61e52/Judgment in favour of respondent (dismiss) following trial No. 49.09.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, with such modifications as are necessary).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can a judge adjourn a trial?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If the jury requests a longer lunch break than usual.","If the judge thinks it expedient in the interests of justice, they may adjourn a trial for such time and on such terms as they think just.","If the media coverage is deemed too extensive.","If the judge wishes to go on vacation."],"justification":"The Judge may, if he or she thinks it expedient in the interests of justice, postpone or adjourn a trial for such time, and on such terms, if any, as he or she thinks just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Adjournment* 12. (1) The Judge may, if he or she thinks it expedient in the interests of justice, postpone or adjourn a trial for such time, and on such terms, if any, as he or she thinks just. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not limit any other power of the Court to adjourn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the respondent appears and the claimant does not appear, and the respondent has no counterclaim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The respondent is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim.","The respondent is required to file a counterclaim within 14 days.","The case is automatically dismissed without any further proceedings.","The claimant is given another chance to appear within 30 days."],"justification":"the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Non-appearance at trial* 13. (1) If, when a case is called in Court, the claimant appears, and the respondent does not appear, the claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her. (2) If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim, but if he or she has a counterclaim, then he or she may prove the counterclaim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court order regarding the payment of a debt or damages?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court can order that the debt or damages be paid in a lump sum immediately upon appeal.","The court can order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs must be paid.","The court can order that the debt or damages be forgiven and not paid at all.","The court can order that the debt or damages must be paid in full within one day from the date of the ruling."],"justification":"When the Court has pronounced a judgment or made an order (or at any later time on notice being given to the opposite party), the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Ancillary orders as to payment* 14. (1) When the Court has pronounced a judgment or made an order (or at any later time on notice being given to the opposite party), the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid. (2) If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order. (3) The Court may stay execution on foot of any judgment or order for such period and on such terms as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What does the court have full jurisdiction to do in all cases?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["To give judgment on the claim or dismiss the claim either on the merits or without prejudice to the claimant’s right to proceed by a new claim notice.","To mediate disputes between parties and suggest amicable settlements.","To appoint a jury for the selection of community service members.","To enforce criminal penalties and issue prison sentences in civil disputes."],"justification":"The Court has full jurisdiction in all cases to give judgment on the claim, or to dismiss the claim either on the merits or without prejudice to the claimant’s right to proceed by a new claim notice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Jurisdiction to give judgment or dismiss on the merits or without prejudice* 15. The Court has full jurisdiction in all cases to give judgment on the claim, or to dismiss the claim either on the merits or without prejudice to the claimant’s right to proceed by a new claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the respondent produces an order of the Court dismissing the same cause of action by the claimant without prejudice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The claimant may not proceed with the case until they have paid the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order.","The case is immediately closed with no possibility of re-filing.","The claimant is automatically awarded additional damages for the dismissal.","The respondent must pay all future legal fees for the claimant."],"justification":"the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Where a dismiss without prejudice is produced* 16. If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent produces an order of the Court dismissing the same cause of action by the claimant against the respondent without prejudice, the claimant may not proceed with the case until the claimant has paid to the respondent the amount of costs due on foot of that order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can the Court order that judgments be set off against each other?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If one party requests a reconciliation between different court rulings involving similar issues but not the same parties.","If the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties or if there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties.","When the Court decides to merge two unrelated cases involving different parties into a single judgment.","If there is a public appeal by one of the parties regarding the fairness of the judgments."],"justification":"If: - (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or - there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Cross judgments may be set off* 17. (1) If: - (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or - there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties, the Court may, on the application of either party, order that the judgments be set off against each other. (2) If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court direct regarding the payment of a sum ordered for the recovery of rates?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court may direct that the sum be paid only in full within one week.","The Court may direct that the sum be paid entirely as a lump sum five years from now.","The Court may direct that the sum be paid either at once or by instalments.","The Court may direct that the sum be paid to any third party instead of the creditor."],"justification":"the Court may direct that the sum be paid either at once or by instalments"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Order for recovery of rates and execution against goods in default of payment* 19. (1) Where the Court makes an order for the recovery of rates, the Court may direct that the sum be paid either at once or by instalments. (2) In an order to which sub-rule (1) applies, the Court may order that, in default of the sum being paid at the time and in the manner directed, the amount not paid be levied by distress and sale of the goods of the respondent against whom the order was made and by taking the money of the respondent against whom the order was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order - Financial Disclosure","Order - Discovery","Order - Jury Selection","Order 49A - Case Management"],"justification":"# Order 49A - Case Management"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49A - Case Management - Court: District # **Order 49A: Case Management******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court do regarding the definition of issues in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Ensure that issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely as possible.","Ensure that issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as vaguely, ambiguously, and extensively as possible.","Allow the issues to be defined by the jury during the trial process.","Leave the definition of issues to the discretion of the parties involved without providing any guidance."],"justification":"ensure that the issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely, as possible;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Case management directions* 1. (1) The Court may, at any time and from time to time, of its own motion and having heard the parties, give such directions and make such orders, including the fixing of time limits, for the conduct of civil proceedings, as appears convenient for the determination of the proceedings in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the cost of those proceedings. (2) Except where these Rules provide otherwise, the Court may: - (a) ensure that the issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely, as possible; - give case management directions as to the steps which remain to be taken to prepare the case for trial, and the timetable for the completion of preparations of the case for trial, and for that purpose may adopt any timetable proposed by the parties if satisfied that it is reasonable; - make orders or give directions with respect to pleadings, the exchange between the parties of statements of issues, the identifying of issues in dispute between the parties, particulars, discovery, inspection of documents, or otherwise, which may be necessary or expedient; - make inquiries of the parties so as to ascertain the likely length of the trial and the arrangements, if any, for witnesses, information and communications technology (including video conferencing) and any other arrangements which require to be made for the trial; - fix the time and mode of trial, and may fix a date for trial and may also give directions as to the service of a notice of trial; - make any orders and give any directions in respect of arrangements for the trial as the Court considers necessary; - direct any expert witnesses to consult with each other within such time as the Court specifies for the purposes of— - identifying the issues in respect of which they intend to give evidence, - where possible, reaching agreement on the evidence that they intend to give in respect of those issues, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can the court invite parties to use an ADR process?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Only when requested by all parties involved in the case","Upon the request of a legal representative only, not any party","On the application of any party or on its own motion.","When the court deems it necessary without any application from the parties"],"justification":"may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution) to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Adjournment to facilitate ADR* 2. The Court when considering case management directions, may on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, exercise its powers in accordance with [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution) to invite the parties to use an ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue and to make consequent orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do regarding case management directions?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Maintain a record of all case management directions given, which can be in electronic form.","Ensure that case management directions are verbally communicated to all parties involved without keeping any written or electronic records.","Provide case management directions only in written form, never allowing them to be documented electronically.","Delegate the responsibility of recording case management directions to the Judge''s assistant instead of maintaining a personal record."],"justification":"The Clerk must maintain a record, which may be in electronic form, of all case management directions given."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Case management records* 3. (1) The Clerk must maintain a record, which may be in electronic form, of all case management directions given. (2) A copy of the case management directions must be placed on the Court file and a further copy of the case management directions must be made available to a party to the civil proceedings at the party’s request.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'What can a judge decide after conducting a case management hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The trial of the civil proceeding should be conducted by a jury instead of a judge.","The trial of the civil proceeding should be before another Judge.","The trial of the civil proceeding should be moved to a different courthouse within the same jurisdiction.","The trial of the civil proceeding should be delayed until further notice."],"justification":"A Judge before whom a case management hearing has been conducted may determine that the trial of the civil proceeding should be before another Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Judge taking case management hearing may decline to hear trial* 5. A Judge before whom a case management hearing has been conducted may determine that the trial of the civil proceeding should be before another Judge. [1] Order 49A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution - Court: District # Order Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''2017 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Employment Relations Act 2017 (No 30 of 2017)","The Consumer Protection Act 2017 (No 25 of 2017)","The Mediation Act 2017 (No 27 of 2017)","The Taxation Act 2017 (No 28 of 2017)"],"justification":"the “**2017 Act**” means the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No 27 of 2017);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order: the “**2017 Act**” means the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No 27 of 2017); each of the expressions “**mediation**”, “**mediation settlement**” and “**mediator**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the 2017 Act; “**another ADR process**” means conciliation or another dispute resolution pro cess approved by the Court, but does not include mediation or arbitration.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do when it considers it appropriate to invite the parties to consider mediation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may invite the parties to consider mediation as a means of resolving the dispute and provide them with information about the benefits of mediation.","The Court may order the parties to engage in mandatory arbitration instead of mediation.","The Court may refuse to hear any further arguments if the parties do not agree to mediation immediately.","The Court may impose sanctions on parties who refuse to participate in mediation."],"justification":"The Court may, in civil proceedings to which the 2017 Act applies, in accordance with section 16(1) of the 2017 Act, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, where it considers it appropriate having regard to all the circumstances of the case: (a) invite the parties to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings, and provide the parties to the proceedings with information about the benefits of mediation to settle the dispute the subject of the proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Invitation to mediate; application for adjournment to facilitate mediation* 2. (1) The Court may, in civil proceedings to which the 2017 Act applies, in accordance with section 16(1) of the 2017 Act, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, where it considers it appropriate having regard to all the circumstances of the case: - (a) invite the parties to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings, and - provide the parties to the proceedings with information about the benefits of mediation to settle the dispute the subject of the proceedings. (2) Where, following an invitation by the Court, the parties decide to engage in mediation, the Court may, in accordance with section 16(2) of the 2017 Act— - (a) make an order adjourning the proceedings to such date as the Court considers just and convenient in all the circumstances, - make an order extending the time for compliance by a party with any relevant provision of these Rules or with any order of the Court in the proceedings, or - make such other order or give such direction as the Court considers necessary to facilitate the effective use of mediation. (3) An application by a party to civil proceedings under section 19(1) of the 2017 Act for an order adjourning the proceedings must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with Order 44, but need not be grounded on any affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'How must an application under section 16(1) of the 2017 Act be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Via email to the opposing counsel alone, bypassing the court''s formal procedures","Through an oral plea directly to the judge during a scheduled hearing without prior notice to the opposing party","By motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with Order 44","By submitting a written request to the court registrar without notifying the other party"],"justification":"An application by a party under section 16(1) of the 2017 Act must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with [Order 44]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Application for invitation to mediate* 3. An application by a party under section 16(1) of the 2017 Act must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with [Order 44]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-44-District-Applications-By-Notice-Of-Motion) within the period mentioned in section 16(4) of the 2017 Act. An application by such a party under section 16(4) of the 2017 Act to dispense with the requirement for an affidavit may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an application to enforce the terms of a mediation settlement be made in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","Form","Form 12A.03","Form 48A.05"],"justification":"notice of application in the [Form 49B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/145c6bab-3e2c-4867-b298-8368aa94e86d/Notice of application to enforce mediation settlement No. 49B.01.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceedings to enforce mediation settlement* 5. (1) An application under section 11(3) of the 2017 Act to enforce the terms of a mediation settlement must be made by notice of application in the [Form 49B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/145c6bab-3e2c-4867-b298-8368aa94e86d/Notice of application to enforce mediation settlement No. 49B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule grounded on an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party which must exhibit and verify the mediation settlement. (2) Copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits must be served, in accordance with Order 41, on each other party to the mediation settlement not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can an application be made parte for dispensing with the requirement of giving a copy of the report to the parties at least seven days before its submission to the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An application can be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.","An application can be made parte only if the Court has been closed for at least seven days prior to the application.","An application can be made parte only during the final hearing of the case, not at any other time.","An application can be made parte only if it is submitted more than thirty days after the initial filing of the case."],"justification":"may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Mediator’s report to Court* 6. (1) A mediator’s report required by section 17 of the Act must be entitled as in the proceedings to which it relates and must be submitted to the Court by the lodgment by the mediator with the Clerk of an affidavit verifying and exhibiting the report. (2) An application under section 17(2) of the 2017 Act for a direction to dispense with the requirement that a copy of the report be given to the parties at least seven days prior to its submission to the Court may be made parte at any sitting of the Court in the Court district concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do if the parties decide to use another ADR process?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may terminate all proceedings related to the case if the parties decide to use another ADR process.","The Court may require the parties to abandon their chosen ADR process and return to the court''s jurisdiction immediately.","The Court may impose sanctions on the parties who choose to use another ADR process instead of the one initially agreed upon.","The Court may extend the time for compliance with Rules or orders and make further orders to facilitate the effective use of the ADR process."],"justification":"Where the parties decide to use another ADR process, the Court may make an order extending the time for compliance by any party with any provision of these Rules or any order of the Court in the proceedings, and may make such further or other orders or give such directions as the Court considers will facilitate the effective use of that process."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 7. (1) The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or - where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process, and may, for the purposes of such invitation or reference, invite the parties to attend such information session on the use of such other ADR process, if any, as the Court may specify. (2) Where the parties decide to use another ADR process, the Court may make an order extending the time for compliance by any party with any pro vision of these Rules or any order of the Court in the proceedings, and may make such further or other orders or give such directions as the Court considers will facilitate the effective use of that process.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'How can an application for an order under Rule 7 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, or without such motion at any other time when the proceedings are before the Court, including at a case management hearing.","By filing a petition with the local law enforcement agency instead of the Court.","Through verbal agreement during a casual meeting between the parties involved, without formal documentation.","By submitting a written request to the opposing party only, without involving the Court."],"justification":"An application by a party for an order under rule 7 may be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, or may be made without such motion at any other time when the proceedings are before the Court, including at a case management hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Application for adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 8. An application by a party for an order under rule 7 may be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, or may be made without such motion at any other time when the proceedings are before the Court, including at a case management hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Unless otherwise agreed, how must witnesses be examined at the trial of any claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["In writing through affidavits submitted to the court.","Orally on oath in open court.","By providing written statements signed under penalty of perjury.","Through video conferencing from remote locations."],"justification":"Unless otherwise agreed in writing by all of the parties to the proceeding, and subject to these Rules and the law of evidence, witnesses at the trial of any claim must be examined orally on oath in open Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Oral evidence* 1. (1) Unless otherwise agreed in writing by all of the parties to the proceeding, and subject to these Rules and the law of evidence, witnesses at the trial of any claim must be examined orally on oath in open Court. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may at any time for such reasons as it thinks right order that a particular fact may be proved by affidavit, or that the affidavit of a witness may be read at the hearing or trial on such conditions as the Court thinks reasonable. (3) An order may not be made authorising the evidence of a witness to be given by affidavit where it appears to the Court that another party bona fide requires the production of the witness for cross-examination, and that the witness can be produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do when a notice of trial is served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed.","Notify all parties involved in the case of the time and place at which the trial is listed.","Serve another notice of trial to confirm receipt of the initial notice.","File the notice of trial with the court without notifying any parties."],"justification":"The Clerk must notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed, and may do so by returning to that party a copy of the notice of trial with those details inserted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(8) The Clerk must notify the party who has served notice of trial of the time and place at which the trial is listed, and may do so by returning to that party a copy of the notice of trial with those details inserted. The party who has served notice of trial must promptly notify all other parties of the time and place at which the trial is listed. (9) No notice of motion seeking discovery or further particulars may be issued by any party later than 14 days after notice of trial has been served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent''s defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant will automatically win the case by default.","The claimant may serve and file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4.","The court will dismiss the case due to procedural error.","The respondent may serve and file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4."],"justification":"Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Service of notice of trial by respondent* 5. Where the claimant fails to serve notice of trial within ten days after the delivery of the respondent’s defence, the respondent may do so and may file the notice of trial in accordance with rule 4.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the claimant appears and the respondent does not appear?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The claimant will be required to pay a fine for the respondent''s absence.","The court will automatically rule in favor of the respondent.","The claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her.","The case will be dismissed immediately due to insufficient evidence."],"justification":"the claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Non-appearance at trial* 13. (1) If, when a case is called in Court, the claimant appears, and the respondent does not appear, the claimant may prove his or her claim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her. (2) If, when a case is called in Court, the respondent appears, and the claimant does not appear, the respondent, if he or she has no counterclaim, is entitled to judgment dismissing the claim, but if he or she has a counterclaim, then he or she may prove the counterclaim so far as the burden of proof lies on him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The respondent is required to pay a lump sum equivalent to the total amount within one month of the order being made.","The court must enforce payment through garnishment of wages immediately upon making the instalment order.","No order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order.","An immediate order for execution can be issued against the respondent."],"justification":"If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Ancillary orders as to payment* 14. (1) When the Court has pronounced a judgment or made an order (or at any later time on notice being given to the opposite party), the Court may order the time or times when, and by what instalments, the debt or damages and costs of the judgment, or the amount stated in the order and the costs must be paid. (2) If an order for instalments is made on pronouncing a judgment or making an order, no order for execution may issue against the respondent until after default of payment or default of some instalment according to the order. (3) The Court may stay execution on foot of any judgment or order for such period and on such terms as the Court considers just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court may order that both judgments be merged into one, with the total amount being the sum of both original judgments.","The Court may reduce the amount of the larger judgment to match the smaller one, ensuring both debts are equal before proceeding.","The Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum is due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment.","The Court may order that the smaller judgment be increased to match the larger one, making both debts equal before issuing any further judgments."],"justification":"If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Cross judgments may be set off* 17. (1) If: - (a) the Court makes cross judgments between the same parties; or - there are at the same time unexecuted or only partially executed judgments of the Court between the same parties, the Court may, on the application of either party, order that the judgments be set off against each other. (2) If judgments ordered to be set off against each other are of unequal amounts, the Court may order that a judgment issue only on which the larger sum due, and that the judgment be issued or executed only for the sum which remains due after deducting the sum due on the other judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49 - Hearing Of Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Does a judgment for the recovery of a sum of money not exceeding €190.46 carry interest?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"A judgment for the recovery of a sum of money for an amount not exceeding €190.46 does not carry interest."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Interest* 20. (1) A judgment for the recovery of a sum of money which (exclusive of costs and witnesses'' expenses) exceeds €190.46, carries interest on the sum at the rate per annum specified for the time being in section 26 of the [Debtors (Ireland) Act 1840](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1840/act/105/enacted/en/print.html), until it is satisfied. (2) Interest must be calculated from the date of the judgment unless the Court otherwise directs. (3) A judgment for the recovery of a sum of money for an amount not exceeding €190.46 does not carry interest. [1] Order 49 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 49 Rule 7A inserted by [S.I. 218 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/218/made/en/print) effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 49A apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","Supreme Court","County Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 49A - Case Management - Court: District # **Order 49A: Case Management******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court adopt a timetable proposed by the parties for preparing the case for trial?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes, if the court finds it reasonable.","Only if the court deems it necessary for the efficient administration of justice, regardless of whether it is reasonable or not.","No, the court cannot adopt any timetables proposed by the parties.","Yes, only if all parties agree unanimously, without the court''s discretion to find it reasonable."],"justification":"may adopt any timetable proposed by the parties if satisfied that it is reasonable"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Case management directions* 1. (1) The Court may, at any time and from time to time, of its own motion and having heard the parties, give such directions and make such orders, including the fixing of time limits, for the conduct of civil proceedings, as appears convenient for the determination of the proceedings in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the cost of those proceedings. (2) Except where these Rules provide otherwise, the Court may: - (a) ensure that the issues, whether as to fact or law, are defined as clearly, as precisely and as concisely, as possible; - give case management directions as to the steps which remain to be taken to prepare the case for trial, and the timetable for the completion of preparations of the case for trial, and for that purpose may adopt any timetable proposed by the parties if satisfied that it is reasonable; - make orders or give directions with respect to pleadings, the exchange between the parties of statements of issues, the identifying of issues in dispute between the parties, particulars, discovery, inspection of documents, or otherwise, which may be necessary or expedient; - make inquiries of the parties so as to ascertain the likely length of the trial and the arrangements, if any, for witnesses, information and communications technology (including video conferencing) and any other arrangements which require to be made for the trial; - fix the time and mode of trial, and may fix a date for trial and may also give directions as to the service of a notice of trial; - make any orders and give any directions in respect of arrangements for the trial as the Court considers necessary; - direct any expert witnesses to consult with each other within such time as the Court specifies for the purposes of— - identifying the issues in respect of which they intend to give evidence, - where possible, reaching agreement on the evidence that they intend to give in respect of those issues, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49A - Case Management', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to copies of case management directions after they are given?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Copies are sent to the national archives for long-term storage.","Copies are placed on the Court file and made available to parties upon request.","Copies are kept in a secure vault at the courthouse and not accessible to the public.","Copies are destroyed immediately after they are given."],"justification":"A copy of the case management directions must be placed on the Court file and a further copy of the case management directions must be made available to a party to the civil proceedings at the party’s request."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Case management records* 3. (1) The Clerk must maintain a record, which may be in electronic form, of all case management directions given. (2) A copy of the case management directions must be placed on the Court file and a further copy of the case management directions must be made available to a party to the civil proceedings at the party’s request.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''another ADR process'' mean?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Arbitration or another dispute resolution process approved by the Court, but excluding conciliation.","Mediation or another dispute resolution process approved by the Court, including arbitration.","Conciliation or another dispute resolution process approved by the Court, but excluding mediation or arbitration.","Conciliation or another legal proceeding initiated by one of the parties involved in the dispute."],"justification":"“**another ADR process**” means conciliation or another dispute resolution pro cess approved by the Court, but does not include mediation or arbitration."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order: the “**2017 Act**” means the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No 27 of 2017); each of the expressions “**mediation**”, “**mediation settlement**” and “**mediator**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the 2017 Act; “**another ADR process**” means conciliation or another dispute resolution pro cess approved by the Court, but does not include mediation or arbitration.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What orders can the Court make if the parties decide to engage in mediation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court may impose fines on the parties for engaging in mediation.","The Court may issue a final judgment without considering the outcomes of mediation.","The Court may adjourn the proceedings, extend the time for compliance with rules or court orders, or make other orders/directions to facilitate mediation.","The Court may mandate that one party pays all legal fees associated with the mediation."],"justification":"Where, following an invitation by the Court, the parties decide to engage in mediation, the Court may, in accordance with section 16(2) of the 2017 Act— (a) make an order adjourning the proceedings to such date as the Court considers just and convenient in all the circumstances, make an order extending the time for compliance by a party with any relevant provision of these Rules or with any order of the Court in the proceedings, or make such other order or give such direction as the Court considers necessary to facilitate the effective use of mediation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Invitation to mediate; application for adjournment to facilitate mediation* 2. (1) The Court may, in civil proceedings to which the 2017 Act applies, in accordance with section 16(1) of the 2017 Act, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, where it considers it appropriate having regard to all the circumstances of the case: - (a) invite the parties to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings, and - provide the parties to the proceedings with information about the benefits of mediation to settle the dispute the subject of the proceedings. (2) Where, following an invitation by the Court, the parties decide to engage in mediation, the Court may, in accordance with section 16(2) of the 2017 Act— - (a) make an order adjourning the proceedings to such date as the Court considers just and convenient in all the circumstances, - make an order extending the time for compliance by a party with any relevant provision of these Rules or with any order of the Court in the proceedings, or - make such other order or give such direction as the Court considers necessary to facilitate the effective use of mediation. (3) An application by a party to civil proceedings under section 19(1) of the 2017 Act for an order adjourning the proceedings must be made by motion to the Court on notice to the other party or parties in accordance with Order 44, but need not be grounded on any affidavit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'When must copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit, and any exhibits be served on each other party to the mediation settlement?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["within 30 days after the date fixed for the hearing of the application","not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","not later than 7 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","immediately upon filing the application, without regard to the hearing date"],"justification":"not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Proceedings to enforce mediation settlement* 5. (1) An application under section 11(3) of the 2017 Act to enforce the terms of a mediation settlement must be made by notice of application in the [Form 49B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/145c6bab-3e2c-4867-b298-8368aa94e86d/Notice of application to enforce mediation settlement No. 49B.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule grounded on an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party which must exhibit and verify the mediation settlement. (2) Copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits must be served, in accordance with Order 41, on each other party to the mediation settlement not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) A statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on each respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than seven days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do when it considers it appropriate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may increase the penalties beyond what is stipulated by law if it considers it appropriate.","The Court may dismiss any case without providing a reason if it considers it appropriate.","The Court may directly appoint a jury member to make final decisions on cases if it considers it appropriate.","The Court may order proceedings or any issue therein to be adjourned for a time it deems just and convenient, and invite or refer the parties to another ADR process."],"justification":"The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or - where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Adjournment to facilitate other ADR process* 7. (1) The Court, on the application of any of the parties or of its own motion, may, when it considers it appropriate and having regard to all the circumstances of the case, order that proceedings or any issue therein be adjourned for such time as the Court considers just and convenient and - - invite the parties to use another ADR process to settle or determine the proceedings or issue, or - where the parties consent, refer the proceedings or issue to such process, and may, for the purposes of such invitation or reference, invite the parties to attend such information session on the use of such other ADR process, if any, as the Court may specify. (2) Where the parties decide to use another ADR process, the Court may make an order extending the time for compliance by any party with any pro vision of these Rules or any order of the Court in the proceedings, and may make such further or other orders or give such directions as the Court considers will facilitate the effective use of that process.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 49B - Mediation And Other Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition is the time limit extension applicable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The time limit extension applies only during weekends and holidays.","The time limit extension applies unless the Court otherwise orders.","The time limit extension applies only if the Court otherwise orders.","The time limit extension applies unless the parties agree otherwise."],"justification":"unless the Court otherwise orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Extension of time limits* 10. Despite any other provision of these Rules, if a proceeding is referred to mediation or an other ADR process, the time for taking any step in a proceeding under any of those Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be calculated as if time did not run during the period of any adjournment to facilitate the mediation or other ADR process. [1] Order originally inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What additional information must a solicitor acting for a plaintiff include on the Civil Bill?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The solicitor’s title within the firm, the firm''s annual revenue, and their client’s email address.","The solicitor’s date of birth, their physical address, and their client''s phone number.","The solicitor’s name or firm name, the registered place of business, and their email address if they consent to receiving documents electronically.","The solicitor’s name, their office telephone number, and their social media profiles."],"justification":"his or her name or that of his or her firm and: - the registered place of business where documents may be left for him or her, and - where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings - Court: Circuit 1. Civil proceedings in the Court shall, unless otherwise provided by Statute or by these Rules, be instituted by the issue of a Civil Bill, which shall be in the appropriate form in accordance with the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) to these Rules (being Forms 2A to 20), or such modification thereof as may be suitable and shall state such facts as may be necessary to show the jurisdiction of the Court. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) Civil Bill Ejectments on the title and Civil Bills issued for the purpose of establishing questions of title to land, other than ejectments for overholding or for non-payment of rent, shall be headed "**Title Jurisdiction**" and shall contain, as the case may be, - (a) a statement that the market value (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html)) of the land does not exceed €3,000,000 or - such statement of the rent as shall show jurisdiction. At the hearing of any such case the plaintiff may be required to produce a map of the land. 3.[[2]](#_ftn2) (1) Subject to [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-Circuit-Actions-by-and-against-firms-and-persons-carrying-on-business-in-names-other-than-their-own), the Civil Bill shall state: - (a) the given or first name, surname, occupation and residence or place of business of the plaintiff; - the surname of the defendant, his residence or place of business, and, where known, his given or first name and his occupation, and, if the defendant is sued in a representative capacity, the capacity in which he is sued. (2) A solicitor acting for a plaintiff shall additionally indorse upon the Civil Bill his or her name or that of his or her firm and: - the registered place of business where documents may be left for him or her, and - where the plaintiff’s solicitor consents to the receipt of such documents by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of his or her registered place of business) to which documents in the proceedings may be sent in electronic form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum time a defendant has to enter an appearance after being served with a Civil Bill?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Ten days or another agreed time limit.","Five days or another agreed time limit.","Seven days unless specifically stated otherwise in the court rules.","Fifteen days or another agreed time limit."],"justification":"The Civil Bill shall call upon a defendant to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the plaintiff, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) The indorsement required by sub-rules (1) and (2) shall be in the following form: “This Civil Bill was issued by......., whose registered place of business is........, \*[and who consents to the service of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail to ............... ], solicitor for the plaintiff, ........., who \*[resides/has his/her place of business] at...... and is..........” (4) A plaintiff suing in person shall additionally indorse upon the Civil Bill: - an address for service, where documents may be left for him or her, and - where the plaintiff consents to the receipt of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail, his or her electronic mail address (in lieu of an address for service) to which documents may be sent in electronic form. (5) The indorsement required by sub-rules (1) and (4) shall be in the following form: “This Civil Bill was issued by the plaintiff,......., who \*[resides/has his/her place of business] at...... and is.......... \*[and who consents to the service of documents in the proceedings by electronic mail to ...............],” 4. The Civil Bill shall call upon a defendant to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the plaintiff, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 5. Every Civil Bill shall be signed by the plaintiff, or by his Solicitor, and shall be endorsed with particulars of the plaintiff’s demand:—'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What information must be included in the endorsement of a claim when proceedings require authorisation under certain sections of the Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The endorsement must confirm whether proceedings have been authorised by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board, specify the relevant section or rule under which authorisation was issued, and cite the date of issue and any related reference or record number.","The endorsement must include the claimant''s medical history and the full details of the injury suffered.","The endorsement must list all parties involved in the case and their respective legal representatives.","The endorsement must state the amount of compensation claimed and provide a summary of the evidence supporting the claim."],"justification":"In the case of proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), the indorsement of claim shall contain a statement - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board](https://www.injuries.ie/eng/) - specifying the section of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html) or the rule made under section 46(3) of that Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(*a*) stating the nature, extent and grounds thereof, full particulars of all items of special damage being claimed and the relief sought and, where it is a money claim, the amount thereof and the rate and amount of interest (if any) claimed. If, in the first instance, the plaintiff desires an account to be taken, that fact shall be stated, together with the specific amount (if any) which the plaintiff claims to be subject to that account; where there is more than one claim, stating like particulars of each claim to those in paragraph (*a*), and the relief sought in respect of each; stating the abandonment of any part of a claim, if the plaintiff desires abandonment in order to bring the claim within the jurisdiction; where the plaintiff sues in a representative capacity, stating the capacity in which he sues; and where the plaintiff sues as assignee, stating the name, address and description of the assignor at the date of the assignment, and the date of such assignment. 5A.[[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) In the case of proceedings the bringing of which requires to be authorised in accordance with sections 14, 17, 32, 36 or 49, or rules under section 46(3) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html), the indorsement of claim shall contain a statement - (a) confirming whether or not the proceedings have been authorised by the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board](https://www.injuries.ie/eng/) - specifying the section of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act, 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html) or the rule made under section 46(3) of that Act in accordance with which any such authorisation has been issued, and - citing the date of issue of the authorisation and any reference or record number relating to any such authorisation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5 - Commencement of Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'How are proceedings initiated if authorised or directed by a statute not mentioned in these rules?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Proceedings authorised or directed by a statute not mentioned in these rules must be commenced by Civil Bill.","Proceedings authorised or directed by a statute not mentioned in these rules must be commenced by a Writ.","Proceedings authorised or directed by a statute not mentioned in these rules must be commenced by Criminal Summons.","Proceedings authorised or directed by a statute not mentioned in these rules must be commenced by a Complaint."],"justification":"Where, by any Statute not mentioned in these Rules, proceedings are authorised or directed to be taken in the Court, such proceedings shall be commenced by Civil Bill."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '6. Whenever the plaintiff’s claim is for a debt or liquidated claim only, the endorsement, besides stating the nature of the claim shall state the amount claimed for debt or in respect of such demand, and for costs, respectively, and shall further state that, upon payment of such amount and costs within six days after service, further proceedings will be stayed. The amount to be so claimed for costs in all such cases where there has not been any order for service of the Civil Bill, or notice thereof, out of the jurisdiction, or for substituted or other service, or declaring service effected sufficient, or any notice by advertisement of the issuing of the Civil Bill, shall be in accordance with a Schedule of fees to be determined by the County Registrar for the County of the City of Dublin from time to time. If there are more defendants than one, the above amounts may be increased by a reasonable sum for each additional defendant served. 7. Where, by any Statute not mentioned in these Rules, proceedings are authorised or directed to be taken in the Court, such proceedings shall be commenced by Civil Bill. 8.[[5]](#_ftn5) The Consent prescribed by Section of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html) which provides for the enlargement of the jurisdiction of the Court by consent of the parties shall be in the form set forth in [Form 1](/content/consent-enlargement-jurisdiction) of the Schedule of Forms, and shall be lodged with the County Registrar either before or at any time during the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 5 - Judges'' Robes', 'Court Rules', 'What is the name of the Rules that came into effect on March 15, 2017?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Supreme Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017","The District Court (Judges'' Uniforms) Rules 2018","The District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017","The High Court (Judges’ Gowns) Regulations 2017"],"justification":"These Rules, which shall come into operation on the day of March 2017, may be cited as the District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5 - Judges'' Robes - Court: District # District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017****[1]**** 1. (1) These Rules, which shall come into operation on the day of March 2017, may be cited as the District Court (Judges’ Robes) Rules 2017. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the District Court Rules 1997 ([S.I. No. 93 of 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93/made/en/print)) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the District Court Rules 1997 to 2017. 2. The District Court Rules 1997 ([S.I. No. 93 of 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93/made/en/print)) are amended by the substitution for Order 5 of the Order set out in the Schedule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 5 - Judges'' Robes', 'Court Rules', 'What is the official attire for judges during court sittings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A black coat and gown with white bands or a black gown with blue double ribbon banding and a single white neck tab or white bands.","A casual business attire including khakis and a polo shirt","A formal suit and tie with a red bow tie","A military uniform with medals and insignia"],"justification":"(a) a black coat and gown of uniform nature and material and white bands or a black gown of uniform nature and material with sleeves bearing blue double ribbon banding and a single white neck tab or white bands."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Schedule 1. (1) Save as otherwise provided by Statute or these Rules, the official attire to be worn by the Judges during the sittings of the Court shall be as follows: - (a) a black coat and gown of uniform nature and material and white bands or - a black gown of uniform nature and material with sleeves bearing blue double ribbon banding and a single white neck tab or white bands. (2) A Judge appointed to the Court after the coming into operation of sub-rule (1) and this sub-rule shall wear the official attire specified in paragraph of sub-rule (1). 2. A Judge, when hearing and determining such proceedings as are referred to in [section 45(1)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/6/section/45/enacted/en/html#sec45) of the [Judicial Separation and Family Law Reform Act 1989 (No. 6 of 1989)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/6/enacted/en/html) or proceedings involving a child shall not be required to wear either such gown but shall during the sittings of the Court wear white bands or a single white neck tab and dark attire. [1] Order 5 substituted by [S.I. 77 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/77/made/en/print?q 77&years 2017), effective 15 March 2017'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 43 - Joining Claims And Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["TRUSTEERS, EXECUTORS AND ADVOCATES","TRUSTEERS, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS","TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ASSISTANTS","TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ATTORNEYS"],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 5 - TRUSTEES, EXECUTORS AND ADMINISTRATORS'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Every originating summons relating to such other matter or matters as Rules of Court may from time to time specify. 5. In the case of any originating summons within rule 4, it shall be the duty of the officer issuing the summons to mark and assign the summons for the Judge assigned as mentioned in the said rule or (if more than one Judge has been so assigned) for the Judges so assigned in rotation. Any case of doubt or difficulty shall be determined by the Master and the assignment or non-assignment of any summons at the time of issue shall be without prejudice to the power of the Master to vary or alter such assignment or non-assignment. 6. Where an originating summons has been so assigned under rules 4 and 5 to a particular Judge or has (whether assigned or not) been heard by a particular Judge, every subsequent summons, notice of motion, or petition, relating to the same matter, or so connected therewith as to be conveniently dealt with by the same Judge, shall whenever practicable be marked by the proper officer with the name of such Judge, and the party or solicitor presenting such summons, notice of motion, or petition, shall, if there be to his knowledge such relation or connection, so certify. Such certificate shall be in the [Form No 5 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon2); and such certificate shall be countersigned by the Registrar of the Judge to whom such originating summons had been assigned or by whom such originating summons had been heard as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'How is an originating summons authenticated and sealed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Authenticated in the name of the Clerk of the Court and sealed with the seal of the local magistrate''s court.","Authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice or the President of the Court of Appeal and sealed with the seal of the High Court.","Authenticated in the name of the Attorney General and sealed with the official stamp of the Ministry of Justice.","Authenticated by any judge of the Supreme Court and sealed with the personal stamp of the presiding judge."],"justification":"Every originating summons shall bear date of the day of issue and shall be authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice, or if the office of Chief Justice be vacant, in the name of the President of the Court of Appeal and shall be sealed with the seal of the High Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. There shall be books in the Central Office to be called Cause Books in which all proceedings commenced by originating summons, issued out of the Central Office, shall be entered. Every summons shall be entered consecutively in order of issue and shall be distinguished by the date of the year and a number in consecutive order commencing on the first day of January in each year, with or without a distinguishing letter or other sign; and the said date and number, together with the distinguishing letter or sign (if any) shall constitute the record number of the proceeding. 8. Every originating summons shall bear date of the day of issue and shall be authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice, or if the office of Chief Justice be vacant, in the name of the President of the Court of Appeal[[2]](#_ftn2) and shall be sealed with the seal of the High Court. 9. Every originating summons shall be sealed and marked with the record number by the proper officer, and shall thereupon be deemed to be issued. No originating summons shall be served until the same shall have been so sealed and marked. 10. One duplicate or more of every originating summons shall be so sealed and marked on the application of the plaintiff or his solicitor. 11. The plaintiff or other party or his solicitor shall, on presenting an originating summons for sealing, leave with the proper officer a copy, written or printed, or partly written and partly printed, on paper of the description aforesaid, of such summons and all the indorsements thereon, and such copy shall be signed by the solicitor leaving the same, or by the plaintiff himself if he sues in person. 12. The officer receiving the copy summons pursuant to rule 11 shall cause the same to be marked with the record number and to be filed and shall also cause an entry of the particulars thereof to be made in the appropriate Cause Book as herein before provided.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can an originating summons or other originating document be served out of the jurisdiction without the leave of the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If the plaintiff resides outside of the jurisdiction.","If each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention.","If the case involves a contractual dispute worth more than 1 million.","If the defendant has agreed in writing to accept service out of the jurisdiction."],"justification":"Service of an originating summons or other originating document or notice of an originating summons or other originating document out of the jurisdiction is permissible without the leave of the Court, if, but only if, it complies with the following conditions: - each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and - no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. The issue of a summons in probate proceedings shall be preceded by the filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons. On issuing the summons the plaintiff shall, if he has not already so done, lodge a caveat in the Probate Office entitled in the estate of the deceased person. 14. [[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) [[5]](#_ftn5) (1) Save as is otherwise provided for in these Rules, no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court. (2) Service of an originating summons or other originating document or notice of an originating summons or other originating document out of the jurisdiction is permissible without the leave of the Court, if, but only if, it complies with the following conditions: - each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and - no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention. 15. Save as otherwise provided in these Rules, every petition to the Court shall be presented by leaving it with the proper officer at the Central Office. Subject thereto, the foregoing provisions of this Order shall apply to a petition in the same manner as they apply to an originating summons, and references in this Order to “**originating summons**” and “**plaintiff**” shall be construed as including references to “**petition**” and “**petitioner**” respectively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'How many clear days must there be between service and the day for hearing of a petition unless the court grants leave?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["No clear days required.","Exactly three clear days.","At least one clear day.","At least two clear days."],"justification":"Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '16. At the foot of every petition presented to the Court, and of every copy thereof, a statement shall be made of the persons, if any, intended to be served therewith, and if no person is intended to be served a statement to that effect shall be made at the foot of the petition and of every copy thereof. 17. Unless the Court gives leave to the contrary there must be at least two clear days between the service and the day for hearing of a petition. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 5 rule substituted by 149 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2010/en.si.2010.0149.pdf). 149 of 2010 is effective 10 May 2010, subject to paragraph 2 which reads: “Any application for registration of a lis pendens containing the particulars required by law before 1 December 2009 for such registration which is received after 1 December 2009 and prior to the date mentioned in paragraph 1 shall be deemed to comply with the requirements for registration of a lis pendens in accordance with section 121 of the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009.” [[2]](#_ftnref2) “President of the Court of Appeal” substituted for “President of the High Court” by 404 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/404/made/en/print), effective 2 October 2017. [[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 5 rule 14 substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) by 14 of 1989](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1989/en/si/0014.html), effective 1 February 1989. [[4]](#_ftnref4) Order 5 rules 14(1), 14(2) and 14(3) were substituted by rules 14(1), 14(2)(1) and 14(2)(2) by 506 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2005/en/si/0506.html), effective 10 August 2005. [[5]](#_ftnref5) Order 5 rule 14(2) substituted by 9 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/9/made/en/print), effective 12 January 2016.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What type of court is addressed in Order 50?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme Court","District Court","County Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the definition of ''videoconference'' in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Any synchronous interaction between two or more individuals using any form of technology that allows them to communicate, excluding those instances where audio and visual elements are combined.","Any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time.","Any form of communication between two or more persons regardless of the medium, including telephone calls and email exchanges, as long as it involves the exchange of information across different locations.","Any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology which enables persons remote from one another to see and hear each other, but not necessarily to be seen and heard by one another in real time."],"justification":"“**videoconference**”[1] includes any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- reference to an affidavit includes reference to any affidavit, solemn affirmation or the acknowledgment of any deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**deponent**” means a person making an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court, but includes reference to a person making a solemn affirmation or acknowledgment of a deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**relevant document**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html), “**videoconference**”[1] includes any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What conditions must be met when swearing an affidavit via videoconference?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The officer must provide a copy of the affidavit, ensure the videoconference facility works properly, and confirm the deponent''s identification by asking for a social security number instead of confirming it if required.","The officer must provide a copy of the affidavit and any exhibits, ensure the videoconference facility works properly, confirm the deponent''s identification if required, and ensure the appropriate sacred text is available.","The officer must ensure that the videoconference facility works properly, provide a copy of the affidavit only, and confirm the deponent''s identification without requiring any sacred text.","The officer must provide a copy of the affidavit and any exhibits, ensure the videoconference facility works properly, and confirm the deponent''s identification if required, but there is no need to ensure the availability of any sacred text."],"justification":"the officer shall be provided in advance or at the videoconference with a copy (which may be in electronic form) of the affidavit, copies of any exhibits referred to in it and, in a case where rule 6(b)(iii) applies, a certified copy of the relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; the officer shall be satisfied that the videoconference facility enables the deponent to see and hear the officer and to be seen and heard by the officer; in a case to which rule 6(b)(ii) applies, the officer shall ensure that the requirement in the paragraph concerned for identification of the deponent has been met before the affidavit is sworn; the officer shall satisfy himself that the appropriate sacred text for taking the oath is available to the deponent;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Making an affidavit* 2.[2] (1) Subject to sub-rule (2), all affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court (which may be in the [Form 50.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b849640e-dfd9-4e8d-b505-99429c139026/Affidavit - general No. 50.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made before a Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court, or a practising solicitor (in the remainder of this sub-rule, the “officer”). (2) Where the person making an affidavit resides outside the State, or is for the time being outside the State, the affidavit may be made before any person authorised by law to administer oaths in the place where the person making the affidavit resides or is. (3) An affidavit sworn in the State may be sworn by the deponent- - (a) in the physical presence of the officer before whom it is to be sworn, or - where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer, subject to and in accordance with sub-rule (4). (4) Where an affidavit is sworn in the manner referred to in sub-rule the following conditions shall be complied with - - (a) the officer shall be provided in advance or at the videoconference with a copy (which may be in electronic form) of the affidavit, copies of any exhibits referred to in it and, in a case where rule 6(b)(iii) applies, a certified copy of the relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; - the officer shall be satisfied that the videoconference facility enables the deponent to see and hear the officer and to be seen and heard by the officer; - in a case to which rule 6(b)(ii) applies, the officer shall ensure that the requirement in the paragraph concerned for identification of the deponent has been met before the affidavit is sworn; - the officer shall satisfy himself that the appropriate sacred text for taking the oath is available to the deponent;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must the deponent do during the videoconference?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Submit a photocopy of their identification instead of producing the original document.","Only sign the affidavit without identifying the pages of the affidavit or marking each exhibit.","Produce the original of any relevant document intended to verify their identity, identify each page of the affidavit and exhibits, sign or mark each exhibit, and sign and swear the affidavit.","Provide a verbal affirmation without signing any documents or identifying the pages of the affidavit and exhibits."],"justification":"during the videoconference and within sight and hearing of the officer, the deponent shall produce the original of any relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; shall identify each page of the affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it, shall sign or mark any and every exhibit, and shall sign and swear the affidavit;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- during the videoconference and within sight and hearing of the officer, the deponent shall produce the original of any relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; shall identify each page of the affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it, shall sign or mark any and every exhibit, and shall sign and swear the affidavit; - the sworn affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it shall immediately following the videoconference be sent to the officer, for attestation by the officer; - the officer shall before attesting the affidavit and signing or marking any and every exhibit referred to in it, satisfy himself that the document (and each and any exhibit) is the same as that which had been identified to him during the videoconference and, where relevant, sign and append to the affidavit the certified copy of the relevant document used to verify the deponent’s identity, and - notwithstanding rule 6, the jurat of the affidavit shall indicate the date on which the affidavit was made by the deponent, the place at which the officer was when taking the affidavit and the fact that the affidavit was sworn using a videoconference.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What format should affidavits be expressed in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["third person of the deponent","objective narrative","first person of the deponent","second person of the deponent"],"justification":"be expressed in the first person of the deponent;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Form of affidavit* 3. All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) be written or printed book-wise; - be expressed in the first person of the deponent; be drawn up in numbered paragraphs; and - include the title of the civil proceedings in which they are sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What information must be included about the deponent''s age in an affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The affidavit must state that the deponent is over 16 years of age.","The affidavit must state that the deponent is over 18 years of age, or if under 18, their exact age.","The affidavit must only mention the deponent''s age if they are exactly 21 years old.","The affidavit must state that the deponent is under 18 years of age."],"justification":"state that the deponent is over 18 years of age, but if the deponent is under 18 years of age, the affidavit must state the deponent’s exact age;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Particulars of deponent and other requirements* 4.[3] All affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court must: - (a) state the deponent’s occupation and - the deponent’s place of business, or - the deponent’s place of residence; - state that the deponent is over 18 years of age, but if the deponent is under 18 years of age, the affidavit must state the deponent’s exact age; - be confined to such facts as the deponent is able to prove of his or her own knowledge; - state the deponent’s means of knowledge of the facts sworn, except on interlocutory motions, on which a statement by the deponent as to his or her belief, and the grounds of his or her belief, may be admitted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is prohibited regarding affidavits in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An affidavit cannot be used if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used, or before the partner, agent, correspondent or clerk of that solicitor, or before the party himself.","Affidavits cannot be accepted if they were prepared without the presence of a court reporter.","An affidavit is invalid if it was signed in the presence of any witness, not just legal representatives.","Affidavits are considered unreliable unless they are notarized by a judge, not a solicitor or their associates."],"justification":"No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used, or before the partner, agent, correspondent or clerk of that solicitor, or before the party himself."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Affidavit may not be sworn before solicitor for party* 5. No affidavit may be used in civil proceedings in the Court if it was sworn before the solicitor acting for the party on whose behalf the affidavit is to be used, or before the partner, agent, correspondent or clerk of that solicitor, or before the party himself.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person taking an affidavit express regarding the date and place?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The date and place where the affidavit is taken.","The date and place where the person signing the affidavit was born.","The date and place where the person signing the affidavit last resided.","The date and place where the affidavit is to be used in court."],"justification":"must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Attestation by person taking affidavit and jurat* 6. Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit; otherwise the affidavit must be taken not to be authentic and must not be filed without the permission of the Court; - must certify in the jurat either: - that he personally knows the deponent, or - that the deponent has been identified to him or her by some person personally known to him or her and named in the jurat who certifies his personal knowledge of the deponent, or - (iii) that the identity of the deponent has been established by him or her by reference to a relevant document containing a photograph of the deponent before the affidavit was taken, and in a case to which paragraph (iii) applies, must give particulars of the relevant document concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must the person taking an affidavit certify when it is sworn or made by someone who appears to be illiterate or blind?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The deponent must verbally state that they fully understand the contents of the affidavit without needing it to be read to them.","The deponent must have a witness present who can confirm they understood the affidavit.","The deponent must acknowledge that the affidavit was not read to them but that they trust the content as written.","The affidavit was read in their presence to the deponent, the deponent appeared to understand it, and the deponent made their signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit."],"justification":"- (a) the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent; - that the deponent appeared to understand it, and - that the deponent made his or her signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Additional requirements for affidavit by illiterate or blind person* 7. (1) When an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court is sworn or made by a person who appears to the person taking the affidavit to be illiterate or blind, the person taking the affidavit must certify that: - (a) the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent; - that the deponent appeared to understand it, and - that the deponent made his or her signature or mark in the presence of the person taking the affidavit. (2) No affidavit mentioned in sub-rule (1) may be used in evidence in the absence of the certificate mentioned in sub-rule (1) unless the Court is otherwise satisfied that the affidavit was read over to, and appeared to be understood by, the deponent. (3)[4] Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What additional document must be filed when a foreign language affidavit is submitted to court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A certificate of authenticity signed by a notary public stating that the foreign language affidavit is genuine.","An affidavit from the attorney confirming that the foreign language affidavit has been translated by a certified translator.","An affidavit of the interpreter setting out their qualifications, exhibiting a copy of the foreign language affidavit, and confirming they read it accurately to the deponent.","A sworn statement from the deponent in English summarizing the content of the foreign language affidavit."],"justification":"Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Additional requirements for swearing and filing a foreign language affidavit* 9. (1) Where the deponent appears to the person taking an affidavit not to be capable of understanding one of the official languages of the State, the person taking the affidavit must: - (a) ensure that the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8; and - ensure that the affidavit is read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter in the presence of the person taking the affidavit, and that the deponent has fully understood it; and - certify in the jurat that the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, that the deponent fully understood it and that the deponent signed the foreign language affidavit in his or her presence. (2) Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit. (3) Where the translator and interpreter are one and the same person, a single affidavit may be sworn by that person for the purposes of rule 8(3) and this rule. (4) No foreign language affidavit may be used in evidence in the absence of the affidavit referred to in rule 8(3), unless the Court is otherwise satisfied as to the evidence contained in the foreign language affidavit. (5)[5] Notwithstanding paragraph of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for an affidavit with alterations or erasures to be used in court proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The affidavit can be used in court proceedings as long as it has been notarized, regardless of any alterations or erasures.","Alterations or erasures must be ignored completely and cannot be used in court proceedings.","Permission of the Court unless alterations are authenticated by initials or erased words are re-written and signed in the margin.","All affidavits with alterations or erasures are automatically invalid and cannot be used in court proceedings."],"justification":"An affidavit which has in either the body or the jurat any interlineation, alteration, or erasure, may not be filed, read, or made use of in any civil proceeding in the Court without the permission of the Court unless:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Amendments* 11. An affidavit which has in either the body or the jurat any interlineation, alteration, or erasure, may not be filed, read, or made use of in any civil proceeding in the Court without the permission of the Court unless: - (a) the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit; or - in the case of an erasure, the words or figures appearing at the time of taking the affidavit and erased are re-written and signed or initialled in the margin of the affidavit by the person taking it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the court take when receiving a defective affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court may immediately dismiss the case due to the defective affidavit.","The court may direct a memorandum to be made on the document indicating it has been received.","The court may amend the defective affidavit without notifying the submitter.","The court may return the defective affidavit to the submitter with a fine imposed."],"justification":"and where the Court does so, it may direct a memorandum to be made on the document that it has been so received."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Power of Court to receive defective affidavit* 12. The Court may receive any affidavit sworn for the purpose of being used in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) despite any defect by misdescription of the parties or otherwise in the title or in the jurat; or - despite any other irregularity in its form, and where the Court does so, it may direct a memorandum to be made on the document that it has been so received.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Can a Judge make an order based on an undertaking to file an affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, a Judge cannot make an order unless the affidavit is physically present in court.","No, a Judge must wait until an affidavit is provided under oath before making any decision.","Yes, but the Judge may stay the issue of any order until the affidavit has been filed.","Yes, but the Judge can only make the order after the affidavit has been reviewed by all parties involved."],"justification":"Sub-rule (1) does not prevent the Judge from making an order on the undertaking of the applicant or his solicitor to file any affidavit sworn before the making of the order, or permitted by the Judge to be made after the order, provided that the Judge may stay the issue of any order until the affidavit has been filed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Filing of affidavits* 13. (1) Before an affidavit is used in civil proceedings in the Court, it must be filed with the Clerk. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not prevent the Judge from making an order on the undertaking of the applicant or his solicitor to file any affidavit sworn before the making of the order, or permitted by the Judge to be made after the order, provided that the Judge may stay the issue of any order until the affidavit has been filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do when an affidavit is filed for use in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Sign the affidavit as a witness to confirm its authenticity.","Stamp each page of the affidavit with the court''s official seal.","Review the content of the affidavit for legal accuracy before filing it.","Endorse the date on which the affidavit was filed on every affidavit."],"justification":"The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Date of filing* 14. The Clerk must endorse on every affidavit which is filed for use in civil proceedings in the Court the date on which the affidavit was filed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if an affidavit is delivered or filed after the special time limit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["It cannot be used without the permission of the Court.","It will be accepted as long as it is within one week of the deadline.","It can be used automatically after a delay fee is paid.","It will be disregarded entirely and cannot be used under any circumstances."],"justification":"no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Affidavit may not be used after limited time without permission* 15. Where a special time is limited for delivering or filing an affidavit, no affidavit delivered or filed after that time may be used without the permission of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit be treated as?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["exhibits","depositions","evidence","testimonies"],"justification":"Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Exhibits* 16. (1) Documents identified by or referred to in an affidavit must not be annexed to the affidavit, but must be referred to in the affidavit as exhibits. (2) Every certificate on an exhibit referred to in an affidavit signed by the person before whom the affidavit is sworn must be marked with the short title of the civil proceedings. (3) Nothing in this rule requires or authorises any marking on an original will which has not been admitted to probate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Does the Court''s decision on bearing costs depend on the outcome of the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court''s decision on bearing costs is made during the hearing itself.","Yes, the outcome of the hearing determines the party that will bear the costs.","No, regardless of the outcome of the hearing.","Yes, the Court only decides on bearing costs after the hearing outcome is known."],"justification":"regardless of the outcome of the hearing at which it is used."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17 Costs of affidavit* 17. The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which: - (a) unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, or - which contains argumentative matter, or - which is of unnecessary length, regardless of the outcome of the hearing at which it is used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can a party require the deponent to attend for cross-examination?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Unless the Court has ordered otherwise, a party may require the deponent to attend by serving written notice at least seven days before the trial or hearing.","A party may require the deponent to attend for cross-examination without any prior notice if they have not been deposed previously.","Unless the Court has ordered otherwise, a party may require the deponent to attend by serving written notice at least three days before the trial or hearing.","A party can require the deponent to attend for cross-examination only if the deponent is within the same city as the trial or hearing."],"justification":"Unless the Court has ordered otherwise, a party may, by written notice served on the party relying on the affidavit concerned at least seven days before the trial or hearing, require the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, for the purpose of being cross-examined."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18 Court or party may require attendance of deponent* 18. (1) The Court may direct the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, where it considers the deponent’s attendance necessary in the interests of justice. (2) Unless the Court has ordered otherwise, a party may, by written notice served on the party relying on the affidavit concerned at least seven days before the trial or hearing, require the deponent to any affidavit to attend at the trial or hearing at which the affidavit is to be used, for the purpose of being cross-examined. (3) In any case mentioned in sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2) in which the deponent does not attend at the trial or hearing. the affidavit may not be used, unless the Court orders otherwise. [1] Order 50, rule 1 definition of “**videoconference**” inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [2] Order 50, rule 2 substituted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [3] Order 50, rule 4 substituted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [4] Order 50, rule 7(3) inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021. [5] Order 50, rule 9(5) inserted by 147 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/147/made/en/print), effective 6 April 2021 **Related link** [S.I. No. 17 of 2014 - provisions overview](https://www.courts.ie/rules/si-no-17-2014-district-court-civil-procedure-rules-2014-provisions-overview)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 51 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","County Court","High Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments - Court: District # **Order 51: Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''warrant of execution'' include when used in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["a warrant to issue fines, a warrant of sale of goods and a warrant for eviction","a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession","a warrant to arrest individuals, a warrant of dismissal and a warrant for imprisonment","a warrant to serve legal documents, a warrant of personal appearance and a warrant for damages"],"justification":"“**warrant of execution**” or, when used without qualification, “**warrant**” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order, unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires— “**warrant of execution**” or, when used without qualification, “**warrant**” includes a warrant to seize property, a warrant of delivery of goods and a warrant for possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'How long do judgments remain in full force and effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Seven years from the date they were recorded.","Ten years from the date they were appealed.","Twelve years from the date they were given or made.","Five years from the date they were given or made."],"justification":"Judgments remain in full force and effect for twelve years from the date on which they were given or made, but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Duration of judgments* 3. (1) Judgments remain in full force and effect for twelve years from the date on which they were given or made, but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court. (2) An application for permission to execute after six years must be made by notice of motion, which must be served on the person sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'When can a party apply to the court to amend a judgment due to a change in parties?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, if a change takes place by death, assignment or otherwise in the parties.","Only within the first year after the judgment has been issued, provided there is a significant change in the financial status of the parties.","Immediately upon the expiration of the twelve-year period following the issuance of the judgment, if there is a change in the parties.","Within six months of the initial judgment being issued, regardless of any changes in the parties involved."],"justification":"If, at any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, a change takes place, by death, assignment or otherwise, in the parties, a party may apply to the Court on notice served on the other party to have the judgment amended accordingly."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Change of parties* 4. (1) If, at any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, a change takes place, by death, assignment or otherwise, in the parties, a party may apply to the Court on notice served on the other party to have the judgment amended accordingly. (2) If satisfied that the party applying under sub-rule (1) is entitled to execution, the Court may make any appropriate order and may make any amendment to a judgment required to give effect to that order and may impose such terms as to costs or otherwise as appear just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if one respondent satisfies the order against multiple respondents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["No further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favour the order was made.","No further steps may be taken against any other respondent unless the court grants permission.","The order becomes void and must be reissued specifically against each respondent individually.","Further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favor the order was made."],"justification":"If an order against two or more respondents jointly is satisfied by any of the respondents, no further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favour the order so satisfied was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *5 Execution against two or more persons* 5. (1) If a judgment is given or made against two or more respondents jointly, the judgment or order may be enforced by warrant or otherwise against any of the respondents as if the order had been made against that respondent separately. (2) If an order against two or more respondents jointly is satisfied by any of the respondents, no further steps may be taken against any other respondent by the party in whose favour the order so satisfied was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Where can execution be issued against a firm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Against any property of the partnership within the State or against any person who has appeared in his own name under Order 43, rule 22 and has failed to deliver a defence, or who has admitted on the pleadings that he is, or who has been adjudged to be, a partner.","Against any person who has merely filed a claim against the firm without delivering a defense.","Against any property owned by former partners who have since left the partnership.","Against any individual partner''s personal assets outside the state where the firm operates."],"justification":"against any property of the partnership within the State; against any person who has appeared in his own name under [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), rule 22 and has failed to deliver a defence, or who has admitted on the pleadings that he is, or who has been adjudged to be, a partner."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Execution against partners* 6. (1) Where a judgment or order is against a firm, execution may issue: - (a) against any property of the partnership within the State; - against any person who has appeared in his own name under [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), rule 22 and has failed to deliver a defence, or who has admitted on the pleadings that he is, or who has been adjudged to be, a partner. (2) If the person who has obtained judgment claims to be entitled to issue execution against any other person as being a member of the firm, he or she may apply to the Court on notice to that other person for permission to do so. (3) The Court may give permission to issue execution if the liability is not disputed. If the liability is disputed, the Court may order that the liability be tried and determined in any manner in which any issue or question in any action may be tried and determined. (4) Except as against any property of the partnership, a judgment against a firm does not render liable, or otherwise affect any member of the partnership who was out of the State when the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued, and who has not entered an appearance unless he has been made a party to the civil proceedings under [Order 43]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-43-District-Joining-Claims-And-Parties), or has been served within the jurisdiction after the claim notice or other document commencing the civil proceedings was issued.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions do the Circuit Court''s rules apply to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Subject to this Order and except where otherwise expressly provided by these Rules.","At all times, regardless of any other provisions or orders.","Whenever law enforcement officers decide that it is necessary.","Only when the warrants are issued by federal agencies."],"justification":"Subject to this Order and except where otherwise expressly provided by these Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Application of certain rules, practice and procedure of Circuit Court* 7. Subject to this Order and except where otherwise expressly provided by these Rules, the rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution apply, with such modifications as are necessary, to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can a warrant addressed to a County Registrar be executed by another County Registrar?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["If the person against whom the warrant has been issued has goods within the county for which that other County Registrar acts.","If the person against whom the warrant has been issued is currently employed in the county for which that other County Registrar acts.","If the person against whom the warrant has been issued has family residing within the county for which that other County Registrar acts.","If the person against whom the warrant has been issued has previously registered goods in the county for which that other County Registrar acts."],"justification":"if the person against whom the warrant has been issued has goods within the county for which that other County Registrar acts"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Execution by another County Registrar* 8. A warrant addressed to a County Registrar may be executed by another County Registrar if the person against whom the warrant has been issued has goods within the county for which that other County Registrar acts.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What does the section title indicate will be discussed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The methods for distributing charitable donations to individuals in need.","The procedures for seizing goods to satisfy judgments for money or costs.","The guidelines for conducting criminal investigations.","The procedures for issuing fines for traffic violations."],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2****-****SEIZURE OF GOODS IN SATISFACTION OF JUDGMENT FOR MONEY OR COSTS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court extend the period for selling seized goods by auction?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court has no authority to extend the period for selling seized goods by auction; this decision is solely within the jurisdiction of the executive branch.","Yes, the court may extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire.","The court can only extend the period for selling seized goods by auction if it is requested by the person whose goods were seized, and the extension can last up to six months.","No, the court cannot extend the period for selling seized goods by auction under any circumstances."],"justification":"Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire and so on from time to time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Execution of warrants* 10. (1) Where a warrant is for the payment of money and goods are seized under the warrant the person to whom the warrant is addressed may sell the goods by auction within the period fixed by the warrant or, if no period is so fixed, within one month from the day on which the goods were seized, unless the sum for which the warrant was issued and the expenses of taking and keeping the goods are paid before the goods are sold. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire and so on from time to time. (3) Where goods are sold under sub-rule (1), the surplus, if any, after retaining: - (a) the amount to be levied; and - all reasonable expenses actually incurred in auctioning the goods; and - the expenses of taking and keeping the goods, must be paid to the person from whom the goods were seized. (4) The person conducting an auction under this rule need not procure a licence to act as an auctioneer. (5) Where the person against whom a warrant under rule 2 is issued pays or tenders to the person responsible for the execution of the warrant the amount to be levied by the warrant, the person responsible for the execution of the warrant must refrain from executing the warrant. (6) When any money is levied or paid to a court messenger under any warrant, the court messenger must give a receipt for the money.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'What is the purpose of Cause Books in the Central Office?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["To document daily weather conditions relevant to office operations.","To maintain a list of all holidays observed by the legal system.","To record attendance of staff members in the Central Office.","To enter all proceedings commenced by originating summonses issued out of the Central Office."],"justification":"There shall be books in the Central Office to be called Cause Books in which all proceedings commenced by originating summons, issued out of the Central Office, shall be entered."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. There shall be books in the Central Office to be called Cause Books in which all proceedings commenced by originating summons, issued out of the Central Office, shall be entered. Every summons shall be entered consecutively in order of issue and shall be distinguished by the date of the year and a number in consecutive order commencing on the first day of January in each year, with or without a distinguishing letter or other sign; and the said date and number, together with the distinguishing letter or sign (if any) shall constitute the record number of the proceeding. 8. Every originating summons shall bear date of the day of issue and shall be authenticated in the name of the Chief Justice, or if the office of Chief Justice be vacant, in the name of the President of the Court of Appeal[[2]](#_ftn2) and shall be sealed with the seal of the High Court. 9. Every originating summons shall be sealed and marked with the record number by the proper officer, and shall thereupon be deemed to be issued. No originating summons shall be served until the same shall have been so sealed and marked. 10. One duplicate or more of every originating summons shall be so sealed and marked on the application of the plaintiff or his solicitor. 11. The plaintiff or other party or his solicitor shall, on presenting an originating summons for sealing, leave with the proper officer a copy, written or printed, or partly written and partly printed, on paper of the description aforesaid, of such summons and all the indorsements thereon, and such copy shall be signed by the solicitor leaving the same, or by the plaintiff himself if he sues in person. 12. The officer receiving the copy summons pursuant to rule 11 shall cause the same to be marked with the record number and to be filed and shall also cause an entry of the particulars thereof to be made in the appropriate Cause Book as herein before provided.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 5 - Issue Of Summonses And Petitions', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede the issuance of a summons in probate proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The appointment of an executor by the court","The payment of a filing fee to the probate court","The filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons.","The death of the decedent and the opening of the probate case"],"justification":"The issue of a summons in probate proceedings shall be preceded by the filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. The issue of a summons in probate proceedings shall be preceded by the filing of an affidavit made by the plaintiff or one of the plaintiffs in verification of the indorsement on the summons. On issuing the summons the plaintiff shall, if he has not already so done, lodge a caveat in the Probate Office entitled in the estate of the deceased person. 14. [[3]](#_ftn3) [[4]](#_ftn4) [[5]](#_ftn5) (1) Save as is otherwise provided for in these Rules, no summons or other originating document for service out of the jurisdiction or of which notice is to be given out of the jurisdiction shall be issued without leave of the Court. (2) Service of an originating summons or other originating document or notice of an originating summons or other originating document out of the jurisdiction is permissible without the leave of the Court, if, but only if, it complies with the following conditions: - each claim made by the summons or other originating document is one which by virtue of Regulation No. 1215/2012, Regulation No. 2201/2003, the 1968 Convention or the Lugano Convention, the Court has power to hear and determine, and - no proceedings between the parties concerning the same cause of action are pending between the parties in another Member State of the European Union or in a Contracting State of the Lugano Convention. 15. Save as otherwise provided in these Rules, every petition to the Court shall be presented by leaving it with the proper officer at the Central Office. Subject thereto, the foregoing provisions of this Order shall apply to a petition in the same manner as they apply to an originating summons, and references in this Order to “**originating summons**” and “**plaintiff**” shall be construed as including references to “**petition**” and “**petitioner**” respectively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''deponent'' mean in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A judge presiding over criminal cases in the Court.","A person making an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court, including those making a solemn affirmation or acknowledgment of a deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court.","A witness providing testimony under oath in a criminal trial.","An attorney representing parties in arbitration proceedings outside of the Court."],"justification":"“**deponent**” means a person making an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court, but includes reference to a person making a solemn affirmation or acknowledgment of a deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- reference to an affidavit includes reference to any affidavit, solemn affirmation or the acknowledgment of any deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**deponent**” means a person making an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court, but includes reference to a person making a solemn affirmation or acknowledgment of a deed or recognizance for use in civil proceedings in the Court; “**relevant document**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html), “**videoconference**”[1] includes any connection of two or more persons at different locations by means of information and communications technology or combination of such technologies which enables persons remote from one another both to see and hear and to be seen and be heard by one another in real time.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Who can administer oaths for affidavits in civil proceedings in the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Any person over the age of 18 with no criminal record","A retired judge who is not currently practicing law","A Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court or a practising solicitor.","A barrister who is not admitted to practice in the State"],"justification":"Subject to sub-rule (2), all affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court (which may be in the [Form 50.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b849640e-dfd9-4e8d-b505-99429c139026/Affidavit - general No. 50.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made before a Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court, or a practising solicitor (in the remainder of this sub-rule, the “officer”)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Making an affidavit* 2.[2] (1) Subject to sub-rule (2), all affidavits for use in civil proceedings in the Court (which may be in the [Form 50.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b849640e-dfd9-4e8d-b505-99429c139026/Affidavit - general No. 50.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule must be made before a Commissioner empowered to administer oaths for the High Court, or a practising solicitor (in the remainder of this sub-rule, the “officer”). (2) Where the person making an affidavit resides outside the State, or is for the time being outside the State, the affidavit may be made before any person authorised by law to administer oaths in the place where the person making the affidavit resides or is. (3) An affidavit sworn in the State may be sworn by the deponent- - (a) in the physical presence of the officer before whom it is to be sworn, or - where, for reasons stated briefly in the affidavit, it is not practicable for the deponent to attend in the physical presence of such officer, by videoconference with the participation of the deponent and the officer, subject to and in accordance with sub-rule (4). (4) Where an affidavit is sworn in the manner referred to in sub-rule the following conditions shall be complied with - - (a) the officer shall be provided in advance or at the videoconference with a copy (which may be in electronic form) of the affidavit, copies of any exhibits referred to in it and, in a case where rule 6(b)(iii) applies, a certified copy of the relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; - the officer shall be satisfied that the videoconference facility enables the deponent to see and hear the officer and to be seen and heard by the officer; - in a case to which rule 6(b)(ii) applies, the officer shall ensure that the requirement in the paragraph concerned for identification of the deponent has been met before the affidavit is sworn; - the officer shall satisfy himself that the appropriate sacred text for taking the oath is available to the deponent;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What information must the jurat of the affidavit include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The time the affidavit was made, the location where the affiant was, and the method by which the affidavit was notarized in person.","The year the affidavit was created, the city where the affiant is registered to vote, and the fact that the affidavit was witnessed through a live video call.","The date the affidavit was made, the place where the officer was, and the fact that the affidavit was sworn using a videoconference.","The date the affidavit was received, the address where the officer resides, and the fact that the affidavit was signed under penalty of perjury without any witness present."],"justification":"the jurat of the affidavit shall indicate the date on which the affidavit was made by the deponent, the place at which the officer was when taking the affidavit and the fact that the affidavit was sworn using a videoconference."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- during the videoconference and within sight and hearing of the officer, the deponent shall produce the original of any relevant document intended to be used to verify the deponent’s identity; shall identify each page of the affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it, shall sign or mark any and every exhibit, and shall sign and swear the affidavit; - the sworn affidavit and any and every exhibit referred to in it shall immediately following the videoconference be sent to the officer, for attestation by the officer; - the officer shall before attesting the affidavit and signing or marking any and every exhibit referred to in it, satisfy himself that the document (and each and any exhibit) is the same as that which had been identified to him during the videoconference and, where relevant, sign and append to the affidavit the certified copy of the relevant document used to verify the deponent’s identity, and - notwithstanding rule 6, the jurat of the affidavit shall indicate the date on which the affidavit was made by the deponent, the place at which the officer was when taking the affidavit and the fact that the affidavit was sworn using a videoconference.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person taking an affidavit certify in the jurat if they do not personally know the deponent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["That the deponent has provided sufficient identification documents to establish their identity.","That the deponent has sworn under penalty of perjury that they are who they claim to be.","That the deponent''s identity has been verified through a background check conducted by the affiant.","That the deponent has been identified by someone personally known to them, who certifies their knowledge of the deponent."],"justification":"that the deponent has been identified to him or her by some person personally known to him or her and named in the jurat who certifies his personal knowledge of the deponent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Attestation by person taking affidavit and jurat* 6. Every person taking an affidavit for use in civil proceedings in the Court: - (a) must express the date on which and the place at which he or she takes the affidavit; otherwise the affidavit must be taken not to be authentic and must not be filed without the permission of the Court; - must certify in the jurat either: - that he personally knows the deponent, or - that the deponent has been identified to him or her by some person personally known to him or her and named in the jurat who certifies his personal knowledge of the deponent, or - (iii) that the identity of the deponent has been established by him or her by reference to a relevant document containing a photograph of the deponent before the affidavit was taken, and in a case to which paragraph (iii) applies, must give particulars of the relevant document concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'What must the person taking an affidavit do if the deponent does not understand one of the official languages of the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Have the deponent sign a blank affidavit and fill in the details later with the assistance of an interpreter, without certifying understanding.","Allow the deponent to sign the affidavit in their native language without requiring any certification or interpretation process.","Ensure the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8, read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, and certify in the jurat that the deponent fully understood it and signed it in their presence.","Ensure the affidavit is translated into English and signed by the deponent without the need for certification."],"justification":"Where the deponent appears to the person taking an affidavit not to be capable of understanding one of the official languages of the State, the person taking the affidavit must: (a) ensure that the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8; and ensure that the affidavit is read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter in the presence of the person taking the affidavit, and that the deponent has fully understood it; and certify in the jurat that the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, that the deponent fully understood it and that the deponent signed the foreign language affidavit in his or her presence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Additional requirements for swearing and filing a foreign language affidavit* 9. (1) Where the deponent appears to the person taking an affidavit not to be capable of understanding one of the official languages of the State, the person taking the affidavit must: - (a) ensure that the affidavit is made as a foreign language affidavit in accordance with rule 8; and - ensure that the affidavit is read to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter in the presence of the person taking the affidavit, and that the deponent has fully understood it; and - certify in the jurat that the affidavit was read in his or her presence to the deponent by a suitably qualified interpreter, that the deponent fully understood it and that the deponent signed the foreign language affidavit in his or her presence. (2) Where a foreign language affidavit is to be filed in Court, in addition to the translator’s affidavit referred to in rule 8(3) an affidavit of the interpreter must be filed at the same time in which the interpreter sets out his qualifications as an interpreter, exhibits a copy of the foreign language affidavit and confirms that he or she read accurately to the deponent the contents of the foreign language affidavit. (3) Where the translator and interpreter are one and the same person, a single affidavit may be sworn by that person for the purposes of rule 8(3) and this rule. (4) No foreign language affidavit may be used in evidence in the absence of the affidavit referred to in rule 8(3), unless the Court is otherwise satisfied as to the evidence contained in the foreign language affidavit. (5)[5] Notwithstanding paragraph of sub-rule (1), where an affidavit to which this rule applies is intended to be made by videoconference in accordance with rule the affidavit concerned may be read to the deponent by videoconference during the videoconference at which the affidavit concerned is sworn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'How should alterations other than erasures be authenticated in an affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Through a digital timestamp added by the affidavit software.","By the signature of a notary public.","With a handwritten note from the witness attesting to the changes.","By the initials of the person taking the affidavit."],"justification":"the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Amendments* 11. An affidavit which has in either the body or the jurat any interlineation, alteration, or erasure, may not be filed, read, or made use of in any civil proceeding in the Court without the permission of the Court unless: - (a) the interlineation or alteration (other than by erasure) is authenticated by the initials of the person taking the affidavit; or - in the case of an erasure, the words or figures appearing at the time of taking the affidavit and erased are re-written and signed or initialled in the margin of the affidavit by the person taking it.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 50 - Affidavits In Civil Proceedings', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances may the Court order a party to bear the costs of an affidavit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["If the affidavit is prepared by a renowned legal expert","If the affidavit is submitted on high-quality paper","If the affidavit includes relevant photographs or diagrams","If the affidavit unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, argumentative matter, or is of unnecessary length."],"justification":"The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which: - (a) unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, or - which contains argumentative matter, or - which is of unnecessary length,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *17 Costs of affidavit* 17. The Court may order that a party must bear the costs of any affidavit which he or she has used which: - (a) unnecessarily contains matters of hearsay, or - which contains argumentative matter, or - which is of unnecessary length, regardless of the outcome of the hearing at which it is used.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order discussed in this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order 47 - Appeals Process","Order 63 - Legal Proceedings Initiation","Order 29 - Discovery And Evidence Gathering","Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments"],"justification":"# Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments - Court: District # **Order 51: Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What is required to execute a judgment after six years?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Permission of the Court.","Automatic execution without any additional requirements","Filing a new lawsuit","Payment of a fee to the court"],"justification":"but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Duration of judgments* 3. (1) Judgments remain in full force and effect for twelve years from the date on which they were given or made, but no judgment may be executed after six years from the date on which it was given or made without permission of the Court. (2) An application for permission to execute after six years must be made by notice of motion, which must be served on the person sought to be made liable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court do if it is satisfied that the applicant is entitled to execution?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court may issue a warrant of arrest for the defendant.","The court may dismiss the application for execution without any further action.","The court may make any appropriate order, amend the judgment to give effect to that order, and impose terms as to costs or otherwise as appear just.","The court may order a retrial of the case in question."],"justification":"If satisfied that the party applying under sub-rule (1) is entitled to execution, the Court may make any appropriate order and may make any amendment to a judgment required to give effect to that order and may impose such terms as to costs or otherwise as appear just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Change of parties* 4. (1) If, at any time during the period of twelve years for which a judgment remains in force, a change takes place, by death, assignment or otherwise, in the parties, a party may apply to the Court on notice served on the other party to have the judgment amended accordingly. (2) If satisfied that the party applying under sub-rule (1) is entitled to execution, the Court may make any appropriate order and may make any amendment to a judgment required to give effect to that order and may impose such terms as to costs or otherwise as appear just.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What rules, practices, and procedures of the Circuit Court apply to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The general administrative guidelines set forth by the local magistrate''s office for warrant executions.","The rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution, with necessary modifications.","The specific statutes of the Supreme Court that govern the issuance of warrants for property seizures.","The procedural codes established by the Federal Bureau of Investigation for the execution of all types of warrants."],"justification":"the rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution apply, with such modifications as are necessary, to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Application of certain rules, practice and procedure of Circuit Court* 7. Subject to this Order and except where otherwise expressly provided by these Rules, the rules, practice and procedure of the Circuit Court which apply to or are adopted by a County Registrar in the execution of warrants of execution apply, with such modifications as are necessary, to the execution of warrants to seize property and warrants of delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the surplus after selling seized goods?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The surplus is retained by the government to fund other law enforcement activities.","The surplus is distributed equally among the law enforcement officers involved in the seizure.","The surplus is used to cover any legal fees associated with the case.","The surplus after retaining the amount to be levied, all reasonable expenses actually incurred in auctioning the goods, and the expenses of taking and keeping the goods must be paid to the person from whom the goods were seized."],"justification":"Where goods are sold under sub-rule (1), the surplus, if any, after retaining: - (a) the amount to be levied; and - all reasonable expenses actually incurred in auctioning the goods; and - the expenses of taking and keeping the goods, must be paid to the person from whom the goods were seized."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Execution of warrants* 10. (1) Where a warrant is for the payment of money and goods are seized under the warrant the person to whom the warrant is addressed may sell the goods by auction within the period fixed by the warrant or, if no period is so fixed, within one month from the day on which the goods were seized, unless the sum for which the warrant was issued and the expenses of taking and keeping the goods are paid before the goods are sold. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period fixed by the warrant or provided by these Rules for sale by auction of goods seized under a warrant for a period of not more than one month from the day on which the period would otherwise expire and so on from time to time. (3) Where goods are sold under sub-rule (1), the surplus, if any, after retaining: - (a) the amount to be levied; and - all reasonable expenses actually incurred in auctioning the goods; and - the expenses of taking and keeping the goods, must be paid to the person from whom the goods were seized. (4) The person conducting an auction under this rule need not procure a licence to act as an auctioneer. (5) Where the person against whom a warrant under rule 2 is issued pays or tenders to the person responsible for the execution of the warrant the amount to be levied by the warrant, the person responsible for the execution of the warrant must refrain from executing the warrant. (6) When any money is levied or paid to a court messenger under any warrant, the court messenger must give a receipt for the money.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can a Clerk release a warrant to seize goods?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When the Court has ordered the seizure of goods due to criminal activity unrelated to debt, such as possession of illegal substances.","When the debtor fails to respond to a civil summons within 24 hours.","When the Clerk personally believes that the debtor is unable to pay and needs to have their goods seized.","When the Court has given judgment for a sum of money or made an order for the payment of a sum of money for costs, and the Act under which the judgment was given or order was made either specifies no method of enforcement or provides for enforcement by distress, and either the time for appealing has expired with no appeal brought, or an appeal has been dismissed and the Circuit Court has not issued execution."],"justification":"Where the Court has given judgment for a sum of money or made an order for the payment of a sum of money for costs, a Clerk may release a warrant to seize goods of the person against who the judgment or order has been made for the purpose of satisfying the judgment debt where: - (a) any Act under which the judgment was given or order was made either specifies no method of enforcement of the order or provides for enforcement by distress, and - either— - the time for appealing against the judgment or order has expired and no appeal has been brought, or - an appeal has been dismissed and the Circuit Court has not issued execution."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Warrant to seize goods* 11. (1) Where the Court has given judgment for a sum of money or made an order for the payment of a sum of money for costs, a Clerk may release a warrant to seize goods of the person against who the judgment or order has been made for the purpose of satisfying the judgment debt where: - (a) any Act under which the judgment was given or order was made either specifies no method of enforcement of the order or provides for enforcement by distress, and - either— - the time for appealing against the judgment or order has expired and no appeal has been brought, or - an appeal has been dismissed and the Circuit Court has not issued execution.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What must a warrant bear according to the rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The address of the property to be searched","The date of its issue","The signature of the issuing officer","The name of the defendant"],"justification":"A warrant referred to in this rule must bear the date of its issue."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Issue of a warrant* 12. (1) A warrant referred to in this rule is issued when the warrant is signed by the Judge and issued by the Clerk to the person requesting its issue. (2) A warrant referred to in this rule must bear the date of its issue.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court extend the validity of a warrant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No, the court cannot extend the validity of a warrant under any circumstances.","Yes, the court may extend the validity for up to one year from the day it would otherwise expire.","The court may extend the validity of a warrant indefinitely as long as there is probable cause.","The court can only extend the validity of a warrant if it expires within 30 days."],"justification":"the Court may from time to time extend the period of the validity of the warrant for the purpose of execution for a period of not more than one year from the day on which it would otherwise expire and so on from time to time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Duration of a warrant of execution* 13. (1) A warrant is valid for the purpose of execution for one year after the day it is issued. (2) Despite sub-rule (1), the Court may from time to time extend the period of the validity of the warrant for the purpose of execution for a period of not more than one year from the day on which it would otherwise expire and so on from time to time. (3) An extension under sub-rule (2) must not be made after the day of expiry of the warrant. (4) An application for an order under sub-rule (2) may be made without notice to any person. (5) A copy of an order under sub-rule (2) must be delivered to the County Registrar by the party obtaining the order. (6) The priority of a warrant in respect of which an extension under sub-rule (2) had been made must be determined by reference to the date on which the warrant was originally delivered to the person to whom it is directed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'When can a Clerk issue and sign a warrant of delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If a Clerk receives a verbal request from a judge to deliver goods","If an order is made by the Court for delivery of goods or for delivery of goods or recovery of their assessed value","If a Clerk determines that the goods are no longer in the possession of the defendant","If a customer requests the delivery of goods without any court order"],"justification":"If an order is made by the Court—(a) for delivery of goods; or(b) for delivery of goods or recovery of their assessed value—a Clerk may issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-35-District-Certified-Copies-Of-Orders-And-Of-Other-Documents) a warrant of delivery."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Warrant of delivery [3]* 14. (1) If an order is made by the Court— - (a) for delivery of goods; or - for delivery of goods or recovery of their assessed value— a Clerk may issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-35-District-Certified-Copies-Of-Orders-And-Of-Other-Documents) a warrant of delivery. (2) If the order of the Court is for the assessed value of goods only, the order may be enforced by the same means as any other order for the payment of money.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["INFRINGEMENTS FOR POSSESSION","WARRANTS FOR POSSESSION","INFRINGEMENTS AND LICENSES","INFRINGEMENTS AND WARRANTS"],"justification":"**4****-****WARRANTS FOR POSSESSION**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **4****-****WARRANTS FOR POSSESSION**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'What is the maximum period within which a Clerk can issue a warrant for possession after an order becomes enforceable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["One year","Three months","Nine months","Six months"],"justification":"at any time not exceeding six months after the date on which the order becomes enforceable"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Warrant for possession [4]* 15.(1) In this rule, “land” has the same meaning as in section 3 of the [Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html). (2) In any case in which the Court is empowered to make, and makes in any proceedings, an order which has the effect of- - (a) requiring a person to vacate, or deliver up possession of, any land; or - requiring a person to be put into possession of, any land, a Clerk may, subject to the provisions of this rule and to the terms of the order of the Court, issue and sign in accordance with [Order 35]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-35-District-Certified-Copies-Of-Orders-And-Of-Other-Documents) a warrant for possession of the land specified in the order, which may be in the [Form 51.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f24402e8-0ed6-4b19-bfcf-7eedc42a53ec/Warrant to Sheriff or County Registrar No. 51.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such modifications as are necessary, when the order is made, or at any time not exceeding six months after the date on which the order becomes enforceable. (3) After the expiration of six months from the date on which the order becomes enforceable, a warrant may only be issued on application to the Court by the claimant, or the successor to or assignee of the estate or interest of the claimant, by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the respondent. (4) A warrant for possession may not issue under this rule at any time when the order mentioned in sub-rule (2) has not taken effect in accordance with its terms or is stayed, whether by order of the Court or otherwise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51 - Execution And Enforcement Of Judgments', 'Court Rules', 'How can an application to stay execution of an order or to postpone the date of possession be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By filing a written objection with the clerk of the court within five business days of receiving the order.","By submitting an appeal to a higher court within 30 days of the order being issued.","By motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the other party or parties.","By requesting a review through the administrative office of the court without notice to the opposing party."],"justification":"An application to the Court to stay execution of an order mentioned in sub-rule (2) or to postpone the date of possession may be made by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the other party or parties to those proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) An application to the Court to stay execution of an order mentioned in sub-rule (2) or to postpone the date of possession may be made by motion in the proceedings in which the order was made, on notice to the other party or parties to those proceedings. In a case of urgency, however, the application may be made parte on the lodgment of the notice of motion with the Clerk and where the Court grants such application the Clerk shall forthwith notify the other party or parties to those proceedings accordingly. (6) A warrant for possession must be addressed for execution to the County Registrar or Sheriff for the county in which the land is situated. [1] Order 51 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 51, rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020 [3] Order 51, rule 14 replaced by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020 [4] Order 51, rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders","Order - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders","Order - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders","Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders"],"justification":"# Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders - Court: District # Order 51A:Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What section is titled ''DEFINITIONS''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Section 1","Section 3","Section 2","Section 4"],"justification":"**1 - DEFINITIONS**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1 - DEFINITIONS**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is an ''instalment order''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["a decree issued by a court mandating periodic payments for alimony or child support","an agreement between parties to extend the repayment period of a debt without court intervention","an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings","a legal document issued by a court ordering immediate full payment of all debts and costs"],"justification":"“**instalment order**” means an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order:- the “**1926 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html) (No. 18 of 1926); the “**1940 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 23 of 1940); the “**1986 Act**” means the [Courts (No. 2) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1986); the “**2009 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due; “**instalment order**” means an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings; “**judgment**” includes any order or decree of a competent court; “**return date**” means the date of the sitting of the Court at which the examination of the debtor is to take place or, as the case may be, at which an application to vary an instalment order is scheduled to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under which acts is enforcement carried out?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Enforcement of Court Orders Acts 1926 to 2009","The Consumer Protection Acts 1967 to 2003","The Taxpayer Relief Acts 1981 to 2006","The Environmental Protection Acts 1970 to 2015"],"justification":"The Enforcement of Court Orders Acts 1926 to 2009"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2 - ENFORCEMENT UNDER THE ENFORCEMENT OF COURT ORDERS ACTS 1926 TO 2009**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the return date must the summons be served on the debtor if it is served by registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["at least 7 days","at least 21 days","at least 14 days","at least 28 days"],"justification":"The summons must be served on the debtor in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days or, if service is by registered post, at least 21 days, before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Summons for attendance of debtor and statutory declaration* 3. (1) When a debt is due on foot of a judgment of a competent court and the creditor requires the attendance of the debtor before the Court for examination as to the debtor’s means under section 15 (as substituted by section 1(1) of the 1986 Act) of the 1926 Act, the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/29460aba-435b-452a-9c88-14168036a521/Summons for attendance of debtor under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.01.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate) required by section 15(2) of the 1926 Act. (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) The summons must be served on the debtor in a manner prescribed in [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days or, if service is by registered post, at least 21 days, before the return date. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7)[2] Where the debt to which the applications relates arises from - a judgment given in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015; - an authentic instrument formally drawn up or registered in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015, or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the statutory declaration include regarding the service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A signed statement confirming the issuance of the certificate without regard to the service requirements specified in Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation.","Proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 52 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation.","Confirmation that the certificate was reviewed by a legal advisor as per Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation.","Proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation."],"justification":"include proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (iii) a court settlement approved or concluded in legal proceedings instituted in a Member State of the European Union (other than the State) on or after 10 January 2015 which falls within the scope of the Jurisdiction Regulation (as defined in [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 1(1)), the statutory declaration by or on behalf of the creditor must also: - (a) exhibit the documents referred to in Article 42(1) or, as the case may be, Article 42(2) and, where required, Article 42(3) or Article 42(4) of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - include proof of service of the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53 of the Jurisdiction Regulation in the manner provided by Article 43 of the Jurisdiction Regulation, and - confirm whether or not the requirements of Article 43(2) (as to service of a translation of the judgment) apply and if so, that they have been complied with.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What does a summons under rule 3 require the debtor to do in addition to attending court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Complete and file a statement of means with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date.","Attend a mandatory credit counseling session organized by the court.","Submit a written apology to the creditor detailing the reasons for the debt.","Pay a specified sum of money to the creditor within one week of receiving the summons."],"justification":"A summons under rule 3, in addition to requiring the attendance of the debtor in Court on the return date for examination as to his or her means, also requires the debtor to complete and file with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date a statement of means ([Form 51A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c2615f2e-91f4-4c33-b865-6e70289549b7/Statement of means under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule attached to the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Statement of means* 4. (1) A summons under rule 3, in addition to requiring the attendance of the debtor in Court on the return date for examination as to his or her means, also requires the debtor to complete and file with the Clerk not less than one week before the return date a statement of means ([Form 51A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c2615f2e-91f4-4c33-b865-6e70289549b7/Statement of means under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule attached to the summons. (2) The creditor or creditor’s solicitor may, on payment of the prescribed fee, inspect and take or obtain copies of the statement of means at any time after it is lodged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the creditor or creditor''s solicitor produce at an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The debtor''s tax return for the last fiscal year, a letter from the creditor stating that the debt is valid, and a proof of service confirming the summons was delivered.","The judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, a certificate in Form 51A.04 setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place.","A copy of the debtor''s passport, a statement of account showing the debt, and a declaration from a witness confirming the debtor''s residence.","An affidavit from the creditor detailing the nature of the debt, a utility bill of the debtor as proof of residence, and a signed agreement between the creditor and debtor."],"justification":"At an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2) the creditor or creditor’s solicitor must produce to the Court: (a) the judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, a certificate in the [Form 51A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f5e9eb2-b30e-401d-80e4-661cf1d834a9/Certificate of amount due under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(6) No. 51A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 5 Creditor’s proofs 5. (1) At an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2) the creditor or creditor’s solicitor must produce to the Court: - (a) the judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, - a certificate in the [Form 51A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f5e9eb2-b30e-401d-80e4-661cf1d834a9/Certificate of amount due under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(6) No. 51A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and - evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place. (2) A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to instalments accruing after an instalment order ceases to be in force?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The instalments accruing after the order ceases are transferred to another active instalment order.","No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable.","All instalments accruing after the order ceases are still payable and recoverable as per the original agreement.","Instalments accruing after the order ceases must be paid double as a penalty for the cessation of the order."],"justification":"No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Instalment order* 6. (1) An instalment order may be served on the debtor in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (2) An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full. (3) No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued when applying to the Court to vary the terms of an instalment order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 51A.05","Form","Form","Form 49A.02"],"justification":"the [Form 51A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cffc020d-ed44-4481-ad36-72f1e5c6270e/Summons to vary an instalment order No. 51A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Variation of an instalment order* 7. (1) Where a person wishes to apply to the Court under section 5 of the 1940 Act to vary the terms of an instalment order, that person must apply to the Clerk for the issue of a summons in the [Form 51A.05](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cffc020d-ed44-4481-ad36-72f1e5c6270e/Summons to vary an instalment order No. 51A.05.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate. (2) The summons to vary must be served on the creditor or the debtor, as the case may be, in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (3) The original summons and a statutory declaration of service must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (4) The applicant must serve the order of the Court granting the application to vary on the other party in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (5) An order varying an instalment order does not operate to make the instalment order enforceable after the expiration of 12 years from the date of the relevant judgment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How must a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act be served on the debtor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By registered mail to the debtor''s last known address.","Personal service, unless the Court directs otherwise.","Publication in a local newspaper once a week for two consecutive weeks.","Mailed to the debtor''s attorney if they have one."],"justification":"A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Failure to comply with an instalment order* 8. (1) When a creditor wishes to apply for a summons under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act (as substituted by section 2 of the 2009 Act), the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2fc18a39-5b44-430b-82cd-f083e1a431d1/Summons on failure to comply with an instalment order No. 51A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and a statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate). (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise) at least 14 days before the return date of the summons. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7) An application for a direction under section of the 1940 Act that a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act be served on the debtor otherwise than by personal service may be made parte to the Court at any sitting of the Court. (8) Where such a direction is given, the summons may, notwithstanding sub-rule (2), be served in accordance with the direction. (9) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notice in writing under section 6(5) of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing of a summons may be handed by the Clerk to the debtor in Court or sent by ordinary post to the debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Court be satisfied about regarding the debtor''s failure to pay?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["That the failure to pay is due to mere inability to pay and that the debtor has sufficient funds in a bank account.","That the failure to pay is due to wilful refusal or culpable neglect and not mere inability to pay, and that the debtor has no goods available for execution.","That the failure to pay is due to temporary financial difficulties and that the debtor has assets worth more than the debt.","That the failure to pay is due to an honest mistake and that the debtor has already settled the debt through alternative means."],"justification":"Where the Court, being satisfied that the instalment order was duly served on the debtor and the debtor has failed to comply with the instalment order, is also satisfied, beyond reasonable doubt, on the evidence presented, that the creditor has established that - - (a) the failure to pay the sum in respect of which the debtor has made default is not due to the debtor’s mere inability to pay but is due to his or her wilful refusal or culpable neglect, and - the debtor has no goods which could be taken in execution under any process of the Court by which the judgment, order or decree for the debt was given,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(10) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notification under section of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing at which the debtor is required to attend must be by notice in writing served personally on the debtor. (11) A copy of a notice mentioned in sub-rule (10) and a statutory declaration of service of the notice must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the new date fixed for the hearing. (12) Where the Court, in accordance with section of the 1940 Act, requests the creditor and the debtor to seek resolution by mediation within such period as the Court may specify, the Court must adjourn the proceeding generally with liberty to re-enter it. (13) Where the creditor wishes to re-enter the proceeding, he or she must apply in writing to the Clerk for re-entry, certifying in that application that mediation has failed to achieve a resolution. (14) The Clerk must re-list the proceeding for hearing and must send notice of the re-listing to the debtor, to any solicitor who appeared for the debtor on the initial hearing of the summons, and to the creditor by ordinary post. (15) The creditor may effect further service of a copy of the notice on the debtor in accordance with sub-rule (2). (16) Where the Court, being satisfied that the instalment order was duly served on the debtor and the debtor has failed to comply with the instalment order, is also satisfied, beyond reasonable doubt, on the evidence presented, that the creditor has established that - - (a) the failure to pay the sum in respect of which the debtor has made default is not due to the debtor’s mere inability to pay but is due to his or her wilful refusal or culpable neglect, and - the debtor has no goods which could be taken in execution under any process of the Court by which the judgment, order or decree for the debt was given,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must a debtor do if they wish to apply to the Court under section 6(9) of the 1940 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Notify the creditor directly about the intention to apply","Apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter","Appeal to the High Court for a review of the case","Submit a written request to the local magistrate"],"justification":"he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'and the Court makes an order under section or section of the 1940 Act, that order must be in the [Form 51A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6f409-24ef-4b8a-9fee-14c16fcf8c60/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.07.docx/docx/1) or [51A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5eac4885-6df8-481d-af2e-e70a07de52f4/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate. (17) Where an order is made under section of the 1940 Act, any failure by the debtor to comply with a condition of postponement may be proved by statutory declaration of the creditor lodged with the Clerk, and a warrant may issue on lodgment of such proof but the Clerk may, in any case, re-enter the matter before the Court. (18) A warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment pursuant to section 6(7) of the 1940 Act must be in the [Form 51A.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4df60f3a-e472-4398-8147-b0e46f51d515/Warrant for arrest of debtor No. 51A.09.docx/docx/1) Schedule and may be added to the form of an order under section or section of the 1940 Act. (19) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(9) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (20) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must send notice of the re-listing to the creditor and to the debtor by ordinary post. (21) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(10) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (22) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must notify the creditor, the debtor and the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned of the re-listing of the matter by ordinary post and such other means as the Clerk considers appropriate. (23) No order under sub-rule (16) may be made against a debtor who is a member of the permanent Defence Forces or a reservist for the time being called out on permanent service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a notice of appeal is lodged before a warrant is issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The appeal will be dismissed automatically as soon as the warrant is issued.","The warrant must be issued immediately regardless of the pending appeal.","The court will ignore the notice of appeal and proceed with issuing the warrant.","The warrant must not be issued until the appeal is decided or the appellant fails to perform the recognisance conditions."],"justification":"the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 No warrant to issue, or warrant to be returned, where an appeal is lodged* 9. (1) Where: - (a) a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and - a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and - the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be. (2) Where a warrant to enforce the order has been issued but not executed when a notice of appeal is lodged, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that a notice of appeal has been lodged (and that a recognisance has been entered into, if that be the case); and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do if the amount due is paid?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Notify the local post office to hold the warrant for future use.","Send a copy of the payment receipt to all local businesses as proof of payment.","Notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána and request the warrant''s return for cancellation.","Inform the nearest hospital about the payment status to ensure patient care services continue."],"justification":"the Clerk must forthwith: (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made; and request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Clerk to secure return of warrant where amount due is paid to him or her* 10. Where a warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been issued but not executed and the amount of the arrears of instalments and costs specified in the order is paid to the Clerk, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that payment has been made; and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances must the Governor give notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the debtor fails to pay their taxes on time.","When the debtor is received in the prison by virtue of a warrant under rule 8.","When the debtor requests a formal meeting with the Governor.","When the debtor has filed for bankruptcy."],"justification":"The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Notice by Governor of prison to Clerk* 11. The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do after receiving payment from a debtor who is in custody?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Release the debtor from custody immediately upon receiving the payment.","Give a certificate of payment to the person making the payment and forward a similar certificate to the Governor of the prison and the creditor or creditor''s solicitor.","Notify the debtor''s family about the payment and keep a copy of the payment receipt.","Issue a new warrant for the debtor''s arrest due to overdue payments."],"justification":"the Clerk must: (a) give a certificate of payment to the person making the payment on behalf of the debtor; forthwith forward a similar certificate to the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned and to the creditor or creditor’s solicitor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Clerk to notify Governor when payment is received and debtor is in custody* 12. Where, subsequent to the arrest and imprisonment of a debtor under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act, the amount of the arrears of instalments and costs specified in the order for arrest and imprisonment is paid to the Clerk, the Clerk must: - (a) give a certificate of payment to the person making the payment on behalf of the debtor; - forthwith forward a similar certificate to the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned and to the creditor or creditor’s solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["INFRINGEMENTS","INFRINGEMENT ACTIONS","OTHER ENFORCEMENT","COMPLAINT PROCEDURES"],"justification":"**3 - OTHER ENFORCEMENT**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3 - OTHER ENFORCEMENT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What actions can the Court take if a company defaults on producing documents or things?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may order a named officer of the company to produce the documents or things and may also order the company to pay costs and expenses occasioned by the default.","The Court may issue a public apology from the company for failing to comply with the document production orders.","The Court may fine the entire company without specifying any individual responsible for the default.","The Court may extend the deadline for document production indefinitely."],"justification":"In the circumstances referred to in sub-rule (1), the Court may - - (a) make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing; and - order the company to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Attendance of company* 13. (1) This Rule applies where - - (a) the Court by witness summons or otherwise makes an order in any proceeding for the production by a company of any document or thing; and - after service of the order the company defaults in producing the document or thing in accordance with the order. (2) In the circumstances referred to in sub-rule (1), the Court may - - (a) make an order that a named officer of the company produce the document or thing; and - order the company to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the court take if an order requiring a person to perform an act is not complied with?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may direct that the act be done by a person appointed by the Court and order the person against whom the order has been made to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.","The court may imprison the person indefinitely until the act is performed.","The court may issue a warning and request compliance within a specified period without imposing additional penalties.","The court may impose a fine equivalent to the value of the act that was supposed to be performed."],"justification":"If an order that has been made against a person requires the person to do an act and the person does not do the act, the Court may - - (a) direct that the act be done by a person appointed by the Court; and - (a) order the person against whom the order has been made to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Substituted performance* 14. (1) If an order that has been made against a person requires the person to do an act and the person does not do the act, the Court may - - (a) direct that the act be done by a person appointed by the Court; and - (a) order the person against whom the order has been made to pay any costs and expenses occasioned by the default.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How can a non-party who obtains an order enforce it?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By enforcing it through social media and public pressure.","By requesting a new order from the court as if they were a party.","By transferring the enforcement to a third party unrelated to the case.","By the same means as if they were a party."],"justification":"A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *15 Enforcement by or against non-party* 15. (1) A person not being a party who obtains an order or in whose favour an order is made may enforce the order by the same means as if that person were a party. (2) If an order may be enforced against a person not a party, the order may be enforced against the person by the same means as if the person were a party. (3) If an order may be enforced against a company not a party, the processes of enforcement apply to an officer of the company as if the company were a party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a person fails to fulfill a condition attached to an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The person is taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order.","The person is given an extension to fulfill the conditions indefinitely.","The person is automatically granted the benefits of the order regardless of the conditions.","The person is required to fulfill double the conditions as compensation."],"justification":"A person entitled to an order subject to the fulfilment of a condition who fails to fulfil the condition must be taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Non-performance of condition* 16. A person entitled to an order subject to the fulfilment of a condition who fails to fulfil the condition must be taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order, and, unless the Court otherwise orders, any other person interested may take any steps which are warranted by the order or which might have been taken if the order had not been made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who can apply for an order aiding the enforcement of a warrant of execution?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A local mayor or other municipal official.","A private lawyer or other legal practitioner not specifically directed by the warrant.","A national parliamentarian or other federal representative.","A County Registrar or other person to whom a warrant of execution is directed."],"justification":"An application for an order under sub-rule (1) may be made by a County Registrar or other person to whom a warrant of execution is directed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Order in aid of enforcement* 17. (1) The Court may make any order that it thinks just in aid of the enforcement of a warrant of execution. (2) An application for an order under sub-rule (1) may be made by a County Registrar or other person to whom a warrant of execution is directed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What order''s provisions apply to warrants issued under Order 51A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order 26","Order 50","Order 39","Order 47"],"justification":"The provisions contained in [Order 26] ([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) (relating to warrants in criminal proceedings) apply to warrants issued under this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Provisions of Order 26 to apply* 18. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) (relating to warrants in criminal proceedings) apply to warrants issued under this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What practice and procedure must be followed for the registration of a judgment or order of the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The standard practice and procedure defined by the Ministry of Justice for the registration of all legal documents, regardless of the court","The practice and procedure in use in the District Courts in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court","The practice and procedure in use in the Supreme Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the Supreme Court","The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court"],"justification":"The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court applies to and must be followed in relation to the registration of a judgment or order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Registration of judgments of the Court* 19. (1) Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the [Courts Act 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/11/enacted/en/html)) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office. (2) The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court applies to and must be followed in relation to the registration of a judgment or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How can Forms in Schedule be adapted for PIAB orders?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Any Form in Schedule which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to dismiss.","Any Form in Schedule which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to appeal.","Any Form in Schedule which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to pay.","Any Form in Schedule which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to adjourn."],"justification":"Any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to pay."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Enforcement of PIAB orders to pay and judgments of courts* 20. (1) The provisions of these Rules which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, with any necessary modifications, to any order to pay issued by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board under section 38(1) of the [Personal Injuries Assessment Board Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/46/enacted/en/html). (2) Any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment may be adapted to refer to an order to pay. (3) The provisions of this Order which relate to the enforcement of any judgment of a court apply, where and to the extent so provided by these Rules, to a judgment or other instrument issued by a court in a Member State of the European Union other than the State. [1] Order 51A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 51A sub-rule (7) of rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 617 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/617/made/en/print?q 617 &years 2015), effective 30 December 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What must a notice of claim to goods taken in execution include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["It must be in writing, contain the full name and description of the claimant, and contain an address for service acceptance.","The notice can be submitted anonymously without providing any personal details.","It should include a detailed inventory of all personal possessions, unrelated to the seized goods.","It must be verbally communicated to the court within a week of the seizure of goods."],"justification":"be in writing ([Form 51B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/477f7eb6-abe4-4109-9051-dec5862ff7cf/Notice of claim to goods taken in execution No. 51B.01.docx/docx/1)Schedule contain the full name and description of the claimant; and contain an address at which service will be accepted by or on behalf of the claimant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Notice of claim to goods taken in execution* 1. A claim to or in respect of any goods or chattels not exceeding in value the monetary limit of the Court’s jurisdiction which have been taken in execution or intended execution by a County Registrar must: - (a) be in writing ([Form 51B.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/477f7eb6-abe4-4109-9051-dec5862ff7cf/Notice of claim to goods taken in execution No. 51B.01.docx/docx/1)Schedule - contain the full name and description of the claimant; and - contain an address at which service will be accepted by or on behalf of the claimant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'When should the County Registrar send the notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At the end of the month following the receipt of the claim.","After verifying the details of the claim with the court.","Immediately after receiving the claim.","Within one week of receiving the claim."],"justification":"the County Registrar must immediately send written notice of the claim"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 County Registrar’s notice to party claiming execution* 2. On receipt of a claim mentioned in rule 1, the County Registrar must immediately send written notice of the claim to the party claiming execution or to his or her solicitor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What must the notice given by the party claiming execution include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["whether they dispute or admit the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or request the County Registrar to withdraw from possession","whether they dispute or admit the validity of the court''s jurisdiction over the case","whether they dispute or admit the date of the execution order","whether they dispute or admit the amount owed in monetary claims"],"justification":"to the County Registrar of whether he or she disputes or admits the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or requests the County Registrar to withdraw from possession"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Notice of admission or denial of claim* 3. Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice (which may be in the [Form 51B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6878de80-1b71-42f1-a18b-92f033863f91/Notice of admission of title of claimant, or request to County Registrar to withdraw No. 51B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the County Registrar of whether he or she disputes or admits the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or requests the County Registrar to withdraw from possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What must the County Registrar do if the claimant does not admit their title or request withdrawal within two days?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Send a verbal warning to the claimant requiring them to deposit the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or the value of the seized goods or chattels within two days of the warning.","Send written notice to the claimant requiring them to deposit the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or the value of the seized goods or chattels within two days of the notice''s service.","Release the seized goods or chattels back to the claimant without any further action if they do not admit their title or request withdrawal within two days.","Notify the court to issue a new warrant of execution within two days of the claimant''s non-admission or failure to withdraw."],"justification":"the County Registrar must immediately send written notice to the claimant: - requiring him or her within two days of the service of that notice to deposit with the County Registrar the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, if the value of the goods or chattels seized is less than the amount set out in the warrant of execution, the value of the goods or chattels, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Deposit by claimant* 4. If within the period of two days mentioned in rule 3 the party claiming execution does not: - (a) admit the title of the claimant or - request the County Registrar to withdraw from possession, the County Registrar must immediately send written notice to the claimant: - requiring him or her within two days of the service of that notice to deposit with the County Registrar the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, if the value of the goods or chattels seized is less than the amount set out in the warrant of execution, the value of the goods or chattels, and - giving the claimant notice that in default of his or her making the deposit required, an application will be made, after service of an interpleader summons (which is a summons in civil proceedings), to the Court for an order for sale.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What must the County Registrar do when the claimant deposits the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The County Registrar must deposit the amount in the claimant''s bank account.","The County Registrar must transfer the warrant of execution to another county.","The County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels.","The County Registrar must keep the goods and chattels in storage indefinitely."],"justification":"the County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Procedure on deposit being made* 5. Where the claimant deposits with the County Registrar: - (a) the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, - if the value of the goods or chattels as determined by the County Registrar or by a valuer appointed by the County Registrar, being less than the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued, a sum equal to the value as so determined, the County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels and the sum deposited may be disposed of as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of application for the sale of goods and chattels seized be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form","Form 49.03","[Form Schedule","Schedule"],"justification":"must be in [Form 51B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7dd5304-f26b-4a2f-8c33-481b35567c49/Notice%20of%20motion%20on%20application%20to%20the%20Court%20for%20sale%20of%20chattels%20No.%2051B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Application for sale* 6. (1) Where the claimant does not make the deposit required under rule 4, the Court may, at any time after the service of an interpleader summons, on application made: - (a) by the execution creditor on notice to the claimant and to the County Registrar, or - by the County Registrar on notice to the parties, make an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized, subject to such conditions as to the giving of security by the execution creditor or otherwise as the Court thinks just. (2) The notice of application to the Court for an order for the sale of all or any of the goods and chattels seized must be in [Form 51B.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7dd5304-f26b-4a2f-8c33-481b35567c49/Notice of motion on application to the Court for sale of chattels No. 51B.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule and must be served two clear days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Who decides the costs of an application under Rule 6?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The local bar association determines the costs based on precedent.","The parties involved in the case decide the costs through mutual agreement.","The Court may provide for the costs on the hearing of the interpleader summons.","The government sets a fixed cost for all interpleader summons applications."],"justification":"The costs of any application under rule 6 may be provided for by the Court on the hearing of the interpleader summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Application may be heard outside of scheduled Court sittings* 7. (1) An application under rule 6 may be heard otherwise than at a scheduled sitting of the Court at any time and place within the appropriate Court district which the Judge deems suitable. (2) The costs of any application under rule 6 may be provided for by the Court on the hearing of the interpleader summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'How must an interpleader summons be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through publication in a national newspaper as per common law practices","In accordance with the rules specified in Order 39","In a manner provided by Order 41","By delivering it personally to the defendant''s residence"],"justification":"An interpleader summons must be served in a manner provided by [Order 41]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Service of interpleader summons* 9. (1) An interpleader summons ([Form 51B.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a4e02878-c4f6-4800-bde8-ac16ff23564a/Interpleader summons No. 51B.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule must be served on the claimant (or where the claim has been made by a solicitor for the claimant, on the claimant’s solicitor) and on the party claiming execution (or where the warrant of execution has been lodged with the County Registrar by a solicitor for the party claiming execution, on the party’s solicitor). (2) An interpleader summons must be served in a manner provided by [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Court determine on the hearing of the interpleader summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses, the amount of the costs and expenses, and by whom and to whom the costs and expenses are to be paid.","the validity of the contract between the parties and the terms under which it was breached","the eligibility of the parties to receive damages and the amount of the damages awarded","the determination of who is responsible for filing the lawsuit and the amount of legal fees associated with the filing"],"justification":"On the hearing of the interpleader summons the Court must determine: - (a) the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses; - the amount of the costs and expenses; and - by whom and to whom the costs and expenses are to be paid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Liability for costs* 10. (1) On the hearing of the interpleader summons the Court must determine: - (a) the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses; - the amount of the costs and expenses; and - by whom and to whom the costs and expenses are to be paid. (2) The scale of costs for tort cases in the Schedule of Costs is the appropriate scale for proceedings begun by interpleader summons. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order - European Enforcement Orders","Order - Pacific Rim Security Protocols","Order - North American Trade Agreements","Order - Asian Economic Cooperation"],"justification":"# Order - European Enforcement Orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - European Enforcement Orders - Court: District # **Order European Enforcement Orders******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''domestic judgment'' mean in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A ruling issued by the Court that pertains solely to procedural matters and does not involve any financial obligations.","Any decision by the Court regarding the interpretation of domestic law, irrespective of whether it involves monetary compensation.","An official statement by the Court concerning the enforcement of international treaties within domestic jurisdiction.","Any judgment or decree of the Court for the recovery of any sum of money, or any order (including an order made by consent) of the Court or dismiss by the Court requiring the payment of any sum of money, to which Regulation No. 805/2004 applies."],"justification":"“**domestic judgment**” means any judgment or decree of the Court for the recovery of any sum of money, or any order (including an order made by consent) of the Court or dismiss by the Court requiring the payment of any sum of money, to which [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) applies;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order:- “**domestic judgment**” means any judgment or decree of the Court for the recovery of any sum of money, or any order (including an order made by consent) of the Court or dismiss by the Court requiring the payment of any sum of money, to which [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) applies; “**Regulation No. 805/2004**” means [Regulation No 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 21 April 2004 creating a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims, 143/15 of 30 April 2004; “**Regulation No. 1869/2005**” means [Commission Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869) replacing the Annexes to Regulation No 805/2004 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 21 April 2004 creating a European Enforcement Order for uncontested claims, 300/6 of 16 November 2005; the “**2005 Regulations**” means the European Communities (European Enforcement Order) Regulations 2005 ([S.I. No. 648 of 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/648/made/en/print)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Which forms can be adapted to refer to a European Enforcement Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Forms in Schedule A containing references to contracts or agreements","Forms in Schedule containing references to judgments, orders, or decrees","Forms in Schedule containing references to applications or appeals","Forms in Schedule containing references to declarations or statements"],"justification":"In such a case, any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, order or decree may be adapted to refer to the European Enforcement Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 2 Provisions on enforcement to apply to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement certified as a European Enforcement Order in the Member State of origin. 2. (1) Subject to [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) and to the 2005 Regulations, the provisions of [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 1 to 12 inclusive, so far as they may be applied to a judgment of the High Court, may be applied to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order in the Member State of origin. (2) Any reference in [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 1 to 12 inclusive to a “**judgment**”, where the context so admits, includes a reference to a judgment, authentic instrument or court settlement which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order in a Member State of origin. In such a case, any Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, order or decree may be adapted to refer to the European Enforcement Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''debt'' include according to this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["any balance of a loan exceeding the amount originally due after partial repayment","any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due","any amount paid in excess of what was originally owed on the debt","any interest accrued before the initial payment was made on the debt"],"justification":"“**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### **1 Definitions** 1. In this Order:- the “**1926 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html) (No. 18 of 1926); the “**1940 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 23 of 1940); the “**1986 Act**” means the [Courts (No. 2) Act 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1986); the “**2009 Act**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**debt**” includes any balance of a debt remaining due after payment or recovery of part of the debt originally due; “**instalment order**” means an order of the Court under section 17 of the 1926 Act for the payment of debt and costs made in examination proceedings; “**judgment**” includes any order or decree of a competent court; “**return date**” means the date of the sitting of the Court at which the examination of the debtor is to take place or, as the case may be, at which an application to vary an instalment order is scheduled to be heard.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When must a copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule be given to the debtor or debtor''s solicitor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At the same time as the return date.","After the court has made its final decision.","Within seven days after the return date.","Before the return date."],"justification":"A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 5 Creditor’s proofs 5. (1) At an examination pursuant to a summons served under rule 3(2) the creditor or creditor’s solicitor must produce to the Court: - (a) the judgment on which the creditor relies or other evidence of the original debt due to the creditor under the judgment, - a certificate in the [Form 51A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f5e9eb2-b30e-401d-80e4-661cf1d834a9/Certificate of amount due under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(6) No. 51A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the creditor or creditor’s solicitor setting out the amount outstanding at the date of the certificate, and - evidence that the debtor is ordinarily resident in the Court area in which the examination is taking place. (2) A copy of the certificate referred to in sub-rule must be given to the debtor or debtor’s solicitor before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How long does an instalment order continue in force?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Until the expiration of 5 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full.","Until the expiration of 10 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, or until the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full, whichever is sooner.","Until the expiration of 12 months from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full.","Until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full."],"justification":"An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Instalment order* 6. (1) An instalment order may be served on the debtor in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State). (2) An instalment order continues in force until the expiration of 12 years from the date of the judgment to which it relates, unless the debt and costs payable have been duly paid in full. (3) No instalment which accrues due under an instalment order after the instalment order ceases to be in force is payable or recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must a creditor do when applying for a summons under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Proceed in accordance with this rule.","Provide proof of payment to the court.","Obtain a court order first.","Submit a written application to the debtor."],"justification":"the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Failure to comply with an instalment order* 8. (1) When a creditor wishes to apply for a summons under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act (as substituted by section 2 of the 2009 Act), the creditor may proceed in accordance with this rule. (2) The creditor or the creditor’s solicitor may lodge with the Clerk in duplicate for issue a summons in the [Form 51A.06](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2fc18a39-5b44-430b-82cd-f083e1a431d1/Summons on failure to comply with an instalment order No. 51A.06.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and a statutory declaration (in the [Form 51A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/444ee767-a474-453d-838b-166dcb78424b/Statutory declaration to accompany application for summons under Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1926, section 15(1) No. 51A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule modified as appropriate). (3) The Clerk must enter a return date on the summons and list the matter for hearing. (4) The creditor must serve the summons on the debtor. (5) A summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act must be served personally on the debtor (unless the Court directs service otherwise) at least 14 days before the return date of the summons. (6) The original of the summons, and a statutory declaration of service of the summons, must be filed with the Clerk at least four days before the return date. (7) An application for a direction under section of the 1940 Act that a summons issued under section 6(1) of the 1940 Act be served on the debtor otherwise than by personal service may be made parte to the Court at any sitting of the Court. (8) Where such a direction is given, the summons may, notwithstanding sub-rule (2), be served in accordance with the direction. (9) Unless otherwise directed by the Court, a notice in writing under section 6(5) of the 1940 Act to the debtor of a new date fixed for a hearing of a summons may be handed by the Clerk to the debtor in Court or sent by ordinary post to the debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an order under section or section of the 1940 Act take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 51A.06","Form","Schedule","[Form 51A.07] or [51A.08], Schedule"],"justification":"that order must be in the [Form 51A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6f409-24ef-4b8a-9fee-14c16fcf8c60/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.07.docx/docx/1) or [51A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5eac4885-6df8-481d-af2e-e70a07de52f4/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'and the Court makes an order under section or section of the 1940 Act, that order must be in the [Form 51A.07](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6f409-24ef-4b8a-9fee-14c16fcf8c60/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.07.docx/docx/1) or [51A.08](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5eac4885-6df8-481d-af2e-e70a07de52f4/Order for arrest and imprisonment - postponed conditionally No. 51A.08.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate. (17) Where an order is made under section of the 1940 Act, any failure by the debtor to comply with a condition of postponement may be proved by statutory declaration of the creditor lodged with the Clerk, and a warrant may issue on lodgment of such proof but the Clerk may, in any case, re-enter the matter before the Court. (18) A warrant to enforce an order for arrest and imprisonment pursuant to section 6(7) of the 1940 Act must be in the [Form 51A.09](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4df60f3a-e472-4398-8147-b0e46f51d515/Warrant for arrest of debtor No. 51A.09.docx/docx/1) Schedule and may be added to the form of an order under section or section of the 1940 Act. (19) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(9) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (20) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must send notice of the re-listing to the creditor and to the debtor by ordinary post. (21) Where a debtor wishes to apply to the Court under section 6(10) of the 1940 Act, he or she must apply to the Clerk for re-entry of the matter. (22) The Clerk must re-list the matter for hearing and must notify the creditor, the debtor and the Governor of the prison in which the debtor is imprisoned of the re-listing of the matter by ordinary post and such other means as the Clerk considers appropriate. (23) No order under sub-rule (16) may be made against a debtor who is a member of the permanent Defence Forces or a reservist for the time being called out on permanent service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What action should the Clerk take if a warrant has been issued but not executed when an appeal is lodged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Continue to execute the warrant as usual until further notice from the court.","Notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána and request the warrant''s return for cancellation.","Destroy the warrant immediately upon receipt of the appeal documents.","Notify the issuing judge that the warrant will no longer be required due to the appeal."],"justification":"notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that a notice of appeal has been lodged (and that a recognisance has been entered into, if that be the case); and request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 No warrant to issue, or warrant to be returned, where an appeal is lodged* 9. (1) Where: - (a) a notice of appeal against an order for arrest and imprisonment under section 6(7) of the 1940 Act has been lodged; and - a recognisance (if required) has been entered into; and - the warrant to enforce the order has not been issued, the warrant must not be issued until the appeal has been decided or the appellant has failed to perform the conditions of the recognisance, as the case may be. (2) Where a warrant to enforce the order has been issued but not executed when a notice of appeal is lodged, the Clerk must forthwith: - (a) notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to whom the warrant was addressed that a notice of appeal has been lodged (and that a recognisance has been entered into, if that be the case); and - request the Superintendent to return the warrant for cancellation by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Governor of a prison do upon receiving a debtor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Give notice in writing to the Clerk specified in the warrant.","Provide the debtor with a copy of the warrant.","Record the debtor''s arrival in the prison logbook.","Inform the local police department about the debtor''s arrival."],"justification":"The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Notice by Governor of prison to Clerk* 11. The Governor of a prison in which the debtor is imprisoned by virtue of a warrant under rule 8 must forthwith on the reception in the prison of the debtor give notice in writing of the reception of the debtor to the Clerk specified in the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What rights do interested parties have if the court does not intervene?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["They can only request the court to reconsider the order without taking any steps.","They may take any steps warranted by the order or steps that could have been taken if the order had not been made.","They may appeal to a higher court immediately regardless of the order.","They lose all rights and cannot take any further actions."],"justification":"unless the Court otherwise orders, any other person interested may take any steps which are warranted by the order or which might have been taken if the order had not been made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Non-performance of condition* 16. A person entitled to an order subject to the fulfilment of a condition who fails to fulfil the condition must be taken to have abandoned the benefit of the order, and, unless the Court otherwise orders, any other person interested may take any steps which are warranted by the order or which might have been taken if the order had not been made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51A - Enforcement Of Judgments And Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What can be registered in the Central Office of the High Court under section 25 of the Courts Act 1981?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any verbal agreement made between parties during a court hearing","Legal briefs submitted by attorneys before the start of a trial","The names of witnesses who are expected to testify in future cases","Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money"],"justification":"Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the [Courts Act 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/11/enacted/en/html)) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Registration of judgments of the Court* 19. (1) Any judgment or order for costs issued or made by the Court providing for the payment of a sum of money may be registered (under section 25 of the [Courts Act 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/11/enacted/en/html)) in the Central Office of the High Court in the like manner as a judgment of the High Court may be registered in that Office. (2) The practice and procedure in use in the Central Office of the High Court in relation to the registration of judgments of the High Court applies to and must be followed in relation to the registration of a judgment or order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Within how many days must a party claiming execution give notice to the County Registrar?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["five days","three days","one day","two days"],"justification":"Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Notice of admission or denial of claim* 3. Within two days after receiving the notice mentioned in rule 2, the party claiming execution must give written notice (which may be in the [Form 51B.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6878de80-1b71-42f1-a18b-92f033863f91/Notice of admission of title of claimant, or request to County Registrar to withdraw No. 51B.02.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the County Registrar of whether he or she disputes or admits the title of the claimant to the goods or chattels or requests the County Registrar to withdraw from possession.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the sum deposited after it is withdrawn from possession?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The sum deposited is returned to the depositor immediately upon withdrawal.","The sum deposited remains in the possession of the bank until the depositor provides further instructions.","The sum deposited is automatically transferred to a government account for safekeeping.","The sum deposited may be disposed of as the Court directs."],"justification":"the sum deposited may be disposed of as the Court directs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Procedure on deposit being made* 5. Where the claimant deposits with the County Registrar: - (a) the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued or, - if the value of the goods or chattels as determined by the County Registrar or by a valuer appointed by the County Registrar, being less than the amount for which the warrant of execution was issued, a sum equal to the value as so determined, the County Registrar must withdraw from the possession of the goods and chattels and the sum deposited may be disposed of as the Court directs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application under Rule 6 be heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Exclusively on the premises of the court where the case was originally filed.","At any time and place within the appropriate Court district deemed suitable by the Judge.","At a designated time and place set by the Court''s administrative office, regardless of the Judge''s preference.","Only during regular business hours in the main courthouse of the district."],"justification":"An application under rule 6 may be heard otherwise than at a scheduled sitting of the Court at any time and place within the appropriate Court district which the Judge deems suitable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Application may be heard outside of scheduled Court sittings* 7. (1) An application under rule 6 may be heard otherwise than at a scheduled sitting of the Court at any time and place within the appropriate Court district which the Judge deems suitable. (2) The costs of any application under rule 6 may be provided for by the Court on the hearing of the interpleader summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51B - Interpleader', 'Court Rules', 'What is the appropriate scale for proceedings begun by interpleader summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The fixed scale of costs applicable to all civil cases under the Civil Procedure Rules.","The indemnity scale of costs as set out in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","The scale of costs for contract disputes in the Schedule of Costs.","The scale of costs for tort cases in the Schedule of Costs."],"justification":"The scale of costs for tort cases in the Schedule of Costs is the appropriate scale for proceedings begun by interpleader summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Liability for costs* 10. (1) On the hearing of the interpleader summons the Court must determine: - (a) the liability of the parties to pay costs and expenses; - the amount of the costs and expenses; and - by whom and to whom the costs and expenses are to be paid. (2) The scale of costs for tort cases in the Schedule of Costs is the appropriate scale for proceedings begun by interpleader summons. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme Court","District Court","High Court","County Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - European Enforcement Orders - Court: District # **Order European Enforcement Orders******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application to certify a domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within one year after the domestic judgment is given or made, in a separate proceeding.","parte to the Court at the hearing where the domestic judgment is given or made, or on another occasion if not made at the initial hearing.","Only after a formal request from the defendant has been received.","During the appeal process of the domestic judgment."],"justification":"may be made parte to the Court at the hearing at which that domestic judgment is given or made; or - if not made at that hearing, must be made parte to the Court on another occasion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Application to certify a judgment as a European Enforcement Order* 4. Where a domestic judgment has been given or made, an application to certify that domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order: - (a) may be made parte to the Court at the hearing at which that domestic judgment is given or made; or - if not made at that hearing, must be made parte to the Court on another occasion.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a certificate given on foot of an application pursuant to Article 6(1) of Regulation No. 805/2004 be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Form in Annex to Regulation No 1869/2005.","The standard format prescribed by the European Commission''s guidelines for all administrative procedures.","The Form in Annex to Regulation No 1869/2005.","The Form in Annex to Regulation No 805/2004."],"justification":"A certificate given on foot of an application pursuant to Article 6(1) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Application to certify to be supported by affidavit* 5. (1) An application to certify a domestic judgment as a European Enforcement Order must, unless the Court otherwise directs or permits, be supported by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The affidavit may be in the [Form No. 51C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6cd051d8-d303-4ba4-8ad4-7753b0ffe6c3/Affidavit to certify a European Enforcement Order No. 51C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with such modifications as are necessary. (2) A certificate given on foot of an application pursuant to Article 6(1) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who can make an application for a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Any legal entity except natural persons","Any party","Only the judge who issued the judgment","The court clerk exclusively"],"justification":"by any party"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Application to certify lack or limitation of enforceability* 6. (1) Where a domestic judgment, which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order, has ceased to be enforceable or its enforceability is or has been suspended or limited, an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of that domestic judgment may be made parte to the Court by any party. (2) A certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment given on foot of an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application for a replacement certificate be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An application can be made parte to the Court only after the judgment or order has been finalized and published.","An application can be made parte to the Sheriff''s office by any party at the hearing where the judgment or order is given.","An application can be made parte to the Court by any party at the hearing where the judgment or order is given.","An application can be made parte to the Court only if all parties agree and sign a consent form prior to the hearing."],"justification":"an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate may be made parte to the Court by any party at the hearing at which that judgment is given or order is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Application for replacement certificate* 7. (1) Where the Court gives a judgment or makes an order following a challenge to a domestic judgment, which has been certified as a European Enforcement Order, an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate may be made parte to the Court by any party at the hearing at which that judgment is given or order is made. (2) A replacement certificate given on foot of an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) must be in the Form in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How must an application under Article 6(2) or 6(3) of Regulation No. 805/2004 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By submitting an email to the designated official listed in Annex A of the regulation.","Via completion of Form No. 44.02, Schedule without any modifications.","By notice of motion in Form No. 44.01, Schedule with necessary modifications.","Through a verbal request during a formal meeting with the regulatory body as outlined in Article 7 of the same regulation."],"justification":"Unless made in accordance with rule 6(1) or, as the case may be, rule 7(1), an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment or an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate must be made by notice of motion in the [Form No. 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice%20of%20motion%20-%20general%20No.%2044.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 8 Application by motion following hearing where decision made 8. (1) Unless made in accordance with rule 6(1) or, as the case may be, rule 7(1), an application under Article 6(2) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a certificate indicating the lack or limitation of enforceability of a domestic judgment or an application under Article 6(3) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the issue of a replacement certificate must be made by notice of motion in the [Form No. 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) A copy of the notice of motion must be served on the judgment creditor or judgment debtor (as the case may be). (3) The application must be supported, where necessary, by an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (4) There must be exhibited to any affidavit in support of any such application a completed draft of the form of European Enforcement Order certificate sought, and the contents of the draft certificate must be verified in the affidavit. (5) A copy of the notice of motion and a copy of any affidavit intended to be used in the application must be served on the judgment creditor or judgment debtor (as the case may be) in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) not later than seven days before the return date of the application. (6) The original of any affidavit intended to be used in the application must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must the moving party do before making an application under Article 10(1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Submit a written affidavit detailing their case to the European Court of Justice","File a petition with the national court where the case is being heard","Complete the Form of application in Annex to Regulation No 1869/2005 and file it with the Clerk","Provide a verbal request to the Secretary-General of the European Commission"],"justification":"Before making an application under Article 10(1), the moving party must complete the Form of application in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869), and must file the completed form of application with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Application for rectification or withdrawal of a European Enforcement Order certificate* 9. (1) An application under Article 10(1) of [Regulation No. 805/2004](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2004/805/oj/eng) for the rectification or the withdrawal of a European Enforcement Order certificate must be made to the Court which certified the domestic judgment concerned as a European Enforcement Order. (2) Before making an application under Article 10(1), the moving party must complete the Form of application in Annex to [Regulation No 1869/2005](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri celex:32005R1869), and must file the completed form of application with the Clerk. (3) The moving party must serve a copy of the completed form of application on the judgment creditor or (as the case may be) the judgment debtor, together with a copy of any affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party and intended to be used in the application. (4) Where rectification is sought, there must be exhibited to any affidavit in support of the application a copy of the form of European Enforcement Order certificate previously issued, marked with the rectification sought, and the contents of the marked certificate must be verified in the grounding affidavit. (5) Where, on an application under this rule, it is determined that the European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned ought to be rectified or withdrawn, the party on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order must within seven days of that determination lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned with the Clerk. (6) In the case of rectification, the party who applied for rectification must lodge a draft rectified certificate with the Clerk. (7) The Clerk must, in a case of rectification, produce the rectified certificate to the Judge to be re-signed. (8) Subject to any direction made by the Court in that regard, the Clerk must issue the rectified certificate to the party on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the person fails to lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate within seven days of a determination?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The European Enforcement Order becomes null and void after thirty days if not rectified.","The Clerk must provide the applicant with a certificate signed by the Judge certifying the fact that the European Enforcement Order certificate has been rectified or withdrawn.","The person is required to pay a fine equivalent to the amount specified in the European Enforcement Order.","The court automatically lifts the European Enforcement Order without any further action."],"justification":"Where the person on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order fails in accordance with sub-rule (5) to lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned with the Clerk within seven days of a determination, the Clerk must, at the request of the applicant, provide the applicant with a certificate signed by the Judge certifying the fact that the European Enforcement Order certificate has been rectified or (as the case may be) withdrawn."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(9) In the case of withdrawal, the Clerk must produce the certificate to the Judge to be cancelled. (10) Where the person on whose application the domestic judgment concerned was certified as a European Enforcement Order fails in accordance with sub-rule (5) to lodge the original European Enforcement Order certificate in respect of the domestic judgment concerned with the Clerk within seven days of a determination, the Clerk must, at the request of the applicant, provide the applicant with a certificate signed by the Judge certifying the fact that the European Enforcement Order certificate has been rectified or (as the case may be) withdrawn.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who may issue a duplicate certificate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Mayor","The Clerk","The Treasurer","The Judge"],"justification":"The Clerk may at the request of a party, present for signature by the Judge and issue to the party a duplicate of any certificate referred to in this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Duplicate certificate* 10. (1) The Clerk may at the request of a party, present for signature by the Judge and issue to the party a duplicate of any certificate referred to in this Order. (2) Any duplicate certificate must be marked as a duplicate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 51C - European Enforcement Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When is it unnecessary for the applicant to lodge a draft certificate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the applicant needs to provide additional information after the initial submission.","When a draft certificate has already been exhibited to an affidavit.","When the applicant wishes to expedite the process without a draft certificate.","When the applicant has not yet submitted any documents."],"justification":"where a draft certificate has not already been exhibited to an affidavit supporting the application for the certificate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Lodgment of draft certificate* 11. The applicant must in every case lodge with the Clerk a draft of the completed form of the certificate for which application has been made, where a draft certificate has not already been exhibited to an affidavit supporting the application for the certificate. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''EAPO Regulation'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Regulation No. 655/2013 of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 2014","Regulation No. 655/2014 of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 2015","Regulation No. 655/2014 of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 2014","Regulation No. 555/2014 of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 2014"],"justification":"“**EAPO Regulation**” means [Regulation No. 655/2014](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/655/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 189/59 of 27 June 2014);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Preliminary and general 1. In this Order:- “**2016 Regulations**” means the European Union (European Account Preservation Order) Regulations 2016 ([S.I. 645 of 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/645/made/en/print)); “**EAPO Regulation**” means [Regulation No. 655/2014](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/655/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and the Council of 15 May 189/59 of 27 June 2014); “**competent authority**” means the Minister for Justice and Equality; “**creditor**” and “**debtor**” each has the same meaning as in the EAPO Regulation; “**Implementing Regulation**” means Commission Implementing [Regulation 2016/1823](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg_impl/2016/1823/oj/eng) of 10 October 2016 establishing the forms referred to in [Regulation No. 655/2014](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/655/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council establishing a European Account Preservation Order procedure to facilitate cross-border debt recovery in civil and commercial matters of 19 October 2016); “**information authority**” means the Minister for Justice and Equality; “**judgment**” has the same meaning as in the 2016 Regulations; “**Member State**” means a member state of the European Union but does not include Denmark or the United Kingdom; “**Member State of enforcement**” means the Member State in which the bank account to be preserved is maintained; “**Preservation Order**” has the same meaning as in the EAPO Regulation. 2. (1) All notifications by the Clerk to the creditor required under this Order or in accordance with Regulation 5 of the 2016 Regulations may be by telephone (if subsequently confirmed in writing by electronic mail, facsimile or letter sent by ordinary prepaid post) or by electronic mail or by such other means as the Clerk considers sufficient. (2) All notifications or requests by the Clerk to the information authority required under this Order or in accordance with the 2016 Regulations may be by electronic mail or by such other means as the Clerk shall agree with the information authority. (3) A notice required under Regulation 10(2) of the 2016 Regulations to be given by the Clerk to the Property Registration Authority shall be given by the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Titles of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'How is a notice required under Regulation 10(4) of the 2016 Regulations given?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By the transmission by the Company Secretary to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court via email.","By the transmission by the Secretary of State to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by registered post.","By the publication of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court in a national newspaper.","By the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post."],"justification":"By the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) A notice required under Regulation 10(4) of the 2016 Regulations to be given by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies shall be given by the transmission by the Clerk to the Registrar of Companies of a certified copy of the relevant order of the Court by ordinary prepaid post. (5) A decision referred to in Article 10.2 or, as the case may be, Article 36.5 of the EAPO Regulation shall be transmitted to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement, in the form set out in Annex III or, as the case may be, Annex VIII to the Implementing Regulation by the transmission by the Clerk to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement of a certified copy of the relevant decision by electronic mail, facsimile or such other means as the Clerk shall agree with the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application for a Preservation Order be made when Article 5(a) of the EAPO Regulation applies?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By posting the completed application form to the court’s postal address along with a cover letter explaining the urgency of the matter.","By submitting the application form via email to the court''s official email address.","By delivering the completed application form to any judge of the court during normal business hours.","By lodging with the Clerk the completed application form in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation, which shall be treated as a motion parte in the intended action."],"justification":"by the lodgment with the Clerk of the completed application in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation which shall be treated as a motion parte* in the intended action;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Application to the Court for a Preservation Order 3. (1) An application to the Court by a creditor for a Preservation Order shall be made: - (a) in the case of an application to which Article 5(a) of the EAPO Regulation applies, by the lodgment with the Clerk of the completed application in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation which shall be treated as a motion parte* in the intended action; - in the case of an application to which Article of the EAPO Regulation applies, by the lodgment with the Clerk of the completed application in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation, which shall be treated as a motion*ex parte* in the action, which may be lodged on or after the delivery of judgment by the Court. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall be grounded upon the verification by the applicant of the completed application form in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation and any evidence submitted with that application. (3) The creditor shall lodge with the application a draft of the Preservation Order in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation with Part A completed in the terms sought. (4) The creditor shall, where: - (a) he has obtained an equivalent national order against the same debtor to secure the same claim during the proceedings for the issuing of a Preservation Order, file an affidavit without delay setting out the terms of the equivalent national order against the debtor which has been obtained and, exhibiting a copy of that order and a certified translation thereof into Irish or English, and providing details of any subsequent execution of the national order granted; - he has made any application for an equivalent national order which has been rejected as inadmissible or unfounded, file an affidavit without delay providing particulars of the same.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the court finds the application is incomplete?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court may extend the deadline for filing the application indefinitely.","The court may fix the time within which and the means by which the creditor may complete or rectify the application and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly.","The court may impose a fine on the creditor for submitting an incomplete application.","The court may dismiss the case immediately without providing any opportunity for the creditor to rectify the application."],"justification":"where the Court considers in accordance with Article 17.3 of the EAPO Regulation that the application is incomplete, may fix the time within which and the means by which the creditor may complete or rectify the application and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. (1) Having considered the application, the Court, in accordance with the time limits set out in Article 18 of the EAPO Regulation: - (a) in a case to which Article 12.1 of the EAPO Regulation applies, unless, in accordance with Article 12.1 of the EAPO Regulation, it considers that the provision of security is inappropriate in the circumstances of the case and dispenses with such requirement, or in a case to which Article 12.2 of the EAPO Regulation applies, where it considers it necessary and appropriate in the circumstances of the case, shall fix the amount of security required and form or forms of security acceptable; - where the Court considers in accordance with Article 9.1 of the EAPO Regulation that the evidence provided is insufficient, may direct the delivery of further documentary evidence verified by affidavit or, subject to Article 9.2 of the EAPO Regulation, oral evidence and the nature of the evidence which the Court requires for the purpose of its determining the application, and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly; - where the Court considers in accordance with Article 17.3 of the EAPO Regulation that the application is incomplete, may fix the time within which and the means by which the creditor may complete or rectify the application and direct the Clerk to notify the creditor accordingly; - in a case to which Article 14.3 of the EAPO Regulation applies, may direct the Clerk to transmit a request for information to the information authority; - in every case, may give such directions and make such orders for the conduct of the proceedings on the application as appear convenient for the determination of the proceedings consistently with the requirements of the EAPO Regulation and in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings, and - shall determine the application and order accordingly. (2) The Clerk shall notify the creditor of all directions as to the amount and form of security required in respect of a Preservation Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Who is responsible for notifying the creditor about the Court''s decision on the application for a Preservation Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The judge","The debtor","The Clerk","The creditor"],"justification":"The Court’s decision on the application for a Preservation Order and, where appropriate, the date by which any appeal may be made against the decision, shall be notified to the creditor by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) The Court’s decision on the application for a Preservation Order and, where appropriate, the date by which any appeal may be made against the decision, shall be notified to the creditor by the Clerk. (4) Where security is required, the creditor shall lodge proof of entry into the security with the Clerk. (5) Where the Court makes a Preservation Order, the order shall, following the lodgment of proof of entry into any security required, issue to the creditor in the form in Annex to the Implementing Regulation. (6) The creditor shall be the person responsible in accordance with Article 23.3 of the EAPO Regulation for the transmission of Part A of the Preservation Order to the competent authority of the Member State of enforcement. (7) The creditor shall be the person responsible in accordance with Article 28.3 of the EAPO Regulation for the transmission of the documents referred to in Article 28.1 of the EAPO Regulation to the competent authority of the Member State in which the debtor is domiciled.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Court does not receive proof of the initiation of proceedings within the time period referred to in Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Court shall extend the Preservation Order automatically by six months.","The Court shall revoke the Preservation Order and shall issue an order of revocation in the form in Annex III to the Implementing Regulation.","The Court shall issue a warning to the parties involved and grant an additional 30-day extension.","The Court shall ignore the absence of proof and continue with the proceedings as if the initiation had been properly documented."],"justification":"the Court shall revoke the Preservation Order and shall issue an order of revocation in the form in Annex III to the Implementing Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## III. Issue of proceedings on the substance of the claim 5. (1) In the case of an application to which Article 5(a) of the EAPO Regulation applies, the creditor shall deliver to the Clerk within the time prescribed by Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation a copy of the originating claim notice in the proceedings on the substance of the matter issued by the Clerk. (2) An application for an extension of time in accordance with Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation shall be by motion on notice in the intended action, which need not be grounded upon an affidavit. 6. Where evidence of the initiation of proceedings on the substance of the matter has not been delivered to the Clerk within the time prescribed by Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation and no extension of time has been permitted, the application shall be listed before the Court and, if the Court has not received proof of the initiation of proceedings within the time period referred to in Article 10.1 of the EAPO Regulation, the Court shall revoke the Preservation Order and shall issue an order of revocation in the form in Annex III to the Implementing Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'What form should every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It should be in the form set out in Annex VIII to the Implementing Regulation and be accompanied by an unsworn declaration from the moving party.","It should be in the form set out in Annex VII to the Implementing Regulation and be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.","It should be in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation and be based on a written testimony provided by the moving party''s legal representative.","It should be in the form set out in Annex to the Implementing Regulation and be supported by a notarized statement from the opposing party."],"justification":"Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall: - (a) be in the form set out in Annex VII to the Implementing Regulation and - be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party, which may be endorsed upon the completed application form, or if not so endorsed, which shall exhibit and verify the completed application form and shall exhibit and verify each other document relied upon in the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Subsequent proceedings 7. (1) Subject to the EAPO Regulation and the 2016 Regulations, any of the following applications to the Court by a creditor or debtor shall be made: - (a) where there are no proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of the EAPO Regulation as between the creditor and the debtor, or - where there are proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of motion in the proceedings: - any application by a debtor pursuant to Regulation 8 of the 2016 regulations and Article 33 of the EAPO Regulation; - any application by a debtor pursuant to Regulation 9 of the 2016 regulations and Article 34 of the EAPO Regulation; - (iii) any application by a debtor or a creditor pursuant to Regulation 9 of the 2016 regulations and Article 35 of the EAPO Regulation. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall: - (a) be in the form set out in Annex VII to the Implementing Regulation and - be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party, which may be endorsed upon the completed application form, or if not so endorsed, which shall exhibit and verify the completed application form and shall exhibit and verify each other document relied upon in the application. 8. (1) Subject to the EAPO Regulation and the 2016 Regulations, any of the following applications to the Court shall be made: - (a) where there are no proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of application entitled in the matter of the EAPO Regulation as between the creditor and the debtor, or - where there are proceedings in being before the Court concerning either the substance of the matter or the Preservation Order, by notice of motion in the proceedings:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'What types of applications are covered under rule 7 or rule 8?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Applications by government entities only.","Applications solely by creditors.","Applications solely by debtors.","Applications by creditors, debtors, third parties, and any other application for relief."],"justification":"- any application by a creditor or debtor pursuant to Article 31 of the EAPO Regulation; - any application by a debtor pursuant to Article 38 of the EAPO Regulation; - (iii) any application by a third party pursuant to Article 39(3) of the EAPO Regulation; - any other application for relief pursuant to the 2016 Regulations, the EAPO Regulation or this Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- any application by a creditor or debtor pursuant to Article 31 of the EAPO Regulation; - any application by a debtor pursuant to Article 38 of the EAPO Regulation; - (iii) any application by a third party pursuant to Article 39(3) of the EAPO Regulation; - any other application for relief pursuant to the 2016 Regulations, the EAPO Regulation or this Order. (2) Every application made in accordance with sub-rule (1) shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 9. (1) Every person served with notice of an application made under rule 7 or rule 8 shall be at liberty to deliver a replying affidavit. (2) On the return date of a notice of application or notice of motion under rule 7 or rule 8 (or on any adjournment from such date), the Court shall give directions and make orders for the conduct of the proceedings on the application as appear convenient for the determination of the application consistently with the EAPO Regulation in a manner which is just, expeditious and likely to minimise the costs of those proceedings which, where appropriate, may include: - (a) directions as to the service of notice of the application on any other person, including mode of service and the time allowed for such service (and the Court may for that purpose adjourn the hearing of the notice of motion or further hearing of such application to a date specified); - directions as to the filing and delivery of any further affidavits by any party or parties; - orders fixing time limits.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 52 - European Account Preservation Order', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions do the enforcement provisions for interim and interlocutory orders apply to a Preservation Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Where the order is issued by a magistrate only","Where the context so admits or requires.","Upon the request of any party involved in the case","When the Preservation Order is related to criminal matters exclusively"],"justification":"where the context so admits or requires, apply with any necessary amendments to the enforcement of such a Preservation Order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Miscellaneous 10. Subject to the EAPO Regulation, the provisions of these Rules, insofar as they apply to interim and interlocutory orders of the Court, shall apply to a Preservation Order issued in accordance with the EAPO Regulation by a court of a Member State other than the State, and the provisions of these Rules applicable to the enforcement of interim and interlocutory orders of the Court, shall, where the context so admits or requires, apply with any necessary amendments to the enforcement of such a Preservation Order. [1] Order 52 inserted by [S.I. 405 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/405/made/en/print?q 405&years 2017), effective 2 October 2017'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 53 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Supreme Court","District Court","County Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 53 - Costs - Court: District # **Order 53: Costs******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Who decides whether to grant or withhold costs in civil proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The parties involved, in their discretion.","The jury, in its discretion.","The Court, in its discretion.","The legal representative, in their discretion."],"justification":"the granting or withholding of the costs of any party to civil proceedings or other proceedings in the Court in which by law the Court may award costs are in the discretion of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *1 Costs in general to be in the discretion of Court* 1.[2] (1) Save as otherwise provided by statute or by these Rules, the granting or withholding of the costs of any party to civil proceedings or other proceedings in the Court in which by law the Court may award costs are in the discretion of the Court. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), the Court - in considering the awarding of the costs in proceedings in which the parties have been invited by the Court to consider mediation as a means of attempting to resolve the dispute the subject of the proceedings in accordance with section 16 (1) of the [Mediation Act 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/27/enacted/en/html) , may, where it considers it just, have regard to the matters set out in section 21 of that Act, - in considering the awarding of the costs in proceedings may, where it considers it just, have regard to the refusal or failure without good reason of any party to participate in another ADR process referred to in [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution), rule 1, where an order has been made in the proceedings under [Order 49B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49B-District-Mediation-And-Other-Alternative-Dispute-Resolution), rule 7'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''actual and necessary outlay'' include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Revenue generated from sales of goods and services","Miscellaneous outlays such as postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries","Capital expenditures on purchasing equipment and property","Salaries and wages paid to employees"],"justification":"\"actual and necessary outlay\" must include a sum for miscellaneous outlays set out under the heading \"Schedule of Outlays\" in the Schedule of Costs to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *2 Scales of costs* 2. (1) Save as otherwise provided, the costs specified in each scale in the Schedule of Costs are the only lawful costs. (2) The Court may, where appropriate in the special circumstances of a case, to be specified by the Court, award an amount for costs and/or counsel’s fees in excess of the amount provided in the Schedule of Costs. (3) The costs in the Schedule of Costs are in every instance exclusive of and in addition to any sum allowed as recovery of value-added tax and all actual and necessary outlay as is allowed. (4) The Schedule of Costs must be revised no less frequently than once every three years. (5) In any case where the Court is of the opinion that there is no appropriate scale of costs provided, it may measure the costs. (6) In this rule: “**actual and necessary outlay**” must include a sum for miscellaneous outlays set out under the heading “**Schedule of Outlays**” in the Schedule of Costs to include postage, photocopying, registered post, fax and sundries and the Schedule of Costs must also be read accordingly.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What must a party have available in court when applying for costs other than those in the Schedule of Costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Information or document which establishes the special circumstances in the case","A standard affidavit form without any specific details","A detailed financial report of the winning party","A list of all parties involved in the case"],"justification":"that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes the special circumstances in the case which to support such an application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *3 Information and documents in support of application for costs* 3. (1) Where a party intends to apply for costs otherwise than in accordance with the Schedule of Costs, that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes the special circumstances in the case which to support such an application. (2) Where a party applies for an item of cost not provided for in the Schedule of Costs to be allowed, that party must have available in Court any information or document which establishes that the item of cost was necessary or reasonable to be incurred, and documents vouching the cost (if already incurred or paid) or providing an estimate of such cost. (3) Where a party applies for the costs of a civil proceeding, that party must have available in Court information or documents sufficient to confirm the particular pre-hearing steps taken or applications made in the proceeding (including particulars, discovery, applications for judgment on affidavit or judgment in default and any case management hearing) so as to enable the proper amount of costs to be determined.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Who has the discretion to allow or refuse witness expenses?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Witness","The Court","The Prosecution","The Jury"],"justification":"The Court has discretion to allow or to refuse to allow the expenses (or any part thereof) of any witness (including a claimant or respondent)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *4 Witnesses’ expenses* 4. The Court has discretion to allow or to refuse to allow the expenses (or any part thereof) of any witness (including a claimant or respondent) and where allowed, the amount of such expenses (or part thereof) may be measured by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What scale of costs applies when a claimant is successful and the respondent is not professionally represented?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The appropriate scale for undefended cases, unless the court directs otherwise.","The punitive scale intended for cases where the respondent engages in misconduct","The standard scale applicable to all professionally represented respondents","The reduced scale applied exclusively to cases involving professional representation on both sides"],"justification":"the costs must be in the appropriate scale for undefended cases, unless the Court, on application made to it at the hearing, directs that the scale for defended cases is to apply."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *6 Where respondent not professionally represented* 6. Where the claimant is successful and the respondent has not been professionally represented at the hearing, the costs must be in the appropriate scale for undefended cases, unless the Court, on application made to it at the hearing, directs that the scale for defended cases is to apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can the court make a separate order for the payment of adjournment costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If the adjournment is requested by the judge themselves.","If the court deems it reasonable, it can make a separate order for the payment of adjournment costs.","If the parties involved agree to share all costs equally, regardless of the reason for the adjournment.","If the adjournment is due to unforeseen circumstances beyond the control of both parties."],"justification":"may if it thinks it reasonable to do so, make a separate order for their payment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *7 Costs of adjournment* 7. The Court may allow the costs and expenses of any adjournment of the hearing or further hearing of any civil proceedings and may order that such costs be added to or deducted from the costs allowed to either party on the final determination of the proceedings, or may if it thinks it reasonable to do so, make a separate order for their payment.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Court do when civil proceedings are brought in an area where it has no jurisdiction?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court must continue the proceedings until a ruling is made on the merits of the case.","The Court must transfer the proceedings to a court with jurisdiction.","The Court must issue a warning to the parties involved and allow them to modify their claims to fall within its jurisdiction.","The Court must order the proceedings to be struck out as soon as the lack of jurisdiction is apparent."],"justification":"the Court must, as soon as such want of jurisdiction becomes apparent, order the proceedings to be struck out."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *8 Power to strike out with costs claims where no jurisdiction* 8. (1) Where civil proceedings are brought in the Court or in a Court district or Court area which the Court has no jurisdiction to hear and determine, the Court must, as soon as such want of jurisdiction becomes apparent, order the proceedings to be struck out. (2) Where the court strikes out proceedings in accordance with sub-rule (1), it may, if it thinks proper, make an order awarding the respondent such costs as the Court could have awarded if it had jurisdiction to try and determine the proceedings and either the claimant did not appear or appeared and failed to prove his or her claim. Note: See [Courts of Justice Act 1936](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1936/act/48/enacted/en/html) (No. 48 of 1936), section 60'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do regarding costs in relation to a specific question or part of a civil proceeding?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may make an order for costs in relation to a particular question in or a particular part of a civil proceeding.","The Court can only determine costs at the conclusion of the entire civil proceeding, not in relation to specific questions or parts.","The Court is required to equally divide the costs among all parties involved in a civil proceeding regardless of the outcome.","The Court may not consider costs in relation to any specific question or part of a civil proceeding."],"justification":"The Court may make an order for costs in relation to a particular question in or a particular part of a civil proceeding."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *9 Costs of question or part of proceeding* 9. (1) The Court may make an order for costs in relation to a particular question in or a particular part of a civil proceeding. (2) If the Court makes an order under sub-rule (1), the Court must by order fix the amount of the total costs of the proceeding which is attributable to the particular question in or the particular part of the proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances is a party required to pay costs when applying for an extension or abridgement of time?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Whenever the application is made without providing sufficient notice","Unless the Court otherwise orders","If the application is made within the original time limit","When the opposing party consents to the extension or abridgement"],"justification":"unless the Court otherwise orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *10 Extension or abridgement of time* 10. If a party applies for an extension or abridgement of any time fixed by these Rules or by any order fixing, extending or abridging time, that party must, unless the Court otherwise orders, pay the costs of and occasioned by the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Does sub-rule (1) apply to small claims proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Yes, sub-rule (1) applies to all types of legal proceedings including small claims.","Sub-rule (1) partially applies to small claims proceedings, but only in specific circumstances.","No, sub-rule (1) does not apply to small claims proceedings.","Sub-rule (1) applies exclusively to small claims proceedings."],"justification":"Sub-rule (1) does not apply to small claims proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *11 Discontinuance or withdrawal* 11. (1) Unless the Court otherwise orders, a party who discontinues or withdraws part of a proceeding, counterclaim or claim by third party notice must pay the costs of the party to whom the discontinuance or withdrawal relates to the time of the discontinuance or withdrawal. (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply to small claims proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a lodgment or tender offer is served and not accepted when a final order is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A new tender offer must be issued immediately by the party serving the original offer.","The offer becomes null and void without any further action required.","The parties involved must renegotiate the terms of the offer.","Liability for costs must be determined in accordance with Order 45."],"justification":"liability for costs must be determined in accordance with [Order 45]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *12 Lodgment or tender offer* 12. If a lodgment or tender offer is served and the lodgment or tender offer has not been accepted at the time a final order is made on the claim that relates to the lodgment, tender offer or offer of compromise, liability for costs must be determined in accordance with [Order 45]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45-District-Lodgments-And-Tenders-In-Lieu-Of-Lodgment).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What applies when counsel is allowed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The scales of counsel’s fees in the Schedule of Costs","The fixed rate of compensation for legal representation","The predetermined budget for litigation expenses","The statutory limit on attorney''s honorarium"],"justification":"the scales of counsel’s fees in the Schedule of Costs apply"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *13 Scale fees* 13. Where counsel is allowed, the scales of counsel’s fees in the Schedule of Costs apply, provided that in any proceedings not covered by these scales the fees must be determined by the Court having regard to the scales and to the amount involved in the case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if there is no specific provision in the Schedule of Costs for a proceeding or matter?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The parties must negotiate a new schedule of costs on their own.","The Court may direct that a scale of costs specified by the Court applies.","The costs are automatically set to zero as no specific provision exists.","The court will defer to the standard industry rates for similar proceedings."],"justification":"in a proceeding or matter for which no provision has been specifically made in the Schedule of Costs, the Court may direct that a scale of costs specified by the Court applies;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *14 Application of scales* 14. (1) In fixing costs for work done in a civil proceeding the appropriate scales must be determined as follows— - (a) as between party and party, the amount recovered or the value of the property in dispute regulates the scale of the claimant''s costs, and the amount sought to be recovered or the value of the property in dispute regulates the scale of the respondent''s costs; and - as between solicitor and client, unless the Court otherwise orders, the amount sued for, or the value of the property in dispute, regulates the scale without reference to the result; - where a counterclaim is made the scale on which the costs of the parties are to be fixed or taxed must be determined as follows— - if the claimant is successful on both claim and counterclaim, by the amount which the claimant recovers on the claim, unless the amount of the respondent''s counterclaim is the larger, in which case the costs incurred subsequently to the delivery of the counterclaim must be determined by the amount of that counterclaim; - if the respondent is successful on both claim and counterclaim, by the amount which the respondent recovers on the counterclaim, or the amount of the claimant''s claim, whichever is the larger; - (iii) if both parties are successful, by the amounts which they recover on their respective claims; and if both claims fail, by the amount claimed by the opposite party; - in a proceeding or matter for which no provision has been specifically made in the Schedule of Costs, the Court may direct that a scale of costs specified by the Court applies; - despite anything in these Rules, if in a proceeding or matter the Court considers that the application of the rules in this Order which determine that a particular scale of costs applies would be inappropriate or unjust, the Court may, either at the hearing, or within a reasonable time after the hearing, fix the costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the amount recovered'' include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The value of any non-monetary relief awarded to the claimant, such as an injunction.","The total expenses incurred by the defendant during the legal proceedings.","The costs associated with court fees and legal representation of both parties.","The amount of the order in the claimant''s favour including any amount for interest or damages in the nature of interest, and any interest or damages in respect of the amount awarded by the Court under any enactment."],"justification":"the amount of the order in the claimant''s favour including any amount for interest or damages in the nature of interest; and any interest or damages in respect of the amount awarded by the Court under any enactment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) For the purposes of sub-rule (1)(a) the amount recovered is— - (a) the amount of the order in the claimant''s favour including any amount for interest or damages in the nature of interest; and - any interest or damages in respect of the amount awarded by the Court under any enactment— but does not include any amount recovered by or awarded to the claimant for interest or damages in the nature of interest relating to the period after the day the payment into Court was made or the offer of compromise was served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a claimant fails to pay costs ordered by the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The case will be transferred to a different jurisdiction for retrial.","The proceeding may be stayed or dismissed.","The claimant will automatically receive a higher court award.","The claimant will be required to attend a mandatory mediation session."],"justification":"if that party is the claimant, that the proceeding be stayed or dismissed;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *16 Time for costs order and payment* 16. (1) The Court may in any proceeding exercise its power and discretion as to costs at any stage of the proceeding or after the conclusion of the proceeding. (2) Costs which a party is required to pay under any of these Rules or an order of the Court must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be paid forthwith. (3) If the Court makes an interlocutory order for costs, the Court may then or thereafter order that if the party liable to pay the costs fails to do so— - (a) if that party is the claimant, that the proceeding be stayed or dismissed; - if that party is a respondent, that the respondent''s defence is to be struck out. (4) In sub-rule (3)— “r**espondent**” includes any person against whom a claim is made in a proceeding; “**claimant**” includes any person who makes a claim in a proceeding.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to a proceeding that is or stands dismissed by or under an order of the Court or these Rules?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It is taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed without any costs.","It is taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed with costs, unless the Court otherwise orders.","It is considered to be a proceeding that is indefinitely postponed.","The proceeding is automatically refiled with the same conditions."],"justification":"A proceeding that is or stands dismissed by or under an order of the Court or these Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed with costs."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *17 Proceeding or counterclaim dismissed* 17. (1) A proceeding that is or stands dismissed by or under an order of the Court or these Rules must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be taken to be a proceeding that is dismissed with costs. (2) Sub-rule (1), with any necessary modification, applies to a counterclaim and to a claim by third party notice as if the counterclaim or third party claim were a claim notice.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Who bears the costs of an amendment to a pleading?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The costs are borne by the losing party regardless of the amendment.","The parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders.","The costs are covered by the court''s budget when an amendment is made.","The costs are always borne by the party requesting the amendment."],"justification":"the costs of and occasioned by the amendment and the costs of any application for permission to make the amendment are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *18 Amendment* 18. If a pleading is amended (whether with or without permission) the costs of and occasioned by the amendment and the costs of any application for permission to make the amendment are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a party disputes a fact under Order Rule 3 and the fact is later proven?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The party must pay the costs of proof.","The case is dismissed due to disputed facts.","The party will receive a warning instead of paying costs.","The opposing party must pay the costs of proof."],"justification":"that party must pay the costs of proof, unless the Court otherwise orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *19 Non-admission of fact or document* 19. If a party serves a notice - - (a) under [Order 45D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45D-District-Admissions), rule 3, disputing a fact, and afterwards that fact is proved in the proceeding; - under [Order 45D]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-45D-District-Admissions), rule 5, disputing the authenticity of a document, and afterwards the authenticity of that document is proved in the proceeding that party must pay the costs of proof, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if costs are reserved by the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The reserved costs are entirely covered by the government, regardless of the Court''s further orders.","The reserved costs are considered as a fixed amount set by law, unaffected by the Court''s discretion.","The reserved costs are automatically awarded to the winning party without any further consideration by the Court.","The reserved costs are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders."],"justification":"the reserved costs are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *20 Costs reserved* 20. If by order of the Court the costs of any interlocutory or other application, or of any step in a proceeding, are reserved, the reserved costs are the parties'' costs in the proceeding, unless the Court otherwise orders.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can a trustee or mortgagee not receive costs from the fund or mortgaged property?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If the trustee or mortgagee has already received payment in full.","If the Court otherwise orders.","If the beneficiary of the trust objects to the payment.","If the mortgaged property is exempted by law from such deductions."],"justification":"unless the Court otherwise orders"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *21 Trustee or mortgagee* 21. A party who sues or is sued as trustee or mortgagee must, unless the Court otherwise orders, be entitled to the costs of the proceeding out of the fund held by the trustee or out of the mortgaged property in so far as the costs are not paid by any other person.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What is the amount sued for in such proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The initial deposit made under the agreement regardless of whether it was paid or not","The amount of the instalments due and unpaid under the agreement at the date of commencement of the proceedings","The total amount of all instalments due and unpaid under the agreement, including those that become due after the date of commencement of the proceedings","The amount of any future instalments that might become due if the agreement is extended beyond its original terms"],"justification":"the amount of the instalments due and unpaid under the agreement at the date of commencement of the proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *22 Costs in hire purchase claims* 22. Proceedings by the owner of a chattel against the hirer of the chattel under a hire-purchase agreement for the recovery or return of the chattel must, for the purpose of the measurement of the costs, be deemed to be an action in contract in which the amount sued for is the amount of the instalments due and unpaid under the agreement at the date of commencement of the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What scale are costs awarded on in claims for wrongful detention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The criminal scale","The tort scale","The punitive damages scale","The contract scale"],"justification":"the costs awarded must be on the tort scale according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *23 Costs in claims for wrongful detention* 23. In claims for wrongful detention brought by virtue of section 33(3) of the [Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/39/enacted/en/html), the costs awarded must be on the tort scale according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What scales of costs apply to proceedings involving the Attorney General or a Minister?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The criminal procedure scales of costs apply.","The scales of costs in the Schedule of Costs apply.","The Uniform Civil Procedure Rules scale of costs applies.","The domestic relations scale of costs applies."],"justification":"The scales of costs in the Schedule of Costs apply to proceedings to which the Attorney General or any Minister of the Government or any Minister of State or any Government Department is a party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *24 Costs in claims to which the Attorney General or a Minister is a party* 24. The scales of costs in the Schedule of Costs apply to proceedings to which the Attorney General or any Minister of the Government or any Minister of State or any Government Department is a party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What must solicitors'' costs be in consent proceedings related to section of the Courts Act 1991 and Order 40, rule 7?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["in accordance with the provisions of item No. 10 in the Schedule of Costs","in accordance with the provisions of item No. 5 in the Schedule of Costs","in accordance with the provisions of item No. 12 in the Schedule of Costs","in accordance with the provisions of item No. 8 in the Schedule of Costs"],"justification":"must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 10 in the Schedule of Costs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *25 Costs in consent proceedings* 25. Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in consent proceedings to which section of the [Courts Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/20/enacted/en/html) and [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 7 relate, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 10 in the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What must solicitors'' costs be in civil proceedings remitted or transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["uniformly set at a fixed rate regardless of the case complexity or duration","in accordance with the provisions of item No. 5 in the Schedule of Costs","in accordance with the provisions of item No. 11 in the Schedule of Costs","as determined by the discretion of the presiding judge without reference to the Schedule of Costs"],"justification":"must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 11 in the Schedule of Costs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *26 Costs in proceedings transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court* 26. Solicitors’ costs, where allowed, in civil proceedings remitted or transferred from the High Court or the Circuit Court and to which [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 8 relates, must be in accordance with the provisions of item No. 11 in the Schedule of Costs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What must be added to the costs and counsel''s fees awarded in a civil proceeding?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Any sum payable by way of value-added tax on the costs if it is not otherwise recoverable.","Any sum payable by way of corporate tax on the costs if it is not otherwise recoverable.","Any sum payable by way of sales tax on the costs if it is not otherwise recoverable.","Any sum payable by way of income tax on the costs if it is not otherwise recoverable."],"justification":"There must be added to the costs and, where relevant, counsel’s fees, awarded in any civil proceeding any sum payable by way of value-added tax on the costs by the party to whom they are awarded where, and only where, that party establishes that the sum payable by way of value-added tax is not otherwise recoverable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *27 Value Added Tax* 27. There must be added to the costs and, where relevant, counsel’s fees, awarded in any civil proceeding any sum payable by way of value-added tax on the costs by the party to whom they are awarded where, and only where, that party establishes that the sum payable by way of value-added tax is not otherwise recoverable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Court''s Fees","Client''s Fees","Counsel''s Fees","Legal Aid Services"],"justification":"**3****-****COUNSEL''S FEES**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3****-****COUNSEL''S FEES**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'In what type of civil proceedings is a fee for counsel not included if the amount recovered or claimed does not exceed €2,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Actions involving intellectual property disputes where the amount does not exceed €2,000","Actions in contract, breach of contract, tort, or claims for damages unconnected with contract","Actions related to family law where the amount claimed does not exceed €2,000","Actions concerning real estate transactions where the amount recovered does not exceed €2,000"],"justification":"in any action in contract, breach of contract, tort or in claims for damages unconnected with contract, where the amount recovered by the claimant or, where the claim was dismissed, the amount claimed against the respondent does not exceed €2,000"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *28 Not allowed where sum does not exceed €2,000* 28. (1) Subject to rule 2(2), in any award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court a fee for counsel may not be included - - (a) in any action in contract, breach of contract, tort or in claims for damages unconnected with contract, where the amount recovered by the claimant or, where the claim was dismissed, the amount claimed against the respondent does not exceed €2,000, and - in any landlord and tenant proceedings for overholding or non-payment of rent, where the annual rent does not exceed €2,000.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'When can a fee for counsel be included in the award of costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the party requesting the fee is a corporation.","If the counsel provided services pro bono (without charge).","Only if the Court certifies that the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned.","Whenever the counsel has been involved in the case, regardless of necessity."],"justification":"a fee for counsel may not be included unless the Court certifies that, in its opinion, the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Court to certify for counsel* 29. In the award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply, a fee for counsel may not be included unless the Court certifies that, in its opinion, the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition is a separate counsel''s fee not allowed in the party''s costs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["When the barrister is employed on a full-time or exclusive basis by the party''s solicitor or the party."],"justification":"Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 No separate counsel’s fee for barrister employed on a full-time basis* 30. Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee. [1] Order 53 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 53 rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 53A refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Criminal Prosecution Standards","Small Claims Procedure","Civil Appeals Process","Bankruptcy Filing Procedure"],"justification":"# Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure - Court: District # Order 53A: Small Claims Procedure **[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''business'' mean in the context of Order 53A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A group of people gathered together for recreational activities such as sports or hobbies","A natural or legal person who only engages in personal transactions unrelated to any commercial activity","An individual who solely provides volunteer services without any form of compensation or exchange","A natural or legal person (including a company, partnership or natural person trading as a sole trader) who supplies, sells or purchases goods or services in the ordinary course of a business"],"justification":"“**business**” means a natural or legal person (including a company, partnership or natural person trading as a sole trader) who supplies, sells or purchases goods or services in the ordinary course of a business;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order- “**business**” means a natural or legal person (including a company, partnership or natural person trading as a sole trader) who supplies, sells or purchases goods or services in the ordinary course of a business; “**business small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order by a business purchaser against a business vendor in relation to a contract in respect of any goods or service purchased, but excluding any claim— - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, or - for debt or liquidated damages, provided that in every such case the amount of the claim does not exceed the sum of €2,000; “**consumer**” means a purchaser of goods or a service of a type ordinarily supplied for private use or consumption, where the purchaser does not make the contract in the course of a business and the vendor does make the contract in the course of a business; “**Consumer Credit Regulations**” means the European Communities (Consumer Credit Agreements) Regulations 2010 ([S.I. 281 of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/281)); “**consumer small claim**” means a civil proceeding instituted under this Order (1) in relation to a consumer contract, by the consumer against the vendor in respect of any goods or service purchased, which is not a claim - - (a) arising from an agreement to which the [Consumer Credit Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/24/enacted/en/html) applies or to which the Consumer Credit Regulations apply, or - arising from an alleged breach of a leasing agreement, (2) in relation to a tort, by the claimant (not being a body corporate) against the respondent in respect of minor damage caused to property belonging to the claimant but excluding personal injuries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Who is referred to as ''the claimant'' in this context?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The person intending to begin civil proceedings in the District Court for a small claim","The defendant in a criminal case","The judge presiding over a small claims trial","The witness providing testimony in a civil dispute"],"justification":"the person so intending (in this Order called “**t****he claimant**”)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Application to begin small claim proceedings* 2. Whenever it is intended to begin civil proceedings in the District Court and the claim to which the proceedings relate is a small claim as defined in this Order, the person so intending (in this Order called “**t****he claimant**”) may, instead of issuing a claim notice, apply to the appropriate Small Claims Registrar to have the claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure, and the proceedings may then be commenced and dealt with in accordance with the provisions of this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application for a small claims procedure be made in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form 53A.01"],"justification":"Form 53A.01"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Filing application* 3. An application to which rule 2 relates must be in writing, which may be in electronic form, in the [Form 53A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/88869131-d146-4c43-8b9b-e75e7cc7423f/Small Claims Procedure - Application to Small Claims Registrar No. 53A.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule The application, when completed, must be filed with the Small Claims Registrar together with any supporting documents required and the appropriate fee. The claimant may call to the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What information must the Small Claims Registrar record for each application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The claimant''s social security number, the respondent''s date of birth, the application fee amount, and the claimant''s bank account details.","The name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent, the date of the application, the nature of the claim, and any other relevant details.","The email addresses of both parties, the date of birth of the respondent, the type of legal representation for both parties, and the claimant''s tax identification number.","The names and contact numbers of both parties, the date of birth of the claimant, the estimated value of the claim, and the claimant''s employment status."],"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Recording of application* 4. The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details. The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a claim does not meet the criteria for the Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Small Claims Registrar informs the defendant and refunds the fee.","The claim is automatically escalated to the High Court without further notice.","The Small Claims Registrar dismisses the claim and does not refund any fees.","The Small Claims Registrar informs the claimant and refunds the fee."],"justification":"Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and must refund the fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Rejection or acceptance of application* 5. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and must refund the fee. (2) If the Small Claims Registrar considers the claim to be appropriate to the Small Claims Procedure, he or she must serve by registered post (or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) on the respondent a Notice of Claim in the [Form 53A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bfcc43c-8d9a-4307-8e92-90fa1b8d239c/Small Claims Procedure - Notice of claim against Respondent No. 53A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (containing also Forms [53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) and [53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule together with a copy of the Notice of Claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the respondent''s agreement to pay is conditional?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Small Claims Registrar must increase the payment amount to cover the conditions.","The Small Claims Registrar must inform the respondent that their agreement is invalid.","The Small Claims Registrar must reject the case immediately.","The Small Claims Registrar must inform the claimant and seek their agreement to comply with the respondent''s requirement."],"justification":"If the respondent''s agreement to pay is conditional, (e.g. on condition that goods are returned by the claimant), the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and seek his agreement to comply with the respondent''s requirement."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Admission of small claim by respondent* 6. (1) If the respondent admits the claim made against him and - (a) agrees to pay the amount claimed, or - consents to judgment being given against him, or - wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, he must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Acceptance of Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. On receipt of such Notice the Registrar must inform the claimant accordingly. (2) Where the respondent agrees to pay the amount claimed, he or she may forward to the Small Claims Registrar, together with [Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule payment by cheque, postal order(s) or money order(s), made payable to the claimant, for the full amount claimed. The Small Claims Registrar must transmit any such payment to the claimant. If the respondent''s agreement to pay is conditional, (e.g. on condition that goods are returned by the claimant), the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and seek his agreement to comply with the respondent''s requirement. (3) Where the respondent consents to judgment being given against him, the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in the manner provided in rule 11. (4) Where the respondent wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, the Small Claims Registrar must seek the consent of the claimant to the terms proposed by the respondent. (5) The details of every agreement reached or settlement effected under this rule must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must the respondent do if they wish to dispute the claim or make a counterclaim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Appear in person before the Small Claims Registrar within 7 days of receiving the Notice of Claim to verbally express disagreement.","Submit a written statement of disagreement via email to the Small Claims Court within 30 days of receiving the Notice of Claim.","Complete, detach and return the Notice of Dispute in Form 53A.04 Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him.","File a formal appeal with the Superior Court of Justice within 15 days of receiving the Notice of Claim."],"justification":"If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim, he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claim disputed by respondent* 7.(1) If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim, he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. (2) Where a counterclaim is made the Notice of Dispute must be accompanied by the appropriate fee (or where the Notice of Dispute is sent electronically, the fee must be paid by cheque, postal order or money order to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following transmission of the Notice of Dispute). (3) The Small Claims Registrar must promptly furnish the claimant with a copy of any Notice of Dispute received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if there is a default in the payment of an instalment in a settlement?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Rule 15 of Order 49 applies, without any modifications.","Rule 13 of Order 50 applies, with any necessary modifications.","Rule 14 of Order 49 applies, with any necessary modifications.","Rule 12 of Order 47 applies, with any necessary modifications."],"justification":"If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Settlement* 8. (1) The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear. (2) Where a settlement is effected, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (3) Where the terms of an agreement or settlement (including an agreement to pay by instalments) are not complied with, the Small Claims Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party. (4) In cases other than those where payment by instalments has been agreed, he or she must proceed in accordance with the provisions of rule 11. (5) If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications. (6) Where a judgment is issued in a case to which this rule relates, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the party against whom it was issued accordingly and particulars of the request for and the issue and notification of such judgment must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Small Claims Registrar fails to settle a dispute?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The matter is referred to the High Court for a preliminary review.","The matter is sent back to the Small Claims Tribunal for reconsideration.","The matter is dismissed as unresolved.","The matter is referred to the District Court for hearing."],"justification":"Where the Small Claims Registrar fails to effect a settlement of the dispute between the parties, he or she must refer the matter to the District Court for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Referral to Court for hearing* 9. (1) Where the Small Claims Registrar fails to effect a settlement of the dispute between the parties, he or she must refer the matter to the District Court for hearing. (2) The Registrar may at any time on his own initiative and must, if so requested by either party, refer any application or proceeding under the Small Claims Procedure to the District Court for hearing. (3) On referral under this rule, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the parties of the place, date and time of hearing. He or she must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Are witnesses'' expenses covered under the Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes, but only if the expenses are incurred by the court itself.","Yes, but only if incurred by the claimant or respondent and they are responsible for their own.","Yes, but only if the witness is a professional hired by the court.","No, witnesses'' expenses are never covered under any circumstances."],"justification":"The claimant and the respondent are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any) incurred in respect of any claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Liability for costs and expenses* 10. The claimant and the respondent are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any) incurred in respect of any claim processed through the Small Claims Procedure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What steps can the claimant take after the respondent is deemed to have admitted the claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The claimant can apply for judgment by swearing an affidavit of debt and lodging it with the Small Claims Registrar along with a requisition for judgment and a Small Claims judgment.","The claimant can immediately seize the respondent''s assets without a court order if the admission is acknowledged in writing.","The claimant can request a new trial by submitting a motion to the court within 30 days of admission.","The claimant can increase the amount of the claim by filing an amended complaint without the need for further admissions from the respondent."],"justification":"The claimant may then apply for judgment by swearing an affidavit of debt and lodging same with the Small Claims Registrar together with a requisition for judgment and a Small Claims judgment, and the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) as if the Notice of Claim and copy claim served under these Rules were a claim notice issued and served under [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Default by respondent* 11. (1) Where the respondent fails to return either the Notice of Acceptance or Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule or the Notice of Dispute ([Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within the time permitted and fails to contact the Small Claims Registrar within that period, he or she must be deemed to have admitted the claim. (2) The claimant may then apply for judgment by swearing an affidavit of debt and lodging same with the Small Claims Registrar together with a requisition for judgment and a Small Claims judgment, and the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) as if the Notice of Claim and copy claim served under these Rules were a claim notice issued and served under [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court). (3) The forms of affidavit provided in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) may, with necessary modifications, be used for that purpose. (4) The claimant may call to the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the forms. (5) When a judgment is issued under this rule, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the respondent accordingly, and particulars of such issue and notification must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to legal costs and witnesses'' expenses when there is an application under Order 47, Part 4 in relation to a default judgment obtained under rules 8 or 11?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any).","The winning party is entitled to recover all legal costs and witness expenses from the losing party.","Both parties are required to equally split all legal costs and witnesses’ expenses.","All legal costs and witnesses’ expenses are covered by the court without contribution from the parties."],"justification":"in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Review of default judgment* 12. The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 (which relates to the review of default judgments) apply, with necessary modifications, in the case of a judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11 and [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 must be construed accordingly, save that in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court award costs in a small claims procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"The Court may not award costs or witnesses'' expenses to any party when determining any matter referred to it by a Small Claims Registrar under the Small Claims Procedure."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 No award of costs in small claims procedure* 13. The Court may not award costs or witnesses'' expenses to any party when determining any matter referred to it by a Small Claims Registrar under the Small Claims Procedure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What type of judgment is granted under the Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Summary judgment","Small Claims judgment","Default judgment","Circuit court judgment"],"justification":"A judgment granted under the Small Claims Procedure is a Small Claims judgment"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Forms of judgment may be used* 14. A judgment granted under the Small Claims Procedure is a Small Claims judgment, and the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What power does a Small Claims Registrar have regarding affidavits and affirmations?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The power to enforce criminal penalties based on the content of affidavits and affirmations.","The power to take affidavits and affirmations for processing claims and issuing judgments under the Small Claims Procedure.","The power to appoint judges for cases involving complex legal matters beyond small claims.","The power to amend laws related to affidavits and affirmations in the Small Claims Procedure."],"justification":"Every Small Claims Registrar has the power and is authorised by these Rules, to take affidavits and affirmations for the purposes of processing claims through the Small Claims Procedure and issuing judgments under the Small Claims Procedure."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Power of Small Claims Registrar to take affidavits and affirmations* 15. (1) Every Small Claims Registrar has the power and is authorised by these Rules, to take affidavits and affirmations for the purposes of processing claims through the Small Claims Procedure and issuing judgments under the Small Claims Procedure. (2) No fee is payable by any party in respect of any affidavit or affirmation made by him before a Small Claims Registrar under this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What documents can be served electronically under Rule 16?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Affidavit of Service","Motion to Compel Discovery","Notice of Claim, Notice of Acceptance of Liability, Notice of Dispute","Petition for Summary Judgment"],"justification":"a Notice of Claim by the Small Claims Registrar on a respondent; a Notice of Acceptance of Liability by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar; a Notice of Dispute by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 16 Electronic filing 16. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Judge for the time being assigned to the relevant Court district (or in the case of the Dublin Metropolitan District, the President of the District Court) has so directed, the service of: - a Notice of Claim by the Small Claims Registrar on a respondent; - a Notice of Acceptance of Liability by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar; - (iii) a Notice of Dispute by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the respondent''s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the respondent) or to the Small Claims Registrar''s electronic mail address (as identified on a website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic message was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as provided for by rules 5, 6 and 7 within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is a document invalid if the fee associated with it is not recorded by stamping the original document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The document becomes void after a certain period if the fee is not recorded by stamping it on the original document.","No, the document is not invalid or ineffective if the fee is recorded or receipted without stamping the original document.","While the document remains valid, all transactions related to it become null until the fee is stamped onto the original document.","Yes, because the absence of a stamped fee renders the document invalid according to standard legal procedures."],"justification":"No document sent under the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of the document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a fee or payment be “lodged together with or forwarded together with” a document or that a document be “accompanied by” a fee, the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and accompanied by a written note quoting any reference or claim number given in respect of the small claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent under the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of the document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document. [1] Order 53A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''claim form''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The initiating document completed by a claimant in a European Small Claims Case in the Form A in the Annex to the Regulation","The form used to appeal a decision in a European Small Claims Case.","The legal document used to initiate a criminal case in a European court.","The final document submitted by the defendant in a European Small Claims Case."],"justification":"“**claim form**” means the initiating document completed by a claimant in a European Small Claims Case in the Form A in the Annex to the Regulation;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order— the “**2****008 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 ([S.I. 533 of 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/533/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,533/2008 - European Communities (European,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2008.&text 1.,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008.)) as amended by the European Communities (European Small Claims Procedure and European Order for Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017 ([S.I. 312 of 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/312/made/en/print)); “**claim form**” means the initiating document completed by a claimant in a European Small Claims Case in the Form A in the Annex to the Regulation; the Regulation**” means [Regulation No 861/2007](https://interlex-portal.eu/FindLaw/Doc/LegalAct/5578101) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 11 July 2007 199 of 31 July 2007, page 1) establishing a European Small Claims Procedure, as amended by [Regulation No. 2015/2421](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2015/2421/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 December 2015, 341 of 24 December 2015; “**European Small Claim**” means a claim referred to in Article 2(1) of the Regulation and which is not excluded from the application of the Regulation by Article 2(2) of the Regulation; “**European Small Claims Procedure**” means the method provided in the Regulation and in this Order for commencing and dealing with a European Small Claim; “**Member State**” means a Member State of the European Union other than Denmark; “**Small Claims Registrar**” or “**Registrar**” has the same meaning as in [Order 53A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53A-District-Small-Claims-Procedure) and, for the avoidance of doubt, includes a District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which a European Small Claim is lodged or to which a European Small Claim is remitted or transferred who for the time being is performing functions of the Court specified in the 2008 Regulations which may be exercised by a District Court Clerk, references in this Order to any form prescribed by or in any Annex to the Regulation include reference to such forms as amended or substituted, and to any other forms for the time being prescribed for use in connection with the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must all proceedings to which this Order applies be brought and determined in accordance with?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["the provisions of Order 40, rule 5 and, where applicable, Order rules 4 and 5","the provisions of Order 41, rule 4 and, where applicable, Order rules 1 and 2","the provisions of Order 40, rules 1 and 2 and, where applicable, Order rules 1 and 2","the provisions of Order 40, rule 4 and, where applicable, Order rules 2 and 3"],"justification":"all proceedings to which this Order applies must be brought and determined in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 and, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rules 2 and 3."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of this Order, all proceedings to which this Order applies must be brought and determined in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 and, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rules 2 and 3. (2) Where proceedings for a European Order for Payment are remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure by the Master of the High Court, the proceedings will be continued and determined in accordance with this Order, and: - the application for a European Order for Payment will stand as the claim form, and - the statement of opposition to a European order for payment will stand as the defendant’s answer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Is a document sent electronically under the European Small Claims Procedure valid if it lacks a manuscript signature?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A document is only valid if it includes both a manuscript signature and a digital certification from a recognized authority.","Yes, a document sent electronically under the European Small Claims Procedure is valid even if it does not include a manuscript signature.","Only documents sent via postal mail are valid in the European Small Claims Procedure, regardless of whether they contain a manuscript signature or not.","No, a document sent electronically must always have a physical signature to be considered valid."],"justification":"No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Electronic filing* 3. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Court or Registrar has so directed, the service of any document required to be sent, delivered, dispatched or served under the European Small Claims Procedure is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the claimant’s or respondent’s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the claimant or respondent, or as used by either to send any communication to the Registrar) or to the Registrar’s electronic mail address (as identified on any website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature. (3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a document be “accompanied by” any fee or payment, such fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is paid or sent to the Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and the mode of payment includes or is accompanied by any reference or claim number given in respect of the European Small Claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of such document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar record in writing for every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.","The name and address of the claimant, the date of birth of the respondent, the date of the claim form, and the nature of the claim.","The name and address of the claimant''s legal representative, the name and address of the respondent''s legal representative, the date of the claim form, and the estimated cost of the proceedings.","The name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent, the date of birth of the claimant, and the type of goods or services involved in the claim."],"justification":"record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Recording of application* 5. The Registrar must, in respect of: - every claim form received, and - every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure, record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the claimant withdraws their claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The claimant must pay an additional withdrawal fee.","The case is automatically assigned to another claimant.","The Registrar must keep the fee as it covers administrative costs.","The Registrar must refund any fee received in respect of the claim."],"justification":"Where the claimant withdraws the claim, the Registrar must refund any fee received in respect of the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Rejection or acceptance of application* 6. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, the Registrar must so inform the claimant, where possible by the same means by which the claimant’s application was sent to the Registrar (and if not possible, by registered or recorded delivery post) and must advise the claimant that he or she may: - (a) withdraw the claim, or - commence proceedings on the claim as ordinary civil proceedings before the Court in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 or, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 2 or 3. (2) Where the claimant withdraws the claim, the Registrar must refund any fee received in respect of the claim. (3) Where the Registrar considers the information provided by the claimant to be inadequate or insufficiently clear, or that the claim form is not filled in properly, he or she must send to the claimant (by the means by which the claim form was sent to him) a request in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation to be completed by the claimant and returned to the Registrar by the same means within the period specified by the Registrar, which must be 21 days of the sending by the Registrar of Form or such longer period as the Registrar may specify. (4) Where the Registrar considers that: - the completed claim is clearly unfounded, or - the application is inadmissible, or - (iii) the information provided by the claimant was inadequate or insufficiently clear or the claim form was not filled in properly, and the claimant was given the opportunity to complete or rectify the claim form or to supply supplementary information or documents or to withdraw the claim, within a period specified by the Registrar, and the claimant fails to complete or rectify the claim form within the time specified,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Registrar refers a claim to the Judge under the European Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Judge must accept the claim without any further evaluation.","The Judge may dismiss the claim or make another order deemed necessary.","The Judge is required to refer the case back to the Registrar for further instructions.","The Judge will automatically award damages to the plaintiff."],"justification":"he or she may refer the claim to the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'he or she may refer the claim to the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) In such circumstances the Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the claimant of the Court’s order and that no appeal lies against the making of such order and must refund any fee, where appropriate. (6) Where the Registrar considers the properly filled in claim comes within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, he or she must, within the time limit prescribed by Article 5.2 of the Regulation: - (a) complete Part of the standard answer form, in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation, and - serve by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) on the respondent copies of the claim form, of the supporting documents (where applicable) and the answer form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must accompany any counterclaim by the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A signed affidavit","A detailed witness statement","The appropriate fee","The original complaint"],"justification":"Any counterclaim by the respondent must be accompanied by the appropriate fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Respondent’s response if claim not admitted* 8. (1) Any counterclaim by the respondent must be accompanied by the appropriate fee. (2) The Registrar must dispatch copies of the respondent’s response, including the completed Part of the standard answer form or answer in other written form and the supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(4) of the Regulation. (3) The Registrar must dispatch copies of any counterclaim and any supporting documents provided (where applicable) to the claimant by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) within the time limit prescribed by Article 5(6) of the Regulation. (4) Where, in his or her standard answer form or answer in other written form, the respondent claims that the value of a non-monetary claim exceeds the limit of €5,000 set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation, the Registrar must refer the proceeding to the District Court, which may make such order as it deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) Where a counterclaim exceeds the limit set out in Article 2(1) of the Regulation the claim and counterclaim must not proceed in the European Small Claims Procedure and the Registrar must so inform the claimant and the respondent, where possible by electronic mail (and if not possible, by registered or recorded delivery post). (6) The Registrar must advise the claimant and the respondent that he or she may commence proceedings on the claim (or counterclaim) as ordinary civil proceedings before the court in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court) or, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rule 2 or 3. (7) The Registrar must notify the claimant of any order made by the Court under this rule. (8) The provisions of this Order apply to any counterclaim made under the European Small Claims Procedure as they apply to any European Small Claim, with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What action can the Registrar take if the terms of a settlement are not complied with?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Registrar may refer the matter back to arbitration for further dispute resolution.","If requested by the claimant, the Registrar may proceed to judgment against the other party.","The Registrar can issue a warning letter to both parties involved in the settlement.","The Registrar has the authority to impose financial penalties on the non-compliant party."],"justification":"Where the terms of a settlement are not complied with, the Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party in accordance with the provisions of rule 14."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Settlement* 9. (1) Whenever he or she considers it appropriate, the Registrar must, in accordance with Article 12(3) of the Regulation, seek to reach a settlement between the parties. In that connection he or she may interview (in person or by such other means as he or she considers appropriate) the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him or her to hear. Where a settlement is reached, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (2) Without prejudice to the generality of Article 14 of the Regulation, the Registrar may extend the time limits provided for in the Regulation where he or she is seeking to reach a settlement between the parties. (3) Where the terms of a settlement are not complied with, the Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party in accordance with the provisions of rule 14.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when the respondent fails to return the answer form or deliver an answer within the 30-day period?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The case is dismissed due to lack of response.","The respondent is automatically granted a default win.","Judgment must be entered in default of answer in accordance with sub-rule (2).","The court extends the deadline by another 30 days."],"justification":"judgment must be entered in default of answer in accordance with sub-rule (2)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *10 Default* 10. (1) Where the respondent fails to return the answer form or deliver an answer in other written form to the Registrar within the 30 day period permitted by Article 5(3) of the Regulation, or where the claimant fails to respond to any counterclaim to the Registrar within the 30 day period permitted by Article 5(6) of the Regulation, judgment must be entered in default of answer in accordance with sub-rule (2). (2) Where judgment in default is sought under sub-rule (1) in a claim or counterclaim for a liquidated amount, the claimant or respondent (as the case may be) may swear an affidavit of debt and file the affidavit with the Registrar, and the Registrar must proceed to judgment in accordance with the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) as if the claim form or counterclaim (as the case may be) were a claim notice issued and served. (3) The forms of affidavit and judgment provided in [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims) may, with necessary modifications, be used for that purpose. (4) The claimant may call to or contact the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the forms. (5) In a case to which sub-rule (2) applies, where requested by the claimant or (as the case may be) the respondent, the Registrar must issue to the claimant or (as the case may be) the respondent a certificate in the amount in which judgment was given in accordance with rule 14. (6) Where a claim to which no answer form or answer in other written form is returned within the time permitted or a counterclaim to which no response is provided within the time permitted is for an unliquidated amount, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court in accordance with rule 11.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar do if a settlement cannot be reached?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Refer the proceedings to the Court and notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court.","Dismiss the case without further action.","Refer the matter to arbitration instead of the Court.","Notify the parties that the proceedings will be cancelled."],"justification":"Within the time prescribed by Article 7(1) of the Regulation, or such extended time as the Registrar has permitted, where the Registrar is satisfied that a settlement of the proceedings cannot be reached, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court and must notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Referral to Court* 11. (1) Within the time prescribed by Article 7(1) of the Regulation, or such extended time as the Registrar has permitted, where the Registrar is satisfied that a settlement of the proceedings cannot be reached, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court and must notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court. (2) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court in considering the proceedings. (3) When the proceedings are before the Court, the Court may: - (a) direct in accordance with Article 7(1)(a) of the Regulation that further details concerning the claim be demanded from the parties within a period of time specified by the Court, and on the giving of same or the expiry of the time permitted for the giving of same, the proceedings be re-entered before the Court; - direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that evidence be taken and give directions for the taking of evidence in accordance with Article 9 of the Regulation as are appropriate; - where it considers that the conditions set out in Article 5(1a) of the Regulation for the holding of an oral hearing are satisfied, direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that the parties be summoned to an oral hearing and give such directions for the conduct of the oral hearing in accordance with Article 8 of the Regulation or otherwise as are appropriate; - subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim. (4) Where the Court refuses a request by a party for an oral hearing, the reasons for refusal must be given in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation. (5) The Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the parties, or relevant party, in writing, of:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What details must the Registrar provide to assist the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Details about the security arrangements for the courtroom during the trial, including the number of bailiffs required and the type of security measures to be implemented.","Details concerning the claim, time for providing them, place, date, time, and communications technology for evidence taking or oral hearings, and any judgments given.","Names of all witnesses who will testify in the case, their contact information, and a detailed schedule of their availability.","The financial records of both parties involved in the dispute, including bank statements and tax returns, within three weeks of the request."],"justification":"- (a) any further details concerning the claim demanded and the time within which they are to be provided; - the place, date and time at which (and where relevant, any communications technology by means of which) evidence is to be taken or any oral hearing is to be conducted; - any judgment given on any claim and/or counterclaim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) any further details concerning the claim demanded and the time within which they are to be provided; - the place, date and time at which (and where relevant, any communications technology by means of which) evidence is to be taken or any oral hearing is to be conducted; - any judgment given on any claim and/or counterclaim. (6) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Registrar take if a party refuses to accept a document due to language issues?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Registrar immediately rejects the document and considers it invalid.","The Registrar asks the refusing party to provide a summary of the document in their preferred language.","The Registrar informs the other party and requests that they provide a translation of the document within 21 days.","The Registrar fines the party who refused the document 500."],"justification":"Where a party to a European Small Claim refuses to accept a document because it is not in: the official language of the Member State addressed, or, if there are several official languages in that Member State, the official language or one of the official languages of the place where service is to be effected or to where the document is to be dispatched, or a language which the addressee understands, the Registrar must so inform the other party and request that other party to provide a translation of the document concerned within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Translations* 12. (1) If a document (other than a document referred to in Article 6(1) of the Regulation) is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English, the Registrar may, where a translation of that document appears to be necessary for giving a judgment on the claim or counterclaim, require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (2) Where a party to a European Small Claim refuses to accept a document because it is not in: - (a) the official language of the Member State addressed, or, if there are several official languages in that Member State, the official language or one of the official languages of the place where service is to be effected or to where the document is to be dispatched, or - a language which the addressee understands, the Registrar must so inform the other party and request that other party to provide a translation of the document concerned within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (3) Where, on request, a party has failed to comply with the translation requirements set out in Article 6(2), Article 6(3)(a) or Article of the Regulation, as may be appropriate, the Registrar must proceed as if the document concerned were never received by the Court, or by the other party, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have regarding costs in European Small Claims proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may make such order for costs as it considers appropriate, consistent with Article 16 of the Regulation.","The Court is prohibited from making any orders for costs in European Small Claims proceedings.","The Court must always award full costs to the winning party, regardless of the circumstances.","The Court can only make orders for costs if both parties agree beforehand."],"justification":"The Court may make such order for costs in proceedings on any European Small Claim as it considers appropriate, consistently with the requirements of Article 16 of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 Costs* 13. The Court may make such order for costs in proceedings on any European Small Claim as it considers appropriate, consistently with the requirements of Article 16 of the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What grounds can a respondent use to apply for review of a judgment in a European Small Claim?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The grounds specified in Article 19(4) of the Regulation.","The grounds specified in Article 20(3) of the Regulation.","The grounds specified in Article 17(2) of the Regulation.","The grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation."],"justification":"on either of the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Application for review of the judgment in accordance with Article 18* 15. (1) A respondent against whom judgment by default has been given in a European Small Claim in accordance with the provisions of this Order may apply by notice of motion (in [Form 44.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/079a8d5f-a0d5-4b0a-b589-95b72e954e1a/Notice of motion - general No. 44.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications) to the Court in the Court area in which the order was obtained for an order to set aside and/or vary the said order on either of the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation. (2) The notice of motion must be issued within the time limit specified in Article 18(2) of the Regulation and must be served on the claimant or solicitor for the claimant, if any, not less than seven days before the date on which the application is listed before the Court. (3) Service of the notice of motion does not operate as a stay of proceedings. (4) The Court may declare sufficient the service of the notice of motion actually effected. (5) The notice of motion must set out clearly and briefly the grounds specified in Article 18(1) of the Regulation relied on by the party applying. (6) The Court may, on the hearing of the motion, grant or refuse the application on the basis of the provisions of Article 18(1) of the Regulation. (7) Where the Court rejects the review on the basis that none of the grounds referred to in Article 18(1) of the Regulation applies, the judgment remains in force. (8) Where the Court decides that the review is justified for one of the reasons laid down in Article 18(1) of the Regulation, then the judgment given in the European Small Claims Procedure must be set aside and is null and void.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What additional documents must a judgment creditor provide to the Clerk when applying for enforcement under Order 51?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The documents referred to in Article 22(3) of the Regulation.","The documents referred to in Article 21(1) of the Regulation.","The documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation.","The documents referred to in Article 20(1) of the Regulation."],"justification":"provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *16 Enforcement* 16. (1) Subject to the Regulation, the provisions of Orders 51 and 51A, insofar as they may be applied to a judgment of the District Court, may be applied to a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State, and any reference in Orders 51 and 51A to a “judgment” includes, where the context so admits, a reference to such a judgment or court settlement. In such a case, any relevant Form in [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) which contains a reference to a judgment, or order may be adapted to refer to such a judgment. (2) Where an application is made by a creditor for enforcement in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), rule 3 in respect of a judgment or court settlement given in the European Small Claims Procedure in a Member State other than the State, the judgment creditor must, in addition to lodging with the Clerk the summons in duplicate and statutory declaration, provide to the Clerk the documents referred to in Article 21(2) of the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'In which type of proceedings is this rule applicable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Civil proceedings where rule 28 does apply.","Administrative hearings where no specific rule is mentioned.","Criminal proceedings where rule 28 applies.","Civil proceedings where rule 28 does not apply."],"justification":"In the award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *29 Court to certify for counsel* 29. In the award of costs in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply, a fee for counsel may not be included unless the Court certifies that, in its opinion, the employment of counsel was necessary for the attainment of justice or for enforcing or defending the rights of the party concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53 - Costs', 'Court Rules', 'What is prohibited when a barrister is employed on a full-time or exclusive basis by a party''s solicitor or the party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Accepting a reduced fee for counsel below the standard solicitor''s scale fee.","Providing additional services beyond legal representation without charging extra fees.","Including a separate fee for counsel in addition to any solicitor''s scale fee.","Engaging in part-time work with another law firm while employed exclusively by the party."],"justification":"Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *30 No separate counsel’s fee for barrister employed on a full-time basis* 30. Where a barrister who acts as advocate for a party in any civil proceedings in the Court to which rule 28 does not apply is employed on a fulltime or exclusive basis by the party’s solicitor or by the party, a fee for counsel may not be included in the party’s costs in addition to any solicitor’s scale fee. [1] Order 53 inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014 [2] Order 53 rule 1 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must accompany the completed application when filing it with the Small Claims Registrar?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["a notarized affidavit","a signed witness statement","the applicant''s birth certificate","any supporting documents required and the appropriate fee"],"justification":"any supporting documents required and the appropriate fee"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Filing application* 3. An application to which rule 2 relates must be in writing, which may be in electronic form, in the [Form 53A.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/88869131-d146-4c43-8b9b-e75e7cc7423f/Small Claims Procedure - Application to Small Claims Registrar No. 53A.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule The application, when completed, must be filed with the Small Claims Registrar together with any supporting documents required and the appropriate fee. The claimant may call to the Court office if assistance is needed in completing the form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What actions can the Small Claims Registrar take after recording the basic details of an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Small Claims Registrar may dismiss the case if the application is not submitted in person by the claimant.","The Small Claims Registrar may immediately award damages to the claimant based on the initial application details without further investigation.","The Small Claims Registrar may issue a warrant for the arrest of the defendant if they fail to respond within 24 hours.","The Small Claims Registrar may interview the claimant or take other steps deemed necessary to record the full facts of the claim."],"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4 Recording of application* 4. The Small Claims Registrar must, in respect of every such application received, record in writing the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the person against whom the claim is made (in this Order called “the respondent”), the date of the application, the nature of the claim and any other relevant details. The Small Claims Registrar must consider the application and may take such steps as he or she deems necessary, whether by way of interviewing the claimant or otherwise, to record the full facts of the claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'How does the Small Claims Registrar serve the Notice of Claim on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By serving it personally to the respondent during business hours.","By registered post or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15.","In person by a bailiff or process server.","Through a local newspaper advertisement as mandated by court rules."],"justification":"he or she must serve by registered post (or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) on the respondent a Notice of Claim in the [Form 53A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bfcc43c-8d9a-4307-8e92-90fa1b8d239c/Small Claims Procedure - Notice of claim against Respondent No. 53A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (containing also Forms [53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) and [53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule together with a copy of the Notice of Claim."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Rejection or acceptance of application* 5. (1) Where the claim does not come within the scope of the Small Claims Procedure or the claimant fails to supply supporting documents sufficient to identify the proper respondent to his or her claim, the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and must refund the fee. (2) If the Small Claims Registrar considers the claim to be appropriate to the Small Claims Procedure, he or she must serve by registered post (or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) on the respondent a Notice of Claim in the [Form 53A.02](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bfcc43c-8d9a-4307-8e92-90fa1b8d239c/Small Claims Procedure - Notice of claim against Respondent No. 53A.02.docx/docx/1), Schedule (containing also Forms [53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) and [53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1), Schedule together with a copy of the Notice of Claim.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must a respondent do if they agree to pay the amount claimed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Complete, detach and return the Notice of Acceptance of Liability to the court clerk within 7 days after receiving the Notice of Claim.","Complete, detach and return the Notice of Acceptance of Liability to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after service of the Notice of Claim.","Sign and return the Notice of Acceptance of Liability to the plaintiff''s lawyer instead of the Small Claims Registrar.","Pay the amount claimed directly to the plaintiff without completing any form."],"justification":"he must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Acceptance of Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *6 Admission of small claim by respondent* 6. (1) If the respondent admits the claim made against him and - (a) agrees to pay the amount claimed, or - consents to judgment being given against him, or - wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, he must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, by electronic mail in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Acceptance of Liability ([Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. On receipt of such Notice the Registrar must inform the claimant accordingly. (2) Where the respondent agrees to pay the amount claimed, he or she may forward to the Small Claims Registrar, together with [Form 53A.03](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e5d917f-38e2-44b1-af4c-178761cf1fca/Small Claims Procedure - notice of acceptance of liability No. 53A.03.docx/docx/1), Schedule payment by cheque, postal order(s) or money order(s), made payable to the claimant, for the full amount claimed. The Small Claims Registrar must transmit any such payment to the claimant. If the respondent''s agreement to pay is conditional, (e.g. on condition that goods are returned by the claimant), the Small Claims Registrar must so inform the claimant and seek his agreement to comply with the respondent''s requirement. (3) Where the respondent consents to judgment being given against him, the Small Claims Registrar must proceed to judgment in the manner provided in rule 11. (4) Where the respondent wishes to pay the amount claimed by instalments, the Small Claims Registrar must seek the consent of the claimant to the terms proposed by the respondent. (5) The details of every agreement reached or settlement effected under this rule must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What accompanies a Notice of Dispute when a counterclaim is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The appropriate fee must accompany the Notice of Dispute when a counterclaim is made.","The original claim form must accompany the Notice of Dispute when a counterclaim is made.","A signed affidavit must accompany the Notice of Dispute when a counterclaim is made.","A detailed witness statement must accompany the Notice of Dispute when a counterclaim is made."],"justification":"Where a counterclaim is made the Notice of Dispute must be accompanied by the appropriate fee (or where the Notice of Dispute is sent electronically, the fee must be paid by cheque, postal order or money order to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following transmission of the Notice of Dispute)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *7 Small claim disputed by respondent* 7.(1) If the respondent disputes the claim or wishes to make a counterclaim, he or she must complete, detach and return (by post or by hand or, where permitted, in electronic form in accordance with rule 15) the Notice of Dispute in the [Form 53A.04](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa53d353-b4e8-4163-8090-6684e76f0b5c/Small Claims Procedure - notice of dispute No. 53A.04.docx/docx/1) Schedule to the Small Claims Registrar within 15 days after the service of the Notice of Claim and copy claim on him. (2) Where a counterclaim is made the Notice of Dispute must be accompanied by the appropriate fee (or where the Notice of Dispute is sent electronically, the fee must be paid by cheque, postal order or money order to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following transmission of the Notice of Dispute). (3) The Small Claims Registrar must promptly furnish the claimant with a copy of any Notice of Dispute received from the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Small Claims Registrar do to settle disputes?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Must refer all disputes to a higher court for resolution.","Is required to settle disputes within 24 hours of their submission.","Should only settle disputes by enforcing a predetermined template agreement.","Use his best endeavours to settle disputes and may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear."],"justification":"The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *8 Settlement* 8. (1) The Small Claims Registrar must use his best endeavours to settle the dispute(s) between the parties and in that connection may interview the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him to hear. (2) Where a settlement is effected, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (3) Where the terms of an agreement or settlement (including an agreement to pay by instalments) are not complied with, the Small Claims Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party. (4) In cases other than those where payment by instalments has been agreed, he or she must proceed in accordance with the provisions of rule 11. (5) If default is made in the payment of an instalment, [Order 49]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-49-District-Hearing-Of-Civil-Proceedings), rule 14 applies, with any necessary modifications. (6) Where a judgment is issued in a case to which this rule relates, the Small Claims Registrar must notify the party against whom it was issued accordingly and particulars of the request for and the issue and notification of such judgment must be recorded in writing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Which part of Order 47 applies with necessary modifications to the review of default judgments obtained under rules 8 or 11?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Part 5 of Order 47.","Part 2 of Order 47.","Part 4 of Order 47.","Part 3 of Order 47."],"justification":"the provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 (which relates to the review of default judgments) apply, with necessary modifications, in the case of a judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Review of default judgment* 12. The provisions of [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 (which relates to the review of default judgments) apply, with necessary modifications, in the case of a judgment obtained under rule 8 or rule 11 and [Order 47]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-47-District-Judgment-In-Default-In-Debt-Claims), Part 4 must be construed accordingly, save that in any application under that rule in relation to a default judgment so obtained the parties are liable for their own legal costs and witnesses’ expenses (if any).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What expenses cannot be awarded by the court in a small claims procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Legal fees","Costs or witnesses'' expenses","Lost income","Damages for emotional distress"],"justification":"The Court may not award costs or witnesses'' expenses to any party when determining any matter referred to it by a Small Claims Registrar under the Small Claims Procedure."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *13 No award of costs in small claims procedure* 13. The Court may not award costs or witnesses'' expenses to any party when determining any matter referred to it by a Small Claims Registrar under the Small Claims Procedure.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Can existing forms of judgment be used in the Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes, with necessary modifications","No, existing forms of judgment cannot be used at all.","Only new forms of judgment can be created specifically for the Small Claims Procedure.","Yes, without any modifications needed."],"justification":"the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *14 Forms of judgment may be used* 14. A judgment granted under the Small Claims Procedure is a Small Claims judgment, and the forms of judgment at present in use may, with necessary modifications, be used when preparing the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'Is there a fee for taking affidavits or affirmations before a Small Claims Registrar?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["There is a standard fee of 50 for this service.","Fees vary by state, ranging from 20 to 100.","No fee is payable.","A nominal fee of 10 is required."],"justification":"No fee is payable by any party in respect of any affidavit or affirmation made by him before a Small Claims Registrar under this rule."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *15 Power of Small Claims Registrar to take affidavits and affirmations* 15. (1) Every Small Claims Registrar has the power and is authorised by these Rules, to take affidavits and affirmations for the purposes of processing claims through the Small Claims Procedure and issuing judgments under the Small Claims Procedure. (2) No fee is payable by any party in respect of any affidavit or affirmation made by him before a Small Claims Registrar under this rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the sender is not satisfied with the delivery of an electronic message?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The receiver must acknowledge receipt of the message within 24 hours.","The electronic message is considered delivered once it enters the recipient''s email server.","The sender must resend the message within one hour.","The electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as provided for by rules 5, 6 and 7 within eight days following such period."],"justification":"where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic message was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as provided for by rules 5, 6 and 7 within eight days following such period."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## 16 Electronic filing 16. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Judge for the time being assigned to the relevant Court district (or in the case of the Dublin Metropolitan District, the President of the District Court) has so directed, the service of: - a Notice of Claim by the Small Claims Registrar on a respondent; - a Notice of Acceptance of Liability by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar; - (iii) a Notice of Dispute by a respondent on the Small Claims Registrar is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the respondent''s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the respondent) or to the Small Claims Registrar''s electronic mail address (as identified on a website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic message was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as provided for by rules 5, 6 and 7 within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53A - Small Claims Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for a fee or payment to be considered validly effected or made when accompanying a document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The fee or payment must be enclosed with the document itself and sent directly to the opposing party, with no need for a written note or specific claim number.","The fee or payment can be made via an online portal designated for small claims cases, but it must be done at least one week before the document is transmitted.","The fee or payment must be sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as possible after the document''s transmission and must be accompanied by a written note with the relevant reference or claim number.","The fee or payment must be sent to the court clerk within 30 days of the document''s transmission without any additional documentation."],"justification":"the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and accompanied by a written note quoting any reference or claim number given in respect of the small claim to which it relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a fee or payment be “lodged together with or forwarded together with” a document or that a document be “accompanied by” a fee, the fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is sent to the Small Claims Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and accompanied by a written note quoting any reference or claim number given in respect of the small claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent under the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of the document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document. [1] Order 53A inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''2008 Regulations'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Act 2008","The European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 as amended by the European Communities (European Small Claims Procedure and European Order for Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017","The United Nations (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008","The European Union (Large Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008"],"justification":"the “**2****008 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 ([S.I. 533 of 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/533/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,533/2008 - European Communities (European,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008\u0026text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2008.\u0026text 1.,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008.)) as amended by the European Communities (European Small Claims Procedure and European Order for Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017 ([S.I. 312 of 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/312/made/en/print);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1 Definitions* 1. In this Order— the “**2****008 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008 ([S.I. 533 of 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/si/533/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,533/2008 - European Communities (European,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of December, 2008.&text 1.,Small Claims Procedure) Regulations 2008.)) as amended by the European Communities (European Small Claims Procedure and European Order for Payment) (Amendment) Regulations 2017 ([S.I. 312 of 2017](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/312/made/en/print)); “**claim form**” means the initiating document completed by a claimant in a European Small Claims Case in the Form A in the Annex to the Regulation; the Regulation**” means [Regulation No 861/2007](https://interlex-portal.eu/FindLaw/Doc/LegalAct/5578101) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 11 July 2007 199 of 31 July 2007, page 1) establishing a European Small Claims Procedure, as amended by [Regulation No. 2015/2421](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2015/2421/oj/eng) of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 December 2015, 341 of 24 December 2015; “**European Small Claim**” means a claim referred to in Article 2(1) of the Regulation and which is not excluded from the application of the Regulation by Article 2(2) of the Regulation; “**European Small Claims Procedure**” means the method provided in the Regulation and in this Order for commencing and dealing with a European Small Claim; “**Member State**” means a Member State of the European Union other than Denmark; “**Small Claims Registrar**” or “**Registrar**” has the same meaning as in [Order 53A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53A-District-Small-Claims-Procedure) and, for the avoidance of doubt, includes a District Court Clerk assigned to the District Court area in which a European Small Claim is lodged or to which a European Small Claim is remitted or transferred who for the time being is performing functions of the Court specified in the 2008 Regulations which may be exercised by a District Court Clerk, references in this Order to any form prescribed by or in any Annex to the Regulation include reference to such forms as amended or substituted, and to any other forms for the time being prescribed for use in connection with the Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What stands as the claim form when proceedings for a European Order for Payment are remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["the complaint in a standard civil lawsuit","the application for a European Order for Payment","the summons issued by the court","the affidavit supporting the claim"],"justification":"the application for a European Order for Payment will stand as the claim form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2 Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of this Order, all proceedings to which this Order applies must be brought and determined in accordance with the provisions of [Order 40]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40-District-Beginning-Civil-Proceedings-In-The-Court), rule 4 and, where applicable, [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), rules 2 and 3. (2) Where proceedings for a European Order for Payment are remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure by the Master of the High Court, the proceedings will be continued and determined in accordance with this Order, and: - the application for a European Order for Payment will stand as the claim form, and - the statement of opposition to a European order for payment will stand as the defendant’s answer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The sender should mark the communication as ''undelivered'' and wait for confirmation from the court before taking any further steps.","If the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient, the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period.","The sender must resend the electronic communication immediately without any further action.","The recipient is required to acknowledge receipt within 24 hours or face legal consequences."],"justification":"where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3 Electronic filing* 3. (1) Notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules, where suitable facilities for that purpose have been established by the Courts Service, and the Court or Registrar has so directed, the service of any document required to be sent, delivered, dispatched or served under the European Small Claims Procedure is valid if transmitted in electronic form as an electronic message to the claimant’s or respondent’s electronic mail address (as identified on any letterhead or stationery of the claimant or respondent, or as used by either to send any communication to the Registrar) or to the Registrar’s electronic mail address (as identified on any website operated by the Courts Service) provided that where the sender is not satisfied that the electronic communication was delivered to the intended recipient (by reason of any delivery status message received) or where no response has been received within a period of seven days following such transmission, then the electronic communication must be treated as if it had never been sent and the relevant document must be served as otherwise provided for in this Order within eight days following such period. (2) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that it does not include a manuscript signature. (3) Where a provision of this Order requires that a document be “accompanied by” any fee or payment, such fee or payment must be deemed to have been validly effected or made provided that it is paid or sent to the Registrar as soon as may be following the transmission in accordance with this rule of the document in question and the mode of payment includes or is accompanied by any reference or claim number given in respect of the European Small Claim to which it relates. (4) No document sent pursuant to the provisions of this rule is invalid or ineffective by reason only of the fact that any fee associated with the lodgment or delivery of such document is recorded or receipted otherwise than by impression of a stamp on the original document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar record in writing for each claim form received?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The claimant''s email address, the respondent''s employment history, the date of the claim form, and any other personal information about both parties.","The name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.","The name and address of the claimant''s lawyer, the respondent''s phone number, the date of the claim form, and the nature of the claim.","The claimant''s social security number, the respondent''s date of birth, the date of the claim form, and the claimant''s bank account details."],"justification":"record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *5 Recording of application* 5. The Registrar must, in respect of: - every claim form received, and - every proceeding for a European Order for Payment remitted to the European Small Claims Procedure, record in writing (which may be in electronic form) the name and address of the claimant, the name and address of the respondent named in the claim form, the date of the claim form, nature of the claim and any other relevant details.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar do if they consider a claim falls within the European Small Claims Procedure?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["File a counterclaim against the applicant using the standard answer form.","Complete Part of the standard answer form and serve copies of the claim form, supporting documents, and answer form on the respondent.","Notify the court in writing that the claim is out of scope for the European Small Claims Procedure.","Complete Part of the standard answer form and send it directly to the applicant without serving any other documents."],"justification":"Where the Registrar considers the properly filled in claim comes within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, he or she must, within the time limit prescribed by Article 5.2 of the Regulation: - (a) complete Part of the standard answer form, in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation, and - serve by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) on the respondent copies of the claim form, of the supporting documents (where applicable) and the answer form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'he or she may refer the claim to the Judge assigned to the court district concerned, who may dismiss the claim or make such other order as he or she deems necessary in the circumstances. (5) In such circumstances the Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the claimant of the Court’s order and that no appeal lies against the making of such order and must refund any fee, where appropriate. (6) Where the Registrar considers the properly filled in claim comes within the scope of the European Small Claims Procedure, he or she must, within the time limit prescribed by Article 5.2 of the Regulation: - (a) complete Part of the standard answer form, in the Form in the Annex to the Regulation, and - serve by registered post (or, where relevant, as otherwise permitted by rule 3) on the respondent copies of the claim form, of the supporting documents (where applicable) and the answer form.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar do when seeking a settlement between the parties?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Registrar must wait for both parties to request a settlement before intervening.","The Registrar is only allowed to seek a settlement if explicitly instructed by a judge.","The Registrar must seek to reach a settlement between the parties whenever he or she considers it appropriate.","The Registrar must seek a settlement at least once every business day regardless of the circumstances."],"justification":"Whenever he or she considers it appropriate, the Registrar must, in accordance with Article 12(3) of the Regulation, seek to reach a settlement between the parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *9 Settlement* 9. (1) Whenever he or she considers it appropriate, the Registrar must, in accordance with Article 12(3) of the Regulation, seek to reach a settlement between the parties. In that connection he or she may interview (in person or by such other means as he or she considers appropriate) the parties and any other person whom either party may wish him or her to hear. Where a settlement is reached, particulars of the settlement must be recorded in writing. (2) Without prejudice to the generality of Article 14 of the Regulation, the Registrar may extend the time limits provided for in the Regulation where he or she is seeking to reach a settlement between the parties. (3) Where the terms of a settlement are not complied with, the Registrar may, if requested so to do by the claimant, proceed to judgment against the other party in accordance with the provisions of rule 14.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Court do if it refuses a request for an oral hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Provide verbal explanation of the refusal during a public session.","Give reasons for refusal in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation.","Conduct the trial without the presence of the parties involved.","Notify the requesting party via email within five business days."],"justification":"Where the Court refuses a request by a party for an oral hearing, the reasons for refusal must be given in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *11 Referral to Court* 11. (1) Within the time prescribed by Article 7(1) of the Regulation, or such extended time as the Registrar has permitted, where the Registrar is satisfied that a settlement of the proceedings cannot be reached, the Registrar must refer the proceedings to the Court and must notify the parties of the place, date and time at which the proceedings are listed before the Court. (2) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court in considering the proceedings. (3) When the proceedings are before the Court, the Court may: - (a) direct in accordance with Article 7(1)(a) of the Regulation that further details concerning the claim be demanded from the parties within a period of time specified by the Court, and on the giving of same or the expiry of the time permitted for the giving of same, the proceedings be re-entered before the Court; - direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that evidence be taken and give directions for the taking of evidence in accordance with Article 9 of the Regulation as are appropriate; - where it considers that the conditions set out in Article 5(1a) of the Regulation for the holding of an oral hearing are satisfied, direct in accordance with Article of the Regulation that the parties be summoned to an oral hearing and give such directions for the conduct of the oral hearing in accordance with Article 8 of the Regulation or otherwise as are appropriate; - subject to sub-rule (4), where it does not require further information, evidence or an oral hearing, proceed to give judgment on the claim and any counterclaim. (4) Where the Court refuses a request by a party for an oral hearing, the reasons for refusal must be given in writing in accordance with Article 5(1a) of the Regulation. (5) The Registrar must, on behalf of the Court, notify the parties, or relevant party, in writing, of:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'When must the Registrar assist the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Whenever the Registrar feels it is necessary, independent of the Court''s request.","At the request of the Court during the taking of evidence or conducting an oral hearing.","When requested by any party to the case, not just the Court.","During the initial filing of the case, before any evidence is taken."],"justification":"(6) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) any further details concerning the claim demanded and the time within which they are to be provided; - the place, date and time at which (and where relevant, any communications technology by means of which) evidence is to be taken or any oral hearing is to be conducted; - any judgment given on any claim and/or counterclaim. (6) The Registrar must make himself or herself available to assist the Court at the taking of any evidence or any oral hearing, if requested by the Court so to do.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a document is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The document will be returned to the party which provided it, and they will have one week to resubmit it in either Irish or English.","The Registrar may require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within 21 days.","The document will automatically be considered invalid and will not be processed by the Court.","The Court will reject the document and impose a fine on the party which provided it."],"justification":"If a document (other than a document referred to in Article 6(1) of the Regulation) is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English, the Registrar may, where a translation of that document appears to be necessary for giving a judgment on the claim or counterclaim, require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *12 Translations* 12. (1) If a document (other than a document referred to in Article 6(1) of the Regulation) is submitted to the Court in a language other than Irish or English, the Registrar may, where a translation of that document appears to be necessary for giving a judgment on the claim or counterclaim, require the party which provided the document to provide a translation of that document in accordance with Article 6 of the Regulation within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (2) Where a party to a European Small Claim refuses to accept a document because it is not in: - (a) the official language of the Member State addressed, or, if there are several official languages in that Member State, the official language or one of the official languages of the place where service is to be effected or to where the document is to be dispatched, or - a language which the addressee understands, the Registrar must so inform the other party and request that other party to provide a translation of the document concerned within such time as the Registrar specifies, which must ordinarily not exceed 21 days. (3) Where, on request, a party has failed to comply with the translation requirements set out in Article 6(2), Article 6(3)(a) or Article of the Regulation, as may be appropriate, the Registrar must proceed as if the document concerned were never received by the Court, or by the other party, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'What information must be included in the notifications or notices given by the Registrar?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The date and location of the court where the European Small Claim is being heard","The legal representatives of both parties in the European Small Claim","Particulars and any record number for the European Small Claim concerned","Names of all parties involved in the European Small Claim"],"justification":"must include particulars and any record number for the European Small Claim concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *18 Notifications by Registrar* 18. Any notification or notice given by the Registrar to a party to a European Small Claim for any purpose set out in the Regulation must be given by the means by which that party has communicated to him (or to the address or contact detail provided for that party) and must include particulars and any record number for the European Small Claim concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 53B - European Small Claims Procedure (For Cross-Border Small Claims Within The European Union)', 'Court Rules', 'Can a participant disconnect from a hearing without permission?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["No, a participant cannot disconnect from a hearing without obtaining the express consent of the Judge or Registrar.","Yes, a participant can disconnect at any time during the hearing without needing the judge''s permission.","A participant may disconnect from a hearing without permission if they are experiencing technical difficulties.","Participants are allowed to disconnect from a hearing without permission if the hearing exceeds one hour."],"justification":"A person may not cease to take part in a hearing conducted in accordance with this rule by disconnecting his telephone or other means of communication unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of the Judge or Registrar"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *19 Hearings by videolink or telephone* 19. (1) For the purposes of this Order, the contemporaneous linking together by telephone or other means of electronic communication of persons entitled or permitted to be present in the Court at a hearing must be deemed to constitute a hearing before the Court, and all the provisions in these Rules as to hearings apply to such hearing, provided that: - each of the persons taking part in such a hearing is able to hear, and speak to, each of the other persons taking part; and - at the commencement of such a hearing each such person acknowledges his presence and that he or she accepts that the proceedings will be deemed to be a hearing before the Court. (2) A person may not cease to take part in a hearing conducted in accordance with this rule by disconnecting his telephone or other means of communication unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of the Judge or Registrar and a person must be conclusively presumed to have been present at all times during the hearing unless he or she has previously obtained the express consent of Judge or Registrar to leave the hearing. [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftnref1) Order inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), substituted by [S.I. 315 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/315/made/en/print?q 315&years 2018), effective 2 September 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Order 23 - Provision of Educational Assistance to Dependents","Order 17 - Support for Elderly Relatives","Order 68 - Health Care Benefits for Veterans'' Families","Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children"],"justification":"# Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children - Court: District # **Order 54: Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1976'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Taxation Act 1976 (No. 10 of 1976)","The Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 (No. 11 of 1976)","The Environmental Protection Act 1976 (No. 15 of 1976)","The Copyright Act 1976 (No. 23 of 1976)"],"justification":"“**the Act of 1976**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No. 11 of 1976);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions. 1. In this Order— “**the Act of 1976**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No. 11 of 1976); the “**Act of 1987**” means the [Status of Children Act 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/26) (No. 26 of 1987); the “**Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995); the “**Act of 1996**” means the [Family Law (Divorce) Act 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) (No. 33 of 1996); the “**Act of 2010**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (No. 24 of 2010); the “**Act of 2015**” means the [Children and Family Relationships Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) (No. 9 of 2015); “**competent authority**” has the meaning assigned to it in [Order 98]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-98-District-Social-welfare).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Clerk certifies that the proceedings are urgent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.","The case is automatically dismissed due to the declaration of urgency by the Clerk.","The proceedings are delayed until a special session can be convened.","The Clerk must then adjourn all other cases to prioritize the urgent proceedings."],"justification":"the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2.(1) Subject to the provisions of [Order 41B]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41B-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-Outside-The-State-Without-The-Permission-Of-The-Court), proceedings under the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Acts should proceedings be heard otherwise than in public?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings under the Act of 1966 or the Act of 2000","Proceedings under the Act of 1976 or the Act of 2010","Proceedings under the Act of 1986 or the Act of 2005","Proceedings under the Act of 1996 or the Act of 2015"],"justification":"Proceedings under the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* 3. Proceedings under the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What forms can an order for lump sum payments take under the 1995 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The order can be in the form of Forms 54.01, 54.02, 54.03, or 54.04 Schedule A.","The order can be in the form of Forms 54.20, 54.21, 54.22, or 54.23 Schedule","The order can be in the form of Forms 54.24, 54.25, 54.26, or 54.27 Schedule","The order can be in the form of Forms 54.28, 54.29, 54.30, or 54.31 Schedule"],"justification":"the order of the Court may be in the Form [54.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b4eb2ec-ced5-4096-a26e-24453a5d88af/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) (A) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.24.docx/docx/1), [54.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e410ed40-f291-4a4c-94c5-bd9fdce034a0/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.25.docx/docx/1), [54.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cf6f0e07-c4ec-4d7d-a727-c0edcd16c7a4/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.26.docx/docx/1) or [54.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/101a15ef-86bb-4452-be5b-f71ea3f71e6d/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(2) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where, under the powers conferred by section 42 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) or, as the case ma\y be, under the powers conferred by section 51 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), an order is made in the District Court providing for the making of a lump sum payment or lump sum payments, the order of the Court may be in the Form [54.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b4eb2ec-ced5-4096-a26e-24453a5d88af/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) (A) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.24.docx/docx/1), [54.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e410ed40-f291-4a4c-94c5-bd9fdce034a0/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5 (1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.25.docx/docx/1), [54.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cf6f0e07-c4ec-4d7d-a727-c0edcd16c7a4/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(1) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.26.docx/docx/1) or [54.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/101a15ef-86bb-4452-be5b-f71ea3f71e6d/Lump sum maintenance order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 5A(2) - Family Law Act, 1995 section 42 No. 54.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can either party apply to discharge or vary a maintenance order made by the District Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Under section of the Act of 1968","Under section of the Act of 1972","Under section 5(2)(a) of the Act of 1980","Under section of the Act of 1976"],"justification":"by either party to the proceedings under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) to discharge or vary a maintenance order made by the District Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to discharge or vary maintenance order.* 5.(1) An application: - (a) by a maintenance debtor for the discharge of a maintenance order under section 6(1)(a) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by either party to the proceedings under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) to discharge or vary a maintenance order made by the District Court, or - by a maintenance debtor for the discharge of part of a maintenance order under section 6(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by the maintenance creditor, the maintenance debtor or the Clerk on whose application the order was made, for an order discharging or varying an attachment of earnings order under section 17(1) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - by either party to the proceedings under section 46 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) to discharge, vary or terminate a maintenance order made by the District Court, or - by either party to the proceedings under section 173(6) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) to vary or discharge an order or to suspend or revive a provision of an order made under section 175 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), or - by the maintenance creditor, the maintenance debtor or the Clerk on whose application the order was made, for an order discharging or varying an attachment of earnings order under section 183(1) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24),'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What forms can the court use for the order when an application is made to discharge or vary a maintenance order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 63.09","Form 54.10 or Form 54.12","Form 78.15","Form 45.07"],"justification":"The order of the Court on the application may be in the [Form 54.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9a42b3fc-e8ee-4e34-8f78-1c508e8a1ee2/Order discharging maintenance order or part thereof No. 54.10.docx/docx/1) or [54.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/401889bb-1270-4f1b-b982-525f03e1ea02/Order discharging maintenance order varying No. 54.12.docx/docx/1) , Schedule with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], 'must be preceded by the completion by the applicant of an application form in the [Form 54.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/674d4ee7-8dd2-4342-b325-2a3c7a9a6454/Summons to discharge maintenance order or part thereof - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application form, the Clerk shall issue a maintenance summons in the [Form 54.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cfbc556f-537f-4880-bf03-7333a56ff05e/Maintenance Summons - Family Law (Maintenance Of Spouses And Children) Act, 1976 section as amended No. 54.2.docx/docx/1). The maintenance summons and a copy of the application form must be served on the maintenance debtor and on any other person who would be affected by the making of the order sought by the maintenance creditor. (2) The order of the Court on the application may be in the [Form 54.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9a42b3fc-e8ee-4e34-8f78-1c508e8a1ee2/Order discharging maintenance order or part thereof No. 54.10.docx/docx/1) or [54.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/401889bb-1270-4f1b-b982-525f03e1ea02/Order discharging maintenance order varying No. 54.12.docx/docx/1) , Schedule with the necessary modifications where the order is made under the 2010 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What form can an interim order take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["[Form 54.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 54.13.docx/docx/1) Schedule","[Form 54.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 54.14.docx/docx/1) Schedule A","[Form 55.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 55.13.docx/docx/1) Schedule","[Form 48.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 48.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule"],"justification":"[Form 54.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 54.13.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Interim order.* 6. An interim order made by the Court under: - (a) section 7 of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11), or - section 47 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), may be in the [Form 54.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4127f01-aaaf-493e-bf07-f3bdf53db3b1/Interim order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 section 7 No. 54.13.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given for an application to have payments made to the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least 7 days prior to the date of the intended application.","At least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application.","At least 1 week and 1 day prior to the date of the intended application.","At least 24 hours prior to the date of the intended application."],"justification":"Notice of such application in the [Form 54.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a799024a-e277-4b7c-8d88-f0511d68a317/Notice of application to have payments made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 54.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for direction that payments be made to Clerk.* 8. An application under section of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), for a direction that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order be made to the Clerk may be made parte. Notice of such application in the [Form 54.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a799024a-e277-4b7c-8d88-f0511d68a317/Notice of application to have payments made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 54.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the maintenance creditor or by his or her solicitor, must be lodged with the Clerk at least 48 hours prior to the date of the intended application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 54.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b8241e4b-354d-4b09-afaa-780b16bbca6c/Order directing that payments under a maintenance - variation - interim order shall be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.17.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What action must the Clerk take when directed by the Court to receive payments under a maintenance order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk must send a notice to the maintenance debtor indicating where, when, and how payments should be made.","The Clerk must notify the maintenance debtor that payments should be sent directly to the court without specifying any details.","The Clerk must deposit all maintenance payments into the court’s general fund.","The Clerk must personally collect the payment from the maintenance debtor each month."],"justification":"Where the Court directs that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order shall be made to the Clerk, such Clerk must send a notice in the [Form 54.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/53087a22-e64e-4dd0-ae24-dc1108d8b618/Notice of direction that payments be made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.18.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations, by prepaid ordinary post to the maintenance debtor indicating the place at which and the days and hours during which payments under the order should be made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payments to the Clerk.* 9.(1) Where the Court directs that payments under a maintenance order, a variation order or an interim order shall be made to the Clerk, such Clerk must send a notice in the [Form 54.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/53087a22-e64e-4dd0-ae24-dc1108d8b618/Notice of direction that payments be made to district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.18.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations, by prepaid ordinary post to the maintenance debtor indicating the place at which and the days and hours during which payments under the order should be made. (2) The Clerk shall give a receipt to the maintenance debtor for each payment made by him or her and shall transmit such payment to the maintenance creditor or, if authorised in writing by the maintenance creditor so to do, the Clerk may transmit the payment to the competent authority.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served upon the maintenance creditor when a maintenance debtor applies to discharge a direction?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 54.19","Form 54.18","Form 54.21","Form 54.20"],"justification":"summons in the [Form 54.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0644dad-4442-43cb-a658-6bc384ed3425/Summons to discharge direction that payments under - maintenance - variation - interim order be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to discharge direction.* 10. An application under section 9(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section 50(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), by a maintenance debtor to have a direction under section 9(1) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or, as the case may be, section 50(1) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), discharged must be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance creditor of a summons in the [Form 54.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0644dad-4442-43cb-a658-6bc384ed3425/Summons to discharge direction that payments under - maintenance - variation - interim order be made to the district court clerk - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 54.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9146ff2b-d4fc-4674-ac6f-e6935acd99ce/Order discharging direction that payments under maintenance - variation - interim order be made to the district court clerk No. 54.20.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary adaptations.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must a summons be served according to Order 54?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At least 30 days before the date of the sitting of the Court","Immediately before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least 7 days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court"],"justification":"A summons (and any document required to accompany it) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the summons is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of summonses.* 12.(1) A summons (and any document required to accompany it) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the summons is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, a statutory declaration as to service of the summons (and any other document concerned) must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Acts can the Clerk receive orders for maintenance pending suit, periodical payments orders, or secured periodical payments orders?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk can receive orders under the Act of 1995, the Act of 1996, and the Act of 2010.","The Clerk can receive orders under the Act of 1993, the Act of 1994, and the Act of 1997.","The Clerk can receive orders under the Act of 1985, the Act of 1986, and the Act of 1990.","The Clerk can receive orders under the Act of 2005, the Act of 2006, and the Act of 2009."],"justification":"of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 18 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 22 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html), or - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Rules to apply to orders for maintenance pending suit etc.* 13. Where the Clerk receives a copy— - (a) of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 18 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 22 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html), or - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), from the Registrar of the Court which made that order, and payments under the order are directed to be made to the District Court Clerk (as provided for in section 20 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) and in section 28 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) (or, as the case may be, section 50, or section 50 as applied by section 134 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24))), such Clerk shall register particulars of the order and shall proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'Who can apply to the court to secure periodical payments?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any individual who has filed a complaint in the same court","Only the primary litigant in the case","Only legal entities registered as stakeholders in the proceedings","Any person having an interest in the proceedings"],"justification":"by any person having an interest in the proceedings to secure the said payments to the maintenance creditor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Orders to secure payments.* 14.(1) Where the Court has made an order providing for periodical payments by way of support or maintenance by a maintenance debtor to a maintenance creditor, an application may be made to the Court on a date subsequent to the date on which such order is made pursuant to the provisions of section 41 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) or, as the case may be, section 52 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), by any person having an interest in the proceedings to secure the said payments to the maintenance creditor. (2) Such application must be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 54.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd67ed61-5ef9-4380-9150-6bce33999806/Application to secure maintenance payments - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 & Family Law Act, 1995 No. 54.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order of the Court granting such application may be in the [Form 54.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/00f50b6b-fa81-4e47-8694-8b7a20287e61/Order to secure maintenance payments - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 54.23.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used when the Court grants an application for an order to procure a report on welfare questions?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["[Form 58.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a4c3e9e1-7f3b-49f3-8b97-5e51c5e45f4e/Order for specific issue - Children Act 1987, section 14 No. 58.55.docx/docx/1), Schedule","[Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order directing report - Family Law Act 1995, section 47 No. 58.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule","[Form 58.45](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4e4b7e6c-6f3d-4e3f-a58f-cd4439e0399c/Order for custody or access - Children Act 1987, section 16 No. 58.45.docx/docx/1), Schedule","[Form 58.60](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9e5b6a4d-5f4d-4932-9e2e-df8436b89c33/Order for maintenance pending litigation - Family Law Act 1995, section 46 No. 58.60.docx/docx/1), Schedule A."],"justification":"the order requisitioning the report may be in the [Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order directing report - Family Law Act 1995, section 47 No. 58.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report under section 47 of the Act of 1976.* 16.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order giving directions for the purpose of procuring a report in writing on any question affecting the welfare of a party to the proceedings or any other person to whom they relate may be included in writing in the application form or summons, or made at the hearing. (2) Where the Court grants an application for an order mentioned in sub-rule (1), or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report may be in the [Form 58.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dd29f42a-afc3-46dc-b17f-17dfbd57359a/Order directing report - Family Law Act 1995, section 47 No. 58.50.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54 substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Act does Order 54A operate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Family Law Reform Act 1969","Marriage Act 1944","Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010","Domestic Relations Act 1968"],"justification":"Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 - Court: District # Order 54A: Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Data Protection Act 2010 (No. 24 of 2010)","The Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 (No. 24 of 2010)","The Marriage Act 2010 (No. 24 of 2010)","The Employment Equality Act 2010 (No. 24 of 2010)"],"justification":"“**the Act**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2010)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - “**the Act**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2010).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under the Act be brought, heard and determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before any local magistrate where either party to the proceedings has previously conducted business.","At any sitting of the Tribunal for the court area where either party to the proceedings is currently located.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","In any federal court regardless of the location of the parties involved in the proceedings."],"justification":"Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2.(1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situate, certifies on a summons or a notice of application that the proceedings are urgent, the summons or notice may be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at, any sitting of the Court in that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'How should proceedings under the Act be conducted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings under the Act shall be conducted in public unless a specific exception applies.","Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public.","Proceedings under the Act shall be conducted exclusively in public.","Proceedings under the Act shall be conducted in the presence of all media representatives."],"justification":"Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the Act shall be heard otherwise than in public. # Shared Home Protection'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for issuing a notice in an application under section 34(1) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["[Form 60]","[Form 60.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1)","[Form 60.2]","[Form 59]"],"justification":"An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(1) of the Act* 4. An application by a civil partner under section 34(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the other civil partner from disposing of or removing household chattels shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f86fb3ab-d9fc-4b3e-9d67-b7af5da927dd/Order prohibiting - disposition - removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a summons be issued in when a civil partner complains under section 34(3) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 60.5 Schedule A with necessary modifications","Form 60.5 Schedule with necessary modifications","Form 60.6 Schedule without any modifications","Form 60.4 Schedule with necessary modifications"],"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 34(3) of the Act* 5. Where complaint is made by a civil partner to a Judge under section 34(3) of the Act that the other civil partner has contravened the provisions of section 34(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the court''s order granting the application under section 34(4) of the Act be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["[Form 75.1](https://www.example.com/form751.pdf)","[Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1)","[Form 60.8](https://www.example.com/form608.pdf)","[Form 45.2](https://www.example.com/form452.pdf)"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(4) of the Act* 6. An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the summons take when a complaint is made under section 39 of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 59.8 Schedule without any modifications","Form 60.7 Schedule with necessary modifications","Form 61.8 Schedule A with necessary modifications","Form 60.8 Schedule with necessary modifications"],"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 39 of the Act* 7. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 39 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What order''s provisions apply to proceedings under section 34(5) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order 56","Order 42A (Third Party Procedure)","Order 34","Order 42"],"justification":"The provisions of [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure) (Third Party Procedure) shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 34(5) of the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Joinder of parties* 8. The provisions of [Order 42A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42A-District-Third-Party-Procedure) (Third Party Procedure) shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 34(5) of the Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in when declaring a conveyance void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 70.30","Form 60.10","Form 60.05","Form 50.20"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order%20declaring%20a%20conveyance%20void%20-%20Family%20Home%20Protection%20Act%201976%20No.%2060.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person do after instituting proceedings to declare a conveyance void under section 28(1) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Serve a notice of appeal to the court within 14 days of filing the proceedings.","Publish a public notice in a national newspaper within 7 days of initiating the proceedings.","Cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009.","Obtain a certificate from a solicitor confirming the validity of the conveyance."],"justification":"A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of section 28(1) of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the [Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Lis Pendens* (3) A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of section 28(1) of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the [Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What document must be annexed to the notice of application if it is alleged that the civil partner is incapable of consenting?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist","original certificate in writing by a general practitioner","a notarized affidavit from a close family member","a sworn statement from a mental health social worker"],"justification":"Where it is alleged that the civil partner whose consent is required under section 28 of the Act is incapable of consenting, the original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist, within the meaning of the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), shall be annexed to the notice of application lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order dispensing with consent or giving consent* 10. (1) An application for an order under section 29(1), section 29(3) or section 29(4) of the Act to dispense with, or as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, of a civil partner to the conveyance of the shared home shall be in the [Form 54A.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1584a21-776d-486c-88ad-e98591ac402b/Notice of Application to -dispense with consent †give consent of civil partner to conveyance of shared home No. 54A.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where it is alleged that the civil partner whose consent is required under section 28 of the Act is incapable of consenting, the original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist, within the meaning of the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), shall be annexed to the notice of application lodged with the Clerk. The Court may accept affidavit evidence of the certification, subject to the right of any party contesting the certification to cross-examine. (3) The order of the Court on such an application shall be in the [Form 54A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f66baa3-063e-4444-b063-9edd66eb2db2/Order -Dispensing with Consent †Giving Consent of Civil Partner to Conveyance of Shared Home - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 29 No. 54A.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4) On granting an application under section 29 of the Act to dispense with or, as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, the Court may order pursuant to section 33 of the [Trustee Act 1893](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1893/act/53/enacted/en/print.html) that a person be appointed to execute the conveyance of the interest in question and the order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6232d23b-0016-4559-a960-0b355c5c68c0/Order appointing a person to execute consent to conveyance of family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 4(1) No. 60.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application to the Court for an order under section 30(1) of the Act for the protection of the shared home be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 60","Form 60.25","Form 60.17","Form 60.16"],"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under section 30(1) of the Act for the protection of the shared home in the interest of the applicant civil partner or a dependant child of the civil partners shall be in the [Form 60.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Protection of Shared Home* 11.(1) An application to the Court for an order under section 30(1) of the Act for the protection of the shared home in the interest of the applicant civil partner or a dependant child of the civil partners shall be in the [Form 60.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6342e31-1520-448a-9ee7-509e76cd2abf/Order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(1) No. 60.17.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court order be made in when granting compensation for loss of interest in the shared home?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 60.19","Form 70.05","Form 45.23","Form 60.21"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Conduct leading to loss of Shared Home* 12.(1) An application to the Court for an order under section 30(2) of the Act to compensate the applicant civil partner or a dependant child of the civil partners for loss of interest in the shared home occasioned by the conduct of the other civil partner shall be in the [Form 60.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3ae2cb1e-21c5-4e31-92a0-2a6a60b55277/Application for an order for compensation for loss relating to the family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(2) No. 60.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served on the legal personal representative of a qualified cohabitant when applying for an order under section 194?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form","Form","Form 54A.1","Form"],"justification":"summons in the [Form 54A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e0402f-8d78-4ea1-ac0b-d7dad17d58e3/Summons - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 194 No. 54A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 194* 13. An application by a qualified cohabitant for an order under section 194 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the legal personal representative of the cohabitant of a summons in the [Form 54A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e0402f-8d78-4ea1-ac0b-d7dad17d58e3/Summons - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 194 No. 54A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 54A substituted in full by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme Court","District","High Court","Magistrates Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings - Court: District #'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1995'' refer to in Order 56?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act, 1995 (No. 26 of 1995)","The Family Law Act, 1995 (No. 26 of 1995)","The Employment Relations Act, 1995 (No. 26 of 1995)","The Criminal Law Act, 1995 (No. 26 of 1996)"],"justification":"“**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions. 1.[1] In this Order — “**the Act**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11/enacted/en/html) (No. 11 of 1976); “**the Act of 1995**” means the [Family Law Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1995); “**competent authority**” has the meaning assigned to it in [Order 98]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-98-District-Social-welfare) of these Rules;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under this Order be brought, heard or determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings under this Order can only be brought, heard or determined at the Supreme Court in the capital city regardless of where the parties reside.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where neither party to the proceedings resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where the proceedings were initiated, irrespective of the location of residence or professional activities of the parties."],"justification":"Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Venue. 2. (1) Proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides, or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Where are attachment of earnings hearings held?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["In a public courtroom","Within the chambers of a judge","Otherwise than in public.","During a private arbitration session"],"justification":"(2) such proceedings shall be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* (2) such proceedings shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for the court order after granting an attachment of earnings application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 57.3 Writ of Execution","Form [56.3] or [56.4] Schedule","Form 56.2 Notice of Hearing","Form 56.1 Order to Show Cause"],"justification":"the order of the Court shall be in accordance with Form [56.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a225df3-572c-4c7e-8dbf-c9b2a7ac2c0c/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.3.docx/docx/1) or [56.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/737fe077-d48e-44fb-afc3-dc7f3b20872e/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application.* 3.[2] An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons in the Form [56.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bf99d413-4010-4654-a8b2-838840cd81af/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) Section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.1.docx/docx/1) or [56.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/689f01ce-dd1a-44c1-8127-b34a84073475/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be. Where the Court grants the application or, where the Court, having made an antecedent order, makes, in accordance with subsection (1A) (a) of the Act, as inserted by the Act of 1995, an attachment of earnings order in the same proceedings in order to secure payments under the antecedent order, the order of the Court shall be in accordance with Form [56.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a225df3-572c-4c7e-8dbf-c9b2a7ac2c0c/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.3.docx/docx/1) or [56.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/737fe077-d48e-44fb-afc3-dc7f3b20872e/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'How can service be effected under Order 56?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By handing the order directly to any member of the person''s immediate family who resides at the person''s last known address.","By delivering a copy of the order via email to the person''s last known email address.","By posting the order on the official court website and assuming it has been seen by the person to be served.","By leaving a copy of the order at, or sending a copy of the order by registered prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of the person to be served."],"justification":"Such service may be effected by leaving a copy of the order at, or sending a copy of the order by registered prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of the person to be served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mode of service.* 5. Such service may be effected by leaving a copy of the order at, or sending a copy of the order by registered prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of the person to be served. A copy of the order shall also be sent by registered prepaid post to the maintenance debtor.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'How does the Clerk send the payment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["via fax","by email","in person","by post"],"justification":"The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Payment by Clerk.* 7. The Clerk may send by post any payment received by him or her under an attachment of earnings order to the person entitled thereto.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'How should the Clerk serve the order on the person to whom it is directed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["by delivering a verbal notification of the order during a public event in any state","by sending a copy by prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State","by handing over a printed copy of the order at their last known international address","by faxing the order directly to their personal email address outside the state"],"justification":"The Clerk shall cause the order to be served upon the person to whom it is directed by sending a copy thereof by prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of such person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order requiring statement of particulars.* 8. An order under section 13 (1) of the Act requiring a statement of particulars of a maintenance debtor’s earnings shall be in accordance with [Form 56.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55da6c2-3c16-41c9-b312-825be96ac80a/Order of the court requiring statement of particulars of maintenance debtor''s earnings - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.5.docx/docx/1)Schedule The Clerk shall cause the order to be served upon the person to whom it is directed by sending a copy thereof by prepaid post to the residence or place of business in the State of such person.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments are earnings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The filing of a complaint by any party involved in the proceedings","The issuance of a notice of intent to review earnings to all relevant parties","The submission of a written affidavit regarding the nature of the payments","The issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule upon each of the other parties to the proceedings."],"justification":"shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule upon each of the other parties to the proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for determination as to earnings.* 9. An application under section 15 of the Act for a determination as to whether payments of a particular class or description are earnings for the purposes of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons (Form 56.6 Schedule upon each of the other parties to the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'Who are the parties to proceedings in respect of an application under rule 9?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The employee, the creditor, and the person who receives payments under the contract.","The employee, the maintenance creditor, and the individual who is owed maintenance payments.","The employer, the maintenance debtor and the person to whom payments under the order are being made.","The employer, the debtor, and the beneficiary of the trust fund."],"justification":"The parties to proceedings in respect of an application under rule 9 shall be the employer, the maintenance debtor and the person to whom payments under the order are being made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Parties to such proceedings Order of Court.* 10. The parties to proceedings in respect of an application under rule 9 shall be the employer, the maintenance debtor and the person to whom payments under the order are being made. The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with Form 56.7 Schedule A copy of such order shall be sent by the Clerk by prepaid post to each of the parties to the proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54 - Maintenance of Spouses, Civil Partners and Children', 'Court Rules', 'What actions should the Clerk take when receiving a copy of an order for maintenance pending suit, periodical payments order, or secured periodical payments order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk should notify all parties involved via email and then proceed to distribute copies of the order to relevant departments.","The Clerk should register particulars of the order and proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned.","The Clerk should amend the order to reflect additional details before registering it with the court.","The Clerk should file the order in the court''s archive without taking any further action."],"justification":"such Clerk shall register particulars of the order and shall proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Rules to apply to orders for maintenance pending suit etc.* 13. Where the Clerk receives a copy— - (a) of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 18 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html), - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) or of any such order as aforesaid as affected by an order under section 22 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html), or - of an order for maintenance pending suit, of a periodical payments order or of a secured periodical payments order made under the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), from the Registrar of the Court which made that order, and payments under the order are directed to be made to the District Court Clerk (as provided for in section 20 of the [Act of 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/26/enacted/en/html) and in section 28 of the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/33/enacted/en/html) (or, as the case may be, section 50, or section 50 as applied by section 134 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24))), such Clerk shall register particulars of the order and shall proceed in relation thereto as if it were a maintenance order made at a sitting of the District Court for the district court area to which that Clerk is assigned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What court is associated with Order 54A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","Supreme","High","Magistrate"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 - Court: District # Order 54A: Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served on the respondent civil partner before an application under section 34(4) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 60.5","[Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1)","Form","Form 12A"],"justification":"the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under section 34(4) of the Act* 6. An application by a civil partner under section 34(4) of the Act for an order that the respondent civil partner provide household chattels for the applicant civil partner or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent civil partner of a notice in the [Form 60.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications, a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent civil partner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Which order''s provisions apply in cases where a summons is issued under section 39 of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order 20","Order 15","Order 14","Order 16"],"justification":"The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under section 39 of the Act* 7. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 39 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule with the necessary modifications. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application to the Court be in to declare a conveyance void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 70.1","Form 60.9","Form 50.3","Form 60.8"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application%20to%20have%20conveyance%20declared%20void%20No.%2060.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 54A - Other Proceedings Under the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application for an order under sections 29(1), 29(3), or 29(4) of the Act to dispense with or give consent required under section 28 of the Act be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form 54A.2","Form","Form 54A.3"],"justification":"An application for an order under section 29(1), section 29(3) or section 29(4) of the Act to dispense with, or as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, of a civil partner to the conveyance of the shared home shall be in the [Form 54A.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1584a21-776d-486c-88ad-e98591ac402b/Notice of Application to -dispense with consent †give consent of civil partner to conveyance of shared home No. 54A.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order dispensing with consent or giving consent* 10. (1) An application for an order under section 29(1), section 29(3) or section 29(4) of the Act to dispense with, or as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, of a civil partner to the conveyance of the shared home shall be in the [Form 54A.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a1584a21-776d-486c-88ad-e98591ac402b/Notice of Application to -dispense with consent †give consent of civil partner to conveyance of shared home No. 54A.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) Where it is alleged that the civil partner whose consent is required under section 28 of the Act is incapable of consenting, the original certificate in writing by a consultant psychiatrist, within the meaning of the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), shall be annexed to the notice of application lodged with the Clerk. The Court may accept affidavit evidence of the certification, subject to the right of any party contesting the certification to cross-examine. (3) The order of the Court on such an application shall be in the [Form 54A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5f66baa3-063e-4444-b063-9edd66eb2db2/Order -Dispensing with Consent †Giving Consent of Civil Partner to Conveyance of Shared Home - Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010, section 29 No. 54A.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4) On granting an application under section 29 of the Act to dispense with or, as the case may be, to give, the consent required under section 28 of the Act, the Court may order pursuant to section 33 of the [Trustee Act 1893](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1893/act/53/enacted/en/print.html) that a person be appointed to execute the conveyance of the interest in question and the order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6232d23b-0016-4559-a960-0b355c5c68c0/Order appointing a person to execute consent to conveyance of family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 4(1) No. 60.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used when applying for an attachment of earnings order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 56.2 Application","Form 56.3 Schedule A","Form [56.1] or [56.2] Schedule","Form 54.1 Schedule"],"justification":"An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons in the Form [56.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bf99d413-4010-4654-a8b2-838840cd81af/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) Section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.1.docx/docx/1) or [56.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/689f01ce-dd1a-44c1-8127-b34a84073475/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application.* 3.[2] An application for an attachment of earnings order under section 10 of the Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the maintenance debtor of a summons in the Form [56.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bf99d413-4010-4654-a8b2-838840cd81af/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) Section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.1.docx/docx/1) or [56.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/689f01ce-dd1a-44c1-8127-b34a84073475/Attachment of earnings summons - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be. Where the Court grants the application or, where the Court, having made an antecedent order, makes, in accordance with subsection (1A) (a) of the Act, as inserted by the Act of 1995, an attachment of earnings order in the same proceedings in order to secure payments under the antecedent order, the order of the Court shall be in accordance with Form [56.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a225df3-572c-4c7e-8dbf-c9b2a7ac2c0c/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.3.docx/docx/1) or [56.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/737fe077-d48e-44fb-afc3-dc7f3b20872e/Attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 (as amended) section 10 (1) (A) (iii) No. 56.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What document must be issued and served before an application to vary or discharge an attachment of earnings order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["an affidavit","a warrant","a subpoena","A summons"],"justification":"An application under section 17 of the Act for the variation or discharge of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to vary or discharge attachment of earnings order.* 11. An application under section 17 of the Act for the variation or discharge of an attachment of earnings order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons ([Form 56.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/48a13e52-8edd-4ff7-a05d-8cbc5e1842cb/Summons to vary or discharge attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.8.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the maintenance creditor and/or the maintenance debtor, as the case may be. The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in accordance with [Form 56.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0526426a-fae3-4939-aeb1-f22b846c7f1b/Order varying - discharging attachment of earnings order - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act, 1976 No. 56.9.docx/docx/1) Schedule The Clerk or the maintenance creditor, as the case may be, shall cause the order to be served upon the employer in the manner prescribed in rule 5 of this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to proceedings commenced under section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1940 when an attachment of earnings order is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The attachment of earnings order shall be disregarded, and the proceedings under section 8 will proceed independently.","The proceedings shall lapse and any warrant or order issued or made under that section shall cease to have effect.","The proceedings shall continue as if no attachment of earnings order was made.","The proceedings under section 8 will be suspended indefinitely until further notice."],"justification":"any proceedings commenced under section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), shall lapse and any warrant or order issued or made under that section in any such proceedings shall cease to have effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Cesser of warrant and lapse of enforcement proceedings.* 13. Where an attachment of earnings order has been made, any proceedings commenced under section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), shall lapse and any warrant or order issued or made under that section in any such proceedings shall cease to have effect.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 56 - Attachment Of Earnings', 'Court Rules', 'What additional information must the Clerk prove during the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk must also prove the debtor''s criminal history.","The Clerk must also prove the amount of arrears due.","The Clerk must also prove the debtor''s employment status.","The Clerk must also prove the debtor''s current address."],"justification":"The Clerk shall also prove the amount of arrears due."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to produce documents.* 14. On the hearing of an application for an attachment of earnings order the Clerk to whom payments under the maintenance order, variation order, interim order, or enforceable maintenance order are payable shall tender as evidence - - (a) the maintenance order, variation order, interim order (as the case may be) and in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order, - the request in writing received by the Clerk from the maintenance creditor, - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court, and - any other relevant document. The Clerk shall also prove the amount of arrears due. [1] Order 56 rule 1 amended by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [2] Order 56 rule 3 substituted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What is the definition of ''child'' in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A person who has not reached the age of majority","A person who is still enrolled in primary education","An individual under the age of 18","A person who has not attained full age"],"justification":"“**child**” means a person who has not attained full age;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - “**the 1964 Act**” means the [Guardianship of Infants Act 1964](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (No. 7 of 1964); “**the 1987 Act**” means the [Status of Children Act 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/26/enacted/en/html) (No. 26 of 1987); “**the 1997 Act**’’ means the [Children Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html) (No. 40 of 1997); “**the 2015 Act**” means the [Children and Family Relationships Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) (No. 9 of 2015); “**child**” means a person who has not attained full age; “**intending parent**” has the meaning assigned to it in section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under the 1964 Act be brought, heard or determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before any administrative agency designated by the government, rather than in a formal court setting.","At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the parties involved in the proceedings.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where any party to the proceedings resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","In the court area where the incident leading to the proceedings occurred, irrespective of the residence or business location of the parties."],"justification":"Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where any party to the proceedings resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2.(1) Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where any party to the proceedings resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (2) Where, however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on an originating document that the proceedings are urgent, the said originating document may, subject to the provisions of rule 10, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which an applicant ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or where no applicant under that section ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation in the State, at any sitting of the Court for the Dublin Metropolitan District.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances will proceedings concerning a child under 18 years be heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["All proceedings involving children under 18 years old must be conducted in private only if the child requests it.","Proceedings concerning a child under 18 years shall always be held in public to ensure transparency.","Proceedings under the 1964 Act and proceedings under section 21 of the 2015 Act concerning a child under the age of 18 years shall be heard otherwise than in public.","Proceedings concerning a child under 18 years shall be heard in public unless the court orders otherwise."],"justification":"Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) and proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) concerning a child under the age of 18 years shall be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) and proceedings under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) concerning a child under the age of 18 years shall be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Who must the notice and copy application form be served on when applying under section 6A of the 1964 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The local education authority and the school principal.","The other parent and any other guardian of the child.","The social services department and the child''s primary care physician.","The child''s legal representative and the court clerk."],"justification":"the notice and copy application form must be served on the other parent and on any other guardian of the child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of applications* 4. An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) may be begun by the completion by the applicant of an application form in the [Form 58.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application form, the Clerk will issue a notice in the [Form 58.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/850a2605-a072-411b-84e6-dfd3fd171597/Notice of application by surviving guardian - testamentary guardian for order - Guardianship of Infants Acts 1964, section 7(4) No. 58.3.docx/docx/1): - (a) under section 6A (as inserted by the 1987 Act and as substituted by section 48 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person who, being a parent of a child, is not a guardian of the child, for an order appointing the person as guardian of the child; the notice and copy application form must be served on the other parent and on any other guardian of the child; - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person who, not being a parent of a child, is eligible under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) to make such application for an order appointing the person as a guardian of the child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each person who is a parent or guardian of the child concerned and in the case of an application by a person to whom section 6C(2)(b) of the 1964 Act applies, the notice and copy application form must also be served upon the Child and Family Agency;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served on each person mentioned in section of the 1964 Act when applying for an order under section', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The notice and a summary of the application form along with a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 7.","Only the application form and a certified copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6.","The notice and copy application form and a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6.","A detailed statement of the applicant''s qualifications, a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6, and a letter of intent."],"justification":"the notice and copy application form and a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6 must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) appointing a nominated person as a guardian of the child, on the application of a qualifying guardian or nominated person under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form and a copy of the nomination signed in accordance with rule 6 must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a temporary guardian or the qualifying guardian concerned for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) on the application of a person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a declaration that a person named in the application is or is not a guardian, by virtue of the circumstances set out in section 2(4A) or of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), of a child named in the application (the “child concerned”): the notice and copy application form must be served on each person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) and upon any other person directed by the Court to be given notice of the application; - for an order under section 7(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 50 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on the surviving guardian or testamentary guardian of the child, as the case may be;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'When must notice and a copy of the application form be served on each guardian of the child when applying to remove a guardian under section 8(6) of the 1964 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The notice and copy application form must be posted on a public bulletin board within the jurisdiction.","The notice and copy application form must be sent via email to each guardian''s personal account.","The notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child.","The notice and copy application form must be served only on the primary guardian of the child."],"justification":"the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(2) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), unless the application is made by the surviving parent (in which case it can be made parte* in accordance with rule 5): where the application is not heard parte*, the notice and copy application form must be served on any person directed by the Court to be given notice of the application; - for an order to remove from office a guardian mentioned in section 8(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (substituted by section 51 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) and to appoint another guardian in his or her place under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order to appoint a guardian in place of a deceased guardian, under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), unless the child has no guardian, or the applicant is the only guardian (in which case it can be made parte* in accordance with rule 5): where the application is not heard parte*, the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order to remove from office a guardian mentioned in section 8(6) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 51 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child; - for an order giving the Court’s direction under section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html): the notice and copy application form must be served on each other person who is a parent or guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) giving a relative of a child or a person with whom the child resides or has formerly resided access to the child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each other guardian of the child concerned;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served on each guardian of the child when applying for an order under section of the 1964 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The application form and a letter of intent must be served on each guardian of the child concerned.","Each guardian of the child must be notified via email about the upcoming order under section of the 1964 Act.","The notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child concerned.","Only one guardian of the child needs to be served with the notice and application form."],"justification":"the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 57 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) giving a person mentioned in section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) custody of a child: the notice and copy application form must be served on each guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under Part III of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) for the production of a child: the notice and copy application form must be served on the person having custody of the child; - for an enforcement order under section 18A(1) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 60 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)): the notice and copy application form must be served on each parent and guardian of the child concerned; - for an order under section of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 60 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)), on the application of a parent or guardian of the child, requiring another guardian or parent to reimburse expenses incurred: the notice and copy application form must be served on each parent and guardian of the child concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What type of application must be made initially for an order to appoint a guardian under section 8(1) of the 1964 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["parte","appeal","inter partes","motion"],"justification":"An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall be made parte* in the first instance subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the [Form 58.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1):"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications parte* 5.(1) An application to the Court for any one or more of the following orders under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall be made parte* in the first instance subject to the prior lodgment with the Clerk of an application form in the [Form 58.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/684a0daf-43c8-4e4e-8ad2-885584c92c36/Notice of application by a person to be appointed a guardian - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section 6A No. 58.1.docx/docx/1): - (a) an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(1) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - an order to appoint a guardian or guardians under section 8(2) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the application is made by the surviving parent, - for an order to appoint a guardian in place of a deceased guardian, under section 8(5) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), where the child has no guardian, or the applicant is the only guardian;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a nomination under section of the 1964 Act be made in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 58.33 Schedule A","Form 58.32 Schedule","Form 58.30 Schedule","Form 58.31 Schedule"],"justification":"A nomination under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) by a qualifying guardian shall be in the [Form 58.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77911c9d-7de9-4045-a206-b5f9fd657ab8/Nomination - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section (inserted by section 49 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) No. 58.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Nomination* 6.(1) A nomination under section (as inserted by section 49 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) by a qualifying guardian shall be in the [Form 58.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77911c9d-7de9-4045-a206-b5f9fd657ab8/Nomination - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section (inserted by section 49 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) No. 58.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be signed and dated by the qualifying guardian concerned in the presence of a witness who is not the nominated person. (2) The original or a true copy of the nomination shall be annexed to the application form lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'Which Order''s provisions apply when a summons is issued for an alleged offence of failure or refusal to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The relevant provisions of Order 15 apply.","The relevant provisions of Order 12 apply.","The relevant provisions of Order 8 apply.","The relevant provisions of Order 23 apply."],"justification":"The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where complaint is made to a Judge alleging an offence of failure or refusal under section 5 of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986, to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order under section 7 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or section (inserted by the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the [Form 58.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3e57c96e-f893-4c05-8a0b-39b5d0b778d7/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.28.docx/docx/1) or [58.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b802823-d92d-4d19-9693-8aabef61b2ec/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued by the applicants before making an application to the court for a declaration of parentage?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 37","Form 102","Form 58.54","Form 58.62"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) for a declaration of parentage shall be preceded by the issue by the applicants of a notice in the [Form 58.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6a26fa7f-6bac-49a5-9c05-67fbbea7f3ba/Notice of Application for a declaration of parentage, Children and Family Relationships Act 2015, Section 21 No. 58.54.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for declaration of parentage: DAHR* 9.****[2]****(1) An application to the Court under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) for a declaration of parentage shall be preceded by the issue by the applicants of a notice in the [Form 58.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6a26fa7f-6bac-49a5-9c05-67fbbea7f3ba/Notice of Application for a declaration of parentage, Children and Family Relationships Act 2015, Section 21 No. 58.54.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The child to whom an application for a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) relates shall be named as a respondent to the application. (3) The application shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn by each applicant, and where necessary other affidavit evidence in support of the application, which shall: - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the child to whom the application relates is a child to whom section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, and in particular in a case to which section 20(1)(b)(ii) of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) applies, verify that the person who performed the DAHR procedure outside the State was authorised to do so under the law of the place where the procedure was performed and the law providing for such authorisation; - include, and verify, the facts grounding the statement that the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html) was, at the time referred to in section 20 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the intending parent of the child, and - (iii) in the case of the applicant referred to in section of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), confirm that he or she consents to the making of a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html). (4) True copies of the notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be served on each respondent not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing. (5) The original notice, affidavits and any exhibits thereto shall be lodged, together with a statutory declaration as to service, with the Clerk not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum service period for non-urgent proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least 21 days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least 30 days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least 7 days before the date of the sitting of the Court"],"justification":"A notice and copy application form (and any relevant court order) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents* 10.(1) A notice and copy application form (and any relevant court order) required by this Order to be served must be served upon the person to whom it is directed in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice is returnable. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2), the notice and copy application form (and any relevant court order) must be served at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice is returnable. (3) Additionally, in proceedings under: - section 6A (as inserted by section 12 of the 1987 Act and as substituted by section 48 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html); - section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or - (iii) section (inserted by section 9 of the 1987 Act) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), in which a solicitor is acting for the applicant, the notice and copy application form must be accompanied by a copy of a statutory declaration of the solicitor indicating, if it be the case, that the solicitor has complied with subsection (2) of section 20 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 11 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html) and as amended by section 24 of the Mediation Act 2017) in relation to the matter. The original statutory declaration must be filed with the Clerk. (4) A statutory declaration as to service of any notice, application form or court order served in accordance with rule 4 or rule 8 must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What is the Clerk required to do when the Court makes an order under the 1964 Act or a declaration under section 21 of the 2015 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk is required to give or send by ordinary post a copy of the order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made.","The Clerk is required to email a copy of the order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made.","The Clerk is required to publish the order or declaration in a national newspaper.","The Clerk is required to verbally inform each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made."],"justification":"the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11. Where the Court makes an order under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) or a declaration under section 21 of the [2015 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/9/enacted/en/html), the Clerk shall give, or send by ordinary post, a copy of such order or declaration to each person in whose favour or against whom the order or declaration was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'How can the age of a child be proven?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By producing a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the child’s birth or by such other evidence as the Court considers sufficient.","By presenting a letter from a pediatrician stating the estimated age of the child based on developmental milestones.","By showing a recent utility bill in the child''s name with the address where they were born.","By providing a copy of the child''s school report card which includes their date of birth."],"justification":"The age of a child may be proved by producing a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the child’s birth or by such other evidence as the Court considers sufficient."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proof of age* 12. The age of a child may be proved by producing a certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the child’s birth or by such other evidence as the Court considers sufficient.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the court have in proceedings under the 1964 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court may impose a fine on any person who fails to serve notice.","The court may direct the service of notice upon any person not already served.","The court may order the immediate arrest of any person not already served with notice.","The court may extend the statute of limitations for cases under the 1964 Act."],"justification":"the Court may direct the service of notice upon any person not already served"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court may direct service* 13. In any proceedings under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) the Court may direct the service of notice upon any person not already served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for an appeal from an order made under the 1964 Act to stay the operation of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The court must consult with the parties involved before making any decision on the stay.","The court must determine the conditions under which the stay will apply.","The court must enforce the order immediately regardless of any appeal.","The court must automatically grant the stay without reviewing the conditions."],"justification":"an appeal from an order made under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall stay the operation of the order only if, and to such extent and upon such terms (if any), as the Court shall determine."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Effect of appeal from orders* 14. Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 4 and Order 101 and that an appellant has entered into a recognizance for appeal, an appeal from an order made under the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) shall stay the operation of the order only if, and to such extent and upon such terms (if any), as the Court shall determine.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the Court give directions under section 20(2) of the Child Care Act 1991 regarding the care and custody of a child pending an investigation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 84.33","Form 85.11","Form 84.22","Form 95.67"],"justification":"an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where, under either 12A(4) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html) or section 20 of the Child Care Act 1991, the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Child and Family Agency to undertake an investigation of a child''s circumstances, if the Child and Family Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Child and Family Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s decision. (7) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the Child Care Act 1991 as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation by the Child and Family Agency — - (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. [1] Order 58 originally amended as per Schedule 1 to [S.I. 125 of 1999](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1999/si/125/made/en/print?q 125&years 1999), substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016, and resubstituted by [S.I. 434 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/434/made/en/print), effective 22 October 2020 and resubstituted by [S.I. 220 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/220/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [2] Order 58 rule 9 substituted by [S.I. 9 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/9/made/en/print?q 9&years 2018), effective 22 January 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 59 pertain to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Corporate Taxation","Domestic Violence","Environmental Regulations","Traffic Violations"],"justification":"Order 59 - Domestic Violence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 59 - Domestic Violence - Court: District # **Order 59: Domestic Violence**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''2018 Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act 2018 (No. 9 of 2018)","The Cybersecurity Act 2018 (No. 15 of 2018)","The Employment Act 2018 (No. 3 of 2018)","The Domestic Violence Act 2018 (No. 6 of 2018)"],"justification":"the “**2****018 Act**” means the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6) (No. 6 of 2018);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order- the “**2****018 Act**” means the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6) (No. 6 of 2018); “**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency, and unless the context otherwise requires, words and phrases used in this Order which are defined in section 2 of the 2018 Act have the same meaning as in the 2018 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under this Order be brought, heard and determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Before a sitting of the High Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court as residing, or a special sitting of the High Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act.","Before a sitting of the District Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court as residing, or a special sitting of the District Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act.","Before a sitting of any Magistrates'' Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court as residing, or a special sitting of the Magistrates'' Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act.","Before a sitting of the Supreme Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court as residing, or a special sitting of the Supreme Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act."],"justification":"Proceedings under this Order may be brought, heard and determined before: a sitting of the District Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 22(2) of the 2018 Act as residing or, if the application is for a barring order or an emergency barring order, where there is situate the place in relation to which that application is made, or a special sitting of the District Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings under this Order may be brought, heard and determined before: - a sitting of the District Court for the Court District in which the applicant resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 22(2) of the 2018 Act as residing or, if the application is for a barring order or an emergency barring order, where there is situate the place in relation to which that application is made, or - a special sitting of the District Court arranged in accordance with section 24(3) of the 2018 Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances must proceedings under the 2018 Act be heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings must be heard in public at all times, with no exceptions.","Proceedings must be heard otherwise than in public, subject to section 23 of the 2018 Act.","Proceedings can only be heard in private if the court requests it.","Proceedings must be heard in public unless the court orders otherwise under section 24 of the 2018 Act."],"justification":"Proceedings under the 2018 Act must, subject to section 23 of the 2018 Act, be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under the 2018 Act must, subject to section 23 of the 2018 Act, be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What is the first step an applicant must take to apply for a safety order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The applicant must contact their local police department to request a safety briefing.","The applicant must attend a mandatory counseling session before applying for a safety order.","The applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons and provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons.","The applicant must notify their employer and obtain a letter of support before applying."],"justification":"the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Safety Order* 4.(1) An application to the Court under section 6 of the 2018 Act for a safety order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a safety order may be in the [Form 59.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8782b974-2642-44b0-aa3d-f4396f780f8b/Safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 No. 59.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'How does the Clerk serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk serves the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent via email without requiring any acknowledgment of receipt.","The Clerk serves the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13.","The Clerk serves the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent by sending it through regular postal mail without any tracking or proof of delivery.","The Clerk serves the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent by posting it on their social media profile."],"justification":"the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Barring Order* 5.(1) An application to the Court under section 7 of the 2018 Act for a barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a barring order may be in the [Form 59.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55a5bf8-b6ee-4b19-a89c-4a9fefa0218c/Barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 7 No. 59.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Can an interim barring order be made parte even if the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An interim barring order can only be made after the summons required by rule 5 has been served.","Yes, an interim barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served.","An interim barring order can only be made parte if the summons required by rule 5 has been served at least 7 days prior.","No interim barring order can be made parte regardless of whether the summons required by rule 5 has been served or not."],"justification":"An interim barring order may be made parte notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Interim Barring Order* 6.(1) An application to the Court under section 8(1) of the 2018 Act for an interim barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons ( [Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)); - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An interim barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 5 has not yet been served. (3) An order of the Court granting an interim barring order may be in the [Form 59.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/63a952ab-89e5-4b08-8341-7fdf769a49df/Interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.7.docx/docx/1). (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an interim barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can an emergency barring order be made parte?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Where the application is made more than 7 days after the alleged incident.","Where the applicant has previously been convicted of a criminal offense.","Where the respondent consents to the order being made without notice.","Where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice having regard to the circumstances of the particular case."],"justification":"may, where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Emergency Barring Order* 7.(1) An application to the Court under section 9(3) of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order must, subject to sub-rule (3), be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 59.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f9afe07-f783-46db-ac43-344a44039615/Summons for an emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.17.docx/docx/1). (2) An application to the Court under section 9 of the 2018 Act for an emergency barring order: - may be made on the date on which the summons has been listed for hearing (provided the summons has been served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1); or - may, where the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant in the [Form 59.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/04f8a7c6-33ed-4d1b-aaad-f10b90686e35/Information - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 9 No. 59.18.docx/docx/1). (3) An emergency barring order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by sub-rule (1) has not been served. (4) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86fc13e3-6868-4b1a-801f-bce8b0bf749d/Emergency barring order - Domestic Violence Act section 9 No. 59.19.docx/docx/1). (5) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where an emergency barring order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What must an applicant do before applying for a protection order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The applicant must provide evidence of a criminal conviction related to domestic violence to the court clerk.","The applicant must submit a written declaration of intent to apply for a protection order to the local police department.","The applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a safety order and/or a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons.","The applicant must first attend a mandatory counseling session on conflict resolution before submitting any application."],"justification":"the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a safety order and/or a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Protection Order* 8.(1) An application to the Court under section 10(1) of the 2018 Act for a protection order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must have applied to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons in which a safety order and/or a barring order is sought, and the Clerk must have issued a Domestic Violence Summons; - where, having regard to the circumstances of the particular case, the Court considers it necessary or expedient in the interests of justice, the application may be made parte* grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the Applicant, or - where the application is not being made parte*, it may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 59.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2ee6a934-bfdd-4ee4-85e7-cd0462285716/Notice of motion for an interim barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 8 No. 59.5.docx/docx/1), to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant. (2) An order of the Court granting a protection order may be in the [Form 59.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5b60d519-6deb-4554-b964-a8866bdd5138/Protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.9.docx/docx/1). (3) A protection order may be made parte* notwithstanding the fact that the summons required by rule 4 or rule 5 has not yet been served. (4) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath, provided that where a protection order is made parte*, copies of the order and the grounding affidavit or information and a note of any oral evidence must be served on the respondent as soon as practicable.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an order of the Court granting an application to vary a safety order, barring order, interim barring order, emergency barring order, or protection order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 60.11","Form 59.21","Form 59.11","Form 49.11"],"justification":"An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df43420-af97-4146-811a-4b79576c72c2/Order varying a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.11.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Vary Safety/ Barring/ Interim Barring/ Emergency Barring Order/ Protection Order* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 6(8) to vary a safety order, section 7(12) to vary a barring order, section 8(7) to vary an interim barring order, section 9(8) to vary an emergency barring order or section 10(4) to vary a protection order, must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b921df5c-f0e6-42ab-bebf-e788db94793a/Summons to vary a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring order - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.10.docx/docx/1). (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df43420-af97-4146-811a-4b79576c72c2/Order varying a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.11.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'In what form may an order of the Court granting an application to discharge a safety order, barring order, interim barring order, emergency barring order, or protection order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 59.12, Schedule","Form 62.10, Schedule A","Form 59.13, Schedule","Form 48.7, Schedule"],"justification":"An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.13, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Discharge Safety/Barring/ Interim Barring / Emergency Barring/ Protection Order* 10.(1) An application to the Court under section 21 of the 2018 Act for the discharge of a safety order, a barring order, an interim barring order, an emergency barring order or a protection order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/10350a75-187a-4b09-9aad-e936cff77e2f/Summons to discharge a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 21 No. 59.12.docx/docx/1). (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c8f54875-17e0-4ea9-b50d-c84366e802bf/Order discharging a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 21 No. 59.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'How does the Clerk deliver a certified copy of a safety order or protection order to the Garda Síochána member in charge of the station where the protected person resides?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Through a private courier service without any form of certification","By prepaid registered post or, where agreed, by electronic mail.","In person during regular business hours at the Garda Síochána headquarters","By standard post without registration or any form of tracking"],"justification":"to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person for whose benefit the safety order or protection order was made resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a safety order or a protection order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such safety order or protection order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to supply copies of orders* 11.(1) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a safety order or a protection order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(1) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, the applicant for the safety order or barring order concerned, - to the respondent to the application for the safety order or in respect of a protection order, the respondent to the application for the safety order or barring order concerned, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the safety order or, in respect of a protection order, for the safety order or barring order, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person for whose benefit the safety order or protection order was made resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a safety order or a protection order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such safety order or protection order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (2) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a barring order or an interim barring order, the Clerk must, in accordance with section 19(2) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the barring order,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'To whom must the Clerk send a copy of an emergency barring order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk must send a copy of the emergency barring order to the applicant, the respondent, the Agency (if applicable), and the Garda Síochána station in charge of the area where the application was made.","The Clerk must send a copy of the emergency barring order to the applicant, the respondent, and the nearest Garda Síochána station, regardless of where the application was made.","The Clerk must send a copy of the emergency barring order only to the applicant and the respondent.","The Clerk must send a copy of the emergency barring order to the applicant, the respondent, and the Department of Justice."],"justification":"(3) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an emergency barring order, the Clerk must in accordance with section 19(3) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the emergency barring order, - to the respondent to the application for the emergency barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the emergency barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the emergency barring order was made, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- to the respondent to the application for the barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the barring order was made, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a barring order or an interim barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such barring order or interim barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail. (3) Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an emergency barring order, the Clerk must in accordance with section 19(3) of the 2018 Act, give or send a certified copy of the order as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant for the emergency barring order, - to the respondent to the application for the emergency barring order, - where the Agency by virtue of section 11 of the 2018 Act made the application for the emergency barring order concerned, to the Agency, by ordinary prepaid post, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situate the place in relation to which the application for the emergency barring order was made, and'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'How does the clerk supply copies of orders to the Garda Síochána member when the order is a variation or discharge of an emergency barring order and the place is elsewhere?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By prepaid registered post or, where agreed, by electronic mail.","Through a secure in-person handover at the Garda station","By regular unregistered post or fax","By courier service without any tracking or confirmation"],"justification":"by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the order in question is a variation or discharge of an emergency barring order and the place in respect of which the previous order was made is elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which is situated that place but only if that member had previously been sent under this rule a copy of such emergency barring order or any order relating thereto, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'How does the Clerk notify the Gardaí when an interim barring order ceases to have effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Clerk must send a verbal message via telephone to the relevant Gardaí.","The Clerk must post an announcement on a public noticeboard outside the courthouse.","The Clerk must inform the relevant Gardaí verbally in person.","The Clerk must send notice that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where agreed, by electronic mail, to the relevant Gardaí."],"justification":"the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Gardaí concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Gardaí referred to in rule or as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Protection Order/Interim Barring Order/Emergency Barring Order ceases to have effect* 12.(1) Where a protection order has been made and: - the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined, or - the protection order is discharged before the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be. (2) Where an interim barring order has been made and the interim barring order has ceased to have effect otherwise than by expiry of the time for which the order is stated on its face to be in force, the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What is considered prima facie evidence of service?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A notarized statement from the postal worker who delivered the summons.","A witness''s sworn affidavit stating they observed the delivery of the summons.","The Clerk''s endorsement on the original of every such summons served, indicating the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted.","The plaintiff''s personal acknowledgment that they have received the summons."],"justification":"The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service* 13.(1) A summons issued under this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) A request for a direction under section 18(4) of the 2018 Act that a relevant order be served personally by a member of the Garda Síochána on a respondent who was not present at the sitting of the Court at which the order was made may be made *viva voce* at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte* at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. The Court may in any case give such a direction of its own motion when the order is made, (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under the 2018 Act in accordance with section 31 of the 2018 Act, direct or deem sufficient service of a document under the 2018 Act by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the operation of a safety order or a barring order during an appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The operation of the order is automatically suspended as soon as the appeal is filed.","The operation of the order is modified according to the discretion of the appealing party.","The operation of the order continues until the appeal is fully resolved.","The operation of the order is stayed if the Court or the Circuit Court so determines, but not otherwise."],"justification":"an appeal from a safety order or a barring order shall, if the Court or the Circuit Court so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Effect of appeal from orders* 14.(1) In accordance with section 20 of the 2018 Act, notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 9(4) and Order 101 and that an appellant has entered into a recognisance for appeal: - (a) an appeal from a safety order or a barring order shall, if the Court or the Circuit Court so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination; - an appeal from a protection order, an interim barring order or an emergency barring order shall not stay the operation of the order. (2) An application to the Court to stay the operation of a safety order or a barring order under the terms of section 20 of the 2018 Act, may be made following the service and lodgment of a notice of appeal and lodgment of the recognisance for appeal and when made otherwise than upon the occasion of the making of those orders must be preceded by the issue of a notice in the [Form 59.15, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9b0bb38d-2de1-44bb-83bf-6f34c56e7bb3/Application for a stay on the operation of a safety order - barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.15.docx/docx/1) which must be served upon the respondent to the application two days before the hearing of the application. (3) Where the Court grants a stay on the operation of a safety order or a barring order, and the Clerk has previously supplied the copies of the orders as directed by rule 11, the Clerk must send a copy of the order granting the stay (which may be in the [Form 59.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/829bd6d2-f7e6-44d7-8690-fc0aa82cd503/Order staying operation of a safety order - barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.16.docx/docx/1)) or notice of the making of that order to the same persons and in the manner directed by rule 11.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when the court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to investigate a dependent person’s circumstances?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the judge shall personally inform the Agency of the Court''s direction.","If the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall notify the Agency of the Court''s direction.","If the Agency is involved in the proceedings, the Clerk shall notify the Agency of the Court''s direction.","The court will directly investigate the dependent person’s circumstances without involving the Agency."],"justification":"Where, in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation (or further investigation) of a dependent person’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report/ascertaining the views of the child* 15.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order: - under section 12 of the 2018 Act for a care order or a supervision order to be made with respect to a dependent person concerned in the proceedings, or - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, may be made at the hearing. (2) The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order: - to adjourn the proceedings and give a direction under section 12(1) of the 2018 Act and to give such directions under the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as it sees fit as to the care and custody of, and/or make a supervision order in respect of, the dependent person concerned pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, at any time and from time to time during the proceedings, having heard the parties. (3) Where, in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation (or further investigation) of a dependent person’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s direction. (4) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation (or further investigation) by the Agency —'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order of the Court giving directions be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 90.11, Schedule A","Form 84.22, Schedule","Form 75.45, Schedule","Form 84.33, Schedule"],"justification":"- (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1), - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. (5) Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3822a621-37c7-41bb-9ce4-858ff7413791/Order directing report - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section No. 58.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. [1] Order 59 substituted in full by [S.I. 219 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/219/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 5A deal with?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Procedure by Criminal Summons","Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons","Procedure by Summary Summons","Procedure by Civil Summons"],"justification":"# Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons - Court: Circuit # Order 5A: Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons **[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''2004 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004","The Taxation Act 2004","The Environmental Protection Act 2004","The Education Act 2004"],"justification":"the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires - the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); the “**2022 Act**” means the [Garda Síochána (Compensation) Act 2022](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**dependant**” includes: - a dependant within the meaning of section 47 of the [Civil Liability Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/41/enacted/en/html), and - in the case of a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), a claimant who had been an applicant to whom section or 8(4) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) refers, who brings proceedings in accordance with section 23(1) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**Garda compensation personal injuries summons**” means a summons by which a personal injuries action involving proceedings in the Court under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**personal injuries action**” has the same meaning as section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), but includes proceedings referred to in section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) in accordance with section 24 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), and “**action**” shall be interpreted accordingly; “**personal injury**” includes any disease and any impairment of a person’s physical or mental condition; “**personal injuries summons**” means an initiating document by which a personal injuries action is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**plaintiff**” includes a deceased person, where a personal injuries action is instituted for the benefit of dependants of a deceased person; “**pleading**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); “**Personal Public Service Number**” means the Personal Public Service Number allocated and issued to a person under section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26/enacted/en/index.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 58 - Custody and Guardianship of Children, Declaration of Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the summons take when a complaint is made alleging an offence of failure or refusal to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The summons should be in Form 58.30 or 58.31 Schedule as appropriate.","The summons should be in Form 58.28 or 58.29 Schedule as appropriate.","The summons should be in Form 58.26 or 58.27 Schedule as appropriate.","The summons should be in Form 58.22 or 58.23 Schedule as appropriate."],"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the [Form 58.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3e57c96e-f893-4c05-8a0b-39b5d0b778d7/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.28.docx/docx/1) or [58.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b802823-d92d-4d19-9693-8aabef61b2ec/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where complaint is made to a Judge alleging an offence of failure or refusal under section 5 of the Courts (No. 2) Act 1986, to comply with the requirements of a direction given in an order under section 7 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), section 11 of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), or section (inserted by the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/40/enacted/en/html)) of the [1964 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1964/act/7/enacted/en/html), the summons which may be issued and served upon the person against whom the offence is alleged shall be in the [Form 58.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3e57c96e-f893-4c05-8a0b-39b5d0b778d7/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.28.docx/docx/1) or [58.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b802823-d92d-4d19-9693-8aabef61b2ec/Summons - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 section 5 No. 58.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate. The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What type of court is involved in Order 59?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["County Court","Supreme Court","District Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 59 - Domestic Violence - Court: District # **Order 59: Domestic Violence**[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for issuing a safety order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 34.5, Schedule","Form 59.2, Schedule","[Form 59.2, Schedule","Form 60.1, Schedule A"],"justification":"[Form 59.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Safety Order* 4.(1) An application to the Court under section 6 of the 2018 Act for a safety order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a safety order may be in the [Form 59.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8782b974-2642-44b0-aa3d-f4396f780f8b/Safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 No. 59.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What is the first step an applicant must take to apply for a barring order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The applicant must submit a written request to the local mayor''s office to start the barring order application.","The applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons.","The applicant must contact the local police department to initiate the barring order process.","The applicant must first obtain a recommendation letter from a family member or close friend before applying for a barring order."],"justification":"the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for Barring Order* 5.(1) An application to the Court under section 7 of the 2018 Act for a barring order must be made by taking the following steps: - (a) the applicant must apply to the Clerk to issue a Domestic Violence Summons, and must provide the Clerk with the information necessary to complete the Summons; - the Clerk will issue a completed Domestic Violence Summons ([Form 59.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/357da420-934b-4ffe-a875-74d89eccbcb4/Summons for a safety order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6(2) No. 59.1.docx/docx/1)) and provide a copy to the applicant, and - the Clerk will serve the Domestic Violence Summons on the respondent in accordance with rule 13. (2) An order of the Court granting a barring order may be in the [Form 59.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55a5bf8-b6ee-4b19-a89c-4a9fefa0218c/Barring order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 7 No. 59.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served before applying to vary a safety order, barring order, interim barring order, emergency barring order, or protection order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 59.10","Form 59.20","Form 58.10","Form 60.10"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 6(8) to vary a safety order, section 7(12) to vary a barring order, section 8(7) to vary an interim barring order, section 9(8) to vary an emergency barring order or section 10(4) to vary a protection order, must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b921df5c-f0e6-42ab-bebf-e788db94793a/Summons to vary a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring order - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.10.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Vary Safety/ Barring/ Interim Barring/ Emergency Barring Order/ Protection Order* 9.(1) An application to the Court under section 6(8) to vary a safety order, section 7(12) to vary a barring order, section 8(7) to vary an interim barring order, section 9(8) to vary an emergency barring order or section 10(4) to vary a protection order, must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 59.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b921df5c-f0e6-42ab-bebf-e788db94793a/Summons to vary a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring order - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.10.docx/docx/1). (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 59.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df43420-af97-4146-811a-4b79576c72c2/Order varying a safety - barring - interim barring - emergency barring - protection order - Domestic Violence Act 2018 section 6 - 7 - 8 - 9 - 10 No. 59.11.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do when a protection order ceases to have effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Clerk must publish a notice in a national newspaper stating that the protection order has ceased to have effect.","The Clerk must send a verbal notification to the relevant Gardaí informing them that the protection order has ceased to have effect.","The Clerk must update the public register of protection orders and ensure it reflects the cessation of the order without notifying the relevant Gardaí.","The Clerk must send notice that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where agreed, by electronic mail, to the relevant Gardaí."],"justification":"the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Gardaí concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Gardaí referred to in rule or as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Protection Order/Interim Barring Order/Emergency Barring Order ceases to have effect* 12.(1) Where a protection order has been made and: - the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined, or - the protection order is discharged before the application for a safety order or a barring order has been determined the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the protection order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be. (2) Where an interim barring order has been made and the interim barring order has ceased to have effect otherwise than by expiry of the time for which the order is stated on its face to be in force, the Clerk must send notice, which may be in the [Form 59.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8aad700f-3c00-4f98-84c1-3b72ce693468/Notice that interim barring - emergency barring - protection order has ceased to have effect - Domestic Violence Act 2018 No. 59.14.docx/docx/1)that the interim barring order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail, to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule or as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'How long before the hearing must a summons be served by the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","At least three days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","Exactly fourteen days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","Within twenty-four hours after the date fixed for the hearing of the application."],"justification":"A summons issued under this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service* 13.(1) A summons issued under this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) A request for a direction under section 18(4) of the 2018 Act that a relevant order be served personally by a member of the Garda Síochána on a respondent who was not present at the sitting of the Court at which the order was made may be made *viva voce* at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte* at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. The Court may in any case give such a direction of its own motion when the order is made, (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under the 2018 Act in accordance with section 31 of the 2018 Act, direct or deem sufficient service of a document under the 2018 Act by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application be made to the court to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An application can only be made after the final judgment has been delivered.","An application can be made exclusively by the legal representatives of one of the parties involved in the case, not by the court itself.","An application can be made at the hearing or the court can exercise its power of its own motion to appoint an expert.","An application can be made by any party to the case, including the child''s friends or relatives, without the court''s permission."],"justification":"An application to the Court by a party to make an order: - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, may be made at the hearing. The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order: - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Report/ascertaining the views of the child* 15.(1) An application to the Court by a party to make an order: - under section 12 of the 2018 Act for a care order or a supervision order to be made with respect to a dependent person concerned in the proceedings, or - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, may be made at the hearing. (2) The Court may exercise the power of its own motion to make an order: - to adjourn the proceedings and give a direction under section 12(1) of the 2018 Act and to give such directions under the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as it sees fit as to the care and custody of, and/or make a supervision order in respect of, the dependent person concerned pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency - under section 27(2) of the 2018 Act to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, at any time and from time to time during the proceedings, having heard the parties. (3) Where, in accordance with sub-rule (2), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation (or further investigation) of a dependent person’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to the proceedings, the Clerk shall as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications) of the Court''s direction. (4) Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20(2) of the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation (or further investigation) by the Agency —'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 59 - Domestic Violence', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order requisitioning a report to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 60.52, Schedule A, with necessary modifications","Form 57.52, Schedule with necessary modifications","Form 58.52, Schedule with necessary modifications","Form 58.25, Schedule with necessary modifications"],"justification":"(5) Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3822a621-37c7-41bb-9ce4-858ff7413791/Order directing report - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section No. 58.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1), - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby. (5) Where the Court grants an application for an order to appoint an expert to ascertain and convey the views of a child, or makes such an order of its own motion, the order requisitioning the report shall be in the [Form 58.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3822a621-37c7-41bb-9ce4-858ff7413791/Order directing report - Guardianship of Infants Act 1964, section No. 58.52.docx/docx/1), Schedule with the necessary modifications. [1] Order 59 substituted in full by [S.I. 219 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/219/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''personal injury'' include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Any breach of contract between two parties.","Any damage to property including vehicles and buildings.","Any disease and any impairment of a person’s physical or mental condition","Any financial loss suffered by an individual due to negligence."],"justification":"“**personal injury**” includes any disease and any impairment of a person’s physical or mental condition;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order unless the context or subject matter otherwise requires - the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); the “**2022 Act**” means the [Garda Síochána (Compensation) Act 2022](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**dependant**” includes: - a dependant within the meaning of section 47 of the [Civil Liability Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/41/enacted/en/html), and - in the case of a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), a claimant who had been an applicant to whom section or 8(4) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) refers, who brings proceedings in accordance with section 23(1) of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print); “**Garda compensation personal injuries summons**” means a summons by which a personal injuries action involving proceedings in the Court under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**personal injuries action**” has the same meaning as section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), but includes proceedings referred to in section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) in accordance with section 24 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print), and “**action**” shall be interpreted accordingly; “**personal injury**” includes any disease and any impairment of a person’s physical or mental condition; “**personal injuries summons**” means an initiating document by which a personal injuries action is instituted in accordance with rule 3; “**plaintiff**” includes a deceased person, where a personal injuries action is instituted for the benefit of dependants of a deceased person; “**pleading**” has the same meaning as in section 2 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); “**Personal Public Service Number**” means the Personal Public Service Number allocated and issued to a person under section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26/enacted/en/index.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'In case of conflict with other rules, which prevails?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["the most recently added rule","the rule with the highest number","the provision of the rule of this Order","the rule that was verbally agreed upon last"],"justification":"the provision of the rule of this Order shall, in respect of personal injuries actions, prevail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application of this Order* 2.(1) The provisions of this Order shall apply to personal injuries actions and to all proceedings in personal injuries actions. (2) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, in the event that any conflict shall arise between the provision of any rule of this Order and any other provision of these Rules, the provision of the rule of this Order shall, in respect of personal injuries actions, prevail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a personal injuries action take if it does not involve proceedings under section 23 of the 2022 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["It should be instituted by an originating document in accordance with Form of the Schedule of Forms and referred to as a personal injuries summons.","It should be instituted by a writ of summons in accordance with common law procedures and referred to as a personal injuries complaint.","It should be instituted by an originating document in accordance with Form of the Schedule of Forms and referred to as a personal injuries claim.","It should be instituted by a letter of demand in accordance with the Civil Procedure Rules and referred to as a personal injuries notice."],"justification":"A personal injuries action shall be instituted by an originating document which shall be in accordance with [Form 2P](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-summons) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms), and shall be referred to as a personal injuries summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Personal injuries summons and Garda compensation personal injuries summons* 3.(1) A personal injuries action shall be instituted by an originating document which shall be in accordance with [Form 2P](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-summons) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms), and shall be referred to as a personal injuries summons. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), a personal injuries action involving proceedings under section 23 of the [2022 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2022/act/33/enacted/en/print) shall be instituted by an originating document, which shall be accordance with [Form 2U](https://www.courts.ie/content/garda-compensation-personal-injuries-summons) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms), and shall be referred to as a Garda compensation personal injuries summons. (3) Save where otherwise expressly provided by this Order, the provisions of these Rules which apply to a Civil Bill shall, with appropriate modifications, apply to a personal injuries summons and to a Garda compensation personal injuries summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What must a personal injuries summons include if a plaintiff alleges a reasonable cause for failing to serve the notice required by section 8(1) of the 2004 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Particulars of the cause of the said failure","Particulars of the defendant''s negligence","Reasons for the plaintiff''s delay in filing the lawsuit","Details of the plaintiff''s medical expenses"],"justification":"the personal injuries summons shall include particulars of the cause of the said failure"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Failure to serve letter of claim* 4.(1) Where a plaintiff who has not served the notice required by section 8(1) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) within the time prescribed for service of such a notice alleges that there was a reasonable cause for such failure, the personal injuries summons shall include particulars of the cause of the said failure. (2) Where a plaintiff alleges that he was unable, at the time at which a personal injuries summons or Garda compensation personal injuries summons was issued, to include in the summons any of the information required by the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or these Rules to be specified there, he shall include in the personal injuries summons or, as the case may be, the Garda compensation personal injuries summons, a statement of the reasons why it is claimed that any such information could not be provided at the time of issue of the summons. The plaintiff shall, at the time the summons is served or as soon as may be thereafter (whether by amendment or otherwise) provide such of the information required as was not included in the summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What must pleadings conform to in a personal injuries action?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The requirements of section 13 of the 2004 Act","The guidelines outlined in the 1987 Act","The standards specified in section 14 of the 2004 Act","The principles set forth in the 2005 Regulations"],"justification":"In every personal injuries action pleadings shall conform to the requirements of section 13 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Pleadings* 5. In every personal injuries action pleadings shall conform to the requirements of section 13 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Within what timeframe must a defence be delivered to the plaintiff or their solicitor after a defendant enters an appearance?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Within 2 weeks.","Within 8 weeks.","Within 6 weeks.","Within 4 weeks."],"justification":"The defence shall be delivered to the plaintiff or his Solicitor within 6 weeks of the entry by the defendant of an Appearance."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appearance, defence and counterclaim* 6.(1) A defence shall be delivered by each defendant who has entered an Appearance. The defence shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(i)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-defence) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) (with the necessary adaptations in the case of a defence to a Garda compensation personal injuries summons). Where any defendant makes a counterclaim, such counterclaim shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(ii)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-counterclaim) of the Schedule of Forms and shall be appended to the defence. (2) The defence shall be delivered to the plaintiff or his Solicitor within 6 weeks of the entry by the defendant of an Appearance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an affidavit of verification take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be in accordance with Form 3C(vi) of the Schedule of Forms annexed to the rules.","It should be in accordance with Form 12B(iv) of the Schedule of Forms annexed to the rules.","It should be in accordance with Form 7D(ii) of the Schedule of Forms annexed to the rules.","It should be in accordance with Form 6A(iii) of the Schedule of Forms annexed to the rules."],"justification":"An affidavit of verification of a pleading or of further information requiring under section 14(1), 14(2) or 14(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be verified on oath shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) annexed hereto."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Affidavit of verification* 7.(1) An affidavit of verification of a pleading or of further information requiring under section 14(1), 14(2) or 14(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be verified on oath shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms) annexed hereto. Where the affidavit is not made separately to the pleading or other document concerned, it shall be appended to such pleading or other document. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading or other document is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is appended to the pleading or other document, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading or other document. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 14 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for lodgement of the affidavit in court. (3) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading or other document, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading or other document in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy. (4) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 14(4) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) by being filed in the Office.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What conditions must be met before issuing an application under sections 10(3) or 11(3)/12(3) of the 2004 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The moving party must serve a formal complaint on the opposing party and receive a non-compliance certification from a judge before issuing the application.","The moving party must obtain a court order requiring the opposing party to comply with the request before issuing the application.","The moving party must first write to the opposing party requesting agreement, allow a 28-day period for compliance, and ensure the opposing party fails, refuses, or neglects to comply.","The moving party must provide written notice to the opposing party requesting agreement and wait for a mandatory 30-day period before issuing the application."],"justification":"An application referred to in paragraphs or of this sub-rule shall not be issued unless: - (a) the moving party shall have first written to the relevant opposing party requesting that such party agree to the moving party’s request; - a period of 28 days for compliance with the moving party’s request has been allowed; and - the party requested has failed, refused or neglected to comply with, such request."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications by motion on notice* 8.(1) The following applications in a personal injuries action shall, subject to the following rules of this Order, be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded, where necessary, upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - An application by a defendant under section 10(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for a stay or dismissal of the action by reason of a plaintiff’s failure to provide the information necessary to comply with section 10 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - An application under section 11(3) or section 12(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) for relief by reason of the opposing party’s failure to provide further information requested under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), or for an order for the delivery by the opposing party of further and better particulars of any pleading delivered by such party; - (iii) An application by a party wishing to have evidence in the action given by affidavit, under section 19 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); An application referred to in paragraphs or of this sub-rule shall not be issued unless: - (a) the moving party shall have first written to the relevant opposing party requesting that such party agree to the moving party’s request; - a period of 28 days for compliance with the moving party’s request has been allowed; and - the party requested has failed, refused or neglected to comply with, such request. (2) No application for judgment or for other relief in default of pleading shall be granted in a personal injuries action unless the moving party has satisfied the Court that he has verified his previous pleadings in that action on oath in accordance with this Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What information must the report of the mediation chairperson include?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Appointment as mediator, whether the conference was held, reasons if not held, time and place of conference, parties in attendance, settlement reached, and terms of any settlement.","Appointment as mediator, whether the conference was held, reasons if not held, time and place of conference, parties in attendance, settlement reached, and legal judgments rendered.","Appointment as mediator, whether the conference was held, reasons if not held, time and place of conference, parties in attendance, settlement reached, and personal opinions of the mediator on the case.","Appointment as mediator, financial transactions made during the conference, reasons if not held, time and place of conference, parties in attendance, settlement reached, and terms of any settlement."],"justification":"The report under section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) of the person appointed under section 15(4) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be the chairperson of a mediation conference shall be by way of affidavit which, in addition to any matters required by section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be contained in such report, shall verify: - (a) his or her appointment as mediator; - whether the mediation conference was or was not held; - if not held, the reasons why the mediation conference did not take place; - if held, - the time and place at which the mediation conference was held; - the parties in attendance; - (iii) whether or not a settlement has been reached in the action and - the terms of any settlement signed by the parties."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mediation* 9.(1) A request by a party for a direction of the Court under section 15 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) that a mediation conference be held shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where the Court directs that a mediation conference be held, it may adjourn the proceedings for such time as it considers appropriate to enable the mediation conference to be held. (3) Where the Court directs that a mediation conference be held, it may extend the time for compliance by the parties or any of them with any provision of these Rules or any order of the court in the proceedings. (4) The report under section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) of the person appointed under section 15(4) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be the chairperson of a mediation conference shall be by way of affidavit which, in addition to any matters required by section 16 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) to be contained in such report, shall verify: - (a) his or her appointment as mediator; - whether the mediation conference was or was not held; - if not held, the reasons why the mediation conference did not take place; - if held, - the time and place at which the mediation conference was held; - the parties in attendance; - (iii) whether or not a settlement has been reached in the action and - the terms of any settlement signed by the parties. (5) The Court may give a direction under section 15 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) of its own motion on any occasion on which the personal injuries action is before the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of an offer of terms of settlement take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The notice should be in accordance with Form 5C(iii) of the Schedule of Forms.","The notice should be in accordance with Form 7B(v) of the Schedule of Forms.","The notice should be in accordance with Form 6B(iv) of the Schedule of Forms.","The notice should be in accordance with Form 6A(iv) of the Schedule of Forms."],"justification":"Such notice shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iv)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-notice-offer-terms-settlement) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notices under the 2004 Act* 10.(1) Where a party intends both to request further information under section 11(1) or section 11(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and to request further particulars in accordance with [Order 17]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-17-Circuit-Particulars-and-further-particulars-in-claim-or-defence), all such requests shall, except by consent or order of the Court, be made in the same notice or letter, and be replied to in the same notice or letter. (2) Copies of the plaintiff’s notice of an offer of terms of settlement required by section 17(1) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and of the defendant’s notice required by section 17(2) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be lodged in court by being filed (together with an affidavit as to the service of the same on the opposing party) in the Office as soon as may be after the expiry of the prescribed period referred to in section 17(3) of the 2004 Act. Such notice shall be in accordance with [Form 6A(iv)](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/content/personal-injuries-notice-offer-terms-settlement) of the [Schedule of Forms](https://courts.ie/circuit-court-forms).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5A - Procedure by Personal Injuries Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What can a person presiding over a pre-trial hearing directed by the Court under section 18 of the 2004 Act do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Give directions and make orders to determine what matters relating to the action are in dispute.","Assess the guilt or innocence of the defendant before the trial begins.","Negotiate a settlement between the parties involved in the legal action.","Determine the final verdict of the case based on the evidence presented."],"justification":"A person presiding over a pre-trial hearing directed by the Court under section 18 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as may be necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the action are in dispute."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Pre-trial hearings under section 18 of the 2004 Act* 11.(1) A person presiding over a pre-trial hearing directed by the Court under section 18 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) may at such hearing give such directions and make such orders as may be necessary for the purposes of determining what matters relating to the action are in dispute. (2) Any direction given or order made at a pre-trial hearing by a person, other than a Judge, presiding over such hearing, may be appealed to the Court by a party affected. [1] Order 5A inserted by 526 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/526/made/en/print), effective 20 September 2005, and substituted in its entirely by 230 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/230/made/en/print#:~:text 1.,Court Rules 2001 to 2022.), effective 31 May 2024. Superseded amendments: Order 5A rule 4 substituted by 215 of 2019](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/215/made/en/print), effective 19 June 2019. Order 5A rule 9(5) inserted by 11 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/11/made/en/), effective 22 January 2018.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served with the Civil Bill in proceedings under Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A witness statement conforming to Form 54 in the Schedule of Forms, verifying and supporting the claim endorsed on the Civil Bill.","An affidavit conforming to Form 54 in the Schedule of Forms, verifying and supporting the claim endorsed on the Civil Bill.","A sworn declaration conforming to Form 54 in the Schedule of Forms, verifying and supporting the claim endorsed on the Civil Bill.","An affidavit conforming to Form 55 in the Schedule of Forms, verifying and supporting the claim endorsed on the Civil Bill."],"justification":"There shall be served with the Civil Bill a copy of an affidavit which shall conform to the requirements of [Form 54](/content/affidavit-support-civil-bill-possession-order-authorising-sale-under-section-1003-land-and) in the Schedule of Forms (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) sworn by or on behalf of the plaintiff, verifying and supporting the claim indorsed on the Civil Bill."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) A Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall be served, together with a copy of the affidavit mentioned in rule 5, on each defendant not later than 21 days before the return date mentioned in rule 4. 4. Every Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall, upon being issued, be assigned a return date before the County Registrar, which date shall be entered in the Civil Bill. (1) There shall be served with the Civil Bill a copy of an affidavit which shall conform to the requirements of [Form 54](/content/affidavit-support-civil-bill-possession-order-authorising-sale-under-section-1003-land-and) in the Schedule of Forms (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) sworn by or on behalf of the plaintiff, verifying and supporting the claim indorsed on the Civil Bill. (2) Where the agreement for a mortgage on foot of which proceedings to which this Order relates have been commenced is or was at the material time or times one to which a code drawn up by the Central Bank of Ireland in accordance with section 117 of the [Central Bank Act 1989](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/16/enacted/en/html) applies, the affidavit shall identify the code concerned. (3) A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in [Form 5](/content/entry-appearance) in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date. 6. (1) No party shall have the right in proceedings to which this Order applies to adduce any evidence otherwise than by affidavit, except - - (a) by leave of the Judge, - where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or - where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'What can the County Registrar do on the return date of the Civil Bill?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Grant a divorce decree between the parties involved in the civil bill","Order service of the Civil Bill on another person, enlarge time for entry of an appearance, give directions for filing affidavits, prepare proceedings for trial, make an order for possession, and receive consent orders.","Issue a criminal warrant against one of the parties in the civil case","Order the immediate payment of damages without a hearing"],"justification":"the County Registrar may, in addition to any other order which the County Registrar has power to make:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) Any party desiring to cross-examine a deponent who has sworn an affidavit filed on behalf of the opposite party may serve upon the party by whom such affidavit has been filed a notice in writing requiring the production of the deponent for cross-examination, and unless such deponent is produced accordingly his affidavit shall not be used as evidence unless by the special leave of the Court. (1) On the return date of the Civil Bill (or on any adjournment from such date), the County Registrar may, in addition to any other order which the County Registrar has power to make: - (a) order service of the Civil Bill on any other person; - make an order enlarging the time for entry of an appearance; - give directions and fix time limits for the filing and delivery of any further affidavits by any party or parties; - give any other directions for the preparation of the proceedings for trial; - where an appearance has not been entered or an affidavit in accordance with rule 5(2) setting out a defence has not been filed and delivered, make an order for possession in accordance with paragraph (xxxiii) or (xxxiv) of the Second Schedule to the [Courts and Courts Officers Act 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/31/enacted/en/html); - where the parties are sui juris, make an order to receive a consent and make the same a rule of court. (2) Where a replying affidavit has been filed in accordance with rule 5(2) which discloses a prima facie defence, the County Registrar shall transfer the Civil Bill, when in order for hearing, to the Judge’s list on the first opportunity. (3) For the purposes of this rule, or for the purpose of any hearing before himself, the County Registrar may extend the time for filing affidavits and give such directions and adjourn the case before himself as he thinks fit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Judge do on the hearing of a Civil Bill to which this Order applies?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Grant a retrial due to procedural errors in the initial filing.","Award damages to the defendant if they appear to be innocent.","Give judgment for the relief to which the plaintiff appears to be entitled.","Order the case to be dismissed due to lack of evidence."],"justification":"On the hearing of any Civil Bill to which this Order applies, the Judge may give judgment for the relief to which the plaintiff appears to be entitled"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the defendant is seeking time to remedy any other breach of obligation arising under the mortgage, set out detailed particulars of the defendant’s proposal to effect such remedy. 9. On the hearing of any Civil Bill to which this Order applies, the Judge may give judgment for the relief to which the plaintiff appears to be entitled. 10. (1) The Judge may give any special directions touching the carriage or execution of any judgment or order, or the service thereof upon persons not parties, as he thinks just. (2) The Judge or the County Registrar may make such order as to costs as he considers just, including an order measuring any costs awarded [1] Order inserted by 264 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/264/made/en/print), effective 8 July 2009. [2] Title amended by 171 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/171/made/en/print), effective 19 May 2016. [3] Order rule 1 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [4] Order rule 3 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [5] Order rule 5 substituted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015. [6] Order rule 5(2) substituted by 358 of 2012](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2012/si/358/made/en/print), effective 15 October 2012. [7] Order 5 rule 7(2) and 7(4) substituted by 358 of 2012](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2012/si/358/made/en/print), effective 15 October 2012. [8] Order rule 8(3) inserted by 346 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/346/made/en/print), effective 17 August 2015.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What act does Order relate to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Privacy Act 2009","Criminal Law Reform Act 2009","Defamation Act 2009","Consumer Protection Act 2009"],"justification":"Order - Defamation Act 2009"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Circuit # **Order Defamation Act 2009******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What is the definition of ''defamation action'' in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Is synonymous with any criminal prosecution under the same Act","Refers specifically to any civil lawsuit involving breach of contract","Has the same meaning as in section 2 of the Act","Describes a legal proceeding initiated for the recovery of a debt"],"justification":"“**defamation action**” has the same meaning as in section 2."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1. In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Defamation Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) and any reference in this Order to a section shall, unless the context otherwise requires, be deemed to be a reference to a section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html); “**defamation action**” has the same meaning as in section 2.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a pleading requiring verification on affidavit take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 5A(iii) of the Schedule of Forms, with necessary modifications","Form 6A(iii) of the Schedule of Forms, with necessary modifications","Form 6B(iv) of the Schedule of Forms, with necessary modifications","Form 7A(iii) of the Schedule of Forms, with necessary modifications"],"justification":"A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the Schedule of Forms, with such modifications as may be necessary."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8 3. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form 6A(iii)](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-affidavit-verification) of the Schedule of Forms, with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate to the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon that pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of that pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court, as required by section 8(5), by filing the same in the Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What type of notice is given when making applications for a ruling under section 14, an interlocutory order under section 33, summary relief under section 34(1), and to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["On public notice through official government announcements.","On notice to all parties including those not directly involved in the proceedings.","On notice to the opposing party or parties.","On notice to the presiding judge only."],"justification":"The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 4. (1) An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (3) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How is an application made under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) when an offer to make amends is accepted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By motion on notice to the opposing party, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.","By submitting an unsworn statement of facts and intentions to the court registrar.","Through a verbal agreement made in the presence of a judge during a scheduled hearing.","By written agreement between the parties without the need for any formal filing with the court."],"justification":"shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted 5. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include directions as to the terms upon which any pleadings may be amended) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1). 6. Where an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) to bring or to proceed with a defamation action against another person in respect of the statement to which the offer to make amends applies shall: - where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What must a grounding affidavit include when it comes to identifying the statement related to the offer of amends?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Mention the date and time of the offer of amends without the actual statement","Include a vague reference to the offer of amends without any specific content","Identify with sufficient precision or exhibit a copy or transcript of the statement","Provide a general summary of the statement without specific details"],"justification":"identify with sufficient precision, or exhibit a copy or transcript of, the statement to which the offer of amends relates"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of paragraph of section 23(1) and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the other person referred to in paragraph of section 23(1) shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 5 and 6 shall: - identify with sufficient precision, or exhibit a copy or transcript of, the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. In addition to any other order which may be made on the hearing of an originating notice of motion under sub-rule (3) of rule 4 or paragraph of rule 6, the Court may, at such hearing: - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application; - direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How does a defendant notify a plaintiff of their intention to give evidence of an apology?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By including a statement in their defence of such intention.","By submitting an apology letter directly to the plaintiff outside of formal court proceedings.","Through a public announcement in a newspaper or media outlet.","By verbally informing the judge during a pre-trial hearing without any written documentation."],"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What should the title of the motion be in an application for a declaratory order under section 28?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The motion should be an originating notice of motion entitled ''Application for Declaratory Order''","The motion should be a notice of appeal entitled in the matter of section 28","The motion should be an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 28.","The motion should be a cross-motion entitled in the matter of section 28"],"justification":"A motion referred to in section 28(5) shall be an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 28"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications for declaratory orders under section 28 10. (1) A motion referred to in section 28(5) shall be an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 28 and in which the person who claims to be the subject of a statement that he or she alleges is defamatory shall be named as applicant and the person against whom relief is sought shall be named as respondent. (2) A grounding affidavit referred to in section 28(5) shall: - (a) set out the circumstances in which it is claimed that the alleged defamatory statement was made, including the time and method of publication; - set out the grounds on which it is claimed that the statement is defamatory of the applicant; - contain an averment that the respondent has no defence to the application; - contain an averment that the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish an apology, correction or retraction (as the case may be) in relation to the alleged defamatory statement and specify when and the manner in which the applicant requested the respondent to make and publish such apology, correction or retraction in relation to the alleged defamatory statement (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such request and proof of delivery of same), and - produce evidence of the response (if any) by the respondent to the request (and if in writing, exhibit a copy of such response).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for a defendant to give evidence in chief regarding the circumstances of publication or the character of the plaintiff in a defamation action?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The defendant must secure the approval of both parties involved and submit their evidence anonymously to the court clerk five days before the trial.","The defendant must obtain the plaintiff''s consent and provide a detailed report on the publication three days before the trial.","The defendant must file a motion with the court at least thirty days before the trial and submit a summary of evidence to the judge.","The defendant must obtain the judge''s leave and furnish particulars to the plaintiff at least seven days before the trial."],"justification":"the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation to be given 11. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by 486 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/486/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What court does Order 6 - Parties apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["District Court","Supreme Court","Circuit Court","County Court"],"justification":"- Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Parties - Court: Circuit'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can multiple persons be joined as plaintiffs in one action?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, only one person can be a plaintiff in any legal action.","Yes, if they have different claims but the defendants agree to the consolidation of cases.","Yes, if they have rights to relief arising from the same transaction and there are common questions of law or fact, provided they consent.","Only if they are part of the same family or organization, regardless of whether their claims arise from the same transaction."],"justification":"All persons may be joined in one action as plaintiffs in whom any right to relief in respect of or arising out of the same transactions is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if such persons brought separate actions, any common question of law or fact would arise; provided that if, upon a motion on notice by any defendant, it shall appear that such joinder may embarrass or delay the trial, the Judge may order separate trials, or make such other order as may be right, and provided also that no person shall be made a plaintiff without his consent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **PARTIES** 1. All persons may be joined in one action as plaintiffs in whom any right to relief in respect of or arising out of the same transactions is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if such persons brought separate actions, any common question of law or fact would arise; provided that if, upon a motion on notice by any defendant, it shall appear that such joinder may embarrass or delay the trial, the Judge may order separate trials, or make such other order as may be right, and provided also that no person shall be made a plaintiff without his consent. 2. All persons may be joined as defendants against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. When the plaintiff is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more defendants, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the defendants is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him; but the Judge may make such order as may appear just, to prevent any defendant from being embarrassed, or put to expense, by being required to attend any proceedings in which he has no interest. 3. The plaintiff may, at his option, join as defendants to the same action all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can an infant sue by themselves?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Yes, an infant can sue by themselves as long as they have a legal guardian present.","An infant can sue on their own behalf once they turn 14 years old.","Infants can only sue if they are represented by a parent or legal guardian in court proceedings.","No, an infant must sue through a next friend."],"justification":"An infant may sue by his next friend, and in such case there shall be lodged with the Civil Bill a written authority authorising the commencement and prosecution of the suit on behalf of the infant and the use of the name of such person as next friend, signed by such person."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. [[1]](#_ftn1) No action, cause or matter shall be defeated by reason of the misjoinder or non-joinder of parties, and the Judge may in every action, cause or matter deal with the subject in controversy so far as regards the rights and interests of the parties actually before him. The Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, either upon or without the application of any party, and on such terms as may appear to him to be just, order that the name of any party, whether plaintiff or defendant, who has been improperly joined, be struck out, and that the name of any person who ought to have been joined as a party, or whose presence before the Court may be necessary in order to enable the Judge to adjudicate upon and settle all the questions involved in the cause or matter, be added as a plaintiff or a defendant. No person shall be added as a plaintiff suing without a next friend, or as the next friend of a plaintiff under any disability, without his consent in writing thereto. Every person whose name is so added as defendant shall be served with a Civil Bill in such manner as may be prescribed by any Order of the Court, and the action, cause or matter, as against such party, shall be deemed to have begun only on the making of the Order adding such party. 5. An infant may sue by his next friend, and in such case there shall be lodged with the Civil Bill a written authority authorising the commencement and prosecution of the suit on behalf of the infant and the use of the name of such person as next friend, signed by such person. 6. An infant may defend by his guardian litem* appointed for that purpose in accordance with [Order 19]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-19-Circuit-Side-bar-applications) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when proceedings are brought on behalf of or against an infant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proceedings involving infants are automatically dismissed without the need for any further action.","The Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem to act for or on behalf of the infant, and may change or appoint another in his place.","The Court requires the infant''s parents or legal guardians to personally appear in court to represent the infant.","The Court must appoint a legal representative from a specific government agency to represent the infant."],"justification":"When proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against an infant, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem* to act for or on behalf of such infant, and may change any next friend or guardian litem*, and appoint another in his place"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. When proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against an infant, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem* to act for or on behalf of such infant, and may change any next friend or guardian litem*, and appoint another in his place, and may also direct that any money or other personal property to which such infant may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of such infant in such manner as the Judge shall consider advisable. 8. [[2]](#2) (1) In this rule, the “**2015 Act**” means the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person a decision-making representation order which authorises a decision-making representative appointed in respect of the person to institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her decision-making representative, and service on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power of attorney in respect of which a notification of lack of capacity has been accepted, which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney, and service on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/12/enacted/en/html), which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney under the Act of 1996, and service on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the Court have if an issue arises regarding the capacity of an adult party to proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may make such orders or give directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice.","The Court may order the adult party to undergo mandatory psychiatric evaluation before continuing with the proceedings.","The Court may dismiss the case immediately if there is any doubt about the capacity of an adult party.","The Court may appoint a legal guardian to represent the adult party without their consent."],"justification":"Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where there is in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer a registered co-decision-making agreement which provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered in the proceedings shall be signed by, or shall include a certificate that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by, the appointer and co-decision-maker. (6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee 9. Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and shall be considered as representing such persons; but the Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of such persons to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties. This rule shall apply to trustees, executors, and administrators sued in proceedings to enforce a security by sale or otherwise. 10. Save in actions founded on tort, when there are numerous persons having the same interest in one action or matter, one or more of such persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Judge to defend, in such action or matter, on behalf of or for the benefit of all persons so interested.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a person not named in or served with the Civil Bill appears and defends at the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Judge may dismiss the case against the person who was not named or served.","The Judge may ignore the appearance and defend of the person who was not named or served.","The Judge may deal with such person, both as to costs and otherwise, as if they had originally been served with the Civil Bill as defendant.","The Judge may require the person to leave the courtroom immediately without addressing their defense."],"justification":"Where proceedings are taken as mentioned in the last preceding rule, any person not named in or served with the Civil Bill may by leave of the Judge appear and defend at the hearing, and the Judge may thereafter deal with such person, both as to costs and otherwise, as if he had originally been served with the Civil Bill as defendant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '11. Where proceedings are taken for the recovery of land, any tenant, under-tenant, or other person in actual possession of the property sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, may be named as defendant and the Civil Bill shall be directed to such tenant, under-tenant, or other person, with the addition of the words ‘‘and all persons concerned’’. 12. Where proceedings are taken as mentioned in the last preceding rule, any person not named in or served with the Civil Bill may by leave of the Judge appear and defend at the hearing, and the Judge may thereafter deal with such person, both as to costs and otherwise, as if he had originally been served with the Civil Bill as defendant. 13. When any person residing outside the Circuit, but inside the State, is a necessary and proper party to a proceeding properly instituted in the Court against some person within the Circuit, such first mentioned person may be served with the Civil Bill or other document without special leave. 14. Subject to the requirements of Rule 9 of Section 66 of the [Chancery (Ireland) Act, 1867](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1867/act/44/enacted/en/print.html), wherever, in any action for the administration of the estate of a deceased person, or for the execution of the trusts of any deed or instrument, or for the partition or sale of any hereditaments, a judgment or order has been pronounced affecting the rights or interests of persons not parties to the action, the Court may direct that any persons interested in the estate, or under the trusts, or in the hereditaments, shall be served with notice of the judgment or order; and after such notice such persons shall be bound by the proceedings, in the same manner as if they had originally been made parties, and shall be at liberty to attend the proceedings under the judgment or order. Any person so served may within one month after such service apply to the Court to discharge, vary or add to the said judgment or order. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 6 rule 4 substituted by 312 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/312/made/en/print), effective 20 July 2007. [2] Order 6 rule 8 substituted by 201 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/201/made/en/pdf) effective 27 April 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 6 - Right of Audience', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 6 - Right of Audience?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High","County","Supreme","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Right of Audience - Court: District # Order 6: Right of Audience [1] ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 6 - Right of Audience', 'Court Rules', 'In whose name can a person appear and prosecute in proceedings initiated by the Director of Public Prosecutions?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Attorney General","The Chief Justice","The Prime Minister","The Director of Public Prosecutions"],"justification":"in proceedings at the suit of the Director of Public Prosecutions in respect of an offence, the said Director or any member of the Garda Síochána or other person appearing on behalf of or prosecuting in the name of the Director."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Persons entitled to appear and address the court* 1. The following persons shall be entitled to appear and address the Court and conduct proceedings— - (a) any party to the proceedings; or - a solicitor for such party; or - a counsel instructed by the solicitor for such party; or - where the proceedings are in relation to the taxes and duties under the care and management of the Revenue Commissioners, or in relation to any fine, penalty or forfeiture incurred in connection therewith or otherwise incurred under the Customs Acts, a duly authorised officer of the Revenue Commissioners or the Revenue solicitor; or - in proceedings at the suit of the Director of Public Prosecutions in respect of an offence, the said Director or any member of the Garda Síochána or other person appearing on behalf of or prosecuting in the name of the Director. 2. Save where otherwise provided by statute or by rules of court, the father, mother, son, daughter, husband, wife, brother or sister of any party may appear on behalf of that party provided that any such person has the leave of the Court to appear and be heard and that the Court is satisfied that the party is, from infirmity or other unavoidable cause, unable to appear. [1] Order 6 inserted by[S.I. No. 93/1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) - District Court Rules, 1997'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses', 'Court Rules', 'What can a plaintiff issue concurrently with the original summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["An appeal to a higher court","A request for a jury trial","A counterclaim against another party","One or more concurrent summonses"],"justification":"The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summonses"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 6 - Concurrent Summonses - Court: Superior 1. The plaintiff in any proceedings may, at the time of, or at any time during twelve months after the issuing of the originating summons, issue one or more concurrent summons or summonses, each concurrent summons to bear the same date of issue as the original summons, and to be marked with a seal bearing the word “**concurrent**” and the date of issue of the concurrent summons; and such seal shall be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer; provided always, that such concurrent summons or summonses shall only be in force for the period during which the original summons in such proceedings shall be in force. 2. A summons for service within the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction; and a summons for service, or of which notice in lieu of service is to be given, out of the jurisdiction may be issued and marked as a concurrent summons with one for service within the jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What court is Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home under?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme Court","District Court","High Court","Magistrates'' Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Family Home Protection Act, 1976 (No. 27 of 1976)","The Employment Rights Act, 1985 (No. 34 of 1985)","The Consumer Protection Act, 1980 (No. 20 of 1980)","The Environmental Protection Act, 1990 (No. 12 of 1990)"],"justification":"“**the Ac**t” means the [Family Home Protection Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1976)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition.* 1. In this Order — “**the Ac**t” means the [Family Home Protection Act, 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1976).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Under what condition can proceedings be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for the district?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the defendant requests a faster trial due to personal convenience.","When the Clerk certifies that the proceedings are urgent after consulting the Judge.","When the case involves a high-profile celebrity.","When the case is scheduled on a day when the court is not usually in session."],"justification":"Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the court district within which such court area is situate, certifies on a notice of application or a summons that the proceedings are urgent, the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2. (1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home, as defined in section 2 of the Act, is situate. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the court district within which such court area is situate, certifies on a notice of application or a summons that the proceedings are urgent, the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Who is allowed to be present at the hearing besides officers of the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The parties, their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to certain rules), and other persons as the Judge allows","The media, including journalists and photographers","Tourists visiting the courthouse on a guided tour","Random members of the public who have no connection to the case"],"justification":"only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hearing to be otherwise than in public.* 3. Proceedings under or referred to in the Act in which each spouse is a party (whether by joinder or otherwise) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses (subject to the provisions of [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 2 of these Rules) and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion shall allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court order granting the application take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 60.4 Schedule","Form 60.3 Schedule","Form 60.4 Schedule A","Form 61.4 Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(1).* 4. An application by a spouse under section 9(1) of the Act for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/134dc84e-bdf3-42fe-9207-7bea0a07e24b/Notice of application for an order prohibiting the disposition or removal of household chattels - Family Home Protection Act, 1976. No. 60.1.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for issuing a notice before an application under section 9(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["[Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1)","[Form 75 Schedule A](https://www.example.com/form75)","[Form 50 Schedule C](https://www.example.com/form50C)","[Form 60.4 Schedule B](https://www.example.com/form60_4B)"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(2).* 5. An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the summons take when a spouse complains under section 9(4) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 61.5 Schedule A","Form 60.5 Schedule","Form 60.4 Schedule","Form 60.5 Schedule"],"justification":"the summons which may be issued and served upon the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 9(4).* 6. Where complaint is made by a spouse to a Judge under section 9(4) of the Act that the other spouse has contravened the provisions of section 9(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served on the respondent spouse before an application under section 9(5) is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 60.6 Schedule A","Form 60.6 Schedule","Form 60.7","Form 60.5 Schedule"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 60.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(5).* 7. An application by a spouse under section 9(5) of the Act for an order that the respondent spouse provide household chattels for the applicant spouse or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Which order''s provisions apply in cases where a summons is issued under section 15?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 16","Order 20","Order 15","Order 14"],"justification":"The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 15.* 8. Where complaint is made to a Judge under section 15 of the Act that a person knowingly gave information which was false or misleading in any material particular, the summons which may be issued and served upon that person shall be in the [Form 60.8 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3aba16a6-9846-460f-b80a-6efdaa8f3d04/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 15 No. 60.8.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the court sitting must a notice or summons be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At least ten days, unless the proceedings are certified as routine.","At least twenty-one days, with no exception for urgent proceedings.","At least seven days, or at least one day if the proceedings are certified as urgent.","At least fourteen days, or at least two days if the proceedings are certified as urgent."],"justification":"every such notice shall be served at least fourteen days or, in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2) hereof, at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents.* 9. (1) A notice or summons required by this Order to be served may be served in accordance with the provisions of [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) of these Rules and every such notice shall be served at least fourteen days or, in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2) hereof, at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What procedure''s provisions apply, with necessary modifications, to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Conciliation Procedure from Order 50","The Third Party Procedure from Order 42","The Arbitration Procedure from Order 35","The Mediation Procedure from Order 27"],"justification":"The provisions of [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) (Third Party Procedure) of these Rules shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Joinder of parties.* 10. The provisions of [Order 42]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-42-District-Defence-Particulars-And-Counterclaim) (Third Party Procedure) of these Rules shall, with necessary modifications, apply to the proceedings mentioned in section 11 of the Act.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in when declaring a conveyance void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 60.10, Section","Form 60.10, Schedule","Form 60.10, Schedule","Form 59.10, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void.* 11.[1] (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person do after instituting proceedings to declare a conveyance void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["File a separate application to freeze the assets related to the conveyance under the Prevention of Fraudulent Disposals Act.","Notify all parties involved in the conveyance via registered mail that proceedings have been instituted.","Cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844.","Publish a notice in a national newspaper declaring the conveyance void without any formal legal entry."],"justification":"A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lis Pendens.* (3) A person who instituted proceedings to have a conveyance declared void by reason of subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act shall, as soon as may be, cause relevant particulars of the proceedings to be entered as a lis pendens under and in accordance with the Judgments (Ireland) Act, 1844.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court order be in when dispensing with the consent of a spouse for the conveyance of the family home?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 65.12, Schedule","Form 60.12, Schedule A","Form 60.12, Schedule","Form 60.11, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df0ce4a-6d5d-4c09-939d-6893aeb7ca2b/Order dispensing with consent of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.12.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Dispensing with consent.* 12.[2] (1) An application under subsection (1) of section 4 of the Act to dispense with the consent required under section 3 of that Act, of a spouse to the conveyance of the family home shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df0ce4a-6d5d-4c09-939d-6893aeb7ca2b/Order dispensing with consent of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.12.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8df0ce4a-6d5d-4c09-939d-6893aeb7ca2b/Order dispensing with consent of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.12.docx/docx/1). (3) On granting an application under section 4 of the Act to dispense with the consent required under section 3 of that Act, the Court may order pursuant to section 33 of the [Trustee Act, 1893](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1893/act/53/enacted/en/print.html) that a person be appointed to execute the conveyance of the interest in question and the order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6232d23b-0016-4559-a960-0b355c5c68c0/Order appointing a person to execute consent to conveyance of family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 4(1) No. 60.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application be made to the Court for consent on behalf of a spouse?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the spouse is traveling abroad for leisure.","When the spouse is incapable of consenting due to unsoundness of mind or other mental disability, or cannot be found after reasonable inquiries.","When the spouse is temporarily unavailable due to work commitments.","When the spouse is capable of consenting but refuses to do so."],"justification":"Where the spouse whose consent is required under subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act is incapable of consenting by reason of unsoundness of mind or other mental disability or has not after reasonable inquiries been found"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Consent by the Court.* 13.[3] (1) Where the spouse whose consent is required under subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act is incapable of consenting by reason of unsoundness of mind or other mental disability or has not after reasonable inquiries been found, application may be made to the Court in the [Form 60.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1310b421-b173-42aa-8a7a-6ee0eed68d8a/Application for an order giving consent on behalf of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.14.docx/docx/1), under subsection (4) of section 4 of that Act for the Court to give the consent on behalf of that spouse. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.15, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a7da286-3928-4f2d-a647-bba86336145b/Order consenting to conveyance of family home No. 60.15.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 60.15, Schedule","Form 60.17, Schedule A","Form 60.20, Schedule","Form 60.16, Schedule"],"justification":"An application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home in the interest of the applicant spouse of a dependent child shall be in the [Form 60.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Protection of Family Home.* 14.[4] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home in the interest of the applicant spouse of a dependent child shall be in the [Form 60.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6342e31-1520-448a-9ee7-509e76cd2abf/Order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(1) No. 60.17.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in after an application is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 60.20, Schedule","Form 60.19, Schedule","Form 60.19, Schedule","Form 60.18, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Conduct leading to loss of Family Home.* 15.[5] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (2) of Conduct leading section 5 of the Act to compensate the applicant spouse and any dependent to loss of Family child of the family for loss occasioned by the conduct of the other spouse Home. shall be in the [Form 60.18, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3ae2cb1e-21c5-4e31-92a0-2a6a60b55277/Application for an order for compensation for loss relating to the family home - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(2) No. 60.18.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.19, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1e4f976b-0d51-4686-97aa-c13481731e57/Order of compensation for loss relating to family home - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.19.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 60 rule 11 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [2] Order 60 rule 12 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [3] Order 60 rule 13 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [4] Order 60 rule 14 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998 [5] Order 60 rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 42 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/42/made/en/print?q 42&years 1998), effective 15 March 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'In which court is Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage applicable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Appellate Court","District Court","Family Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be used when applying for a direction for the use of blood tests?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 70.4 Schedule","Form 50.3 Schedule A","Form 61.2 Schedule","Form 61.1 Schedule"],"justification":"an application under section 38 (1) of the Act by a party to the proceedings for a direction for the use of blood tests shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 61.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83d7a649-d1b7-4e05-bda2-03e28cff563c/Notice of application for direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 section 38(1) No. 61.1.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for a direction for the use of blood tests* 2. (1) Where in any civil proceedings before the Court the parentage of any person is in question, an application under section 38 (1) of the Act by a party to the proceedings for a direction for the use of blood tests shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 61.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83d7a649-d1b7-4e05-bda2-03e28cff563c/Notice of application for direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 section 38(1) No. 61.1.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other party or parties to the proceedings and upon each person in respect of whom the direction is sought or, where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her and shall be served at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (3) Where the Court of its own motion proposes to give a direction for the use of blood tests or where application for such a direction is made in the course of hearing the proceedings, and if each of the parties to the proceedings and each person in respect of whom the direction is proposed or sought (or his or her legal or other representative, as the case may be) is then present in court, the Court may dispense with the requirement to serve notice of application. (4) The direction of the Court shall be in the [Form 61.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b10be890-211b-4f39-a987-0f83ec683d17/Direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act, 1987 section 38 (1) No. 61.2.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person in respect of whom it was given or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'How should an order revoking or varying a direction be served if the person affected is covered by section 39(3) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By posting it on the official government bulletin board","Upon the person having charge of or control over him or her","Upon the local police station where the person is registered","Upon the nearest relative of the person affected"],"justification":"upon the person having charge of or control over him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order revoking or varying a direction* 3. Where under section 38 (3) of the Act the Court revokes or varies a direction previously given under section 38 (1) of the Act, the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d12db6d0-b7b7-40cc-8859-ef8fba9b0317/Order revoking - varying a direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.3.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a notice under section 40(5) of the Act take when a party intends to call a person as a witness?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 40.5 Schedule A","Form 62.4 Schedule","Form 61.4 Schedule","Form 61.3 Schedule"],"justification":"A notice under section 40 (5) of the Act by a party to civil proceedings of that party''s intention to call a person as a witness shall be in the [Form 61.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ed129f6-37c8-46f4-926a-7adee2623b90/Notice of intention to call witness - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of intention to call witness* 4. (1) A notice under section 40 (5) of the Act by a party to civil proceedings of that party''s intention to call a person as a witness shall be in the [Form 61.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ed129f6-37c8-46f4-926a-7adee2623b90/Notice of intention to call witness - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.4.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served by registered prepaid post upon the other parties to the proceedings or upon such of them as the Court may direct, at least fourteen days before the sitting of the Court at which it is intended to call as a witness the person named in the notice. (2) The original of every such notice served, together with statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What action should the Clerk take when the Court directs under section 38(1) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Clerk should email a copy of the direction form to the sampler named in the direction.","The Clerk should only complete Part of the direction form and leave Part blank before sending it by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler.","The Clerk should complete and sign Part and the relevant section of Part of a direction form and send it by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction.","The Clerk should verbally inform the sampler named in the direction about the court''s directive."],"justification":"Where the Court gives a direction under section 38 (1) of the Act, the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to send direction form to sampler* 5. Where the Court gives a direction under section 38 (1) of the Act, the Clerk shall complete and sign Part and the appropriate section of Part of a direction form as prescribed in the Regulations and shall send that form by prepaid ordinary post to the sampler named in the direction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order 61A - Section 40 of the Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Supreme Court","District Court","Magistrates Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004 - Court: District # Order 61A: Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004**[1][2]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''2004 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Taxation Reform Act 2004","The Environmental Protection Act 2004","The Digital Economy Act 2004","The Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004"],"justification":"the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this rule: the “**2004 Act**” means the [Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); a “**recorder**” means a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) intending to attend or attending any proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of such proceedings in accordance with section 40(3) of the 2004 Act; “**relevant enactment**” has the same meaning as in section 39 of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'What must a recorder do before or at the commencement of the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Swear in all witnesses and request a summary of proceedings.","Identify themselves to the Court and apply for directions.","Provide evidence to the Court and request a recess.","Introduce the jury members and ask for a continuance."],"justification":"A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court and apply for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Recorders* 2.[3] (1) A recorder must, prior to or at the commencement of the hearing of the proceedings, identify himself or herself to the Court and apply for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(3) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (2) On any such application, the Court - (a) if satisfied that the applicant is a person referred to in section 40(3)(a) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) and that the recorder intends to attend the proceedings for the purpose of the preparation and publication of a report of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, and - having heard any submission made by or on behalf of any party to the proceedings, may allow the recorder to attend the proceedings (or any part of the proceedings) subject to such directions as the Court may give in that regard. (3) The Court may, of its own motion or on the application of any party or person, vary or modify any such directions given under section 40(3) of the Act during the course of the proceedings. (4) Where the Court refuses to allow a recorder who has made an application under sub-rule (1) to attend the relevant proceedings, the Court must give its reasons for such refusal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'What may the court do prior to, at the commencement of, or during the course of the hearing of proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings to verify if they are a bona fide representative of the press.","The court may require all attendees to sing the national anthem before proceeding with the hearing.","The court may allow the jury to deliberate on the case before the trial has concluded.","The court may dismiss the case immediately without hearing any evidence."],"justification":"make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press within the meaning of section 40(3A) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Bona fide representatives of the press* 3. (1) Prior to, at the commencement of, or during the course of the hearing of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, the Court may - (a) make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press within the meaning of section 40(3A) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - hear any application by or on behalf of a party or person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub- section refers) for an order under 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or may for the purposes of considering the making of any such order of its own motion, hear submissions from any such party or person. (2) The Court may, at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings, of its own motion or on the application of a person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub-section refers), having heard the parties and any other person it considers necessary, vary or modify any order made in accordance with sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'In parte applications, who decides whether an accompanying person is approved?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Jury","The Judge","The Court","The Legal Representative"],"justification":"the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Accompanying persons* 4.[4] (1) Where a party (in this rule referred to as the “applicant”) wishes to be accompanied in court in any proceedings referred to in section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), save for proceedings to which section 26 of the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6/enacted/en/html) applies, by another person (in this rule referred to as “the accompanying person”), the applicant must, unless the Court otherwise directs, complete a notice of application in the [Form 61A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) Where the other party or parties agree to the accompanying person, the applicant must lodge [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed, with the Clerk prior to the commencement of the hearing in the proceedings, and must apply to the Court at that hearing to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (3) Except in parte applications, where the other party or parties have not agreed to the accompanying person, the applicant must, by application to the Court in the [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1), on notice to the other party or parties, returnable not later than seven days prior to the date fixed for the hearing in such proceedings, apply to the Court to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (4) In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a certificate of qualification be made if the applicant plans to operate in a single court area?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At the nearest courthouse outside the planned court area.","At any sitting of the Court in the court area where the applicant plans to carry on business.","Online through the provincial government''s website, regardless of the court area.","At the central office of the provincial legal authority in the capital city."],"justification":"at any sitting of the Court in the court area in which the applicant proposes to carry on business"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for certificate of qualification* 2. (1) An application for a certificate of qualification pursuant to Part III of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court in the court area in which the applicant proposes to carry on business or, in case the applicant proposes to carry on business in more than one court area, in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must notice be served on the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["no specific time frame","at least twenty-eight days","at least fourteen days","exactly thirty days"],"justification":"at least twenty-eight days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the applicant publish notice in a newspaper?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["exactly thirty days","at least twenty-eight days","no specific time requirement","at least fourteen days"],"justification":"at least twenty-eight days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published, at least twenty-eight days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must these documents be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Within twenty-four hours prior to the date of hearing of the application.","Exactly fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application.","At least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.","At least three days before the date of hearing of the application."],"justification":"at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and newspaper* (4) A copy of the notice of the application together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant provide to the court during the hearing of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The certificate required by section 10 (2) (a) of the Regulations","The applicant must provide a sworn affidavit detailing their financial status under section 15 of the Act","The certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act","The applicant must present a character reference letter from at least two individuals mentioned in section 8 of the Act"],"justification":"the applicant shall furnish to the Court the certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to furnish required certificates* (5) On the hearing of the application the applicant shall furnish to the Court the certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act (as inserted by section 12 of the [Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1967](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1967/act/9/enacted/en/print.html)) as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 63.2 Schedule","Form 63.1 Schedule A","Form 63.1 Schedule","Form 63.0 Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 63.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ed8d17e-7da9-4d5a-9042-f4577cde3d5b/Certificate of qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1947 No. 63.1.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 63.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ed8d17e-7da9-4d5a-9042-f4577cde3d5b/Certificate of qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1947 No. 63.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a notice of objection take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 74.5 Schedule A","Form 63.3 Schedule","Form 63.1 Schedule","Form 63.2 Schedule"],"justification":"Form 63.2 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. A notice of objection pursuant to section 11 (5) of the Act to the grant of a certificate of qualification shall be in accordance with [Form 63.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7d63184-090a-4651-990b-62fde646d8a5/Notice Of Objection To The Grant Of A Certificate Of Qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act 1947 No. 63.2.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served upon the applicant and a copy, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in Order 64?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Lottery Act, 1932 (No. 28 of 1932)","The Betting Act, 1931 (No. 27 of 1931)","The Gambling Act, 1930 (No. 26 of 1930)","The Betting Act, 1928 (No. 25 of 1928)"],"justification":"\"the Act\" means the [Betting Act, 1931 (No. 27 of 1931)]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931 - Court: District 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Betting Act, 1931 (No. 27 of 1931)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 64 - Betting Act, 1931', 'Court Rules', 'Which certificates can be appealed if refused by a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["certificate of public liability insurance","certificate of financial stability","certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises","certificate of professional indemnity"],"justification":"a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Procedure for appeal against refusal of Superintendent to grant certificate* 2. The procedure to be followed in an appeal from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a certificate of personal fitness or a certificate of suitability of premises under the Act is the procedure set out in the [Betting Act (District Court and Garda Síochána) Regulations, 1931 (Statutory Rules and Orders, 1931 No. 81)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1931/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order 65 - Fisheries?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Magistrate","District","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 65 - Fisheries - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''business'' mean in the context of this order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The processing or packaging of any agricultural products unrelated to fish or shellfish","The selling or exporting for sale of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate","The importing or purchasing for personal consumption of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate","The breeding or farming of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate"],"justification":"\"**business**\" means the selling or exporting for sale of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order "**the Act of 1962**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1962 (No. 31 of 1962)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1978**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1978 (No. 18 of 1978)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1980**" means the [Fisheries Act, 1980 (No. 1 of 1980)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1994**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1994 (No. 23 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/23/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959; (No. 14 of 1959)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html); "**business**" means the selling or exporting for sale of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice for an application for a certificate of fitness take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 65.1, Schedule","Form 65.1, Schedule","Form 65.0, Schedule","Form 65.2, Schedule A"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 65.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08e99c10-7260-410a-bac2-8f1c8548b8e5/Notice of application for a certificate of fitness - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 section 158 No. 65.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for cert. of fitness* 2. (1) An application pursuant to section 158 (as amended by section 14 of [the Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html) and the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 65.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08e99c10-7260-410a-bac2-8f1c8548b8e5/Notice of application for a certificate of fitness - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 section 158 No. 65.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3)[1] The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 324 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) A certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence granted under the said section 158 shall be in the [Form 65.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2776117-18da-4d59-809b-aa6d1b39086c/Certificate of fitness to hold a salmon dealer''s licence - eel dealer''s licence - molluscan shellfish dealer''s licence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the applicant use before making an application for detention?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 65.3, Schedule","Form 65.2, Schedule","Form 70.1, Section A","Form 65.4, Schedule"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 65.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ded52b27-89d4-4f64-a4f5-613bd5189680/Notice of application for an order authorising the continued detention of a boat and persons under section 233A as amended (for 48 hours) No. 65.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for detention of boat and persons (for 48 hours)* 3. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court pursuant to section 233A (as amended by section 12 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) and as substituted by section 11 of [the Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/23/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for an Order authorising the continued detention of a boat and the persons on board the boat (for a period of 48 hours) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which is situated the port in which the boat and persons concerned are detained. (2) Before making such application the applicant shall complete and lodge with the Clerk a notice in the [Form 65.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ded52b27-89d4-4f64-a4f5-613bd5189680/Notice of application for an order authorising the continued detention of a boat and persons under section 233A as amended (for 48 hours) No. 65.3.docx/docx/1), and shall deliver a copy thereof to each of the persons in respect of whom the order is sought. (3) Where the Court grants the application the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 65.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08ba4aac-0bda-4e2e-a035-1d99f461aecf/Order for detention under section 233a of the act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an order of the Court requiring the detention of a boat and persons on board?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 70, Detention Order","Form 66, Vessel Seizure Notice","Form 65.4, Schedule","Form 65.5, Schedule"],"justification":"Form 65.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat and persons pending adjudication of proceedings* 4. An order of the Court pursuant to section 234 (1) - as substituted by section 13 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the detention of a boat and persons (including the master) on board such boat until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/17b05ad3-0423-4b2f-a78f-c12720b11b83/Order for detention under section 234 (1) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order of the Court require for the detention of a boat until a fine and costs are paid?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 68.6 Schedule","Form 65.7 Schedule A","Form 65.5 Schedule","Form 65.6 Schedule"],"justification":"An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the further detention of a boat until a fine and costs (if any) are paid shall be in the [Form 65.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6e71db7-dbaa-4853-9785-28dcacf02fb0/Order for detention pending the payment of fine and costs - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) section 236 (1) No. 65.6.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat pending payment of fine and costs* 5. An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the further detention of a boat until a fine and costs (if any) are paid shall be in the [Form 65.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6e71db7-dbaa-4853-9785-28dcacf02fb0/Order for detention pending the payment of fine and costs - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) section 236 (1) No. 65.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can a boat be subject to distress and sale?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["When the boat is found to be in violation of environmental regulations","On the non-payment of a fine and costs (if any)","On the non-payment of crew wages","During a routine inspection by maritime authorities"],"justification":"An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for distress and the sale of a boat on the non-payment of a fine and costs (if any) shall be in the [Form 65.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05092604-13a3-449e-ad6d-6fff1fddf4fc/Order for detention of boat pending the taking of possession of article ordered to be - which stands - forfeited - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.8.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order for distress and sale of boat* 6. An order of the Court pursuant to section 236 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for distress and the sale of a boat on the non-payment of a fine and costs (if any) shall be in the [Form 65.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/05092604-13a3-449e-ad6d-6fff1fddf4fc/Order for detention of boat pending the taking of possession of article ordered to be - which stands - forfeited - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order for further detention of a boat take when a person is sent forward for trial or sentence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The order should be in Form 45.7 or 45.8, Schedule as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 65.9 or 65.10, Schedule as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 75.5 or 75.6, Schedule A, as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 30.12 or 30.13, Schedule as appropriate."],"justification":"shall be in the [Form 65.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/21862828-3330-408b-aaa2-fc23b2a85e4b/Order for further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (including appeals) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.9.docx/docx/1) or [65.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f25ec15-eef3-449b-a0ab-681f0f750b9b/Order for further detention of boat on sending forward - for trial - for sentence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (incl. appeals and trials)* 8. An order of the Court pursuant to section 235 (1) - as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the further detention of a boat pending, - in the case of an appeal from, or any other proceedings in relation to, an order convicting a person of an offence under Chapter or III of Part XIII of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) or an order dismissing proceedings in relation to such an offence, the determination of the appeal or any other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), in a case where a person is sent forward for trial or for sentence charged with an offence under the said Chapter or III, the determination of the case in the court to which that person was sent forward and, in the event of an appeal or other proceedings arising therefrom, the determination of the appeal or the other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), shall be in the [Form 65.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/21862828-3330-408b-aaa2-fc23b2a85e4b/Order for further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (including appeals) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.9.docx/docx/1) or [65.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f25ec15-eef3-449b-a0ab-681f0f750b9b/Order for further detention of boat on sending forward - for trial - for sentence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order of the Court require for releasing a boat?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 65.22, Schedule","Form 66.11, Schedule A","Form 65.10, Schedule","Form 65.11, Schedule"],"justification":"shall be in the [Form 65. 11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/02f45e63-688a-4889-b777-e0359f98a68d/Order requiring the release of a boat - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.11.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order for release of a boat* 9. An order of the Court pursuant to section 235 (2) (a) — as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring a boat to be released shall be in the [Form 65. 11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/02f45e63-688a-4889-b777-e0359f98a68d/Order requiring the release of a boat - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.11.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order of the Court for detention of a boat and/or persons pending adjudication be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 65,12, Schedule","Form 65,12, Schedule","Form 65,11, Schedule","Form 65,13, Schedule"],"justification":"shall be in the [Form 65,12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/47d29fc7-0609-4de2-aeb3-7bacdc26474d/Order for detention under section 301 (2A) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.12.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat/boat and persons pending adjudication of proceedings* 10. An order of the Court pursuant to section 301 (2A) — as inserted by section 53 of [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the detention of a boat and person or persons or of the boat only until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65,12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/47d29fc7-0609-4de2-aeb3-7bacdc26474d/Order for detention under section 301 (2A) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.12.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a warrant under section 297 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the District Court in the court district where the garden, dwellinghouse, or curtilage is located.","At any sitting of the High Court outside the court district where the garden, dwellinghouse, or curtilage is located.","At any local magistrate''s office within the same county as the garden, dwellinghouse, or curtilage.","At any sitting of the Supreme Court in the state capital where the garden, dwellinghouse, or curtilage is located."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the garden, dwellinghouse or curtilage thereof in respect of which the issue of the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *— venue* 11. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a warrant pursuant to section 297 — as amended by section 71 of [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the garden, dwellinghouse or curtilage thereof in respect of which the issue of the warrant is sought is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Who can make the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any citizen who has been a resident for more than five years","An individual listed in the first schedule of the Act of 1980","A legal entity registered under the Companies Act of 2000","An authorised person within the meaning of section 292 as substituted in the fourth schedule to the Act of 1980."],"justification":"of an authorised person within the meaning of section 292 — as substituted in the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *— by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 65.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0549f5af-f10b-4cdd-b171-c0974f25291b/Information for warrant (under section 297) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.13.docx/docx/1), of an authorised person within the meaning of section 292 — as substituted in the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant take when issued following a court''s grant of an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 65.10, Schedule A","Form 65.14, Schedule","Form 65.14, Schedule","Form 65.28, Schedule"],"justification":"the warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 65.14, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) Where the Court grants the application, the warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 65.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d15f3391-61fb-4640-b65f-71d29d028ae4/Warrant under section 297 - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act 1959 (as amended) No. 65.14.docx/docx/1). [1] Reference to Inland Fisheries Ireland substituted for the inland fisheries board by section 8 and Schedule 3, Part 6 of the [Inland Fisheries Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/10/).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","Magistrate","Supreme","High"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries - Court: District # Order 66: Gaming and lotteries**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''2019 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Gaming and Lotteries (Amendment) Act 2019 (No. 44 of 2019)","The Environmental Protection Act 2019 (No. 33 of 2019)","The Education and Training Act 2019 (No. 55 of 2019)","The Health Services Act 2019 (No. 22 of 2019)"],"justification":"the “**2019 Act**” means the [Gaming and Lotteries (Amendment) Act 2019 (No. 44 of 2019).](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order: the “**1956 Act**” means the [Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 (No. 2 of 1956)](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html); the “**2019 Act**” means the [Gaming and Lotteries (Amendment) Act 2019 (No. 44 of 2019).](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application under this order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The payment of a specified administrative fee to the regulatory body","The filing of a formal complaint with the relevant court","The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 66.1, Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.","The submission of an affidavit confirming the applicant''s identity"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/481b1d1f-ea20-4506-ba4b-69e615e0da41/Application for a certificate - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of Notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 66.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/481b1d1f-ea20-4506-ba4b-69e615e0da41/Application for a certificate - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'How many days prior to the hearing must the applicant publish a notice in a local newspaper?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least 14 days","No prior notice is required","Exactly 20 days","At least 7 days"],"justification":"The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 14 days before such date of hearing in a newspaper circulating in the locality."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 14 days before such date of hearing in a newspaper circulating in the locality. (5) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act 1981](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/section/24/enacted/en/html) shall apply to such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The original of the notice of appearance, together with a certificate of service and a copy of the court order","The original of the notice of motion, together with an affidavit of service and a copy of the legal document","The original of the affidavit of application, together with a proof of service and a copy of the summons","The original of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper"],"justification":"The original of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (6) The original of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a lottery licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By submitting an application to the relevant state''s department of taxation.","Through an online portal provided by the national lottery commission.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries.","At any local government office within the court area where the lottery will be promoted."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries to which the application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for Lottery Licence* 3.(1) An application for the grant of a licence for the promotion of a lottery pursuant to section 28 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 12 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries to which the application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for a lottery licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The payment of an initial deposit to the relevant government authority","The submission of a detailed business plan outlining the financial viability of the lottery","An announcement in a national newspaper declaring the intention to apply for a lottery licence","The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 66.3, Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the licence take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 66.5, Schedule","Form 67, Schedule A","Form 66.3, Schedule","Form 66.4, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 66.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4d2ac493-93d6-417b-85ef-839e588bbb3d/Licence for promotion of a lottery - 28 Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 No. 66.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 66.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4d2ac493-93d6-417b-85ef-839e588bbb3d/Licence for promotion of a lottery - 28 Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 No. 66.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an appeal be brought if a Superintendent refuses to grant a gaming permit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any local municipal council meeting where the application was previously discussed.","To the Gaming Appeals Board within the same court area where the application was initially denied.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated.","Before the Minister of Gaming and Lottery for a personal review of the decision."],"justification":"An appeal...may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue- Appeal against refusal to grant gaming permit* 4.(1) An appeal pursuant to section 9A(18) of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 4 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a gaming permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice for an appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The respondent or solicitor for the respondent.","The appellant or solicitor for the appellant.","The judge presiding over the case.","The court clerk."],"justification":"signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice of appeal* (3) An appeal under sub-rule (1) or sub-rule (2) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.5,](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b9005911-1bca-4513-b74a-5513e8726cc0/Notice of appeal against refusal of superintendent to grant a permit - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 27 No. 66.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'When must the Superintendent lodge documents with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least 24 hours before the sitting","At least 48 hours before the sitting","Within 7 days before the sitting","Immediately after the sitting"],"justification":"The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (4) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána concerned at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court at which the appeal is to be heard. When service has been effected the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of the said sitting. (5) The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court hearing the appeal follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 66.5, Schedule","Form 66.6, Schedule","Form 67, Schedule","Form 66.6, Schedule A"],"justification":"The order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 66.6], Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) The order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 66.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c77e320a-7b74-4d39-af6e-229c50218c81/Order on appeal from refusal of superintendent to grant permit for promotion of lottery - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 No. 66.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Execution of search warrant","Order granting search warrant","Application for search warrant","Affidavit in support of search warrant"],"justification":"*Application for search warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for search warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a search warrant under section 39 of the 1956 Act be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At the nearest courthouse, regardless of whether it is within the same court district as the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought.","At any police station within the same county as the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district where the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated.","To the Attorney General''s office for approval before presenting it to the relevant court."],"justification":"An application for the issue of a search warrant under section 39 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue* 5.(1) An application for the issue of a search warrant under section 39 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the place or premises in respect of which the warrant is sought is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application made under this order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By information on oath and in writing in Form 66.7","Through a sworn affidavit submitted orally in front of a judge","Through an electronic submission via the online portal without the need for a specific form","By verbal declaration before a notary public"],"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fed46a08-bd3a-4bda-8545-696d98d68c27/Information for search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fed46a08-bd3a-4bda-8545-696d98d68c27/Information for search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a search warrant take when issued on foot of granted application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 77.9, Schedule","Form 65.10, Schedule","Form 66.8, Schedule A","Form 66.8, Schedule"],"justification":"a search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 66.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f036d233-d395-4335-9815-6bfdcc023c49/Search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) Where the Court grants the application, a search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 66.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f036d233-d395-4335-9815-6bfdcc023c49/Search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application for revocation or suspension of a licence or permit be made orally?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When the individual verbally requests it during a routine administrative review.","When the applicant has missed two consecutive deadlines for annual license renewal.","When the licensing authority decides to revoke the permit due to non-payment of fees.","When the Court has determined the criminal proceedings concerned and the person would not be prejudiced."],"justification":"Where possible, an application for an order under section 46 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 19 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) that a lottery licence, lottery permit, gaming licence or gaming permit be revoked or suspended may be made orally to the Court when the Court has determined the criminal proceedings concerned, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that the person to whom the application relates would not thereby be prejudiced."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for an order that a licence or permit be revoked or suspended* 6.(1) Where possible, an application for an order under section 46 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 19 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) that a lottery licence, lottery permit, gaming licence or gaming permit be revoked or suspended may be made orally to the Court when the Court has determined the criminal proceedings concerned, without the necessity for the issue of a further notice of application, provided that the Court is satisfied that the person to whom the application relates would not thereby be prejudiced. (2) In any other case, such an application shall be in the [Form 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule with any necessary modifications, to which shall be attached a copy of the order of conviction, and shall be served by personal service or by prepaid registered post on the respondent. (3) If served personally, the notice shall be served at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable; if served by prepaid registered post, the notice must be served at least 14 days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. [1] Order 66 substituted by [S.I. 63 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/63/made/en/print) effective 25 February 2021'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5B - Procedure in certain Actions for Possession or Sale of Land and Actions for and Well-charging Relief', 'Court Rules', 'In what circumstances may evidence be adduced other than by affidavit in proceedings under Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By leave of the Magistrate, where permitted in accordance with rule 6(4) or rule 9(1), or where the proceedings have been adjourned for preliminary hearing in accordance with rule 9(2).","By leave of the Attorney General, where permitted in accordance with rule 7(3) or rule 9(1), or where the proceedings have been adjourned for summary judgment in accordance with rule 9(2).","By leave of the Judge, where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2).","By leave of the Registrar, where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(3), or where the proceedings have been adjourned for mediation in accordance with rule 8(4)."],"justification":"No party shall have the right in proceedings to which this Order applies to adduce any evidence otherwise than by affidavit, except - - (a) by leave of the Judge, - where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or - where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) A Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall be served, together with a copy of the affidavit mentioned in rule 5, on each defendant not later than 21 days before the return date mentioned in rule 4. 4. Every Civil Bill to which this Order applies shall, upon being issued, be assigned a return date before the County Registrar, which date shall be entered in the Civil Bill. (1) There shall be served with the Civil Bill a copy of an affidavit which shall conform to the requirements of [Form 54](/content/affidavit-support-civil-bill-possession-order-authorising-sale-under-section-1003-land-and) in the Schedule of Forms (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) sworn by or on behalf of the plaintiff, verifying and supporting the claim indorsed on the Civil Bill. (2) Where the agreement for a mortgage on foot of which proceedings to which this Order relates have been commenced is or was at the material time or times one to which a code drawn up by the Central Bank of Ireland in accordance with section 117 of the [Central Bank Act 1989](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1989/act/16/enacted/en/html) applies, the affidavit shall identify the code concerned. (3) A defendant intending to defend proceedings to which this Order applies shall enter an Appearance in the Office in [Form 5](/content/entry-appearance) in the Schedule of Forms within ten days of the service upon him of the Civil Bill and shall defend the plaintiff’s claim by filing a replying affidavit to the plaintiff’s affidavit setting out the defendant’s defence and serving a copy of that affidavit (and copies of any exhibits to that affidavit) on the plaintiff not later than four days before the return date. 6. (1) No party shall have the right in proceedings to which this Order applies to adduce any evidence otherwise than by affidavit, except - - (a) by leave of the Judge, - where permitted in accordance with rule 7(4) or rule 8(1), or - where the proceedings have been adjourned for plenary hearing in accordance with rule 8(2).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What court is associated with Order of the Defamation Act 2009?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Circuit","Supreme Court","High Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Circuit # **Order Defamation Act 2009******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Criminal Justice Act 2005","The Defamation Act 2009","The Data Protection Act 2018","The Employment Equality Act 2007"],"justification":"“**the Act**” means the [Defamation Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1. In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Defamation Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html) and any reference in this Order to a section shall, unless the context otherwise requires, be deemed to be a reference to a section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/31/enacted/en/print.html); “**defamation action**” has the same meaning as in section 2.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How is an application for leave under section 11(2) made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.","Through a verbal request during a scheduled court hearing.","By filing a written complaint with the court clerk.","By submitting an online form available on the official court website."],"justification":"An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 4. (1) An application to the Court for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party or parties, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (3) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957 shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the parties cannot agree on damages or costs after an offer to make amends is accepted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Both parties must attend a mediation session within 30 days of accepting the offer to make amends.","The defendant shall apply by motion on notice to the plaintiff for the Court’s directions for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1).","The plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1).","The parties shall resolve the dispute through arbitration as per the Alternative Dispute Resolution clause in their agreement."],"justification":"the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include directions as to the terms upon which any pleadings may be amended) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted 5. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include directions as to the terms upon which any pleadings may be amended) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1). 6. Where an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) to bring or to proceed with a defamation action against another person in respect of the statement to which the offer to make amends applies shall: - where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 5C - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What document is used when a defamation action has not been brought before the court and an offer to make amends is accepted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["offer of settlement","letter of demand","statement of claim","Originating notice of motion"],"justification":"where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of paragraph of section 23(1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of paragraph of section 23(1) and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the other person referred to in paragraph of section 23(1) shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 5 and 6 shall: - identify with sufficient precision, or exhibit a copy or transcript of, the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. In addition to any other order which may be made on the hearing of an originating notice of motion under sub-rule (3) of rule 4 or paragraph of rule 6, the Court may, at such hearing: - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application; - direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Can the plaintiff join multiple defendants when unsure about liability?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No, the plaintiff can only sue one defendant at a time.","Yes, to determine liability among defendants, even if not all defendants are interested in all aspects of the case.","The plaintiff cannot join multiple defendants unless they are all equally liable.","The plaintiff must choose the most likely defendant and cannot include others in the lawsuit."],"justification":"When the plaintiff is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more defendants, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the defendants is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **PARTIES** 1. All persons may be joined in one action as plaintiffs in whom any right to relief in respect of or arising out of the same transactions is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative, where, if such persons brought separate actions, any common question of law or fact would arise; provided that if, upon a motion on notice by any defendant, it shall appear that such joinder may embarrass or delay the trial, the Judge may order separate trials, or make such other order as may be right, and provided also that no person shall be made a plaintiff without his consent. 2. All persons may be joined as defendants against whom the right to any relief is alleged to exist, whether jointly, severally, or in the alternative. When the plaintiff is in doubt as to the person from whom he is entitled to redress, he may join two or more defendants, to the intent that the question as to which, if any, of the defendants is liable, and to what extent, may be determined as between all parties. It shall not be necessary that every defendant shall be interested as to all the relief sought, or as to every cause of action included in any proceedings against him; but the Judge may make such order as may appear just, to prevent any defendant from being embarrassed, or put to expense, by being required to attend any proceedings in which he has no interest. 3. The plaintiff may, at his option, join as defendants to the same action all or any of the persons severally, or jointly and severally, liable on any one contract, including parties to bills of exchange and promissory notes.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'How does a decision-making representation order affect who sues or defends in proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["If there is a decision-making representation order, the relevant person shall sue or defend by their decision-making representative, and service on the representative is good and sufficient.","If there is a decision-making representation order, the relevant person can choose to sue or defend independently without their representative.","Service on the decision-making representative is only considered good and sufficient if it is delivered via certified mail.","A decision-making representation order allows the relevant person to appoint any legal advisor of their choice as the representative for legal proceedings."],"justification":"Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person a decision-making representation order which authorises a decision-making representative appointed in respect of the person to institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her decision-making representative, and service on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. When proceedings have been brought on behalf of or against an infant, the Court may appoint a next friend or guardian litem* to act for or on behalf of such infant, and may change any next friend or guardian litem*, and appoint another in his place, and may also direct that any money or other personal property to which such infant may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of such infant in such manner as the Judge shall consider advisable. 8. [[2]](#2) (1) In this rule, the “**2015 Act**” means the [Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/act/64/enacted/en/html), and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person a decision-making representation order which authorises a decision-making representative appointed in respect of the person to institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her decision-making representative, and service on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power of attorney in respect of which a notification of lack of capacity has been accepted, which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney, and service on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where there is in force in respect of a relevant person as the donor a registered enduring power under the [Act of 1996](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1996/act/12/enacted/en/html), which includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the relevant person shall sue or defend by his or her attorney under the Act of 1996, and service on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'What must be included in documents if there is a registered co-decision-making agreement between the appointer and a co-decision-maker?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The documents must be stamped with a special seal indicating joint approval without needing signatures from both parties.","The documents must only be signed by the appointer and do not require any involvement from the co-decision-maker.","The documents must be signed by both the appointer and co-decision-maker or include a certificate stating that the decision to issue and deliver the document was made jointly by them.","The documents must be reviewed by an independent third party before being issued, regardless of the co-decision-making agreement."],"justification":"Where there is in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer a registered co-decision-making agreement which provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered in the proceedings shall be signed by, or shall include a certificate that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by, the appointer and co-decision-maker."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where there is in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer a registered co-decision-making agreement which provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered in the proceedings shall be signed by, or shall include a certificate that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by, the appointer and co-decision-maker. (6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee 9. Trustees, executors and administrators may sue and be sued on behalf of, or as representing the property or estate of which they are trustees or representatives, without joining any of the persons beneficially interested in the trust or estate, and shall be considered as representing such persons; but the Judge may, at any stage of the proceedings, order any of such persons to be made parties either in addition to or in lieu of the previously existing parties. This rule shall apply to trustees, executors, and administrators sued in proceedings to enforce a security by sale or otherwise. 10. Save in actions founded on tort, when there are numerous persons having the same interest in one action or matter, one or more of such persons may sue or be sued, or may be authorised by the Judge to defend, in such action or matter, on behalf of or for the benefit of all persons so interested.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 6 - Parties', 'Court Rules', 'Who may be named as a defendant in proceedings for the recovery of land?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Any tenant, under-tenant, or other person in actual possession of the property sought to be recovered, or any part thereof.","Anyone who has a financial interest in the neighboring properties, but does not possess the property in question.","Only the current legal owner of the property, excluding tenants or under-tenants.","Any person who has previously owned the property, regardless of current possession."],"justification":"Where proceedings are taken for the recovery of land, any tenant, under-tenant, or other person in actual possession of the property sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, may be named as defendant and the Civil Bill shall be directed to such tenant, under-tenant, or other person, with the addition of the words ‘‘and all persons concerned’’."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '11. Where proceedings are taken for the recovery of land, any tenant, under-tenant, or other person in actual possession of the property sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, may be named as defendant and the Civil Bill shall be directed to such tenant, under-tenant, or other person, with the addition of the words ‘‘and all persons concerned’’. 12. Where proceedings are taken as mentioned in the last preceding rule, any person not named in or served with the Civil Bill may by leave of the Judge appear and defend at the hearing, and the Judge may thereafter deal with such person, both as to costs and otherwise, as if he had originally been served with the Civil Bill as defendant. 13. When any person residing outside the Circuit, but inside the State, is a necessary and proper party to a proceeding properly instituted in the Court against some person within the Circuit, such first mentioned person may be served with the Civil Bill or other document without special leave. 14. Subject to the requirements of Rule 9 of Section 66 of the [Chancery (Ireland) Act, 1867](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1867/act/44/enacted/en/print.html), wherever, in any action for the administration of the estate of a deceased person, or for the execution of the trusts of any deed or instrument, or for the partition or sale of any hereditaments, a judgment or order has been pronounced affecting the rights or interests of persons not parties to the action, the Court may direct that any persons interested in the estate, or under the trusts, or in the hereditaments, shall be served with notice of the judgment or order; and after such notice such persons shall be bound by the proceedings, in the same manner as if they had originally been made parties, and shall be at liberty to attend the proceedings under the judgment or order. Any person so served may within one month after such service apply to the Court to discharge, vary or add to the said judgment or order. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 6 rule 4 substituted by 312 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/312/made/en/print), effective 20 July 2007. [2] Order 6 rule 8 substituted by 201 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/201/made/en/pdf) effective 27 April 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under the Act be brought, heard or determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["In any virtual courtroom platform approved by the national legal authority, irrespective of the physical location of the family home.","At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the family home.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home is situate.","At any county court within the same state as the family home, but not at the local court sitting where the family home is located."],"justification":"Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home, as defined in section 2 of the Act, is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue.* 2. (1) Proceedings under the Act may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the family home, as defined in section 2 of the Act, is situate. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the court district within which such court area is situate, certifies on a notice of application or a summons that the proceedings are urgent, the said notice or summons may, subject to the provisions of rule 9 hereof, be issued for, and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court for that district.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for the court order granting an application under section 9(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["[Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1)","[Form 61.4 Schedule C](https://www.example.com/form61_4_schedule_c)","[Form 60.4 Schedule B](https://www.example.com/form60_4_schedule_b)","[Form 59.4 Schedule C](https://www.example.com/form59_4_schedule_c)"],"justification":"order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(2).* 5. An application by a spouse under section 9(2) of the Act for an order permitting the disposition or removal of household chattels in the family home shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.4 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/582d82ed-d553-4c76-809d-c404224d9413/Order permitting disposition - removal of household chattels No. 60.4.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'Which order''s provisions apply when a spouse makes a complaint under section 9(4)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 12","Order 8","Order 15","Order 20"],"justification":"The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Summons under sec. 9(4).* 6. Where complaint is made by a spouse to a Judge under section 9(4) of the Act that the other spouse has contravened the provisions of section 9(2) of the Act, the summons which may be issued and served upon the other spouse shall be in the [Form 60.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6e7ddda3-b1ca-41da-8042-3d1c71c8fc2a/Summons - Family Home Protection Act 1976 section 9(4) No. 60.5.docx/docx/1). The relevant provisions of [Order 15]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-15-District-Issue-Of-Summonses-Alleging-Offences) of these Rules shall apply in such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court use when granting an application under section 9(5)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 60.7 Schedule","Form 60.7 Part","Form 60.7 Schedule","Form 61.7 Schedule"],"justification":"[Form 60.7 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 9(5).* 7. An application by a spouse under section 9(5) of the Act for an order that the respondent spouse provide household chattels for the applicant spouse or a sum of money in lieu thereof shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent spouse of a notice in the [Form 60.6 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50afe9f3-7566-49a1-8f80-6cb6ed573c6d/Notice of application for an order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 No. 60.6.docx/docx/1). The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 60.7 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6aa03ee6-d4e1-4d13-b1df-547e08ce42a1/Order under section 9 (5) - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.7.docx/docx/1), a copy of which shall be served upon the respondent spouse.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done with the original notice or summons served, except when the Clerk serves it?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It must be posted in a public place such as a community board or local newspaper.","It must be filed directly with the court without any additional documentation.","It must be returned to the original sender with a confirmation of receipt.","It must be lodged with the Clerk along with a statutory declaration of service at least two days before the court sitting."],"justification":"Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service and lodgment of documents.* 9. (1) A notice or summons required by this Order to be served may be served in accordance with the provisions of [Order 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) of these Rules and every such notice shall be served at least fourteen days or, in the case of proceedings certified as urgent under rule 2(2) hereof, at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) Save where service has been effected by the Clerk, the original of every such notice or summons served shall, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application to the Court be in to declare a conveyance void?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 59.10, Schedule","Form 60.9, Schedule","Form 60.8, Schedule","Form 61.1, Schedule A"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 3 of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Declaring a conveyance void.* 11.[1] (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the Act to have a conveyance declared void shall be in the [Form 60.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/03e16f21-650a-4e5e-ad7b-68ab4633b251/Application to have conveyance declared void No. 60.9.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24bb992f-a6aa-4ac9-826c-b2978cc088f7/Order declaring a conveyance void - Family Home Protection Act 1976 No. 60.10.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when applying to the Court for consent on behalf of a spouse?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 60.14, Schedule A","Form 60.15, Schedule","Form 60.13, Schedule","[Form 60.14, Schedule"],"justification":"[Form 60.14, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Consent by the Court.* 13.[3] (1) Where the spouse whose consent is required under subsection (1) of section 3 of the Act is incapable of consenting by reason of unsoundness of mind or other mental disability or has not after reasonable inquiries been found, application may be made to the Court in the [Form 60.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1310b421-b173-42aa-8a7a-6ee0eed68d8a/Application for an order giving consent on behalf of spouse to conveyance of family home No. 60.14.docx/docx/1), under subsection (4) of section 4 of that Act for the Court to give the consent on behalf of that spouse. (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.15, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2a7da286-3928-4f2d-a647-bba86336145b/Order consenting to conveyance of family home No. 60.15.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 60 - Protection of the Family Home', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in when granting an order for the protection of the family home?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 60.18, Schedule A","Form 59.17, Schedule","Form 60.17, Schedule","Form 60.17, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6342e31-1520-448a-9ee7-509e76cd2abf/Order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(1) No. 60.17.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Protection of Family Home.* 14.[4] (1) An application to the Court for an order under subsection (1) of section 5 of the Act for the protection of the family home in the interest of the applicant spouse of a dependent child shall be in the [Form 60.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5384c858-3d86-44cd-8d85-24f10f9e0b34/Application for an order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child No. 60.16.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court thereon shall be in the [Form 60.17, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6342e31-1520-448a-9ee7-509e76cd2abf/Order for the protection of family home in the interest of the spouse or dependent child - Family Home Protection Act, 1976 section 5(1) No. 60.17.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61 - Use Of Blood Tests In Determining Parentage', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order revoking or varying a direction take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 61.5 Schedule","Form 61.3 Schedule","Form 61.2 Schedule A","Form 61.4 Schedule"],"justification":"the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d12db6d0-b7b7-40cc-8859-ef8fba9b0317/Order revoking - varying a direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order revoking or varying a direction* 3. Where under section 38 (3) of the Act the Court revokes or varies a direction previously given under section 38 (1) of the Act, the order so revoking or so varying shall be in the [Form 61.3 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d12db6d0-b7b7-40cc-8859-ef8fba9b0317/Order revoking - varying a direction for the use of blood tests - Status of Children Act 1987 No. 61.3.docx/docx/1), and shall be served by prepaid ordinary post upon each person directly affected by that order or where such person is a person to whom section 39 (3) of the Act applies, upon the person having charge of or control over him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Which act does Order 61A - Section 40 belong to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004","Public Liability and Courts Act 2004","Criminal Liability and Courts Act 2004","Civil Rights and Courts Act 2004"],"justification":"Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004 - Court: District # Order 61A: Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004**[1][2]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court vary or modify an order made under sub-rule', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Yes, the court may vary or modify an order made under sub-rule at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings.","No, the court cannot vary or modify an order made under sub-rule once it has been issued.","The court can only vary or modify an order made under sub-rule if it is within the first 30 days after the order was made.","The court may vary or modify an order made under sub-rule only if all parties agree to the modification."],"justification":"The Court may, at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings, of its own motion or on the application of a person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub- section refers), having heard the parties and any other person it considers necessary, vary or modify any order made in accordance with sub-rule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Bona fide representatives of the press* 3. (1) Prior to, at the commencement of, or during the course of the hearing of proceedings to which a relevant enactment relates, the Court may - (a) make inquiries of any person attending the proceedings with a view to verifying whether that person is a bona fide representative of the press within the meaning of section 40(3A) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html); - hear any application by or on behalf of a party or person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub- section refers) for an order under 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) or may for the purposes of considering the making of any such order of its own motion, hear submissions from any such party or person. (2) The Court may, at any time during the course of the hearing of the proceedings, of its own motion or on the application of a person mentioned in section 40(3A)(b) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html) (or the Director of Public Prosecutions in a case to which paragraph of that sub-section refers), having heard the parties and any other person it considers necessary, vary or modify any order made in accordance with sub-rule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 61A - Section 40, Civil Liability and Courts Act 2004', 'Court Rules', 'What form must an applicant complete if they wish to be accompanied in court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","Form 61A.1","Form","Form"],"justification":"the applicant must, unless the Court otherwise directs, complete a notice of application in the Form 61A.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Accompanying persons* 4.[4] (1) Where a party (in this rule referred to as the “applicant”) wishes to be accompanied in court in any proceedings referred to in section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html), save for proceedings to which section 26 of the [Domestic Violence Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/6/enacted/en/html) applies, by another person (in this rule referred to as “the accompanying person”), the applicant must, unless the Court otherwise directs, complete a notice of application in the [Form 61A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) Where the other party or parties agree to the accompanying person, the applicant must lodge [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed, with the Clerk prior to the commencement of the hearing in the proceedings, and must apply to the Court at that hearing to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (3) Except in parte applications, where the other party or parties have not agreed to the accompanying person, the applicant must, by application to the Court in the [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1), on notice to the other party or parties, returnable not later than seven days prior to the date fixed for the hearing in such proceedings, apply to the Court to approve the accompanying person and for such directions as the Court may give under section 40(5) of the [2004 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/31/enacted/en/html). (4) In parte applications, subject to the lodgment of [Form No. 61A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/beab1983-2d41-4430-872a-c748299d2096/Request for the court’s permission to be accompanied by a person at the hearing - Civil Liability And Courts Act 2004 No. 61A.1.docx/docx/1) duly completed in accordance with sub-rule (1), the approval of any accompanying person is at the discretion of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a certificate of qualification be made if the applicant plans to operate in multiple court areas?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At the nearest provincial office of the Ministry of Justice, irrespective of the proposed principal place of business.","In any court area where the applicant has previously worked, regardless of their principal place of business.","In the court area where the applicant proposes to have their principal place of business.","Through an online portal provided by the national legal authority, without specifying the principal place of business."],"justification":"in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for certificate of qualification* 2. (1) An application for a certificate of qualification pursuant to Part III of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court in the court area in which the applicant proposes to carry on business or, in case the applicant proposes to carry on business in more than one court area, in the court area in which the applicant proposes to have his or her principal place of business.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Who must the notice of the application be served upon?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["the Minister for Justice","the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána","the Chief Justice","the Mayor of Dublin"],"justification":"the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the principal place of business is situate at least twenty-eight days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'Which act inserted the requirement for the certificate mentioned in the application process?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1967","The Property Brokers Regulation Act, 1975","The Estate Agents Act, 1989","The Real Estate Licensing Act, 1992"],"justification":"as inserted by section 12 of the [Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1967]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to furnish required certificates* (5) On the hearing of the application the applicant shall furnish to the Court the certificate required by section 12 (3) or 12 (4) of the Act (as inserted by section 12 of the [Auctioneers and House Agents Act, 1967](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1967/act/9/enacted/en/print.html)) as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 63 - Auctioneers and house agents', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must a notice of objection be served on the applicant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["within one week after the hearing date","immediately before the hearing starts","at least three days before the date of hearing","at least seven days before the date of hearing"],"justification":"at least seven days before the date of hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. A notice of objection pursuant to section 11 (5) of the Act to the grant of a certificate of qualification shall be in accordance with [Form 63.2 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7d63184-090a-4651-990b-62fde646d8a5/Notice Of Objection To The Grant Of A Certificate Of Qualification - Auctioneers and House Agents Act 1947 No. 63.2.docx/docx/1). Such notice shall be served upon the applicant and a copy, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1962'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Voting Rights Act of 1965","The Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1962 (No. 31 of 1962)","The Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965","The Civil Rights Act of 1964"],"justification":"\"**the Act of 1962**\" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1962 (No. 31 of 1962)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order "**the Act of 1962**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1962 (No. 31 of 1962)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1978**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1978 (No. 18 of 1978)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1980**" means the [Fisheries Act, 1980 (No. 1 of 1980)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1994**" means the [Fisheries (Amendment) Act, 1994 (No. 23 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/23/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959; (No. 14 of 1959)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html); "**business**" means the selling or exporting for sale of salmon and trout, eels, or molluscan shellfish as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any local police station in the court area where the applicant resides.","By submitting a written request to the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business.","Through an online portal provided by the Ministry of Justice."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 158 (as amended by section 14 of [the Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html) and the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for cert. of fitness* 2. (1) An application pursuant to section 158 (as amended by section 14 of [the Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/31/enacted/en/html) and the fourth schedule to [the Act of 1980](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1980/act/1/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for a certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant carries on or proposes to carry on business. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 65.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08e99c10-7260-410a-bac2-8f1c8548b8e5/Notice of application for a certificate of fitness - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 section 158 No. 65.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3)[1] The applicant shall serve the notice upon Inland Fisheries Ireland not less than fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 324 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) A certificate of fitness to hold a Part licence granted under the said section 158 shall be in the [Form 65.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e2776117-18da-4d59-809b-aa6d1b39086c/Certificate of fitness to hold a salmon dealer''s licence - eel dealer''s licence - molluscan shellfish dealer''s licence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for detention of a boat and persons be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any federal court regardless of the location of the port where the boat is detained.","At any maritime authority office in the country where the boat is registered.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district in which is situated the port in which the boat and persons concerned are detained.","At any local police station within the jurisdiction where the boat is located."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which is situated the port in which the boat and persons concerned are detained."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for detention of boat and persons (for 48 hours)* 3. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court pursuant to section 233A (as amended by section 12 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) and as substituted by section 11 of [the Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/23/enacted/en/html)) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) for an Order authorising the continued detention of a boat and the persons on board the boat (for a period of 48 hours) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which is situated the port in which the boat and persons concerned are detained. (2) Before making such application the applicant shall complete and lodge with the Clerk a notice in the [Form 65.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ded52b27-89d4-4f64-a4f5-613bd5189680/Notice of application for an order authorising the continued detention of a boat and persons under section 233A as amended (for 48 hours) No. 65.3.docx/docx/1), and shall deliver a copy thereof to each of the persons in respect of whom the order is sought. (3) Where the Court grants the application the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 65.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/08ba4aac-0bda-4e2e-a035-1d99f461aecf/Order for detention under section 233a of the act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Under which section of the Principal Act is the order of the Court for detention issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section 233 (1)","Section 234 (2)","Section 235 (1)","Section 234 (1)"],"justification":"section 234 (1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Detention of boat and persons pending adjudication of proceedings* 4. An order of the Court pursuant to section 234 (1) - as substituted by section 13 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) - of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the detention of a boat and persons (including the master) on board such boat until proceedings have been adjudicated upon by the Court shall be in the [Form 65.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/17b05ad3-0423-4b2f-a78f-c12720b11b83/Order for detention under section 234 (1) of the Act - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'In what circumstances is a boat detained further pending determination of proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When a person is sent forward for trial or sentence charged with an offence under Chapter or of Part XIII of the Principal Act.","When a person is sent forward for trial or sentence charged with an offence under Chapter or of Part XII of the Principal Act.","When a person is sent forward for trial or sentence charged with an offence under Chapter or VII of Part XIV of the Principal Act.","When a person is sent forward for trial or sentence charged with an offence under Chapter or III of Part XIII of the Principal Act."],"justification":"in a case where a person is sent forward for trial or for sentence charged with an offence under the said Chapter or III, the determination of the case in the court to which that person was sent forward and, in the event of an appeal or other proceedings arising therefrom, the determination of the appeal or the other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (incl. appeals and trials)* 8. An order of the Court pursuant to section 235 (1) - as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring the further detention of a boat pending, - in the case of an appeal from, or any other proceedings in relation to, an order convicting a person of an offence under Chapter or III of Part XIII of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) or an order dismissing proceedings in relation to such an offence, the determination of the appeal or any other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), in a case where a person is sent forward for trial or for sentence charged with an offence under the said Chapter or III, the determination of the case in the court to which that person was sent forward and, in the event of an appeal or other proceedings arising therefrom, the determination of the appeal or the other proceedings (and any proceedings consequent upon the appeal or the other proceedings), shall be in the [Form 65.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/21862828-3330-408b-aaa2-fc23b2a85e4b/Order for further detention of boat pending determination of proceedings (including appeals) - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.9.docx/docx/1) or [65.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f25ec15-eef3-449b-a0ab-681f0f750b9b/Order for further detention of boat on sending forward - for trial - for sentence - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'Under which section is the order of the Court for releasing a boat based?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["section 235(2)(a) as substituted by section 14 of the Act of 1978","section as amended by section 10 of the Act of 1980","section as modified by section 12 of the Act of 1978","section 236(2)(a) as revised by section 15 of the Act of 1976"],"justification":"pursuant to section 235 (2) (a) — as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order for release of a boat* 9. An order of the Court pursuant to section 235 (2) (a) — as substituted by section 14 of [the Act of 1978](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1978/act/18/enacted/en/html) — of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1959/act/14/enacted/en/html) requiring a boat to be released shall be in the [Form 65. 11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/02f45e63-688a-4889-b777-e0359f98a68d/Order requiring the release of a boat - Fisheries (Consolidation) Act, 1959 (as amended) No. 65.11.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 65 - Fisheries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["*Application for warrant*","Forms of evidence submission","Conditions for arrest","Procedure for search and seizure"],"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Under what legislation can an application for a lottery licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section 18 of the 1956 Act (as amended by section 3 of the 2020 Act).","Article 28 of the 1956 Regulations (as modified by section 10 of the 2018 Act).","Clause 28 of the 1956 Ordinance (as revised by section 14 of the 2017 Act)","Section 28 of the 1956 Act (as substituted by section 12 of the 2019 Act)."],"justification":"pursuant to section 28 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 12 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html))"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue - Application for Lottery Licence* 3.(1) An application for the grant of a licence for the promotion of a lottery pursuant to section 28 of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 12 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which it is proposed to promote lotteries to which the application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice issued before an application for a lottery licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The applicant or solicitor for the applicant.","The previous licensee","The local government official","The lottery commissioner"],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 66.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e3f369a3-78c7-411f-b9bf-b7a76292800a/Application for a lottery licence - Gaming and Lotteries Act 1956 No. 66.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Under what legislation is the appeal made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Section 9A(18) of the 1956 Act (as inserted by section 4 of the 2019 Act).","Section of the 1956 Act (as amended by section 3 of the 2020 Act).","Section 9A(17) of the 1957 Act (as inserted by section 5 of the 2018 Act).","Section 9A(18) of the 1960 Act (as inserted by section 4 of the 2021 Act)."],"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 9A(18) of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 4 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a gaming permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue- Appeal against refusal to grant gaming permit* 4.(1) An appeal pursuant to section 9A(18) of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 4 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a gaming permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises to which the application relates is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an appeal be brought if a Superintendent refuses to grant a lottery permit?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the lottery is to be held.","To the Provincial Supreme Court''s Appeals Division in the capital city.","At any local municipal council meeting in the area where the lottery is to be held.","Before the Minister responsible for the Gaming Act in a formal written petition."],"justification":"may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the lottery is to be held."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue- Appeal against refusal to grant lottery permit* (2) An appeal pursuant to section of the [1956 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/2/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 11 of the [2019 Act](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/act/44/enacted/en/html)) from the refusal of a Superintendent of the Garda Síochána to grant a lottery permit may be brought at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the lottery is to be held.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the court sitting must the notice be served on the Superintendent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Exactly five days","At least three days","At least seven days","No specific time requirement"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána concerned at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court at which the appeal is to be heard."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (4) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána concerned at least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court at which the appeal is to be heard. When service has been effected the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of the said sitting. (5) The Superintendent shall lodge with the Clerk at least 48 hours before the sitting a copy of the application for the permit and a copy of the decision from which the appeal is being brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 66 - Gaming and lotteries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum rank of the Garda Síochána member who can provide the information?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Inspector","Constable","Sergeant","Chief Superintendent"],"justification":"of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing (in the [Form 66.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fed46a08-bd3a-4bda-8545-696d98d68c27/Information for search warrant - Gaming and Lotteries Act, 1956 section 39 No. 66.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule of a member of the Garda Síochána not below the rank of Inspector.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Under which court does Order 67 apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["High Court","District Court","Supreme Court","County Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 67 - General dealers - Court: District 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1903/act/44/enacted/en/print.html) (3 Edw. VII 44).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["*General Dealers Licence Application Form*","*Application for Specialised Dealers Licence*","*Dealership License Application*","*Application for General Dealers Licence*"],"justification":"*Application for General Dealers Licence*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for General Dealers Licence*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a General Dealer''s Licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through an online application on the provincial government’s official website.","At the nearest branch of the Ministry of Business Licensing and Compliance.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the proposed business premises are located.","At the local town hall for the area in which the proposed business premises are located."],"justification":"An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 2. (1) An application for a General Dealer''s Licence pursuant to section 1 (2) of the Act may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises in which it is proposed to carry on business are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice for a general dealer''s licence application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The local licensing officer","Any member of the applicant''s family","The applicant''s bank manager","The applicant or solicitor for the applicant."],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34bc3ede-f823-4446-b466-3366f4277bc6/Notice of application for a general dealer''s licence - General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 section 1 No. 67.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk after service has been effected?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A copy of the notice and a notarized affidavit of service","A signed acknowledgment form from the recipient and a letter of intent","The original of the notice and a certificate of delivery from the post office","The original of the notice and a statutory declaration as to service thereof"],"justification":"the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) When service has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the licence be in if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 57.2, Schedule","Form 58.2, Schedule A","Form 57.1, Schedule","Form 57.3, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4dde7091-171c-4c95-b51f-5402ef56bb8a/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act are declarations of fitness covered by Order 68?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960","The Public Health Act 1984","The Environmental Protection Act 1990","The Food Safety Act 2010"],"justification":"- Declarations of fitness under section 15 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 - Court: District # Order 68: Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018 [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftn1) **- Certificates for spirit retailers’ licences, beer retailers’ licences, wine retailers’ licences, wholesale beer licences, producer’s retail licences;** **- Declarations of fitness under section 15 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["*Off-licence applications*","Retail applications","General licence applications","On-licence applications"],"justification":"*Off-licence applications*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Off-licence applications*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a certificate or declaration be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At the nearest municipal courthouse regardless of whether it is within the same court area.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises are located.","At any local post office within the state where the premises or proposed premises are located.","Online through the official website of the national government''s legal department."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 1. (1) An application for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive an excise licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor for consumption off the premises or for a declaration as to the fitness and convenience of proposed licensed premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises or proposed premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice issued before an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["the judge presiding over the case","the applicant or solicitor for the applicant","the court clerk","the witness providing testimony in the case"],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Forms of notice* (2) Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 68.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ba678d47-364c-423d-a6d3-635a539b9ebc/Notice Of Application For A Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence. No. 68.1.docx/docx/1) to [68.5A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b655656f-3ba7-458f-adb7-2c4b25b2f01e/Notice of application for a certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (Breweries and Distilleries) Act 2018, section 1 No. 68.5A.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum notice period required for publishing a notice of an application for a spirit retailer’s licence, beer retailer’s licence, wine retailer’s licence, or producer’s retail licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At least 14 days before the date of the hearing of the application","At least 7 days before the date of the hearing of the application","At least 30 days before the date of the hearing of the application","At least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application"],"justification":"the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice for spirit, beer or wine retailer’s or producer’s application* (4) Where the application is for the grant of a certificate entitling the applicant to receive a spirit retailer’s licence, a beer retailer’s licence, a wine retailer’s licence or a producer’s retail licence, the applicant shall, at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application, cause a notice of the intended application to be published in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant do when applying for a declaration regarding the fitness and convenience of premises for licensing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Publish a notice of the intended application at least 21 days before the hearing in a newspaper circulating in the area where the premises are located.","Submit a written declaration to the local government office within 7 days of the intended application.","Announce the intention on social media platforms like Facebook and Twitter at least one week prior to the hearing.","Post a sign at the premises for a minimum of 30 days prior to the hearing."],"justification":"the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice of application for declaration* (5) Where the application is for a declaration that the premises would be fit and convenient to be licensed the applicant shall cause a notice of the intended application to be published at least 21 days before the date of the hearing of the application in a newspaper circulating in the place in which the premises concerned are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance of the hearing date must these documents be lodged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Immediately upon filing the application, regardless of the hearing date.","Within two weeks after the date of hearing of the application.","At least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.","At least five days before the date of hearing of the application."],"justification":"at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, newspaper, etc.* (6) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises shall be lodged with the Clerk at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'When was Order 68 last re-substituted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Re-substituted by S.I. 566 of 2019, effective 9 January 2020","Re-substituted by S.I. 566 of 2018, effective 9 January 2019","Re-substituted by S.I. 566 of 2017, effective 9 January 2018","Re-substituted by S.I. 766 of 2018, effective 9 January 2019"],"justification":"Order 68 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174\u0026years 2009), re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566\u0026years 2018), effective 9 January 2019"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (7) Where the application is granted, the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 68.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eff3a56c-ed83-45fb-9512-6f52327059d3/Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence No. 68.6.docx/docx/1) to [68.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/edd299f3-eebd-4444-a908-7e4b9817732e/Certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (breweries and Distilleries) Act 2019, section 1 No. 68.11.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be. [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftnref1) Order 68 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order 69?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","Magistrate","High","Supreme"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Where may an application for a restaurant certificate be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situated.","At the local health department office.","Through an online portal on the city''s official website.","By sending a written request to the mayor''s office."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for applications* 2. (1) An application for the grant of - - (a) a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), - a restaurant certificate, made by the holder of a wine retailer''s on-licence pursuant to section 12 (1A) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 8 of the [Act of 1943](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1943/act/7/enacted/en/html)), - a restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12 (1) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 12 of the said Act (as inserted by section 48 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)), - a limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 12A of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as inserted by section 9 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html)), or - a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, pursuant to section 16 of the [Act of 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate or declaration is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice issued before an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The opposing party''s attorney","The applicant or solicitor for the applicant","The clerk of the court","The judge presiding over the case"],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Forms of notice* (2) Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 69.1 to 69.5 Schedule C,](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings) as the case may be, signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'What additional document must be deposited with the officer when the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A copy of the plan of the premises","A certificate of good character from the local community","A signed affidavit from the property owner confirming the building''s structural integrity","A copy of the menu for the proposed restaurant"],"justification":"the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana for the licensing area at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application and, where the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the documents be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least two days.","At least four days.","No specific time frame is required.","Exactly three days."],"justification":"at least four days before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and map* (4) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'What forms should a certificate or declaration be in accordance with if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["One of Forms 70.1 to 70.5, Schedule","One of Forms 65.1 to 65.5, Schedule A","One of Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule","One of Forms 58.2 to 58.6, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 69.6 to 69.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What court does Order 7 - Third Party Procedure apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["County Court","Supreme Court","High Court","Circuit Court"],"justification":"- Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Third Party Procedure - Court: Circuit'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application for leave to issue a third party notice made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By filing a petition with the court clerk in accordance with Form","By sending a written request to the defendant in accordance with Form 6A.","By submitting an affidavit to the judge in accordance with Form","By motion on notice to the plaintiff in accordance with Form"],"justification":"The application for such leave shall be made by motion on notice to the plaintiff in accordance with [Form 6C](http://icsmweb09/content/application-leave-issue-and-serve-third-party-notice) as set out in the Schedule of Forms attached hereto."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Actions by and against Firms and Persons Carrying on Business in names other than their own** 1. Where in any action a defendant claims as against any person not already a party to the action (in this Order called ‘‘**the third party**’’) (*a*) that he is entitled to contribution or indemnity; that he is entitled to any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the action and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the plaintiff; that any question or issue relating to or connected with the said subject matter is substantially the same as some question or issue arising between the plaintiff and the defendant and should properly be determined not only as between the plaintiff and the defendant but as between the plaintiff and the defendant and the third party or between any or either of them, the Court may give leave to the defendant to issue and serve a third party notice and may, at the same time, if it shall appear desirable to do so, give the third party liberty to appear at the trial and take such part therein as may be just, and generally give such directions as to the Court shall appear proper for having any question or the rights or liabilities of the parties most conveniently determined and enforced and as to the mode and extent in or to which the third party shall be bound or made liable by the decision or judgment in the action. 2. The application for such leave shall be made by motion on notice to the plaintiff in accordance with [Form 6C](http://icsmweb09/content/application-leave-issue-and-serve-third-party-notice) as set out in the Schedule of Forms attached hereto. Unless the plaintiff wishes to add the third party as a defendant, his attendance at the hearing of the motion shall not be necessary. If the plaintiff does attend he shall not be entitled to costs in respect of the motion except by special direction of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'How long does the third party notice need to be served after the order is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Immediately upon the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court.","Within seven days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court.","Within thirty days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court.","Within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court."],"justification":"The third party notice shall be served within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Application for leave to issue the third party notice shall, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, be made after the service of an Appearance and at any time prior to the trial of the action. 4. The third party notice shall state the nature and grounds of the claim or the nature of the question or issue sought to be determined and all information required to be set out in the indorsement of a Civil Bill as provided for in these rules and any directions of the Court given under Rule 1 hereof. The third party notice shall be issued and served in the same manner as in the case of a Civil Bill and shall be served within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. A copy of the Civil Bill and defence together with a copy of the Order joining the third party shall be served with the third party notice which said third party notice shall also be served upon the Plaintiff(s). Where the third party is joined as a defendant, an amended Civil Bill together with a copy of the Order joining the third party as a defendant shall be served upon all defendants by the plaintiff within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. Any amended defence of an original defendant to the proceedings shall be served upon the plaintiff within ten days from the date of service of the amended Civil Bill. 4A.[1] A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt)) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt) and, in the case of service, where the third party or third party’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'How long does a third party have to enter an appearance after receiving the third party notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Within thirty days after service, regardless of any agreement between the parties.","Immediately upon receipt of the third party notice, without regard to any stated time periods.","Within a stated time after service, which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court.","Within five days after service, unless extended by the court for good cause shown."],"justification":"The third party notice shall call upon a third party to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the defendant, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant and shall be entitled to be served with all pleadings in the proceedings by the party filing and/or delivering same. 6. The third party notice shall call upon a third party to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the defendant, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 7. Where a third party enters an appearance, he shall deliver his defence within ten days from the date thereof or within such further period as may be allowed by the Court or consented to by the defendant(s) in the proceedings. 8. After the third party enters an appearance, and before the expiration of the time limited for the delivery of defence, he may, after serving notice of the intended application upon the plaintiff and all defendants, apply to the Court to vary any directions given by the Court under Rule 1 of this Order. 9. The Court may decide all questions of costs as between a third party and the other parties to the action, and may order any one or more to pay the costs of any other or others or give such directions as to costs as the justice of the case may require. [1] Order 7 rule 4A inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order 7?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District Court","County Court","Supreme Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''minor'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The term ''minor'' indicates a person who has not completed their secondary education as per the Education Act, 2000.","The term ''minor'' is defined as any individual under the age of consent as stated in the Marriage Act, 2004.","The term ''minor'' refers to a person below the age specified by the Income Tax Act, 1961.","The term ''minor'' is defined in accordance with section 3 of the Age of Majority Act, 1985."],"justification":"“**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1985/act/2/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 2 of 1985)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Construction* 1. In this Order- “**minor**” shall be construed in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of the [Age of Majority Act, 1985](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1985/act/2/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 2 of 1985).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Who can a minor sue by?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["legal guardian","parent","sister","next friend"],"justification":"A minor may sue by his or her next friend"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Minors - next friend/guardian litem* 2. A minor may sue by his or her next friend, and may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem. In any such case, before the name of any person shall be used in proceedings as next friend or guardian litem of the minor, such person shall sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule for that purpose, which shall be lodged with the Clerk together with the civil summons or other originating document or, as the case may be, with a notice of intention to defend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Can the court replace a person who has been appointed as a next friend or guardian litem?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, once appointed, a next friend or guardian litem cannot be replaced by the court.","The court can only replace a next friend or guardian litem if they have served for more than one year.","Yes, the court may replace a person so appointed at any time.","The replacement of a next friend or guardian litem is solely at the discretion of the appointing authority, not the court."],"justification":"and may at any time replace a person so appointed"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appointment by the Court* 3. Where any proceedings are brought before the Court on behalf of or against a minor the Court may, if it thinks it expedient so to do, at any stage of the proceedings by an order in writing in the Form 7.2, Schedule appoint a next friend or a guardian litem to act for and on behalf of such minor, and may at any time replace a person so appointed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What is required when a sum of money is lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong where the plaintiff is a minor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An application to the judge to decide whether the sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial.","A declaration from the defendant that they admit to the wrongdoing and agree to pay the sum of money.","A petition filed by the plaintiff requesting immediate payment of the damages without the need for further proceedings.","An agreement between the plaintiff''s guardian and the defendant to settle the case out of court."],"justification":"Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court approval required for acceptance of lodgments, etc.* 4.(1) Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing. (2) The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 2 (4) of these Rules shall apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor, where a settlement, compromise, payment or acceptance of money paid into court therein is proposed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to copies of orders made under rules 4, 5, or 6 of this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Copies of these orders shall be destroyed immediately after being reviewed.","Copies of these orders shall be retained by the Clerk without sending them anywhere.","Copies of these orders shall be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant where appropriate.","Copies of these orders shall be sent by the Accountant to the Clerk where appropriate."],"justification":"A copy of any order made under rule 4, 5 or 6 of this Order shall, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Orders for investment, etc.* 5.(1)[1] The Court may, subject to the provisions of [Order 12A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12A-District-Funds-In-Court), direct that any sum of money or other personal property to which the minor may be declared entitled in such proceedings be secured or invested for the benefit of the minor in such manner as the Court may consider advisable. A copy of any order made under rule 4, 5 or 6 of this Order shall, where appropriate, be sent by the Clerk to the Accountant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Who can apply for an interim payment on behalf of a minor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The minor''s next friend or guardian litem","The minor''s friend or classmate","The minor''s teacher or school principal","The minor''s sibling or cousin"],"justification":"the minor''s next friend or guardian litem"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim payments* (2) Unless the Court shall otherwise decide, no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court made upon the application of the minor''s next friend or guardian litem. Such application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the proceedings were heard and determined, upon lodging with the Clerk a notice in the Form 7.4, Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What document must be provided if requested by the court during the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Proof of income verification as stated in rule 9.","Proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7.","Proof of residence in the manner prescribed in rule 8.","Proof of employment status as outlined in rule 5."],"justification":"The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Payment out of sums invested* (2) A person who, on attaining full age, seeks the payment of any sum of money which was secured or invested for his or her benefit under rule 5 (1) hereof or any balance of such sum remaining due, may apply at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the proceedings were heard and determined for an order authorising such payment. Notice of the application in the Form 7.5, Schedule shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days prior to the date of hearing. The applicant shall, if required at the hearing, produce proof of age in the manner prescribed in rule 7 hereof.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court do after hearing an application for payment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The court may direct the payment out to the applicant of any sum of money due, with accrued interest or dividend, or make any other order deemed just.","The court may require the applicant to pay a fine for submitting the application.","The court may dismiss the application for payment if it finds the applicant is not entitled to any money.","The court may order the payment to be directed to a charity instead of the applicant."],"justification":"On hearing the application the Court may by order direct the payment out to the applicant of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to the applicant, together with accrued interest or dividend thereon (if any), or may make any other order on such application as to the Court shall seem just."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order for payment* (3) On hearing the application the Court may by order direct the payment out to the applicant of any sum of money which the Court is satisfied is due to the applicant, together with accrued interest or dividend thereon (if any), or may make any other order on such application as to the Court shall seem just. 6A[2]. (1) An application by the next friend, committee or other person referred to in subsection (1) of section 35 of the Act shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district within which the claimant ordinarily resides. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the Form 7.6, Schedule and shall be addressed to the respondent by name and shall be served by the applicant on the respondent not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. Such notice shall be served- - (a) by delivering it to the respondent; - by leaving it at the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished by the respondent, at that address, or - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter to the address at which the respondent ordinarily resides or, in a case in which an address for service has been furnished, to that address. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4)[3] Where the Court approves an assessment in accordance with this rule it may give directions as to how the amount recoverable by the minor, ward or relevant person within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 is to be dealt with, including a direction for lodgement in Court and investment of the amount concerned. (5) The Clerk shall send by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail to the Personal Injuries Assessment Board a certified copy of any order made pursuant to this rule. (6) In the event of an order to pay issuing in accordance with section 38 of the 2003 Act, a copy thereof shall be sent forthwith by the Personal Injuries Assessment Board to the Clerk by ordinary pre-paid post or by e-mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Where should the date of birth be noted in any Court order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["In the margin notes of the Court''s official records","In the footer section of the Court''s official records","In any order of the Court made in any such proceeding or application","On a separate document attached to the Court''s official records"],"justification":"The said date of birth shall be noted in any order of the Court made in any such proceeding or application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proof of age* 7. A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth shall, if required, be produced and proved on behalf of the minor at the hearing of proceedings involving such minor, on an application to have a proposed settlement approved by the Court or on any other application relating to a minor or a person who has lately been a minor. The said date of birth shall be noted in any order of the Court made in any such proceeding or application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''2015 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015","The Data Protection Act 2015","The Taxation Act 2015","The Employment Equality Act 2015"],"justification":"the “2015 Act” means the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Relevant person to whom the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 applies* 8[4].(1) In this rule, the “2015 Act” means the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015, and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where notification of lack of capacity has been accepted in respect of a registered enduring power of attorney made by a relevant person as the donor, which power includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where a registered enduring power under the Act of 1996, made by a relevant person as the donor, includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney under the Act of 1996 may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service. (5) Where a registered co-decision-making agreement in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered on behalf of that party in such proceedings shall state that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by the appointer and co-decision-maker.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What can a ward of court do in legal proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A ward of court may represent themselves in legal proceedings without a committee.","A ward of court can only appeal decisions made by their committee.","A ward of court cannot participate in any legal proceedings.","A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee."],"justification":"A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What rules govern the service of documents on a relevant person to whom rule 8 applies?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The provisions of Order 41, including rule 9.","The provisions of Order 57, specifically rule 13.","The common law principles of service as outlined in the Civil Procedure Act.","The guidelines set forth in Rule 20 of the Administrative Orders."],"justification":"and upon a relevant person to whom rule 8 applies in accordance with the provisions (including rule 9) of that Order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of documents* 9.[5] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents upon a minor shall be effected in accordance with the provisions (including rule 8) of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules, and upon a relevant person to whom rule 8 applies in accordance with the provisions (including rule 9) of that Order. [1] Order 7 rule 5(1) substituted by [S.I. 258 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/258/made/en/print?q 258&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005 [2] Order 7 rule 6A inserted by [S.I. 526 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/526/made/en/print?q 526&years 2004), effective 8 September 2004 [3] Order 7 rule 6A(4) substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.[4] [4] Order 7 rule 8 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [5] Order 7 rule 9 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can a party change their solicitor or discharge their solicitor in any cause or matter?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Yes, unless the court orders otherwise in all cases.","Yes, at any time during the proceedings.","No, except in matrimonial causes or matters.","Yes, but only with the consent of the opposing party."],"justification":"save in any matrimonial cause or matter, be at liberty to change his solicitor or to discharge his solicitor and sue or defend in person, and any party suing or defending in person shall be at liberty to appoint a solicitor, in any cause or matter, without an order for that purpose, upon notice of such change, discharge, or appointment being filed in the Central Office, but until such notice is so filed and a copy thereof served as hereinafter provided, no such change, discharge, or appointment shall be deemed to have taken effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Solicitors - Court: Superior 1. Every solicitor whose name shall be indorsed on any summons or other originating document shall, on demand in writing made by or on behalf of any defendant who has been served with the same or with notice thereof, or has appeared thereto, declare forthwith in writing whether such summons or other originating document has been issued by him or with his authority or privity; and if such solicitor shall declare that the summons or other originating document was not issued by him or with his authority or privity all proceedings upon the same shall be stayed, and no further proceedings shall be taken thereon without leave of the Court. 2. (1) A party suing or defending by a solicitor shall, save in any matrimonial cause or matter, be at liberty to change his solicitor or to discharge his solicitor and sue or defend in person, and any party suing or defending in person shall be at liberty to appoint a solicitor, in any cause or matter, without an order for that purpose, upon notice of such change, discharge, or appointment being filed in the Central Office, but until such notice is so filed and a copy thereof served as hereinafter provided, no such change, discharge, or appointment shall be deemed to have taken effect. (2) The party giving such notice shall serve a copy thereof upon every other party to the proceedings (not being a party in default as to entry of appearance). (2A)[[1]](#_ftn1) Where such notice is given at any time in which an appeal is pending in the Court of Appeal or the Supreme Court, the party concerned shall additionally lodge a copy of the notice in the Office of the Registrar of the Court of Appeal or, as the case may be, the Office of the Registrar of the Supreme Court. (3) Every such notice shall state a registered place of business or address for service as prescribed by [Order 4](full-court-rule?id abaea3e0-921b-4d8d-b19c-1be17598937b).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'What must happen after the court makes an order declaring that a solicitor has ceased to act for a party?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The party or solicitor who applied for the order must give a notice to the same effect as the order.","The solicitor who is no longer acting must immediately pay any outstanding legal fees to the court.","The court must issue a new writ requiring the solicitor to continue representation.","The party or solicitor who applied for the order must file an affidavit confirming the solicitor''s ongoing representation."],"justification":"Where such order shall have been made the party or the solicitor who applied therefor shall forthwith give a notice to the same effect as the order, and the provisions of rule 2 as to filing and service shall apply thereto with the necessary modifications and subject to any direction in such order as to service on the first-mentioned party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The party giving any such notice may perform the duties prescribed by this rule either in person or (except where he intends to act in person) through his new solicitor. 3. (1) Where a solicitor who has acted for a party in any proceedings has died or become bankrupt or cannot be found or has failed to take out a practising certificate or has been struck off the roll of solicitors or has ceased to act for the party, and the party has not given notice of change of solicitor or notice of intention to act in person in accordance with the provisions of rule 2, any other party to the proceedings or (where the solicitor has ceased to act) the solicitor may, on notice to be served on the first-mentioned party, personally, or by letter addressed to his last-known place of residence, unless the Court otherwise directs, apply to the Court for an order declaring that the solicitor has ceased to be the solicitor acting for the first-mentioned party in the proceedings, and the Court may make an order accordingly. (2) Where such order shall have been made the party or the solicitor who applied therefor shall forthwith give a notice to the same effect as the order, and the provisions of rule 2 as to filing and service shall apply thereto with the necessary modifications and subject to any direction in such order as to service on the first-mentioned party. (3) Where the party or solicitor who applied for such order shall have complied with the said provisions then, if the first-mentioned party does not appoint another solicitor or give such an address for service as is required of a party acting in person, and comply with the provisions of rule 2, any documents in respect of which personal service is not requisite may be served on the said party by being filed with the proper officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'Can an order under rule 3 be made on an parte application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes, but only if the applicant provides written notice to the opposing party at least 14 days in advance.","Yes, unless the Court directs otherwise.","No, orders under rule 3 can only be made after a full hearing with both parties present.","No, unless the case involves issues of national security or public safety."],"justification":"An order under the provisions of rule 3 may be made on an parte application unless the Court shall otherwise direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) Where the said order is made on the application of a solicitor, such solicitor shall, subject to the provisions of rules 2 and 3 be considered the solicitor of the party to the final conclusion of the proceedings unless and until he has complied with the provisions of paragraph (2) of this rule. 4. An order under the provisions of rule 3 may be made on an parte application unless the Court shall otherwise direct. 5. Any order made under the provisions of rule 3 shall not affect the rights of the solicitor and the party as between themselves. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 7 rule 2A inserted by 485 of 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/485/made/en/print), effective 28 October 2014, subject to the provisions of paragraph 2 of 485 of 2014.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the summons be issued and served upon the applicant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least seven days prior to the court sitting","At least three days prior to the court sitting","At least one day prior to the court sitting","At least fourteen days prior to the court sitting"],"justification":"at least seven days prior to the sitting of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection—* 2. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 70.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d001a1a1-4aca-48ea-a1f5-647dd3990559/Summons (objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence) - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act 1860 No. 70.1.docx/docx/1) upon the applicant for such licence at least seven days prior to the sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the court sitting must the original summons and statutory declaration be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least two days","No specific time requirement","At least four days","Exactly three days"],"justification":"When the summons has been served the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of the said sitting of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *caveat to Collector of Customs & Excise* (2) Upon issuing the summons for service the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a notice by way of caveat in the [Form 70.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e09bd10-6ae5-46d1-af8d-f70596b18719/Notice by way of caveat to collector of custom and excise - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.2.docx/docx/1). (3) When the summons has been served the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of the said sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court''s order take when it hears an objection?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The order should be in Form 50.2 or 50.3, as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 65.1 or 65.2, as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 80.1 or 80.2, as appropriate.","The order should be in Form 70.3 or 70.4, as appropriate."],"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 70.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/84cca641-8697-47f4-91c7-2e122ef3ce6e/Order affirming objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.3.docx/docx/1) or [70.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d08e01e8-276e-43e1-bd05-7d94b151adb0/Order disallowing objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* 3. (1) The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 70.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/84cca641-8697-47f4-91c7-2e122ef3ce6e/Order affirming objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.3.docx/docx/1) or [70.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d08e01e8-276e-43e1-bd05-7d94b151adb0/Order disallowing objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act, 1860 No. 70.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate. A certified copy of such order shall be sent by the Clerk to the Collector of Customs and Excise. (2) Where a notice of appeal against such an order is lodged with the Clerk he or she shall forthwith send notice to that effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 71?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","Supreme","County","High"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 71 - Special exemption orders - Court: District # Order 71: Special exemption orders**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a special exemption order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Through an online portal specific to the Supreme Court, regardless of the location of the premises.","At any local government office within the same state as the premises for which the order is sought.","At the nearest police station to the premises for which the order is sought.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) Save as is hereinafter provided, an application for a special exemption order pursuant to section 5 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 11 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) and as amended by section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/17/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Order take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be in accordance with Form 82.3, Schedule A.","It should be in accordance with Form 71.1, Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 59, Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 71.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 71.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 71.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b3aa71ae-b309-4ac4-83a0-cace9fe92db7/Special exemption order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927, section 5 as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008, section 10 No. 71.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 71 - Special exemption orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can a Judge grant an exemption order at any sitting?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["When the case involves a minor traffic violation where the fine is less than 50.","Where the applicant has previously been denied an exemption order three times.","Where special circumstances so require, a Judge may hear an application and grant an exemption order.","If the application is submitted more than one week after the initial court date."],"justification":"A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such exemption order at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *In certain circumstances may be granted at any sitting.* (4) A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such exemption order at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district. [1] Order 71 originally substituted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), re-substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), effective 25 May 2009'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 72 - General Exemption Orders?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["County","District","High","Supreme"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 72 - General Exemption Orders - Court: District # Order 72: General Exemption Orders**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where specifically should the application for a general exemption order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At the nearest municipal courthouse","Through the online portal on the Department of Licensing''s website","At the Annual Licensing Court.","At the Local Community Council"],"justification":"The application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application for a general exemption order pursuant to section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), as amended by section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html), section 15 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) and section 5 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2008/act/17/enacted/en/html), may be made at a sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. The application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice for an application for a general exemption order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The court clerk","The local mayor","The judge presiding over the case","The applicant or solicitor for the applicant"],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Form of notice (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 72.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b4575765-00ec-484f-9686-b7167b6977d8/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a public market or fair - Intoxicating Liquor Acts No. 72.1.docx/docx/1) or [72.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/58a0fce5-0cdb-4dd2-ad8f-40026f0e8d7d/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a place at which a considerable number of persons are following a lawful trade or calling No. 72.2.docx/docx/1) [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the default duration of an order under this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Indefinitely, until revoked by the Licensing Authority","Until the next Quarterly Licensing Review","For a period of six months from the date of issuance","Until the next Annual Licensing Court for the relevant court area."],"justification":"remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *In force to Annual Licensing Court* \*(6) Every such order shall, unless withdrawn in pursuance of subsection (6) of section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), or expressed to expire sooner, remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What acts support the prohibition of general exemption orders on certain days?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Licensing Act 1890 and the Licensing Act 1949","The Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960 and the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927.","The Alcohol Control Act 1970 and the Beverage Services Act 1930","The Public House Regulation Act 1950 and the Tavern Management Act 1935"],"justification":"\\*[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) [Sec. 10]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (Sec. 4(7) as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008 [Sec. 5] and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) [Sec."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited premises and days* †2.[2] A general exemption order shall not be granted in respect of premises unless a general exemption order was in force in respect of the premises on 30 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) [Sec. 10]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (Sec. 4(7) as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008 [Sec. 5] and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) [Sec. [1] Order 72 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), effective 25 May 2009 [2] Order 72 rule 2 re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 73?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme","District","High","Magistrate"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 73 - Exemptions for special events - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an exemption order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.","At the nearest police station to the premises where the exemption is sought.","Through an online application portal on the national court website.","At any local government office within the same county as the premises."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in the county borough of Dublin for an exemption order in respect of a special event pursuant to section 10 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must notice of the application be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least seven days","at least three days","at least five days","at least fourteen days"],"justification":"at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'In which type of publication should the notice be published?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["in a specialized academic journal","in an international magazine","on a national television news channel","in a newspaper circulating in the locality"],"justification":"in a newspaper circulating in the locality"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must these documents be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No specific time frame, as long as it''s before the hearing.","At least four days.","At least two days.","Exactly three days."],"justification":"at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Order take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 72, Schedule","Form 74, Schedule A","Form 73.2, Schedule","Form 73.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f853200-09a8-468c-b759-f0ce1443579d/Exemption order for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 10 No. 73.1.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4f853200-09a8-468c-b759-f0ce1443579d/Exemption order for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 10 No. 73.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'When should notice of the application be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Before the date of hearing of the application","After the hearing of the application has concluded","On the same day as the hearing of the application","Within one week after the hearing of the application"],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of Notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be lodged with the Clerk before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in when hearing an application under Order 73?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 73.1, Schedule","Form 73.2, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule A","Form 58.6, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) The order of the Court hearing such application shall be in accordance with [Form 73.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cce42bdc-661a-4032-b000-1eb6b0c895f6/Order revoking exemption for special event - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962 No. 73.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Who is required to give notice of the making of an order to the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk","The Jury","The Attorney","The Judge"],"justification":"Notice of the making of such order shall be given by the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Notice to Garda Síochána* (4) Notice of the making of such order shall be given by the Clerk to the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the revoked application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate given by the Clerk follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 73.3, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule A","Form 73.2, Schedule","Form 74.3, Schedule"],"justification":"[Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of applications to which rules 1 and 2 of this Order relate shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an exemption order be made if the premises are not in a county or other borough?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.","At the High Court in London, irrespective of the location of the premises.","At the local magistrate''s court regardless of the specific location of the premises.","At any sitting of the County Court in the nearest county to where the premises are situate."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order in respect of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day between the hours of twelve o''clock and half-past twelve in the afternoon, pursuant to section 16 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The original notice of application, a certificate of service, and a copy of the affidavit","An affidavit of service, a copy of the application, and a letter of intent","A copy of the summons, a confirmation of receipt of the application, and a copy of the legal advertisement","A copy of the notice of application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the newspaper."],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (5) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Order take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 74.1, Schedule","Form 75, Schedule","Form 74.1, Schedule","Form 74.2, Schedule A"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4eeab324-ae33-4e1d-b0f8-9c5018e0f6c9/Exemption order for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s Day - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 No. 74.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What can be done if an application under rule 1(1) or 1(2) of this Order has been granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The decision can be appealed in a higher court within one month.","A new application can be submitted under rule 1(3) of the Order.","The original application can be amended to change its terms.","A subsequent application can be made to revoke the same."],"justification":"a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation* 2. (1) Where an application referred to in rule 1 (1) or 1 (2) of this Order has been granted, a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must notice be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At least fifteen days","At least five days","At least three days","At least ten days"],"justification":"at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum number of days before the hearing that the applicant must publish a notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["five days","seven days","ten days","three days"],"justification":"at least seven days before such hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper Notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the notice of application, a certificate of mailing as to service thereof, and a copy of the court calendar.","A copy of the notice of application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the applicant''s resume.","A copy of the notice of application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the newspaper.","A copy of the notice of application, a sworn affidavit as to service thereof, and a copy of the legal brief."],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Order take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 74.3, Schedule","Form 74.2, Schedule","Form 74.2, Schedule A","Form 75.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 74.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aff577ec-10d6-4395-915b-54bca6e604d2/Order revoking exemption for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 74.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act is the certificate required to be given by the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Food Safety Standards Act, 2011","Occupational Health and Safety Act, 1989","Environmental Protection Act, 1974","Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962"],"justification":"The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List%20of%20all%20the%20holders%20-%20Intoxicating%20Liquor%20Act%201962%20section%2025%20as%20substituted%20in%20First%20Schedule%20of%20the%20Courts%20(No.%202)%20Act%201986%20No.%2073.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 75?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["High","District","Magistrate","Supreme"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Where should an application for an existing exemption order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Before the Supreme Court.","At the local municipal court.","Through the Department of Motor Vehicles.","At the Annual Licensing Court."],"justification":"the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence (not being a licence granted by virtue of paragraph (2) of section 2 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1902](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1902/act/18/enacted/en/print.html)) in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order to open or keep open the premises for the purpose of carrying on any business other than the sale or supply of intoxicating liquor during any one period and not exceeding forty-five minutes in duration on the mornings of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day, pursuant to section 17 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The application form, a certificate of residence, and a summary of the case","A letter of intent, a proof of identity, and a copy of the court calendar","A copy of the notice of application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the newspaper.","A copy of the summons, a receipt for postage, and a list of witnesses"],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (5) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order take if an application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 75.1, Schedule","Form 75.2, Schedule","Form 75.1, Schedule A","Form 76, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (6) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2eb82a05-a935-4d0f-8971-227985d82fbd/Order permitting the opening and keeping open of premises for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What can be done after an application under rule 1(1) or 1(2) is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A subsequent application can be made to revoke or amend the granted application.","The granted application can be converted into a patent without any further process.","The granted application can be appealed to a higher court.","A new application can be filed under rule 1(1) or 1(2) immediately."],"justification":"a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked or amended"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation or amendment* 2. (1) Where an application referred to in rule 1 (1) or 1 (2) of this Order has been granted, a subsequent application may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein such application was granted to have the same revoked or amended.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum time frame for publishing a notice of the intended application in a newspaper?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least seven days before the hearing","At least three days before the hearing","Within five days after the hearing","At least fourteen days after the hearing"],"justification":"at least seven days before such hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the affidavit, a proof of service, and a certificate of mailing","The original notice of application, a sworn statement of non-service, and a confirmation email from the clerk","A copy of the notice of application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the newspaper.","The applicant''s personal identification documents, a receipt of payment for filing fees, and a copy of the court docket"],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (4) A copy of the notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Order take if an application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 80, Schedule A","Form 75.2, Schedule","Form 75.1, Schedule","Form 76, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in accordance with [Form 75.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb242f64-64bc-4749-9446-79f888d75e0d/Order revoking an order permitting premises to open or keep open for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s Day No. 75.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate given by the Clerk follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 74.3, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule","Form 73.2, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule A"],"justification":"in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'What court is responsible for Order 76 - Occasional licences?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High Court","County Court","Supreme Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 76 - Occasional licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an occasional licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through an online portal on the government''s official website for licensing matters.","At any local police station in the vicinity of the place to which the application relates.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.","By submitting a written request to the relevant municipal council office."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) Save as is hereinafter provided, an application for an occasional licence, pursuant to section 11 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) (as amended) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 67 - General dealers', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for a general dealer''s licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 67.1, Schedule","A criminal background check conducted within the last year","The payment of a non-refundable application fee of 500","The submission of a character reference letter from a previous employer"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34bc3ede-f823-4446-b466-3366f4277bc6/Notice of application for a general dealer''s licence - General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 section 1 No. 67.1.docx/docx/1))"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 67.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34bc3ede-f823-4446-b466-3366f4277bc6/Notice of application for a general dealer''s licence - General Dealers (Ireland) Act, 1903 section 1 No. 67.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What forms must be used for issuing a notice preceding an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Letters A to Section 6","Notices of Intent 78.1 to 78.5, Schedule","Forms 101 to 105, Schedule","Forms 68.1 to 68.5A, Schedule"],"justification":"Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 68.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ba678d47-364c-423d-a6d3-635a539b9ebc/Notice Of Application For A Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence. No. 68.1.docx/docx/1) to [68.5A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b655656f-3ba7-458f-adb7-2c4b25b2f01e/Notice of application for a certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (Breweries and Distilleries) Act 2018, section 1 No. 68.5A.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Forms of notice* (2) Every such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in one of the [Forms 68.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ba678d47-364c-423d-a6d3-635a539b9ebc/Notice Of Application For A Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence. No. 68.1.docx/docx/1) to [68.5A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b655656f-3ba7-458f-adb7-2c4b25b2f01e/Notice of application for a certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (Breweries and Distilleries) Act 2018, section 1 No. 68.5A.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be lodged with the Clerk after service of the notice of application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The original notice, statutory declaration of service, copy of the newspaper (if required), and a plan of the premises.","The original notice, a notarized letter of service, and a copy of the recipient''s driver''s license.","The original notice, a signed affidavit from the recipient acknowledging receipt, and a copy of the applicant''s passport.","The original notice, a receipt from the post office confirming delivery, and a copy of the applicant''s"],"justification":"the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, newspaper, etc.* (6) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, a copy of the newspaper (where required) and a plan of the premises shall be lodged with the Clerk at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 68 - Licensing Acts 1833 to 2018', 'Court Rules', 'What forms should the certificate or declaration follow if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["One of Forms 68.12 to 68.18, as per Schedule","One of Forms 58.6 to 58.11, as per Schedule","One of Forms 68.6 to 68.11, as per Schedule","One of Forms 78.6 to 78.11, as per Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted, the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 68.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eff3a56c-ed83-45fb-9512-6f52327059d3/Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence No. 68.6.docx/docx/1) to [68.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/edd299f3-eebd-4444-a908-7e4b9817732e/Certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (breweries and Distilleries) Act 2019, section 1 No. 68.11.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (7) Where the application is granted, the certificate or declaration shall be in accordance with one of the [Forms 68.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eff3a56c-ed83-45fb-9512-6f52327059d3/Certificate For A New Spirit Retailer''s Off-Licence No. 68.6.docx/docx/1) to [68.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/edd299f3-eebd-4444-a908-7e4b9817732e/Certificate for a producer''s retail off-licence - Intoxicating Liquor (breweries and Distilleries) Act 2019, section 1 No. 68.11.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be. [[1]](https://irishcourts-my.sharepoint.com/personal/brendanhoulihan_courts_ie/Documents/Desktop/Family Law updates 2025/Consolidated Rules/Consolidated District Court Rules 24.12.3.doc#_ftnref1) Order 68 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 69 pertain to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises","Military discharge procedures","Environmental protection regulations","Vehicle registration forms"],"justification":"# Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served on the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Exactly seven days","No specific time frame is required","At least five days","At least ten days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana for the licensing area at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochana for the licensing area at least ten days before the date of hearing of the application and, where the application is for a declaration as to suitability of licensed premises for a restaurant certificate or limited restaurant certificate, the applicant shall also cause a copy of the plan of the premises to be deposited with the said officer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 69 - Restaurant certificates and declarations as to suitability of premises', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk when the notice of application has been served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The original notice and a detailed financial statement of the applicant.","The original notice and a copy of the applicant''s identification document.","The original notice and a map or plan of the premises.","The original notice and a signed affidavit from two witnesses."],"justification":"the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice and map* (4) When service of the notice of application has been effected, the original of such notice, together with a map or plan of the premises, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What conditions must be met for a defendant to issue a third party notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The defendant must have previously won a case against the plaintiff in a related matter.","The defendant must be financially unable to cover their own legal costs and require financial support from a third party.","The defendant must prove that the third party has a direct familial relationship with the plaintiff.","The defendant must claim entitlement to contribution or indemnity, entitlement to relief or remedy related to the original subject matter of the action, or that a question or issue is substantially the same as one arising between the plaintiff and the defendant."],"justification":"Where in any action a defendant claims as against any person not already a party to the action (in this Order called ‘‘**the third party**’’) (*a*) that he is entitled to contribution or indemnity; that he is entitled to any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the action and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the plaintiff; that any question or issue relating to or connected with the said subject matter is substantially the same as some question or issue arising between the plaintiff and the defendant and should properly be determined not only as between the plaintiff and the defendant but as between the plaintiff and the defendant and the third party or between any or either of them, the Court may give leave to the defendant to issue and serve a third party notice"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Actions by and against Firms and Persons Carrying on Business in names other than their own** 1. Where in any action a defendant claims as against any person not already a party to the action (in this Order called ‘‘**the third party**’’) (*a*) that he is entitled to contribution or indemnity; that he is entitled to any relief or remedy relating to or connected with the original subject matter of the action and substantially the same as some relief or remedy claimed by the plaintiff; that any question or issue relating to or connected with the said subject matter is substantially the same as some question or issue arising between the plaintiff and the defendant and should properly be determined not only as between the plaintiff and the defendant but as between the plaintiff and the defendant and the third party or between any or either of them, the Court may give leave to the defendant to issue and serve a third party notice and may, at the same time, if it shall appear desirable to do so, give the third party liberty to appear at the trial and take such part therein as may be just, and generally give such directions as to the Court shall appear proper for having any question or the rights or liabilities of the parties most conveniently determined and enforced and as to the mode and extent in or to which the third party shall be bound or made liable by the decision or judgment in the action. 2. The application for such leave shall be made by motion on notice to the plaintiff in accordance with [Form 6C](http://icsmweb09/content/application-leave-issue-and-serve-third-party-notice) as set out in the Schedule of Forms attached hereto. Unless the plaintiff wishes to add the third party as a defendant, his attendance at the hearing of the motion shall not be necessary. If the plaintiff does attend he shall not be entitled to costs in respect of the motion except by special direction of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'When should an application for leave to issue a third party notice be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Concurrently with the service of the Appearance, but only if the third party has been previously notified.","After the conclusion of the trial and before the verdict is delivered.","Before the service of an Appearance and immediately after the filing of the lawsuit.","After the service of an Appearance and at any time prior to the trial of the action."],"justification":"Application for leave to issue the third party notice shall, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, be made after the service of an Appearance and at any time prior to the trial of the action."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Application for leave to issue the third party notice shall, unless otherwise ordered by the Court, be made after the service of an Appearance and at any time prior to the trial of the action. 4. The third party notice shall state the nature and grounds of the claim or the nature of the question or issue sought to be determined and all information required to be set out in the indorsement of a Civil Bill as provided for in these rules and any directions of the Court given under Rule 1 hereof. The third party notice shall be issued and served in the same manner as in the case of a Civil Bill and shall be served within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. A copy of the Civil Bill and defence together with a copy of the Order joining the third party shall be served with the third party notice which said third party notice shall also be served upon the Plaintiff(s). Where the third party is joined as a defendant, an amended Civil Bill together with a copy of the Order joining the third party as a defendant shall be served upon all defendants by the plaintiff within twenty-one days of the making of the Order unless otherwise directed by the Court. Any amended defence of an original defendant to the proceedings shall be served upon the plaintiff within ten days from the date of service of the amended Civil Bill. 4A.[1] A digital user (within the meaning of [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt)) may file and/or serve a third party notice by digital delivery, where same is for the time being authorised in accordance with [Order 11A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url requirements-as-to-form-and-delivery-of-pleadings-documents-and-notices-used-in-civil-proceedings-in-the-courtt) and, in the case of service, where the third party or third party’s solicitor is or becomes a digital user.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 7 - Third Party Procedure', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the third party after they receive the third party notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The third party becomes a party to the action with the same rights as if they were sued by the defendant and is entitled to be served with all pleadings.","The third party becomes a witness in the case and is not involved further in the legal proceedings.","The third party is required to respond within 10 days or automatically loses the case.","The third party is obligated to pay a fine for receiving the notice."],"justification":"The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant and shall be entitled to be served with all pleadings in the proceedings by the party filing and/or delivering same."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '5. The third party shall, as from the time of service upon him of the third party notice, be a party to the action with the same rights in respect of defence against any claim made against him and otherwise as if he had been duly sued in the ordinary way by the defendant and shall be entitled to be served with all pleadings in the proceedings by the party filing and/or delivering same. 6. The third party notice shall call upon a third party to enter an appearance within a stated time after service (which shall not be less than ten days or other time limited for appearance by agreement of the parties or any order of the Court) to answer the claim of the defendant, and shall warn him of the consequences of failure to do so provided that the expiry of such time shall not entitle the Office to refuse to permit an appearance to be entered. 7. Where a third party enters an appearance, he shall deliver his defence within ten days from the date thereof or within such further period as may be allowed by the Court or consented to by the defendant(s) in the proceedings. 8. After the third party enters an appearance, and before the expiration of the time limited for the delivery of defence, he may, after serving notice of the intended application upon the plaintiff and all defendants, apply to the Court to vary any directions given by the Court under Rule 1 of this Order. 9. The Court may decide all questions of costs as between a third party and the other parties to the action, and may order any one or more to pay the costs of any other or others or give such directions as to costs as the justice of the case may require. [1] Order 7 rule 4A inserted by 217 of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/217/made/en/print), effective 18 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What must a person do before being named as a next friend or guardian litem in proceedings involving a minor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["provide a notarized statement of consent on Form 6.3, Schedule A","file a signed affidavit on Form 9.0, Schedule","sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule","submit a written declaration on Form 8.2, Schedule"],"justification":"such person shall sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule for that purpose"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Minors - next friend/guardian litem* 2. A minor may sue by his or her next friend, and may defend any proceeding by his or her guardian litem. In any such case, before the name of any person shall be used in proceedings as next friend or guardian litem of the minor, such person shall sign an authorisation in the Form 7.1, Schedule for that purpose, which shall be lodged with the Clerk together with the civil summons or other originating document or, as the case may be, with a notice of intention to defend.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'Which rules apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor involving a settlement, compromise, payment, or acceptance of money paid into court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The provisions of Order 41, rule 2(4) of these Rules.","The provisions of Order 41, rule 2(2) of these Rules.","The provisions of Order 37, rule 5(6) of these Rules.","The provisions of Order 40, rule 3(3) of these Rules."],"justification":"The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 2 (4) of these Rules shall apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor, where a settlement, compromise, payment or acceptance of money paid into court therein is proposed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court approval required for acceptance of lodgments, etc.* 4.(1) Where a sum of money has been lodged in court by the defendant in an action for a wrong in which the plaintiff is a minor, an application made to the judge pursuant to section 63(1) of the Civil Liability Act, 1961 (No. 41 of 1961) by the plaintiff to decide whether that sum of money should be accepted or the action should go to trial may, upon notice to the defendant and the Clerk in the Form 7.3, Schedule be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the action is listed for hearing. (2) The provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), rule 2 (4) of these Rules shall apply to proceedings brought by or on behalf of a minor, where a settlement, compromise, payment or acceptance of money paid into court therein is proposed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What form is required for applying for an interim payment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 6.5, Schedule","Form 7.3, Schedule","Form 8.2, Schedule A","Form 7.4, Schedule"],"justification":"Form 7.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim payments* (2) Unless the Court shall otherwise decide, no interim payment out of any money so secured or invested shall be made save in pursuance of an order of the Court made upon the application of the minor''s next friend or guardian litem. Such application may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the proceedings were heard and determined, upon lodging with the Clerk a notice in the Form 7.4, Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What document must be produced and proved on behalf of a minor at the hearing of proceedings involving the minor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth","A certified letter from the minor''s school confirming their enrollment status","A certified extract from the Register of Deaths showing the date of the minor''s death","A passport or any other government-issued card of the minor"],"justification":"A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth shall, if required, be produced and proved on behalf of the minor at the hearing of proceedings involving such minor, on an application to have a proposed settlement approved by the Court or on any other application relating to a minor or a person who has lately been a minor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proof of age* 7. A certified extract from the Register of Births showing the date of the minor''s birth shall, if required, be produced and proved on behalf of the minor at the hearing of proceedings involving such minor, on an application to have a proposed settlement approved by the Court or on any other application relating to a minor or a person who has lately been a minor. The said date of birth shall be noted in any order of the Court made in any such proceeding or application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when a decision-making representation order authorises a representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the representative is considered good and sufficient service.","The representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, but service of such proceedings on the representative is not considered good and sufficient service without additional written consent from the client.","The representative can only advise the client on the proceedings but cannot institute, prosecute or defend them.","Service of proceedings on the representative is considered invalid unless specifically authorized by a court order separate from the decision-making representation order."],"justification":"Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Relevant person to whom the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015 applies* 8[4].(1) In this rule, the “2015 Act” means the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015, and expressions used have the meanings assigned to them by the 2015 Act. (2) Where a decision-making representation order in respect of a relevant person authorises a decision-making representative to institute, prosecute or defend proceedings, the decision-making representative may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the decision-making representative shall be good and sufficient service. (3) Where notification of lack of capacity has been accepted in respect of a registered enduring power of attorney made by a relevant person as the donor, which power includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney shall be good and sufficient service. (4) Where a registered enduring power under the Act of 1996, made by a relevant person as the donor, includes authority to act on the donor’s behalf in relation to the institution, prosecution or defence of proceedings, the attorney under the Act of 1996 may institute, prosecute or defend such proceedings, and service of such proceedings on the attorney under the Act of 1996 shall be good and sufficient service. (5) Where a registered co-decision-making agreement in force in respect of an intending party or party to proceedings as the appointer provides for the making jointly by the appointer and a co-decision-maker of decisions concerning proceedings, the originating document or defence, and each subsequent document delivered on behalf of that party in such proceedings shall state that the decision to issue and deliver same was made jointly by the appointer and co-decision-maker.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'When can the Court make orders regarding the capacity of an adult party in proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Court may make such orders only during criminal proceedings and not in civil or family law matters.","The Court may make such orders only if requested by a government official or legal representative, not on application by any other person.","The Court may make such orders when there is an issue about the capacity of an adult party, after hearing the parties or on application by a party or person interested.","The Court may make such orders solely when there is no issue about the capacity of an adult party and without the need to hear from the parties involved."],"justification":"Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(6) Where any issue arises as to, or arising from, the capacity of any adult party to proceedings, the Court may, of its own motion having heard the parties, or on the application by motion on notice of any party, or person sufficiently interested, make such orders or give such directions concerning the further conduct of the proceedings as are necessary in the interests of justice. (7) A ward of court may sue or defend by his or her committee.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 7 - Minors And Other Persons Under Disability', 'Court Rules', 'How is service of documents on a minor generally carried out?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["In accordance with the provisions of Order 41, including rule 10.","In accordance with the provisions of Order 50, including rule 12.","In accordance with the provisions of Order 37, including rule 6.","In accordance with the provisions of Order 41, including rule 8."],"justification":"Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents upon a minor shall be effected in accordance with the provisions (including rule 8) of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of documents* 9.[5] Save where the Court otherwise orders, service of documents upon a minor shall be effected in accordance with the provisions (including rule 8) of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules, and upon a relevant person to whom rule 8 applies in accordance with the provisions (including rule 9) of that Order. [1] Order 7 rule 5(1) substituted by [S.I. 258 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/258/made/en/print?q 258&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005 [2] Order 7 rule 6A inserted by [S.I. 526 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/526/made/en/print?q 526&years 2004), effective 8 September 2004 [3] Order 7 rule 6A(4) substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.[4] [4] Order 7 rule 8 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024. [5] Order 7 rule 9 substituted by 326 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/326/made/en/print#:~:text No.-,326/2024 - District Court (Assisted Decision-Making (,Capacity) Act 2015) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 8 July 2024.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 7 - Solicitors', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a solicitor declares that a summons or originating document was not issued by them?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["All proceedings upon the same shall be stayed, and no further proceedings shall be taken thereon without leave of the Court.","All proceedings upon the same shall be immediately dismissed without any possibility of revival.","The solicitor shall be fined and required to issue a new document.","The proceedings shall continue as if the declaration had not been made."],"justification":"if such solicitor shall declare that the summons or other originating document was not issued by him or with his authority or privity all proceedings upon the same shall be stayed, and no further proceedings shall be taken thereon without leave of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 7 - Solicitors - Court: Superior 1. Every solicitor whose name shall be indorsed on any summons or other originating document shall, on demand in writing made by or on behalf of any defendant who has been served with the same or with notice thereof, or has appeared thereto, declare forthwith in writing whether such summons or other originating document has been issued by him or with his authority or privity; and if such solicitor shall declare that the summons or other originating document was not issued by him or with his authority or privity all proceedings upon the same shall be stayed, and no further proceedings shall be taken thereon without leave of the Court. 2. (1) A party suing or defending by a solicitor shall, save in any matrimonial cause or matter, be at liberty to change his solicitor or to discharge his solicitor and sue or defend in person, and any party suing or defending in person shall be at liberty to appoint a solicitor, in any cause or matter, without an order for that purpose, upon notice of such change, discharge, or appointment being filed in the Central Office, but until such notice is so filed and a copy thereof served as hereinafter provided, no such change, discharge, or appointment shall be deemed to have taken effect. (2) The party giving such notice shall serve a copy thereof upon every other party to the proceedings (not being a party in default as to entry of appearance). (2A)[[1]](#_ftn1) Where such notice is given at any time in which an appeal is pending in the Court of Appeal or the Supreme Court, the party concerned shall additionally lodge a copy of the notice in the Office of the Registrar of the Court of Appeal or, as the case may be, the Office of the Registrar of the Supreme Court. (3) Every such notice shall state a registered place of business or address for service as prescribed by [Order 4](full-court-rule?id abaea3e0-921b-4d8d-b19c-1be17598937b).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 70 - Objections to the first grant of wine retailers'' on-licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form of notice must precede an objection to a wine retailer''s on-licence application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A letter of intent in Form 85.3, Schedule","An official complaint in Form 62.4, Schedule","A summons in Form 70.1, Schedule","A notice of appeal in Form 71.2, Schedule A"],"justification":"Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 70.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection—* 2. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 70.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d001a1a1-4aca-48ea-a1f5-647dd3990559/Summons (objection to the grant of a wine retailer''s on-licence) - Refreshment Houses (Ireland) Act 1860 No. 70.1.docx/docx/1) upon the applicant for such licence at least seven days prior to the sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for a general exemption order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form","The filing of a formal complaint with the relevant court","Payment of a specific fee to the regulatory body","An approval from the local administrative authority"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Form of notice (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 72.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b4575765-00ec-484f-9686-b7167b6977d8/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a public market or fair - Intoxicating Liquor Acts No. 72.1.docx/docx/1) or [72.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/58a0fce5-0cdb-4dd2-ad8f-40026f0e8d7d/Notice of application for a general exemption order in respect of premises situate in the vicinity of a place at which a considerable number of persons are following a lawful trade or calling No. 72.2.docx/docx/1) [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), as the case may be) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can an order be withdrawn before the next Annual Licensing Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["If it is withdrawn by a customer who no longer wishes to purchase the license.","If it is withdrawn in accordance with subsection (6) of section 4 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927.","If it is withdrawn after the next Annual Licensing Court has taken place.","If it is withdrawn during the Annual Licensing Court session."],"justification":"unless withdrawn in pursuance of subsection (6) of section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *In force to Annual Licensing Court* \*(6) Every such order shall, unless withdrawn in pursuance of subsection (6) of section 4 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html), or expressed to expire sooner, remain in force until the next Annual Licensing Court for the court area in which the premises are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 72 - General Exemption Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When is a general exemption order not granted in respect of premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Unless a general exemption order was in force on 30 May 2009, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day.","Unless a general exemption order was in force on 30 May 2008, or for any time on Monday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day.","Unless a general exemption order was in force on 31 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day.","Unless a general exemption order was in force on 30 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day."],"justification":"A general exemption order shall not be granted in respect of premises unless a general exemption order was in force in respect of the premises on 30 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited premises and days* †2.[2] A general exemption order shall not be granted in respect of premises unless a general exemption order was in force in respect of the premises on 30 May 2008, or for any time on any Sunday, Patrick’s Day or Christmas Day. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) [Sec. 10]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (Sec. 4(7) as amended by Intoxicating Liquor Act 2008 [Sec. 5] and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) [Sec. [1] Order 72 substituted by [S.I. 174 of 2009](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/174/made/en/print?q 174&years 2009), effective 25 May 2009 [2] Order 72 rule 2 re-substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'To whom must notice of the application be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates","the local mayor of the area to which the application relates","the chief justice of the nearest county court","the head of the nearest police station regardless of the application''s locality"],"justification":"the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the locality to which the application relates at least seven days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum time before the hearing that the applicant must publish a notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["at least five days","at least ten days","at least seven days","at least three days"],"justification":"at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (3) The applicant shall also cause a notice of the intended application to be published, at least seven days before such hearing, in a newspaper circulating in the locality.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 73 - Exemptions for special events', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Act is the certificate required to be given?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Environment Protection Act, 1986","Occupational Health and Safety Act, 2009","Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962","Food Safety Standards Act, 2011"],"justification":"section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of applications to which rules 1 and 2 of this Order relate shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Where should an application be made if there is already an existing exemption order for the premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At the Annual Licensing Court.","To the district magistrate''s office","Through an online portal on the premises'' website","At the local municipal office"],"justification":"the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order in respect of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day between the hours of twelve o''clock and half-past twelve in the afternoon, pursuant to section 16 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 74 - Exemptions for licensed business on Sunday afternoons and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate given by the Clerk follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 74.3, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule A","Form 73.2, Schedule","Form 73.3, Schedule"],"justification":"The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List%20of%20all%20the%20holders%20-%20Intoxicating%20Liquor%20Act%201962%20section%2025%20as%20substituted%20in%20First%20Schedule%20of%20the%20Courts%20(No.%202)%20Act%201986%20No.%2073.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Where should an application for an exemption order be made if it is for premises outside a county or borough?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Through an online form on the national government''s website.","To the local council office where the premises are located.","At the nearest police station to the premises.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises are located."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 1. (1) An application by the holder of a licence (not being a licence granted by virtue of paragraph (2) of section 2 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1902](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1902/act/18/enacted/en/print.html)) in respect of premises situate in any locality not in a county or other borough for an exemption order to open or keep open the premises for the purpose of carrying on any business other than the sale or supply of intoxicating liquor during any one period and not exceeding forty-five minutes in duration on the mornings of Sundays and Saint Patrick''s Day, pursuant to section 17 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the order is sought are situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of premises for which such an exemption order is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 75 - Exemptions for unlicensed business on Sunday mornings and Saint Patrick''s day', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act is the certificate required to be given by the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Alcohol Consumption Control Act, 1975","Poison Control Act, 1985","Tobacco Regulation Act, 2004","Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962"],"justification":"section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of certificate to be given by Clerk* 3. The certificate required to be given by the Clerk pursuant to section 25 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) as substituted in the Schedule of the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/26/enacted/en/html), for the purpose of an application under rule 1 of this Order shall be in accordance with [Form 73.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c1be3ac-9386-4c3b-b325-4f04128b6dc7/List of all the holders - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 section 25 as substituted in First Schedule of the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986) No. 73.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the licence take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 76.1, Schedule A","Form 75, Schedule","Form 76.2, Schedule","Form 76.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 76.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 76.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afadc1ab-9522-4564-8435-e48214152f9a/Occasional licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1962 No. 76.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'What is the earliest time an occasional licence can be granted, except for dinners or dances?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Nine o''clock in the morning","Eight o''clock in the morning","Ten o''clock in the morning","Seven o''clock in the morning"],"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time...before the hour of eight o''clock in the morning"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Hours* \*2. An occasional licence shall not be granted for any time after the hour of ten o''clock in the evening or before the hour of eight o''clock in the morning unless the event to which the licence relates is a dinner or dance.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'On which day is an occasional licence not granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Christmas Day","Easter Sunday","New Year''s Day","Halloween"],"justification":"An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prohibited days* †3.[1] An occasional licence shall not be granted in respect of Christmas Day.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 76 - Occasional licences', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can a judge grant an occasional licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["When the local government requests it for community events.","If the applicant promises to use the licence only once.","Where the applicant has previously been denied a standard licence.","Where special circumstances so require, a judge may grant an occasional licence."],"justification":"A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *In certain cases may be granted at any sitting* 4. A Judge may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application and grant such occasional licence at a sitting of the Court in any court area in his or her district. \*[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11 (10)]. †[Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) 11(5) as amended by [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2000 10)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/17/enacted/en/print) and [Intoxicating Liquor (Amendment) Act 2018](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/act/1/enacted/en/html) 4(a)) [1] Order 76 rule 3 and note substituted by [S.I. 566 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/566/made/en/print?q 566&years 2018), effective 9 January 2019'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What court is mentioned in Order 77?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme","High","District","Magistrate"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Who should receive notice of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises are located.","The property owner of the premises in which the application is being made.","The local mayor of the licensing area in which the premises are located.","The nearest police station''s desk sergeant in the licensing area in which the premises are located."],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 77.2, Schedule","Form 76.1, Schedule","Form 77.1, Schedule","Form 77.1, Schedule"],"justification":"The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26eb9350-0ca7-4721-9ac0-2038eb75af01/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence No. 77.1.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (3) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26eb9350-0ca7-4721-9ac0-2038eb75af01/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence No. 77.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'How long after the transfer can the person continue trading?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court next after the expiration of three months from the date of the transfer","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court next after the expiration of two weeks from the date of the transfer","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court next after the expiration of six months from the date of the transfer","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer"],"justification":"until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to trade until Annual Licensing Court* (5) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What does the Court have the power to do under the Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Transfer temporarily an on-licence or an off-licence upon the death of the holder to any person approved by the Court and not disqualified by law, nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or any person with an interest in the premises.","Suspend any on-licence or off-licence indefinitely if the holder is found guilty of a criminal offense unrelated to liquor sales.","Grant an on-licence or an off-licence to any person disbarred from holding such licences by law, provided they pay a specified fine.","Extend permanently an on-licence or an off-licence to any individual without the need for approval by the Court or nomination by an executor or administrator."],"justification":"The power conferred on the Court under the Licensing Acts to transfer temporarily an on-licence or an off-licence upon the death of the holder of the licence shall, pursuant to section 34 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), include power to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Extension of power to temporarily transfer licences* 2. (1) The power conferred on the Court under the Licensing Acts to transfer temporarily an on-licence or an off-licence upon the death of the holder of the licence shall, pursuant to section 34 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), include power to transfer the licence to any person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) nominated by the executor or administrator of the holder or, if there is no executor or administrator, by any person having an interest in the premises to which the licence relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Until when is the person authorized to carry on the business?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of three months from the date of the transfer.","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held immediately after the expiration of one week from the date of the transfer.","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of six months from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, thinks fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the third year after the sitting aforesaid.","Until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid."],"justification":"until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *To trade until Annual Licensing Court* (2) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the licence is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer or, if the Court should then or on any subsequent application to it, think fit so to order, until the sitting of such Annual Licensing Court in the year or in the second year (as the Court may think fit to order) after the sitting aforesaid.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Who can apply to the Court for transferring a licence to another person?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The holder of the current licence","The licensee''s legal representative","The nominee of the transferee","The nominator of the transferee"],"justification":"on the application by the nominator of the transferee to the Court at any sitting thereof for the court area within which the premises are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to transfer to another person* (3) Where the licence has been transferred, such licence may, on the application by the nominator of the transferee to the Court at any sitting thereof for the court area within which the premises are situate, be transferred by endorsement made by the Court on the licence or, if the licence is not available, on a copy thereof, to such other person (being a person approved of by the Court and not disqualified by law) as the nominator may nominate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice take when applying for an ad-interim transfer of a licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The notice should be submitted via email to the Licensing Department.","The notice should be a verbal declaration made over the phone to the Licensing Officer.","The notice should be in the appropriate form (Form 77.2 or 77.3, Schedule","The notice should be in the form of a handwritten letter addressed to the Licensing Board."],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 77.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce8c1245-89c9-42c4-802a-9e7c5db968d2/Notice of application for ad-interim transfer of a licence to person other than the owner - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960 No. 77.2.docx/docx/1) or [77.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b843971a-fcf7-4234-a38c-fdc2fee8c320/Notice of application for a certificate for the renewal of a licence in cases where the owner has ceased to carry on business - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 No. 77.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ([Form 77.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce8c1245-89c9-42c4-802a-9e7c5db968d2/Notice of application for ad-interim transfer of a licence to person other than the owner - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1960 No. 77.2.docx/docx/1) or [77.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b843971a-fcf7-4234-a38c-fdc2fee8c320/Notice of application for a certificate for the renewal of a licence in cases where the owner has ceased to carry on business - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 No. 77.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'When should a copy of the notice be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Within seven days after the date of hearing of the application.","Immediately after the conclusion of the hearing of the application.","At least twenty-four hours before the date of hearing of the application.","At least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application."],"justification":"lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 77.4, Schedule","Form 77.3, Schedule","Form 77.4, Schedule A","Form 80, Schedule"],"justification":"The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/175887a8-9569-407e-a76a-294dcd06aa0a/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence (to person other than the owner) No. 77.4.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (4) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/175887a8-9569-407e-a76a-294dcd06aa0a/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence (to person other than the owner) No. 77.4.docx/docx/1), and the provisions contained in the Licensing Acts regarding temporary transfer of licences as set out in rules 1 (4) and 1(5) of this order shall apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a renewal certificate take if the licence has expired and the application is made within one year?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["It should be in accordance with Form 77.5, Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 88.2, Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 77.4, Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 66.1, Schedule A."],"justification":"the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of renewal certificate* (5) Where the licence has expired and the application is made within one year after such expiry, the renewal certificate, if granted by the Court, shall be in accordance with [Form 77.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can the Court hear an application for a temporary transfer?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Court may hear an application for a temporary transfer only during business hours on weekdays.","Where special circumstances so require, the Court may hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer.","If the applicant provides a written promise to pay legal fees, the Court may hear an application for a temporary transfer.","Where the application is filed more than 7 days after the initial court date, the Court may hear an application for a temporary transfer."],"justification":"The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Special circumstances* 4.[1] The Court may, where special circumstances so require, hear an application under rule 1 (1), rule 2 (3) or rule 3 (1) and grant such temporary transfer at any sitting of the Court in the District. [1] Order 77 rule 4 inserted by [S.I. 123 of 1998](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/si/123/made/en/print?q 123&years 1998), effective 28 April 1998'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court mentioned in Order 78?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High","Supreme","Magistrates","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must a copy of the notice be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Immediately upon the filing of the application.","Within seven days prior to the date of hearing of the application.","At least twenty-four hours before the date of hearing of the application.","At least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application."],"justification":"lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 78.2, Schedule","Form 78.1, Schedule A","Form 65, Schedule","Form 78.1, Schedule"],"justification":"The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 78.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (3) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 78.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/892731dd-d4b4-42fd-a72e-da4fe0bba592/Form of endorsement of transfer of licence held by nominee No. 78.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 79 - Certificates of transfer?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Supreme Court","High Court","Magistrate","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 79 - Certificates of transfer - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'How many days in advance must the documents be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least three days.","No more than four days.","At least seven days.","Exactly five days."],"justification":"at least seven days before the date of such Annual Licensing Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice etc* (4) A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk for retention by him or her, at least seven days before the date of such Annual Licensing Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'What is the requirement for the applicant''s attendance at the Annual Licensing Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The applicant only needs to send a written notice of absence to qualify for not attending in person.","The applicant can attend via video conference without any additional requirements.","The applicant must attend in person unless the court finds a good reason for their absence.","The applicant must attend remotely through a live-streamed broadcast."],"justification":"The applicant shall attend in person (unless the Court is satisfied that there is good reason for his or her non-attendance)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applicant to attend in person* 2. The applicant shall attend in person (unless the Court is satisfied that there is good reason for his or her non-attendance) at the Annual Licensing Court and present himself or herself for examination as to his or her general character, possession of the premises, and any other questions which the Court may think fit to put to the said applicant. 3. The applicant shall produce in Court any document upon which he or she grounds the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'When will the appropriate certificate be given to the applicant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The appropriate certificate shall be given once the interview process is completed.","The appropriate certificate shall be given immediately upon application submission.","The appropriate certificate shall not be given until the document is produced.","The appropriate certificate shall be given after a background check has been conducted."],"justification":"The appropriate certificate shall not be given to such applicant until such document is produced."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Grant of certificate subject to production of documents* 4. Where the applicant has not at the time obtained or is for any other reason unable to produce any document upon which he or she relies, the Court may grant such application subject to the subsequent production of such document. The appropriate certificate shall not be given to such applicant until such document is produced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 79 - Certificates of transfer', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate take when the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 79.2, Schedule","Form 80, Schedule","Form 79.1, Schedule A","Form 79.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 79.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of Court* 5. Where the application is granted the certificate shall be in accordance with [Form 79.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f0851cc5-0388-4c62-9757-36334b739c1e/Certificate of transfer of a licence - Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833 section 6 - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 29 No. 79.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if plaintiffs or their solicitors fail to declare the names of the partners on demand?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["All proceedings in the action may be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct.","The case automatically proceeds without any further action required.","The judge dismisses the entire case immediately.","The court imposes a fine on the plaintiffs or their solicitors."],"justification":"If the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall fail to comply with such demand, all proceedings in the action may, upon an application for that purpose, be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own - Court: Circuit 1. Any two or more persons claiming or being liable as co-partners and carrying on business within the jurisdiction may sue or be sued in the name of the respective firms, if any, of which such persons were co-partners at the time of the accruing of the cause of action and in the names of such persons; and any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct. 2. When a Civil Bill is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall, on demand in writing by or on behalf of any defendant, forthwith declare in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. If the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall fail to comply with such demand, all proceedings in the action may, upon an application for that purpose, be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct. When the names of the partners are so declared, the action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'How do partners appear when sued as a firm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["They appear collectively under a single name that represents the firm, without individual representation.","They appear individually in their own names, but all subsequent proceedings continue in the name of the firm.","Partners appear only under the name of the firm, and no individual partner is named in the suit.","Each partner appears in the name of the firm, with all proceedings continuing under each partner''s individual name."],"justification":"Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, they shall appear individually in their own names; but all subsequent proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm under Rule 1 of this Order, the Civil Bill shall be served either upon any one or more of the partners personally or at the principal place, within the jurisdiction, of the business of the partnership, upon any person having at the time of service the control or management of the partnership business there; and, subject to these rules, such service shall be deemed good service on the firm so sued, whether any of the members thereof are out of the jurisdiction or not, and no leave to issue a Civil Bill against them shall be necessary; provided that in the case of a partnership which has been dissolved to the knowledge of the plaintiff before the commencement of the action, the Civil Bill shall be served on every person within the jurisdiction sought to be made liable. 4. Where persons are sued as partners in the name of their firm, they shall appear individually in their own names; but all subsequent proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm. 5. Debts owing by a firm carrying on business within the jurisdiction may be attached under [Order 38]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-38-Circuit-Attachment-of-debts-by-garnishee), although one or more members of such firm may be resident abroad, provided that any person having the control or management of the partnership business, or any member of the firm within the jurisdiction, is served with the garnishee order. An appearance by any member pursuant to an order shall be a sufficient appearance by the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'Can a person carrying on business in a name other than their own be sued in that name?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["No, because the person conducting business under a different name cannot be legally recognized unless they are registered under the Registration of Business Names Act, 1963.","Yes, if the business is within the jurisdiction and not registered under the Registration of Business Names Act, 1963.","Yes, only if the person has a trademark registered under that business name, regardless of the Registration of Business Names Act, 1963.","No, as long as the person conducting business under a different name maintains a separate bank account for that business."],"justification":"Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in such name or style;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '6. The above Rules shall apply to actions between a firm and one or more of its members, and to actions between firms having one or more members in common, provided such firm or firms carry on business within the jurisdiction, but no execution shall be issued in such actions without leave of the Judge after motion on notice to the party so to be affected, and on an application for leave to issue such execution, all such accounts and inquiries may be directed to be taken and made and directions given as may be just. 7. Any person carrying on business within the jurisdiction in a name or style other than his own name which is not registered pursuant to the [Registration of Business Names Act, 1963](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1963/act/30/enacted/en/html), may be sued in such name or style; and the plaintiff in such cases may apply by Notice of Motion to the Court for an Order directing the person who appears to have control or to be managing such business to furnish the name, description and place of residence of the person who at the time of the accruing of the cause of action was carrying on the business as aforesaid, in such manner and verified upon oath or otherwise as the Court may direct. 8. In all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies service of a Civil Bill or any other document may be effected by service in the manner provided by these Rules on the person carrying on business or on such person who at the time of the service appears to have control or to be managing the said business, at the place where the said business is carried on. Such service shall be deemed to be good service upon the person sued whether or not that person is out of the jurisdiction and no leave to issue the Civil Bill or other document shall be necessary. 9. In so far as the nature of the case will permit, all rules relating to the proceedings against firms shall apply to all cases to which Rule 7 of this Order applies.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 7 - Tendering Of Evidence","Order 8 - Admitting Witnesses","Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence","Order 9 - Tendering Of Evidence"],"justification":"# Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence - Court: District # **Order 8: Tendering of Evidence******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence', 'Court Rules', 'How should the evidence of witnesses in court be given?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By video testimony without an oath","Viva voce and on oath","Through anonymous statements","In written form only"],"justification":"Save where any enactment or rule otherwise provides, the evidence of all witnesses in the Court shall be given viva voce and on oath."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Evidence by a witness* 1. Save where any enactment or rule otherwise provides, the evidence of all witnesses in the Court shall be given viva voce and on oath. 2. In any proceedings a witness who is not a party shall not absent himself or herself from the Court without leave. The Court may, however, order such witness to leave the Court until his or her evidence is required or after such evidence has been given. [1] Order 8 rule 3 deleted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What is the maximum duration for which an original summons remains valid?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Eighteen months from the date of issuance, including the day of issuance.","Twelve months from the date of issuance, including the day of issuance.","Nine months from the date of issuance, including the day of issuance.","Six months from the date of issuance, not including the day of issuance."],"justification":"No original summons shall be in force for more than twelve months from the day of the date thereof, including the day of such date;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Renewal of Summons - Court: Superior 1. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) No original summons shall be in force for more than twelve months from the day of the date thereof, including the day of such date; but if any defendant therein named shall not have been served therewith, the plaintiff may apply before the expiration of twelve months to the Master for leave to renew the summons. (2) The Master on an application made under sub-rule (1), if satisfied that reasonable efforts have been made to serve such defendant, or for other good reason, may order that the original or concurrent summons be renewed for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive. (3) After the expiration of twelve months, and notwithstanding that an order may have been made under sub-rule (2), application to extend time for leave to renew the summons shall be made to the Court. (4) The Court on an application under sub-rule (3) may order a renewal of the original or concurrent summons for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive where satisfied that there are special circumstances which justify an extension, such circumstances to be stated in the order. (5) The summons shall, where an order of renewal has been made, be renewed by being stamped with the date of the day, month and year of such renewal; such stamp to be provided and kept for that purpose in the Central Office and to be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer, upon delivery to him by the plaintiff or his solicitor of a memorandum in the [Form No. 4 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon1); and a summons so renewed shall remain in force and be available to prevent the operation of any statute whereby a time for the commencement of the action may be limited and for all other purposes from the date of the issuing of the original summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'What constitutes sufficient evidence of the renewal of a summons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Presentation of a receipt indicating payment for the initial issuance of the summons.","Production of a summons without any markings or stamps.","A verbal confirmation from a court officer that the summons was renewed.","Production of a summons marked with a stamp showing it was renewed."],"justification":"The production of a summons purporting to be marked with a stamp showing the same to have been renewed in the matter aforesaid, shall be sufficient evidence of its having been so renewed and of the commencement of the action as of the first date of such renewed summons for all purposes."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '2. In any case where a summons has been renewed on an parte application, any defendant shall be at liberty before entering an appearance to serve notice of motion to set aside such order. 3. The production of a summons purporting to be marked with a stamp showing the same to have been renewed in the matter aforesaid, shall be sufficient evidence of its having been so renewed and of the commencement of the action as of the first date of such renewed summons for all purposes. 4. Where a summons, of which the production is necessary, has been destroyed or lost, the Court upon being satisfied of the destruction or loss, and of the correctness of a copy thereof, may order that such copy shall be sealed and served in lieu of the original summons. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 8 rule 1 substituted by 482 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/482/made/en/print), effective 11 January 2019.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What court is mentioned in Order 80?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme","High","District","County"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1986'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Education Reform Act, 1986 (No. 25 of 1986)","The Environmental Protection Act, 1986 (No. 27 of 1986)","The Criminal Law Act, 1986 (No. 30 of 1986)","The Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 (No. 26 of 1986)"],"justification":"\"**the Act of 1986**\" means the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 (No. 26 of 1986)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 (No. 26 of 1986)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html); "**the Act of 1988**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1988 (No. 16 of 1988)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Where should an objection be made if it concerns the renewal of an on-licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At the local municipal council meeting where the licence is issued.","During the next general election when voting on local issues.","Before the Supreme Court in the jurisdiction where the licence is applied for.","At the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate."],"justification":"it shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (2) of this rule, where an objection is made under section 4 (6) of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html) to the renewal of - - (a) an on-licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor, - a special restaurant licence granted under Part of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - a licence or licences for the sale of spirits or beer in retail quantities for consumption off the premises where sold, it shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate. (2) Where the objection is made to the renewal of a wholesale beer dealer''s licence or any other off-licence which, by virtue of section 49 of the [Finance (1909-10) Act, 1910](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1910/act/8/enacted/en/html), expires on the thirtieth day of June each year, such objection may be made at the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice of objection?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The objector or solicitor for the objector","The judge presiding over the case","The applicant or solicitor for the applicant","The witness or solicitor for the witness"],"justification":"signed by the objector or solicitor for the objector"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of objection* 3. (1) Such objection shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 80.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dc936958-b2db-44be-99ed-105b826761d1/Notice of objection to renewal of intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986 No. 80.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the objector or solicitor for the objector. (2) The notice shall be served upon the holder of the licence or licences attached to the premises to which the objection relates at least twenty-one days before the date of sitting of the said Annual Licensing Court or other sitting of the Court before which the objection has been listed for hearing. When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk as soon as possible but not later than seven days before the date of the said sitting.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do upon receiving a notice of objection?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Inform the Minister for Health and the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.","Contact the President of Ireland and the Director of Tourism.","Notify the local mayor and the head of the education board.","Notify the Collector of Customs and Excise and, if applicable, the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána."],"justification":"Upon receipt of the notice of objection the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the [Form 80.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7648106-7b2f-45a2-a586-c857c9c5b515/Notification of the lodgment of a notice of objection to the renewal of an intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986. No. 80.2.docx/docx/1)) the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly and, where the objector is not a member of the Garda Síochána, the Clerk shall also notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the area."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Clerk to notify Collector of & etc.* 4. Upon receipt of the notice of objection the Clerk shall forthwith notify (in the [Form 80.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f7648106-7b2f-45a2-a586-c857c9c5b515/Notification of the lodgment of a notice of objection to the renewal of an intoxicating liquor licence - Courts (No. 2) Act 1986. No. 80.2.docx/docx/1)) the Collector of Customs and Excise for the district in which the said premises are situate accordingly and, where the objector is not a member of the Garda Síochána, the Clerk shall also notify the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court take when hearing objections to the renewal of intoxicating liquor licences?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 80.3, Schedule","Form 75.3, Schedule","Form 80.4, Schedule","Form 80.3, Schedule A"],"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 80.3, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Order of the Court* 5. (1) The order of the Court on hearing the objection shall be in the [Form 80.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85bd770e-8620-490f-8f68-407e7d125349/Order on hearing objection to the renewal of intoxicating liquor licence No. 80.3.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Clerk take if the Court allows the objection and no appeal is lodged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk sends a certified copy of the order to the Collector of Customs and Excise.","The Clerk updates the court''s internal records but does not send any external notification.","The Clerk sends a notice of the decision to all parties involved in the case.","The Clerk files the order with the local law enforcement agency."],"justification":"the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certified copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to send copy to Collector & (2) Where the Court allows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certified copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What document does the Clerk send to the Collector of Customs and Excise when the Court disallows an objection and no appeal is lodged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Certificate for the renewal of the licence in Form 80.4, Schedule","Certificate for the renewal of the licence in Form 80.5, Schedule","Notice of Disallowance in Form 79.3, Schedule","Acknowledgment of Receipt of Appeal in Form 81.2, Schedule A"],"justification":"the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence in the [Form 80. 4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to send a renewal cert. (or copy) to Collector* (3) Where the Court disallows the objection and no notice of appeal against such order is lodged with the Clerk within the time prescribed in that behalf the Clerk shall forthwith send to the Collector of Customs and Excise a certificate for the renewal of the licence in the [Form 80. 4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1).(or copy thereof).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Clerk do upon lodging of an appeal notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Clerk must notify all citizens within the jurisdiction of the appeal.","The Clerk must file the appeal notice with the Supreme Court directly.","The Clerk must send notice of the appeal to the local newspaper.","The Clerk must send notice of the appeal to the Collector of Customs and Excise."],"justification":"such Clerk shall forthwith send notice to this effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- to notify Collector in cases of appeal* 6. Where notice of an appeal against any order of the Court to which this Order relates is at any time lodged with the Clerk, such Clerk shall forthwith send notice to this effect to the Collector of Customs and Excise.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'How can documents required by this Order to be sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise be delivered?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Through a third-party courier service without tracking","By registered post or delivered to the office of the Collector","By standard post without registration","By email attachment only"],"justification":"Documents which are required by this Order to be sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise may be sent by registered post or, may be delivered to the office of the said Collector where appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Mode of service* 7. Documents which are required by this Order to be sent to the Collector of Customs and Excise may be sent by registered post or, may be delivered to the office of the said Collector where appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 77.5, Schedule A","Form 77.5, Schedule","Form 88.5, Schedule","Form 77, Schedule"],"justification":"Where a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) such certificate shall be in the [Form 77.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Forms of renewal certificate* 8. The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the [Form 80.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1). Where a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) such certificate shall be in the [Form 77.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'To whom should an application for an order under Section 19 of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 be directed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The licensing authority of the county council in which the relevant licensed premises are situated.","The Secretary of State for the Department of Health and Social Care.","The local police chief for the area where the relevant licensed premises are located.","The Judge for the time being assigned to the Court for the court district in which the relevant licensed premises are situated."],"justification":"An application to the Court for an order pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be made to the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court for the court district in which the relevant licensed premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications for redress under the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003* 10.[1] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) shall be made to the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court for the court district in which the relevant licensed premises are situated. Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 80.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/83c69ddd-f2d6-4abd-813d-2c9ed6078f15/Notice of application - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 section 19 [section 23] No. 80.5.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to sub-section (2) or sub-section (6) of Section 19 of the said [Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 80.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d6c622bf-fec0-4217-9967-474cb6667497/Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 - Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003 No. 80.6.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 80 rule 10 inserted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 81 - Annual licensing court', 'Court Rules', 'When does the Annual Licensing Court take place in the Dublin Metropolitan District?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["On the last Thursday in September","On the third Friday in August","On the second Monday in November","On the first Tuesday in October"],"justification":"the day of the last sitting of the Court in the month of September in the Dublin Metropolitan District shall be that sitting held on the last Thursday in that month each year"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 81 - Annual licensing court - Court: District 1. A Judge of the District Court shall hold a court, to be known as the Annual Licensing Court, in each court area in the Judge''s district on the day of the last sitting of the Court for that court area for the transaction of the business of the Court exercising its summary jurisdiction held in the month of September each year. 2. Every such Annual Licensing Court shall hear and determine - all such applications made to it for certificates, licenses, orders, or renewals thereof, and objections to the grant or renewal of such certificates, licences or orders, as are provided for in [Orders 63]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-63-District-Auctioneers-and-house-agents) to [89]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-89-District-Wildlife) of these [Rules]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]C07733B1-CAA0-4F89-8468-D48198AE2F9F?page 3#targetSearch) and are required to be made at the Annual Licensing Court; - any other application, objection or other matter which is required by statute or by Rules of Court to be made or brought at that court; and the Judge may adjourn any such court from time to time as circumstances may deem it necessary. 3. For the purposes of this Order the day of the last sitting of the Court in the month of September in the Dublin Metropolitan District shall be that sitting held on the last Thursday in that month each year.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What is the name of the book the Clerk is required to maintain?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Ledger of Permits","The Register of Licences","The Logbook of Transactions","The Book of Deeds"],"justification":"The Clerk shall keep a book which shall be known as the Register of Licences"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 82 - Register of licences - Court: District 1. The Clerk shall keep a book which shall be known as the Register of Licences ([Form 82.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e6f0b62-d97f-4918-9de6-47dbac268070/Register of licences No. 82.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall enter or cause to be entered in such Register particulars of all licences for the sale of intoxicating liquors existing in respect of premises situate within the court area and of all renewals, transfers and other proceedings affecting the said licences or any of them and shall retain all maps, plans or other documents lodged which relate to such licences or premises.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What must every holder of a licence deliver to the Clerk within ten days of obtaining it?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A verbal declaration made directly to the Clerk over the phone","A note in writing setting forth the holder''s full name and address, description and location of the licensed premises, and the owner''s full name and address.","A photograph of the licensed premises along with the holder''s signature","An electronic copy of the license application form filled out by the applicant"],"justification":"Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing ([Form 82.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f3b3e1c3-089d-43ee-8bf6-5acff952358e/Notice describing licensed premises No. 82.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the holder, setting forth the holders full name and address and description and location of the house or premises in which intoxicating liquors are licensed to be sold and the full name and address of the owner of the said house or premises in accordance with the provisions of section 10 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1833/act/68/enacted/en/print.html), as amended."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of particulars of licensed premises* 2. Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing ([Form 82.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f3b3e1c3-089d-43ee-8bf6-5acff952358e/Notice describing licensed premises No. 82.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the holder, setting forth the holders full name and address and description and location of the house or premises in which intoxicating liquors are licensed to be sold and the full name and address of the owner of the said house or premises in accordance with the provisions of section 10 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1833/act/68/enacted/en/print.html), as amended. 3.[1] Where a temporary closure order is made pursuant to section 36A(2) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) , the order shall be in the [Form 82.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec1c77e6-8976-4a4f-a108-36851c4e44d5/Temporary Closure Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988 No. 82.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 82 rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2006), effective 9 May 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What court is responsible for Order 83?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["County Court","High Court","District Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Taxation Act, 1904 (4 Edw. 7. 9)","The Registration of Voters Act, 1904 (4 Edw. 7. 9)","The Education Act, 1904 (4 Edw. 7. 9)","The Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act, 1904 (4 Edw. 7. 9)"],"justification":"\"**the Act**\" means the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (4 Edw. 7. 9);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1.[1] In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (4 Edw. 7. 9); "**the Act of 1924**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) (No. 62 of 1924); "**the Act of 1927**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (No. 15 of 1927); "**the Act of 1962**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1962); "**the Act of 1988**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 1988); "**licensing year"** means a period of twelve months ending on the thirtieth day of September in any year; "**registered club**" means a club holding a certificate of registration in force at the time. “**the Act of 2000**” means the [Equal Status Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) (No. 8 of 2000); “**Determination Order**” means an Order made under sub-section (6) or sub-section (15) of section 8 of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)[.](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Who is the Registrar of Clubs referred to as in this Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["the President of the local council","the Secretary of the relevant department","the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated","the Chief Justice of the jurisdiction"],"justification":"the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Registrar of Clubs* 2. (1) For the purposes of the Act the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What must the Registrar of Clubs do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Ensure that all clubs adhere to a specific set of club activities mandated by the court.","Provide financial assistance to clubs that apply for funding.","Organize annual events for all registered clubs within their court area.","Keep a register of clubs within their court area that have been granted a certificate of registration."],"justification":"Every such Registrar of Clubs shall keep a register in which shall be entered the name of each club situate within his or her court area to which a certificate of registration is granted under the provisions of the Act and, where appropriate, the further particulars required by the Act."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to keep a register* (2) Every such Registrar of Clubs shall keep a register in which shall be entered the name of each club situate within his or her court area to which a certificate of registration is granted under the provisions of the Act and, where appropriate, the further particulars required by the Act. # **Application for certificate of registration**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What action must the registrar take upon receiving an application for an original certificate of registration?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The registrar must forward the application to the local mayor''s office.","The registrar must publish the application in a national newspaper.","The registrar must give notice of the application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána.","The registrar must send a confirmation email to the applicant."],"justification":"the registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to notify Garda Supt.* 3. (1) Where the secretary of a club desiring an original certificate of registration lodges with the registrar, pursuant to subsection (1) of section 2 of the Act, the documents mentioned in that subsection, the registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána in like manner as prescribed in rule 4 (6) hereof in the case of an application for the renewal of such a certificate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What happens after the expiration of ten days from the date of lodgment?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The documents are automatically approved by the registrar without further action.","The registrar discards the documents if no fee is paid within the ten-day period.","The registrar transmits the documents to the appropriate County Registrar.","The registrar sends a notice to the applicant requesting additional information."],"justification":"After the expiration of ten days from the date of the said lodgment the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to transmit file to Registrar* (2) After the expiration of ten days from the date of the said lodgment the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'In what form is the certificate of registration issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Certificate of registration in Form 83.4, Schedule","Certificate of registration in Form 83.3, Schedule","Certificate of registration in Form 83.4, Schedule","Certificate of registration in Form 83.5, Schedule"],"justification":"in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted - to record particulars and issue certificate* (3) Upon the return of the file together with notification from the County Registrar of the granting of the application the registrar shall enter in the register of clubs the particulars required by section 1 (1) of the Act, and shall thereupon issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1). # **Renewal of certificates, Objections thereto**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant do after publishing the notice in a daily newspaper?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Lodge a copy of the newspaper with the registrar.","Publish a second notice in a weekly newspaper.","Submit an affidavit to the court confirming the publication of the notice.","Announce the publication on social media platforms."],"justification":"shall, when the notice has been published, lodge a copy of the newspaper with the registrar."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (2) The applicant shall also publish the notice of such application once in a daily newspaper circulating in the locality and shall, when the notice has been published, lodge a copy of the newspaper with the registrar.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must accompany an application for renewal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["One copy of the club''s financial statements, a list of past events, and a letter of recommendation from a previous official.","Two copies of the club''s constitution, a list of potential new members, and a certificate of good standing from the local government.","Three copies of the club newsletter, a list of current projects, and a signed affidavit from the legal representative of the neighboring property.","Two copies of the rules of the club, a list of officials and members, and a certificate signed by Peace Commissioners or the owner/legal representative of the premises."],"justification":"Such application for renewal shall be accompanied by— - (a) two copies of the rules of the club, - a list containing the names and addresses of the officials and committee of management or governing body and the names of the members, and - a certificate in the [Form 83.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f990d829-5435-4e71-8e05-2a7d0cb17fdd/Certificate to accompany application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.2.docx/docx/1), signed by two Peace Commissioners for the district in which the club premises are situated, and where such premises are not owned by the club, the certificate shall be signed by the owner of such premises or, where the owner is under any legal disability, by the legal representative of the owner."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Documents to accompany application* (3) Such application for renewal shall be accompanied by— - (a) two copies of the rules of the club, - a list containing the names and addresses of the officials and committee of management or governing body and the names of the members, and - a certificate in the [Form 83.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f990d829-5435-4e71-8e05-2a7d0cb17fdd/Certificate to accompany application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.2.docx/docx/1), signed by two Peace Commissioners for the district in which the club premises are situated, and where such premises are not owned by the club, the certificate shall be signed by the owner of such premises or, where the owner is under any legal disability, by the legal representative of the owner. The application form shall be stamped to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee (if any) required by law to be paid in respect of such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Under what legislation must a club''s rules comply to be eligible for registration?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Non-Profit Organization Act, 1995","The Community Club Regulations, 2007","The Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988","The Sports Governance Act, 2010"],"justification":"the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Club rules qualifying for registration* (4) In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of - section 4 of the Act, as amended by section 42 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), and - section 56 (which relates to prohibited hours for the supplying for consumption on club premises of excisable liquor) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 26 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Which act''s section 24 applies to every application under this order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Traffic Regulation Act, 1985","The Fire Services Act, 1981","The Environmental Protection Act, 1990","The Wildlife Protection Act, 1972"],"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) (No. 30 of 1981) shall apply to every such application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) (No. 30 of 1981) shall apply to every such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Along with the notice, what else does the registrar provide to the Garda Superintendent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A list of all club members","A copy of the club''s financial statements","A copy of the club''s rules","The club''s annual report"],"justification":"together with a copy of the rules of the club"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Registrar to notify Garda Supt.* (6) The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12f2f2e8-bfb6-48b7-a784-8509ed14ce18/Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.3.docx/docx/1), together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What grounds must objections to the renewal of a certificate be based on?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Section 5 of the Act as amended by section 46 of the Act of 1988, section 24(2) of the Act of 1924, or section 19(10) of the Public Order Act 2003.","Section 5 of the Act as amended by section 46 of the Act of 1988, section 24(3) of the Act of 1924, or section 19(11) of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003.","Section 5 of the Act as amended by section 46 of the Act of 1988, section 24(2) of the Act of 1924, or section 19(10) of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003.","Section 6 of the Act as amended by section 47 of the Act of 1988, section 25(2) of the Act of 1924, or section 20(10) of the Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003."],"justification":"The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in - section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html), or - section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Objections to grant or renewal of certificate* 7.(1) It shall be competent for the superintendent of the Garda Síochána on receiving notice of an application given as aforesaid, and for any person resident in the parish in which the club premises are situated, to lodge objections to the grant of the certificate on any of the grounds of objection specified in the Act, and it shall be competent for any person to lodge objections to the renewal of the certificate on any such grounds. (2)[2] The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in - section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html), or - section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the superintendent of the Garda Síochána is not an objector?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The judge gives notice of the lodgment of the objection to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána.","The superintendent of the Garda Síochána gives notice of the lodgment of the objection to the registrar.","The solicitor gives notice of the lodgment of the objection to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána.","The registrar gives notice of the lodgment of the objection to the superintendent"],"justification":"When the superintendent of the Garda Síochána is not an objector, the registrar shall give notice of the lodgment of the objection or objections to the said superintendent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (3) An objection to the grant or renewal of a certificate of registration of a club shall be by notice in the [Form 83.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f82d20e0-58df-41fc-8ddf-c1ac5865cb3f/Notice of objection to the grant-renewal of certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.5.docx/docx/1), signed by the objector or solicitor for the objector, and shall be lodged with the registrar within ten days of the receipt or publication of notice of the application, and at the same time a copy of such notice of objection shall be sent to the secretary of the club applying for the grant of renewal of the certificate. When the superintendent of the Garda Síochána is not an objector, the registrar shall give notice of the lodgment of the objection or objections to the said superintendent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What does the Registrar of Clubs do after the Court grants the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Registrar updates the club''s social media profiles.","The Registrar sends a notification to all existing club members.","The Registrar records the required entries in the register of clubs and issues a certificate of registration.","The Registrar schedules a meeting with the new club''s executive committee."],"justification":"the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted registrar to record particulars and issue certificate* (5) If, upon hearing the application and the objection, the Court grants the application, the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What is the duration of a certificate of registration issued by a Registrar of Clubs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It expires one year after the grant of the application for such certificate.","It becomes invalid if the club fails to pay the annual licensing fee within 30 days of the due date.","It remains valid indefinitely unless revoked by the Registrar of Clubs.","It remains in force until the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the club premises are situated held next after the grant of the application for such certificate, and then expires."],"justification":"remain in force until the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the club premises are situated held next after the grant of the application for such certificate, and shall then expire."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Duration of certificate* 8. (1) A certificate of registration duly issued by a Registrar of Clubs under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 shall, as provided in section 3 (3) of the Act (as amended by the first schedule to the Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 — No. 26 of 1986), and subject to the other provisions of the Act, remain in force until the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the club premises are situated held next after the grant of the application for such certificate, and shall then expire.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the current certificate when a renewal application is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The current certificate is suspended until new conditions are met by the applicant.","The current certificate is automatically extended for one year while the renewal is processed.","The current certificate is immediately invalidated upon submission of the renewal application.","The current certificate remains in force pending the final decision of the Court."],"justification":"where a renewal has been applied for the current certificate shall remain in force pending the final decision of the Court"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- extension pending Court''s decision* (2) Notwithstanding the provisions of the Act as to the duration of certifcates, where a renewal has been applied for the current certificate shall remain in force pending the final decision of the Court, but not exceeding three months unless the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What follows the section title?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["10. [3]","9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**","3. [9]","8. [3]"],"justification":"9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners* 9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an authorisation under section 21(1) of the Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 as amended by the Act of 1962 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By submitting a written request to the Secretary of State responsible for alcohol control.","At the local police station for the district in which the club premises are located.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.","Through an online form on the government''s official website dedicated to liquor licensing."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 10. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 21 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) as amended by section 8 of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána before the hearing of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least forty-eight hours","No notice is required","Exactly one week","At least twenty-four hours"],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the authorisation take when an application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 94, Schedule A","Form 83.6, Schedule","Form 83.7, Schedule","Form 83.7, Schedule"],"justification":"the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (3) Where the application is granted, the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fb19bab5-78a1-4b4c-add6-c84979d9c518/Club authorisation - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 - Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924 section 21 (as amended) No. 83.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What is the maximum number of authorisations a club can receive in one licensing year?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Ten","Twenty","Fifteen","Five"],"justification":"Not more than fifteen such authorisations shall be granted to any club in any licensing year."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Not more than 15 per year* (4) Not more than fifteen such authorisations shall be granted to any club in any licensing year. # **Authorisations for special events**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What type of application can be made by the secretary of a registered club?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An application for tax exemption status pursuant to section 8 of the Act of 1990.","An application for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the Act of 1962.","An application for club membership renewal pursuant to section 5 of the Act of 1980.","An application for dissolution of the club pursuant to section 20 of the Act of 1975."],"justification":"An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 11. (1) An application by the secretary of a registered club for an authorisation pursuant to section 14 (1) of the [Act of 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the club premises for which the authorisation is sought are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána before the hearing of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least twenty-four hours","Exactly thirty-six hours","At least forty-eight hours","No notice is required"],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochana within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochana within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a copy of the notice of an application for a Determination Order be served on the club?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["three days","five days","ten days","seven days"],"justification":"a copy of such notice shall be served upon the club (or in the case of an application under section 8(15), upon the original applicant) in the manner prescribed by section 8(5) of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of* (3) Where the application is granted, the authorisation shall be in accordance with [Form 83.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cae20262-a429-4ae4-ad7a-ba43edccca5c/Club authorisation for special event - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962 No. 83.8.docx/docx/1). 12.[4] An application pursuant to section 8(3) or section 8(15) of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) for a Determination Order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the club is situated. Notice of an application for a Determination Order shall be in the [Form 83.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49d0a221-efe7-4f8c-a0cf-433cef03e507/Notice Of Application For Determination Order - Registration Of Clubs Acts 1904 To 2000 - Equal Status Act 2000 section 8(3) - 8(15) No. 83.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule a copy of such notice shall be served upon the club (or in the case of an application under section 8(15), upon the original applicant) in the manner prescribed by section 8(5) of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct. A Determination Order shall be in the [Form 83.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/16eccbad-631b-4b73-9784-14924de97dd6/Determination Order - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 2000 - Equal Status Act 2000 section 8(3) - 8(15) No. 83.10.docx/docx/1), Schedule The Clerk shall transmit a copy of any Determination Order to the Minister for Justice, Equality and Law Reform. [1] Order 83 rule 1 amended by [S.I. 161 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/161/made/en/print?q 161&years 2006), effective 8 May 2006 [2] Order 83 sub-rule (2) of rule 7 substituted by [S.I. 259 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/259/made/en/print?q 259&years 2005), effective 3 June 2005 [3] Order 83 rule 9 deleted by [S.I. 198 of 2005](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/si/198/made/en/print?q 198&years 2005), effective 6 April 2005 [4] Order 83 rule 12 inserted by [S.I. 161 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/161/made/en/print?q 161&years 2006), amended by [S.I. 397 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/397/made/en/print?q 397&years 2006), effective 25 August 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'In which court is Order 84 - Child care heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Family Court","District Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84 - Child care - Court: District # **Order 84: Child Care******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''child'' mean in this context?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A person under the age of twenty-one years","Someone who has never been married regardless of their age","A person under the age of eighteen years, except those who are or have been married","An individual who is not yet sixteen years old"],"justification":"“**child**” means a person under the age of eighteen year other than a person who is or has been married;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1.[2] In this Order: “**the Act**” means the [Child Care Act 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (No. 17 of 1991); “**the Act of 2001**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2001); “**Agency**” means the Child and Family Agency established under section 7 of the [Child and Family Agency Act 2013](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/act/40/enacted/en/html) (No. 40 of 2013); “**child**” means a person under the age of eighteen year other than a person who is or has been married; “**parents**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 2(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). 2.[3] (1) Proceedings under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be heard otherwise than in public and only officers of the Court, the parties and their legal representatives, witnesses and such other persons as the Judge in his or her discretion may allow, shall be permitted to be present at the hearing. (2) The Judge may, if he or she thinks it proper to do so, order any witness who is not a party to the proceedings to leave the court either until his or her evidence is required or after his or her evidence has been given. (3) Proceedings in the Court under Part III, Part Part IVA (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)), Part IVB (inserted by the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) or Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be as informal as is practicable and consistent with the administration of justice. Neither Judges hearing and determining such proceedings nor barristers nor solicitors appearing in such proceedings shall wear wigs or gowns. (4)[4] Unless otherwise provided in this Order or permitted by the Court, all applications under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application specifying the order or other relief sought in the application, the provisions of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) relied on and the grounds of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How can a document be served on a person when they cannot be conveniently met with?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By mailing the document to the person’s current address if known, via registered post.","By posting the document on a public notice board in the nearest town hall.","By sending an email to the person''s last known email address if it is accessible.","By leaving a copy of the document at their last known residence or most usual place of abode with a relative aged 16 or older believed to reside there, or with the person in charge of the house or premises."],"justification":"if he or she cannot be conveniently met with, by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode with any relative of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age and who is believed to reside there with him or her, or by leaving it with the person in charge of the house or premises of such residence or abode,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of documents* 3. (1) A document required by these Rules to be served shall, subject to paragraphs (2) and (3) hereof, be served upon the person to whom it is directed— - (a) by delivering to him or her a copy thereof or, - if he or she cannot be conveniently met with, by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode with any relative of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age and who is believed to reside there with him or her, or by leaving it with the person in charge of the house or premises of such residence or abode, or, - by leaving a copy thereof for him or her at his or her place of business with any agent, clerk, employee or servant of such person who is not less than sixteen years of age, or - by sending a copy thereof by ordinary prepaid post in an envelope addressed to him or her at his or her last known residence or most usual place of abode or at his or her place of business. (2)[7] A document may be served on the Agency or any other statutory board or body or on an unincorporated society by leaving a copy of the document with any employee of the Agency, or of the board, body or society concerned at its principal office or by sending such copy by ordinary prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the Agency or to the board, body or society concerned at such principal office. (3) The Court may, if for special reason in any particular case it considers it proper to do so, deem the service actually effected to be good and sufficient service, even though it was not effected in accordance with the provisions of this Order. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done immediately after serving a notice of application, summons, or notice of appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A confirmation email must be sent to all parties involved within 24 hours of serving the notice.","The served party must acknowledge receipt of the notice in writing within 7 days.","The original notice or summons, along with a statutory declaration of service, must be lodged with the Clerk for entry for hearing.","The original notice or summons must be returned to the court that issued it for cancellation."],"justification":"When a notice of application, summons or notice of appeal issued under this Order has been served, the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgment for hearing* 4. When a notice of application, summons or notice of appeal issued under this Order has been served, the original notice or summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged forthwith with the Clerk for entry for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Provisions under Part of the Act","Proceedings under Part III of the Act","Preliminary matters under Part of the Act","Regulations under Part of the Act"],"justification":"**Proceedings under Part III of the Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part III of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Can an application for an emergency care order be heard parte?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, an application for an emergency care order cannot be heard parte under any circumstances.","Yes, but only if the applicant provides a detailed affidavit explaining why notice cannot be given to the other party.","Yes, it can be heard parte if the notice of application is lodged with the Clerk.","An application for an emergency care order can be heard parte, but only if the court grants permission after a full hearing with all parties present."],"justification":"an application for an emergency care order may be heard and made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the notice of application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- (a) an application for an emergency care order may be heard and made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the notice of application ([Form 84.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/578b4525-2f2f-4f59-a65a-9967f0b17c40/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 12 (4) No. 84.1.docx/docx/1) or [84.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d188ed27-41b1-4b7a-8f08-b83aa6a4625c/Notice of application for an emergency care order (where child is not in custody of health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13(1) No. 84.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be) duly completed; - an application for an emergency care order may be heard and an order may be made thereon elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court; - the Judge may deem sufficient the notice of the application actually given to the respondent. (3) An application to which sub-rule (2) applies shall be made on affidavit unless the Judge permits the application to be heard on oral evidence because of the exceptional urgency of the case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an emergency care order take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It should be in Form 79.5 or 79.6 Schedule as applicable.","It should be in Form 102 or 103 Schedule A, as applicable.","It should be in Form 84.3 or 84.4 Schedule as applicable.","It should be in Form 98.1 or 98.2 Schedule as applicable."],"justification":"An emergency care order shall be in the [Form 84.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85df8e22-6926-41e5-af5c-2d4b7d31c55a/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.3.docx/docx/1) or [84.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 6.[9] (1) An application for an emergency care order under section 13(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) must be made to the Judge assigned to the district in which the child resides or is for the time being. Where, however, such Judge is not immediately available, the application may be made to any judge of the District Court. (2) An emergency care order shall be in the [Form 84.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/85df8e22-6926-41e5-af5c-2d4b7d31c55a/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.3.docx/docx/1) or [84.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the order to be served on a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, upon a person acting in loco parentis, together with, as the case may be, a copy of the affidavit which grounded the application and copies of any exhibits (unless previously served on that person) or a copy of the note of oral evidence mentioned in rule 2(5). (3) A warrant issued under section 13(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the purpose of executing such an Order may be in the [Form 84.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/14aa135a-515f-470d-836c-d5822ddad575/Warrant to execute an emergency care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 13(3) No. 84.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule (4) An appeal from an emergency care order shall not stay the operation of the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when making an application for the Judge''s directions under section 13 (7)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 85.6","Form 84.5","Form 90.2","[Form 84.6]"],"justification":"[Form 84.6]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions under section 13 (7)* 7. (1)[10] Where, otherwise than at the hearing of an application for an emergency care order, application is made under section 13 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Judge''s directions, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency, the parents of the child or either of them, a person acting in loco parentis, or any other person, as appropriate. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application An order giving directions on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which shall be served upon each person directly affected by the Order. (2) An application to vary or discharge a direction given under the said section 13 (7) (a) shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1). Schedule The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1) Schedule which shall be served as prescribed in the said paragraph (1). 8. It shall not be necessary in any notice or application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) or in any order made under that section to name the child if such name is unknown. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Regulations Under Part III of the Act","Proceedings Under Part of the Act","Enforcement Procedures Under Part of the Act","Compliance Measures Under Part of the Act"],"justification":"**Proceedings Under Part of the Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings Under Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued before an interim care order application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["[Form 84.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d768e869-970c-4538-8b75-6367c62c667b/Notice of application for an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.10.docx/docx/1)","Form 84.11","Form 11.2","Form"],"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d768e869-970c-4538-8b75-6367c62c667b/Notice of application for an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.10.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim care order* 9. [11](1) An application by the Agency under section 17(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim care order shall, except where the Judge directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d768e869-970c-4538-8b75-6367c62c667b/Notice of application for an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.10.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and any other person directly affected by the Order. (2) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in rule 27) for the purpose of executing an interim care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served before an application for an extension of an interim care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 84.11","Form","Form 84.12","Form 79"],"justification":"a notice in the [Form 84.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9bce7aa4-5c98-4d2e-8420-814bd2b699f4/Notice of application for an extension of an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (2) No. 84.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3) An application under section 17(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs under section 17(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9bce7aa4-5c98-4d2e-8420-814bd2b699f4/Notice of application for an extension of an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (2) No. 84.12.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/48eea238-5f1b-4de7-959b-46b81c6a7683/Order extending the period of an interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (2) No. 84.13.docx/docx/1)Schedule and may, where appropriate, be added to or endorsed on the interim care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["at most four days","at least seven days","at least three days","exactly five days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Care Order* 10.(1)[12] An application by the Agency under section 18 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a care order in respect of a child who resides or is found in its area shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b9979d0-2a7f-44ec-9965-d27d8023b8b3/Notice of application for a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.14.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should a care order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 84.05","Form","Form 84.15","Form 85"],"justification":"Form 84.15"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* (2) A care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said Order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What does the transfer authorise the person to do?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["To sell the business authorised by the licence immediately upon signing the transfer","To modify the terms of the licence as per the transfer agreement","To carry on the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court","To renew the licence without attending the Annual Licensing Court"],"justification":"Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Power to trade until Annual Licensing Court* (5) Such transfer shall operate to authorise the person to whom the license is transferred to carry on in the premises to which the licence relates the business authorised by the licence until the date of the sitting of the Annual Licensing Court in the court area in which the premises are situate held next after the expiration of one month from the date of the transfer.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'To whom should the notice be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situated.","The resident magistrate of the jurisdiction where the premises are located","The nearest police station''s general duty officer","The head of the local council''s property management department"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 77 - Ad-interim transfers of licences', 'Court Rules', 'Which rules specify the provisions for temporary transfer of licences?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["rules 2(3) and 2(4) of this order","rules 3(1) and 3(2) of this order","rules 1(1) and 1(2) of this order","rules 1 (4) and 1(5) of this order"],"justification":"the provisions contained in the Licensing Acts regarding temporary transfer of licences as set out in rules 1 (4) and 1(5) of this order shall apply"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of endorsement* (4) The endorsement of transfer by the Court on the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 77.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/175887a8-9569-407e-a76a-294dcd06aa0a/Form of endorsement of ad-interim transfer of licence (to person other than the owner) No. 77.4.docx/docx/1), and the provisions contained in the Licensing Acts regarding temporary transfer of licences as set out in rules 1 (4) and 1(5) of this order shall apply.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 78 - Transfers of licences held by nominees', 'Court Rules', 'Who must be served with notice of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The owner or manager of the premises where the application is being made.","The officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises are located.","The local mayor or chief administrative officer of the county council.","The nearest police station commander outside of the licensing area."],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the officer in charge of the Garda Síochána for the licensing area in which the premises to which the application relates are situate and a copy thereof, endorsed as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least forty-eight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own', 'Court Rules', 'How should the action proceed once the names of the partners are declared?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall continue in the name of the firm.","All proceedings shall cease immediately and a new action shall be initiated under the names of the individual partners.","The action shall proceed in the opposite manner to how it was initiated, with the names of the partners being disregarded.","The action shall proceed only if all partners agree to continue it, otherwise it will be automatically dismissed."],"justification":"When the names of the partners are so declared, the action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Actions by and against firms and persons carrying on business in names other than their own - Court: Circuit 1. Any two or more persons claiming or being liable as co-partners and carrying on business within the jurisdiction may sue or be sued in the name of the respective firms, if any, of which such persons were co-partners at the time of the accruing of the cause of action and in the names of such persons; and any party to an action may in such cases apply by notice of motion to the Court for a statement of the names, descriptions and places of residence of the persons who were, at the time of the accruing of the cause of action, co-partners in any such firm, to be furnished in such manner, and verified on oath or otherwise, as the Court may direct. 2. When a Civil Bill is issued by partners in the name of their firm, the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall, on demand in writing by or on behalf of any defendant, forthwith declare in writing the names, descriptions and places of residence of all the persons constituting the firm on whose behalf the action is brought. If the plaintiffs or their solicitors shall fail to comply with such demand, all proceedings in the action may, upon an application for that purpose, be stayed upon such terms as the Judge may direct. When the names of the partners are so declared, the action shall proceed in the same manner, and the same consequences in all respects shall follow, as if they had been named as plaintiffs in the Civil Bill, but all proceedings shall, nevertheless, continue in the name of the firm.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 8 - Tendering Of Evidence', 'Court Rules', 'Can a non-party witness absent themselves from court without permission?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Yes","No"],"justification":"In any proceedings a witness who is not a party shall not absent himself or herself from the Court without leave."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Evidence by a witness* 1. Save where any enactment or rule otherwise provides, the evidence of all witnesses in the Court shall be given viva voce and on oath. 2. In any proceedings a witness who is not a party shall not absent himself or herself from the Court without leave. The Court may, however, order such witness to leave the Court until his or her evidence is required or after such evidence has been given. [1] Order 8 rule 3 deleted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 8 - Renewal of Summons', 'Court Rules', 'Who can grant an extension beyond the initial twelve-month period?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Attorney General","The Secretary of State","The President","The Court."],"justification":"application to extend time for leave to renew the summons shall be made to the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 8 - Renewal of Summons - Court: Superior 1. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) No original summons shall be in force for more than twelve months from the day of the date thereof, including the day of such date; but if any defendant therein named shall not have been served therewith, the plaintiff may apply before the expiration of twelve months to the Master for leave to renew the summons. (2) The Master on an application made under sub-rule (1), if satisfied that reasonable efforts have been made to serve such defendant, or for other good reason, may order that the original or concurrent summons be renewed for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive. (3) After the expiration of twelve months, and notwithstanding that an order may have been made under sub-rule (2), application to extend time for leave to renew the summons shall be made to the Court. (4) The Court on an application under sub-rule (3) may order a renewal of the original or concurrent summons for three months from the date of such renewal inclusive where satisfied that there are special circumstances which justify an extension, such circumstances to be stated in the order. (5) The summons shall, where an order of renewal has been made, be renewed by being stamped with the date of the day, month and year of such renewal; such stamp to be provided and kept for that purpose in the Central Office and to be impressed upon the summons by the proper officer, upon delivery to him by the plaintiff or his solicitor of a memorandum in the [Form No. 4 in Appendix A, Part I](https://courts.ie/content/originating-summons-appearance#_mon1); and a summons so renewed shall remain in force and be available to prevent the operation of any statute whereby a time for the commencement of the action may be limited and for all other purposes from the date of the issuing of the original summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'When can an objection be made if it concerns the renewal of a wholesale beer dealer''s licence that expires on the thirtieth day of June each year?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter.","Within ten days after the expiration date of the licence, regardless of the court''s schedule.","At any time during the month of May for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate.","During the regular bi-weekly meetings of the local licensing board, irrespective of the specific month."],"justification":"such objection may be made at the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. (1) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (2) of this rule, where an objection is made under section 4 (6) of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/43/enacted/en/html) to the renewal of - - (a) an on-licence for the sale of intoxicating liquor, - a special restaurant licence granted under Part of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - a licence or licences for the sale of spirits or beer in retail quantities for consumption off the premises where sold, it shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate. (2) Where the objection is made to the renewal of a wholesale beer dealer''s licence or any other off-licence which, by virtue of section 49 of the [Finance (1909-10) Act, 1910](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1910/act/8/enacted/en/html), expires on the thirtieth day of June each year, such objection may be made at the last sitting of the Court for the transaction of summary business in the month of June for the court area wherein the premises to which the objection relates are situate, or at the first available sitting of the Court thereafter.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 80 - Objections to renewal of intoxicating liquor licences, forms of renewal certificate, forms of renewal certificate, recording renewals of licences', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 80.4, Schedule","Form 80.3, Schedule","Form 80.5, Schedule","Form 80.4, Schedule"],"justification":"The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the [Form 80.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Forms of renewal certificate* 8. The certificate to be issued for the renewal of a six-day licence or an early closing licence shall be in the [Form 80.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd6235f8-cad9-4013-9d5e-6b9391b7f4ed/Certificate for renewal of licence - Licensing Acts, 1833 to 1988 - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 80.4.docx/docx/1). Where a certificate for renewal is granted pursuant to section 30 (1) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1960/act/18/enacted/en/html) such certificate shall be in the [Form 77.5 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74d0600a-79ad-4693-b77c-5bbc2efb3a95/Certificate for renewal of licence - Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1960 section 30 (1) - Courts (No. 2) Act, 1986 No. 77.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 81 - Annual licensing court', 'Court Rules', 'What type of court holds the Annual Licensing Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["County Court","Circuit Court","Supreme Court","The District Court"],"justification":"Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 81 - Annual licensing court - Court: District 1. A Judge of the District Court shall hold a court, to be known as the Annual Licensing Court, in each court area in the Judge''s district on the day of the last sitting of the Court for that court area for the transaction of the business of the Court exercising its summary jurisdiction held in the month of September each year. 2. Every such Annual Licensing Court shall hear and determine - all such applications made to it for certificates, licenses, orders, or renewals thereof, and objections to the grant or renewal of such certificates, licences or orders, as are provided for in [Orders 63]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-63-District-Auctioneers-and-house-agents) to [89]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-89-District-Wildlife) of these [Rules]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]C07733B1-CAA0-4F89-8468-D48198AE2F9F?page 3#targetSearch) and are required to be made at the Annual Licensing Court; - any other application, objection or other matter which is required by statute or by Rules of Court to be made or brought at that court; and the Judge may adjourn any such court from time to time as circumstances may deem it necessary. 3. For the purposes of this Order the day of the last sitting of the Court in the month of September in the Dublin Metropolitan District shall be that sitting held on the last Thursday in that month each year.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 82 - Register of licences', 'Court Rules', 'When was Order 82 Rule 3 inserted and when did it become effective?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 82 Rule 3 was inserted by S.I. 162 of 2007 and became effective on 9 May 2007.","Order 82 Rule 3 was inserted by S.I. 162 of 2006 and became effective on 9 June 2006.","Order 82 Rule 3 was inserted by S.I. 162 of 2006 and became effective on 9 May 2006.","Order 82 Rule 3 was inserted by S.I. 162 of 2005 and became effective on 9 May 2005."],"justification":"[1] Order 82 rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/162/made/en/print?q 162\u0026years 2006), effective 9 May 2006"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of particulars of licensed premises* 2. Every holder of such licence shall, within ten days after having obtained same, deliver or cause to be delivered to the Clerk a note in writing ([Form 82.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f3b3e1c3-089d-43ee-8bf6-5acff952358e/Notice describing licensed premises No. 82.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule signed by the holder, setting forth the holders full name and address and description and location of the house or premises in which intoxicating liquors are licensed to be sold and the full name and address of the owner of the said house or premises in accordance with the provisions of section 10 of the [Licensing (Ireland) Act, 1833](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1833/act/68/enacted/en/print.html), as amended. 3.[1] Where a temporary closure order is made pursuant to section 36A(2) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) , the order shall be in the [Form 82.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec1c77e6-8976-4a4f-a108-36851c4e44d5/Temporary Closure Order - Intoxicating Liquor Act 1988 No. 82.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 82 rule 3 inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2006), effective 9 May 2006'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 83 pertain to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Student disciplinary actions","Allocation of school facilities for events","Conduct of sports tournaments","Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations"],"justification":"# Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''registered club''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A club holding a certificate of registration in force at the time.","A club that is recognized only through informal agreements among its members.","A club that operates without any form of legal recognition or documentation.","A club that has been officially banned by local authorities."],"justification":"\"**registered club**\" means a club holding a certificate of registration in force at the time."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions 1.[1] In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Registration of Clubs (Ireland) Act, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (4 Edw. 7. 9); "**the Act of 1924**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor (General) Act, 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html) (No. 62 of 1924); "**the Act of 1927**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (No. 15 of 1927); "**the Act of 1962**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1962](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1962); "**the Act of 1988**" means the [Intoxicating Liquor Act, 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 1988); "**licensing year"** means a period of twelve months ending on the thirtieth day of September in any year; "**registered club**" means a club holding a certificate of registration in force at the time. “**the Act of 2000**” means the [Equal Status Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html) (No. 8 of 2000); “**Determination Order**” means an Order made under sub-section (6) or sub-section (15) of section 8 of the [Act of 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)[.](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/8/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What role does the Registrar of Clubs play in relation to the court area where club premises are located?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Cleaner for the court area","Security guard for the court area","Judge for the court area","Clerk for the court area"],"justification":"Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Registrar of Clubs* 2. (1) For the purposes of the Act the Registrar of Clubs (otherwise referred to herein as the registrar) Shall be the Clerk for the court area wherein the club premises concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'How does the registrar notify the superintendent of the Garda Síochána about the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through a verbal communication as stated in clause 5.","As specified in article 3 of the Garda Síochána Act 2014.","In like manner as prescribed in rule 4 (6) hereof.","In accordance with section 7 of the same regulation."],"justification":"in like manner as prescribed in rule 4 (6) hereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to notify Garda Supt.* 3. (1) Where the secretary of a club desiring an original certificate of registration lodges with the registrar, pursuant to subsection (1) of section 2 of the Act, the documents mentioned in that subsection, the registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána in like manner as prescribed in rule 4 (6) hereof in the case of an application for the renewal of such a certificate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What additional items does the registrar send along with the documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Any confirmation letter from the applicant and any digital copies of the signed documents.","Any notice of approval for the grant of the certificate and any legal documents related to the application process.","Any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application.","Any proof of payment for the application fees and any biometric data provided by the applicant."],"justification":"together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- to transmit file to Registrar* (2) After the expiration of ten days from the date of the said lodgment the registrar shall transmit the documents to the appropriate County Registrar, together with any notice of objection to the grant of the certificate and any newspaper containing notice of the application, which were lodged with him or her.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What must be confirmed on the application form regarding fees?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The application form must include a credit card authorization form attached to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee.","The application form must have an electronic signature confirming the applicant''s agreement to pay the court fee.","The application form must be signed by a judge to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee.","The application form must be stamped to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee."],"justification":"The application form shall be stamped to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee (if any) required by law to be paid in respect of such application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Documents to accompany application* (3) Such application for renewal shall be accompanied by— - (a) two copies of the rules of the club, - a list containing the names and addresses of the officials and committee of management or governing body and the names of the members, and - a certificate in the [Form 83.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f990d829-5435-4e71-8e05-2a7d0cb17fdd/Certificate to accompany application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.2.docx/docx/1), signed by two Peace Commissioners for the district in which the club premises are situated, and where such premises are not owned by the club, the certificate shall be signed by the owner of such premises or, where the owner is under any legal disability, by the legal representative of the owner. The application form shall be stamped to confirm payment of the appropriate court fee (if any) required by law to be paid in respect of such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What sections of which acts must a club''s rules comply with to be eligible for registration?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Section 4 of the Act (amended by section 42 of the Act of 1988) and section 56 of the Act of 1927 (as substituted by section 26 of the Act of 1988)","Section 3 of the Act (amended by section 41 of the Act of 1988) and section 55 of the Act of 1927 (as substituted by section 25 of the Act of 1988)","Section 5 of the Act (amended by section 43 of the Act of 1988) and section 57 of the Act of 1927 (as substituted by section 27 of the Act of 1988)","Section 4 of the Act (amended by section 40 of the Act of 1988) and section 54 of the Act of 1927 (as substituted by section 24 of the Act of 1988)"],"justification":"- section 4 of the Act, as amended by section 42 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), and - section 56 (which relates to prohibited hours for the supplying for consumption on club premises of excisable liquor) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 26 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html))."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Club rules qualifying for registration* (4) In order that a club may be eligible to be registered under the [Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1904/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) to 1988 the rules of the club shall comply with the requirements of - section 4 of the Act, as amended by section 42 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), and - section 56 (which relates to prohibited hours for the supplying for consumption on club premises of excisable liquor) of the [Act of 1927](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1927/act/15/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 26 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html)).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What is the number of the Fire Services Act mentioned?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["No. 30 of 1981","No. 31 of 1981","No. 29 of 1981","No. 30 of 1980"],"justification":"(No. 30 of 1981)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the [Fire Services Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) (No. 30 of 1981) shall apply to every such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What document does the registrar send to the Garda Superintendent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Confirmation of receipt of payment for the certificate of registration in Form 83.3, Schedule","Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration in Form 83.3, Schedule","Notice of application for a driving license in Form 83.3, Schedule","Acknowledgement of receipt of the renewal request for the vehicle registration in Form 83.3, Schedule"],"justification":"The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12f2f2e8-bfb6-48b7-a784-8509ed14ce18/Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.3.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Registrar to notify Garda Supt.* (6) The registrar shall forthwith give notice of such application, in the [Form 83.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12f2f2e8-bfb6-48b7-a784-8509ed14ce18/Notice of lodgment of application for (renewal of) certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts 1904 to 1988 No. 83.3.docx/docx/1), together with a copy of the rules of the club, to the superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the Garda district in which the club, the subject of the application, is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'Who can lodge objections to the grant of a certificate?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Minister for Justice and non-residents of the parish where the club premises are located.","Any member of the local council and visitors to the club premises.","The local sheriff and individuals who have been denied membership in the club.","The superintendent of the Garda Síochána and any person resident in the parish where the club premises are located."],"justification":"It shall be competent for the superintendent of the Garda Síochána on receiving notice of an application given as aforesaid, and for any person resident in the parish in which the club premises are situated, to lodge objections to the grant of the certificate on any of the grounds of objection specified in the Act, and it shall be competent for any person to lodge objections to the renewal of the certificate on any such grounds."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Objections to grant or renewal of certificate* 7.(1) It shall be competent for the superintendent of the Garda Síochána on receiving notice of an application given as aforesaid, and for any person resident in the parish in which the club premises are situated, to lodge objections to the grant of the certificate on any of the grounds of objection specified in the Act, and it shall be competent for any person to lodge objections to the renewal of the certificate on any such grounds. (2)[2] The Court shall not consider any objection to the renewal of a certificate unless it is taken upon one or more of the grounds specified in - section 5 of the Act, as amended by section 46 of the [Act of 1988](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1988/act/16/enacted/en/html), or - section 24(2) of the [Act of 1924](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1924/act/62/enacted/en/html), or - section 19(10) of the [Intoxicating Liquor Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/31/enacted/en/html)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'In what form is the certificate of registration issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 84.4, Schedule","Form 83.3, Schedule","Form 83.4, Schedule","Form 83.5, Schedule"],"justification":"in the [Form 83.4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *When granted registrar to record particulars and issue certificate* (5) If, upon hearing the application and the objection, the Court grants the application, the Registrar of Clubs shall make the entries required by the Act in the register of clubs and thereupon shall issue to the applicant a certificate of registration in the [Form 83.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c2d9037-01ce-48e4-8279-6cf871fc628e/Certificate of registration - Registration of Clubs Acts, 1904 to 1988 No. 83.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'For how long can the current certificate remain in force beyond the initial three months?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Court may extend the time for a further period not exceeding three months.","The Court may extend the time for a further period not exceeding one year.","The certificate automatically renews after three months without the need for any extension.","The certificate can remain in force indefinitely as long as it is used within the jurisdiction."],"justification":"unless the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- extension pending Court''s decision* (2) Notwithstanding the provisions of the Act as to the duration of certifcates, where a renewal has been applied for the current certificate shall remain in force pending the final decision of the Court, but not exceeding three months unless the Court shall in its discretion extend such time to a further period not exceeding three months.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["*Club holiday schedules — notice to Revenue Commissioners*","*Annual club membership fees update — notice to members*","*New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners*","*New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to local authorities*"],"justification":"*New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *New clubs, clubs ceasing to be registered — notice to Revenue Commissioners* 9. [3] # **Club Authorisations**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 83 - Registration of clubs and granting of club authorisations', 'Court Rules', 'What must also be done simultaneously when serving notice on the superintendent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the notice must be sent to each member of the club via email.","A copy of the notice must be handed over to the club treasurer.","A copy of the notice must be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs","A copy of the notice must be posted on the club''s official website."],"justification":"and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the superintendent of the Garda Síochana within whose district the club premises are situated at least forty-eight hours prior to the date of hearing of the application, and a copy thereof shall at the same time be lodged with the Registrar of Clubs.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the order concerning child care?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 92: Adult Care","Order 83: Youth Services","Order 84: Child Care","Order 79: Child Education"],"justification":"**Order 84: Child Care******[1]****"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84 - Child care - Court: District # **Order 84: Child Care******[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Who is responsible for serving the care order on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["the applicant","the police","the court","the social worker"],"justification":"the applicant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* (2) A care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said Order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant issued under section 35 of the Act for executing a care order be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.43 Schedule","Form 84.43 Schedule","Form 84.44 Schedule","Form 84.42 Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- warrant* (3) A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (and as prescribed in Rule 27 hereof) for the purpose of executing a care order shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used to notify the respondent of an application to extend a care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 84.20","Form 84.15","Form 84.1","Form 84.16"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 84.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5872f203-b05b-4125-8109-144cd2afcb45/Notice of application to extend the operation of a care order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Extension of Care Order* 11. An application under section 18 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to extend the operation of a care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5872f203-b05b-4125-8109-144cd2afcb45/Notice of application to extend the operation of a care order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.16.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ec02e236-ea2e-468f-950e-c2d7ca448531/Order extending the operation of a care order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.17.docx/docx/1) Schedule and may, where appropriate, be added to or endorsed on the care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'Who is responsible for serving the supervision order on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["the applicant","the court clerk","the judge","the police"],"justification":"the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order* 12.[13] Where, on an application for a care order, the Court makes a supervision order (as provided for in section 18 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 84.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1) and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least two days prior","three hours before the hearing","on the same day as the hearing","at least one day prior"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions pending Care Order* 13.[14] An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the care and custody of a child pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2976462c-51fd-494a-98ba-43cb56c20e3f/Notice of application for court''s directions (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.19.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. the Agency, the parent having custody of the child, the person acting in loco parentis, as appropriate. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8cce50fe-fc88-440a-8815-a6a8e9e245ed/Directions under section 18 (6) of the Act (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.20.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served on each party and any other person affected directly by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the court order granting a supervision order be issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 85.33","Form 84.21","Form 84.11","Form 84.22"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting an application for a supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 18* 14.[15] (1) An application under section 18(6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1) Schedule at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) The order of the Court granting an application for a supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given before an application to vary or discharge a contribution order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["at least three days","at least fourteen days","at least seven days","at least twenty-one days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Contribution by parent* 15. (1)[16] Where, in addition to making a care order, the Court makes an order under section 18 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requiring the parent or parents of a child to contribute towards his or her maintenance, such contribution order shall be in the [Form 84.23](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e66422b-7a44-4728-b339-805474934216/Contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (7) No. 84.23.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant Agency shall cause the said order to be served upon the said parent or parents. (2) An application under section 18 (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to vary or discharge a contribution order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.24](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e63e3346-dd89-4893-9552-ba87fec2e54f/Notice of application to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.24.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2e744c31-76ee-4c72-9c16-8bf9d1ce9f1e/Order to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.25.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon the parent required to contribute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice and affidavits be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least seven days","at least five days","at least three days","at least ten days"],"justification":"served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 19* 16.[17] (1) An application by the Agency under section 19(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order with respect to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58f9df8-d7bb-46c6-aaf3-14b284fb02ac/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 19 (1) No. 84.26.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent or respondents, i.e. the parents of the child or, as the case may be, the parent having custody of the child or a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) A supervision order made on an application under this rule shall be in the [Form 84.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/816ce2e4-77ad-43db-817a-e63cacd726bd/Supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served upon the respondent Agency before an application for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 84.28","Form 84.3","Form 101","Form 76.5"],"justification":"An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4cc90cc9-12ce-4a2d-b140-a425fa78ecb1/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.28.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent Agency at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Directions as to visits* 17.[18] An application under section 19 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions as to the manner in which a child is to be visited shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.28](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4cc90cc9-12ce-4a2d-b140-a425fa78ecb1/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.28.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent Agency at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.29](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42c17ab7-a5fb-4119-ada3-23357b7afbd1/Directions under section 19 (3) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.29.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance should the notice be served before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least three days","at least fourteen days","at least one day","at least seven days"],"justification":"at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Further directions* 18.[19] An application by the Agency under section 19 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), made during the currency of a supervision order, for the Court''s directions as to the care of the child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.30](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cd859c3-206b-422e-ad88-60cab7dc7e53/Notice of application for directions (under section 19 (4) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.30.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.31](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dec75767-2057-4357-9d15-8d2a87ae79ec/Directions under section 19 (4) of the Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.31.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the Clerk use to notify the Agency when the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to investigate a child''s circumstances?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 85.32","Form 84.31","Form 84.32","Form 84.23"],"justification":"the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule of the Courts decision"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Investigations under section 20 (1)* 19. (1)[20] Where, under section 20(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), the Court adjourns proceedings and directs the Agency to undertake an investigation of a child’s circumstances, if the Agency is not a party to those proceedings, the Clerk must as soon as possible notify the Agency (in the [Form 84.32](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24963f9e-0255-436a-ac6d-3f27d84df79d/Notice of adjournment of proceedings and of direction to health board - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.32.docx/docx/1) Schedule of the Courts decision (2)[21] Where, upon so adjourning, the Court gives directions under section 20 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) as to the care and custody of the child or makes a supervision order in respect of the child pending the outcome of the investigation by the Agency — - (a) an order of the Court giving such directions shall be in the [Form 84.33](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/98194548-8c79-4317-bb3a-895806c3ad6f/Directions under section 20 (2) of the Act (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.33.docx/docx/1) Schedule - any such supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.34](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/74b34a98-0052-4630-aee1-4e9fc7d5f25f/Supervision order (pending outcome of investigation by health board) - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.34.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the order shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form of notice is required before an application to vary or discharge a care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 84.35, 84.36, or 84.37 Schedule","Form 85.35, 85.36, or 85.37 Schedule","Form 84.10, 84.20, or 84.25 Schedule","Form 90.35, 90.36, or 90.37 Schedule"],"justification":"in the Form [84.35](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/311c2145-a1b2-4b1d-aff5-e7931afb05f6/Notice of application to vary - discharge - a care order - a condition - direction attaching to a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.35.docx/docx/1), [84.36](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cbf019b4-13dc-446b-a2ce-f0c5fdb142fc/Notice of application to discharge a care order and make a supervision order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.36.docx/docx/1) or [84.37](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c89980b-801b-4ed2-8be2-b4b0fdbe37fb/Notice of application to - vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.37.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, upon the respondent or respondents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary or discharge care order* 20. An application under section 22 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) - - (a) to vary or discharge a care order or any condition or direction attaching to such order or to discharge the care order and make a supervision order, or - to vary or discharge a supervision order or any condition or direction attaching to such order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [84.35](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/311c2145-a1b2-4b1d-aff5-e7931afb05f6/Notice of application to vary - discharge - a care order - a condition - direction attaching to a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.35.docx/docx/1), [84.36](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cbf019b4-13dc-446b-a2ce-f0c5fdb142fc/Notice of application to discharge a care order and make a supervision order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.36.docx/docx/1) or [84.37](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c89980b-801b-4ed2-8be2-b4b0fdbe37fb/Notice of application to - vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.37.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting such application shall be in the Form [84.38](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b289db7-aeac-4228-97cb-6e927d670bd2/Order to - vary - discharge a care order a - condition - direction attaching to a care order No. 84.38.docx/docx/1), [84.39](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dcdacbc9-6402-4e42-afaa-b33abaf7d6e9/Supervision order (made on discharging a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.39.docx/docx/1) or [84.40](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f06f7cc7-ec92-4f5a-a611-f261f99e5a03/Order to vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order No. 84.40.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to an order when an appeal is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The operation of the order may be stayed by the court or the court to which the appeal is brought.","The order is immediately enforced more strictly pending the outcome of the appeal.","The order is automatically overturned without any further action.","The order is transferred to a different jurisdiction for reevaluation."],"justification":"An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA (inserted by section 16 of the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the Court making the determination."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeals* 21.[22] An appeal from an order made by the Court under Part or Part IVA (inserted by section 16 of the [Act of 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall, if the Court or the Court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the Court making the determination. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an application by the Agency for a special care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form","Form","Form 84.40A","Form"],"justification":"An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6dd96b5-8fd8-419b-b09a-213846cc5672/Notice Of Application For A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part A of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21A.[23] (1)[24] An application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40A](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6dd96b5-8fd8-419b-b09a-213846cc5672/Notice Of Application For A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. A special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77f9218a-5954-49ef-832d-9234ef175763/Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section 23 (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act, 2001) No. 84.40B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order. (2)[25] An application by the Agency under section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.40C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64d2f8b3-2884-4b70-bd86-bb11d4fa0902/Notice Of Application For Extension Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (4) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40C.docx/docx/1), Schedule An order granting such an extension shall be in the [Form 84.40D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/afa0b2f2-0c17-407b-a0cb-6a817bbf0599/Order Extending The Period Of Validity Of A Special Care Order No. 84.40D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the special care order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How much time before the hearing must a notice be served when applying for an interim special care order under section', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least two days","at least four hours","at least one day","at least three days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3)[26] An application by the Agency under section (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.40E](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9f0d1129-cb46-4917-ac57-89bdb646649e/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (5) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40E.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4)[27] Except in a case where the Judge otherwise directs under Section (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), an application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40F](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d86d6a49-65e6-4061-8689-6c71bd0589a7/Notice Of Application For An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40F.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40G](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c04874eb-e4c8-4b44-9e10-7ceb689c6f83/Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40G.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used for an order extending the period of an interim special care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.40I](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa975463-42d1-4b6c-8dbe-94342380d8cc/Order Extending The Period Of An Interim Special Care Order No. 84.40I.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the interim special care order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5)[28] An application by a person specified in section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim special care order shall, except where the Judge has otherwise directed under section (3), be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent referred to in sub-rule (4) hereof (or, as the case may be, on the Agency) of a notice in the [Form 84.40H](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6f6558fd-fb78-44c1-89ba-19d4a56586a9/Notice Of Application For An Extension Of An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40H.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.40I](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa975463-42d1-4b6c-8dbe-94342380d8cc/Order Extending The Period Of An Interim Special Care Order No. 84.40I.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the interim special care order. (6) An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for the Court’s directions pending the determination of an application for a special care order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 13 of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2976462c-51fd-494a-98ba-43cb56c20e3f/Notice of application for court''s directions (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.20](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8cce50fe-fc88-440a-8815-a6a8e9e245ed/Directions under section 18 (6) of the Act (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an application for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a special care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.10","Form 84.21","Form 84.20","Form 85.30"],"justification":"Such application shall be in the [Form 84.21](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(7) An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a special care order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 14 of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.21](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. (8)[29] Where, in addition to making a special care order, the Court makes an order under section 18 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requiring the parent or parents of the child to contribute towards his or her maintenance, such contribution order shall be in the [Form 84.23](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0e66422b-7a44-4728-b339-805474934216/Contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (7) No. 84.23.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served by the Agency upon the said parent or parents. (9) An application under section 18 (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section (8) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) to vary or discharge a contribution order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 15(2) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.24](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e63e3346-dd89-4893-9552-ba87fec2e54f/Notice of application to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.24.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.25](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2e744c31-76ee-4c72-9c16-8bf9d1ce9f1e/Order to vary - discharge a contribution order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (8) No. 84.25.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon the parent required to contribute.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application for directions under section 13(7)(a) be made in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 84.7","Form 84","Form 84.5","Form 84.6"],"justification":"Such application shall be in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(11) An application under section 13 (7)(a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for directions shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(1) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0b23edb0-d132-4e8f-9961-0bf79da7c9ac/Notice Of Application For Directions (under section 13 (7) (A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/42604cef-bdb7-4a9b-9522-2c19365badcc/Directions Under Section 13 (7) (A) Of The Act - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. (12) An application under section 13 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to interim special care orders by section (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) to vary or discharge a direction shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 7(2) of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/504569e1-b219-421e-a712-82c521000ce9/Notice of application to vary - discharge a direction (under section (7) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.8.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75c7d42c-9628-4bc7-98c6-b8f06e4fde43/Order To vary - discharge a direction (under section 13(7)(A) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'To whom should an application for a warrant under section of the 1991 Act be directed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing.","A police officer in charge of the precinct where the child is believed to reside.","A member of the local council assigned to the district where the child is believed to reside.","The Director of Social Services for the region where the child is believed to reside."],"justification":"An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part of the Act (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001)** 21B.[31](1)[32]An application for the issue of a warrant under section (2) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to and sitting in the District Court District wherein are situated the premises in which it is believed the child may be residing. Such application shall be by the information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.40P](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/053971f0-cf2b-4287-a636-717f58040a91/Information For Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, Section (2) (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40P.docx/docx/1) of an authorised officer appointed by the Agency under section (1) of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). A warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 84.40Q](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9cae8d1b-6479-4637-8e1a-398a22b85b12/Warrant To Inspect Premises - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40Q.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served before an application for an order under section of the Act of 1991?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application for an order under section of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the person mentioned in paragraphs (a) and of section of the said Act of a notice in the [Form 84.40R](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5beab9f5-7b74-48f5-84d0-e4a9414e478e/Notice Of Application For Order In Respect Of Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40R.docx/docx/1) , Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) An application for an order under section of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the person mentioned in paragraphs (a) and of section of the said Act of a notice in the [Form 84.40R](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5beab9f5-7b74-48f5-84d0-e4a9414e478e/Notice Of Application For Order In Respect Of Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40R.docx/docx/1) , Schedule Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section such order shall be in the [Form 84.40S](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/755f0f12-1289-498c-a6ff-dd860ea0f9af/Order To Terminate Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, Section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40S.docx/docx/1), Schedule Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph or paragraph of section such order shall be (as the case may be) in the [Form 84.4](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1), [84.11](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1), [84.15](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) or [84.18](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), modified as appropriate ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Regulations and guidelines under Part of the Act","Provisions related to enforcement under Part of the Act","Applications etc. under Part III of the Act","Applications etc. under Part of the Act"],"justification":"**Applications etc. under Part of the Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications etc. under Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served when applying for an order requesting the preparation of a report?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least two days","five days","at least one day","three days"],"justification":"at least two days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Requests for reports* 22. (1) Where, other than during the hearing of the proceedings, application is made by any of the parties for an order under section 27 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) requesting the preparation of a report, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.41](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c60c7466-369d-411f-9720-7837c6c18cda/Notice of application for an order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991, section 27 No. 84.41.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the other party or parties. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.42](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7085b8a3-c9e9-47f5-8b7a-c45b3bab366a/Order requesting the preparation of a report - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.42.docx/docx/1)Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the person nominated therein to prepare the report. (2) When the report has been prepared it shall be lodged with the Clerk. A copy of the report shall be made available by the applicant to the counsel or solicitor representing each party or, if any party is not so represented, to that party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant issued under section 35 of the Act to execute an interim care order or a care order take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.43 Schedule A","Form 84.43 Schedule","Form 84.41 Schedule","Form 84.42 Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Warrant to execute care order* 24.[33] A warrant issued under section 35 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to execute an interim care order or a care order made under Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be placed or maintained in the care of the Agency shall be in the [Form 84.43](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/60300e6b-48cf-43e0-b907-78d77d0236d9/Warrant to execute an interim care order - a care order - a special care order - an interim special care order - Child Care Act 1991 section 35 No. 84.43.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served on the Agency before an application for an order regarding access to a child is heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 98.55","Form 102.33","Form 84.44","Form 76.12"],"justification":"An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.44](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c2f2b3-2008-4e35-9ffc-b8c6367f1007/Notice of application for an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37(2) No. 84.44.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Access to child* 25. (1)[34] An application under section 37 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order regarding access to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.44](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c2f2b3-2008-4e35-9ffc-b8c6367f1007/Notice of application for an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37(2) No. 84.44.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the Agency at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.45](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4857a91e-c87b-4d48-a6a4-1c80bd2fe56b/Order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.45.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for a notice when varying or discharging an access order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 84.39","Form 84.52","Form 84.46","Form 84.48"],"justification":"Form 84.46"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *Vary access* (2)[35] An application under the said section 37 (2) to vary or discharge an order to which paragraph (1) hereof relates shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.46](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b9084419-d4dd-4ed4-b802-b29e1cbcbcc1/Notice of application to vary - discharge an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.46.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents, i.e. the Agency, the parents, the persons mentioned in section 37 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), as appropriate. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.47](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e1d7af80-6b81-4452-9f08-9db3d682fb6d/Order to vary - discharge an order regarding access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.47.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How much time before the hearing must the notice be served on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least two days","at least three days","at least twenty-four hours","at least one day"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Authority to refuse access* 26.[36] (1) An application by the Agency under section 37 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising it to refuse access to a child in its care shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.48](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eea6cf4d-32f5-49a2-afa9-beddc132f546/Notice of application for an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.48.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent (the person against whom the order is sought). Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.49](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e4dff991-6a51-4fde-bd02-5928eb75e8c1/Order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 37 (3) (A) No. 84.49.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent. (2) An application under the said section 37 (3) to vary or discharge an order to which paragraph (1) hereof relates shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.50](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ef82cf9b-2bb9-4868-9f89-7e32bceb0b75/Notice of application to vary - discharge an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child - Child Care Act, 1991 37 (3) No. 84.50.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.51](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/130a7ae7-0ff0-44d7-845f-e5f421e933fd/Order to vary - discharge an order authorising refusal to allow access to a child No. 84.51.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing date for an application under section 43(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least two days prior","at least five days prior","at least one day prior","at least three days prior"],"justification":"Such notice must be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order to deliver up child to the Child and Family Agency — 27.[37] An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b7e851aa-60c6-4ef7-9d6b-f2dc9325bddc/Notice of application for an order that child be delivered up to custody of the health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.52.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent. Such notice must be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 84.53](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8fb48c60-ed36-4cc6-83bf-9a8934605663/Order that child be delivered up to custody of health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.53.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Agency must cause the said order to be served on the respondent 27A.[38] (1) An application for an order under section 43A of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by a foster parent or relative with whom the child has been placed shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant of a notice in the [Form 84.53A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/765bd7e6-e9a9-44c9-ab01-4fea44d17853/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 Of The Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the Agency. A copy of the notice shall, where section 43A(2)(d)(ii) applies, be served by the Agency on the parent having custody of the child at the relevant time or a person (other than the applicant) acting in loco parentis to the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if written consent is not appended or produced at the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The hearing will be automatically dismissed.","Such consent shall be proved by other means as the court considers appropriate.","The case will be transferred to a different jurisdiction.","The court will impose sanctions on the parties involved."],"justification":"where such consent in writing is not so appended or produced, such consent shall, where required, be proved by such other means as the court considers appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) The consent of the Agency under section 43A(2)(c) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order shall be in writing and the original consent shall be appended to the original notice of application. Where a consent has been obtained under section 43A(2)(d)(i) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) to the granting of the order the original of such consent, if in writing, shall be appended to the original notice of application or produced at the hearing of the application, and where such consent in writing is not so appended or produced, such consent shall, where required, be proved by such other means as the court considers appropriate. (3) A copy of the notice of application shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50548b4b-29c2-4194-bb65-c3deb5f4f4ad/Order under section 43A of the Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53B.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when applying to vary or discharge an order made under section 43A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall, to the extent possible, be served upon each of the persons referred to in section 43B(1)(a) to of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6cf2c6b-7f10-49ae-b5bf-a33b0be2f3d4/Order Varying - Discharging - A Condition Restriction - Attaching To - An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each of the respondents and upon any other person directly affected by the Order'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the applicant use when laying information before the Judge for an order under section 46(3)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 84.54","Form 90.1","Form 46.3","Form 84.53"],"justification":"the applicant shall lay information before the Judge on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a12d36a7-7320-4233-90a5-ac23add07eaa/Information (under section 46 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.54.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Information - (3)* 28. Where an order is sought under section 46 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency, the applicant shall lay information before the Judge on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a12d36a7-7320-4233-90a5-ac23add07eaa/Information (under section 46 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.54.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Judge may, on foot of such information, sign and issue a summons in the [Form 84.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1)[.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1) Schedule Such summons shall be served upon the respondent at least two days prior to the return date thereof. Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.56](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/445956b7-324f-4cb1-8f81-f4aa02343f39/Order That Child Be Delivered Up To Custody Of Health Board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 46(3) No. 84.56.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an application for a search warrant under section 46(6) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 84.6","Form 84.5","Form 85.57","Form 84.57"],"justification":"in the [Form 84.57.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/31012ae6-9eb4-42a4-9550-ffdb0ee99812/Information (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.57.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Search warrant* 29. An application under section 46 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a search warrant shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.57.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/31012ae6-9eb4-42a4-9550-ffdb0ee99812/Information (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.57.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.58](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b0f3c5a3-a0a6-44b1-b2b6-716bba960629/Search Warrant (under section 46 (6) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.58 .docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served before an application under section 47?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 84.59","Form 45","Form 84","Form 102"],"justification":"An application under section 47 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.59](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6eab7fc4-745a-4f38-83e6-91030a8e39b1/Notice Of Application For Directions On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 47 No. 84.59.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Direction under 47* 30.(1) An application under section 47 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for the Court''s directions on a question affecting the welfare of a child in the care of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.59](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6eab7fc4-745a-4f38-83e6-91030a8e39b1/Notice Of Application For Directions On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 section 47 No. 84.59.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.60](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e878cfde-21b5-490d-b06c-977472a63db7/Order On Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child (under section 47 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.60.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when applying to vary or discharge an order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.55","Form 84.61","Form 84.59","Form 84.72"],"justification":"Form 84.61"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- variation or discharge* (2) An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64e61fc5-3791-4d17-9ba7-91bbbf674fec/Notice Of Application To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.61.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.62](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75f7dce1-80fb-4075-b4f8-9ff125d0dd85/Order To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction No. 84.62.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant issued by a judge for entering and inspecting premises where a pre-school service is provided be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.54","Form 84.64.","Form 90.12","Form 78.36"],"justification":"Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.64.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1aef1076-3f97-4672-b249-22975bdaac45/Warrant To Enter And Inspect Premises - Child Care Act, 1991 section 55 (2) No. 84.64.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Pre-School service — warrant* (2) An application under section 55 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter and inspect premises in which a pre-school service is being carried on shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.63.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b5d4b0da-c0bb-426c-9589-c2b23b73ce1e/Information (under section 55 (2) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.63.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.64.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1aef1076-3f97-4672-b249-22975bdaac45/Warrant To Enter And Inspect Premises - Child Care Act, 1991 section 55 (2) No. 84.64.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Proceedings under Part VIII of the Act","Provisions under Part VII of the Regulation","Chapters related to Part VIII of the Agreement","Sections concerning Part of the Act"],"justification":"**Proceedings under Part VIII of the Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Proceedings under Part VIII of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How many days prior to the hearing must the notice be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least three days","at least five days","at least ten days","at least seven days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Children''s residential centre* 32. An appeal to the Court under section 62 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by the registered proprietor or, as the case may be, the person intending to be the registered proprietor of a children''s residential centre, against a decision, specified in subsection (1) of that section, of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.65](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19803d89-7193-4e0e-95fc-0cd8d9dcb550/Notice Of Appeal (under section 62 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.65.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the Agency. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the appeal. The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 84.66](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/94a0ecd6-7d38-4813-8338-0dc9eae3eaad/Order Of Appeal - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.66.docx/docx/1). Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Directives outlined in Section 34 of the Act","Regulations detailed in Chapter of the Act","Orders provided for in Part of the Act","Orders provided for in Part of the Act"],"justification":"**Orders provided for in Part of the Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Orders provided for in Part of the Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the act mentioned?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["School Attendance Act","Student Behavior Policy","Learning Enhancement Law","Education Reform Act"],"justification":"*School Attendance Act*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *School Attendance Act*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in Order 84A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Civil Procedure Act 2001","The Family Law Act 2001","The Criminal Procedure Act 2001","The Mental Health Act 2001"],"justification":"“**the Act**” means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001 - Court: District # Order 84A: Mental Health Act **[1]** 1. (1) In this Order – “**the Act**” means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html). (2) The provisions of rules 2, 3 and 4 of [Order 84]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-84-District-Child-care) of these Rules shall apply, mutatis mutandis, to proceedings to which this Order applies. 2. (1). Save where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) or in a case to which section 25(7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, an application under section 25(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising the detention of a child in an approved centre shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district court district in which the child resides or is for the time being to be found at a sitting of the Court for the said District. Save in a case to which section 25(7) of the Act applies, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84A.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/70390850-5689-4ac6-9fef-390b0d0ec1af/Notice of application for order authorising detention in an approved centre. No. 84A.1.docx/docx/1) upon the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child. Such notice shall be served at least ten days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), such notice shall be served as promptly as reasonably possible and prior to the hearing of the application at a sitting of the Court held within the time specified in section 23(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), and may be served by delivering a copy of the notice to the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'Under what circumstances can an application under section 25 of the Act be made parte?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Where the Judge is satisfied that the matter does not require urgent attention","Where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires","Where the applicant has provided insufficient notice to the opposing party","Where the Judge is satisfied that the applicant has a higher social status"],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '8. Notwithstanding any of the preceding rules, where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - - (a) be made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the appropriate notice of application duly completed; - in the case of a child to whom section 23 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, be heard, and an order made thereon, elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court. [1] Order 84A inserted by [S.I. 97 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/97/made/en/print?q 97&years 2007), effective 2 April 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'What court is associated with Order 85 - Water disconnection rules?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["County Court","High Court","District Court","Magistrates'' Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 85 - Water disconnection rules - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of application take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 85.2 Schedule","Form 85.0 Schedule","Form 85.1 Schedule","Form 85.1 Schedule A"],"justification":"Notice of such application shall be in the [Form 85.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24a4ac07-80a9-4a22-8ad7-ae2e0dd9ce0e/Notice Of An Application For An Order Under Section 3 (2) - Local Government (Delimitation Of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995 No. 85.1.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of application* 2. An application by the sanitary authority for an order under section 3 (2) of the [Local Government (Delimitation of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/18/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the supply of water for domestic purposes is provided to the consumer. Notice of such application shall be in the [Form 85.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24a4ac07-80a9-4a22-8ad7-ae2e0dd9ce0e/Notice Of An Application For An Order Under Section 3 (2) - Local Government (Delimitation Of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995 No. 85.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court level for Order 86 - Public dancing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme","District","Magistrates","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 86 - Public dancing - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What is defined as ''public dancing'' in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Performative dancing where individuals dance on a stage or platform while others in the audience watch passively without the opportunity to join in.","Any form of dancing that takes place outdoors in public spaces, regardless of whether participants can join or not.","Dancing that occurs privately within a residence or venue where admission is restricted to invited guests only.","Dancing which is open to the public and in which persons present are entitled to participate actively."],"justification":"\"**public dancing**\" means dancing which is open to the public and in which persons present are entitled to participate actively."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### 1. In this Order "**the Act**" means the [Public Dance Halls Act, 1935](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) (No. 2 of 1935); "**place**" means a building (including part of a building), yard, garden, or other enclosed place, whether roofed or not roofed and whether the enclosure and the roofing (if any) are permanent or temporary; "**public dancing**" means dancing which is open to the public and in which persons present are entitled to participate actively.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a public dancing licence be made if there is no existing licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["To the nearest police station.","Through an online application portal on the national government''s website.","At the local city hall or municipal office.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."],"justification":"An application for a public dancing licence pursuant to section 2 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under section 2* 2. (1) An application for a public dancing licence pursuant to section 2 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of a place for which a licence is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the said court area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within the same week as the hearing date of the application.","At least one month before the date of hearing of the application.","No specific time frame is required, as long as it is served before the hearing.","At least two weeks before the date of hearing of the application."],"justification":"at least one month before the date of hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district, and upon the local authority within whose functional area, is situate the place to which such application relates, at least one month before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'In which newspaper should the notice be published?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Any international newspaper that covers local news.","A newspaper circulating in the district where the place of application is situated.","A newspaper with the highest circulation in the country.","The national online newspaper regardless of the location of the application."],"justification":"in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What is applied to the application under section 24?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["provisions of section 25 of the Fire Services Act, 1981","rules outlined in section 24 of the Health and Safety Regulations, 1981","provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981","regulations set forth in section 24 of the Environmental Protection Act, 1981"],"justification":"The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shall apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A copy of the application form and a receipt of payment for filing fees","A signed affidavit and a list of requested documents","A summary of the case details and witness statements","A copy of the notice of the application, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and a copy of the newspaper."],"justification":"A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice, etc.* (6) A copy of the notice of the application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and a copy of the newspaper, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least seven days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Who must be served with notice of the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which such application relates","The Minister for Justice","The President of Ireland","The Chief Justice of the Supreme Court"],"justification":"Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which such application relates"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notice* (2) Notice of the application shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána within whose district is situate the place to which such application relates and a copy thereof, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least fortyeight hours before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a public dancing licence take if the application is granted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 85.4, Schedule","Form 87.3, Schedule A","Form 86.2, Schedule","Form 86.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2db55c76-fdec-4189-9ea5-e0743d94a77b/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) Where the application is granted the licence shall be in accordance with [Form 86.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2db55c76-fdec-4189-9ea5-e0743d94a77b/Public Dancing Licence - Public Dance Halls Act 1935 No. 86.2.docx/docx/1).'),
