                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice preceding an appeal in these cases?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The respondent or solicitor for the respondent","The judge presiding over the case","The clerk of the court","The appellant or solicitor for the appellant"],"justification":"signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 88.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cd5a422c-0500-4e52-84b7-88a8cd76e4a4/Notice of appeal to the district court - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13 (3) No. 88.5.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a supervision order take when issued by the court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","Form 84.18","Form","Form 84.20"],"justification":"the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 84.18]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order* 12.[13] Where, on an application for a care order, the Court makes a supervision order (as provided for in section 18 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) the order of the Court shall be in the [Form 84.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1) and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used for issuing a notice in an application for a supervision order under section 18(6)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.15","Form 84.21","Form 90.12","Form 84.23"],"justification":"in the [Form 84.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1) Schedule at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 18* 14.[15] (1) An application under section 18(6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order pending the determination of an application for a care order shall, unless made viva voce at the hearing of the latter application, be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c0725b03-512c-4a93-97ac-843418004d7e/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.21.docx/docx/1) Schedule at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) The order of the Court granting an application for a supervision order shall be in the [Form 84.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/487104e7-64f5-47d9-8569-c0b7cc381f57/Supervision order (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 18 (6) No. 84.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice take before an application for a supervision order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form 84.25","Form","Form 84.26"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 84.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58f9df8-d7bb-46c6-aaf3-14b284fb02ac/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 19 (1) No. 84.26.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Supervision Order Under Section 19* 16.[17] (1) An application by the Agency under section 19(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a supervision order with respect to a child shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.26](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a58f9df8-d7bb-46c6-aaf3-14b284fb02ac/Notice of application for a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 19 (1) No. 84.26.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent or respondents, i.e. the parents of the child or, as the case may be, the parent having custody of the child or a person acting in loco parentis. The notice shall be grounded on an affidavit sworn on behalf of the moving party setting out and verifying the grounds of the application. The original affidavit shall be lodged with the Clerk when the notice is issued. The notice and copies of the grounding affidavit and any exhibits shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) A supervision order made on an application under this rule shall be in the [Form 84.27](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/816ce2e4-77ad-43db-817a-e63cacd726bd/Supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.27.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least two weeks","at least fourteen days","at least three days","at least seven days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary or discharge care order* 20. An application under section 22 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) - - (a) to vary or discharge a care order or any condition or direction attaching to such order or to discharge the care order and make a supervision order, or - to vary or discharge a supervision order or any condition or direction attaching to such order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [84.35](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/311c2145-a1b2-4b1d-aff5-e7931afb05f6/Notice of application to vary - discharge - a care order - a condition - direction attaching to a care order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.35.docx/docx/1), [84.36](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/cbf019b4-13dc-446b-a2ce-f0c5fdb142fc/Notice of application to discharge a care order and make a supervision order - Child Care Act 1991 No. 84.36.docx/docx/1) or [84.37](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7c89980b-801b-4ed2-8be2-b4b0fdbe37fb/Notice of application to - vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.37.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, upon the respondent or respondents. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting such application shall be in the Form [84.38](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2b289db7-aeac-4228-97cb-6e927d670bd2/Order to - vary - discharge a care order a - condition - direction attaching to a care order No. 84.38.docx/docx/1), [84.39](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/dcdacbc9-6402-4e42-afaa-b33abaf7d6e9/Supervision order (made on discharging a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.39.docx/docx/1) or [84.40](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f06f7cc7-ec92-4f5a-a611-f261f99e5a03/Order to vary - discharge a supervision order a - condition - direction attaching to a supervision order No. 84.40.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be, and shall be served upon each person directly affected thereby.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served upon the respondent before an application by the Agency under section for an order discharging a special care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application by the Agency under section (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.40E](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9f0d1129-cb46-4917-ac57-89bdb646649e/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (5) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40E.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(3)[26] An application by the Agency under section (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging a special care order shall, except where the Judge otherwise directs, be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent prescribed in sub-rule (1) of a notice in the [Form 84.40E](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9f0d1129-cb46-4917-ac57-89bdb646649e/Notice Of Application For Discharge Of A Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (5) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40E.docx/docx/1), Schedule (4)[27] Except in a case where the Judge otherwise directs under Section (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html), an application by the Agency under section (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an interim special care order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.40F](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d86d6a49-65e6-4061-8689-6c71bd0589a7/Notice Of Application For An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40F.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the respondent, i.e. a parent having custody of the child or, as the case may be, a person acting in loco parentis. Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. An interim special care order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.40G](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c04874eb-e4c8-4b44-9e10-7ceb689c6f83/Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, Section (As Inserted By Section 16 Of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40G.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent and upon any other person directly affected by the Order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used for an application to extend the period of an interim special care order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application by a person specified in section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim special care order shall, except where the Judge has otherwise directed under section (3), be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent referred to in sub-rule (4) hereof (or, as the case may be, on the Agency) of a notice in the [Form 84.40H](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6f6558fd-fb78-44c1-89ba-19d4a56c20e39/Notice Of Application For An Extension Of An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40H.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5)[28] An application by a person specified in section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an extension of the period of an interim special care order shall, except where the Judge has otherwise directed under section (3), be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent referred to in sub-rule (4) hereof (or, as the case may be, on the Agency) of a notice in the [Form 84.40H](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6f6558fd-fb78-44c1-89ba-19d4a56586a9/Notice Of Application For An Extension Of An Interim Special Care Order - Child Care Act 1991, section (2) (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40H.docx/docx/1) Schedule The order granting the extension shall be in the [Form 84.40I](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aa975463-42d1-4b6c-8dbe-94342380d8cc/Order Extending The Period Of An Interim Special Care Order No. 84.40I.docx/docx/1), Schedule and may be endorsed upon the interim special care order. (6) An application under section 18 (6) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) (as applied to special care orders by section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html)) for the Court’s directions pending the determination of an application for a special care order shall be made in the manner prescribed by rule 13 of this Order. Such application shall be in the [Form 84.19](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2976462c-51fd-494a-98ba-43cb56c20e3f/Notice of application for court''s directions (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (6) No. 84.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate and an order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.20](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8cce50fe-fc88-440a-8815-a6a8e9e245ed/Directions under section 18 (6) of the Act (pending determination of application for care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate, and shall be served upon each party and upon any other person affected directly by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used when the court makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section such order shall be in the [Form 84.40S](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/755f0f12-1289-498c-a6ff-dd860ea0f9af/Order To Terminate Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, Section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40S.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(2) An application for an order under section of the [Act of 1991](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the person mentioned in paragraphs (a) and of section of the said Act of a notice in the [Form 84.40R](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5beab9f5-7b74-48f5-84d0-e4a9414e478e/Notice Of Application For Order In Respect Of Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 16 of the Children Act 2001) No. 84.40R.docx/docx/1) , Schedule Such notice shall be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph (iii) of section such order shall be in the [Form 84.40S](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/755f0f12-1289-498c-a6ff-dd860ea0f9af/Order To Terminate Private Foster Care Arrangement - Child Care Act 1991, Section (as inserted by section 16 of The Children Act 2001) No. 84.40S.docx/docx/1), Schedule Where the Court on such application makes an order referred to in paragraph or paragraph of section such order shall be (as the case may be) in the [Form 84.4](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8012be77-8ef0-4ac6-94e3-52984cffffa2/Emergency care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 13 (1) No. 84.4.docx/docx/1), [84.11](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2c0add82-7c52-4379-8c2f-c35d928109c8/Interim care order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 17 (1) No. 84.11.docx/docx/1), [84.15](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9e8e1e5-05f7-43ca-8254-e2d8a5b73ab5/Care Order - Child Care Act, 1991 section 18 (1) No. 84.15.docx/docx/1) or [84.18](https://courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c9f3f8b1-3a23-475f-b31d-b12bd4ee0f20/Supervision order (in lieu of a care order) - Child Care Act, 1991 Sections 18 (5), 19 No. 84.18.docx/docx/1), [Schedule C](https://courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), modified as appropriate ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served on the respondent before an application by the Agency under section 43(2) is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 90.12","Form 84.25","Form 85","Form 84.52"],"justification":"An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b7e851aa-60c6-4ef7-9d6b-f2dc9325bddc/Notice of application for an order that child be delivered up to custody of the health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.52.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order to deliver up child to the Child and Family Agency — 27.[37] An application by the Agency under section 43(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.52](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b7e851aa-60c6-4ef7-9d6b-f2dc9325bddc/Notice of application for an order that child be delivered up to custody of the health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.52.docx/docx/1) Schedule on the respondent. Such notice must be served at least two days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 84.53](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8fb48c60-ed36-4cc6-83bf-9a8934605663/Order that child be delivered up to custody of health board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 43(2) No. 84.53.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Agency must cause the said order to be served on the respondent 27A.[38] (1) An application for an order under section 43A of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by a foster parent or relative with whom the child has been placed shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant of a notice in the [Form 84.53A](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/765bd7e6-e9a9-44c9-ab01-4fea44d17853/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section 43a (as inserted by section 4 Of The Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53A.docx/docx/1), Schedule upon the Agency. A copy of the notice shall, where section 43A(2)(d)(ii) applies, be served by the Agency on the parent having custody of the child at the relevant time or a person (other than the applicant) acting in loco parentis to the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if the Judge finds the urgency of the matter requires it?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The case is dismissed immediately without further proceedings.","The Judge must wait for a response from the opposing party before making any decisions.","The application may be made parte and an order may be made based on the sworn information without issuing a summons.","Both parties are required to attend a mandatory mediation session before any decision is made."],"justification":"Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Information - (3)* 28. Where an order is sought under section 46 (3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) directing that a child be delivered up to the custody of the Agency, the applicant shall lay information before the Judge on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.54](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a12d36a7-7320-4233-90a5-ac23add07eaa/Information (under section 46 (3) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.54.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the Judge may, on foot of such information, sign and issue a summons in the [Form 84.55](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1)[.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/34b79aa6-1150-4d32-bde5-fe87e3c60129/Summons - Child Care Act, 1991 Section 46 (3) No. 84.55.docx/docx/1) Schedule Such summons shall be served upon the respondent at least two days prior to the return date thereof. Where, however, the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, the application may be made parte and an order under the said section may be made on foot of the sworn information without the necessity to issue such summons. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.56](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/445956b7-324f-4cb1-8f81-f4aa02343f39/Order That Child Be Delivered Up To Custody Of Health Board - Child Care Act, 1991 section 46(3) No. 84.56.docx/docx/1) Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court order granting the application to vary or discharge be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 84.61","Form 84.62","Form 84.55","Form 84.70"],"justification":"Form 84.62"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- variation or discharge* (2) An application to have any such order or direction varied or discharged shall be preceded by the issue and service as prescribed in paragraph (1) hereof of a notice in the [Form 84.61](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64e61fc5-3791-4d17-9ba7-91bbbf674fec/Notice Of Application To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction On A Question Affecting The Welfare Of A Child - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.61.docx/docx/1) Schedule upon the respondent or respondents. The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 84.62](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/75f7dce1-80fb-4075-b4f8-9ff125d0dd85/Order To Vary - Discharge - An Order - A Direction No. 84.62.docx/docx/1) Schedule and shall be served upon each of the parties and any other person directly affected by the order.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application for a warrant to enter and inspect premises where a pre-school service is provided be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Via an affidavit sent via email to the local magistrate.","By information on oath and in writing in Form 84.63.","By verbal testimony before a judge.","Through a formal declaration signed by at least three witnesses."],"justification":"An application under section 55 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter and inspect premises in which a pre-school service is being carried on shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.63.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b5d4b0da-c0bb-426c-9589-c2b23b73ce1e/Information (under section 55 (2) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.63.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Pre-School service — warrant* (2) An application under section 55 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter and inspect premises in which a pre-school service is being carried on shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 84.63.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b5d4b0da-c0bb-426c-9589-c2b23b73ce1e/Information (under section 55 (2) of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.63.docx/docx/1) Schedule Where the Judge receiving such information issues a warrant under that section such warrant shall be in the [Form 84.64.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1aef1076-3f97-4672-b249-22975bdaac45/Warrant To Enter And Inspect Premises - Child Care Act, 1991 section 55 (2) No. 84.64.docx/docx/1) Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served on the Agency before an appeal can be heard?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 84.56","Form 94.65","Form 84.60","Form 84.65"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 84.65](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19803d89-7193-4e0e-95fc-0cd8d9dcb550/Notice Of Appeal (under section 62 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.65.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Children''s residential centre* 32. An appeal to the Court under section 62 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) by the registered proprietor or, as the case may be, the person intending to be the registered proprietor of a children''s residential centre, against a decision, specified in subsection (1) of that section, of the Agencyshall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84.65](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/19803d89-7193-4e0e-95fc-0cd8d9dcb550/Notice Of Appeal (under section 62 of the Act) - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.65.docx/docx/1)Schedule upon the Agency. Such notice shall be served at least seven days prior to the date fixed for hearing the appeal. The appellant shall lodge with the Clerk prior to the hearing a copy of the decision against which the appeal is brought or a copy of the notification referred to in section 61 (11) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html). The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 84.66](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/94a0ecd6-7d38-4813-8338-0dc9eae3eaad/Order Of Appeal - Child Care Act, 1991 No. 84.66.docx/docx/1). Schedule ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'How much notice must be given before an application under section 25(1) of the Act is heard, unless the child has been detained under section 23(2)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least three weeks","At least five days","At least ten days","At least fifteen days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served at least ten days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001 - Court: District # Order 84A: Mental Health Act **[1]** 1. (1) In this Order – “**the Act**” means the [Mental Health Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html). (2) The provisions of rules 2, 3 and 4 of [Order 84]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-84-District-Child-care) of these Rules shall apply, mutatis mutandis, to proceedings to which this Order applies. 2. (1). Save where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) or in a case to which section 25(7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, an application under section 25(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) for an order authorising the detention of a child in an approved centre shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the district court district in which the child resides or is for the time being to be found at a sitting of the Court for the said District. Save in a case to which section 25(7) of the Act applies, such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 84A.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/70390850-5689-4ac6-9fef-390b0d0ec1af/Notice of application for order authorising detention in an approved centre. No. 84A.1.docx/docx/1) upon the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child. Such notice shall be served at least ten days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. Where a child has been detained in accordance with section 23(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), such notice shall be served as promptly as reasonably possible and prior to the hearing of the application at a sitting of the Court held within the time specified in section 23(3) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html), and may be served by delivering a copy of the notice to the parents of the child or either of them or upon a person acting in loco parentis of the child.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84A - Mental Health Act 2001', 'Court Rules', 'In which cases can an application under section 25 of the Act be heard and an order made elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["In the case of a child to whom section 23 of the Act applies","In the case of an adult to whom section 24 of the Act applies","In the case of a minor to whom section 19 of the Act applies","In the case of a company to whom section 30 of the Act applies"],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '8. Notwithstanding any of the preceding rules, where the Judge is satisfied that the urgency of the matter so requires, an application under section 25 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) may - - (a) be made parte, subject to the lodgment with the Clerk of the appropriate notice of application duly completed; - in the case of a child to whom section 23 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/25/enacted/en/html) applies, be heard, and an order made thereon, elsewhere than at a public sitting of the Court. [1] Order 84A inserted by [S.I. 97 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/97/made/en/print?q 97&years 2007), effective 2 April 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 85 - Water disconnection rules', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice of application be served on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["at least seven days prior","at least thirty days prior","at least twenty one days prior","at least fourteen days prior"],"justification":"shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Notice of application* 2. An application by the sanitary authority for an order under section 3 (2) of the [Local Government (Delimitation of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1995/act/18/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the supply of water for domestic purposes is provided to the consumer. Notice of such application shall be in the [Form 85.1 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/24a4ac07-80a9-4a22-8ad7-ae2e0dd9ce0e/Notice Of An Application For An Order Under Section 3 (2) - Local Government (Delimitation Of Water Supply Disconnection Powers) Act, 1995 No. 85.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post at least twenty one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant do regarding the notice of the intended application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Email it to all residents of the relevant district at least one week before the hearing.","Announce it on social media platforms at least one month prior to the hearing.","Submit it directly to the relevant government office without publication.","Cause it to be published at least one month before the hearing in a newspaper circulating in the relevant district."],"justification":"The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Newspaper notice* (4) The applicant shall also cause notice of the intended application to be published at least one month before such hearing in a newspaper circulating in the district in which is situate the place to which such application relates.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Which act''s section 24 applies to the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Environmental Protection Act, 1981","Fire Services Act, 1981","Public Order Act, 1981","Criminal Justice Act, 1981"],"justification":"section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (5) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shall apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a public dancing licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By submitting the application to the nearest police station in the jurisdiction of the dance venue.","At the local city hall or municipal office for the area where the dance event will take place.","Through an online platform designated by the national government''s cultural department.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under section 8 (2)* 4. (1) An application in respect of any place for which a public dancing licence is in force, for a public dancing licence in respect of that place to another person pursuant to section 8 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1935/act/2/enacted/en/html), made with the consent of the licensee, may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place to which the application relates is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 86 - Public dancing', 'Court Rules', 'What act''s section 24 applies to the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Road Traffic Act, 1981","Environmental Protection Act, 1981","Criminal Justice Act, 1981","Fire Services Act, 1981"],"justification":"section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Applicant to notify Fire Authority* (4) The provisions of section 24 of the Fire Services Act, 1981 shat apply to the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 87 - Public music and singing', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a public music and singing licence be made if there is no existing licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Through an online form on the government''s official website dedicated to entertainment licensing.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situated.","By submitting an application to the nearest police station.","At the local council office in the area where the event will take place."],"justification":"An application for a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under sec. 51 (2)* 2. (1) An application for a public music and singing licence pursuant to section 51 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the place sought to be licensed is situate. (2) Where the application is in respect of a place for which a licence under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1890/act/59/enacted/en/print.html) is in existence at the time of such application, the application shall be made at the Annual Licensing Court for the said court area.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 84 - Child care', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used for issuing a notice of application to vary or discharge an order made under section 43A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form 84.5","Form"],"justification":"the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An application pursuant to section of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) for an order varying or discharging an order made under section 43A shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 84.53C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/155928ec-fca4-495b-b4b3-65ce090fea41/Notice Of Application To Vary- Discharge- A Condition- Restriction- Attaching To- An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, Section No. 84.53C.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application shall, to the extent possible, be served upon each of the persons referred to in section 43B(1)(a) to of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1991/act/17/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 84.53D](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e6cf2c6b-7f10-49ae-b5bf-a33b0be2f3d4/Order Varying - Discharging - A Condition Restriction - Attaching To - An Order Under Section 43a Of The Act - Child Care Act 1991, section (as inserted by section 4 of the Child Care (Amendment) Act 2007) No. 84.53D.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon each of the respondents and upon any other person directly affected by the Order'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the date of hearing must the notice be served on the Chief Superintendent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No specific time requirement","Exactly five days","At least seven days","At least three days"],"justification":"Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Chief Superintendent at least seven days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A copy of the notice and a statutory declaration as to service thereof","A written affidavit and proof of identity of the parties involved","The original notice and a witness affidavit of service","A copy of the summons and a confirmation of receipt"],"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date of such hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court follow when hearing an appeal under this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 99.7, Schedule A","Form 45.2, Schedule","Form 88.6, Schedule","Form 88.6, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 88.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e7df7bf9-2542-4e31-85e7-615f4b1e2d36/Order on appeal - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 section 13(3) No. 88.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23(1) be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Before the President of Ireland for approval.","To the Commissioner of the Garda Síochána directly.","At the office of the Minister for Justice and Equality.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit."],"justification":"An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application under Sec. 23 (1)* 5. (1) An application by a Chief Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for an order under section 23 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1962/act/13/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area forming any part of the locality in which the collection was held pursuant to a collection permit.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice be served before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least seven days","at least twelve hours","at least twenty-four hours","at least forty-eight hours"],"justification":"at least forty-eight hours"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of, and service of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 88.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/92048d44-e8a1-4ac3-ac7d-9e2f700d53dc/Notice of application for an order under section 23 (1) of the Act - Street and House to House Collections Act, 1962 No. 88.7.docx/docx/1) upon the person (the respondent) to whom was granted the collection permit pursuant to which the collection was held. The notice shall be served at least forty-eight hours before the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done after service has been effected?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.","The notice must be forwarded to the court''s central registry instead of being lodged with the Clerk.","The served party must acknowledge receipt of the notice in writing within 24 hours.","The original notice must be destroyed upon service to maintain confidentiality."],"justification":"When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 88 - Street and house to house collections', 'Court Rules', 'What must be provided to the respondent after the Order is issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["an oral notification of the order","a certified copy of the order","a signed affidavit related to the case","a preliminary hearing transcript"],"justification":"A certified copy of such order shall be given or sent to the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) Where the application is granted the Order shall be in the [Form 88.8, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/9c721def-fff2-4ab0-adcb-f6d6ac13b419/Order for information about proceeds of collection - Street and House to House Collections Act 1962 No. 88.8.docx/docx/1). A certified copy of such order shall be given or sent to the respondent'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 89 - Wildlife?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["High Court","District","Supreme Court","Magistrate"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 89 - Wildlife - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What is the venue for an appeal if the appellant is ordinarily resident within the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the appellant''s place of residence.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides.","In the nearest High Court to the appellant''s place of residence, irrespective of the court area.","Before the Federal Court located in the capital city, regardless of the appellant''s ordinary residence."],"justification":"at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 29 (7)* 2. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 29 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against the refusal by the Minister to grant or renew a licence to hunt with firearms may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides or, where the appellant is ordinarily resident outside the State, temporarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice of appeal against refusal of a hunting license?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The judge who refused the hunting license.","The respondent or solicitor for the respondent.","The local wildlife officer.","The appellant or solicitor for the appellant."],"justification":"signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ff20174-1e3f-46a0-8f04-7b01bf4f26b9/Notice of appeal against refusal of the minister to a licence to hunt with firearms - renew - Wildlife Act, 1976 No. 89.1.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What action is required by the Clerk if the Court allows the appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Publish the order of the Court in a national newspaper","Send a copy of the order of the Court to the Minister","Provide a summary of the case to the Supreme Court","Notify all parties involved in the appeal via email"],"justification":"Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e981c916-43d9-4f8b-9225-3fcf1aaf901c/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 29(7) No. 89.2.docx/docx/1). (5) Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a certificate authorising the issue of a wildlife dealer''s licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situate.","At the nearest police station within the jurisdiction where the premises are situated.","At the local wildlife conservation office in the area where the premises are located.","Through an online portal on the Ministry of Environment''s official website."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application for certificate* 3. (1) An application for the grant of a certificate authorising the issue of a licence or renewal of a licence to carry on business as a wildlife dealer pursuant to section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the premises for which the certificate is sought are situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice for a wildlife dealer''s licence application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The provincial wildlife commissioner.","The nearest veterinarian.","The local wildlife conservation officer.","The applicant or solicitor for the applicant."],"justification":"signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8eac24c9-6d07-4437-a196-902c196cc28d/Notice of application for a certificate authorising the issue - renewal of a wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["To the local wildlife dealer association.","At the nearest wildlife conservation office.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted.","Through an online portal on the official wildlife management website."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for application to amend licence* 4. (1) An application for the amendment of a wildlife dealer''s licence pursuant to section 48 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the certificate authorising the issue of a licence was granted.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'When should the notice be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["One day before the date of hearing of the application","Immediately after the hearing of the application","On the same day as the hearing of the application","At least two days before the date of hearing of the application"],"justification":"which shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the completion of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d9c2c498-7806-4f94-b46d-36cb81488b97/Notice of application to amend wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.5.docx/docx/1)) which shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Clerk take when the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk sends a copy of the order of the Court to the Minister as soon as may be.","The Clerk destroys all records related to the wildlife dealer’s licence upon revocation.","The Clerk updates the public registry to reflect the revocation of the wildlife dealer’s licence immediately.","The Clerk informs the wildlife dealer directly about the revocation of their licence."],"justification":"Where pursuant to section 49 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation of licence* 5. Where pursuant to section 49 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court. 6. Where, pursuant to section 75 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), the Court revokes a firearm certificate or a licence to hunt with firearms and imposes a disqualification, the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an appeal be made under section 77 of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the seizure and detention.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the seizure and detention was made.","Through an online form submitted to the Ministry of Justice within 30 days of the seizure and detention.","Before a magistrate''s court in the county where the seizure and detention took place."],"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 77 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against seizure and detention under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such seizure and detention was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeal under sec. 77* 7. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 77 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) against seizure and detention under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such seizure and detention was made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice of appeal in wildlife cases?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Any member of the public interested in the case","The respondent or solicitor for the respondent","The judge presiding over the case","The appellant or solicitor for the appellant"],"justification":"signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fcd8b62-a25c-4f3f-a183-ce7a18dde282/Notice of appeal against seizure and detention - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 77 No. 89.6.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a notice be served if it is delivered by registered prepaid post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least fourteen days","at least twenty-one days","at least seven days","at least ten days"],"justification":"at least fourteen days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal, in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), at least seven days or, where service is effected by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the hearing?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A copy of the summons and a notarized affidavit","A copy of the complaint and a witness statement","A copy of the notice and a statutory declaration as to service thereof","The original notice and a certificate of mailing"],"justification":"A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Lodgment of notice* (4) A copy of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court be in when hearing an appeal under the Wildlife Act 1976?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The order should be in accordance with Form 90.1 or 90.2 Schedule as the case may be.","The order should be in accordance with Form 89.7 or 89.8 Schedule as the case may be.","The order should be in accordance with Form 34.5 or 34.6 Schedule A, as the case may be.","The order should be in accordance with Form 72.1 or 72.2 Schedule as the case may be."],"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/55bd89bf-fa2f-4689-b7b7-eb25942efe37/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.7.docx/docx/1) or [89.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7082ac7d-a829-4d9a-b80d-876e7ab00e40/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (5) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/55bd89bf-fa2f-4689-b7b7-eb25942efe37/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.7.docx/docx/1) or [89.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7082ac7d-a829-4d9a-b80d-876e7ab00e40/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 77 No. 89.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an appeal in accordance with the Wildlife Act, 1976?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The publication of a public announcement in a national newspaper","The submission of a written affidavit by the appellant to the Department of Natural Resources","The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 89.9 Schedule","The issuance of a formal apology by the appellant to the Wildlife Conservation Board"],"justification":"Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.9 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f738a32e-a4cc-4e86-adfa-6a504d490ed3/Notice of appeal against a direction under section 78 (3) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 78 (5) No. 89.9.docx/docx/1))"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.9 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f738a32e-a4cc-4e86-adfa-6a504d490ed3/Notice of appeal against a direction under section 78 (3) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 78 (5) No. 89.9.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court''s order follow when hearing an appeal under the Wildlife Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The order should be in accordance with Form 89.09 or 89.12 Schedule depending on the circumstances.","The order should be in accordance with Form 75.23 or 75.24 Schedule depending on the circumstances.","The order should be in accordance with Form 89.10 or 89.11 Schedule depending on the circumstances.","The order should be in accordance with Form 90.05 or 90.06 Schedule A, depending on the circumstances."],"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22775a7e-21b0-4f08-bfdb-3132be53dc35/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 78(5) No. 89.10.docx/docx/1), or [89.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ee51a3b-b56e-44d2-aa6c-269789892ec4/Order on appeal (Wildlife Act, 1976) No. 89.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court on hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/22775a7e-21b0-4f08-bfdb-3132be53dc35/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 78(5) No. 89.10.docx/docx/1), or [89.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7ee51a3b-b56e-44d2-aa6c-269789892ec4/Order on appeal (Wildlife Act, 1976) No. 89.11.docx/docx/1) Schedule as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Prohibition of air travel","*Application to prohibit entry on land*","Regulation of maritime boundaries","Enforcement of commercial zoning laws"],"justification":"*Application to prohibit entry on land*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to prohibit entry on land*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 9. (1) An application pursuant to section 68 (5) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) for an order prohibiting an authorised officer from entering on land may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the land is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served if it is sent by registered prepaid post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Ten days","Twenty-one days","Seven days","Fourteen days"],"justification":"Service shall be effected at least seven days or, where the notice is being served by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date fixed for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 89.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/46467192-4950-4c80-ad47-75a19d7f2669/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Wildlife Act 1976 No. 89.12.docx/docx/1) upon the respondent (the authorised officer) in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html). Service shall be effected at least seven days or, where the notice is being served by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall then be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court take when it hears an application under this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The order should be in Form 89.12, Schedule","The order should be in Form 89.13, Schedule","The order should be in Form 89.1, Schedule A.","The order should be in Form 89.14, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 89.13, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- order of the Court* (3) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 89.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/87c7f6c7-c1c8-457c-99c2-f21b8ca691b4/Order (prohibiting entry on land) - (specifying conditions for entry on land) - Wildlife Act 1976 No. 89.13.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["*Application for search warrant*","*Affidavit in support of search warrant*","*Procedure for executing search warrant*","*List of seized items*"],"justification":"*Application for search warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for search warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a search warrant be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the Supreme Court for the court district where the premises or land are located.","At any police station within the same county as the premises or land.","At any local municipal court for the town where the premises or land are located.","At any sitting of the District Court for the court district where the premises or land are located."],"justification":"An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a search warrant pursuant to section 73 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or other land in respect of which the warrant is sought is situate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 10. (1) An application to a Judge of the District Court for the issue of a search warrant pursuant to section 73 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or other land in respect of which the warrant is sought is situate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What forms can a search warrant issued under the Wildlife Act take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 89.25 or 89.26, Schedule","Form 89.15 or 89.16, Schedule","Form or Schedule","Form WLA-10 or WLA-11, Schedule A"],"justification":"A search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 89.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8227dc00-5bf1-426e-a369-f900a16dd47b/Search warrant (to a member of the Garda Síochána) - Wildlife Act 1976 section 73 No. 89.15.docx/docx/1) or [89.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a9b62b44-6f58-453e-9c2c-e05134312b5f/Search warrant (to an authorised person) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 73 No. 89.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of warrant* (3) A search warrant issued on foot of such information shall be in the [Form 89.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8227dc00-5bf1-426e-a369-f900a16dd47b/Search warrant (to a member of the Garda Síochána) - Wildlife Act 1976 section 73 No. 89.15.docx/docx/1) or [89.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a9b62b44-6f58-453e-9c2c-e05134312b5f/Search warrant (to an authorised person) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 73 No. 89.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 9 - Joinder of Claims', 'Court Rules', 'What types of claims can be joined with a claim for the recovery of land?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Claims for mesne profits, arrears of rent, double rent, and damages for breach of contract or wrong/injury to the land.","Claims for alimony, child support, and wrongful termination.","Claims for punitive damages, defamation, and breach of warranty.","Claims for bankruptcy, tax evasion, and intellectual property infringement."],"justification":"No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof, and damages for breach of any contract under which the land, or any part thereof, is held, or for any wrong or injury to the said land, or any part thereof"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Joinder of Claims - Court: Circuit 1. Save as in the next succeeding Rule provided, two or more claims may be made in one originating document, either alternatively or otherwise, so long as the claims are not mutually inconsistent or based on inconsistent allegations of fact, but, if it appears to the Judge that claims joined in any action or matter cannot be conveniently tried together, he may order separate trials or may exclude any claim, and may order the record to be amended accordingly, and may make such order as to costs as may seem just. 2. No claim may be joined with one for the recovery of land except in respect of mesne profits or arrears of rent, or double rent in connection therewith, or any part thereof, and damages for breach of any contract under which the land, or any part thereof, is held, or for any wrong or injury to the said land, or any part thereof. An action for redemption, and a motion for delivery by a defendant of possession of mortgaged property therein, shall not be deemed a claim for the recovery of land within the meaning of this Rule.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'What is one way to serve a summons on a defendant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By personal service upon the person to be served","By leaving the summons at the defendant''s residence with any person of suitable age and discretion who resides there","By sending the summons via standard mail to the last known address of the defendant","By posting the summons in a local newspaper and on the courthouse bulletin board"],"justification":"by personal service upon the person to be served, or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Service of summons - Court: Superior # Mode of service** 1. No service of a summons shall be required when the defendant, by his solicitor, accepts service, and undertakes in writing to enter an appearance. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) Service of any summons on the defendant shall, except in the cases in the following rules of this Order specified, be effected: - by personal service upon the person to be served, or - by personal service upon another person referred to in sub-rule (2) on behalf of the person to be served, or - (iii) by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served, provided that such service shall not be deemed effective without proof of delivery of the said envelope to the address of the person to be served, or - where the defendant is a company, in accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014. (2) Where it shall appear by affidavit that the defendant is personally within the jurisdiction and that due and reasonable diligence has been exercised in endeavouring to effect personal service on him or her, service of the summons may be effected by delivering a copy thereof at - (a) the defendant''s usual or last known place of residence within the jurisdiction, or - the defendant''s principal or last known place of business or office, to the wife, husband, civil partner (within the meaning of section 3 of the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010) father, mother, brother, or sister of the defendant, or to any employee of the defendant (the person to whom such copy shall be delivered being of the age of sixteen years or upwards) and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'When are both husband and wife required to be served in legal proceedings?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Both husband and wife must be served unless one of them has previously filed for divorce.","Both husband and wife must be served unless they have been living separately for more than six months.","Both husband and wife must be served unless the Court orders otherwise.","Both husband and wife must be served only if they are co-owners of a property involved in the case."],"justification":"When husband and wife are both defendants in any proceedings, they shall both be served unless the Court shall otherwise order."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '3. Personal service shall be effected by delivering a copy of the summons to the defendant in person, and showing him the original or duplicate original. # On particular defendants** 4. When husband and wife are both defendants in any proceedings, they shall both be served unless the Court shall otherwise order. 5. When an infant is defendant in any proceedings service on his father or mother or guardian, or, if none, then upon the person with whom the infant resides or under whose care he is, shall, unless the Court otherwise orders, be deemed good service on the infant; provided that the Court may order that service made or to be made on the infant shall be deemed good service. 6.[[4]](#2612023) Service on a relevant person (within the meaning of section 2(1) of the Assisted Decision-Making (Capacity) Act 2015) who is a defendant to an action, shall be in accordance with [Order 15](full-court-rule?id 0469ffe2-3989-4afd-96eb-61d6db2e2a22), rule 17.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'How should a summons be served in an action for recovery of land due to non-payment of rent or overholding?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Service of the summons requires publication in a national newspaper and posting on the property.","It is not necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant.","It is necessary to serve the summons on every tenant who has ever occupied the property within the last five years.","The summons must be served on all legal representatives of the landlord before it can be considered valid."],"justification":"In an action brought for recovery of land for non-payment of rent or for overholding, it shall not be necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. In the absence of any statutory provision regulating service, every summons issued against a corporation aggregate may be served on the mayor or other head officer, or on the town clerk, clerk, treasurer, or secretary of such corporation; and every summons issued against the inhabitants of a county district or other like district may be served on any officer of the Gárda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent stationed in the county in which such district is situate and every summons issued against the inhabitants of any county or any city or town, or the inhabitants of any franchise, liberty, city, town, or place not being part of the county district or other like district on some peace officer thereof: provided always that in all such cases a sufficient notice of the issuing of the summons shall be given in Iris Oifigiúil and in one of the local newspapers of the county, city, or district in which the defendant or defendants or the officer or other person to be served shall reside, the times for appearing to run in such cases from the day of the publication of such notice in Iris Oifigiúil or such newspaper, whichever shall be the latest; and where, by any statute, provision is made for service of any proceedings upon any corporation, or upon any society or fellowship, or any body or number of persons, whether corporate or incorporate, every summons may be served in the manner so provided. # **III. In particular actions** 8. In an action brought for recovery of land for non-payment of rent or for overholding, it shall not be necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 9. In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'How can service of a summons be effected in actions for the recovery of land if personal service is not possible?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By delivering a copy of the summons to any friend of the person to be served, as long as they are over the age of twelve and reside in the same city.","By posting the summons publicly on the courthouse door and sending a notice via certified mail to the last known address of the person to be served.","By delivering a copy of the summons to the employer of the person to be served, provided that the employer is aware of the individual''s whereabouts.","By delivering a copy of the summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister of the person to be served, at their house, office, or place of business, provided the person receiving the copy is at least sixteen years old."],"justification":"delivering a copy of such summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister, of such person, at her house, or office, or place of business (the person with whom such copy shall be left being of the age of sixteen years or upwards), and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '10. In actions for the recovery of land service of a summons may be effected either by personal service on the person to be served at any place within the jurisdiction or by delivering a copy of such summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister, of such person, at her house, or office, or place of business (the person with whom such copy shall be left being of the age of sixteen years or upwards), and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons, and such service as last aforesaid may be effected whether the person to be served is within the jurisdiction or not. 11. Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property; provided, however, that in such case before any judgment by default shall be given, the Court shall be satisfied that there was no person in actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits on whom other service might have been effected. # General** 12. [[2]](#_ftn2) (1) The person serving a summons shall, within three days at most after service, indorse on the summons the day and date of the service thereof; and every affidavit of service of such summons shall mention the date on which such indorsement was made. (1A) An Indorsement of service by prepaid registered post shall be in the following terms: “INDORSEMENT OF SERVICE served the within summons on [person to be served] by posting the same by prepaid registered post to [him] [her] at [address] on the ... day of ........ 20...” Signed ................ This ... day of ........ 20..”. (2) Every affidavit of service of a summons by prepaid registered post shall exhibit proof of delivery of the envelope in which a copy of the summons is contained to the address of the person to be served.”;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'What must an affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent or overholding state?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The deponent must confirm that the land is free from any encumbrances or liens.","The deponent must affirm that no one else besides the landlord has legal ownership of the property.","The deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant.","The deponent must declare that all tenants have vacated the premises within 24 hours of service."],"justification":"Every affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent, or for overholding, shall state that the deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '13. Every affidavit of service of a summons in actions for the recovery of land for non-payment of rent, or for overholding, shall state that the deponent does not know of any person, other than those who have been served, who is in actual possession of the land sought to be recovered or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 14. Every affidavit of service of a summons in other actions for recovery of land, shall state that the deponent does not know of and does not believe that there is any person, other than those who have been served, in the actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits of the land sought to be recovered, or any part thereof, and the said statement shall be verified by the affidavit of the plaintiff or of one of the plaintiffs, or of the solicitor for the plaintiff. 15. In any case the Court may, upon just grounds, declare the service actually effected sufficient. 16. [[3]](#_ftn3) This Order shall, so far as practicable, apply to an originating document and to notice in lieu of service, save where any other Order of these Rules requires personal service of such document or notice. [[1]](#_ftnref1) Order 9 rule 2 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017. [[2]](#_ftnref2) Order 9 rule 12 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[3]](#_ftnref3) Order 9 rule 16 substituted by 475 of 2017](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/si/475/made/en/print), effective 27 November 2017.[[4]](#26120231) Order 9 rule 6 substituted by 261 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/261/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,(Capacity) Act 2015) 2023&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of May, 2023.)effective 15 May 2023.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High","Circuit","Supreme","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol) - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'Where should proceedings be brought if the defendant does not have a residence or registered office in the State but has a place of business in the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area nearest to where the contract was signed.","Before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the plaintiff resides.","Before any federal court regardless of the location of the defendant''s place of business.","Before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the defendant has a place of business."],"justification":"- if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located in the State, wherein the defendant has a place of business, or"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings brought before the Court pursuant to section 7 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) for the recovery of a sum due to the Organisation in respect of air navigation facilities and services provided by that body, or by any other person, shall be brought, heard and determined before sittings of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area - wherein the defendant''s residence or, as the case may be, the defendant''s registered office, is located, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located in the State, wherein the defendant has a place of business, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business in the State, wherein the defendant has assets, or - if such residence or, as the case may be, such registered office is not located, or he or she has no place of business or assets in the State, wherein the Organisation, for the time being, has its headquarters.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to the provisions of the Rules concerning civil summons for debt or liquidated money demand?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["They apply mutatis mutandis to such proceedings","They are replaced by the common law procedures for debt recovery","They are disregarded in favor of special rules for debt cases","They only apply to criminal proceedings involving financial claims"],"justification":"the provisions of these Rules relating thereto shall mutatis mutandis apply to such proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings by civil summons* 3. Such proceedings shall be instituted by the issue of a civil summons for a debt or liquidated money demand in the Form 39.2, [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), and the provisions of these Rules relating thereto shall mutatis mutandis apply to such proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'What does the Clerk do after the decree is signed by the Judge?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["File the original decree and affidavit in the court archives and destroy all copies.","Send the original decree and affidavit to an external legal firm for review before issuing copies.","Deliver the original decree and affidavit directly to the applicant without issuing any copies.","Retain the original decree and affidavit, and certify and issue the copies to the applicant."],"justification":"When the decree has been signed by the Judge, the Clerk shall retain the original decree and affidavit, and shall certify and issue the copies to the applicant therefor."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Copies of decrees and civil summonses* 4. (1) A person seeking a certified copy of a determination for the purposes of section 9 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall complete and lodge with the Clerk the relevant decree in duplicate, together with an affidavit of debt (where appropriate) in duplicate, and shall pay any prescribed court fee. When the decree has been signed by the Judge, the Clerk shall retain the original decree and affidavit, and shall certify and issue the copies to the applicant therefor. (2) Upon application being made under the said section 9 and upon payment of the prescribed court fee, the Clerk shall prepare, certify and issue to the applicant therefor a copy of the original civil summons (including the statutory declaration as to service).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the certificate issued by the Clerk under section of the Act of 1983 be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 90.1, Schedule","Form 90.2, Schedule A","Form 80.2, Schedule","Form 90.1, Schedule"],"justification":"The certificate to be issued by the Clerk under section 9 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 90.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/23319377-f25a-4d1d-9095-3557de347bba/Certificate (Air Navigation (Eurocontrol) Act, 1983) No. 90.1.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Certificate under section 9 5. The certificate to be issued by the Clerk under section 9 of the [Act of 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 90.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/23319377-f25a-4d1d-9095-3557de347bba/Certificate (Air Navigation (Eurocontrol) Act, 1983) No. 90.1.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in Order 90A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 (No. 55 of 2001)","The Transport (Maritime Infrastructure) Act 2001 (No. 55 of 2001)","The Transport (Road Infrastructure) Act 2001 (No. 55 of 2001)","The Transport (Air Infrastructure) Act 2001 (No. 55 of 2001)"],"justification":"“**the Act**” means the [Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) (No. 55 of 2001);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure - Court: District # Order 90A: Railway Infrastructure [1] 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) (No. 55 of 2001); the expression “**railway undertaking**” shall have the meaning given to it by [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html). 2. (1) An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 90A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1d1db340-330e-4387-938c-e9a5ecc61795/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 No. 90A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served by the applicant on the railway undertaking by or on whose behalf the notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) was served by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) An order made pursuant to paragraph of sub-section (1) of section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 90A.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26b82729-add3-4081-bb86-32bbaa7cb989/Order (Prohibiting entry on land) - (Specifying conditions for entry on land) - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act, 2001 No. 90A.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 90A inserted by [S.I. 534 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/534/made/en/print?q 534&years 2004), effective 9 October 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What court is responsible for Order 91 - Control of dogs?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["High Court","Supreme Court","Magistrates'' Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 91 - Control of dogs - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Wildlife Protection Act, 1972","The Environmental Conservation Act, 1990","The Public Health Act, 1984","The Control of Dogs Act, 1986 (No. 32 of 1986)"],"justification":"\"**the Act**\" means the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order— "**the Act**" means the [Control of Dogs Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) (No. 32 of 1986).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum notice period required for serving a summons in civil proceedings related to offences under the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least five days if served by regular means, or at least fifteen days if served by prepaid registered post.","At least seven days if served by regular means, or at least twenty-one days if served by prepaid registered post.","At least ten days if served by regular means, or at least thirty days if served by prepaid registered post.","At least three days if served by regular means, or at least fourteen days if served by prepaid registered post."],"justification":"Such summons shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Prosecution of offences* 2. (1) Proceedings in respect of an offence alleged under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the offence is alleged to have been committed. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a summons that such proceedings are urgent, the summons may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) An offence under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be prosecuted by the local authority in whose area the offence is alleged to have been committed. (4) Proceedings in respect of such an offence may be commenced by the issuing by the appropriate office of the District Court, on the application of the relevant local authority, of a summons in the Form 7, [Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings). Such summons shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the summons. (5) When service has been effected the original summons, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Where can a complaint under section 22 (1) (a) be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any local police station within the same city as where the incident occurred.","To the national dog registry office in the capital city.","Through an online petition on the official government website.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises of the owner of the dog or, as the case may be, of the person in charge of the dog are situated."],"justification":"A complaint under section 22 (1) (a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a dog is dangerous and not kept under proper control may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises of the owner of the dog or, as the case may be, of the person in charge of the dog are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings under section 22 (1) (a)* 3. (1) A complaint under section 22 (1) (a) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a dog is dangerous and not kept under proper control may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises of the owner of the dog or, as the case may be, of the person in charge of the dog are situated. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/544ad476-7a56-498b-8aa5-8f590c7e857a/Notice of intention to make a complaint that a dog is dangerous - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.1.docx/docx/1) upon the defendant (the person in charge of the dog) and, where the defendant is not the owner of the dog, also upon such owner. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days before the date of hearing of the complaint. (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7fde4400-ce69-4e93-aae2-e5cf8a343f62/Order in relation to a dangerous dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.2.docx/docx/1). A copy of such order shall be given to the defendant and, where the defendant is not the owner of the dog, a copy of the order shall also be given to such owner.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Where can a complaint under section 25(1) be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any online portal designated by the national government for lodging complaints about dogs.","At any police station within the same city as where the dog is kept.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the owner of the dog resides."],"justification":"A complaint under section 25 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a nuisance has been created as a result of excessive barking by a dog may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog, is kept are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings under sec. 25* 4. (1) A complaint under section 25 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a nuisance has been created as a result of excessive barking by a dog may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog, is kept are situated. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the occupier of the premises in which the dog is kept of the notice referred to in section 25 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) and which is prescribed in the [Control of Dogs (No. 2) Regulations, 1987 (S.I. No. 59 of 1987)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/si/59/made/en/print#). Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall forthwith be lodged with the Clerk. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eb9b13cb-37ea-4fa3-82e3-9ca378b2c360/Order in relation to excessive barking by a dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.3.docx/docx/1). A copy of such order shall be given to the defendant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the application for a search warrant be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It should be a detailed affidavit without any specific form requirements.","It should be by information on oath and in writing in Form 91.4, Schedule","It should be submitted anonymously via email with supporting documents attached.","It should be verbally submitted to the judge during an oral hearing."],"justification":"The application shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 91.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aea308cb-d223-424f-81f3-9650004e1bc1/Information for search warrant - Control of Dogs Act, 1986 section 26 No. 91.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant (sec. 26)* 5. (1) An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a search warrant under section 26 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated. (2) The application shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 91.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aea308cb-d223-424f-81f3-9650004e1bc1/Information for search warrant - Control of Dogs Act, 1986 section 26 No. 91.4.docx/docx/1). (3) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 91.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/215e6650-979f-4004-8e77-ca3f7cf4a220/Search Warrant - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used to notify the local authority about an application to remove a disqualification?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 92.6, Schedule","Form 91.6, Schedule","Form 91.5, Schedule","Form 91.6, Schedule A"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/882474dd-72bc-48b5-bee9-bd2a11777c05/Notice of application to remove a disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.6.docx/docx/1) upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application to remove disqualification (sec. 29)* 6. (1) An application under section 27 (1) of the Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act, 1965 (as substituted by section 29 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html)) to remove a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 91.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/882474dd-72bc-48b5-bee9-bd2a11777c05/Notice of application to remove a disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.6.docx/docx/1) upon the local authority in whose area the offence, on conviction of which the disqualification order was made, was committed. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the application. (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the [Form 91.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ff2c7d9-466f-4e80-90c8-e7b4e83c097a/Order Removing Disqualification - Protection of Animals (Amendment) Act 1965 No. 91.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 92 - Fire services?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","Magistrates'' Court","District","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 92 - Fire services - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice of application be served if sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least twenty-one days","At least seven days","At least fourteen days","At least thirty days"],"justification":"The notice shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Fire safety notice —* 3. (1) An application under section 20 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) for an order concerning expenses or their apportionment shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 92.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/779274ae-4cf3-451e-83a4-2fad89593bf6/Notice Of Application Under Section 20 (4) - Fire Services Act 1981 No. 92.1.docx/docx/1), signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant; which notice shall be served upon the occupier or the owner, as the case may be, of the building or land to which the fire safety notice relates, and upon the fire authority which served the fire safety notice. The notice shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which it is returnable. (2) The original of every such notice of application, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court hearing the application shall be in the [Form 92.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54de9278-0351-4425-b9ad-85aaa9ec4414/Order Pursuant To Section 20 (4) - Fire Services Act 1981 No. 92.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice of appeal be given to the respondent fire authority if sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least seven days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least three days before the date of the sitting of the Court","At least twenty-one days before the date of the sitting of the Court"],"justification":"at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice of appeal is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeal against fire safety notice* 4. (1) An appeal under section 21 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal in the [Form 92.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68b51881-c383-4d75-b941-078c4ad85a8e/Notice Of Appeal - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.3.docx/docx/1), signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant; which notice shall be given to the respondent fire authority, in accordance with the provisions of sections 21 (2) and 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html), at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice of appeal is returnable. (2) A copy of the notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 92.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36288ceb-a7e4-42c5-9a63-dec4bdf9011e/Order On Appeal (Fire Services Act, 1981) No. 92.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the information on oath and in writing take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 15.3, Appendix","Form 15.2, Schedule A","Form 15.3, Schedule","Form 16.3, Schedule"],"justification":"The information shall be in the [Form 15.3, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d4746c0f-a588-4e2d-85f0-2c1c313b6d04/Information No. 15.3.docx/docx/1), with suitable modifications."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Warrant under section 22 (7)* 5. (1) An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority. The information shall be in the [Form 15.3, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d4746c0f-a588-4e2d-85f0-2c1c313b6d04/Information No. 15.3.docx/docx/1), with suitable modifications. (2) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 92.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86b21325-bbf4-4ecf-99b7-50543cb92d4e/Warrant Under Section 22 (7) Of The Act - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Magistrates","District","High","County"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings) - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Planning and Development Act, 1982 (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the Planning and Development (Amendment) Act, 1983 (No. 22 of 1983).","The Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982 (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) (Amendment) Act, 1983 (No. 22 of 1983).","The Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1972 (No. 6 of 1972), as amended by the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) (Amendment) Act, 1973 (No. 22 of 1973).","The Employment Equality Act, 1982 (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the Employment Equality (Amendment) Act, 1983 (No. 22 of 1983)."],"justification":"\"**the Act**\" means the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) (Amendment) Act, 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 1983)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definition* 1. In this Order - "**the Act**" means the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act, 1982](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) (No. 6 of 1982), as amended by the [Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) (Amendment) Act, 1983](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1983/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 1983).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under the Act be brought, heard or determined?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Before the Supreme Court of the jurisdiction where the relevant dwelling is situated.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the relevant dwelling is located.","In front of any judge from any state within the same country as the relevant dwelling.","At any federal court regardless of the location of the relevant dwelling."],"justification":"Proceedings under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which is situated the dwelling in relation to which the proceedings are brought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. Proceedings under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which is situated the dwelling in relation to which the proceedings are brought.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'What is the minimum period before the court sitting date for serving a notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Two weeks","One month.","Three months","Seven days"],"justification":"Every such notice shall be served one month at least before the date of sitting of the Court to which the notice has been made returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of notices* 4. (1) Notices required by this Order to be served shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 4 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), and where service is effected by registered prepaid post the provisions of section 7 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended, shall apply. (2) Every such notice shall be served one month at least before the date of sitting of the Court to which the notice has been made returnable. Proof of service shall be by statutory declaration. The original of every such notice, with the statutory declaration endorsed thereon, shall be lodged with the Clerk four days at least before the date of sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'What are the costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["In accordance with the appropriate scales set out in the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any similar scales in any other such schedule for the time being in force.","As determined by the discretion of the presiding judge without reference to any set scales.","In accordance with the fixed fee structure outlined in Part of the Act.","In accordance with the standard legal billing rates agreed upon between the parties."],"justification":"Costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), where allowed, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scales set out in the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any similar scales in any other such schedule for the time being in force."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs of proceedings under sections 15 and 16 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), where allowed, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scales set out in the Schedule of Costs annexed to these Rules or any similar scales in any other such schedule for the time being in force. Costs of any other proceedings under [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html) shall be at the discretion of the Court and may be measured under [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), 14 hereof. [1]Order 93, sub-rules (4) to (7) of rule 3 replaced by sub-rules (4) to (6) by 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93A - Applications under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'When must the copy of the notice of application be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Not later than two days before the date fixed for hearing the application.","Within one week prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.","On the same day as the date fixed for hearing the application.","Not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application."],"justification":"The copy of the notice of application referred to in this Order shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) The copy of the notice of application referred to in this Order shall be served not later than four days before the date fixed for hearing the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 93A.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b27e136e-ac12-4e35-8a72-a566d53d6a28/Order that damage be made good - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 44(4)(a)(i) No. 93A.4.docx/docx/1), [93A.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4ef4206f-ba02-4849-9cec-f4a822a47a29/Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 45 No. 93A.5.docx/docx/1) or [93A.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3afbc994-29ad-44d1-adea-f811721a336f/Order Discharging - Modifying A Works Order - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 47 No. 93A.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, and the applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served upon the building owner and every adjoining owner concerned, and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. (5) Every application mentioned in this rule may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court area wherein the party structure to which the application relates is situated. 3. Proceedings in the Court under section 44(4)(a)(ii) or under section may be commenced by civil summons in accordance with [Order 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93A - Applications under the Land and Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the notice of application take before an application under section 98(2) of the Act can proceed?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 93A.8","Form","Form 93A.7","Form"],"justification":"Such an application shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant on the mortgagor concerned of a copy of a notice of application in the [Form 93A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bd9a4c8-9dd2-4777-9b4f-10a704cb5bb6/Notice Of Application For Order Authorising Mortgagee To Take Possession Of Abandoned Property - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 98(1) No. 93A.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which notice shall state whether any court is already seised of an application or proceedings relating to the mortgaged property."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. An application to the Court for an order under section 98(2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/act/27/enacted/en/html) authorising a mortgagee to take possession of property may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court area wherein the mortgaged property to which the application relates is situated. Such an application shall be preceded by the issue and service by the applicant on the mortgagor concerned of a copy of a notice of application in the [Form 93A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7bd9a4c8-9dd2-4777-9b4f-10a704cb5bb6/Notice Of Application For Order Authorising Mortgagee To Take Possession Of Abandoned Property - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 98(1) No. 93A.7.docx/docx/1), Schedule which notice shall state whether any court is already seised of an application or proceedings relating to the mortgaged property. Without prejudice to the power of the Court to make an order for substituted service or to substitute notice for service, the Court may deem it sufficient service, if the mortgagor is untraceable, if a copy of the notice is affixed to, or posted at, the entrance of the property concerned. An order made on such application shall be in the [Form 93A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e395eb35-4084-438f-a84d-77c8b289ed05/Order Authorising Mortgagee To Take Possession Of Abandoned Property - Land And Conveyancing Law Reform Act 2009, section 98(2) No. 93A.8.docx/docx/1), and the applicant shall cause a copy of the said order to be served as directed by the Court. [1] Order 93A inserted by [S.I. 162 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/162/made/en/print?q 162&years 2010), effective 17 May 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(4) An affidavit relied on in an application under this Order shall be sworn by a director or secretary of the applicant and shall- - (a) verify the facts set out in the notice of application; - where the annual return proposed to be delivered has been prepared, exhibit a copy of same (including both the annual return in the form for the time being prescribed by the Registrar of Companies and any financial statements of the company required to be delivered to the Registrar of Companies), or explain why it has not been possible to prepare same; - set out, and verify any facts supporting, the reasons why the annual return was not delivered to the Registrar within the time permitted by section 343(2) or section 343(3) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) and set out, and verify any facts supporting, any additional reasons why it is alleged that it would be just to make an order extending time; - exhibit any correspondence between the applicant and the Registrar concerning the application, including in particular any correspondence from the applicant notifying the Registrar of its intention to make the application and any response by the Registrar. 3. (1) The applicant shall serve on the Registrar a copy of the notice of application and copies of any affidavit and exhibits relied on not later than 21 days before the date fixed for hearing the application. (2) In every case, the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The applicant shall, when lodging the original notice of application with the Clerk, also lodge a statutory declaration as to service on the Registrar. 4. Notwithstanding rule 2- - (a) the applicant shall be obliged to produce at the hearing of the application any correspondence received from the Registrar which has not been exhibited to any affidavit;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93B - Applications to extend time for delivery of annual return under section 324 of the Companies Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order extending time be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form Schedule","Form 56, Part","Form Schedule","Form 101, Section A"],"justification":"An order extending time in accordance with section 343(5) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 93B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1bad2aea-2220-45d6-9d57-ba97c84951aa/Order extending the time in which annual return may be delivered to the registrar of companies No. 93B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the Court may allow, or may direct, that evidence on the application be given viva voce and on oath by an officer of the applicant or another person in addition to, or in lieu of, evidence on affidavit. 5. An order extending time in accordance with section 343(5) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html) shall be in the [Form 93B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1bad2aea-2220-45d6-9d57-ba97c84951aa/Order extending the time in which annual return may be delivered to the registrar of companies No. 93B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and the applicant shall cause a certified copy of the order to be served upon the Registrar in accordance with section 343(6) of the [Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/38/enacted/en/html), and on any other person whom the Court directs should be served with a copy of the order. 6. An application under this Order may be brought, heard and determined at any sitting of the court for the court district wherein the registered office of the applicant company is situated. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 256 of 2015](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2015/si/256/made/en/print?q 256&years 2015), effective 1 July 2015'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Supreme","District","County","High"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 - Court: District # Order Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'What is an ''authorised officer''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An individual designated by the court under section 164A of the Act of 2003 as an authorised officer","A representative chosen by the local council under section 164A of the Act of 2004 for administrative purposes","A person appointed under section 164A of the Act of 2004 to be an authorised officer","A person appointed under section of the Act of 2005 to be an authorised officer"],"justification":"“**authorised officer** ” means a person appointed under section 164A of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) to be an authorised officer;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Definitions** In this Order— the “**Act of 2004**” means the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended; “**authorised officer** ” means a person appointed under section 164A of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) to be an authorised officer; the “**Board**” means the Residential Tenancies Board as established by section 150 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html); a “**determination order**” shall be interpreted having regard to the provisions of section 121 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'How must applications for enforcement of a determination order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through submission of an affidavit","Via written consent of both parties","By way of notice of application.","By way of a formal complaint"],"justification":"All applications by the Board or by a party mentioned in a determination order under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for enforcement of a determination order must be made by way of notice of application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Determination orders** 2. (1) All applications by the Board or by a party mentioned in a determination order under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for enforcement of a determination order must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the tenancy or dwelling concerned is or was situated. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must include particulars of the relief sought appropriate to the case. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of section 124 of the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended and must contain the name and address of the applicant as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The notice of application must set out the grounds on which the applicant relies for the reliefs sought and must have annexed thereto the original determination order or a certified copy of same, certified by the applicant as being a true copy of the determination order. The return date of the notice of application must be not less than 21 days after the date on which the notice of application is issued. (6) The notice of application must be supported by a grounding affidavit setting out and verifying the facts relied on in the application. Copies of the affidavit and any exhibits must be served with the notice of application on the respondent. (7) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally or in accordance with sub-rule (9). (8) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'What is the deadline for the respondent to notify the Board and the applicant of their intention to oppose the application, if the applicant is not the Board?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The respondent must give notice of their intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition within seven days following the receipt of the notice of application.","The respondent must give notice of their intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition no later than two days after the return date specified in the notice of application.","The respondent must give notice of their intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition immediately upon receiving the notice of application.","The respondent must give notice of their intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application."],"justification":"If the respondent intends to oppose the application and the applicant is not the Board, the respondent must give notice of such intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition to the Board and to the applicant no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(9) Where the relief sought in an application includes the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, the proceedings may be served by delivering copies of the notice of application, grounding affidavit and any exhibits, addressed to the respondent at the dwelling to which the determination relates or, where such service cannot be effected, by leaving copies of those documents at the dwelling or by attaching those documents to the door or some other conspicuous part of the dwelling. In all other cases, the notice of application must be served personally or by prepaid registered post. (10) If the respondent intends to oppose the application and the applicant is not the Board, the respondent must give notice of such intention to oppose and the grounds of opposition to the Board and to the applicant no later than four days prior to the return date specified in the notice of application. Such notice must be served on the Board by leaving a true copy of same at the registered offices of the Board or by pre-paid registered post to the registered offices of the Board. (11) Save by special leave of the Court, all applications under section 124 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be heard on affidavit evidence or as may be determined by the Court. (12) On the return date of the notice of application the Court may, if it does not hear and determine the application, proceed in accordance with [Order 40C]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-40C-District-Procedure-In-Statutory-Applications-By-Notice-Of-Application), rule 7. (13)[2] Where an order is made for the enforcement of a determination for recovery of vacant possession of a dwelling, a warrant for possession may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments), and [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments) shall apply to such warrant for possession. Where an order is made for the recovery of money, or for costs, a warrant authorising execution may issue in accordance with [Order 51]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51-District-Execution-And-Enforcement-Of-Judgments). ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'How must an application by an authorised officer under section be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Through oral declaration in court.","By way of notice of application.","By way of written affidavit.","Via electronic submission to the secretary."],"justification":"An application by an authorised officer under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be made by way of notice of application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers under section 3. (1) An application by an authorised officer under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under section of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person in respect of whom the application is made resides or carries on any profession, trade or business. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must: - show on its face how or by whom the consent of the Board to the making of the application was given; - where the requirement to which the application relates was made in writing, have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the written requirement, and include particulars of service of the requirement on the respondent or delivery of the requirement to the respondent; - (iii) where the requirement to which the application relates was not made in writing, include particulars of the requirement and of how it was communicated to the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of section of the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the applicant as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The return date of the notice of application must be not less than 21 days after the date on which the notice of application is issued. (6) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (7) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'What form must the notice of application be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form No. Schedule","Form No. Schedule modified as appropriate to the case.","Form No. Schedule","Form No. Schedule"],"justification":"The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the notice in writing issued to the respondent under paragraph 2 of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and include particulars of service of the notice on the respondent."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Applications by authorised officers or the Board under Schedule 3** 4. (1) An application: - by an authorised officer for an order under paragraph 5 of Part of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, or - by the Board for an order under paragraph 5 of Part 2 of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order under that paragraph, must be made by way of notice of application. (2) Applications under this rule must be brought in the court area in which the person required to attend the oral hearing ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. (3) The notice of application must be in [Form No. 40C.01](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f41cd296-af0b-46f1-80e9-bf6c87ccc64b/Notice of statutory application No. 40C.01.docx/docx/1), Schedule modified as appropriate to the case, and must have appended (to the original notice of application and to any copy of the notice of application served on the respondent) a true copy of the notice in writing issued to the respondent under paragraph 2 of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), and include particulars of service of the notice on the respondent. (4) The notice of application must be entitled in the matter of Part 1 or, as the case may be, Part 2, of Schedule 3 to the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 , as amended and must contain the name and address of the authorised officer or, as the case may be, the Board as claimant and the name and address of the respondent. (5) The respondent must be served not later than 21 days before the return date where service is by registered post or not less than seven days before the return date where service is effected personally. (6) The original notice of application and a statutory declaration as to the service of the notice of application on the respondent must be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the return date. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 69 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/69/made/en/print?q 69&years 2018), effective 23 March 2018 and substituted by [S.I. 431 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/431/made/en/print), effective 22 October 2020 [2] Order rule 2(13) inserted by 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 94?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Supreme Court","Court of Appeals","High Court","District"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Where should a declaration of fidelity and loyalty be made if it is before a Judge of the District Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["In writing, submitted to the court clerk before the trial starts.","In a private meeting with the Judge before any official court proceedings begin.","In open court and may be made at any sitting of the Court.","During a deposition outside of the courtroom."],"justification":"when made before a Judge of the District Court, shall be made in open court and may be made at any sitting of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue* 2. A declaration of fidelity to the nation and loyalty to the State pursuant to section 15 (1) — (as inserted by section 4 of the [Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/23/enacted/en/html)) - of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/act/26/enacted/en/print.html), when made before a Judge of the District Court, shall be made in open court and may be made at any sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 94 - Irish nationality and citizenship', 'Court Rules', 'Where is the prescribed form of declaration for Irish nationality found?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["In the Irish Naturalisation and Administration Act 2014","In the British Nationality Act, 1981","In the Irish Constitution","In the Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations, 1956 (S.I. No. 216 of 1956)"],"justification":"The prescribed form of such declaration is contained in [Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations, 1956 (S.I. No. 216 of 1956)]"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Form of declaration* 3. The prescribed form of such declaration is contained in [Irish Nationality and Citizenship Regulations, 1956 (S.I. No. 216 of 1956)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1956/si/216/made/en/print#).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What court is mentioned in Order 95 - Malicious injuries?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High","Supreme","District","Magistrates"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 95 - Malicious injuries - Court: District'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Acts'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981 and 1986","The Environmental Protection Acts, 1981 and 1986","The Tax Evasion Acts, 1981 and 1986","The Social Security Acts, 1981 and 1986"],"justification":"\"**the Acts**\" means the [Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) and [1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - "**the Acts**" means the [Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) and [1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Malicious Injuries Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 9 of 1981). "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Malicious Injuries (Amendment) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1986); "**ratepayer**" means any ratepayer of a local authority which is a party to any proceedings for compensation under the Acts; "**third party**" means a local authority notified under section 10 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the purpose of the Malicious Injuries Book?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["To record particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate.","To keep track of all criminal convictions and sentences handed down by the courts.","To document the personal information of individuals suspected of malicious activities.","To maintain a record of all civil disputes unrelated to malicious injuries."],"justification":"in which shall be entered particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Malicious Injuries Book* 5. The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book in which shall be entered particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What determines the costs when they are awarded in cases other than applications for compensation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules.","The discretion of the presiding judge based on the complexity of the case.","The amount of time spent by the legal team on the case, as determined by hourly rates.","The fixed statutory rate applicable to all civil cases, regardless of complexity."],"justification":"Costs, where awarded, other than costs of an application for compensation which are payable by a local authority, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs, where awarded, other than costs of an application for compensation which are payable by a local authority, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules. Where liability for compensation is apportioned between two or more local authorities, the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Who notes the settlement in the Malicious Injuries Book?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Clerk.","The Mayor","The Sheriff","The Judge"],"justification":"who shall note the settlement in the Malicious Injuries Book and retain the documents in his or her custody."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Settlements* 7. Where under section 16 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) a local authority settles a claim brought against it, the form of consent or settlement (and withdrawal of application) signed by the parties (or a copy thereof) shall be lodged with the Clerk, who shall note the settlement in the Malicious Injuries Book and retain the documents in his or her custody.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'When must a lodgment under section 16(2) of the Principal Act be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","Not later than three days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","Immediately upon the applicant filing their initial application","Within fourteen days after the date fixed for the hearing of the application"],"justification":"A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Lodgments in court* 8. A lodgment made under section 16 (2) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) shall be made not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application and the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) of these Rules relating to lodgments shall mutatis mutandis apply to such lodgment, but a notice of intention to defend shall not be required.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Can the Court exempt an appellant from entering into a recognisance for appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["No, the Court cannot exempt an appellant from entering into a recognisance for appeal.","The Court can only exempt an appellant if they are a minor or a non-citizen.","Yes, the Court may exempt an appellant from entering into a recognisance for appeal.","Yes, but only if the appellant provides a written guarantee instead of a recognisance."],"justification":"The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation under [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) as amended by [the Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeals to the Circuit Court* 9. (1) The provisions of [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed shall mutatis mutandis apply to every appeal, including an appeal by a ratepayer, taken under section 17 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation under [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) as amended by [the Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What order contains the procedure for cases stated for the opinion of the Supreme Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Order 111","Order 99","Order 102","Order 45"],"justification":"The procedure to be followed in relation to cases stated for the opinion of the Supreme Court under section 18 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) are contained in [Order 102]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-102-District-Cases-stated) of these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Cases stated to the Supreme Court* 10. The procedure to be followed in relation to cases stated for the opinion of the Supreme Court under section 18 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) are contained in [Order 102]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-102-District-Cases-stated) of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court follow when hearing an appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form Schedule A","Form 90, Appendix","Form 75, Section 4","Form 89.2, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e981c916-43d9-4f8b-9225-3fcf1aaf901c/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 29(7) No. 89.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Order of Court* (4) The order of the Court hearing such appeal shall be in accordance with [Form 89.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e981c916-43d9-4f8b-9225-3fcf1aaf901c/Order on appeal - Wildlife Act 1976 section 29(7) No. 89.2.docx/docx/1). (5) Where the Court allows the appeal the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for a wildlife dealer''s licence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A background check approved by the wildlife conservation board","Completion of a mandatory wildlife management course","The payment of a non-refundable application fee","The issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form (Form 89.3, Schedule"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8eac24c9-6d07-4437-a196-902c196cc28d/Notice of application for a certificate authorising the issue - renewal of a wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.3.docx/docx/1))"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8eac24c9-6d07-4437-a196-902c196cc28d/Notice of application for a certificate authorising the issue - renewal of a wildlife dealer''s licence No. 89.3.docx/docx/1)) signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Clerk take when the Court revokes a firearm certificate or a hunting licence and imposes a disqualification?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk updates the national firearms registry with the details of the order without sending any copies.","The Clerk sends a copy of the order of the Court to the Minister as soon as may be.","The Clerk notifies the individual in writing about the revocation and disqualification.","The Clerk sends a copy of the order of the Court to the Chief Justice as soon as may be."],"justification":"Where, pursuant to section 75 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), the Court revokes a firearm certificate or a licence to hunt with firearms and imposes a disqualification, the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Revocation of licence* 5. Where pursuant to section 49 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html) the Court revokes a wildlife dealer''s licence the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court. 6. Where, pursuant to section 75 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), the Court revokes a firearm certificate or a licence to hunt with firearms and imposes a disqualification, the Clerk shall, as soon as may be, send to the Minister a copy of the order of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a notice be served if it is delivered by regular means?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["at least ten days","at least three days","at least five days","at least seven days"],"justification":"at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service of notice* (3) Such notice shall be served upon every person directly affected by the appeal, in accordance with the provisions of section 3 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/39/enacted/en/print.html), at least seven days or, where service is effected by registered prepaid post, at least fourteen days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 89 - Wildlife', 'Court Rules', 'Who should sign the notice issued before an appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The judge presiding over the case.","The court clerk.","The respondent or solicitor for the respondent.","The appellant or solicitor for the appellant."],"justification":"signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of notice* (2) Such appeal shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the appropriate form ( [Form 89.9 Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/f738a32e-a4cc-4e86-adfa-6a504d490ed3/Notice of appeal against a direction under section 78 (3) - Wildlife Act, 1976 section 78 (5) No. 89.9.docx/docx/1)) signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'How can a summons be served if the defendant is a company?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["In accordance with section 45 of the Consumer Protection Act 2018","In accordance with section 37 of the Civil Procedure Rules","In accordance with section 12 of the Employment Rights Act 2002","In accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014"],"justification":"where the defendant is a company, in accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 9 - Service of summons - Court: Superior # Mode of service** 1. No service of a summons shall be required when the defendant, by his solicitor, accepts service, and undertakes in writing to enter an appearance. 2. [[1]](#_ftn1) (1) Service of any summons on the defendant shall, except in the cases in the following rules of this Order specified, be effected: - by personal service upon the person to be served, or - by personal service upon another person referred to in sub-rule (2) on behalf of the person to be served, or - (iii) by the sending of a copy of the summons by registered prepaid post in an envelope addressed to the person to be served at his last known residence or place of business in the State, or at an address in the State for service provided by the person to be served, provided that such service shall not be deemed effective without proof of delivery of the said envelope to the address of the person to be served, or - where the defendant is a company, in accordance with section 51 of the Companies Act 2014. (2) Where it shall appear by affidavit that the defendant is personally within the jurisdiction and that due and reasonable diligence has been exercised in endeavouring to effect personal service on him or her, service of the summons may be effected by delivering a copy thereof at - (a) the defendant''s usual or last known place of residence within the jurisdiction, or - the defendant''s principal or last known place of business or office, to the wife, husband, civil partner (within the meaning of section 3 of the Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010) father, mother, brother, or sister of the defendant, or to any employee of the defendant (the person to whom such copy shall be delivered being of the age of sixteen years or upwards) and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'What is required in terms of service of summons in other actions for recovery of land?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Only the primary occupant of the land needs to be served, regardless of whether they are in receipt of the rents and profits.","Every person who has ever owned a portion of the land must be served, irrespective of their current possession or connection to the land.","Service of summons is not required in actions for recovery of land; a notice posted on the property is sufficient.","Every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof must be served, unless the Court directs otherwise."],"justification":"In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. In the absence of any statutory provision regulating service, every summons issued against a corporation aggregate may be served on the mayor or other head officer, or on the town clerk, clerk, treasurer, or secretary of such corporation; and every summons issued against the inhabitants of a county district or other like district may be served on any officer of the Gárda Síochána not below the rank of superintendent stationed in the county in which such district is situate and every summons issued against the inhabitants of any county or any city or town, or the inhabitants of any franchise, liberty, city, town, or place not being part of the county district or other like district on some peace officer thereof: provided always that in all such cases a sufficient notice of the issuing of the summons shall be given in Iris Oifigiúil and in one of the local newspapers of the county, city, or district in which the defendant or defendants or the officer or other person to be served shall reside, the times for appearing to run in such cases from the day of the publication of such notice in Iris Oifigiúil or such newspaper, whichever shall be the latest; and where, by any statute, provision is made for service of any proceedings upon any corporation, or upon any society or fellowship, or any body or number of persons, whether corporate or incorporate, every summons may be served in the manner so provided. # **III. In particular actions** 8. In an action brought for recovery of land for non-payment of rent or for overholding, it shall not be necessary to serve the summons upon any person other than the person or persons in the actual possession of the land or any part thereof, as tenant or under-tenant. 9. In other actions for the recovery of land, it shall be necessary to serve every person in actual possession, or in receipt of the rents and profits, of the lands or any part thereof, unless the Court shall otherwise direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 9 - Service of summons', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for service by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The person serving the summons must provide a witness signature confirming the delivery of the summons.","The person serving the summons must photograph the recipient holding the envelope as proof of delivery.","The person serving the summons must indorse the summons with the day and date of service and include proof of delivery of the envelope containing the copy of the summons to the address of the person to be served.","The person serving the summons must obtain a notarized affidavit from the recipient acknowledging receipt of the document."],"justification":"Every affidavit of service of a summons by prepaid registered post shall exhibit proof of delivery of the envelope in which a copy of the summons is contained to the address of the person to be served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '10. In actions for the recovery of land service of a summons may be effected either by personal service on the person to be served at any place within the jurisdiction or by delivering a copy of such summons to the wife, husband, child, father, mother, brother, or sister, of such person, at her house, or office, or place of business (the person with whom such copy shall be left being of the age of sixteen years or upwards), and showing to such person the original or duplicate original of such summons, and such service as last aforesaid may be effected whether the person to be served is within the jurisdiction or not. 11. Service of a summons in an action to recover land may, in the case of vacant possession, when it cannot otherwise be effected, be made by posting a copy of the summons upon the door of the dwellinghouse or other conspicuous part of the property; provided, however, that in such case before any judgment by default shall be given, the Court shall be satisfied that there was no person in actual possession or in receipt of the rents and profits on whom other service might have been effected. # General** 12. [[2]](#_ftn2) (1) The person serving a summons shall, within three days at most after service, indorse on the summons the day and date of the service thereof; and every affidavit of service of such summons shall mention the date on which such indorsement was made. (1A) An Indorsement of service by prepaid registered post shall be in the following terms: “INDORSEMENT OF SERVICE served the within summons on [person to be served] by posting the same by prepaid registered post to [him] [her] at [address] on the ... day of ........ 20...” Signed ................ This ... day of ........ 20..”. (2) Every affidavit of service of a summons by prepaid registered post shall exhibit proof of delivery of the envelope in which a copy of the summons is contained to the address of the person to be served.”;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90 - Air Navigation (Eurocontrol)', 'Court Rules', 'How are proceedings initiated for a debt or liquidated money demand?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By serving a notice of arbitration in Form 27.","By issuing a civil summons in Form 39.2","By filing a motion for summary judgment in Form 45.","By issuing a criminal complaint in Form 10."],"justification":"Such proceedings shall be instituted by the issue of a civil summons for a debt or liquidated money demand in the Form 39.2,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings by civil summons* 3. Such proceedings shall be instituted by the issue of a civil summons for a debt or liquidated money demand in the Form 39.2, [Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/content/forms-civil-proceedings), and the provisions of these Rules relating thereto shall mutatis mutandis apply to such proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application under section 48(1) of the Act be served on the railway undertaking?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By hand delivery at least two weeks prior to the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","By electronic submission via email or online portal no later than three days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","By ordinary mail not later than five days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","By prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."],"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 90A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1d1db340-330e-4387-938c-e9a5ecc61795/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 No. 90A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served by the applicant on the railway undertaking by or on whose behalf the notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) was served by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 90A - Railway Infrastructure - Court: District # Order 90A: Railway Infrastructure [1] 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) (No. 55 of 2001); the expression “**railway undertaking**” shall have the meaning given to it by [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html). 2. (1) An application by or on behalf of a person to whom a notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) has been given shall be made to a Judge of the District Court assigned to the court district in which the land which is the subject of said notice is situated. (2) Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 90A.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1d1db340-330e-4387-938c-e9a5ecc61795/Notice of application to prohibit entry on land - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act 2001 No. 90A.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served by the applicant on the railway undertaking by or on whose behalf the notice pursuant to section 48(1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) was served by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. (3) The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4) An order made pursuant to paragraph of sub-section (1) of section 48 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/55/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form 90A.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/26b82729-add3-4081-bb86-32bbaa7cb989/Order (Prohibiting entry on land) - (Specifying conditions for entry on land) - Transport (Railway Infrastructure) Act, 2001 No. 90A.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 90A inserted by [S.I. 534 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/534/made/en/print?q 534&years 2004), effective 9 October 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court take after hearing a complaint under section 25?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The order of the Court shall be in Form 91.3, Schedule","The order of the Court shall be in Form 87.3, Schedule","The order of the Court shall be in Form 91.3, Schedule","The order of the Court shall be in Form 91.2, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eb9b13cb-37ea-4fa3-82e3-9ca378b2c360/Order in relation to excessive barking by a dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.3.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Proceedings under sec. 25* 4. (1) A complaint under section 25 (1) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) that a nuisance has been created as a result of excessive barking by a dog may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area wherein the premises in which the dog, is kept are situated. (2) Where however the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the district within which such area is situated, certifies on a notice of intention to make a complaint that the proceedings are urgent, such notice may be issued for and the proceedings may be heard and determined at any sitting of the Court in that district. (3) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the occupier of the premises in which the dog is kept of the notice referred to in section 25 (2) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) and which is prescribed in the [Control of Dogs (No. 2) Regulations, 1987 (S.I. No. 59 of 1987)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/si/59/made/en/print#). Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html). (4) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall forthwith be lodged with the Clerk. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the complaint shall be in the [Form 91.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/eb9b13cb-37ea-4fa3-82e3-9ca378b2c360/Order in relation to excessive barking by a dog - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.3.docx/docx/1). A copy of such order shall be given to the defendant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 91 - Control of dogs', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a search warrant under section 26 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the applicant resides.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the dog''s owner resides.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the judge resides.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated."],"justification":"An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a search warrant under section 26 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant (sec. 26)* 5. (1) An application by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a search warrant under section 26 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/32/enacted/en/html) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises in which the dog is kept are situated. (2) The application shall be by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 91.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aea308cb-d223-424f-81f3-9650004e1bc1/Information for search warrant - Control of Dogs Act, 1986 section 26 No. 91.4.docx/docx/1). (3) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 91.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/215e6650-979f-4004-8e77-ca3f7cf4a220/Search Warrant - Control of Dogs Act 1986 No. 91.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'What document must be issued before an appeal against a fire safety notice?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["An official complaint filed with the fire department","A formal letter addressed to the local council","A notice of appeal in Form 85.7, Schedule","A notice of appeal in Form 92.3, Schedule"],"justification":"An appeal under section 21 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal in the [Form 92.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68b51881-c383-4d75-b941-078c4ad85a8e/Notice Of Appeal - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.3.docx/docx/1), signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeal against fire safety notice* 4. (1) An appeal under section 21 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) against a fire safety notice shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of appeal in the [Form 92.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/68b51881-c383-4d75-b941-078c4ad85a8e/Notice Of Appeal - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.3.docx/docx/1), signed by the appellant or solicitor for the appellant; which notice shall be given to the respondent fire authority, in accordance with the provisions of sections 21 (2) and 38 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html), at least seven days or, where it is sent by prepaid registered post, at least fourteen days before the date of the sitting of the Court to which the notice of appeal is returnable. (2) A copy of the notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to service, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said sitting of the Court. (3) The order of the Court on hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form 92.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/36288ceb-a7e4-42c5-9a63-dec4bdf9011e/Order On Appeal (Fire Services Act, 1981) No. 92.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 92 - Fire services', 'Court Rules', 'Who makes the application to the court for issuing a warrant under section 22 (7)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A member of the public concerned about fire safety","A person duly appointed by the relevant fire authority","A judge presiding over the case involving the fire authority","A police officer in charge of the local precinct"],"justification":"An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Warrant under section 22 (7)* 5. (1) An application to the Court for the issue of a warrant under section 22 (7) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/30/enacted/en/html) to enter land or a building shall be by the information on oath and in writing of a person duly appointed in that behalf by the relevant fire authority. The information shall be in the [Form 15.3, Schedule B](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d4746c0f-a588-4e2d-85f0-2c1c313b6d04/Information No. 15.3.docx/docx/1), with suitable modifications. (2) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 92.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/86b21325-bbf4-4ecf-99b7-50543cb92d4e/Warrant Under Section 22 (7) Of The Act - Fire Services Act, 1981 No. 92.5.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93 - Housing (private rented dwellings)', 'Court Rules', 'How should notices required by this Order be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["In accordance with the common law rules of service of notices, irrespective of any statutory requirements.","In accordance with the provisions of section 4 of the Act and, if by registered prepaid post, the provisions of section 7 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended.","By personal delivery only, without regard to any statutory provisions regarding service of notices.","In accordance with the provisions of section 5 of the Act and, if by registered prepaid post, the provisions of section 8 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended."],"justification":"Notices required by this Order to be served shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 4 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), and where service is effected by registered prepaid post the provisions of section 7 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended, shall apply."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Service of notices* 4. (1) Notices required by this Order to be served shall be served in accordance with the provisions of section 4 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1982/act/6/enacted/en/html), and where service is effected by registered prepaid post the provisions of section 7 of the Courts Act, 1964, as amended, shall apply. (2) Every such notice shall be served one month at least before the date of sitting of the Court to which the notice has been made returnable. Proof of service shall be by statutory declaration. The original of every such notice, with the statutory declaration endorsed thereon, shall be lodged with the Clerk four days at least before the date of sitting of the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'Which acts does Order relate to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Employment Relations Act 2004 to 2020","Criminal Code Acts 2004 to 2020","Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020","Education Acts 2004 to 2020"],"justification":"Order - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 - Court: District # Order Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020 [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 93C - Residential Tenancies Acts 2004 to 2020', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Act of 2004'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act 2004, as amended","The Residential Tenancies Act 2004, as amended","The Privacy Act 2004, as amended","The Employment Standards Act 2004, as amended"],"justification":"the “**Act of 2004**” means the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Definitions** In this Order— the “**Act of 2004**” means the [Residential Tenancies Act 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html), as amended; “**authorised officer** ” means a person appointed under section 164A of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html) to be an authorised officer; the “**Board**” means the Residential Tenancies Board as established by section 150 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html); a “**determination order**” shall be interpreted having regard to the provisions of section 121 of the [Act of 2004](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Principal Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act, 1980 (No. 10 of 1980)","The Malicious Injuries Act, 1981 (No. 9 of 1981)","The Penal Code Act, 1973 (No. 25 of 1973)","The Vandalism Prevention Act, 1985 (No. 12 of 1985)"],"justification":"\"**the Principal Act**\" means the [Malicious Injuries Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 9 of 1981)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order - "**the Acts**" means the [Malicious Injuries Acts, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) and [1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html); "**the Principal Act**" means the [Malicious Injuries Act, 1981](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 9 of 1981). "**the Act of 1986**" means the [Malicious Injuries (Amendment) Act, 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html) (No. 27 of 1986); "**ratepayer**" means any ratepayer of a local authority which is a party to any proceedings for compensation under the Acts; "**third party**" means a local authority notified under section 10 (1) of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'Who is responsible for keeping the Malicious Injuries Book?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Judge","The Deputy Clerk","The Clerk.","The Sheriff"],"justification":"The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Malicious Injuries Book* 5. The Clerk shall keep a book to be known as the Malicious Injuries Book in which shall be entered particulars of all notices of application and third party notices lodged under this Order and details of all applications and orders made in the proceedings to which the notices relate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'How are costs apportioned when liability for compensation is shared among multiple local authorities?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Similarly apportioned.","Proportionally based on the number of previous compensation claims.","Allocated according to the financial health of each authority.","Equally distributed based on population size."],"justification":"the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Costs* 6. Costs, where awarded, other than costs of an application for compensation which are payable by a local authority, shall be in accordance with the appropriate scale of costs set out in the schedule of costs annexed to these Rules. Where liability for compensation is apportioned between two or more local authorities, the costs (and expenses, if any) awarded to the applicant shall be similarly apportioned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What rules apply to appeals to the Circuit Court under section 17 of the Principal Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The provisions of Order 101 of these Rules relating to criminal proceedings apply mutatis mutandis.","The provisions of Order 42 of these Rules relating to appeals to the High Court apply mutatis mutandis.","The provisions of Order 53 of these Rules relating to civil litigation in general apply mutatis mutandis.","The provisions of Order 101 of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed apply mutatis mutandis."],"justification":"The provisions of [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed shall mutatis mutandis apply to every appeal, including an appeal by a ratepayer, taken under section 17 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Appeals to the Circuit Court* 9. (1) The provisions of [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) of these Rules relating to appeals to the Circuit Court and the forms therein prescribed shall mutatis mutandis apply to every appeal, including an appeal by a ratepayer, taken under section 17 of [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html). (2) The Court may exempt an appellant from the requirement to enter into a recognisance for appeal against a decision on an application for compensation under [the Principal Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1981/act/9/enacted/en/print.html) as amended by [the Act of 1986](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1986/act/27/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What is the consequence of non-compliance with the rules of this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Proceedings will not be rendered void unless the Court directs otherwise.","The parties involved will be subject to immediate fines.","Non-compliance results in automatic dismissal of all cases under the Order.","Proceedings will automatically be considered invalid."],"justification":"Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Non-compliance with rules* 11. Non-compliance with any of the foregoing rules of this Order shall not render any proceedings void unless the Court shall so direct.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 95 - Malicious injuries', 'Court Rules', 'What power does the court have regarding acts or proceedings under the Acts or this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The court may refuse to hear any cases related to the Acts or this Order.","The court may increase the penalties for violations of the Acts or this Order.","The court may extend the time for, set aside wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in a just manner.","The court may delegate its powers to local authorities to enforce the Acts or this Order."],"justification":"The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court may extend time, set aside, amend, etc.* 12. The Court may, in relation to any act or proceedings under the Acts or under this Order, extend the time for, set aside either wholly or in part, amend or otherwise deal with in such manner and on such terms as the Court may think just, such act or proceedings.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act are Order 96 proceedings conducted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Air Pollution Act, 1987","Solid Waste Disposal Act, 1987","Noise Control Act, 1987","Water Quality Improvement Act, 1987"],"justification":"under the Air Pollution Act, 1987 (No. 6 of 1987)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution - Court: District # **Proceedings: - under the Air Pollution Act, 1987 (No. 6 of 1987)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["*Application for warrant*","Arrest Report","Probation Violation Form","Custody Release Notice"],"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a warrant to enter premises be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.","At any police station within the same county as the premises.","Before a judge in any courthouse outside the court district where the premises are located.","Online through a government portal dedicated to warrant applications."],"justification":"An application under section 14 (5) of the Air Pollution Act, 1987 by an authorised person or the person by whom he or she was appointed for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 1. (1) An application under section 14 (5) of the [Air Pollution Act, 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) (hereinafter referred to as "**t****he Act of 1987**") by an authorised person or the person by whom he or she was appointed for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application for a warrant made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By submitting an anonymous tip to the court.","Through a phone call to the local law enforcement agency.","By verbal testimony in front of a judge.","By information on oath and in writing, using Form 96.1, Schedule"],"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96.1, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/833ac759-d6d5-446d-9645-02e736dd0bb0/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act, 1987 section 14 (6) No. 96.1.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant to enter premises be in when granted based on certain information?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 96.2, Schedule","Form 97.3, Schedule A","Form 95.4, Schedule","Form 96.1, Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of warrant* (3) A warrant to enter premises granted on foot of such information shall be in [Form 96.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/621b859c-730e-4948-9a51-9531bb7a22f4/Warrant To Enter Premises - Air Pollution Act 1987 section 14(6) No. 96.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application be made for an order relating to an emission from a premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At the nearest post office to the location of the premises where the emission is taking place.","Through an online form on the official government website of the state where the premises are located.","At any local police station within the county where the premises are located.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises concerned are situated or wherein the emission concerned takes place."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises concerned are situated or wherein the emission concerned takes place"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 2. (1) An application to the Court under subsection (1) of section 28A (inserted by the third schedule to the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) — No. 7 of 1992) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) for an order pursuant to that subsection in relation to an emission from a premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises concerned are situated or wherein the emission concerned takes place.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served if it is sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["no specific timeframe, as long as it''s before the hearing","at least fifteen days","at least twenty-one days","exactly fourteen days"],"justification":"at least twenty-one days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of, service and lodgment of notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bc6e99d6-bc5d-4161-b3de-f92395301595/Notice Of Application For AnOrder Under Section 28a(1) - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.3.docx/docx/1), upon the respondent in a manner prescribed in section 15 of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), and shall be served at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court order take when granting an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 96.4, Schedule","Form 101, Schedule A","Form 96.5, Appendix","Form 96.3, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 96. 4, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- order of the Court on* (3) The order of the Court on granting the application shall be in the [Form 96. 4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4acb8965-52dd-49c3-8964-be16ab8e36da/Order Under Section 28a (1) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must the Clerk transmit when an application is transferred to the Circuit Court or High Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["a summary of the case, a list of witnesses, and the judge''s personal notes","a certified copy of the order, any other orders made in the proceedings, the notice of application, and any other documents or exhibits related to the application","the applicant''s birth certificate, a copy of the court seal, and the clerk''s personal identification","a transcript of all hearings, a video recording of the proceedings, and the original signatures of all parties involved"],"justification":"the Clerk shall forthwith transmit a certified copy of the said order and any other order made in the proceedings, the notice of application and any other document or exhibit handed into court in relation to that application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *transfer to Circuit Court or High Court* (4) Where, pursuant to the provisions of section 28A (1) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), the Court transfers an application made under the said subsection (1) to the Circuit Court or the High Court, the order so transferring shall be in the [Form 96.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d0549e9f-fc83-46fc-902c-fb879996b208/Order Transferring An Application To The Circuit Court High Court - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.5.docx/docx/1), and the Clerk shall forthwith transmit a certified copy of the said order and any other order made in the proceedings, the notice of application and any other document or exhibit handed into court in relation to that application, to the appropriate County Registrar or, as the case may be, Registrar of the High Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for an order under section 55 (2) of the Act of 1987?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The submission of a preliminary hearing request form under Section 70 of the Act of 1987.","The issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in Form 96.6, Schedule","The issuance of a summons in Form 101.2, Schedule A.","The filing of a sworn affidavit under Section 34 of the Act of 1987."],"justification":"An application for an order under section 55 (2) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) deeming consent to have been given and directing that required works be carried out shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e2bf300-61a3-4537-8279-f1c07b2ba9c7/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (2) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.6.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 55 (2)* (2) An application for an order under section 55 (2) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) deeming consent to have been given and directing that required works be carried out shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e2bf300-61a3-4537-8279-f1c07b2ba9c7/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (2) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.6.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application for an order under section 55(3) of the Act of 1987?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The submission of a written consent form signed by both parties.","The issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in Form 96.7, Schedule","The issue and service upon the applicant of a notice in Form 96.7, Schedule","The filing of a declaration of intent under Section 42 of the same Act."],"justification":"An application for an order under section 55 (3) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) in relation to the cost of works required to be carried out pursuant to that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8d7561b3-10ad-402f-98b6-915b81fc34f5/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (3) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.7.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 55 (3)* (3) An application for an order under section 55 (3) of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html) in relation to the cost of works required to be carried out pursuant to that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a notice in the [Form 96.7, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8d7561b3-10ad-402f-98b6-915b81fc34f5/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 55 (3) Of The Act - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.7.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a notice of application be served if it is not sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["seven days","three days","five days","ten days"],"justification":"Service shall be effected at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- service of notices of* (4) A notice of application required by this rule to be served shall be served in a manner prescribed in section 15 of that Act. Service shall be effected at least seven days or, if being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the order of the Court take when granting an application under this rule?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The order should be in Form 101.5 or 101.6, Schedule A, with any necessary modifications.","The order should be in Form 45.2 or 45.3, Schedule with any necessary modifications.","The order should follow the standard template provided by the Supreme Court, without any specific forms mentioned in Rule 96.","The order should be in Form 96.8 or 96.9, Schedule with any necessary modifications."],"justification":"The order of the Court on granting an application to which this rule relates shall be in the [Form 96.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e938bf-1419-4041-97b2-31ee706f29b5/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (2) - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.8.docx/docx/1) or [96.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/402be530-61dd-4d7a-b27f-d020636ebd9e/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (3) - Air Pollution Act 1967 No. 96.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, with any necessary modifications required in particular cases."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- orders of the Court* (5) The order of the Court on granting an application to which this rule relates shall be in the [Form 96.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1e938bf-1419-4041-97b2-31ee706f29b5/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (2) - Air Pollution Act 1987 No. 96.8.docx/docx/1) or [96.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/402be530-61dd-4d7a-b27f-d020636ebd9e/Order Pursuant To Section 55 (3) - Air Pollution Act 1967 No. 96.9.docx/docx/1), Schedule as the case may be, with any necessary modifications required in particular cases. # **Proceedings: -****under the Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 (No. 1 of 1977)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1977'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Water Conservation Act, 1977 (No. 3 of 1977)","The Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 (No. 1 of 1977)","The Local Government (Air Pollution) Act, 1977 (No. 1 of 1977)","The Environmental Protection Act, 1977 (No. 2 of 1977)"],"justification":"\"**the Act of 1977**\" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 4. In this Order - "**t****he Act of 1977**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977); "**the** **Act of 1990**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1990).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Overview of sec. 10","*Application under sec. 10*","Introduction to sec. 10","Conclusion of sec. 10"],"justification":"*Application under sec. 10*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application under sec. 10*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an order under section 10(1) of the Act of 1977 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the relevant waters, land, or other premises.","At any regional office of the Department of Environmental Protection within the state.","Online through the official government portal for all cases under the Act of 1977.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district where the relevant waters, land, or other premises are located."],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 5. (1) An application for an order under section 10 (1) of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of [the Act of 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html)) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the waters concerned or the land or other premises from which the entry or discharge concerned takes place is or are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Who must receive the notice when the applicant is not a local authority or regional board?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The national environmental agency","The applicant''s nearest relative","The local community service center","The local authority or regional board in whose functional area the waters concerned are situated"],"justification":"upon the local authority or regional board in whose functional area the waters concerned are situated"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/213ab9a4-3a14-41b0-9789-ef367e4837a6/Notice Of Application For An Order Under Section 10 (1) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977 No. 96.10.docx/docx/1), upon the person against whom the order is sought (the respondent) and, where the applicant is not a local authority or regional board, upon the local authority or regional board in whose functional area the waters concerned are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served if it is sent by registered prepaid post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least twenty-one days","at least ten days","at least fourteen days","at least thirty days"],"justification":"at least twenty-one days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- service* Service of the notice shall be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 32 of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) at least seven days or, where service is being effected by registered prepaid post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The original notice, a copy of the service email confirmation, and where appropriate, the affidavit of service.","The original notice, a statutory declaration of service, and where appropriate, the receipt of payment.","The draft notice, a statutory declaration of service, and where appropriate, the proof of delivery.","The original notice, a statutory declaration of service, and where appropriate, the certificate of posting."],"justification":"When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '#### *- lodgment* When service has been effected and declared the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting) shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["*Conditions of probation*","*Application for warrant*","*Procedure for arrest*","*Criteria for bail*"],"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a warrant to enter a premises or vessel be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At the nearest federal courthouse regardless of the location of the premises or vessel.","At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or vessel is situated.","At any police station within the state where the premises or vessel is located.","At an online judicial platform approved by the Department of Justice."],"justification":"An application for a warrant under section 28 (7) of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) to enter a premises or vessel may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or vessel is situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 6. (1) An application for a warrant under section 28 (7) of [the Act of 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) to enter a premises or vessel may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises or vessel is situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application be made under this order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By verbal declaration before a notary.","By information on oath and in writing in Form 96.12, Schedule","Through an oral testimony in front of a judge.","By filing a digital form through an online portal."],"justification":"Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 96.12, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by information on oath and in writing in the [Form 96.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/d8ff4043-3dea-48f7-8fd0-3a0479af492e/Information (application for warrant to enter) - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977 section 28 (7) No. 96.12.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant granted pursuant to an application take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 96.14, Schedule A","Form 96.13, Schedule","Form 96.12, Schedule","Form 96.13, Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.13, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) A warrant granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8ccd799c-d469-43b7-94f8-ec29a93d3678/Warrant To Enter A Premises - Vessel - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977 No. 96.13.docx/docx/1). # **Proceedings:****- under the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (No. 7 of 1992)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["*Application for warrant*","*Arrest report*","*Investigation report*","*Witness testimony*"],"justification":"*Application for warrant*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for warrant*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a warrant to enter premises under section 13(6) of the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.","At the nearest police station in the vicinity of the premises.","At any local government office within the county where the premises are located.","At the Environmental Protection Agency headquarters in Dublin."],"justification":"An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 7. (1) An application under section 13 (6) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) for a warrant to enter premises may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the premises are situated.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How is the application for a warrant made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By submitting a verbal request over the phone to a police officer.","By sworn information on oath and in writing, using Form 96.14, Schedule","Through an informal email to the local magistrate.","Orally in front of a judge during a public hearing."],"justification":"Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96. 14, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96. 14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/360bf441-bfcd-4c5c-a1d8-2d9f77156e4c/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 section 13 (6) No. 96.14.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the issue of the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant to enter premises take when granted pursuant to an application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It should be in Form 96.1, Schedule A.","It should be in Form 96.15, Schedule","It should be in Form 45.7, Schedule","It should be in Form 96.25, Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant to enter premises which is granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.15, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) A warrant to enter premises which is granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.15, Schedule C.](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7a57d6db-6553-4b07-b191-79c676846eac/Warrant To Enter Premises - Environmental Protection Agency Act 1992 section 13(6) No. 96.15.docx/docx/1)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Report on traffic congestion issues","Grievance concerning water quality","*Complaint in relation to noise*","Complaint in relation to lighting"],"justification":"*Complaint in relation to noise*"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Complaint in relation to noise*'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Where can a complaint about noise be made under section 108(1) of the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located.","At any environmental agency office in the state capital.","At any police station within the county where the source of the noise is located.","At any municipal council meeting within the city limits where the noise is occurring."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue for* 8. (1) A complaint to the Court under section 108 (1) of the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/7/enacted/en/html) in relation to noise which is alleged to be so loud, so continuous, so repeated, of such duration or pitch or occurring at such times as to give reasonable cause for annoyance may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district wherein the source of the noise is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What document must precede a complaint under this regulation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["An official letter of apology from the accused party","A signed affidavit supporting the complaint","A preliminary investigation report","A notice of the intention to make the complaint"],"justification":"Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the form prescribed in the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (Noise) Regulations, 1994 (S.I. No. 179 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/si/179/made/en/print), of the intention to make such a complaint, within such time as may be specified in the notice, upon the defendant, that is to say, the person alleged to have made or have caused or have been responsible for the noise."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of service lodgment* (2) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the form prescribed in the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (Noise) Regulations, 1994 (S.I. No. 179 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/si/179/made/en/print), of the intention to make such a complaint, within such time as may be specified in the notice, upon the defendant, that is to say, the person alleged to have made or have caused or have been responsible for the noise. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 14 of that Act, and the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a court order take when made under section 108(1)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be in the form specified in Form 78.11, Schedule A.","It should be in the form specified in Form 45.32, Schedule","It should be in the form specified in Form 96.17, Schedule","It should be in the form specified in Form 96.16, Schedule"],"justification":"the order shall be in the [Form 96.16, Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of court order* (3) Where, upon hearing such complaint, the Court makes an order under the said section 108 (1), the order shall be in the [Form 96.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ac512aa7-a167-48df-972c-5753c0deaf43/Order Pursuant To Section 108 (1) In Relation To Noise - Environmental Protection Agency Act 1992 No. 96.16.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice of application be served on the proprietor or person in charge of the premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Not less than thirty days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","Not later than three weeks before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","Not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","Not earlier than two days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."],"justification":"shall be served on or given to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises by the applicant not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 96A - Food Safety - Court: District # **Order 96A: Food Safety******[1]**** 1. In this Order- “**the Act**” means the [Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/29/enacted/en/html) (No. 45 of 1998); the expressions “**authorised officer**”, “**Authority**”, “**improvement notice**”, and “**official agency**” shall have the meanings given to each of them by the Act. 2(1). An application by or on behalf of the Authority or an official agency for an improvement order pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which are situated the premises which are the subject of an improvement notice served on a proprietor or person in charge of a premises pursuant to sub-section (1) of Section 52 of the Act. (2). Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 96A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/faf5ed3b-091e-4a6d-b1f9-446227bd8005/Notice Of Application - Food Safety Authority of Ireland Act 1998, section 52 No. 96A.1.docx/docx/1) and shall be served on or given to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises by the applicant not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. Such notice may be served or given - - (a) by addressing it to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises by name and delivering it to him or her, - by leaving it at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, - by sending it by post in a prepaid registered letter addressed to the proprietor or person in charge of the premises at the address at which he or she ordinarily resides or carries on business, - if an address for the service of notices has been furnished by the proprietor or person in charge of the premises, by leaving it at, or sending it by prepaid registered post addressed to him or her to that address,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'How can a notice be served if the proprietor''s address cannot be found?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises.","By sending it via email to a generic email address associated with the business.","By leaving it at the nearest post office without any specific instructions.","By posting it on social media platforms such as Facebook or Twitter."],"justification":"where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises, or - where there is a facility for receiving a facsimile of the notice by electronic means at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, by transmitting a facsimile of the notice by such means to that address, provided that the notice is also served or given in any of the other ways referred to in this sub-rule. (3). The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4). An order made pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act on such application shall be in the [Form 96A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3279a05f-9ef0-431b-a7a4-f227273726ba/Order (Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998, Section 52) No. 96A.2.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 96A inserted by [S.I. 700 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/700/made/en/print?q 700&years 2004), effective 14 November 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 2003'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Public Order (Amendment) Act 2003 (No. 16 of 2004)","The Public Order (Criminal Justice) Act 2003 (No. 15 of 2003)","The Criminal Justice (Public Safety) Act 2003 (No. 17 of 2003)","The Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 (No. 16 of 2003)"],"justification":"“**the Act of 2003**” means the [Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 2003);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 - Court: District # Order Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 ****[1]**** 1. In this Order: *“**the Act of 2003**” means the [Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 2003);* *“**t****he Act of 2010**” means the [Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 2010);* *“**closure order**” has the meaning given to it by section 2 of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html);* *“**prohibition order**” means an order under section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html)*.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must a copy of the notice of application be served on the licensee or manager of the catering premises?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Immediately upon filing the application, without any specific time frame.","Not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","Not later than fourteen days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.","Not later than three days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the licensee or manager of the catering premises concerned not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 2. An application pursuant to section 4 of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html) for a closure order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which: in the case of a food stall or food vehicle, the stall or vehicle is used for the sale of food or is kept when not being so used, or* in the case of any other catering premises, the catering premises are situated*. 3. Notice of an application for a closure order shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/71b5ddfd-cfee-4600-8583-543082c2183c/Notice of application for closure order - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 section 4 No. 96B.1.docx/docx/1) and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the notice in writing which was served in accordance with section 4(2) of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the licensee or manager of the catering premises concerned not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct. A closure order shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b886988c-eae2-4635-a63c-c5b4191e0a68/Closure order - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 section 5 No. 96B.2.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of an application for a prohibition order be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 96A.4, Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule"],"justification":"Notice of an application for a prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bee0d4e5-64ff-4945-b634-82d19c4b730d/Notice of application for prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the prohibition notice which was served in accordance with section 7 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 5. An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) applies) of the Court for the court district in which: the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or* any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or* *(iii) any such structure, stall or vehicle is kept when not in use.* 6. Notice of an application for a prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bee0d4e5-64ff-4945-b634-82d19c4b730d/Notice of application for prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the prohibition notice which was served in accordance with section 7 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct in accordance with section 8(2) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2bf9faa1-8cf8-414b-8224-7135236e0c97/Prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule The applicant shall serve a copy of the order on the respondent. Where a prohibition order specifies any premises to which the order relates, and the owner of the premises is not the respondent, the applicant shall, where practicable, cause a copy of the prohibition order to be served by registered post on the owner of the premises concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when applying to vary a prohibition order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form 85A.7","Form"],"justification":"such an application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96B.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6c73a20e-fed8-487c-a7a4-7bf4e49b1b1d/Notice of application to vary a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. An application pursuant to section 9(1) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for an order varying a prohibition order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the prohibition order was made. Save where the Court otherwise directs or permits, such an application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96B.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6c73a20e-fed8-487c-a7a4-7bf4e49b1b1d/Notice of application to vary a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application (with a copy of the prohibition order appended, where the person applying is in possession of a copy of that order) shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána who applied for the prohibition order concerned not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The member shall produce the prohibition order or a true copy at the hearing. Where the Court makes an order varying the prohibition order, the order shall be in the [Form 96B.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de3b0ecb-1487-4f28-984b-c4a6e024e2dd/Order varying a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.7.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 545 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/545/made/en/print?q 545&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 536 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/536/made/en/print?q 536&years 2011), effective 4 April 2011'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Preliminary","Introduction","Conclusion","Methodology"],"justification":"**Preliminary**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Preliminary**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''section 28 order''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["An order under section 28 of the Employment Rights Act 2022","An order under section 28 of the Taxation Law 2023","An order under section 28 of the Criminal Justice (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2023","An order under section 28 of the Environmental Protection Act 2021"],"justification":"“**section 28 order**” means an order under section 28 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _1. Definitions_ 1. In this Order— “**the 2001 Act**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html); “**the 2006 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice Act 2006](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 26 of 2006); “**the 2023 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2023); “**behaviour order**” has the meaning given to it by section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html), (inserted by section 162 of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html)); “**civil order**” has the same meaning as in section 113(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html); “**relevant conduct**” has the same meaning as in section 27 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html); “**section 28 order**” means an order under section 28 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Economic Policies under the 2006 Act","Military Orders under the 2006 Act","Civil Orders under the 2006 Act","Environmental Regulations under the 2006 Act"],"justification":"**Civil Orders under the 2006 Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Civil Orders under the 2006 Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what section of the 2006 Act can an application for a civil order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section 114(1)","Section 116(1)","Section 115(2)","Section 115(1)"],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _2. Application for civil order_ 2. An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of application for a civil order be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule"],"justification":"Notice of an application for a civil order may be in the Form Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _3. Notice of application_ 3.(1) Notice of an application for a civil order may be in the [Form 96C.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b1ee9a62-c7ab-4d87-a94c-ee0d07e96a81/Notice Of Application For Civil Order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115 No. 96C.1.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section 114 of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon the respondent in accordance with Order 10 not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form can a civil order take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It may be in the form specified in Form Schedule","It may be in the form specified in Form Schedule A.","It may be in the form specified in Form Schedule","It may be in the form specified in Form Schedule"],"justification":"A civil order may be in the [Form 96C.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1644c92a-97fa-4443-b38b-aae26e085127/Civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 115 No. 96C.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _4. Form and service of civil order_ 4. (1) A civil order may be in the [Form 96C.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1644c92a-97fa-4443-b38b-aae26e085127/Civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 115 No. 96C.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The applicant must cause a copy of any civil order to be served on the respondent in accordance with Order 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application to vary or discharge a civil order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At the nearest police station during business hours.","Online through the national government''s official website.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person subject to the civil order resides at the time such application is made.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant resides at the time such application is made."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 115(7) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for an order discharging or varying a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person subject to the civil order resides at the time such application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _5. Application to vary or discharge a civil order_ 5.(1) An application pursuant to section 115(7) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for an order discharging or varying a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person subject to the civil order resides at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c78b0a4-b7e9-44f7-89e5-4ee90cab0a9d/Notice of application for variation - discharge of civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115(7) No. 96C.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with true copies of the notice of application for a civil order and attachments thereto and of the civil order) must be served upon the person referred to in section 115(8) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) in accordance with Order 10 not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application to vary or discharge and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Clerk take if an order discharging or varying a civil order is made in a different Court area?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Clerk sends a copy of the order to the parties involved but takes no further action.","The Clerk updates the court records without notifying any other Clerk or party.","The Clerk sends notice to the Clerk assigned to the original Court area that the civil order has been discharged or varied.","The Clerk informs the local police department about the discharge or variation of the civil order."],"justification":"Where an order discharging or varying a civil order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the civil order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the civil order was made notice that the civil order has been discharged, or a copy of the civil order as varied, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _6. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 6.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a civil order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the original or a copy of the civil order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a civil order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the civil order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the civil order was made notice that the civil order has been discharged, or a copy of the civil order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Behaviour Orders under the 2001 Act","Environmental Regulations under the 2001 Act","Taxation Provisions under the 2001 Act","Powers of Local Authorities under the 2001 Act"],"justification":"**Behaviour Orders under the 2001 Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Behaviour Orders under the 2001 Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what section of the 2001 Act can an application for a behaviour order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section","Section","Section","Section"],"justification":"pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a behaviour order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _7. Application for behaviour order_ 7. An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the notice of application for a behaviour order be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 101A.1, Schedule A","Form Schedule","Form Schedule","Form Schedule"],"justification":"Notice of an application for a behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cadca7a-81ac-4669-9325-afdd44c98f72/Notice Of Application For Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001, section 257D.No. 96C.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _8. Notice of application_ 8.(1) Notice of an application for a behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cadca7a-81ac-4669-9325-afdd44c98f72/Notice Of Application For Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001, section 257D.No. 96C.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or a copy of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who must receive a copy of a behaviour order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The persons referred to in section of the 2001 Act.","The persons referred to in section of the 2001 Act.","The persons referred to in section of the 2001 Act.","The persons referred to in section of the 2001 Act."],"justification":"The applicant must cause a copy of any such order to be served on each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _9. Form and service of civil order_ 9.(1) A behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1dcc90a1-d68f-4ab2-8efb-e8c4085f68be/Behaviour order - Children Act 2001, section No. 96C.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The applicant must cause a copy of any such order to be served on each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application to vary or discharge a behaviour order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before a magistrate at any district court within the state where the child was originally charged with the behavior offense.","Through an online portal on the official government website dedicated to juvenile cases, regardless of the child''s current residence.","At any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made.","At any sitting of the Family Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order was residing at the time such application was first issued."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging or varying a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _10. Application to vary or discharge a behaviour order_ 10.(1) An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging or varying a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99023c06-0ef4-4c8e-bc40-58193f9b66d8/Notice Of Application For Variation - Discharge Of Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001 section No. 96C.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with copies of the notice of application for a behaviour order and attachments thereto and of the behaviour order) must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application for discharge or variation and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What happens when the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The varied terms must be recorded in a separate document and appended to the original order without requiring the Judge''s signature.","The original order is nullified, and a completely new order with the varied terms must be issued by the court.","The varied terms are verbally communicated during a court hearing and do not require any written documentation.","The terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge."],"justification":"Where the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _11. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 11.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Section 28 Rules under the 2023 Regulations","Section 28 Orders under the 2023 Act","Section 28 Guidelines under the 2022 Act","Section 17 Orders under the 2023 Act"],"justification":"**Section 28 Orders under the 2023 Act**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Section 28 Orders under the 2023 Act**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under Part 5 of the 2023 Act be brought?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before a virtual hearing conducted by video conference without regard to the physical location of the applicant or the respondent.","Before a sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the residence of the applicant or the respondent.","Before a sitting of the Court for the Court District in which the applicant or the respondent resides or is treated by the Court as residing, or a special sitting of the Court arranged in accordance with section 38 of the 2023 Act.","Before any local magistrate''s court within the state where the applicant or the respondent resides."],"justification":"Proceedings under Part 5 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before: - a sitting of the Court for the Court District in which the applicant or the respondent resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 36(2) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) as residing, or - a special sitting of the Court arranged in accordance with section 38 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _12. Venue_ 12. Proceedings under Part 5 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before: - a sitting of the Court for the Court District in which the applicant or the respondent resides or is treated by the Court in accordance with section 36(2) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) as residing, or - a special sitting of the Court arranged in accordance with section 38 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'In what form may an order of the Court granting an application for a section 28 order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _13. Section 28 Order_ 13.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for the notice of application for an interim section 28 order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["[Form 96C.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/447149a6-8627-48f0-bacc-7a2e97745c47/Form Notice of Application for Interim Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12.docx/docx/1)","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"in the [Form 96C.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/447149a6-8627-48f0-bacc-7a2e97745c47/Form Notice of Application for Interim Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the respondent"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _14. Interim order inter partes_ 14.(1) When a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(12) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an interim section 28 order (save where made on or in the course of the hearing of an application for a section 28 order) may be made by motion on notice in the [Form 96C.9](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/447149a6-8627-48f0-bacc-7a2e97745c47/Form Notice of Application for Interim Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12.docx/docx/1), Schedule to the respondent (such notice and a copy of the grounding affidavit or information to be served on the respondent at least two clear days before the hearing) and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'In what form can an order of the Court granting an parte application be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["In Form","In Form","In Form","In Form"],"justification":"in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _15. parte order_ 15.(1) Whether or not a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(7) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an parte section 28 order may be made at any sitting of the Court mentioned in rule 12 and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'In what form may an order of the Court granting an application to vary or discharge a section 28 order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/16ac0514-2f37-4c86-af3b-394b8d14a06e/Form Order Varying Discharging Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 29.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _16. Vary or discharge section 28 order_ 16.(1) An application to the Court under section 29 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) to vary or discharge a section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 96C.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/a60d4b1e-1e78-491f-a433-d9466e30eaef/Form Summons to Vary Discharge Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 29.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/16ac0514-2f37-4c86-af3b-394b8d14a06e/Form Order Varying Discharging Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 29.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served before an application for a further section 28 order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a further section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _17. Further section 28 order_ 17.(1) An application to the Court under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a further section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who must the Clerk give or send a certified copy of the order to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Minister for Justice, the Director of Public Prosecutions, and the solicitor representing either party in the case.","The local postmaster, the applicant''s next-of-kin, and any member of the public who requests it.","The applicant, the respondent, a member of the Garda Síochána who applied in accordance with section 31, the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the station for the area where the person for whom the order is made resides, and possibly another Garda Síochána member if the person previously resided elsewhere and the member had received a copy of the original order.","The applicant''s employer, the landlord of the applicant, and the chief medical officer of health."],"justification":"- (a) to the applicant, and - to the respondent, - where an application has been made by a member of the Garda Síochána acting in accordance with section 31 of [the 2023 Act], to that member, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person, for whose benefit the order is made, resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a section 28 order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided, but only if that member had previously been sent a copy of the section 28 order, or any order relating thereto under section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act] and this rule,"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _18. Clerk to supply copies of orders_ 18. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a section 28 order or makes a further order under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), the Clerk must, in accordance with section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant, and - to the respondent, by ordinary prepaid post, and - where an application has been made by a member of the Garda Síochána acting in accordance with section 31 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), to that member, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person, for whose benefit the order is made, resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a section 28 order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided, but only if that member had previously been sent a copy of the section 28 order, or any order relating thereto under section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) and this rule, and - where the order in question prohibits or restricts the respondent from approaching a specified place and the Court so directs, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the specified place is situated, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How long before the hearing must a summons be served by prepaid ordinary post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At least three days","At least five days","At least seven days","At least fourteen days"],"justification":"A summons issued under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) in accordance with this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _19. Service_ 19.(1) A summons issued under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) in accordance with this Order must be served by the Clerk by prepaid ordinary post upon the person to whom it is directed at least seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. Where, however, the Clerk, having consulted the Judge for the time being assigned to the Court District in which the summons is being issued, otherwise certifies on the summons that the proceedings are urgent, the summons may be served at least two days before the date fixed for the hearing. (2) The Clerk must endorse on the original of every such summons served the date and place of posting of the envelope containing the copy summons for service and the party to whom the envelope was posted (or such other particulars of service as are appropriate to the case) and that endorsement shall be prima facie evidence of such service. (3) The summons shall be deemed to be issued when it has been signed by the Judge or the Clerk. It shall be deemed to be served at the time at which the said envelope would be delivered in the ordinary course of post. (4) Without prejudice to the power of the Court to give such a direction of its own motion, a request for a direction under section 34(4) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) may be made viva voce at the time the order is made or if made subsequently may be made parte at any sitting of the Court for the Court District. (5) The Court may, for the purpose of ensuring the expeditious hearing of applications under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), direct or deem sufficient service of a document under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) by other means, including by electronic mail, where it is satisfied that such service is likely to bring, or has brought, the document to the attention of the person to be served.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Under what conditions can the court give a direction under section 32 or section 39 of the 2023 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Upon a request made by the presiding judge alone, without input from any parties or witnesses.","Upon a request made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, or on its own motion.","When there is a unanimous agreement among all jurors regarding the necessity of such a direction.","Only when requested by a third-party observer present in the courtroom."],"justification":"- (a) upon a request for such a direction made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, and having heard the parties, or - on its own motion and having heard the parties"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _20. Direction in relation to cross-examination or for evidence through television link_ 20. The Court may give a direction under section 32 or section 39 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) at any time in the course of proceedings under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)– - (a) upon a request for such a direction made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, and having heard the parties, or - on its own motion and having heard the parties, and may adjourn the proceedings for the purposes of section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for such period as it considers appropriate in the circumstances, and may make such orders and give further directions in accordance with section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) accordingly. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2007), effective 20 July 2007, substituted in entirety including title by 364 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/364/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,and Behaviour Orders) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 2 September 2024. Superseded amendments: Order title substituted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007 Order rule 7 inserted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 97 - Road Traffic?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["District","Magistrates'' Court","Supreme Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 97 - Road Traffic - Court: District # Order 97: Road Traffic**[1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''2016 Act'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Road Traffic Act 2016 (No. 21 of 2016)","The Consumer Protection Act 2016 (No. 25 of 2016)","The Environmental Protection Act 2016 (No. 15 of 2016)","The Employment Rights Act 2016 (No. 21 of 2016)"],"justification":"the “**2016 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) (No. 21 of 2016);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 1. In this Order— the “**1961 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 1961](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 1961) (as amended); the “**1968 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 1968](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html) (No. 25 of 1968); the “**2016 Act**” means the [Road Traffic Act 2016](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) (No. 21 of 2016); the “**Agreement**” has the same meaning as in section 40(12)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an appeal be made under section 18(8)(c)(ii) of the 1961 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any local magistrate''s court within the state where the vehicle is registered.","At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location of the vehicle.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the vehicle is ordinarily kept.","At any sitting of the High Court irrespective of the vehicle''s usual place of storage."],"justification":"An appeal pursuant to section 18(8)(c)(ii) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the refusal of the issuing authority to issue a test certificate may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the vehicle is ordinarily kept."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Venue for appeals - under section 18(8)(c)(ii)* 2. (1) An appeal pursuant to section 18(8)(c)(ii) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the refusal of the issuing authority to issue a test certificate may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the vehicle is ordinarily kept. (2) An appeal'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act was section 33(3A)(b) inserted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The 1974 Act","The 1959 Act","The 1982 Act","The 1968 Act."],"justification":"inserted by section 21 of the [1968 Act](https://www.irishstatatusbook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 33(3A)(b)* - pursuant to section 33(3A)(b) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [1968 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of the issuing authority to carry out a test,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What does section 33(5)(a) pertain to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Deferring decisions by issuing authorities to issue certificates of competency","Granting permissions for construction projects","Providing guidelines for training programs","Issuing fines for non-compliance with safety standards"],"justification":"against the deferring of a decision by the issuing authority to issue a certificate of competency"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 33(5)(a)* - pursuant to section 33(5)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the deferring of a decision by the issuing authority to issue a certificate of competency,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Under what section can a person appeal against the decision of the issuing authority?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Section of the 1961 Act","Section of the 1961 Act","Section of the 1961 Act","Section 33(6)(a) of the 1961 Act"],"justification":"pursuant to section 33(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the decision of the issuing authority under section 33(4) of the [961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under sec. 33(6)(a)* - (iii) pursuant to section 33(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the decision of the issuing authority under section 33(4) of the [961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html), or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Where may an appeal be made under section 34(5)(a) of the 1961 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Before the Supreme Court during its special sessions irrespective of the appellant''s ordinary residence.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent ordinarily resides.","At any sitting of the High Court regardless of the appellant''s place of residence."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 34(5)(a)* - pursuant to section 34(5)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) against the decision of the issuing authority under section 34(4) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) or the deferring of such a decision. may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the appellant ordinarily resides.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a special disqualification order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Through an online form on the official government website, regardless of the person''s residence.","At the nearest community center within the court area where the person is employed.","At any police station in the court area where the person is registered to vote.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person ordinarily resides."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 28(1) or 28(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by an officer of the Garda Síochána for a special disqualification order in respect of any person may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such person ordinarily resides."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Applications under sec. 28* 4. (1) An application pursuant to section 28(1) or 28(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by an officer of the Garda Síochána for a special disqualification order in respect of any person may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which such person ordinarily resides. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.12](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ae22a254-870f-44a4-bd3e-b280d78858e6/Notice Of Application For Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(1) No. 97.12.docx/docx/1) or [97.13](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/067c742b-8c5b-4b41-b82f-6cf2d2128506/Notice Of Application For Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(2) No. 97.13.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate, signed by such officer. (3) Such notice shall be served upon the person to whom the application relates at least 10 days before the date of hearing of the application. (4) The original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the application may be in the Form [97.14](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/69c2a360-7094-4294-b022-cf625a0f95e5/Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(1) No. 97.14.docx/docx/1) or [97.15](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/77ea9fd7-680c-4a41-b505-f6f826d7416f/Special Disqualification Order - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 28(2) No. 97.15.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be used when making an application for removal of a disqualification?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 98.20","Form 97.15","Form 96.14","Form 97.16"],"justification":"Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/df3fa82d-8c2f-4a31-8d00-d6b7d688da91/Notice Of Application For The Removal Of Disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(2)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for removal of disqualification* 5.[2] (1) An application pursuant to section 29(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) for the removal of a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the court for the court area in which the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/df3fa82d-8c2f-4a31-8d00-d6b7d688da91/Notice Of Application For The Removal Of Disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(2)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the district in which the applicant ordinarily resides at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the application. (4) The original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the Form [97.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de60ac49-ced2-4787-bc17-76e5b08f93fd/Order for the removal of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.17.docx/docx/1) or [97.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64ffa69e-d7ad-4458-96f0-da64dc1e1c1d/Order confirming period specified in order of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for the warrant if the application is granted by the Judge of the District Court or the Peace Commissioner?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 97.22 Schedule","Form 97.22 Schedule","Form 85.33 Schedule A","Form 97.21 Schedule"],"justification":"the warrant may be in the [Form 97.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/76d54504-08eb-4f65-9395-646de3aa29bf/Information For Search Warrant - Road Traffic Act, 1961 section 106 (6) (a) No. 97.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant under sec. 106 (6)* 6. An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule and, where the Judge of the District Court or the Peace Commissioner grants the application, the warrant may be in the [Form 97.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/76d54504-08eb-4f65-9395-646de3aa29bf/Information For Search Warrant - Road Traffic Act, 1961 section 106 (6) (a) No. 97.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule Application for disqualification under the Agreement on the Mutual Recognition of Driving Disqualifications between Ireland and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What is a ''mutual recognition application''?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement.","An appeal process initiated by a disqualified individual to overturn a decision made in the United Kingdom under the terms of the Agreement.","An application submitted by a driver requesting permission to drive in the United Kingdom after being disqualified in Ireland under the 2016 Act.","A request by a licensing authority under section 39(2) of the 2016 Act for an exemption allowing a person who has been disqualified in the to hold a license in Ireland."],"justification":"An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- venue* 7.[2] (1) An application by a licensing authority under section 40(2) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) for an order declaring the person to whom the notification which is the subject of the application relates to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) Act for the purposes of giving effect to the decision imposing disqualification from driving made in the United Kingdom in accordance with the Agreement (in this rule, a “mutual recognition application”) may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area: - where the person the subject of the mutual recognition application concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - in which the address which appears on the Irish driving licence or learner permit held by the respondent is located.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede a mutual recognition application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The issue and service of a notice of application in Form 97.19","The submission of a formal complaint letter","The completion of a preliminary discovery process","A successful mediation between the parties involved"],"justification":"A mutual recognition application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application [in the [Form 97.19](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/acc/alfresco/4d97d0a7-2e9d-4df9-a60c-a25f209fb489/Notice of Application for an order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence ... 40 Road Traffic Act 2016 No. 97.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Form of mutual recognition application* (2) A mutual recognition application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application [in the [Form 97.19](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/acc/alfresco/4d97d0a7-2e9d-4df9-a60c-a25f209fb489/Notice of Application for an order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence ... 40 Road Traffic Act 2016 No. 97.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed on behalf of the moving party or by the solicitor for the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What documents should be appended if a certificate is provided under section 40(3)(a) of the 2016 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The original of any report concerning the case of the applicant and any document identified in and attached to such report.","The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent and any document identified in and attached to such certificate.","The summary of any certificate concerning the case of the applicant and any document identified in and attached to such summary.","A copy of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent and any document identified in and attached to such certificate."],"justification":"The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent signed by an officer of the licensing authority concerned authorised in that behalf by the chief executive of the licensing authority concerned given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) and any document identified in and attached to such certificate;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Documents to be appended to mutual recognition application* (3) There shall be appended to the original notice of application: - The original of any certificate concerning the case of the respondent signed by an officer of the licensing authority concerned authorised in that behalf by the chief executive of the licensing authority concerned given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/) and any document identified in and attached to such certificate; - Where no certificate is given for the purposes of section 40(3)(a) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/), copies of: - (a) the notification in writing concerning the case of the respondent received by the licensing authority in accordance with Article 3 of the Agreement and section 40(1) of the [2016 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/act/21/enacted/en/); - the information and documents specified in paragraph 1 of Article 6 of the Agreement concerning the case of the respondent, and - where appropriate, pursuant to the Agreement, the evidence referred to in paragraph 2 of that Article and the supplementary information referred to in paragraph 3 thereof concerning the case of the respondent.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What must be served on the respondent at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the appeal?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A copy of the final judgment only","A copy of the original notice of application and copies of all documents appended to it","A new set of legal arguments presented by the appellant","A summary of the case proceedings"],"justification":"A copy of the original notice of application, and copies of all documents appended to it, shall be served, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), upon the respondent at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the appeal."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Service* (4) A copy of the original notice of application, and copies of all documents appended to it, shall be served, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), upon the respondent at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the hearing date?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The applicant''s updated resume and cover letter","A copy of the applicant''s identification and proof of residence","The court''s official calendar and schedule of hearings","The original notice of application, all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof"],"justification":"The original notice of application, together with all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Lodgment* (5) The original notice of application, together with all documents appended to it, and a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'When was Order 97 substituted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["effective 3 September 2018","effective 3 July 2018","effective 3 August 2019","effective 3 August 2018"],"justification":"Order 97 substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235\u0026years 2018), effective 3 August 2018"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Form of order* (6) The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 97.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 97 substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018 [2] Order 97 rule 5 originally substituted by [S.I. 564 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/564/made/en/print?q 564&years 2007), re-substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018 [3] Order 97 rule 7 originally inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order 98 - Social welfare relate to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Administrative procedures for business licenses","Regulations for public transportation services","Proceedings for criminal offenses","Proceedings for contribution towards benefit or allowance"],"justification":"# Proceedings for - contribution towards benefit or allowance"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 98 - Social welfare - Court: District # Proceedings for - contribution towards benefit or allowance'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for an order for contribution be brought?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative was born or has citizenship.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of criminal business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area outside the jurisdiction where the liable relative occasionally visits."],"justification":"may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for order for contribution* 2. (1) An application to the Court by a competent authority pursuant to subsection (2) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order directing the person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of that section (hereinafter referred to as the liable relative) to make a contribution towards a benefit or allowance being paid by that authority to a recipient may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance of the hearing date must these documents be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least four days prior to the date of hearing.","Immediately upon receiving the notice of hearing, regardless of the hearing date.","Within one day before the date of hearing, but not on the same day.","At least two days prior to the date of hearing."],"justification":"at least four days prior to the date of hearing"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- lodgment of notice, etc.* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'How should the applicant serve the court order on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["by sending it via regular post","by leaving it at the respondent''s address without any proof of delivery","by registered prepaid post","by handing it directly to the respondent"],"justification":"The applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent by registered prepaid post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court order - form and service of* 3.(1) Where, upon hearing such application, the Court makes an order under section 286 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) the order shall be in the [Form 98.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12910b1e-19e5-498d-bbff-6790903272d7/Order Directing Payment Of Contribution Towards Benefit - Allowance - Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 1993 No. 98.2.docx/docx/1) (or such modification thereof as may be appropriate). The applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent by registered prepaid post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Which rules'' provisions apply to orders made under section 286(4) of the Act when varied or enforced?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The relevant provisions of Order 47 (Interpretation) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed.","The relevant provisions of Order 50 (Service of Documents) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed.","The relevant provisions of Order 53 (Enforcement of Judgments) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed.","The relevant provisions of Order 62 (Execution of Orders) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed."],"justification":"The relevant provisions of [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), (Enforcement of Judgments) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed, with any necessary adaptation, shall for such purposes apply in relation to every such order made under the said section 286 (4)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- variation or enforcement of* (2) For the purposes of varying or enforcing an order made under subsection (4) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) the order shall, as provided in subsection (5) of that section be deemed to be an order for payment by instalments made under section 17 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act, 1926](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1926/act/18/enacted/en/html). The relevant provisions of [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), (Enforcement of Judgments) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed, with any necessary adaptation, shall for such purposes apply in relation to every such order made under the said section 286 (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'Which rules'' provisions do not apply to orders made under section 286 (4)?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Rules 5 (2) and 6 (4) of Order 53","Rules 6 (1) and 7 (3) of Order 53","Rules 7 (2) and 8 (4) of Order 53","Rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of Order 53"],"justification":"The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said [Order 53], which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- 6 (2), 7 (4) of 0.53 not to apply to* (3) The provisions of rules 6 (2) and 7 (4) of the said [Order 53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs), which relate respectively to the duration of instalment orders and variation orders, shall not apply to orders made under the said section 286 (4).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'When can an application for an attachment of earnings order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["During the annual review session of the court where the liable relative has previously been convicted of a criminal offense.","At any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any time, as long as it is submitted electronically to the court’s central office regardless of the location of the liable relative.","Only during specific hours designated by the court for such applications in the county where the liable relative''s last known address is located."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- attachment of earnings* (4) Where, in order to secure payments under an order made pursuant to the said section 286(4), application is made by a competent authority under section 287 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an attachment of earnings order such application, if not made at the time of the hearing of the application under section 286(2), may be made at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation. The relevant provisions of Part of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) shall apply in every such case. The procedures to be followed and the forms to be used in relation to such applications are those provided in Order 56 (other than rule 2) of these Rules which are relevant, and that Order and those forms, with any necessary modifications, shall apply in every such case.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'What do references to ''creditor'' and ''maintenance creditor'' become when applied to applications or orders related to rule 3 of Order 98?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["\"competent authority\"","maintenance provider","financial guarantor","legal debtor"],"justification":"References in Orders [53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs) and [56]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-56-District-Attachment-Of-Earnings) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed to \"**creditor**\" and \"**maintenance creditor**\" or to \"**debtor**\" and \"**maintenance debtor**\" shall, in so far as they apply to applications or orders to which rule 3 of this Order relates, be construed as references to \"**competent authority**\" and \"**liable relative\"**, respectively."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Construction of references* 4. References in Orders [53]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-53-District-Costs) and [56]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-56-District-Attachment-Of-Earnings) of these Rules and the forms therein prescribed to "**creditor**" and "**maintenance creditor**" or to "**debtor**" and "**maintenance debtor**" shall, in so far as they apply to applications or orders to which rule 3 of this Order relates, be construed as references to "**competent authority**" and "**liable relative"**, respectively. [1] Order 98 rule 1 definition of “c**ompetent authority**” substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Acts does Order 99A apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 and Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014","Housing (Planning and Development) Act 1996 and Housing (Rent Control) Act 2012","Housing (Landlord and Tenant Relationships) Act 1999 and Housing (Community Services) Act 2013","Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1998 and Housing (Adjudication) Act 2010"],"justification":"Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 - Court: District # Order 99A: Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["GENERAL","SPECIFIC","III. DETAIL","APPLICATION"],"justification":"GENERAL**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## GENERAL**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What must the applicant do if they believe a respondent is under the age of 18?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Include a note in the cover letter mentioning that the respondent is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.","Mark the respondent''s age as ''Under 18'' in the demographic section of the application form.","Expressly indicate on the face of the form that the respondent is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.","Attach a separate affidavit stating that the respondent is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years."],"justification":"(2) Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Definitions and requirement to identify where respondent is a child* 1. (1) In this Order— the “**1****997 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html); the “**2014 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**dwelling**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 6 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**house**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/18/enacted/en/html); “**site**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Traveller Accommodation) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/33/enacted/en/html). (2) Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What does this section primarily concern?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Proceedings under the Residential Tenancies Act 1986","Proceedings under the Planning and Development Act 2000","Proceedings under the Social Welfare Act 2005","Proceedings under the Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997"],"justification":"## PROCEEDINGS UNDER 1997 ACT**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## PROCEEDINGS UNDER 1997 ACT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must the notice be served if it is not sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["at least seven days","at least five days","at least ten days","at least three days"],"justification":"at least seven days"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- form of, service and lodgment of notice of* (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 96.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bc6e99d6-bc5d-4161-b3de-f92395301595/Notice Of Application For AnOrder Under Section 28a(1) - Air Pollution Act, 1987 No. 96.3.docx/docx/1), upon the respondent in a manner prescribed in section 15 of [the Act of 1987](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1987/act/6/enacted/en/html), and shall be served at least seven days or, where service is being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a notice of application be served if it is sent by prepaid registered post?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["fifteen days","thirty days","ten days","twenty-one days"],"justification":"if being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- service of notices of* (4) A notice of application required by this rule to be served shall be served in a manner prescribed in section 15 of that Act. Service shall be effected at least seven days or, if being effected by prepaid registered post, at least twenty-one days prior to the date fixed for hearing the application. The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof (and, where appropriate, the certificate of posting), shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the said date for hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 1990'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Local Government (Air Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990 (No. 21 of 1990)","The Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990 (No. 21 of 1990)","The Public Health (Water Quality Improvement) Act, 1990 (No. 21 of 1990)","The Environmental Protection (Water Conservation) Act, 1990 (No. 21 of 1990)"],"justification":"\"**the Act of 1990**\" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1990)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Definitions* 4. In this Order - "**t****he Act of 1977**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) Act, 1977](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1977/act/1/enacted/en/html) (No. 1 of 1977); "**the** **Act of 1990**" means the [Local Government (Water Pollution) (Amendment) Act, 1990](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/21/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 1990).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Under which act are the proceedings conducted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Water Quality Act, 1986 (No. 5 of 1986)","National Parks Act, 1974 (No. 12 of 1974)","Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (No. 7 of 1992)","Clean Air Act, 1980 (No. 34 of 1980)"],"justification":"under the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (No. 7 of 1992)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Form of warrant* (3) A warrant granted pursuant to such application shall be in the [Form 96.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8ccd799c-d469-43b7-94f8-ec29a93d3678/Warrant To Enter A Premises - Vessel - Local Government (Water Pollution) Act 1977 No. 96.13.docx/docx/1). # **Proceedings:****- under the Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (No. 7 of 1992)**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'Who makes the application for the warrant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The police officer executing the warrant.","The judge issuing the warrant.","The person seeking the issue of the warrant.","The lawyer defending against the warrant."],"justification":"of the person seeking the issue of the warrant."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- by sworn information* (2) Such application shall be made by the information on oath and in writing, in the [Form 96. 14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/360bf441-bfcd-4c5c-a1d8-2d9f77156e4c/Information For Warrant To Enter Premises - Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 section 13 (6) No. 96.14.docx/docx/1), of the person seeking the issue of the warrant.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96 - Protection of the environment and control of pollution', 'Court Rules', 'What must be done with the original notice and declaration after service?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Submit them to the opposing party","File them with the local court","Lodge them with the Clerk","Send them to the appellate court"],"justification":"the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- notice of service lodgment* (2) Such complaint shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice, in the form prescribed in the [Environmental Protection Agency Act, 1992 (Noise) Regulations, 1994 (S.I. No. 179 of 1994)](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/si/179/made/en/print), of the intention to make such a complaint, within such time as may be specified in the notice, upon the defendant, that is to say, the person alleged to have made or have caused or have been responsible for the noise. Service may be effected in accordance with the provisions of section 14 of that Act, and the original of the notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96A - Food Safety', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an order made under subsection (4) of Section 52 of the Act take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be in Form Schedule","It should be in Form 96A.2, Schedule","It should be in Form 96A.3, Schedule","It should be in Form 96A.2, Schedule"],"justification":"An order made pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act on such application shall be in the [Form 96A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3279a05f-9ef0-431b-a7a4-f227273726ba/Order (Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998, Section 52) No. 96A.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- where the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business cannot be ascertained by reasonable inquiry, by delivering it to a person over the age of 16 years resident in or employed on the premises, or by affixing it in a conspicuous position on or near the premises, or - where there is a facility for receiving a facsimile of the notice by electronic means at the address at which the proprietor or person in charge of the premises ordinarily resides or carries on business, by transmitting a facsimile of the notice by such means to that address, provided that the notice is also served or given in any of the other ways referred to in this sub-rule. (3). The original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the said date of hearing. (4). An order made pursuant to sub-section (4) of Section 52 of the Act on such application shall be in the [Form 96A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3279a05f-9ef0-431b-a7a4-f227273726ba/Order (Food Safety Authority Of Ireland Act 1998, Section 52) No. 96A.2.docx/docx/1). [1] Order 96A inserted by [S.I. 700 of 2004](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2004/si/700/made/en/print?q 700&years 2004), effective 14 November 2004'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 2010'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act 2010 (No. 21 of 2010)","The Data Protection Act 2010 (No. 23 of 2010)","The Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 (No. 22 of 2010)","The Consumer Rights Act 2010 (No. 20 of 2010)"],"justification":"“**the Act of 2010**” means the [Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 2010);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 - Court: District # Order Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 ****[1]**** 1. In this Order: *“**the Act of 2003**” means the [Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html) (No. 16 of 2003);* *“**t****he Act of 2010**” means the [Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) (No. 22 of 2010);* *“**closure order**” has the meaning given to it by section 2 of [the Act of 2003](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/act/16/enacted/en/html);* *“**prohibition order**” means an order under section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html)*.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a prohibition order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or where any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or kept when not in use.","At the nearest post office to the location where the prohibited activity is taking place","At any local police station within the same county as the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice","Through an online form submitted to the national government''s website"],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) applies) of the Court for the court district in which: the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or* any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or* *(iii) any such structure, stall or vehicle is kept when not in use."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 5. An application pursuant to section 8 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for a prohibition order may be made at any sitting (including a sitting to which section 8(11) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) applies) of the Court for the court district in which: the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or* any structure, stall or vehicle to which the prohibition notice relates is located or used, or* *(iii) any such structure, stall or vehicle is kept when not in use.* 6. Notice of an application for a prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bee0d4e5-64ff-4945-b634-82d19c4b730d/Notice of application for prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule and there shall be attached to such notice a copy of the prohibition notice which was served in accordance with section 7 of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A copy of the notice of application shall be served upon the person who is the subject of the prohibition notice concerned (in this rule, the “respondent”) not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The Court may adjourn the hearing of such application and direct service of notice of the application upon such persons as the Court may direct in accordance with section 8(2) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html). A prohibition order shall be in the [Form 96B.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2bf9faa1-8cf8-414b-8224-7135236e0c97/Prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 8 No. 96B.5.docx/docx/1), Schedule The applicant shall serve a copy of the order on the respondent. Where a prohibition order specifies any premises to which the order relates, and the owner of the premises is not the respondent, the applicant shall, where practicable, cause a copy of the prohibition order to be served by registered post on the owner of the premises concerned.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96B - Orders concerning retail premises: - Criminal Justice (Public Order) Act 2003 - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010', 'Court Rules', 'When must the notice of application be served on the Garda Síochána member who applied for the prohibition order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","not later than seven days after the date fixed for the hearing of the application","not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","immediately upon the member applying for the prohibition order"],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application (with a copy of the prohibition order appended, where the person applying is in possession of a copy of that order) shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána who applied for the prohibition order concerned not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '7. An application pursuant to section 9(1) of [the Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/22/enacted/en/html) for an order varying a prohibition order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the prohibition order was made. Save where the Court otherwise directs or permits, such an application shall be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96B.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/6c73a20e-fed8-487c-a7a4-7bf4e49b1b1d/Notice of application to vary a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy of the notice of application (with a copy of the prohibition order appended, where the person applying is in possession of a copy of that order) shall be served upon the member of the Garda Síochána who applied for the prohibition order concerned not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application, and the original notice of application shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. The member shall produce the prohibition order or a true copy at the hearing. Where the Court makes an order varying the prohibition order, the order shall be in the [Form 96B.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de3b0ecb-1487-4f28-984b-c4a6e024e2dd/Order varying a prohibition order - Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010 section 9 No. 96B.7.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 545 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/545/made/en/print?q 545&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 536 of 2011](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/536/made/en/print?q 536&years 2011), effective 4 April 2011'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the 2001 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The Children Act 2001","The Criminal Justice Act 2001","The Environmental Protection Act 2001","The Education Act 2001"],"justification":"“**the 2001 Act**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _1. Definitions_ 1. In this Order— “**the 2001 Act**” means the [Children Act 2001](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html); “**the 2006 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice Act 2006](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) (No. 26 of 2006); “**the 2023 Act**” means the [Criminal Justice (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) (No. 24 of 2023); “**behaviour order**” has the meaning given to it by section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html), (inserted by section 162 of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html)); “**civil order**” has the same meaning as in section 113(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html); “**relevant conduct**” has the same meaning as in section 27 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html); “**section 28 order**” means an order under section 28 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a civil order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the applicant resides at the time the application is made.","Online through the official website of the national government without the need to visit a physical courthouse.","At any police station within the jurisdiction where the incident leading to the application occurred.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _2. Application for civil order_ 2. An application pursuant to section 115(1) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Who must serve a copy of a civil order on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Any member of the public can serve it without any specific requirements.","The applicant must cause it to be served.","The judge must personally serve it on the respondent.","The respondent must serve it on themselves."],"justification":"The applicant must cause a copy of any civil order to be served on the respondent in accordance with Order 10."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _4. Form and service of civil order_ 4. (1) A civil order may be in the [Form 96C.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1644c92a-97fa-4443-b38b-aae26e085127/Civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006, section 115 No. 96C.2.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) The applicant must cause a copy of any civil order to be served on the respondent in accordance with Order 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued before making an application to vary or discharge a civil order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The notice of application in Form Schedule","The notice of application in Form Schedule","The notice of application in Form Schedule","The notice of application in Form Schedule"],"justification":"Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c78b0a4-b7e9-44f7-89e5-4ee90cab0a9d/Notice of application for variation - discharge of civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115(7) No. 96C.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _5. Application to vary or discharge a civil order_ 5.(1) An application pursuant to section 115(7) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) for an order discharging or varying a civil order may be made at any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the person subject to the civil order resides at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3c78b0a4-b7e9-44f7-89e5-4ee90cab0a9d/Notice of application for variation - discharge of civil order - Criminal Justice Act 2006 section 115(7) No. 96C.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with true copies of the notice of application for a civil order and attachments thereto and of the civil order) must be served upon the person referred to in section 115(8) of [the 2006 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/act/26/enacted/en/print.html) in accordance with Order 10 not later than seven days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application to vary or discharge and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for a behaviour order be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any sitting of the Magistrates'' Court for the court area in which the respondent was born.","At any sitting of the High Court for the court area in which the applicant resides at the time the application is made.","At any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.","At any sitting of the Family Court for the court area in which the applicant''s lawyer resides at the time the application is made."],"justification":"may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _7. Application for behaviour order_ 7. An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the respondent resides at the time the application is made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'When must a copy of the notice of application be served on the relevant persons?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Not earlier than 21 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","Not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","Not later than 7 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application","Within 30 days after the date fixed for the hearing of the application"],"justification":"A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _8. Notice of application_ 8.(1) Notice of an application for a behaviour order may be in the [Form 96C.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/2cadca7a-81ac-4669-9325-afdd44c98f72/Notice Of Application For Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001, section 257D.No. 96C.4.docx/docx/1), Schedule A copy or copies of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings or a copy of the written record of the behaviour warning or behaviour warnings issued to the respondent in accordance with section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) which are intended to be relied upon in the application must be attached to the notice of application. (2) A copy of the notice of application must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than 14 days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (3) The original notice of application and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued before making an application to vary or discharge a behaviour order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The notice of application in Form","The application for variation in Form","The notice of application in Form","The request for reconsideration in Form"],"justification":"Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99023c06-0ef4-4c8e-bc40-58193f9b66d8/Notice Of Application For Variation - Discharge Of Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001 section No. 96C.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _10. Application to vary or discharge a behaviour order_ 10.(1) An application pursuant to section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an order discharging or varying a behaviour order may be made at any sitting of the Children Court for the court area in which the child subject to the behaviour order is residing at the time such application is made. (2) Such an application must be preceded by the issue of a notice of application in the [Form 96C.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/99023c06-0ef4-4c8e-bc40-58193f9b66d8/Notice Of Application For Variation - Discharge Of Behaviour Order - Children Act 2001 section No. 96C.6.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) A copy of the notice of application (together with copies of the notice of application for a behaviour order and attachments thereto and of the behaviour order) must be served upon each of the persons referred to in section of [the 2001 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2001/act/24/enacted/en/html) not later than four days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application. (4) The original notice of application for discharge or variation and attachments must be lodged with the Clerk not later than two days before the date fixed for the hearing of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What action does the Clerk take if an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a different Court area?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk informs the police department directly about the discharge or variation of the behaviour order.","The Clerk sends notice to the Clerk assigned to the original Court area that the behaviour order has been discharged or a copy of the varied order.","The Clerk sends a copy of the discharge or variation order to all Clerks within the same judicial district.","The Clerk updates the court records without notifying any other Clerks."],"justification":"Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _11. Variation or discharge of a civil order_ 11.(1) Where the Court varies the terms of a behaviour order, the terms of any such variation may be indorsed upon the behaviour order and re-signed by the Judge. (2) Where an order discharging or varying a behaviour order is made in a Court area different from the Court area in which the behaviour order to which the application relates was made, the Clerk shall send to the Clerk assigned to the Court area wherein the behaviour order was made notice that the behaviour order has been discharged, or a copy of the behaviour order as varied, as the case may be.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form must be issued and served on the respondent before making an application for a section 28 order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form"],"justification":"summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _13. Section 28 Order_ 13.(1) An application to the Court under section 28(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for a section 28 order must be preceded by the issue and service upon the respondent of a summons in the [Form 96C.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/aaffd7ce-ff88-4977-8366-162a9c651c72/Form Summons Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/bd624fb7-1855-4e39-b21c-c5a838cef7ca/Form Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 1.docx/docx/1), Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What form can an parte section 28 order application be grounded on?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An affidavit sworn by the applicant or information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in Form","A letter of intent sent by the applicant to the opposing party outlining their claims or a written document containing unverified information in Form","A verbal statement made by the applicant during a court hearing or a written declaration not sworn under oath in Form","An affidavit sworn by a witness unrelated to the case or information on oath and in writing sworn by a third party in Form"],"justification":"an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _15. parte order_ 15.(1) Whether or not a summons for a section 28 order has been issued, an application to the Court in accordance with section 28(7) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for an parte section 28 order may be made at any sitting of the Court mentioned in rule 12 and grounded on an affidavit sworn by the applicant, or on information on oath and in writing sworn by the applicant in the [Form 96C.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/59a15f73-0b26-409e-af74-36585c4e1d3f/Form Information Supporting Application for Interim Order Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (2) An order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 96C.11](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/ce040b59-9d82-4a14-b4e8-f295c57f82eb/Form Interim Parte Order Criminal Justice Miscellaneous Provisions Act 2023 section 28 12 7.docx/docx/1), Schedule (3) In any case under this rule, the Court may hear evidence viva voce and on oath.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'How should the Clerk deliver a certified copy of an order that prohibits or restricts the respondent from approaching a specified place?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By prepaid registered post or, where agreed with the Garda Síochána member, by electronic mail.","In person to the respondent''s last known address or, where agreed with the Garda Síochána member, by courier service.","Through a publicly accessible notice board or, where agreed with the Garda Síochána member, via social media.","By regular unregistered post or, where agreed with the Garda Síochána member, by fax."],"justification":"- where the order in question prohibits or restricts the respondent from approaching a specified place and the Court so directs, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the specified place is situated, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _18. Clerk to supply copies of orders_ 18. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges a section 28 order or makes a further order under section 30 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), the Clerk must, in accordance with section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable: - (a) to the applicant, and - to the respondent, by ordinary prepaid post, and - where an application has been made by a member of the Garda Síochána acting in accordance with section 31 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html), to that member, and - to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the person, for whose benefit the order is made, resides, and - where the order in question is a variation or discharge of a section 28 order and the person for whose benefit the order was made had previously resided elsewhere, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which that person had so resided, but only if that member had previously been sent a copy of the section 28 order, or any order relating thereto under section 35(1) of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) and this rule, and - where the order in question prohibits or restricts the respondent from approaching a specified place and the Court so directs, to the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána station for the area in which the specified place is situated, by prepaid registered post or, where so agreed with the member of the Garda Síochána concerned, by electronic mail.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 96C - Civil Restraining and Behaviour Orders', 'Court Rules', 'What can the court do after giving a direction under section 32 or section 39?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Increase the sentence beyond what is stipulated by law.","Order the immediate release of all parties involved in the proceedings.","Adjourn the proceedings for a period considered appropriate and make further orders and give additional directions.","Dismiss the case immediately without any further proceedings."],"justification":"and may adjourn the proceedings for the purposes of section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for such period as it considers appropriate in the circumstances, and may make such orders and give further directions in accordance with section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) accordingly."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _20. Direction in relation to cross-examination or for evidence through television link_ 20. The Court may give a direction under section 32 or section 39 of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) at any time in the course of proceedings under [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html)– - (a) upon a request for such a direction made by either party or a witness affected by a proposed cross-examination, and having heard the parties, or - on its own motion and having heard the parties, and may adjourn the proceedings for the purposes of section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) for such period as it considers appropriate in the circumstances, and may make such orders and give further directions in accordance with section 32 or, as the case may be, section 39, of [the 2023 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/act/24/enacted/en/html) accordingly. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2007), effective 20 July 2007, substituted in entirety including title by 364 of 2024](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2024/si/364/made/en/print#:~:text S.I.-,No.,and Behaviour Orders) Rules 2024&text “Iris Oifigiúil” of July, 2024.), effective 2 September 2024. Superseded amendments: Order title substituted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007 Order rule 7 inserted by [S.I. 408 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/408/made/en/print?q 408&years 2007), effective 27 July 2007'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What is the purpose of section 33(3A)(b) under the 1961 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["To allow for an appeal against the refusal of the issuing authority to carry out a test.","To provide guidelines for the conduct of tests by the issuing authority.","To establish the criteria for determining the validity of test results.","To permit the issuance of a license without a test upon request."],"justification":"against the refusal of the issuing authority to carry out a test"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- under section 33(3A)(b)* - pursuant to section 33(3A)(b) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (inserted by section 21 of the [1968 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1968/act/25/enacted/en/html)) against the refusal of the issuing authority to carry out a test,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Where can an application for removal of a disqualification be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At a designated tribunal specifically established for handling disqualification appeals.","Through an online form on the official government website without needing to appear in person.","At any sitting of the court for the court area in which the disqualification order was made.","At any sitting of the court for the court area in which the applicant resides."],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 29(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) for the removal of a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the court for the court area in which the disqualification order was made."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for removal of disqualification* 5.[2] (1) An application pursuant to section 29(2) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) for the removal of a disqualification may be made at any sitting of the court for the court area in which the disqualification order was made. (2) Such application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the Form [97.16](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/df3fa82d-8c2f-4a31-8d00-d6b7d688da91/Notice Of Application For The Removal Of Disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(2)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.16.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed by the applicant or solicitor for the applicant. (3) Such notice shall be served upon the Superintendent of the Garda Síochána for the district in which the applicant ordinarily resides at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the application. (4) The original of such notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the said date of hearing. (5) The order of the Court on hearing the application shall be in the Form [97.17](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de60ac49-ced2-4787-bc17-76e5b08f93fd/Order for the removal of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 section 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.17.docx/docx/1) or [97.18](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/64ffa69e-d7ad-4458-96f0-da64dc1e1c1d/Order confirming period specified in order of disqualification - Road Traffic Act 1961 29(4)(as substituted by section 7 of the Road Traffic Act 2006) No. 97.18.docx/docx/1), Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for an application for a search warrant under section 106(6)(a) of the 1961 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Form 97.21 Schedule","Form 98.21 Schedule","Form 97.21 Schedule","Form 97.22 Schedule"],"justification":"An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Search warrant under sec. 106 (6)* 6. An application pursuant to section 106(6)(a) of the [1961 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1961/act/24/enacted/en/html) by a member of the Garda Síochána for the issue of a warrant under that section shall be by information on oath and in writing in the Form 97.21 Schedule and, where the Judge of the District Court or the Peace Commissioner grants the application, the warrant may be in the [Form 97.22](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/76d54504-08eb-4f65-9395-646de3aa29bf/Information For Search Warrant - Road Traffic Act, 1961 section 106 (6) (a) No. 97.22.docx/docx/1) Schedule Application for disqualification under the Agreement on the Mutual Recognition of Driving Disqualifications between Ireland and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland:'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'Who can sign the notice of application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The moving party or their solicitor","The opposing party or their solicitor","The judge presiding over the case","A witness in the case"],"justification":"signed on behalf of the moving party or by the solicitor for the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Form of mutual recognition application* (2) A mutual recognition application shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice of application [in the [Form 97.19](https://courts-ie-aut.sitefinity.cloud/acc/alfresco/4d97d0a7-2e9d-4df9-a60c-a25f209fb489/Notice of Application for an order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence ... 40 Road Traffic Act 2016 No. 97.19.docx/docx/1), Schedule signed on behalf of the moving party or by the solicitor for the moving party.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'According to which order should the service be carried out?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Order 42","Order 41","Order 40","Order 39"],"justification":"[Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Service* (4) A copy of the original notice of application, and copies of all documents appended to it, shall be served, in accordance with the provisions of [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State), upon the respondent at least 14 days before the date of hearing of the appeal.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 97 - Road Traffic', 'Court Rules', 'What form is used for the court order granting the application?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["[Form 97.21](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(2) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.21.docx/docx/1)","[Form 97.25](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(3) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.25.docx/docx/1)","[Form 97.10](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.10.docx/docx/1)","[Form 97.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.20.docx/docx/1)"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 97.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- Form of order* (6) The order of the Court granting the application may be in the [Form 97.20](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/50b56531-9887-4b30-8f28-752a91b53979/Order declaring the respondent to be disqualified for holding a licence for the period referred to in section 40(1) of the Road Traffic Act 2016 ...No. 97.20.docx/docx/1), Schedule [1] Order 97 substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018 [2] Order 97 rule 5 originally substituted by [S.I. 564 of 2007](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2007/si/564/made/en/print?q 564&years 2007), re-substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018 [3] Order 97 rule 7 originally inserted by [S.I. 314 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/314/made/en/print?q 314&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 235 of 2018](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2018/si/235/made/en/print?q 235&years 2018), effective 3 August 2018'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''liable relative'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The relative who inherits the majority of the estate and is therefore required to manage it according to subsection (2) of section 287 of the Act.","The family member designated by the court to make healthcare decisions for an incapacitated individual under subsection (3) of section 286 of the Act.","The person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of section 286 of the Act.","The individual responsible for paying taxes on behalf of the deceased under section 285 of the Act."],"justification":"the person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of that section (hereinafter referred to as the liable relative)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Application for order for contribution* 2. (1) An application to the Court by a competent authority pursuant to subsection (2) of section 286 of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) for an order directing the person who is liable to contribute under subsection (1) of that section (hereinafter referred to as the liable relative) to make a contribution towards a benefit or allowance being paid by that authority to a recipient may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the transaction of civil business for the court area wherein the liable relative ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk when service has been effected?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The original notice, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and the affidavit of service.","The original notice, a statutory declaration as to service thereof, and the certificate of posting.","The original notice, a confirmation of service from the recipient, and the postal receipt.","The original notice, a copy of the email confirming receipt, and the certificate of posting."],"justification":"the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *- lodgment of notice, etc.* (3) When service has been effected the original notice, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof and the certificate of posting, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days prior to the date of hearing.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 98 - Social welfare', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a court order take when made under section 286(4) of the Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Form 98.2, Schedule (or a suitable modification)","Form 98.1, Schedule","Form 75, Schedule","Form 98.3, Schedule A"],"justification":"the order shall be in the [Form 98.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12910b1e-19e5-498d-bbff-6790903272d7/Order Directing Payment Of Contribution Towards Benefit - Allowance - Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 1993 No. 98.2.docx/docx/1) (or such modification thereof as may be appropriate)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *Court order - form and service of* 3.(1) Where, upon hearing such application, the Court makes an order under section 286 (4) of [the Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1993/act/27/enacted/en/html) the order shall be in the [Form 98.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/12910b1e-19e5-498d-bbff-6790903272d7/Order Directing Payment Of Contribution Towards Benefit - Allowance - Social Welfare (Consolidation) Act 1993 No. 98.2.docx/docx/1) (or such modification thereof as may be appropriate). The applicant shall cause the said order to be served upon the respondent by registered prepaid post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court associated with Order 99A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["High Court","County Court","District Court","Supreme Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 - Court: District # Order 99A: Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 ****[1]****'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What does the term ''1997 Act'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Environmental Protection Act 1997","The Education Reform Act 1997","The Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997","The Criminal Justice Act 1997"],"justification":"the “**1****997 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Definitions and requirement to identify where respondent is a child* 1. (1) In this Order— the “**1****997 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html); the “**2014 Act**” means the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**dwelling**” has the meaning assigned to it by section 6 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html); “**house**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1992](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1992/act/18/enacted/en/html); “**site**” has the meaning assigned to it by the [Housing (Traveller Accommodation) Act 1998](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1998/act/33/enacted/en/html). (2) Where applicable in any proceedings to which this Order applies, the applicant shall expressly indicate on the face of the Form by which the application is made that a respondent in any such application is or is believed to be under the age of 18 years.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Under which sections of the 1997 Act can proceedings be heard otherwise than in public?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Sections 4, 5, 6, and 7","Sections 2, 6, and 10","Sections 1, 2, 5, and 8","Sections 3, 3A, 4, and 9"],"justification":"Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proceedings may be heard otherwise than in public* 3. Proceedings under section 3, 3A, 4 or 9 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served before applying for an excluding order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","Form 99A.1","Form","Form"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/331b2936-1752-49cc-82e8-f8bb1cff527f/Application For An Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.1.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Excluding Orders* 4. (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/331b2936-1752-49cc-82e8-f8bb1cff527f/Application For An Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1). (3) Where an excluding order is made by the Court in accordance with the provisions of section 12(12)(a) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) on foot of a possession application under section 12 of that Act, the order shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the order of the Court granting the application for a site excluding order be issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["In Form 99A.4, Schedule A.","In Form 100A.4, Schedule","In Form 99A.4, Schedule","In Form 99A.3, Schedule"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Site Excluding Orders* 5. (1) An application to the court under section 3A of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for a site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.4, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0ae66036-b301-4df8-82cb-98b3c5e78d27/Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.4.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What form should an application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order be grounded on?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The application should be grounded on an informal letter of intent from the applicant.","The application should be grounded on verbal testimony provided during a court hearing.","The application should be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the Form 99A.5 or on an affidavit incorporating the matter in that Form.","The application should be based on a preliminary report submitted by a third-party investigator."],"justification":"An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8590fb7f-0de3-4171-a21d-356ce5134af5/Information - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.5.docx/docx/1) or on an affidavit sworn by the applicant incorporating the matter in that Form."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Interim Excluding Orders/Site Excluding Orders* 6.[2] (1) An application for an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made under the terms of section 4 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) on the occasion of the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order or between the making of an application for an excluding order or site excluding order and its determination shall be grounded on the information on oath and in writing of the applicant in the [Form 99A.5, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8590fb7f-0de3-4171-a21d-356ce5134af5/Information - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.5.docx/docx/1) or on an affidavit sworn by the applicant incorporating the matter in that Form. (2) The order of the Court shall be in the [Form 99A.6, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/8c08a91c-e6c8-421e-88d9-0db1d7d5fb86/Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.6.docx/docx/1). (3) An application for confirmation under section of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) of an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order made parte under the terms of section 4(3) of that Act shall be preceded by the issue and service on the respondent by the applicant at least 2 days before the date fixed for such application of a notice in the [Form 99A.14, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c14e9af0-5f7b-4c77-a2b8-0c2515212e98/Application To Confirm An Interim Excluding - Interim Site Excluding Order Made Parte - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.14.docx/docx/1). The applicant shall also serve on the respondent the documents referred to in section 4(3)(c)(ii) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html). (4) Where, on such application, the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order is confirmed, such confirmation shall be indorsed upon the order and signed by the Judge.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What form should the court use when granting an application to vary an excluding order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 99A.9","Form 99A.8","Form","Form 99A.7"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ee4a98d-c7c5-44f1-a4ed-9981fa04bbd1/Order Varying An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.8.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary Excluding/ Site Excluding/ Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders* 7. (1) An application to the Court under - (a) section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an excluding order, - section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, - section 3A(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary a site excluding order, or section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) and section 3A(9) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b135a660-4139-4bf7-9106-e0177cefb952/Application To Vary An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.7.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ee4a98d-c7c5-44f1-a4ed-9981fa04bbd1/Order Varying An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the Court''s order granting an application to discharge an excluding order be issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form 99A.5","Form 99A.10"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e9130d4-ae3e-4664-a740-0ed9bf4d754e/Order Discharging An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.10.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Discharge Excluding Site Excluding or Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders 8. (1) An application to the Court under section 9(1) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to discharge an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.9, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b98b105d-e0e2-4674-8f94-49219cc93bf1/Application To Discharge An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.9.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.10, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/7e9130d4-ae3e-4664-a740-0ed9bf4d754e/Order Discharging An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.10.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Who should receive a certified copy of the order when the court makes, varies or discharges an excluding order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The applicant''s employer, the respondent''s landlord, the local councilor, the county librarian, and the head teacher of the nearest primary school.","The applicant''s next of kin, the respondent''s legal representative, the local school principal, the nearest hospital administrator, and the postmaster of the nearest post office.","The applicant concerned, the respondent, the housing authority in whose functional area the house, site or dwelling is located, the Health Service Executive, and the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána Station for the area where the house, site or dwelling is located.","The applicant''s financial advisor, the respondent''s accountant, the local community center director, the regional sports coach, and the neighborhood watch coordinator."],"justification":"the applicant concerned, - the respondent, - the housing authority in whose functional area the house, site or dwelling in respect of which the application for the order was made is situate, and the Health Service Executive by ordinary prepaid post and - the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Clerk to supply copies of order 10. Where the Court makes, varies or discharges an excluding order, site excluding order, interim excluding order or interim site excluding order, the Clerk shall give or send a certified copy of the order in question as soon as practicable to- - (a) the applicant concerned, - the respondent, - the housing authority in whose functional area the house, site or dwelling in respect of which the application for the order was made is situate, and the Health Service Executive by ordinary prepaid post and - the member of the Garda Síochána in charge of the Garda Síochána Station for the area in which the house, site or dwelling in relation to which the application for the order was made is situate by prepaid registered post.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'In what form is the notice sent to the Garda Síochána?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The notice is sent in Form Schedule A.","The notice is sent in Form 99A.11, Schedule","The notice is sent in Form Schedule","The notice is sent in Form Schedule"],"justification":"notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Interim Excluding/Site Excluding orders ceases to have effect.* 11.[4] Where an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has been made and the application for an excluding order or site excluding order has been determined, the Clerk shall send notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1), that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to an appeal from an excluding order or a site excluding order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The appeal automatically suspends the operation of the order without any further determination by the court.","The appeal has no effect on the operation of the order until a higher court reviews and modifies the decision.","The appeal stays the operation of the order if the court that made the order or the court to which the appeal is brought so determines.","The appeal dismisses the operation of the order immediately upon being filed."],"justification":"an appeal from an excluding order or a site excluding order shall, if the court that made the order or the court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Effect of appeal from orders* 12.(1) Notwithstanding the provisions of [Order 25]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-25-District-Issue-Of-Warrants-In-Execution-Of-Court-Orders), rule 9(4) and [Order 101]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-101-District-Appeals-to-the-circuit-court) and that an appellant has entered into a recognisance for appeal, - (a) an appeal from an excluding order or a site excluding order shall, if the court that made the order or the court to which the appeal is brought so determines (but not otherwise), stay the operation of the order on such terms (if any) as may be imposed by the court making the determination; - an appeal from an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order shall not stay the operation of the order. (2) - (a) An application to the District Court to stay the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under section 8 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be made following the service and lodgment of a notice of appeal and lodgment of the recognisance of appeal and when made otherwise than upon the occasion of the making of that order shall be preceded by the issue of a notice in the [Form 99A.12, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/937d34a2-ae9f-44f7-bbd1-e0bf160a77b4/Application For A Stay On The Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.12.docx/docx/1), which shall be served upon the respondent to the application two days before the hearing of the application. - Where the Court grants a stay on the operation of an excluding order or site excluding order under this rule, the order granting such stay shall be in the [Form 99A.13, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/49fd2430-7992-4468-89ca-63ee0730271f/Order Staying Operation Of An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.13.docx/docx/1). Where the Clerk has supplied the copies of the orders as directed by rule 10, the Clerk shall also send a copy of the order granting the stay, to the persons referred to, and in the manner directed, by rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Proceedings Under 2014 Act","Proceedings Under 2015 Act","Regulations Under 2014 Act","Amendments Under 2014 Act"],"justification":"**III. PROCEEDINGS UNDER 2014 ACT**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **III. PROCEEDINGS UNDER 2014 ACT**'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings under the 2014 Act be held?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Before a sitting of the Federal Court for the federal judicial division where the dwelling is located.","Before a sitting of the County Court for any court area in the state.","Before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where the dwelling is located.","Before a sitting of the Supreme Court for the state where the dwelling is located."],"justification":"proceedings under the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Venue* 13. Subject to the provisions of section 12(15), section 13(12) or, as the case may be, section 17(11) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html), proceedings under the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be brought, heard and determined before a sitting of the District Court for the court area where there is situate the dwelling in relation to which an application under section 12, 13, 16 or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) is being made.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Under what sections of the 2014 Act can proceedings be heard otherwise than in public?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Section 12, 13, or 17","Section 8, 9, or 14","Section 11, 15, or 16","Section 5, 6, or 10"],"justification":"Proceedings under section 12, 13, or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Proceedings may be heard otherwise than in public* 14. Proceedings under section 12, 13, or 17 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) may be heard otherwise than in public, in accordance with the provisions of section 12(11), section 13(10) or, as the case may be, section 17(9) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What must precede an application to the Court under section 16 of the 2014 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The issuance of a warning letter from the housing authority to the applicant.","The publication of a public notice in a national newspaper.","The submission of a formal complaint to the local council regarding housing conditions.","The issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in Form 99A.16, Schedule"],"justification":"An application to the Court under section 16 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in the [Form 99A.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fa2e86f-09d5-4fa6-8d02-1ae9dbf6986b/Application in respect of a tenancy terminated under section 15 Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 No. 99A.16.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application to Court in respect of terminated tenancy* 16. An application to the Court under section 16 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in the [Form 99A.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fa2e86f-09d5-4fa6-8d02-1ae9dbf6986b/Application in respect of a tenancy terminated under section 15 Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 No. 99A.16.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'How many working days before the hearing must a notice under this Part and any sworn information be served?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least 7 working days","At least 10 working days","At least 5 working days","At least 15 working days"],"justification":"Save where the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) otherwise provides, a notice under this Part and information sworn, if any, shall be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 10 working days before the date for hearing of the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notices* 17. (1) Save where the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) otherwise provides, a notice under this Part and information sworn, if any, shall be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 10 working days before the date for hearing of the application. (2) A copy of the notice and information sworn, if any, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date for hearing the application. [1] Order 99A inserted by [S.I. 217 of 1999](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1999/si/217/made/en/print?q 217&years 1999), substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [2] Order 99A rule 6 originally substituted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), re-substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [3] Order 99A sub-rule of rule 7 originally inserted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [4] Order 99A sub-rule of rule 11 substituted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), re-substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [5] Order 99A, sub-rule (3) of rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99B - Employment Equality Act 1998 and Equal Status Act 2000', 'Court Rules', 'When must the original notice of appeal be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["At least five days after the date of the sitting of the Court.","At least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court.","Within one day after the date of the sitting of the Court.","On the same day as the date of the sitting of the Court."],"justification":"The original of every notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to the service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. The original of every notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to the service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court. The Order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b2e23701-561f-4ecf-a414-0f6ecc0c5cce/Order - Employment Equality Act 1998 No. 99B.2.docx/docx/1). 5.[2] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to Section 9 of the [Terms of Employment (Information) Act, 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the respondent employer carries on any trade profession, business or occupation. 6.[3] Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 99B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e4ee31-e67a-4e79-a727-232520a11772/Notice Of Application - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to section 9 of the said [Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1da65de6-ec5f-445b-87e5-6783b9dd15eb/Order - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.4.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 263 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/263/made/en/print?q 263&years 2006), effective 20 June 2006 [2] Order rule 5 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003 [3] Order rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the document providing an overview of the rules?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Provisions Overview - District Court (Criminal Procedure) Rules 2014","Regulations Guide - County Court Civil Procedures 2014","Rules Summary - Supreme Court Civil Procedures 2014","Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014"],"justification":"# Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 - Court: District # Provisions Overview[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What are the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 also known as?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The High Court Rules 2014","The Supreme Court Rules 2014","The Civil Procedure Act Rules 2014","The District Court Rules 1997 to 2014"],"justification":"The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) to [2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Title and citation* 1. (1) These Rules, which may be cited as the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014, shall come into operation on the day of February 2014. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) (S.I. No. 93 of 1997) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) to [2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What provisions are being substituted for the ''Interpretation of Terms'' in the District Court Rules 1997?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The provisions set out in Schedule 1","The provisions set out in Schedule 2","The provisions set out in Part III","The provisions set out in Chapter 4"],"justification":"The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Amendments* 2. (1) The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997. (2) The following provisions shall be deleted from the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93), namely [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 3; Order 9; [Orders 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules) to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100. (3) The provisions set out in Schedule 2 shall be inserted to the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Order 38. (4) The Schedule of Costs set out in Schedule 3 shall be substituted for the [Schedule of Costs]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Schedule-of-Costs-District-Court-Solicitors-costs-Rules) and the Schedule of Counsel’s Fees to the District Court Rules 1997. (5) Orders 10 and 12 respectively set out in Schedule 4 shall be substituted for [Orders 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) and [12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions) of the District Court Rules 1997.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Which forms will be deleted from Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Forms 8.1 to 8.6 inclusive, Forms 40.1 to inclusive, Forms 63.1 to 63.25 inclusive and Form 98.1","Forms 7.1 to 7.6 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.25 inclusive and Form 99.1","Forms 7.1 to 7.5 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.24 inclusive and Form 99.2","Forms 7.1 to 7.7 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.26 inclusive and Form 99.0"],"justification":"Forms 7.1 to 7.6 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.25 inclusive and Form 99.1 shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3. Replacement of forms* 3. (1) Forms 7.1 to 7.6 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.25 inclusive and Form 99.1 shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (2) Forms 100.1 to 100.6 inclusive shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (3) The forms set out in Schedule 5 shall be added to Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Form'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What happens to civil proceedings in the District Court that were in progress before these Rules came into effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["They shall be transferred to another court upon these Rules taking effect.","They shall be discontinued immediately upon these Rules taking effect.","They shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect.","They shall be automatically amended according to the new Rules without any further proceedings."],"justification":"Notwithstanding the amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *4. Application and transitional arrangements* 4. (1) The amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules apply to every civil proceeding commenced in the District Court on or after the date on which these Rules come into effect. (2) Notwithstanding the amendments to the District Court Rules 1997 effected by these Rules any civil proceeding in being in the District Court before the date on which these Rules come into effect shall be continued and determined as if these Rules had not taken effect. [1] Provisions Overview inserted by [S.I. 17 of 2014](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2014), effective 3 February 2014'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of the rules governing solicitors'' costs in the District Court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Schedule of Fees - High Court (Solicitors'' Costs) Regulations","Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules","Civil Procedure Rules - Solicitors'' Billing Standards","District Court Cost Guidelines (Barristers'' Fees) Act"],"justification":"# Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules - Court: District # District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What are the solicitors'' costs if the amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice for an amount not exceeding €3,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["€100.00","€150.00","€137.00","€125.00"],"justification":"If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | € | € | Not exceeding €3,000 | 82.00 | 137.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1. Solicitors’ costs in civil debt claims** | | | | | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at date of issue of the claim notice | If amount due is paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 82.00 | 137.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 164.00 | 273.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 246.00 | 410.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 328.00 | 546.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 410.00 | 682.00 | The above scale of costs (1) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. If the claim notice is defended the costs of the successful party are in accordance with the contract, breach of contract and tort scale for assessment of damages.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the cost if a case is settled without necessity for appearance when the amount due is not exceeding €3,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["€345.00","€20.00","€295.00","€315.00"],"justification":"Not exceeding €3,000 | 315.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **2. Solicitors’ costs in contract, breach of contract and tort proceedings and in claims for damages unconnected with contract** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at the date of issue of claim notice or, (as the case may be) the amount decreed for debt | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 315.00 | 525.00 | 725.00 | 975.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 630.00 | 1,050.00 | 1,450.00 | 1,950.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,175.00 | 2,725.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 1,260.00 | 2,100.00 | 2,900.00 | 3,500.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 1,575.00 | 2,625.00 | 3,625.00 | 4,275.00 | The above scale of costs (2): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - applies to actions for wrongful detention brought by virtue of section 33(3) of the Courts (Supplemental Provisions) Act 1961, according to the value of the goods as determined by the Court; - applies to actions for wrongful detention arising out of a hire-purchase transaction.'),
