                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'In which types of cases are counsel''s fees awarded?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Defended cases of contract, breach of contract, tort, and claims for damages unconnected with contract; ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent; and cases where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer.","Cases involving criminal proceedings, defamation, and disputes over intellectual property rights.","Cases concerning employment disputes, environmental law violations, and immigration appeals.","Cases related to family law, bankruptcy, and administrative law matters."],"justification":"(1) in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract (2) in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent (3) where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **13. Counsel’s Fees** (1) in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract (2) in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent (3) where awarded under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 to a respondent or to or against a ratepayer'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the brief fee for compensation claimed between €2,000 and €3,000 under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["525.00","500.00","475.00","600.00"],"justification":"Exceeds €2,000 and does not exceed €3,000 | 525.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Part 1: Brief fee in respect of preparation for and attending on the trial or hearing of the claim To the claimant’s counsel when the amount recovered, or to the respondent’s counsel when the amount claimed, in any defended case of contract, breach of contract, tort and claims for damages unconnected with contract - To the claimant’s or respondent’s counsel when the annual rent in any defended case of ejectment for overholding or non-payment of rent - When the amount of compensation claimed under the Malicious Injuries Acts 1981 and 1986 – | | | | --- | --- | | | | | | € | | Exceeds €2,000 and does not exceed €3,000 | 525.00 | | Exceeds €3,000 and does not exceed €4,000 | 577.00 | | Exceeds €4,000 and does not exceed €5,000 | 630.00 | | Exceeds €5,000 and does not exceed €7,000 | 788.00 | | Exceeds €7,000 and does not exceed €9,000 | 840.00 | | Exceeds €9,000 and does not exceed €11,000 | 892.00 | | Exceeds €11,000 and does not exceed €13,000 | 998.00 | | Exceeds €13,000 and does not exceed €15,000 | 1,102.00 |'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the fee for drafting a claim notice or defence?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["100.00","150.00","200.00","175.00"],"justification":"Drafting Claim Notice or Defence | 175.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### Part 2: Additional counsel’s fees for particular work undertaken by counsel, where certified | | | | --- | --- | | | | | | € | | Drafting Claim Notice or Defence | 175.00 | | Drafting Notice of Motion | 50.00 | | Drafting Affidavit | 125.00 | | Brief on hearing of Motion | 150.00 | | Advice on Proofs | 150.00 | | Consultation | 150.00 | | Drafting Notice for Particulars | 100.00 | | Drafting Reply to Notice for Particulars | 100.00 | [1] District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules substituted in full by [S.I. 418 of 2023](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2023/si/418/made/en/print) effective from 25 August 2023'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What is the court level for Order of the Defamation Act 2009?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["District","Superior","Supreme","High"],"justification":"- Court: Superior"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Superior # **Order Defamation Act 2009 [1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a pleading requiring verification on affidavit take?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It should be in Form No 1 in Appendix with necessary modifications.","It should be in Form No 3 in Appendix without any modifications.","It should be in Form No 4 in Appendix with necessary modifications.","It should be in Form No 5 in Appendix with necessary modifications."],"justification":"A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form No 4 in Appendix CC](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-actions-civil-liability-and-courts-act-2004#_fri4), with such modifications as may be necessary."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Verifying affidavit under section 8** 2. (1) A pleading requiring, under section 8, to be verified on affidavit shall be in the [Form No 4 in Appendix CC](https://courts.ie/content/personal-injuries-actions-civil-liability-and-courts-act-2004#_fri4), with such modifications as may be necessary. The affidavit, if not separate from the pleading concerned, may be endorsed upon such pleading. (2) A copy of the affidavit of verification shall be delivered to the party to whom the pleading is to be delivered. Where the affidavit is endorsed on the pleading, the copy of the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of such pleading. Otherwise, the affidavit shall be delivered within the time prescribed by section 8(5) for filing of the affidavit in court. (3) An affidavit of verification shall be lodged in court as required by section 8(5) by filing the same in the Central Office. (4) Where the copy of the affidavit of verification is delivered subsequent to delivery of the pleading, the time prescribed by these Rules for delivery of any pleading in reply shall run from the date of delivery of such copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How is an application for leave under section 11(2) made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party.","Through an oral request during a scheduled court hearing.","By sending a formal letter to the judge presiding over the case.","By filing a written complaint with the court clerk."],"justification":"An application for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **III. Applications under sections 11, 14, 33 and 34, and under section of the Statute of Limitations 1957** 3. (1) An application for leave under section 11(2) may be brought by originating motion parte, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. The Court may, on the hearing of such an application, give such directions, if any, as to the giving of notice of the application or otherwise, as it considers just and convenient. (2) Where a defamation action has not been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an application to the Court for a direction under section of the [Statute of Limitations 1957](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1957/act/6/enacted/en/html) shall be brought by originating notice of motion, in which the intending plaintiff shall be named as applicant and the intended defendant as respondent. The application shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (3) The following applications in a defamation action shall be made by motion to the Court on notice to the opposing party, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party: - an application for a ruling under section 14; - an application for an interlocutory order under section 33; - (iii) an application for summary relief under section 34(1), and - an application to dismiss the defamation action under section 34(2). (4) Where no defamation action has been brought in relation to a statement referred to in section 33, an application: - for an interim order under subsection (3)(a) of that section shall, unless the Court otherwise directs, be made by originating motion parte, entitled in the matter of section 33, in which the person referred 3 to as plaintiff in section 33 is named as applicant and the person referred to as defendant in section 33 is named as respondent, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the applicant;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What type of application must be made when an offer to make amends is accepted after a defamation action has been brought?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["An application must be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, grounded upon an affidavit.","An application must be made orally in open court without prior notice to the opposing party.","An application must be made by filing a written declaration under penalty of perjury, rather than an affidavit.","The application must be submitted via email to the judge''s chambers with no requirement for an affidavit."],"justification":"shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Applications under section 23 where an offer to make amends is accepted** 4. (1) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned, or - under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication shall be made by motion on notice to the opposing party, and shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question, an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, and the parties do not agree as to the damages or costs that should be paid by the person who made the offer, the plaintiff shall apply by motion on notice to the defendant for the Court’s directions (which may, without limitation, include an order allowing either party to alter or amend his pleadings) for the conduct of an application for a determination under paragraph(c) of section 23(1). 5. (1) Where no defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question and an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court: - under paragraph (a) of section 23(1) for an order directing the party who made the offer to take the measures concerned,'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application under paragraph or of section 23(1) be initiated?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By an originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 23, with the person to whom the offer was made named as applicant and the person who made the offer named as respondent.","By filing a complaint with the court clerk, naming the person who made the offer as the complainant and the person to whom the offer was made as the respondent.","Through a written agreement between the parties involved, where both sign a document stating that they agree to have a third party resolve any disputes arising from the offer.","By submitting an affidavit to the court, signed by the person to whom the offer was made, requesting that the court order the person who made the offer to comply with the terms of the offer."],"justification":"shall be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 23 and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the person who made the offer shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication, or - (iii) for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1) shall be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 23 and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the person who made the offer shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Notice of an application under sub-rule (1) shall be given by delivering copies of the originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit and any exhibits thereto to the respondent not later than four clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion. (3) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the respondent to such originating notice of motion may deliver a replying affidavit within two weeks of the delivery to him or her of copies of the said originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit. (4) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the applicant may deliver a further affidavit within two weeks of the delivery of any replying affidavit. 6. Save in the case of an application under paragraph (a) of section 23(1), the Court may, at the hearing of an originating motion under rule 5(and in addition to any other order it may make): - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) be made if a defamation action has already been brought against the defendant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The application should be sent via email to the court''s administrative office with no need for an affidavit or notice to the defendant.","The application should be filed as a separate lawsuit from the defamation action, requiring a new set of documents unrelated to the existing case.","The application should be made verbally during the first court hearing without any formal documentation.","The application should be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party."],"justification":"- where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- direct that the application (or any undetermined part of the application) be determined by way of plenary hearing, where it appears to the Court that the subject matter of the application is likely to involve a substantial dispute of fact or it is otherwise necessary or desirable in the interests of justice (and the Court may for that purpose make orders and give directions in relation to the exchange of pleadings or points of claim or defence between the parties). 7. A grounding affidavit referred to in rules 4 and 5 shall: - identify with sufficient precision or exhibit a copy or transcript of the statement to which the offer of amends relates; - exhibit a copy of the offer of amends, and - (iii) give particulars of any agreement asserted to have been made arising from the acceptance of the offer of amends. 8. Where an offer to make amends under section 22 is accepted, an application to the Court under paragraph of section 23(1) to bring or proceed with a defamation action against another person in respect of the statement to which the offer to make amends applies shall: - where a defamation action has been brought before the Court in respect of the statement in question against that other person, be made by motion in that defamation action on notice to the defendant, grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'How can a defendant notify a plaintiff of their intention to give evidence of an apology?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["By including a statement in their defence of such intention.","By sending a written letter of intent to the plaintiff before the trial.","By announcing their intention verbally during the opening statements of the trial.","By mentioning it directly to the judge outside of the courtroom proceedings."],"justification":"he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Notification of evidence of apology under section 24** 9. Where a defendant in a defamation action intends to give evidence to which section 24(1) applies, he may notify the plaintiff of such intention in accordance with section 24(2) of the Act by including a statement in his defence of such intention.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What is required for a defendant to give evidence in chief regarding the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published or the character of the plaintiff?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The defendant must obtain the judge''s leave unless they furnish particulars to the plaintiff at least seven days before the trial.","The defendant must obtain the plaintiff''s consent unless they provide details about the defamatory statement to the judge at least ten days before the trial.","The defendant can give evidence in chief without any restrictions as long as they have previously testified in another related case.","The defendant must secure the approval of both the judge and the jury unless they present relevant documents to the plaintiff at least five days prior to the trial."],"justification":"the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation** 10. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 511 of 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/511/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Under which Act does Order 57 proceed under Section 8?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Civil Procedure Code Act 1908","The Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940","The Contempt of Courts Act 1971","The Code of Criminal Procedure Act 1973"],"justification":"Section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc. - Court: District # Order 57: Proceedings Under:**[1]** **- Section 8 of the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html)** **- Section 9A of the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11)** **- Section 52A of the**[**Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010**](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24)'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''the Act of 2010'' refer to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Marriage Act 2010","The Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010 (No. 24 of 2010)","The Equality Act 2010","The Environmental Protection Act 2010"],"justification":"“**the Act of 2010**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (No. 24 of 2010);"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Definitions** 1. (1) In this Order: “**the Act of 1940**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. [23 of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/print.html)); “**the Act of 1976**” means the [Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (No. 11 of 1976); “**the Act of 2009**” means the [Enforcement of Court Orders (Amendment) Act 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (No. 21 of 2009); “**the Act of 2010**” means the [Civil Partnership and Certain Rights and Obligations of Cohabitants Act 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (No. 24 of 2010); “**the Act of 2011**” means the [Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23) (No. 31 of 2011); “**Maintenance Regulation**” means [Council Regulation 4/2009](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>) of 18 December 2008 on jurisdiction, applicable law, recognition and enforcement of decisions and cooperation in matters relating to maintenance obligations of 10 January 2009, page 1); “**2011 Regulations**” means the European Communities (Maintenance) Regulations 2011 ([S.I. 274 of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print)); “**2019 Regulations**” means the European Union (Hague Maintenance Convention) Regulations 2019 ([S.I. 594 of 2019](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print)). (2) References in this Order to an “**order**” shall, as the circumstances require, be construed in accordance with: - (a) sections 65 and 136 of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), or - regulation 10(2) of the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print), or - the definition of “**enforceable maintenance order**” in regulation 14(1) of the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings related to enforcing an order be held if either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["At any sitting of the Supreme Court regardless of the location where the parties reside or conduct business.","At a special tribunal designated by the international body overseeing the enforcement of orders, regardless of the parties'' location.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made.","In any federal court located in the country where the enforcement is sought, irrespective of the residence or business location of the parties involved."],"justification":"proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Venue** 2.(1) Subject to sub-rule (2), proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made and, save where the context otherwise requires, any reference in this Order to the “**Clerk**” is a reference to the Clerk for that court area. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings to which this Order relates concerning an enforceable maintenance order to which the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print) or, as the case may be, the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print) apply may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for: - (a) where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State, the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned does not reside in the State but is employed by a person residing or having a place of business in the State or by a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, the court area in which the person resides or the body has its seat.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'How should an application under section 8(1) of the Act of 1940 be submitted?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be submitted verbally during a court hearing.","It can be submitted electronically through the official court email.","The application must be sent via postal mail to the Supreme Court.","It should be submitted in writing and may be done by lodging a completed draft form of summons with the Clerk."],"justification":"An application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) for the issue of a summons shall be in writing (and may be by the lodgment with the Clerk of a completed draft form of summons) and shall include:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application in writing for summons under section 8(1) of the Act of** **1940** 3. An application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) (as substituted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) for the issue of a summons shall be in writing (and may be by the lodgment with the Clerk of a completed draft form of summons) and shall include: - (a) a copy of the antecedent order concerned and, where relevant, a copy of any enforcement order made by the Master of the High Court in respect of the maintenance order concerned or, as the case may be, a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), of the decision issued by the court of origin; - the period(s) for which the monetary amounts directed to be paid by the antecedent order have not been duly paid; - the amount of the arrears, and any amount provided by the antecedent order for costs and expenses which is unpaid; - a statement that the applicant understands that the information included in the application may have to be proved on oath at the hearing of any summons issued on foot of the application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'When must the defaulter lodge the statement of means and assets?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Not less than one week before the date of the sitting","On the same day as the sitting","Not more than one day before the date of the sitting","Within two weeks after the date of the sitting"],"justification":"not less than one week before the date of the said sitting"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Issue of summons under section 8(1) of the Act of 1940** 4.(1) The summons shall be in the [Form 57.1](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/4dde7091-171c-4c95-b51f-5402ef56bb8a/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.1.docx/docx/1) Schedule The summons shall, in addition to requiring the attendance of the defaulter at a sitting of the Court, also require the defaulter to complete, detach and lodge with the Clerk not less than one week before the date of the said sitting a statement of means and assets (in the Form 53.3 Schedule with the necessary modifications), which shall be attached to the summons. (2) The applicant or solicitor for the applicant shall be entitled, on payment of the prescribed fee, to inspect and take or obtain copies of the statement of means at any time after it is lodged.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant of distress and sale under section of the Act of 1940 follow?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 60.3 Schedule","Form 57.2 Schedule","Form 57.1 Schedule","Form 57.2 Schedule A"],"justification":"A warrant of distress and sale under section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/38749eea-3bc2-43d2-be1a-ada03602921d/Warrant of distress and sale - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Distress warrant** 5. A warrant of distress and sale under section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.2](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/38749eea-3bc2-43d2-be1a-ada03602921d/Warrant of distress and sale - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (as amended by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 63) No. 57.2.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What happens upon receipt of the completed application form by the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Clerk will schedule a court hearing.","The Clerk will issue a summons.","The Clerk will send an email confirmation to the applicant.","The Clerk will forward the application to the relevant department for review."],"justification":"Upon receipt of the completed application from, the Clerk will issue a summons."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application\*\*\***in writing for summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010\*\*\* 6.**[2]** An application under section 9A(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (as inserted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) or under section 52A(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (as inserted by section 146 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) for the issue of a summons may be made by the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in the [Form 57.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de505ada-98be-4de0-97bc-a3cd9276d517/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.3.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application from, the Clerk will issue a summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What form must a summons addressed to a maintenance debtor be in?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form 57.3A Schedule","Form 57.3A Schedule","Form Schedule","Form 57.3 Schedule"],"justification":"The summons addressed to the maintenance debtor must be in the Form [57.3A Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/06eb5b14-6585-4a62-b3cb-05032e52813a/57.3A_SI_Basic_text_Summons_to_recover_Maintenance_Arrears_specified_in_Court Rules.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010** 7.[3] The summons addressed to the maintenance debtor must be in the Form [57.3A Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/06eb5b14-6585-4a62-b3cb-05032e52813a/57.3A_SI_Basic_text_Summons_to_recover_Maintenance_Arrears_specified_in_Court Rules.docx/docx/1). ##'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should an order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the Act of 1940 be made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the Act of 1940 must be in Form 57.1 Schedule A.","An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the Act of 1940 must be in Form 57.3 Schedule","An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the Act of 1940 must be in Form 57.5 Schedule","An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the Act of 1940 may be in Form 57.4 Schedule"],"justification":"An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) may be in the [Form 57.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3022a2b1-6ed7-4036-94c6-7ff708590ba3/Notice Of Application To Vary A Garnishee Order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Service of summonses, application forms and orders** 8.[4] (1) [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons and application form mentioned in rule 4. (2) [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 8(5), 8(7) and 8(8) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons mentioned in rule 7 and application form mentioned in rule 6. A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing. (3) An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) may be in the [Form 57.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3022a2b1-6ed7-4036-94c6-7ff708590ba3/Notice Of Application To Vary A Garnishee Order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such order must be sent by registered post by the Clerk to every person directed to pay monies to the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'When must copies of the notice of application be served on the defaulter and the applicant?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Not later than three days before the hearing of the application.","Not later than seven days before the hearing of the application.","Immediately upon filing the application, regardless of the hearing date.","Within thirty days after the hearing of the application has concluded."],"justification":"A copy of the notice shall be served on the defaulter and on the applicant not later than seven days before the hearing of the application"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Persons affected by garnishee order** 9.(1) A person served with an order mentioned in rule 8(3) who is unable to comply with the order may apply to the Court by notice of application in the [Form 57.5](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/537ff74b-79ab-44a4-9185-6c4ea61f9014/Notice of application to vary a garnishee order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.5.docx/docx/1) Schedule to set aside or vary the order. A copy of the notice shall be served on the defaulter and on the applicant not later than seven days before the hearing of the application and the original notice shall be lodged with the Clerk not later than four days before the hearing of the application. (2) Where the Court is considering making an order under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), the Court may adjourn the hearing of the summons and direct that the person who would be directed to pay monies to the Clerk under any such order be put on notice of the adjourned application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant of arrest take when issued under specific sections of the Acts of 1976 and 2010?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It should be in accordance with Form 45.3 Schedule A.","It should be in accordance with Form 72.2 Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 68.9 Schedule","It should be in accordance with Form 57.6 Schedule"],"justification":"A warrant of arrest issued under section 9A(5) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or 52A(5) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fa7efc1e-7516-4693-960e-e597ff6c36de/Warrant of arrest - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976, section 9A(5) (as inserted by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 31) No. 57.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Warrant of arrest** 10. A warrant of arrest issued under section 9A(5) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or 52A(5) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) shall be in accordance with [Form 57.6](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/fa7efc1e-7516-4693-960e-e597ff6c36de/Warrant of arrest - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976, section 9A(5) (as inserted by Civil Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2011, section 31) No. 57.6.docx/docx/1) Schedule'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What form should a warrant of detention take when an order of imprisonment is made due to contempt of court?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["It should be in accordance with Form 60.9 or 60.10 Schedule as appropriate.","It should be in accordance with Form 57.7 or 57.8 Schedule as appropriate.","It should be in accordance with Form 45.6 or 45.7 Schedule as appropriate.","It should be in accordance with Form 12.3 or 12.4 Schedule A, as appropriate."],"justification":"the warrant of detention shall be in accordance with [Form 57.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c232310a-6e21-4ab3-9e64-3238d268540d/Warrant of detention (where debtor has attended) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.7.docx/docx/1) or [57.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55796fe-ed99-4d9d-b822-009865e6013f/Warrant of detention (failure to attend) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Warrant of detention** 11. Where a failure by the maintenance debtor is treated as constituting contempt of court and an order of imprisonment is made, the warrant of detention shall be in accordance with [Form 57.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/c232310a-6e21-4ab3-9e64-3238d268540d/Warrant of detention (where debtor has attended) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.7.docx/docx/1) or [57.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/e55796fe-ed99-4d9d-b822-009865e6013f/Warrant of detention (failure to attend) - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.8.docx/docx/1) Schedule as appropriate.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What must happen when a person is imprisoned for contempt of court under certain sections?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The person must appear before the court verbally to explain how they will address the contempt, without written notification.","The person shall be automatically released after a set period without needing to take any specific actions.","The person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge their contempt.","The person must be fined an amount determined by the court without any requirement for notification."],"justification":"the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application to purge contempt** 12. Where a person is imprisoned for contempt of court in accordance with section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24): - (a) the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt; - the Court may direct that, if the contempt has not previously been purged, the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What documents must be tendered or caused to be tendered as evidence during the hearing of an application under sections 8(1), 9A, or 52A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The maintenance order, variation order, interim order, a copy of the maintenance order in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or of the Maintenance Regulation in the case of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the Maintenance Regulation, the application for the summons, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, and any other relevant document.","The birth certificate of the applicant, a copy of the national card, a letter of intent, and any other relevant document.","The original passport of all parties involved, a signed affidavit of income, a list of assets and liabilities, and a personal statement from each party.","A marriage certificate, a divorce decree, a child custody agreement, and a financial affidavit."],"justification":"- (a) the maintenance order, variation order, interim order, (as the case may be); - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order; - in the case of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the [Maintenance Regulation](\u003chttps://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng\u003e), a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the [Maintenance Regulation](\u003chttps://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng\u003e), of the decision issued by the court of origin; - the application for the summons; - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court, and - any other relevant document."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Clerk to provide certificate and to be available to tender evidence** 13. (1) Before the time fixed for the hearing of an application under section 8 of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), any Clerk for another court area to whom payments under the maintenance order, variation order, interim order or enforceable maintenance order are payable shall send to the Clerk a certificate signed by him or her certifying the amount of monies outstanding on foot of such order. (2) On the hearing of an application under section 8(1) of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html), section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24), without prejudice to any other evidence which may be required on that hearing, there shall be tendered or cause to be tendered as evidence - - (a) the maintenance order, variation order, interim order, (as the case may be); - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order a copy of the maintenance order; - in the case of a decision referred to in Article 17.1 of the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), a copy of the extract in the form set out in Annex or, as the case may be, Annex to the [Maintenance Regulation](<https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2009/4(1)/oj/eng>), of the decision issued by the court of origin; - the application for the summons; - in the case of an enforceable maintenance order, a copy of the order made by the Master of the High Court, and - any other relevant document.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What provisions regarding warrants apply to those issued under this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The provisions contained in Order 32 regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order.","The provisions contained in Order 26 regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order.","The provisions contained in Order 28 regarding arrest warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order.","The provisions contained in Order 19 regarding search and seizure shall apply to warrants issued under this Order."],"justification":"The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Provisions regarding warrants to apply** 14. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order with the proviso that warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the several Sheriffs and County Registrars. [1] Order 57 substituted in full by [S.I. 202 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/202/made/en/print), effective 5 May 2021. Superseded amendments: Order 57 originally substituted by [S.I. 325 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/325/made/en/print?q 325&years 2010), re-substituted by [S.I. 306 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/si/306/made/en/print?q 306&years 2013), substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016. [2] Order 57 rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [3] Order 57 rule 7 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [4] Order 57 rule 8 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', '', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":[""],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court - Court: District # Order 39A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What section does this chunk belong to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Examples","Conclusion","Definitions","Introduction"],"justification":"Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is meant by ''digital delivery'' in the context of court documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Hand-delivery of a court document or other document to or from a digital user, as defined in the Order.","Physical transportation of court documents via postal mail to or from a digital user, as defined in the Order.","Oral communication of the content of a court document to or from a digital user, as defined in the Order.","Delivery of a court document or other document by electronic means to or from a digital user, as defined in the Order."],"justification":"“**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the Clerk, - by or on behalf of the Clerk to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**Clerk**”, where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk; “**court document**” includes any claim notice, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the Clerk in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the Clerk, - by or on behalf of the Clerk to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership, acting through a person authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person, which is or who is for the time being authorised to deliver to the Clerk and to receive from the Clerk by digital means any court document or other document which may be lodged or filed in or with the Court in or in connection with any proceedings or category of proceedings in the Court, in respect of which digital delivery is for the time being authorised in accordance with section 20 of the [Civil Law and Criminal Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 202](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/act/13/enacted/en/html)0; “**network**” means an electronic information and communications network or system maintained and supported by the Courts Service for the purposes of use by court users in civil proceedings, for the time being in use in or for the purposes of the Court, to which digital users have access, and which is used or capable of use for digital delivery;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is ''personal delivery'' of a court document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Submitting the court document electronically through the court’s online portal, including all necessary copies and proof of payment of court fees.","Lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any required copies and proof of payment of court fees (if applicable), by attending the office used by the Clerk.","Posting the court document via registered mail to the Clerk’s office, including all necessary copies and proof of payment of court fees, ensuring it is received on a weekday during office hours.","Sending an email to the Clerk''s official email address containing the court document as an attachment, along with any required copies and proof of payment of court fees."],"justification":"“**personal delivery**” means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '“**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the Clerk: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the Clerk, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**personal delivery**” means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title of the current part of Order 39A?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Sanctions and penalties","Procedures for filing complaints","Amendments to previous orders","Form of documents and provision of copies"],"justification":"Form of documents and provision of copies"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Form of documents and provision of copies'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'How must notices and notifications required by these Rules be given?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Through email only, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given through other digital means.","Orally, unless expressly required by the Court to be given in writing.","In writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally.","Via social media, unless expressly prohibited by the Court."],"justification":"All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Notices in writing_ 2.(1) All notices and notifications required by these Rules must be given in writing, unless expressly permitted by the Court to be given orally. (2) Nothing in this Order operates to require a document delivered in electronic form, including by digital delivery, to be printed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Can documents delivered digitally be provided without a printed form?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Yes, but only if they are accompanied by an audio recording of the document being read aloud.","No, digital documents cannot replace printed forms under any circumstances.","Yes, if they are capable of being presented or reproduced in legible form.","Only if the recipient specifically requests a digital document instead of a printed form."],"justification":"any such document need not be provided in printed form, notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Form of documents_ 3.(1) Any document for use in Court which is required or permitted to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by delivery in person (of a hard copy) or by delivery by post (of a hard copy) must be clearly and legibly printed or written on A4 size paper. (2) Where a document is for the time being authorised in accordance with this Order to be filed or lodged with the Clerk by digital delivery or to be produced in digital form (in soft copy) for use in Court, such document may comprise or include: - (a) information transmitted in the form of an electronic document or other electronic data to a network (including, for the avoidance of doubt, a statement of truth), and - information made available to a digital user on a network to which the digital user concerned has secure access, which is capable of being presented or reproduced in legible form, and any such document need not be provided in printed form, notwithstanding any other provision of these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if a party fails to provide a requested copy of a document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The party seeking the document may obtain a copy from the Clerk.","The party seeking the document is required to purchase a copy at their own expense.","The party failing to provide the document automatically loses the case.","The party seeking the document may be fined by the court."],"justification":"if that party fails to provide a copy, the party seeking the document may obtain a copy from the Clerk"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Provision of copy documents_ 4. Any party who is entitled to a copy of a document which has been filed by or on behalf of another party may request such a copy from the party who filed it, and if that party fails to provide a copy, the party seeking the document may obtain a copy from the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'How can a party provide a copy of a digitally delivered document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["By sending an unverified email attachment that may not be identical to the digital original.","By offering a verbal summary of the content of the digital document without any physical or digital copies.","By providing a legible print that matches the digital original or a certified copy of such a legible print.","By providing a low-resolution scan that does not match the digital original in terms of clarity and readability."],"justification":"the party who has filed it or his solicitor may satisfy a request for a copy by providing a legible print which corresponds entirely in its content with the digital original document, or by providing a certified copy of such a legible print"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Provision of copies_ 5. Where a document has been filed or lodged by digital delivery, the party who has filed it or his solicitor may satisfy a request for a copy by providing a legible print which corresponds entirely in its content with the digital original document, or by providing a certified copy of such a legible print.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who can certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Judge","The Jury","The Clerk","The Attorney"],"justification":"The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Copy certified by Clerk_ 6. The Clerk may certify a copy of an original document or a legible print of a document which has been filed by digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does the section title indicate about the content?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["It indicates the content will discuss the history of document storage methods.","It indicates the content will discuss legal procedures for document destruction.","It indicates the content will discuss how documents are lodged or filed through personal delivery.","It indicates the content will discuss how documents are stored electronically."],"justification":""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## III. Lodgment or filing of documents by personal delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'How can lodgment or filing of documents be effected?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By leaving the documents in the office''s mailbox after closing hours","By personal delivery during the hours the public office is open to the public","By sending the documents via email at any time of the day","By submitting the documents through regular mail outside of business hours"],"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Personal delivery at office_ 7. Lodgment or filing of documents may be effected by personal delivery during the hours at which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the section title related to lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["III. Lodgment of documents by email attachment","Personal submission of documents during business hours","Submission of digital documents via online portal","Lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy"],"justification":"## Lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Lodgment or filing of documents by non-personal delivery in hard copy'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who may stipulate conditions for non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Postmaster","The Assistant","The Clerk","The Secretary"],"justification":"The Clerk may stipulate conditions, to be published in such manner as the Clerk may approve, subject to which non-personal delivery in hard copy of a court document may be effected."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for non-personal delivery in hard copy_ 8.(1) The Clerk may stipulate conditions, to be published in such manner as the Clerk may approve, subject to which non-personal delivery in hard copy of a court document may be effected. (2) Such conditions referred to in sub-rule (1) may be particular or general, and may include a requirement for the discharge of the expense of returning any court document, or copy of such document, by particular means to the person who has delivered it. Where no such conditions are for the time being stipulated, the existing practice shall continue to be used. (3) Where a provision of these Rules requires or authorises a party or person to lodge or file any court document, such lodgment or filing may be effected by non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with any condition stipulated for that means of non-personal delivery in hard copy.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must accompany a court document when it is authorised to be lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A certified copy of the individual''s driver''s license or government-issued","A declaration of intent signed by the legal representative of the entity submitting the document.","Such document, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with rule 8.","A signed affidavit confirming the identity of the person authorising the non-personal delivery."],"justification":"- (a) the court document must be accompanied by such document, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with rule 8;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Additional requirements for non-personal delivery in hard copy_ 9.(1) Where any court document is authorised to be lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such document, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning non-personal delivery in hard copy in accordance with rule 8; - where payment of a court fee is chargeable in respect of the lodgment of the court document, the court document shall not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee; - the date of lodgment of the document is, unless the contrary is proven, deemed to be the date of lodgment recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk and such date may be endorsed on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk; - for the purpose of fixing the return date of any notice of application (or other originating document or notice of motion requiring a return date) lodged for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, a period of four days must, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - there must be delivered with any court document lodged by non-personal delivery in hard copy so many copies of that document and such other documents as would be required on the personal delivery of that court document. (2) Where a court document, having been issued, has been returned to the party or person who lodged it for issue by non-personal delivery in hard copy, and that court document is not received by that party or person within a reasonable time after it is sent, - (a) the Clerk concerned may, at the request of that party or person, furnish to that person -'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is required when proceeding on a copy of a court document under non-personal delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An email from the Clerk mentioning the existence of the document, without attaching a copy or providing any certification.","A copy of the court document certified by the Clerk with a certificate confirming its issue, or a copy certified by the party or their solicitor as a true copy, along with a certificate about the record of the issue.","A handwritten note from the party stating that they agree with the contents of the document, without any official certification or confirmation of issue.","A simple photocopy of the court document without any certification from either the Clerk or the party''s solicitor."],"justification":"- the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i) or, where the Court so permits, a copy of the court document lodged for issue, certified by the party who lodged it or his or her solicitor to be a true copy of the court document lodged, and a certificate given in accordance with paragraph (a)(ii)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- a copy of any duplicate or copy of the court document concerned retained by the Clerk, with a certificate endorsed thereon confirming the issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates; - a certificate as to any record made of the issue of the court document concerned, and - the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i) or, where the Court so permits, a copy of the court document lodged for issue, certified by the party who lodged it or his or her solicitor to be a true copy of the court document lodged, and a certificate given in accordance with paragraph (a)(ii).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What section title is used to describe the lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Authentication of digital signatures","Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery","Service of process by email","Payment of fees via digital means"],"justification":"Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Lodgment or filing of documents by digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if there is a conflict between a rule of this Order and another rule in these Rules regarding digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The rule with the higher numerical order number prevails.","Both rules are disregarded in favor of a new rule created by the administrator.","The rule of this Order prevails.","The other rule in these Rules regarding digital delivery prevails."],"justification":"In the event that any conflict arises between the provision of any rule of this Order and any other provision of these Rules, the provision of the rule of this Order will, in respect of the digital delivery of any document, prevail."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _This Part prevails where digital delivery is concerned_ 11.(1) In the event that any conflict arises between the provision of any rule of this Order and any other provision of these Rules, the provision of the rule of this Order will, in respect of the digital delivery of any document, prevail. (2) The provisions of this Order are without prejudice to the use of and permission of access to any network used for any purpose not regulated by these Rules.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What happens if digital delivery is authorised under a Practice Direction?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["It requires all documents to be physically delivered within 24 hours of being digitally delivered.","It restricts the use of digital delivery to only weekdays between 9 and 5","It invalidates any previously submitted documents via traditional methods.","It becomes an alternative to any other method by which such document could be filed, lodged, issued or transmitted"],"justification":"Unless otherwise expressly provided in such Practice Direction, where the use of digital delivery is authorised in accordance with sub-rule (1), such delivery will be an alternative to any other method by which such document could be filed, lodged, issued or transmitted by or to the party or person concerned."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Authorisation of digital delivery of court documents or documents_ 12.(1) Having consulted with the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service the President of the Court may, from time to time, by Practice Direction, authorise (including on a temporary or trial basis) the use of digital delivery by or in respect of any: - category or class of proceedings or of applications within proceedings, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - category or class of documents, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - (iii) category or class of parties, legal representatives and/or other persons interested in proceedings (in this rule a “court user”), either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally. (2) Unless otherwise expressly provided in such Practice Direction, where the use of digital delivery is authorised in accordance with sub-rule (1), such delivery will be an alternative to any other method by which such document could be filed, lodged, issued or transmitted by or to the party or person concerned. (3) A network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is, for the purposes of the delivery of any court document or document to any Clerk, deemed to be operational only during the hours during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public. (4) Any period when a network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is inoperative will be treated, for the purposes of [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), Rule as a period during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is closed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a firm of solicitors or legal partnership do to become a digital user?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Submit a list of past clients and their feedback.","Submit evidence of establishment and standing, identity of authorised persons, and undertake to comply with terms and conditions.","Pay a one-time registration fee and provide a business plan.","Provide proof of physical office space and its size."],"justification":"- the firm or partnership has first submitted sufficient evidence of its establishment and standing; - the firm or partnership has submitted sufficient evidence of the identity of each natural person authorised on behalf of the firm to transmit court documents through the network by digital delivery; - (iii) the firm or partnership has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for becoming digital user_ 13.(1) A natural person may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - such person has first submitted sufficient evidence of his or her identity which may, without limitation, include: - (a) production of the original or a certified copy of a relevant document (within the meaning of section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)); - provision of the personal public service number (within the meaning of section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) issued to the person; - provision of proof of the person’s residential address, and - such person has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery. (2) A firm of solicitors or legal partnership may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - the firm or partnership has first submitted sufficient evidence of its establishment and standing; - the firm or partnership has submitted sufficient evidence of the identity of each natural person authorised on behalf of the firm to transmit court documents through the network by digital delivery; - (iii) the firm or partnership has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who has the authority to stipulate additional conditions for use of the network?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The Network Administrator of a Small Business, with the approval of the Manager","The Head of the Local School Board, with the approval of the Principal","The Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service, with the approval of the President of the Court","The Chief Information Officer of a Private Corporation, with the approval of the CEO"],"justification":"The Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service may, with the approval of the President of the Court in respect of proceedings in the Court, stipulate additional conditions for use of the network."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Additional conditions for use of the network_ 14.(1) The Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service may, with the approval of the President of the Court in respect of proceedings in the Court, stipulate additional conditions for use of the network.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must accompany a court document authorised to be filed or lodged by digital delivery when a court fee is chargeable?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["An electronic signature from the party filing the document indicating their agreement to the terms of service.","Payment of the applicable court fee must be recorded by a means authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee.","A copy of the party''s identification proving they are authorized to file documents in the court.","A notarized statement confirming the intention to pay the court fee within the next 30 days."],"justification":"- where a court fee is chargeable in respect of the court document, the court document may not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Documents transmitted by digital delivery_ 15.(1) Any court document transmitted by digital delivery by or on behalf of a party must: - (a) contain: - the name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the same or, as the case may be, - the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person; - include the name of the natural person transmitting the court document concerned; - where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted. (2) Any document other than a court document which is transmitted by or on behalf of a party by digital delivery as a copy in electronic form of an original document must have endorsed on or associated with such copy a certificate given by the party or by a named solicitor that the copy has been compared to, and is a true copy, of the original document. (3) Where any court document is authorised to be filed or lodged by digital delivery: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such information, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning digital delivery in accordance with rule 14; - where a court fee is chargeable in respect of the court document, the court document may not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or issue of a court document if digital delivery is used?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["The date the document was first drafted by the party submitting it.","The date the recipient clicked on the link to view the document electronically.","The date recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk or on the network.","The date the document was printed out after being sent digitally."],"justification":"the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk or on the network"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue of the court document shall, unless the contrary is proven, be deemed to be the date of filing, lodgment or, as the case may be, issue recorded in any record kept for the purpose by or on behalf of the Clerk or on the network and such date may be endorsed electronically on the court document and any copies by or on behalf of the Clerk and may be notified electronically through the network to the party concerned; - for the purpose of fixing a return date for any originating document or notice of motion which requires a return date, and which is lodged for issue by digital delivery, a period of four days will, in any case in which service is necessary, be allowed, subject to the provisions of any order of the Court in that regard; - any obligation or entitlement arising under these Rules to lodge or, as the case may be, to file a court document shall, unless the contrary is proved, be satisfied by the digital delivery of the document to the network and the issuance by the network of confirmation of lodgment or, as the case may be, filing; - the network or the Clerk will alert digital users, prior to submission, where the filing, lodgment or issue of any court document is subject to checking by a court officer. (4) Where the Clerk is satisfied that it is necessary to do so, he or she may: - (a) retransmit a court document, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned; - deliver a printed copy of the court document concerned by delivery in hard copy, and may certify the date of issue of the court document concerned, and in either such case, any party or person affected may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a court document or copy of a court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a) or'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the obligation of the party filing an affidavit via digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["To retain the affidavit with the original manuscript signature and all marked exhibits.","To destroy the original affidavit after submitting it digitally.","To submit the affidavit without retaining any copies or original signatures.","To modify the affidavit after submission to ensure accuracy."],"justification":"it shall be and remain the obligation of the party filing any such affidavit to retain the affidavit bearing the original manuscript signature of the deponent and any and all of the marked exhibits to the affidavit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where any affidavit is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, the affidavit shall be transmitted in such electronic format as is accommodated by the network, and it shall be and remain the obligation of the party filing any such affidavit to retain the affidavit bearing the original manuscript signature of the deponent and any and all of the marked exhibits to the affidavit, which remain subject to the directions of any court before which such affidavit is, or may be, relied upon or opened. (6) Where any written statement of evidence or written statement outlining the essential elements of evidence is authorised or required by any Practice Direction or any order or direction of the Court to be delivered and/or filed in any proceedings in which digital delivery is for the time being authorised, such statement may be delivered and/or filed by transmission through the network, but shall, if intended to be admitted into evidence, be subject to verification on oath or affirmation at the trial of the proceedings. (7) Where any affidavit or any statement referred to in sub-rule (6) is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, [Order 50A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url statements-of-truth), rule 6 shall apply *mutatis mutandis* to any exhibits to such affidavit or statement.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What can satisfy the requirement for a signature on a court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Any digital mark placed on the document, including those created via social media platforms or casual email attachments, as long as they signify approval.","A handwritten signature on paper only, even if scanned and attached as an image to the digital document.","An electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the Electronic Commerce Act 2000 and/or Article 3 of Regulation when used in accordance with the requirements of that Act and/or that Regulation.","A digital watermark embedded within the document, regardless of whether it meets any legal standards specified in the Electronic Commerce Act 2000 or Regulation"],"justification":"such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of that Act and/or that Regulation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Signature_ 16. Where any provision of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires that any court document or document be signed, such requirement may be satisfied in the case of any court document or document transmitted or to be transmitted by digital delivery by the inclusion of an electronic signature within the meaning of section 2 of the [Electronic Commerce Act 2000](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2000/act/27/enacted/en/html) and/or Article 3 of [Regulation 910/2014/EU](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2014/910/oj/eng), which is used in accordance with the requirements of that Act and/or that Regulation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What section title indicates the use of digital delivery for service of documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Physical delivery of documents in person","Handing over documents through a third party","Service of documents via postal mail","Service of documents using digital delivery"],"justification":"## Service of documents using digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Service of documents using digital delivery'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'How can a court document be served if the recipient is a digital user?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["By faxing it to the recipient''s home fax number.","By sending it via regular postal mail to the recipient''s last known address.","By posting it on a public social media platform visible to the recipient.","By transmitting it through digital delivery over the network."],"justification":"such requirement may be satisfied in any case where the person to be served is or becomes a digital user by the transmission by digital delivery of the court document or document through the network to the person concerned"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Service of documents where digital delivery applies_ 17.(1) Where any provision of any enactment, of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires or permits that any court document or document be served upon any person, such requirement may be satisfied in any case where the person to be served is or becomes a digital user by the transmission by digital delivery of the court document or document through the network to the person concerned, and in any such case any record generated by or within the network of such transmission may be produced as evidence of such service in lieu of any statutory declaration of service. (Where the person to be served is not a digital user, such person shall be served with a printed copy of the court document or document in such other manner as is permitted in the circumstances by these Rules). (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply in any case where these Rules or the existing practice of the Court require personal service, but any requirement that a person being served personally with a court document be shown any original or copy of the court document shall, where the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery, be satisfied by serving the person personally with a copy of the court document concerned and, at the same time, providing the person with a written statement that the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Correct use of digital delivery network","Overview of digital security measures","Misuse of digital delivery network","Introduction to cloud computing services"],"justification":"Misuse of digital delivery network"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## VII. Misuse of digital delivery network'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'In which court does Order 11A apply?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme Court","High Court","Circuit Court","District Court"],"justification":"- Court: Circuit"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. - Court: Circuit # Order 11A: Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court. [1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'What is the title of this section?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Definitions","History","III. Applications","Examples"],"justification":"## Definitions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Definitions'),
                                                                                                                 ('Circuit – Order 11A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court.', 'Court Rules', 'What is considered ''digital delivery'' of a court document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Delivery of a document through a verbal agreement from a digital user to the proper officer, by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or by a digital user to another digital user.","Delivery of a document by electronic means from a digital user to the proper officer, by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or by a digital user to another digital user.","Delivery of a document by postal mail from a digital user to the proper officer, by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or by a digital user to another digital user.","Delivery of a physical copy of a document by hand from a digital user to the proper officer, by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or by a digital user to another digital user."],"justification":"“**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the proper officer, - by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party),"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**proper officer”** are references to the Combined Court Office manager for the time being responsible for the management of the Office of the Court for the relevant county, and where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the Circuit Court for the circuit and/or county concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Combined Court Office manager; “**court document**” includes any civil bill, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the proper officer in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the proper officer: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the proper officer, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the proper officer, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the proper officer, - by or on behalf of the proper officer to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership acting through a person or persons authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person,'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'In what form should the court''s order granting an excluding order be issued?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Form","Form 99A.2","Form","Form"],"justification":"The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Excluding Orders* 4. (1) An application to the Court under section 3 of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) for an excluding order shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.1, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/331b2936-1752-49cc-82e8-f8bb1cff527f/Application For An Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.1.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1). (3) Where an excluding order is made by the Court in accordance with the provisions of section 12(12)(a) of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) on foot of a possession application under section 12 of that Act, the order shall be in the Form [99A.2, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/66554d89-6cf0-4d18-ba84-41ed84edf527/Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 section 3 No. 99A.2.docx/docx/1), with any necessary modifications.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What form should be issued and served before an application to vary an excluding order is made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form","Form","Form","Form 99A.7"],"justification":"shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b135a660-4139-4bf7-9106-e0177cefb952/Application To Vary An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.7.docx/docx/1)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Vary Excluding/ Site Excluding/ Interim Excluding/Site Excluding Orders* 7. (1) An application to the Court under - (a) section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an excluding order, - section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, - section 3A(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary a site excluding order, or section 3(5) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) as applied by section 4(2) and section 3A(9) of the [1997 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/act/21/enacted/en/html) to vary an interim excluding order, shall be preceded by the issue and service of a notice in the [Form 99A.7](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b135a660-4139-4bf7-9106-e0177cefb952/Application To Vary An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order No. 99A.7.docx/docx/1). (2) The order of the Court granting the application shall be in the [Form 99A.8](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/5ee4a98d-c7c5-44f1-a4ed-9981fa04bbd1/Order Varying An Interim Excluding Order - An Interim Site Excluding Order - An Excluding Order - A Site Excluding Order - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.8.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What action must the Clerk take when an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order ceases to have effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Clerk must send a verbal notification to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.","The Clerk must send an email notification to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.","The Clerk must publish a notice in a national newspaper when an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order ceases to have effect.","The Clerk must send a notice by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10."],"justification":"the Clerk shall send notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1), that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Clerk to notify Gardaí when Interim Excluding/Site Excluding orders ceases to have effect.* 11.[4] Where an interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has been made and the application for an excluding order or site excluding order has been determined, the Clerk shall send notice in the [Form 99A.11, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/54c951f1-ff98-4814-ba92-5e0364afbcd8/Notice That Interim Excluding Order - Interim Site Excluding Order Has Ceased To Have Effect - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 No. 99A.11.docx/docx/1), that the interim excluding order or interim site excluding order has ceased to have effect, by prepaid registered post to the member of the Garda Síochána referred to in rule 10.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Which form is required before making an application to the Court under section 16 of the 2014 Act?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Form 99A.16, Schedule A","Form 99A.17, Schedule","Form Schedule","Form 99A.16, Schedule"],"justification":"[Form 99A.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fa2e86f-09d5-4fa6-8d02-1ae9dbf6986b/Application in respect of a tenancy terminated under section 15 Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 No. 99A.16.docx/docx/1)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Application to Court in respect of terminated tenancy* 16. An application to the Court under section 16 of the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) shall be preceded by the issue and service upon the housing authority concerned of a notice in the [Form 99A.16, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/0fa2e86f-09d5-4fa6-8d02-1ae9dbf6986b/Application in respect of a tenancy terminated under section 15 Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014 No. 99A.16.docx/docx/1).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99A - Procedure under - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1997 - Housing (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2014', 'Court Rules', 'How many days before the hearing must a copy of the notice and any sworn information, along with a statutory declaration of service, be lodged with the Clerk?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["At least four days","At least one day","At least three days","At least two days"],"justification":"A copy of the notice and information sworn, if any, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date for hearing the application."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### *Service and lodgment of notices* 17. (1) Save where the [2014 Act](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/act/21/enacted/en/html) otherwise provides, a notice under this Part and information sworn, if any, shall be served in accordance with [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) at least 10 working days before the date for hearing of the application. (2) A copy of the notice and information sworn, if any, together with a statutory declaration as to service thereof shall be lodged with the Clerk at least four days before the date for hearing the application. [1] Order 99A inserted by [S.I. 217 of 1999](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1999/si/217/made/en/print?q 217&years 1999), substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [2] Order 99A rule 6 originally substituted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), re-substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [3] Order 99A sub-rule of rule 7 originally inserted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [4] Order 99A sub-rule of rule 11 substituted by [S.I. 133 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/133/made/en/print?q 133&years 2006), re-substituted by [S.I. 506 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/506/made/en/print?q 506&years 2016), effective 21 October 2016 [5] Order 99A, sub-rule (3) of rule 15 inserted by [S.I. 497 of 2020](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/si/497/made/en/print), effective 10 November 2020'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 99B - Employment Equality Act 1998 and Equal Status Act 2000', 'Court Rules', 'How far in advance must the notice of application be served on the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Immediately upon the filing of the application, regardless of the date of the sitting.","Not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","Not later than three days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable.","Within fourteen days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."],"justification":"Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 99B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e4ee31-e67a-4e79-a727-232520a11772/Notice Of Application - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '4. The original of every notice of appeal, together with a statutory declaration as to the service thereof, shall be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the sitting of the Court. The Order of the Court hearing the appeal shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/b2e23701-561f-4ecf-a414-0f6ecc0c5cce/Order - Employment Equality Act 1998 No. 99B.2.docx/docx/1). 5.[2] An application to the Court for an order pursuant to Section 9 of the [Terms of Employment (Information) Act, 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) may be made to any sitting of the Court for the court district in which the respondent employer carries on any trade profession, business or occupation. 6.[3] Such application shall be by notice of application in the [Form 99B.3](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/52e4ee31-e67a-4e79-a727-232520a11772/Notice Of Application - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.3.docx/docx/1), Schedule and shall be served on the respondent by prepaid registered post not later than seven days before the date of the sitting for which the application is returnable. An order made pursuant to section 9 of the said [Act of 1994](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1994/act/5/enacted/en/html) on such application shall be in the [Form Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/1da65de6-ec5f-445b-87e5-6783b9dd15eb/Order - Terms Of Employment (Information) Act, 1994, Section 9 No. 99B.4.docx/docx/1). [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 263 of 2006](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2006/si/263/made/en/print?q 263&years 2006), effective 20 June 2006 [2] Order rule 5 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003 [3] Order rule 6 inserted by [S.I. 409 of 2003](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2003/si/409/made/en/print?q 409&years 2003), effective 9 October 2003'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'What court does the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 apply to?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Supreme Court","Court of Appeal","District Court","High Court"],"justification":"- Court: District"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 - Court: District # Provisions Overview[1]'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'When do the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014 come into effect?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["On the day of March 2014","On the day of February 2014","On the day of February 2015","On the day of January 2014"],"justification":"These Rules, which may be cited as the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014, shall come into operation on the day of February 2014."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *1. Title and citation* 1. (1) These Rules, which may be cited as the District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014, shall come into operation on the day of February 2014. (2) These Rules shall be construed together with the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) (S.I. No. 93 of 1997) and all other District Court Rules. (3) The District Court Rules as amended by these Rules may be cited as the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93) to [2014](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2014/si/17/made/en/print).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Which orders are being deleted from the District Court Rules 1997?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order 8, rule 3; Order 9; Orders 39 to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100","Order 8, rule 2; Order 11; Orders 40 to inclusive; Order 63; Order 101 and Order 102","Order 7, rule 3; Order 8; Orders 38 to inclusive; Order 61; Order 97 and Order 98","Order 5, rule 3; Order 10; Orders 29 to inclusive; Order 52; Order 98 and Order 99"],"justification":"namely [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 3; Order 9; [Orders 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules) to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *2. Amendments* 2. (1) The provisions set out in Schedule 1 shall be substituted for the “**Interpretation of Terms**” provisions of the District Court Rules 1997. (2) The following provisions shall be deleted from the [District Court Rules 1997](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1997/si/93), namely [Order 8]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-8-District-Tendering-Of-Evidence), rule 3; Order 9; [Orders 39]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-39-District-General-Rules) to inclusive; Order 62; Order 99 and Order 100. (3) The provisions set out in Schedule 2 shall be inserted to the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Order 38. (4) The Schedule of Costs set out in Schedule 3 shall be substituted for the [Schedule of Costs]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Schedule-of-Costs-District-Court-Solicitors-costs-Rules) and the Schedule of Counsel’s Fees to the District Court Rules 1997. (5) Orders 10 and 12 respectively set out in Schedule 4 shall be substituted for [Orders 10]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-10-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Criminal-Proceedings) and [12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions) of the District Court Rules 1997.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Provisions Overview - District Court (Civil Procedure) Rules 2014', 'Court Rules', 'Which forms will be deleted from Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Forms 101.1 to 101.6 inclusive","Forms 100.7 to 100.12 inclusive","Forms 200.1 to 200.6 inclusive","Forms 100.1 to 100.6 inclusive"],"justification":"Forms 100.1 to 100.6 inclusive shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## *3. Replacement of forms* 3. (1) Forms 7.1 to 7.6 inclusive, Forms 39.1 to inclusive, Forms 62.1 to 62.25 inclusive and Form 99.1 shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (2) Forms 100.1 to 100.6 inclusive shall be deleted from Schedule to the District Court Rules 1997. (3) The forms set out in Schedule 5 shall be added to Schedule of the District Court Rules 1997 immediately following Form'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What are the solicitors'' costs if the amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice for an amount exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["€682.00","€482.00","€382.00","€882.00"],"justification":"If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | € | € | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 410.00 | 682.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **1. Solicitors’ costs in civil debt claims** | | | | | --- | --- | --- | | Amount due at date of issue of the claim notice | If amount due is paid within ten days of service of claim notice | If amount due is not paid within ten days of service of claim notice | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 82.00 | 137.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 164.00 | 273.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 246.00 | 410.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 328.00 | 546.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 410.00 | 682.00 | The above scale of costs (1) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay. If the claim notice is defended the costs of the successful party are in accordance with the contract, breach of contract and tort scale for assessment of damages.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What is the cost if a case is not defended and the annual rent exceeds €6,000 but does not exceed €9,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["745.00","1045.00","845.00","945.00"],"justification":"Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 1,228.00 | 1,418.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **3. Solicitors’ costs in landlord and tenant (ejectment) proceedings** | | | | | | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Annual Rent | Costs if settled before without necessity for appearance | Costs of judgment (decree) if case not defended | Costs of judgment (decree) if case defended (assessment of damages) | Costs of judgment (decree/ dismiss) if case defended (liability) | | | | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 189.00 | 315.00 | 410.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 378.00 | 630.00 | 819.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 1,228.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 756.00 | 1,260.00 | 1,638.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 945.00 | 1,575.00 | 2,048.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (3): - is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay; - does not apply to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court by summons pursuant to [section 15](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/sec0015.html#sec15) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0092/index.html) ; [section 10](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/sec0010.html#sec10) of the [Summary Jurisdiction (Ireland) Amendment Act 1871](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1871/en/act/pub/0076/index.html) or sections 81, 84, 85 and 86 of the Landlord and Tenant (Ireland) Act 1860 — in such proceedings costs shall be in the discretion of the Court and shall not exceed €110 in any case unless the Court shall, for special reason, otherwise order; - applies to ejectment proceedings brought before the Court on civil summons pursuant to [section 82](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/sec0082.html#sec82) of the [Civil Bill Courts (Ireland) Act 1851](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1851/en/act/pub/0057/index.html) as applied to the District Court by [section 17](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/sec0017.html#sec17) of the [Courts of Justice Act 1928](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1928/en/act/pub/0015/index.html) .'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What are the solicitors'' costs if a case is not defended when the amount of compensation awarded or claimed does not exceed €3,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["€750.00","€463.00","€1,200.00","€250.00"],"justification":"Not exceeding €3,000 | 463.00 | 772.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **5. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings for compensation under section 15 of the Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982** | Amount of compensation awarded or, in case of dismiss, amount of compensation claimed | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended | | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 463.00 | 772.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 926.00 | 1,544.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 1,389.00 | 2,315.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 1,852.00 | 3,087.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 2,315.00 | 3,859.00 | The above scale of costs (5) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What are the solicitors'' costs if a case is defended when the annual rent exceeds €9,000 and does not exceed €12,000?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["€1,950.00","€2,000.00","€1,890.00","€1,750.00"],"justification":"1,890.00"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **6. Solicitors’ costs in proceedings for recovery of possession under section 16 of the *Housing (Private Rented Dwellings) Act 1982*** | Annual rent | Costs if settled without necessity for appearance | Costs if case not defended | Costs if case defended | Costs of judgment for respondent (dismiss) | | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | | | € | € | € | € | | Not exceeding €3,000 | 119.00 | 284.00 | 472.00 | 472.00 | | Exceeding €3,000 and not exceeding €6,000 | 236.00 | 567.00 | 945.00 | 945.00 | | Exceeding €6,000 and not exceeding €9,000 | 355.00 | 850.00 | 1,418.00 | 1,418.00 | | Exceeding €9,000 and not exceeding €12,000 | 472.00 | 1,134.00 | 1,890.00 | 1,890.00 | | Exceeding €12,000 and not exceeding €15,000 | 591.00 | 1,418.00 | 2,362.00 | 2,362.00 | The above scale of costs (6) is in every instance exclusive of and in addition to all actual and necessary outlay.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Schedule of Costs - District Court (Solicitors’ costs) Rules', 'Court Rules', 'What conditions must be met for solicitors'' costs to be allowed in consent proceedings under section of the Courts Act 1991?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The amount claimed must exceed €15,000, the necessary parties must sign the prescribed form of consent, but the court must award an amount less than €15,000.","The amount claimed must exceed €15,000, the necessary parties must sign the prescribed form of consent, and the court must award an amount exceeding €15,000.","The amount claimed must be less than €15,000, the necessary parties must sign the prescribed form of consent, and the court must award an amount exceeding €15,000.","The amount claimed must exceed €15,000, the necessary parties must not sign the prescribed form of consent, and the court must award an amount exceeding €15,000."],"justification":"Where proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 are brought before the District Court and: - the amount claimed in the proceedings exceeds €15,000, and, - pursuant to the proviso to section 77A of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 (inserted by section of the Courts Act 1991), the necessary parties to the proceedings sign the prescribed form of consent, and - (iii) the Court in determining the proceedings awards an amount in excess of €15,000"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **10. Solicitors’ costs in consent proceedings to which section of the Courts Act 1991 relates** Where proceedings of the kind mentioned in paragraph A of section 77 of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 are brought before the District Court and: - the amount claimed in the proceedings exceeds €15,000, and, - pursuant to the proviso to section 77A of the Courts of Justice Act 1924 (inserted by section of the Courts Act 1991), the necessary parties to the proceedings sign the prescribed form of consent, and - (iii) the Court in determining the proceedings awards an amount in excess of €15,000, the successful party may be allowed costs in accordance with the foregoing scales 1 to 9 in respect of the first €15,000 of the award and, in addition, a sum which represents 5% of the amount by which the award exceeds €15,000. Where the proceedings are dismissed, the defendant may be allowed costs similarly calculated on the amount claimed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What does Order refer to in the context of the Defamation Act 2009?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Section of the Copyright Act 2009","Defamation Act 2009 [1]","Chapter of the Privacy Act 2009","Order in the Civil Procedure Rules 2009"],"justification":"# **Order Defamation Act 2009 [1]**"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '# Order - Defamation Act 2009 - Court: Superior # **Order Defamation Act 2009 [1]**'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'What is the deadline for delivering copies of the originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit to the respondent?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["Within seven clear days after the originating notice of motion has been served.","Not later than four clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion.","On the same day as the return date for the originating notice of motion.","Not later than two clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion."],"justification":"Notice of an application under sub-rule (1) shall be given by delivering copies of the originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit and any exhibits thereto to the respondent not later than four clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- under paragraph of section 23(1) for the leave of the Court to make a correction and apology by means of a statement before the Court in such terms as may be approved by the Court and to give an undertaking as to the manner of their publication, or - (iii) for a determination under paragraph of section 23(1) shall be made by originating notice of motion entitled in the matter of section 23 and in which the person to whom the offer was made shall be named as applicant and the person who made the offer shall be named as respondent, which motion shall be grounded upon an affidavit sworn by or on behalf of the moving party. (2) Notice of an application under sub-rule (1) shall be given by delivering copies of the originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit and any exhibits thereto to the respondent not later than four clear days before the return date for the originating notice of motion. (3) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the respondent to such originating notice of motion may deliver a replying affidavit within two weeks of the delivery to him or her of copies of the said originating notice of motion and grounding affidavit. (4) Save as otherwise directed by the Court, the applicant may deliver a further affidavit within two weeks of the delivery of any replying affidavit. 6. Save in the case of an application under paragraph (a) of section 23(1), the Court may, at the hearing of an originating motion under rule 5(and in addition to any other order it may make): - (a) make such orders or give such directions as seem appropriate for the delivery of further affidavits and for the determination of the application;'),
                                                                                                                 ('Superior – Order 1B - Defamation Act 2009', 'Court Rules', 'When was Order inserted into the Defamation Act 2009?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["Order was inserted by S.I. 511 of 2009, effective from 1 January 2010.","S.I. 511 of 2010, which became effective on 1 January 2011.","S.I. 511 of 2006, which became effective on 1 July 2007.","S.I. 311 of 2009, which became effective on 1 October 2009."],"justification":"[1] Order inserted by [S.I. 511 of 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/511/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## Particulars of evidence in mitigation** 10. In a defamation action, in which the defendant does not by his defence assert the truth of the statement complained of in accordance with section 16, the defendant shall not be entitled on the trial to give evidence in chief, with a view to mitigation of damages, as to the circumstances under which the defamatory statement was published, or as to the character of the plaintiff, without the leave of the Judge, unless seven days at least before the trial he furnished particulars to the plaintiff of the matters as to which he intends giving evidence. [1] Order inserted by [S.I. 511 of 2009](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2009/si/511/made/en/print), effective 1 January 2010'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Where can proceedings related to an enforceable maintenance order be held if the debtor resides in the State?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the creditor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the debtor''s family members reside or carry on any profession, business or occupation.","Proceedings may only take place at the main courthouse in the capital city of the State where the debtor resides.","At any sitting of the Court for the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation."],"justification":"the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Venue** 2.(1) Subject to sub-rule (2), proceedings to which this Order relates may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for the court area where either party to the proceedings ordinarily resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation or where the order which it is sought to enforce was made and, save where the context otherwise requires, any reference in this Order to the “**Clerk**” is a reference to the Clerk for that court area. (2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), proceedings to which this Order relates concerning an enforceable maintenance order to which the [2011 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/si/274/made/en/print) or, as the case may be, the [2019 Regulations](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2019/si/594/made/en/print) apply may be brought, heard or determined at any sitting of the Court for: - (a) where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned resides in the State, the court area in which the debtor resides or carries on any profession, business or occupation, or - where the maintenance debtor under the enforceable maintenance order concerned does not reside in the State but is employed by a person residing or having a place of business in the State or by a body whose seat of management or control is in the State, the court area in which the person resides or the body has its seat.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'How is an application for a summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010 made?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["By the completion by the maintenance creditor of a letter of intent in Form 57.1, Schedule A, which must be submitted to the Judge.","By the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in Form 57.3, Schedule which must be submitted to the Clerk.","By the completion by the maintenance creditor of a declaration in Form 57.4, Schedule which must be submitted to the Magistrate.","By the completion by the maintenance creditor of an affidavit in Form 57.2, Schedule which must be submitted to the Sheriff."],"justification":"An application under section 9A(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (as inserted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) or under section 52A(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (as inserted by section 146 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) for the issue of a summons may be made by the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in the [Form 57.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de505ada-98be-4de0-97bc-a3cd9276d517/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.3.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application\*\*\***in writing for summons under section 9A(3) of the Act of 1976 or section 52A(3) of the Act of 2010\*\*\* 6.**[2]** An application under section 9A(3) of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) (as inserted by the [Act of 2011](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2011/act/23)) or under section 52A(3) of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24) (as inserted by section 146 of the Children and Family Relationships Act 2015) for the issue of a summons may be made by the completion by the maintenance creditor of an application form in the [Form 57.3, Schedule C](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/de505ada-98be-4de0-97bc-a3cd9276d517/Summons for attendance of maintenance debtor - Family Law (Maintenance of Spouses and Children) Act 1976 No. 57.3.docx/docx/1), which must be submitted to the Clerk. Upon receipt of the completed application from, the Clerk will issue a summons.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What must be lodged with the Clerk regarding the service of a summons and application form?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["A letter of intent stating the intention to serve the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing.","A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing.","An affidavit confirming the receipt of the summons and application form by the maintenance debtor must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing.","A copy of the summons and application form signed by the defendant must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing."],"justification":"A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Service of summonses, application forms and orders** 8.[4] (1) [Order 41]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-41-District-Service-Of-Documents-In-Civil-Proceedings-Service-Of-Documents-In-The-State) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons and application form mentioned in rule 4. (2) [Order 51A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-51A-District-Enforcement-Of-Judgments-And-Orders), rules 8(5), 8(7) and 8(8) shall apply to the service and lodgment of proof of service of a summons mentioned in rule 7 and application form mentioned in rule 6. A statutory declaration as to service by or on behalf of the maintenance creditor of the summons and application form must be lodged with the Clerk at least two days before the date of the hearing. (3) An order made under section 8(2)(a) or section of the [Act of 1940](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1940/act/23/enacted/en/html) may be in the [Form 57.4](https://www.courts.ie/acc/alfresco/3022a2b1-6ed7-4036-94c6-7ff708590ba3/Notice Of Application To Vary A Garnishee Order - Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, section 8 (2) No. 57.4.docx/docx/1) Schedule and a copy of such order must be sent by registered post by the Clerk to every person directed to pay monies to the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'What can the Court do if the contempt has not been purged?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["The Court may dismiss the case of contempt without any further proceedings.","The Court may grant the person immunity from all future contempt charges.","The Court may issue a formal apology to the person in contempt.","The Court may direct that the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court."],"justification":"the Court may direct that, if the contempt has not previously been purged, the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Application to purge contempt** 12. Where a person is imprisoned for contempt of court in accordance with section 9A of the [Act of 1976](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1976/act/11) or section 52A of the [Act of 2010](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/act/24): - (a) the person shall be notified in writing of the action required to purge his contempt; - the Court may direct that, if the contempt has not previously been purged, the person shall be brought back before the Court at a place and time fixed by the Court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 57 - Proceedings Under: Section 8 of the Enforcement of Court Orders Act 1940, etc.', 'Court Rules', 'Who should address and execute warrants of distress issued under this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the local police departments.","Warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the federal marshals.","Warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the municipal mayors.","Warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the several Sheriffs and County Registrars."],"justification":"warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the several Sheriffs and County Registrars"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '## **Provisions regarding warrants to apply** 14. The provisions contained in [Order 26]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-26-District-Endorsement-Addressing-Execution-Re-Issue-Of-Warrants) regarding warrants shall apply to warrants issued under this Order with the proviso that warrants of distress shall be addressed to and executed by the several Sheriffs and County Registrars. [1] Order 57 substituted in full by [S.I. 202 of 2021](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2021/si/202/made/en/print), effective 5 May 2021. Superseded amendments: Order 57 originally substituted by [S.I. 325 of 2010](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2010/si/325/made/en/print?q 325&years 2010), re-substituted by [S.I. 306 of 2013](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2013/si/306/made/en/print?q 306&years 2013), substituted by [S.I. 17 of 2016](http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2016/si/17/made/en/print?q 17&years 2016), effective 18 January 2016. [2] Order 57 rule 6 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [3] Order 57 rule 7 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025. [4] Order 57 rule 8 substituted by [S.I. 221of 2025](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2025/si/221/made/en/print), effective 3 June 2025.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does ''Clerk'' refer to in this Order?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["A retired judge who provides advice and guidance to the current judges in the District Court.","A legal representative appointed by the Attorney General to oversee all court proceedings within the district.","A member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk.","The chief administrative officer of a corporation responsible for managing daily operations unrelated to judicial matters."],"justification":"references to the “**Clerk**”, where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Definitions_ 1. In this Order:- references to the “**Clerk**”, where the context so admits or requires, include reference to a member of the staff of the Courts Service assigned to the District Court for the court district and/or area concerned and for the time being authorised to receive or issue any court document on behalf of the Clerk; “**court document**” includes any claim notice, pleading, notice, affidavit, or other document required by these Rules to be lodged with the Clerk in or in connection with any civil proceeding; “**digital delivery**” of a court document or other document means delivery of that document by electronic means: - by a digital user to the Clerk, - by or on behalf of the Clerk to a digital user, or - (iii) by a digital user to another digital user (including a digital user who is a party, or who is the solicitor for a party), in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in this Order; “**digital user**” means: - a solicitor, a firm of solicitors or a legal partnership, acting through a person authorised for the purpose by that firm or partnership, or - a party suing or defending in person, which is or who is for the time being authorised to deliver to the Clerk and to receive from the Clerk by digital means any court document or other document which may be lodged or filed in or with the Court in or in connection with any proceedings or category of proceedings in the Court, in respect of which digital delivery is for the time being authorised in accordance with section 20 of the [Civil Law and Criminal Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 202](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2020/act/13/enacted/en/html)0; “**network**” means an electronic information and communications network or system maintained and supported by the Courts Service for the purposes of use by court users in civil proceedings, for the time being in use in or for the purposes of the Court, to which digital users have access, and which is used or capable of use for digital delivery;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What is ''non-personal delivery in hard copy'' of a court document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["Personal hand-delivery of the document to the opposing party''s legal counsel within business hours, as per the guidelines set out in rule 7.","Delivery of the document electronically via email or through a secure online portal, as specified in rule 9.","Delivery of the document via courier service that requires signature upon receipt, provided the courier company is approved by the court under rule 10.","Delivery of the document in hard copy to the Clerk by pre-paid registered post, pre-paid ordinary post, through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or deposit in a box/facility maintained by the Clerk, in accordance with conditions stipulated in rule 8, excluding digital delivery."],"justification":"“**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the Clerk: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the Clerk, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '“**non-personal delivery in hard copy**” of a court document means: - (a) delivery of that document in hard copy to the Clerk: - by pre-paid registered post, - by pre-paid ordinary post, or - (iii) through a document exchange service accepted by the Clerk, or - deposit of that document in hard copy in a box or at a facility maintained for the purpose by the Clerk, in accordance with any conditions stipulated in the manner provided in rule 8, but does not include digital delivery; “**personal delivery**” means lodgment with the Clerk of a court document in hard copy, together with any copy required and proof of payment of any court fee required (where necessary, endorsed on the court document), by attendance at the office used by the Clerk.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What does the Clerk''s certificate confirm?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The signature of the defendant accepting the court''s terms","The issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates.","The payment status of court fees associated with the document","The date on which the trial is scheduled to begin"],"justification":"a copy of any duplicate or copy of the court document concerned retained by the Clerk, with a certificate endorsed thereon confirming the issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '- a copy of any duplicate or copy of the court document concerned retained by the Clerk, with a certificate endorsed thereon confirming the issue of the court document to which the duplicate or copy relates; - a certificate as to any record made of the issue of the court document concerned, and - the party or person may, subject to and in accordance with any order or direction of the Court, proceed on a copy of the court document certified in accordance with paragraph (a)(i) or, where the Court so permits, a copy of the court document lodged for issue, certified by the party who lodged it or his or her solicitor to be a true copy of the court document lodged, and a certificate given in accordance with paragraph (a)(ii).'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'Who has the authority to authorise the use of digital delivery for court documents?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":1,"options":["The Chief Justice, after obtaining approval from the Supreme Court","The President of the Court, after consulting with the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service","The local Post Office Manager, after consulting with the regional postal supervisor","The IT Department Head, after receiving consent from the court clerks"],"justification":"Having consulted with the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service the President of the Court may, from time to time, by Practice Direction, authorise (including on a temporary or trial basis) the use of digital delivery by or in respect of any:"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Authorisation of digital delivery of court documents or documents_ 12.(1) Having consulted with the Chief Executive Officer of the Courts Service the President of the Court may, from time to time, by Practice Direction, authorise (including on a temporary or trial basis) the use of digital delivery by or in respect of any: - category or class of proceedings or of applications within proceedings, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - category or class of documents, either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally; - (iii) category or class of parties, legal representatives and/or other persons interested in proceedings (in this rule a “court user”), either in any specified court district or districts (and/or court area or areas) or generally. (2) Unless otherwise expressly provided in such Practice Direction, where the use of digital delivery is authorised in accordance with sub-rule (1), such delivery will be an alternative to any other method by which such document could be filed, lodged, issued or transmitted by or to the party or person concerned. (3) A network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is, for the purposes of the delivery of any court document or document to any Clerk, deemed to be operational only during the hours during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is open to the public. (4) Any period when a network operated for the purposes of digital delivery is inoperative will be treated, for the purposes of [Order 12]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url Order-12-District-Miscellaneous-Provisions), Rule as a period during which the public office at which the Clerk conducts business is closed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a natural person provide to become a digital user?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":3,"options":["A digital signature and a credit card number.","A valid passport and a social security number only.","A verified email address and a recent utility bill as proof of residence.","Sufficient evidence of their identity including a relevant document, personal public service number, and proof of residential address."],"justification":"- (a) production of the original or a certified copy of a relevant document (within the meaning of section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)); - provision of the personal public service number (within the meaning of section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) issued to the person; - provision of proof of the person’s residential address, and"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Conditions for becoming digital user_ 13.(1) A natural person may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - such person has first submitted sufficient evidence of his or her identity which may, without limitation, include: - (a) production of the original or a certified copy of a relevant document (within the meaning of section 2 of the [Statutory Declarations Act 1938](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1938/act/37/enacted/en/print.html)); - provision of the personal public service number (within the meaning of section 262 of the [Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005](https://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2005/act/26)) issued to the person; - provision of proof of the person’s residential address, and - such person has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery. (2) A firm of solicitors or legal partnership may not be authorised to become a digital user unless: - the firm or partnership has first submitted sufficient evidence of its establishment and standing; - the firm or partnership has submitted sufficient evidence of the identity of each natural person authorised on behalf of the firm to transmit court documents through the network by digital delivery; - (iii) the firm or partnership has undertaken to comply with any published terms and conditions of use of the network concerned for the purposes of digital delivery.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must a court document transmitted by digital delivery contain?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["The name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the document, or the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person.","The tax identification number and bank account details of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the document, or the employment status and salary information of any party suing or appearing in person.","The digital signature and address of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the document, or the passport number and place of birth of any party suing or appearing in person.","The email address and phone number of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the document, or the social security number and date of birth of any party suing or appearing in person."],"justification":"- (a) contain: - the name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the same or, as the case may be, - the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Documents transmitted by digital delivery_ 15.(1) Any court document transmitted by digital delivery by or on behalf of a party must: - (a) contain: - the name and registered place of business of the solicitor for the party transmitting or delivering the same or, as the case may be, - the name and place of residence, or address for service, of any party suing or appearing in person; - include the name of the natural person transmitting the court document concerned; - where submitted otherwise than by the party himself or herself, include a statement that the court document is submitted with the authority of the party on whose behalf it is submitted. (2) Any document other than a court document which is transmitted by or on behalf of a party by digital delivery as a copy in electronic form of an original document must have endorsed on or associated with such copy a certificate given by the party or by a named solicitor that the copy has been compared to, and is a true copy, of the original document. (3) Where any court document is authorised to be filed or lodged by digital delivery: - (a) the court document must be accompanied by such information, if any, as is required under any conditions stipulated concerning digital delivery in accordance with rule 14; - where a court fee is chargeable in respect of the court document, the court document may not be used unless and until payment of the applicable court fee is recorded by a means for the time being authorised for the recording of the payment of a court fee;'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What verification is required for a written statement of evidence intended to be admitted into evidence when delivered via digital delivery?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":2,"options":["Verification by a notary public at the time of document creation","Approval by a legal representative unrelated to the case","Verification on oath or affirmation at the trial of the proceedings.","A simple email confirmation from the declarant that the statement is true"],"justification":"be subject to verification on oath or affirmation at the trial of the proceedings"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '(5) Where any affidavit is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, the affidavit shall be transmitted in such electronic format as is accommodated by the network, and it shall be and remain the obligation of the party filing any such affidavit to retain the affidavit bearing the original manuscript signature of the deponent and any and all of the marked exhibits to the affidavit, which remain subject to the directions of any court before which such affidavit is, or may be, relied upon or opened. (6) Where any written statement of evidence or written statement outlining the essential elements of evidence is authorised or required by any Practice Direction or any order or direction of the Court to be delivered and/or filed in any proceedings in which digital delivery is for the time being authorised, such statement may be delivered and/or filed by transmission through the network, but shall, if intended to be admitted into evidence, be subject to verification on oath or affirmation at the trial of the proceedings. (7) Where any affidavit or any statement referred to in sub-rule (6) is for the time being authorised to be filed by digital delivery, [Order 50A]([f669d9a7-009d-4d83-ddaa-000000000002|lng:en]59D3A380-82AD-48F7-9B9E-F3A4D928E077?url statements-of-truth), rule 6 shall apply *mutatis mutandis* to any exhibits to such affidavit or statement.'),
                                                                                                                 ('District – Order 39A - Requirements as to form and delivery of pleadings, documents and notices used in civil proceedings in the Court', 'Court Rules', 'What must be provided when serving a person personally with a digitally delivered court document?', 'mcq', '{"correct_index":0,"options":["A copy of the document and a written statement that the document was issued by digital delivery.","A signed affidavit by the server stating that the document was delivered via postal mail.","An email notification sent to the recipient confirming the delivery of the document.","A verbal confirmation from the recipient acknowledging receipt of the document."],"justification":"serving the person personally with a copy of the court document concerned and, at the same time, providing the person with a written statement that the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Court Rules'], '### _Service of documents where digital delivery applies_ 17.(1) Where any provision of any enactment, of these Rules or the existing practice of the Court requires or permits that any court document or document be served upon any person, such requirement may be satisfied in any case where the person to be served is or becomes a digital user by the transmission by digital delivery of the court document or document through the network to the person concerned, and in any such case any record generated by or within the network of such transmission may be produced as evidence of such service in lieu of any statutory declaration of service. (Where the person to be served is not a digital user, such person shall be served with a printed copy of the court document or document in such other manner as is permitted in the circumstances by these Rules). (2) Sub-rule (1) does not apply in any case where these Rules or the existing practice of the Court require personal service, but any requirement that a person being served personally with a court document be shown any original or copy of the court document shall, where the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery, be satisfied by serving the person personally with a copy of the court document concerned and, at the same time, providing the person with a written statement that the court document concerned has been issued by digital delivery.'),
